<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. STOCKS PLUNGE AS ASIAN TURMOIL WORSENS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 15th graf for updating on Asian market performance early
Tuesday)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Renewed fears that Asia's economic crisis will stall
growth in the profits of American companies sent U.S. stocks
plunging on Monday, the worst in a string of recent sell-offs that
has now erased the gains of the last three months for the Dow Jones
industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   Since crossing the 9,000 mark in April _ a level almost 1,100
points above where the blue-chip average began the year _ the Dow
has faced trouble sustaining that height.
</P>
<P>
   The widely followed barometer of the nation's top industrial
companies fell 207.01 points on Monday, to 8,627.93, a 2.3 percent
drop that left it down 6.3 percent from its record high. Some other
market gauges have fallen even more, suggesting that a stock market
correction _ a drop of 10 percent or more _ is under way.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are increasingly concerned that Asia has yet to reach
the bottom of its economic cycle. Signs of distress there are not
only persistent, but deepening.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, which many hoped would be the region's rescuer, announced
last week that its economy shrank sharply in the quarter that ended
in March, amounting to its steepest annualized decline since World
War II. The yen, a barometer of Japan's economic weakness, fell to
an eight-year low against the dollar Monday, further elevating
fears throughout Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Prices on the Japanese stock market and at other exchanges
across Asia fell sharply in response, setting the stage for a
decline when trading began on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're really seeing is a truly global market,'' said
Anthony Conroy, a managing director at Bankers Trust Global
Investment Management. ``If you catch a cold in Asia, it really
becomes a flu almost everywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   For American companies that do business in Japan and throughout
Asia, the prospects are growing dimmer for a recovery anytime soon.
Monday, Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing, the maker of Post-it
notes and Scotchguard fabric protector, became the latest American
company to warn investors that earnings would be disappointing this
quarter because of Asian problems.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, analysts predicted that global companies
would be hurt in the first half of the year by Asia's troubles, but
that earnings would pick up in the second half. Now, more and more
analysts are pushing back their estimates of a recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Although companies have been reluctant to say much about how
Asia will lower earnings, Boeing, National Semiconductor, Ford,
Callaway Golf, and Analog Devices have all hinted that their
profits will continue to be pinched in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, 64 percent of the companies that have warned
analysts to revise their profit projections for the second quarter
have suggested that the estimates be lowered, according to First
Call Corp., a Boston-based firm that tracks analysts' earnings
estimates. In an average quarter, only 57 percent of companies give
such negative outlooks, First Call said.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, analysts now expect profits at the companies in
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 to rise 9.2 percent, down from a 13.9
percent estimate at the beginning of the year, according to a
survey by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Those projections may still prove optimistic. Profits in the S&AMP;P
500 actually rose 3.8 percent in the first quarter and are now
expected to climb 4.7 percent in the second quarter, First Call
said. That estimate is down considerably since the first of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   A flight to quality has helped the American financial markets
all year, but only the Treasury market benefitted on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, the Nikkei 225 average of Japanese stocks fell 1.3
percent Monday. Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng index was off 5.72
percent to its lowest level since Jan. 30, 1995. European stock
markets fell as well. In early trading on Tuesday, Japanese stocks
fell slightly and Hong Kong stocks were up a bit. Other Asian
markets were little changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia is a double-edged sword,'' said Charles Johnson, head
equity trader at Blaylock &AMP; Partners in Baltimore. The problems
have dimmed the possibility that the Federal Reserve would soon
raise interest rates _ a rise is considered negative for the market
_ but ``the other edge is corporate profits,'' which may be lower
than expected.
</P>
<P>
   In uncertain times, U.S. Treasuries are seen as a haven, and
Monday a surge in demand for bonds sent the yield on the bellwether
30-year Treasury to record lows. Price increases also pushed down
the yields on most other bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In the stock market, bargain hunters moved in at midday, but
sellers swamped the buyers at the end of the day. The 207-point
fall was the fifth-biggest ever for the Dow average, but in
percentage terms, the 2.3 percent decline was not among even its 20
worst days. The average is still up 9.1 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Some stock analysts said that the blue-chip stock gauge was
merely beginning to reflect the declines already evident in the
broader market.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, laden with technology stocks, fell
29.30 points Monday to 1,715.75, a 1.68 percent decline for the
day. It is now off 10.5 percent from its April 22 high.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index, another broad stock market gauge, fell
7.73 points Monday and is now off 11.7 percent from its high on
April 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall stock market is acting much more poorly than the
blue chip indexes,'' said Steve Shobin, chief technical analyst at
Lehman Brothers. ``Yes, there's really a correction going on.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a Salomon Smith Barney study, through June 2, more
than 43 percent of the stocks in the Nasdaq composite index had
declined 30 percent or more from their 52-week highs. That compares
with 10.2 percent of stocks in the S&AMP;P 500 and almost 18 percent of
the stocks on the New York Stock Exchange. During the same period,
the average decline in a Nasdaq stock has been 30.1 percent from
their 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   When looking at stocks with price declines of at least 10
percent _ the usual measure of a correction _ the percentages are
even higher. Eighty four percent of Nasdaq stocks are off that
amount, as are more than 58 percent of S&AMP;P stocks and almost 69
percent of those traded on the New York Stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Shobin of Lehman Bros. said his indicators point to more trouble
ahead. Fewer stocks are posting new highs now than in mid-April, he
said, and trading volume has been declining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most corrections do not end until volume rises sharply,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
