<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 09:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plug the leaks and run the country
 &HT;    EDS: A bonus column from Tom Teepen for immediate release
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By TOM TEEPEN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only in obsessive Washington D. C., endlessly stewing in
half-scandals and faux scandals, could the admission by Kenneth
Starr that he and his staff have leaked be heard as some sort of
thunderclap.
</P>
<P>
   To the rest of the country, this is a revelation on the order of
a breathless announcement that the sun comes up in the east. Well,
OF COURSE, the independent counsel and his staff leak. Everybody in
Washington leaks. It is an infantile city and there isn't a Pampers
in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and the counsel's office have been leaking at
each other. They are in a leaking match. The rest of us are just
trying to stay out of the cross-squirt.
</P>
<P>
   Now the White House is pretending shock, shock at the
confirmation of the obvious. Indignation abounds. Clinton spinners
have gone dervish for TV news programs, performing paroxysms of
outrage.
</P>
<P>
   The outrage is phony and calculated. The White House senses a
major opportunity to further discredit Starr, though his own,
previous indiscretions and untoward political blunders already had
gone a long ways toward calling his operation into broad question.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming increasingly difficult to pretend that huge
issues of ethical principle and of legal righteousness are aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has closed down his Little Rock shop, reportedly without
establishing that one or another Clinton nicked the law in the
legalistic comings and goings over a minor land deal about a
century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel seems still to be investigating
``travelgate'' even though the White House travel staff works for
the president and can be fired for dumb reasons, the case in this
Clinton rookie mistake. The issue, if you can call it one, appears
to be whether Hillary Clinton had a bigger hand in the foul-up than
she has said. If so, will Starr try to turn political
damage-control into perjury?
</P>
<P>
   Starr at last report was still also looking into all those
Republican names that turned up in a White House computer list. But
what on Earth does it matter? No one on the list has ever suffered
for his or her temporary passage on it.
</P>
<P>
   All of which would appear to reduce Starr's four years and $40
million to a question of whether or not Clinton had extramarital
sex and lied about it in a lawsuit that turned out to have no legal
merit and was pushed partly in hopes of setting up just such a
gotcha. (The latest: a book claims Clinton had left the hotel hours
before Paula Jones says he came on to her there, reportedly the
defense's ace in the hole if the case had gone to trial.)
</P>
<P>
   Now the Clintonians want Starr himself investigated by an
independent counsel to decide whether he vented grand jury dope
despite a statutory obligation to keep a lid on it. Please, no.
This cycle of charge and countercharge doesn't need another whack
that will keep it going around and around even longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr investigation has become an endless attempt to get
something, anything, on one or another Clinton. The president in
turn has been trying to de-pants Starr as if he were the designated
nerd of the dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   Does anyone in Washington remember that we've got a real country
here and somebody damn well ought to be running it?
</P>
<P>
   E-Mail:teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
