<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, June 16, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES (San Antonio) _ San Antonio has seen an explosion of
new diabetes cases in recent years, and if the rest of the country
is following suit, the result could be a reversal of a 30-year
decline in heart disease deaths, a researcher said. By DON FINLEY.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-HUNTER (San Francisco) _ A computerized canine is
``sniffing'' for explosives inside luggage at San Francisco
International Airport. The ``explosive trace detector'' doesn't
look like the robotic pooches of science-fiction films. By KEAY
DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   SNOW-PARKS (San Francisco) _ Many areas of the high country are
accessible only by skis, snowshoes or snowmobile. Some campgrounds
remain snowbound. From Crater Lake, Ore., to Mammoth Mountain, the
story's the same _ warm skies over snow, snow, snow. El Nino is to
blame, of course. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ All rental car agencies, health
clubs and insurance companies offering discounts to married couples
would have to extend the same rates to registered domestic
partners, under a city law proposed by San Francisco's newest
supervisor. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRYSON (San Francisco) _ ``A Walk in the Woods,'' a book
by travel writer Bill Bryson, is about his attempt to walk the
Appalachian Trail, which runs 2,100 miles from Georgia to Maine.
Part of book's charm comes from the fact that Bryson was
breathtakingly ill-suited to the task. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The weather experts say the El
Nino weather phenomenon is over. But apparently no one told the
fish. The continuing saga of the biggest ocean temperature tantrum
in history has created a fishing paradise. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-JORDAN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There is no glory in success if it
comes without the risk of failure. Michael Jordan failed on Friday,
failed to deliver the sort of miracle that he and all earthlings
have come to expect, and this is the first four-letter word that
came to his mind: Cute. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ School choice is scary stuff.
Critics say it would destroy the public school system, and they're
probably right. But unless politicians give public schools the
power to expel troublemakers, school choice will become a more
attractive proposition to more people. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ What is happening now in more
and more news media, unnamed sources are taking an ever larger role
in articles that should not require them. Editors should bear down
hard on limiting unnamed sources and on insisting that their
reporters strive to get on-the-record information. By HARRY
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-TREK (San Francisco) _ ``Star Trek'' is now shown in more
than 100 countries, finding a far wider audience than the original
cultish Trekkers (don't call them Trekkies) of old-time fandom.
Travel writer Jeff Greenwald made it his mission to find out why.
By SAM HURWITT.
</P>
</TEXT>
