   -------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A GLIMPSE OF THE REAL AMERICAN WEST &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE FREE OF CHARGE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take a trip through the picturesque American West on the the
Montana Daylight excursion train with Gene and Adele Malott,
publishers of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus.
You can't see these sights from the interstate: ``Deep gorges where
autos can't go, punctuated with scenic tunnels dug by railroad
workers before the turn of the century; children returning from
school on horses waving at the train; cattle grazing lazily on
ranges; and more.''
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-REAL-AMERICAN-WEST-TRAVEL-NYTSF, category codes t
and l)
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CRUISE CENTRAL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE &QL; 
 &UR; (900 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's full steam ahead in the cruise business, reports New
York-based travel writer Everett Potter. While some industry
pundits point to the film ``Titanic'' as an ironic booster of
sales, that's open to debate. Travel agents and cruise-only agents
report record bookings, sold-out sailings and inquiries many months
in advance of embarkation.
</P>
<P>
   (slugged: BC-CRUISE-CENTRAL-NYTSF, category codes t and l)
