<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-CENTRAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE CENTRAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers.)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's full steam ahead in the cruise business. While some
industry pundits point to the film ``Titanic'' as an ironic booster
of sales, that's open to debate.
 &HT;    But icebergs or not, the fact is that travel agents and
cruise-only agents report record bookings, sold-out sailings and
inquiries many months in advance of embarkation.
 &HT;    ``In Europe, it's boom, boom, boom,'' says Elaine Lerner.
 &HT;    Lerner, president of National Discount Cruise Co./American
Express (1409 N. Cedar Crest Blvd., Allentown, Pa. 18104;
800-788-8108), says ``This summer, it's been difficult to get to
Europe. Hot new ships like Princess' 'Grand Princess,' Holland
America's 'Rotterdam VI' and Royal Caribbean's 'Splendor of the
seas' are sold out.''
 &HT;    That's in keeping with a classic piece of cruise wisdom: New
sells. In this business, any vessel over 18 months is considered
old. And there exists a band of well-heeled salts who will only
sail on new vessels, in some cases regardless of itinerary.
 &HT;    For those devotees, a new ship and all its marvels are the
destination.
 &HT;    Even so, there may still be some good deals for Europe in
shoulder season, which is now longer than ever.
 &HT;    In the past, the major cruise lines would move their ships
across from the Mediterranean to the Caribbean sometime in October.
 &HT;    ``This year, for the first time, we're seeing more ships in the
Mediterranean from October to December,'' says Don Lansky, vice
president of public relations for The Cruise Line (150 NW 168th
St., North Miami Beach, Fla. 33169; 800-777-0707). ``That's the
latest we've ever seen it.''
 &HT;    But while Europe has been hot, Alaska is not _ or not as hot,
anyway, according to some agents. Two-for-one deals on Alaska
sailings may not be quite as prolific as they were last summer, but
they're still around.
 &HT;    ``Alaska has been soft,'' Lerner concedes. ``There are just too
many ships up there. Next summer, there may be fewer.''
 &HT;    For those travelers looking toward the Caribbean next winter,
it's already shaping up as a boom season.
 &HT;    ``There are strong bookings and a lot of the new ships will be
there,'' Lerner says.
 &HT;    And the Caribbean season is growing as well, according to
Lansky, who adds that ``fall has traditionally been off-season, but
a lot of ships are pretty packed this year.''
 &HT;    Other destinations in South America and Asia are attracting
cruise-goers who may have done the Alaska, the Caribbean and
Europe.
 &HT;    ``I'm selling more cruises to the Orient than ever before,''
says Linda Schuller, president of Travel in Style (160 S.
Livingston Ave., Livingston, N.J. 07039; 800-255-2999).
 &HT;    Schuller, who works with such upscale cruise lines as Crystal,
Seabourn and Silversea, claims that business is brisk ``because my
clients really want to visit a destination like Vietnam but they
don't necessarily want to stay in the country. The infrastructure
isn't there yet for deluxe clients.''
 &HT;    Deluxe or not, the perennial question for consumers looking to
save money on a cruise is when to book. No one pays sticker price
for a cruise, but what a traveler ends up paying can vary
considerably depending on when they book. Even three or four months
out it can still be difficult to get a particular type of cabin.
 &HT;    ``My best clients are booking at least six to eight months
before a sailing right now,'' Schuller explains. ``The cruise lines
all offer early-booking discounts. I can't think of one cruise line
that doesn't do it. Everybody had a deal, some with discounts as
high as 30 percent.''
 &HT;    These discounts vary according to destination, cruise line, time
of sailing and cabin category.
 &HT;    Elaine Lerner voices an oft-heard equation when she says,
''There's less discounting in Europe. And on every sailing in every
destination, it's the higher-priced cabins that go fast and
first.''
 &HT;    On the West Coast, Anne Halsey-Smith, president of Halsey Tours
and Cruises (P.O. Box 2650, La Jolla, Calif. 92037; 800-459-3395),
agrees, saying ``I work harder than I did 10 years ago. My clients
are demanding and know more than ever before. If they want a
veranda and I can't get one, I can't change their mind. If it's the
same itinerary but a different ship, they're not interested.
They're booking a year to six months out at a minimum. If they're
looking for suites or hoping to sail at Christmas or New Year's,
they're booking at least one year in advance.''
 &HT;    As for the last-minute cruise market, things have changed there
too.
 &HT;    Last-minute in the cruise business has traditionally meant 30
days from sailing. But now, last-minute can mean getting space on a
cruise that sails two or even three months later.
 &HT;    Lansky admits that ``last-minute has dried up,'' with the
exception of Alaska.
 &HT;    But Schuller of Travel in Style is more optimistic, adding
``there are always cancellations. You can do three to four weeks
out occasionally. That's the minimum, especially if you need a visa
or need to make other arrangements. And there's always something in
the Caribbean.''
 &HT;    As Elaine Lerner says, ``There is a cruise for every taste and
every pocket. But they've got to invent a few more destinations.''
 ---- 
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 Everett Potter  
