<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1052 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-POWER-SIDE-COX-     06-16 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POWER-SIDE-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV21 
 &HT;     SOUTHERN WORKING ON 107 DEFECTS AT CHINA POWER PLANT
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     With CHINA-POWER-$ADV21.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUANGDONG PROVINCE, China _ ``The people who run power plants
are exactly alike all over the world,'' says Jim Webber, a 39-year
Southern Co. veteran who left retirement to help knock the kinks
out of Atlanta-based utility giant's first power plant in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think the same, they have the same hobbies, they are all
engineers,'' Webber said. ``China is very much like Turkey. Turkey
was very much like Italy. Italy is very much like the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can walk into any plant in the world. I know the equipment.
And if I know a guy's position in the plant, I basically know how
he thinks. It's basically the way I think. This is all a very large
family, if you will. We all have the same purpose in life, and that
is to produce power.''
</P>
<P>
   At 57, Webber is one of five Southern Co. engineers and
technicians assigned to monitor operations in the new Shajiao C
coal-fired power plant in Guangdong Province, about 50 miles north
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   When Southern bought the controlling share of Hong Kong
entrepreneur Gordon Wu's Asian power venture, it inherited a
32-percent interest in this 1,980-megawatt coal-fired power plant.
So far, it is Southern's only beachhead in China.
</P>
<P>
   Wu's company had built the plant for the Guangdong Province
Power Bureau, and it became Southern's contractual duty to its
Chinese joint venture partner to make sure the enormous mechanism
is tuned to deliver power at peak efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The Shajiao C plant functions. But not yet at 100-percent
reliability.
</P>
<P>
   When Wu sold out to Southern, he left behind a plant still in
the start-up phase which had more than 120 mechanical,
environmental and structural shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   As of early this month, Southern engineers had managed to trim
Shajiao C's ``punch list'' to 107 flaws that needed fixing before
the Chinese would accept the plant as fully operational.
</P>
<P>
   One recurring problem has involved the three pairs of huge air
fans that blow powdered coal into the three 80-foot-tall combustion
chambers called boilers.
</P>
<P>
   Variation in the demand for power occasionally causes one the
fans to shut down. When that happens, an automatic control box is
supposed to stop some of the unit's coal pulverizing equipment so
that the unit can ``stabilize'' at a 50-percent power output.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons Southern hasn't fully diagnosed, the pulverizing
units sometimes fail to shut down. This causes one of the remaining
fans to heat up and get overloaded, until it shuts down and knocks
one of Shajiao C's three power-producing units out of production.
</P>
<P>
   Except for trying to remedy the defects, Southern has no role in
the day-by-day operations of the plant.
</P>
<P>
   The control room is run by Chinese plant operators employed by
the Guangdong Province Power Bureau, who earn about 17 yuan (about
$2.10) per hour, compared to $20 an hour for a coal-fired power
plant operator in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese engineer in charge of operating Shajiao C, Zheng
Linfu, said he's pleased with Southern's progress in addressing the
plant's defects, even though the remaining problems are ``not a
few.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time Southern took over, the relationship on the
technical level has improved greatly,'' Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
