<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS17-COX     06-16 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Publishers clueless about nurturing mystery writers
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   National book sales are mostly flat, but the mystery field
continues to explode. Mystery bookstores are increasing in number
by 15 percent every year, and today number nearly 150.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, success brings changes, some of them bad. American
Bookseller reports that publisher's expectations have grown, and
they're no longer interested in supporting mystery writers who
amass only modest sales, or in sticking with a writer while he
builds up name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, a new mystery that could sell 3,500 copies got by,
but now publishers want to see as many as 25,000 copies sold before
they make a serious commitment to a writer. This means, in turn,
that smaller presses are getting more mystery submissions.
</P>
<P>
   THE RICH GET RICHER . . . Clive Cussler, along with Mary Higgins
Clark, one of Simon &AMP; Schuster's most popular writers, has re-upped
with a new deal that pays him less up-front but with a higher
percentage of the profits. He'll continue to write his Dirk Pitt
adventures, and he's going to start a new series called The NUMA
Files that will user other writers as well as Cussler.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's going into the franchise business.
</P>
<P>
   HIBERNIAN LITERATURE. . . Roberts Rinehart publishers has issued
``The Quiet Man and Other Stories'' ($12.95), by Maurice Walsh, a
popular Irish author of mid-century. ``The Quiet Man'' was, of
course, the basis for the beloved John Ford film, even though the
only real similarity is the central premise.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's story was originally published in the Saturday Evening
Post in 1936, and Ford bought it almost immediately, although it
took him 15 years to find the money to make it.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh was an Irish civil servant by trade _ he died in 1964 _
but ``The Quiet Man'' is typical of his stories _ rough little
character vignettes; Ford gave the story the poetry that's made it
last.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE . . . ``Do you suppose the world is finished, at
any certain time _ like a contract for paving a street? Do you
suppose because the American government has been formed, and public
school established, we have nothing more to do but take our ease,
and make money, and sleep the rest of the time?'' _ Walt Whitman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
