<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-HEAT17-COX     06-16 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-HEAT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida meteorologists hope for rain
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida temperatures continued to break records with nary a drop
of water in the sky, leaving some farmers, ranchers and water
managers thinking about the dreaded ``D'' word:
</P>
<P>
   Drought.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps just in time, meteorologists at the South Florida Water
Management District say they hope for rain.
</P>
<P>
   They don't know how much it will rain or how long, or if it will
augur a normal summer of daily thunderstorms. But they hope it will
cool things off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say we aren't in any danger right now,'' said district
Executive Director Sam Poole. But, he added, ``If we have a
below-average summer and go into a dry (winter) season, drought is
a very serious possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Winters, director of the Lake Worth Drainage District,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have rain in the next month to a month-and-a-half,
we're going to go into a drought period,'' said Winters, whose
agency's canals replenish the wells that serve coastal communities
from West Palm Beach to Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``One to two weeks of slow, steady rain would really help,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the lack of rain, high temperature records are
falling like heat-stroked tourists. Monday's high in West Palm
Beach was 98 degrees, breaking the old record for that date: 97
degrees on June 15, 1958. It was the third record-setting day in a
row and the fourth so far this month.
</P>
<P>
   A new wave of scattered brush fires broke out Monday from near
Fort Myers to near Jacksonville, destroying at least 11 homes.
Smoke closed parts of Interstate 95 and U.S. 1 in St. Johns and
Nassau counties, and authorities south of St. Augustine called for
evacuation of an entire subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of moisture also threatens to cause $100 million in
losses of soybeans, cotton and other North Florida and Panhandle
crops, state Department of Agriculture spokesman Terence McElroy
said. Agriculture officials aren't expecting big losses in citrus,
vegetables or sugar cane _ although some farmers are wary of the
dry spell persisting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it continues too much longer, it will have a major impact
on next year's crop,'' said Indian River Citrus League Chairman
John Luther. Some citrus growers around the state are reporting
wilting leaves and prematurely dropped fruit, Florida Citrus Mutual
spokeswoman Lisa Backman said.
</P>
<P>
   And some ranchers worry about their cattle's pastures.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Florida cattle are bred for hot weather,'' said Mike
Adams, president of Fort Pierce's Bud Adams Ranch, the rancher
still hopes for rain within the next three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, water district meteorologist Eric Swartz said, a
typical rainy-season weather pattern appears to be forming in the
eastern Gulf of Mexico: a low-pressure trough that should finally
steer some moist weather our way this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   June so far is the third dry month in a row _ not counting the
few rain-filled days that washed out West Palm Beach's so-called
SunFest.
</P>
<P>
   The first week of June also set four new highs for summer
electricity demand as customers cranked their air conditioning,
Florida Power &AMP; Light spokesman Dale Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason it's so hot is it's not raining,'' Swartz
said. And it's so dry that the heat can't draw enough moisture into
the air to get the rain cycle rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, an unusual zone of high pressure is squatting more than
10,000 feet above the state, National Weather Service forecaster
Wayne Colin said. That suppresses the formation of the towering
thunder clouds needed to begin the rains.
</P>
<P>
   Poole said some at the district suspect that El Nino, the
Pacific warm-weather phenomenon that caused this winter's unusually
heavy rains, is giving way to its opposite, La Nina. In strong La
Nina years earlier this century, the result was a dry May and June
in South Florida, according to federal meteorologists.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the fancy explanations, anyway. Poole offered a
simpler one: Florida's weather tends to swing in extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's normal in Florida,'' he said. ``You can get all your
rain in the dry season and then have a dry wet season.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Joe Vidueira and The Associated Press contributed
to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
