<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HEAT17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   AUS-HEAT Texas swelters as heat wave sticks close
</P>
<P>
   By Leigh Hopper
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Unless you've been hiding in a meat locker, you've
noticed it's steamin', fry-an-egg-on-the-sidewalk hot. Time to find
a cool spot under the front porch and let your tongue hang out.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures reaching scorching, record levels, air
conditioners are running without pause while sprinklers and hoses
are spewing millions of gallons of water. Recent highs in Central
Texas were between 103 and 107 degrees. In Austin, the official
high was 104, a record for the date, which came a day after the
temperature at Bergstrom tied the hottest day ever recorded in
Austin in June, possibly the hottest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Today's temperatures will be only slightly more tolerable, with
an expected high of 100, and weather service officials say not to
expect real relief for months.
</P>
<P>
   Ortencia Briones, whose window unit air conditioner has been out
for a year, has resorted to taking cold showers twice a day.
Occasionally she sleeps on a wet towel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I get up in the middle of the night and take a
shower because it's too hot,'' said Briones, 68, a resident of
Chalmers Court, a public housing complex. Those using air
conditioners are taking a toll on electrical power companies.
Several area cities are setting daily records for power
consumption, and the strain is showing.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, high demand for electricity caused transformers
inTexas Utilities Electric Company's Round Rock district to
overload, leaving about 400 homes without air conditioning and
lights for about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everyone I knew was standing in their front
yards,'' said John Hurt of Round Rock. ``It was too hot to stay
inside without air conditioning.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst of it was, the power went out just as the NBA
Championship game was ending, he said. ``Everyone was sitting in
their cars trying to listen to the end of the game on their
radio.''
</P>
<P>
   TU officials said periodic problems could continue this week.
</P>
<P>
   The intense heat had emergency medical workers braced for a
spate of heat-related health problems, but so far none has been
serious.
</P>
<P>
   The unseasonable heat is forcing social service agencies to
scramble to keep up with its relief programs for Austin's elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Meals on Wheels and More is seeking donations of bottled water
to give away to clients. Two years ago, the agency gave out 1,500
bottles of water when the August heat made temperatures soar.
Spokeswoman Lisa Polette said the agency also plans to hand out
pamphlets with detailed information about dehydration. So far a few
clients have complained about discomfort from the heat, but no
serious incidents have been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Family Eldercare has given out more than 600 fans to the elderly
after only two weeks of its eighth annual Summer Fan Drive,
officials there said. That is half of what the agency gave out
during the whole summer last year, Family Eldercare spokeswoman
Cathy Marable said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of fans,'' said Marable. ``We're counting on the
generosity of the community to get the help we need for the elderly
who are out there sweltering.''
</P>
<P>
   This year the agency plans to give away 1,600 fans. If people
want to volunteer to deliver fans, want to donate or need a fan
they can call 459-4326.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly, along with small children and people with diseases
such as diabetes and kidney problems, are at greater risk for
heat-related health problems because their bodies don't regulate
their own temperature as well as healthy adults, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   Austin officials said they are taking the heat into account when
planning children's activities.
</P>
<P>
   Dittmar Recreation Center Director Danny Castro said outdoor
games that require a lot of running around have been confined to
the early hours of the morning, when temperatures are at their
lowest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make sure that the kids who come here get plenty of water,
which is a lot better for you than sodas on a day like this,''
Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters see no marked improvement in the heat wave, which is
not good news for providers of electric power. Electricity demand
in Austin has on some days this summer been 50 percent higher than
last year. TU has seen 20 percent jumps, while customers of
Pedernales Electric Cooperative are using about 25 percent more
electricity since the start of May than they did a year ago. In
Georgetown, residents are using 25 percent more electricity per
capita than they were last June.
</P>
<P>
   Benny Fuelberg, general manager of the Pedernales co-op, said,
``People may try to sleep with the windows open even when it gets
up to 90 degrees, but they use an air conditioner when it gets to
109.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters say some relief for broiled Central Texans could
occur over the next few weeks as sporadic weather systems
containing some rain work their way into the Austin area.
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service meteorologist Jeff Ward said any
long-term relief is not likely until of August. ``It's not until
after the first part of August that storm systems are able to push
their way into Central Texas from the Gulf Coast and Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers Christian Davenport, Clara G.
Herrera, Claire Osborn, Kevin Wishard, Dylan Rivera and Bob Banta
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
