A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTA-CATS17-COX     06-16 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTA-CATS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cats got her in trouble
 &HT;    By Scott Cech
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ To Johnette Lothrop's way of thinking,
the city of Port St. Lucie is telling her to suddenly quit her
abiding hobby and kick 20 of her closest friends out of her house.
Or else.
</P>
<P>
   Along with her husband Robert, Lothrop lives with about 20 Maine
Coon cats, which she said she breeds, shows and occasionally sells
to help recoup the costs of keeping the cats.
</P>
<P>
   But the city has told her that anyone housing more than three
adult cats is running a de facto kennel, and no kennels are allowed
in residential districts.
</P>
<P>
   So Lothrop has been reluctantly giving away her pride of cats,
all of which have names.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it politely, I'm pissed,'' she said. ``But I can't
fight city hall on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   When she and her husband moved into their suburban home off
Thornhill Drive two years ago, she said, she consulted the city's
animal control officers about local regulations and has kept the
animals clean and well-fed. They have to be, she said, to compete
in hobbyists' cat shows she enters more than once a month. Ribbons
from the shows decorate a wall in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, city code enforcement officials said, Lothrop's
feline stewardship is more than just a hobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hobby is not something you get compensated for,'' said Mary
Mastro, an administrative assistant in the occupational licensing
division of the city's Building Department. She said
advertisements, such as those Lothrop has placed to sell the
occasional cat as a pet, put Lothrop in a category different than
the average cat owner.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the scale of sales, Mastro said, ``If you put a
product or a service out there and you get compensated for it,
you're no different from Wal-mart.''
</P>
<P>
   But that argument cuts no ice with Lothrop.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a business,'' she said. ``If it was a business I'd
be making money.'' Even with the cats' value _ up to $1,000 for a
good purebred breeding cat, she said _ Lothrop estimates she loses
$5,000 to $10,000 per year keeping up with the cats' needs. That
includes food, vaccination, veterinary and insurance costs, as well
as cat-show entrance fees and other costs.
</P>
<P>
   Even giving the cats away is expensive, she said, pointing to
the $170-per-cat air fare she's paying to ship them to breeders she
knows.
</P>
<P>
   Lothrop said the city told her to write a letter promising to
get rid of the cats or face the judgment of the city's code board
at its July 8 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Ridsdale, the city's neighborhood services coordinator,
said the board could impose fines of $10 to $250 per day.
</P>
<P>
   But that's nothing compared to the emotional cost of losing her
cats, Lothrop said. She wiped away a tear as she recalled having to
give up a 4-month-old kitten she had to give up recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now it still bothers me that he's gone,'' she said,
surrounded on her couch by stretching, sleeping and frolicking
cats. ``You get attached to these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-15-98 1959E
</P>
