A1069 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPICE-SIDE17-COX     06-16 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICE-SIDE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The pop assembly line
 &HT;    Sidebar to MAKE-SPICE
 &HT;    STAFF
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE MONKEES
</P>
<P>
   HOW THEY WERE MANUFACTURED: Taking a cue from the success of a
certain mop-top quartet, television producers Bert Schneider and
Bob Rafelson put this foursome together in 1965 for a weekly series
_ and the hit records soon followed. Stephen Stills (of Crosby,
Stills and Nash) was among the 400 would-be Monkees rejected during
the auditions.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR STYLE: Goofball rock a la The Beatles in ``A Hard Day's
Night.''
</P>
<P>
   SIGNATURE SONGS: ``Last Train to Clarksville,'' ``Daydream
Believer,'' ``I'm a Believer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Village People
</P>
<P>
   HOW THEY WERE MANUFACTURED: Record producer Jacques Morali
wanted a group he could sell to the gay audience, so in 1977 he
recruited a cast of characters: The G.I., The Construction Worker,
The Biker, The Cowboy, The Indian and The Cop.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR STYLE: Gay culture gone mainstream _ with a disco beat.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNATURE SONGS: ``Y.M.C.A.,'' ``Macho Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Menudo
</P>
<P>
   HOW THEY WERE MANUFACTURED: In 1977, Puerto Rican promoter
Edgardo Diaz conceived of this teen group as the ultimate
expression of pre-fab pop: When a band member's voice matured, he
was replaced. The formula still works _ 21 years and 31 albums
later.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR STYLE: Menudo has always followed the latest musical
trend, be it rock or hip hop, but they're basically Spanish
bubblegum.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNATURE SONGS: ``Quiero Ser,'' ``Si Tu No Estas,'' ``Por
Amor,'' ``Donde Esta Tu Amor.''
</P>
<P>
   New Kids on the Block
</P>
<P>
   HOW THEY WERE MANUFACTURED: After losing control of his first
manufactured group, the all-black New Edition, composer/producer
Maurice Starr hit upon a new idea for an R&AMP;B outfit: The all-white
New Kids was created in 1984 after Starr auditioned kids in the
Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR STYLE: In Starr's words, ``the Osmonds with soul.''
</P>
<P>
   SIGNATURE SONGS: ``Please Don't Go Girl,'' ``You Got It (The
Right Stuff),'' ``Hangin' Tough,'' ``Step by Step.''
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-15-98 1758E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPICE17-COX     06-16 1686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPICE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make your own prefab pop supergroup
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In ``Spice World,'' that cinematic
celebration of all things Spice Girls, there's a scene that could
come only from the fantasy-filled mind of a Hollywood producer. No,
it's not when the girls discover a bomb on their bus. And it's not
when they wander into the woods and encounter a group of aliens.
</P>
<P>
   It's a flashback sequence that shows a younger, more innocent
Spice Girls putting together their act, determined to make a run on
the pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   As the group launches its first American tour and as ``Spice
World'' makes its way to video stores, it's increasingly obvious
that determination is the only true factor in the Spice Girls'
remarkable success story.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else about the quintet-turned-quartet is
manufactured, from their formation through a classified ad to their
cleverly conceived personas: Baby (Emma Bunton), Posh (Victoria
Adams), Scary (Melanie Brown) and Sporty (Melanie Chisolm). A cynic
might even suggest that the recent departure of Ginger (Geri
Haliwell) was also planned _ a way to stimulate interest in a
musical franchise that's dangerously close to its 15th minute on
the Warholian yardstick of fame.
</P>
<P>
   But Spice Girls fans, all gazillion of them, should take heart:
They're hardly the first to fall under the spell of assembly-line
pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one for every generation. The Monkees were the '60s
and the Spice Girls are the '90s,'' says Rhino Records Media
Director David Dorn, whose label owns the Monkees' catalog. ``Some
of them have real staying power and some don't. The Monkees
continue to make money for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the annals of popular music are filled with manufactured
groups. For every embarrassment like Milli Vanilli _ the duo so
contrived it didn't even sing on its records _ there's Menudo, the
Spanish boy band that's still going strong. Whenever one of its
member gets too old, he's replaced.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the phenomenon is a shrewd lesson in marketing,
of tapping an audience and delivering a product. Having a few good
tunes doesn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing new. Natural-born pop talents of yesteryear _ the
Frank Sinatras and Bing Crosbys _ were ``manufactured'' in a sense,
their images and music shaped for mass consumption. ``You could get
somebody to say Colonel Tom Parker fabricated the phenomenon that
was Elvis,'' says Rhino's Dorn.
</P>
<P>
   But by the '60s, the nature of the business changed. Prefab was
out, soul searching, singer-songwriting was in. Still, not everyone
ached for such wisdom. A lot of folks just wanted to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was born the manufactured group: If the industry couldn't
find bubble-brained musicians with telegenic appeal, it would
create them. The Monkees, put together for a weekly TV series in
1966, were the first to tap into this idea.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every band has followed a similar path. It begins with a
timely concept. In The Monkees' case, a pair of TV executives, Bert
Schneider and Bob Rafelson, wanted to cash in on Beatlemania by
giving the craze a goofy, American slant. With the New Kids on the
Block, a late '80s success, talent-show impresario Maurice Starr
was convinced the time was right to sell R&AMP;B and rap to young white
audiences with a white group.
</P>
<P>
   The target market is typically preteen girls. ``They're good
little consumers,'' says Gary Graff, supervising editor of
MusicHound, a series of record guides. That is, not only do they
buy records, but also T-shirts, lunch boxes, breakfast cereals and
anything else you can slap a picture of a band on.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gow, a communications professor at Alfred University and
advisory editor to Popular Music and Society, also suggests they
have the right naive attitude: ``They don't have the concept of
guilt . . . They can unabashedly embrace something the rest of the
world is calling garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that groups can't be manufactured to suit other markets. The
Village People, brainchild of the late French record producer
Jacques Morali, was targeted at gays when it first broke in the
mid-'70s. It was only when ``Macho Man'' became a surprise AM hit
that the rest of America caught on.
</P>
<P>
   Once the idea and audience are in place, the real work begins.
Auditions are usually held to recruit members. But calling these
talent searches would be a misnomer. Since the groups are largely
conceptual, image is everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted kids who had a raw look, not who looked like
models,'' said New Kids promoter Starr in a 1990 interview. ``As
for ability, I was looking for kids who could catch on and learn
real quick. The kids weren't singers, and they weren't dancers . .
. See, a person doesn't have to have talent. I can give them
talent. It's like a doctor doing a heart transplant.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Diaz, the promoter behind Menudo, prefers to think of
the band members as only one part. ``They sing very well and dance
very well, but they don't have the talent to write songs,'' he
explains from a tour date in Mexico. ``And there are people who
have the talent to write songs . . . It's a team working
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at The Monkees, and Diaz's argument makes sense: Sure, Davy
Jones was cute and Peter Tork was silly, but they were also singing
songs by such brilliant pop stylists as Neil Diamond and Carole
King.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you can't ignore the power of the diverse array of
personalities that make up most manufactured groups. Gow says it's
like casting a TV sitcom. ``You take how in `Cheers,' each
character is a part of our personality, and you can identify in
different degrees with Norm or Sam or Carla,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   The final ingredient is promotion. To a great extent,
``organic'' groups _ the term Graff uses _ are influenced by how
they're sold to the public. But at least they control the product.
A record label may advise the Smashing Pumpkins when to deliver
their next album, but it's up to the band to write the songs. With
manufactured groups, everything is controlled, from the timing of
releases to sponsor tie-ins.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a band like this, it's all about marketing,'' said Johnny
Wright, the manager of the Backstreet Boys, another current
manufactured group. ``That's why we went to all those schools,
performed at school assemblies, and signed autographs for 16- and
17-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   But today's best example of manufactured pop is the Spice Girls.
Here is a melding of concept, audience, image and marketing that
has translated into sales of 20 million copies of their first album
(``Spice'') alone.
</P>
<P>
   The group actually claims it is not pre-fabbed. ``We've had so
many people try to say they managed us, but we've all been in the
music industry for years and we've done it ourselves,'' said Mel
Brown (aka Scary Spice) in a 1996 interview with London's Guardian
newspaper. ``We do everything ourselves; we're completely into girl
power and there's nothing (our) lot can't handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. For starters, the Spice Girls were recruited
through an ad placed by promoter Bob Herbert in 1993. They quickly
dumped him, but then hired another manager, Simon Fuller, the
brains behind Annie Lennox's career. Dubbed ``Svengali Spice'' by
the British press, he's been credited with shaping the group's
``girl power'' aesthetic _ call it Wonderbra feminism wedded to a
dance-pop beat.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who's really in charge, The Spice Girls were an
idea waiting to happen. After years of grungy rock from
male-dominated bands, audiences were ready for something lighter in
tone and feminine in perspective. ``We're in the get-happy half of
the '90s,'' says Graff.
</P>
<P>
   The Spices also took the cult of personality to the max,
compensating for their less-than-amazing voices and dancing
abilities by creating characters with brand identities. The Monkees
simply played the part; the Girls gave them names.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Spices mastered the art of salesmanship. Their
first recording broke in Japan before England to immediately
establish the group's international presence. Their second album,
``Spice World,'' was tied to the film of the same name. And do you
think it's by accident the video comes out just when they're
kicking off their first, all-important American tour?
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance, says Winslow Farrell, author of ``How Hits
Happen,'' an analytical look at popular culture. Such strategizing
is ``absolutely critical to keeping it (the phenomenon) controlled,
but going for a long period of time,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   But Farrell says the key difference between The Monkees and the
Spice Girls is the advent of the Internet. While marketing may play
a big role in a group's success, nothing can replace what he calls
``the conversation'' among fans _ the buzz of excitement that's
created when an act is breaking big. Three decades ago, ``the
conversation'' might have taken place in the schoolyard. With the
Internet, the schoolyard becomes the world.
</P>
<P>
   Don't believe it? Just check out the umpteen Spice Girls Web
sites, where the departure of Ginger is being greeted with the
hysteria normally reserved for the death of world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Spice Girls do, however, share one key element with The
Monkees: a burning need for respect. The Monkees rebelled against
their handlers and went on to play their own instruments and write
much of their own material (not that it was any good).
</P>
<P>
   The Spice Girls already take some songwriting credit (and let
the critics be damned, they're fine tunes). But their real stab at
independence came late last year when they fired Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   But will that be enough to sustain them? Rhino's Dorn is not
sure. ``The Spice Girls were a perfect move for somebody interested
in creating a marketing opportunity. It's not about music.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it's not. It's about fun, the packaged entertainment that
only a child can fully appreciate. Which begs a question: Why don't
they make a Spice Girls for adults?
</P>
<P>
   ``They do,'' says Graff. ``It's called `Seinfeld'.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
