</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-FILES17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alienated by the ``X-Files''? Our guide can help.
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The truth is out there, but you'll have to pay about $7 to find
out what it is.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, ``The X-Files'' has been TV's most dense drama.
NASA flight manuals are easier to decipher than the show's
tough-to-follow mythology.
</P>
<P>
   But series creator Chris Carter promises that answers to many of
the show's long-held alien/government conspiracy theories will be
revealed in ``The X-Files: Fight the Future.'' The $60 million
film, which opens Friday, picks up where May's season finale left
off.
</P>
<P>
   In case you forgot, FBI agents Fox Mulder (David Duchovny) and
Dana Scully (Gillian Anderson) learn that an odd-looking,
12-year-old boy possessing psychic powers may hold the key to
unlocking the mysteries of the X-Files. And in a stunning ending,
the dastardly Cigarette-Smoking Man (William B. Davis) snuck into
Mulder's office, stole his sister's file and calmly burned down the
cabinet containing all the cherished X-Files.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Fight the Future'' is one of the summer's most
anticipated movies, there are risks involved. Will people who don't
watch ``The X-Files'' go see the movie? If they do go, will they
get it?
</P>
<P>
   If Carter makes the film too simplistic, the hard-core fans will
gripe. If ``Fight the Future'' is neck-deep in confusing history
and mythology, non X-Philes are likely to throw their popcorn at
the screen. (It's been reported that scenes explaining the
abduction of Mulder's sister were cut because it was considered too
confusing for nonfans.) Somehow Carter must please two very
distinct groups.
</P>
<P>
   In case you're one of those casual viewers or a confused
die-hard fan, we're going to tell you everything you need to know
to get you through the movie.
</P>
<P>
   1) What are ``The X-Files''?
</P>
<P>
   The files are a batch of unsolved FBI cases on paranormal or
unexplained phenomena. Some of them involved vampires, a spooky
serial killer who emerged every 30 years to eat human livers, and
deadly alien parasites. But our alien-battling duo's chief goal is
to determine the truth about extraterrestrial life.
</P>
<P>
   2) How did Scully and Mulder get together?
</P>
<P>
   Mulder was a star FBI profiler who helped nab a notorious serial
killer. But instead of pursuing a stellar career in the Bureau,
Mulder chose ``the basement office with no heat,'' where the FBI
stashes the X-Files. Scully has an impeccable medical background
and once taught at the FBI's training academy. She was partnered
with Mulder to spy on him and discredit his controversial work.
</P>
<P>
   3) Why does Mulder care so much about aliens?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to hypnotic regression, Mulder is convinced that his
sister, Samantha, was abducted by aliens when they were kids.
</P>
<P>
   4) Why is Mulder so skeptical now?
</P>
<P>
   After killing a Department of Defense operative who was spying
on him, Mulder is told that the whole alien conspiracy is a hoax
that dates back to the days just after World War II. At the time,
generals were desperate to continue fueling the nation's economy
via a military build-up. So the government used the Roswell
incident as an elaborate cover story to distract the public from a
top-secret program involving DNA and bioweapons.
</P>
<P>
   5) But if there is a big alien conspiracy, what is it?
</P>
<P>
   That's the $64,000 question. Apparently we haven't been alone
for a long time. According to ``Fight the Future,'' aliens are the
Earth's original inhabitants. Now, as insurgent agent Alex Krycek
(Nicholas Lea) noted, there's an alien ``war raging.'' There's a
nasty batch of shape-shifting aliens hellbent on colonizing Earth.
But, wait . . . there's also a band of faceless alien rebels
attempting to foil the colonist's plans. But those shape-shifting
aliens have help. They're working with The Syndicate, a group of
middle-aged men who wield more power than the president or any
known government. For helping the aliens populate Earth with
alien/human hybrid clones, The Syndicate is promised it'll become
an even bigger power broker after the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   6) What is the black oil?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the key to the alien's colonization plans. It's lethal
to humans. But is the black oil just an icky, out-of-this-world
virus or the real alien life forms who just use the shape-shifters
to carry out their evil plot?
</P>
<P>
   7) Why are the faceless aliens burning up humans with chip
implants?
</P>
<P>
   Nothing against the humans, of course. But the faceless aliens
quite possibly don't want the colonizing aliens getting information
from them.
</P>
<P>
   8) Have Scully and Mulder ever been romantically involved?
</P>
<P>
   No _ although they both want to. The pouty-mouthed Scully is
prone to serious catty looks whenever another woman dares to look
at her partner. If you looked closely, you could see steam coming
out of Scully's ears when Mulder recently met up with a former
partner (Mimi Rogers). We hear Scully and Mulder almost kiss in the
movie, but a buzzing bee kills the moment. If Carter is smart _ and
we know he is _ Mulder and Scully will never take a quick romp in
the sack. The sexual tension between the two is part of the series'
enduring appeal.
</P>
<P>
   OK, got all that? Now, you can handle the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
