June 19-21. (Townsend, AJC freelancer; not for use by New York
Times clients) ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LOTTA-CATS _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ To Johnette Lothrop's way of
thinking, the city of Port St. Lucie is telling her to suddenly
quit her abiding hobby and kick 20 of her closest friends out of
her house. Or else. Along with her husband Robert, Lothrop lives
with about 20 Maine Coon cats. But the city has told her that
anyone housing more than three adult cats is running a de facto
kennel, and no kennels are allowed in residential districts. ``To
put it politely, I'm pissed,'' she said. ``But I can't fight city
hall on my own.'' (Cech, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ ATLANTA _ If you're a twentysomething looking for a
place to settle, check out this month's issue of Swing ($2.95). The
Gen-X mag lists the country's 10 hottest urban centers and the
three best areas in each city to live. And other reviews of this
week's magazine features. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED 6/15.
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ National book sales are
mostly flat, but the mystery field continues to explode. Of course,
success brings changes, some of them bad. American Bookseller
reports that publisher's expectations have grown, and they're no
longer interested in supporting mystery writers who amass only
modest sales, or in sticking with a writer while he builds up name
recognition. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDSHOPPING _ ATLANTA _ Due at retail stores today is
``Imagination,'' the first album of mostly new material in 10 years
from Beach Boy Brian Wilson, who'll celebrate his 56th birthday
Saturday. And petite reviews of recently released CDs. (DeVault,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/15.
</P>
