<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1074 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALAMANDER-LAWSUIT17-     06-16 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALAMANDER-LAWSUIT17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salamander lawsuit arouses suspicion
 &HT;    By Ben Wear
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Back in 1946, when biologists first scooped up and
identified what would become known as the Barton Springs
salamander, they couldn't have known the huge role their discovery
would come to have on the local scene or the potential havoc that
two other amphibian enthusiasts would visit on Austin 52 years
later in defense of the salamander.
</P>
<P>
   The salamander, with considerable help from Alan Hamilton and
Robert Barnhart and a ruling from a federal judge, could cause the
closure of all or most of Barton Springs for the summer, just as
temperatures are soaring over the century mark.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton and Barnhart, who filed a lawsuit last month alleging
that the city is violating the Endangered Species Act by causing
incidental harm to salamanders with its pool cleanings at Barton
Springs, have been identified in various press reports and court
filings as scientists, biologists, herpetologists, as an
environmental consultant (Hamilton) and a sanitation inspector
(Barnhart).
</P>
<P>
   Because their lawyer and a college buddy who has helped them
with the lawsuit work for developers, they've also been identified
_ accused, really _ of being fronts or dupes for developers seeking
to hoist environmentalists on their own legal petard.
</P>
<P>
   In a town where the salamander has assumed the role of aquatic
canary in the coal mine, everyone from Austin's mayor to everyday
lap swimmers have questioned whether Hamilton and Barnhart care
about either the canary or the coal mine. ''I'm as sincere as I can
be, because I'm a nobody, a working stiff,'' Barnhart, a sanitation
inspector for the City of West Lake Hills, said Monday afternoon.
``I think what the city is doing with these things is a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart and Hamilton are credentialed salamander experts, both
having written master's theses in the mid-1970s at Southwest Texas
State University requiring them to capture, preserve and
meticulously measure every possible body dimension of hundreds of
salamanders.
</P>
<P>
   At least one established Austin environmental activist vouches
for the motives of Hamilton, whom he calls a good friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reassured that Alan is not trying to do this for some
monetary or sinister motive,'' says Wayne Gronquist, one of the
founders of the Save Barton Creek Association and a current member
of its board.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bunch, a lawyer for the Save Our Springs Alliance,
discounted Gronquist's endorsement, saying Gronquist had also
developed in the watershed and, with Hamilton's help, built a dam
on Barton Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``His brand of environmentalism is not consistent with most of
our views,'' Bunch said. Gronquist countered that his development
activities don't disqualify him as an environmentalist or as a
judge of his friend's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton and Barnhart's close association with Phil Savoy, an
engineer who works for developers over the Barton Springs
watershed, fuels suspicion that they may be serving an agenda other
than the salamander's preservation.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart said he and Hamilton and Savoy have been friends since
graduate school, when Savoy helped him with the math portions of
his thesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just sort of a consensus of opinion among us that we
ought to do something,'' Barnhart said. They hooked up with lawyer
Robert Kleeman, who filed the lawsuit on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart, acknowledging that he cannot afford to pay the legal
fees if they lose, said, ``We thought it is such an open-and-shut
case, such a flagrant violation of the law that there's no way we
can lose and not recover attorney s fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton told a KLBJ-AM radio reporter in early February that he
would like to see a series of dams upstream on Barton Creek. The
pools behind the dam, in theory, would catch silt before it reaches
the pool. Fewer cleanings with high-pressure hoses and bobcat
tractors _ and thus fewer disturbed or killed salamanders, the
thinking goes _ would be the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pool is nothing more than a silt trap the way the
situation in the creek is now,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the relationship between the purity of Barton Springs
and the salamander's survival is overrated. Salamanders actually
feed on plant life that flourishes in what most people would
consider bad water, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can live in somewhat of a sewer,'' Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 15-minute interview, Hamilton maintained that the
city has not sufficiently studied the Barton Springs salamander's
habits and needs and that the invasive pool cleaning methods are
evidence of that.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who got an undergraduate degree from Texas A&AMP;M,
received a master's from the Southwest Texas aquatic biology
department in 1973. His 66-page thesis focuses on salamanders from
the Blanco River system but not on their survival or eating habits.
His study, as did Barnhart's two years later, is almost exclusively
of the salamander's physique i Barnhart, 56, knew Hamilton at
Southwest Texas State University and even borrowed some of his
salamander samples for his thesis.
</P>
<P>
   Although he works for West Lake Hills as a septic tank and
restaurant inspector, Barnhart lives in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart, according to his resume, got his undergraduate and
graduate degrees at Southwest Texas. He was a building contractor
for 13 years and, from 1978 to 1985, was a sanitarian and then
project director with the San Marcos-Hays County Migrant Project.
In 1995, he was hired by West Lake Hills.
</P>
<P>
   William K. Davis, a retired Southwest Texas biology professor,
advised both Hamilton and Barnhart on their thesis work. He says
Barnhart approached him earlier this year to be an expert witness.
He declined. The lawsuit, he said, is ``frivolous. . . . I don't
approve of what they're doing. ``I'm a great believer that human
beings are the most important animals on this earth,'' Davis said.
``And I don't believe we should put salamanders above human beings.
So I woul Without cleaning, the limestone in the shallow end gets
slick from algae. If Hamilton and Barnhart prevail, there would be
no more cleanings until the city gets a federal permit for
``incidental takings'' of the salamander. That might not happen
until August or September. The city, in a legal brief filed last
week, said that aside from two large areas already closed, no
cleanings this summer would force it to also rope off the shallow
end where young children and families hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Hanson and Watterson said the rock wasn't all that slippery last
week. Then, almost on cue, Watterson's boy Colin executed a
pratfall, landing on the back of his head. He got up a little
dazed, rubbing his elbow, but otherwise OK.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
