<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1076 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CERABINO-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Ginger i
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a while Monday night, I felt what it was like to hold the
answer to the question gripping not only a nation, but perhaps the
entire world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Ginger Spice here?'' they repeatedly asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I answered sagely, knowing for the first time what it
must feel like to be Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   For I had seen the Spice Girls hours before the recent sold out
show at Coral Sky Amphiteatre in Florida, the opening concert of
their world tour, and I had only counted four girls ... Baby Spice,
Scary Spice, Sneezy and Zeppo.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I'll admit it, despite having an 8-year-old daughter, I'm
tragically behind the power curve when it comes to my Spice Girls
knowledge. But I know this. Ginger Spice wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   And neither was Dolly Parton (Spice Rack?).
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry to report that I wasn't able to find the official
story on Ginger Spice's recent defection from the band. The various
Spices (shouldn't there be one named Rosemary?) came out before the
show and posed for photos for the press. But we were repeatedly
asked not to dare ask them any questions.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they were still formulating a unified stance on the
India-Pakistan nuclear proliferation question.
</P>
<P>
   To find out about why Ginger quit the band, I had to rely on the
screaming horde of pre-teen girls in the audience to fill me in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Spice kept yelling at her,'' explained Samantha Galvis,
12, of Sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to tell her how much her fans are missing her,''
said her cousin, Jana Grounds, 10, of Lake Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should all just invite her out to dinner,'' said Jana's
sister, Alyssa.
</P>
<P>
   On another blanket in the lawn area, the Ginger Question was
being discussed by three soon-to-be third graders from Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody will be as cool as Ginger,'' said Katherine Ronan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear she's getting her own act,'' her friend Samantha Shoup
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should get her back by apologizing and stuff,'' Kylie
Bellisari said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, I was told that Ginger wanted to get spicier than the
other girls would allow. Then there was another girl that pinned it
on Posh Spice, who apparently is getting married. Or is that Sporty
Spice?
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend said that if you're sitting in the front row, you
can take Ginger's part in the show,'' Cara Axelrod, 8, of Davie
told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I heard,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the straight story on the Spice Girls is about as tough
as ... well ... about as tough as getting the straight story out of
a group of young girls.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-hour before the show, hundreds of them were
streaming to the edge of the grassy lawn, screaming as they saw a
limousine full of what appeared to be Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fake Spice Girls,'' announced Andi Wandt, 10, of Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you know they're fake?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell,'' she said. ``I know everything about the Spice
Girls. I even know their heights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, ``and did you know that Baby Spice went to
jail?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. She was naked in front of the Prince. Or the Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I heard,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to finally hear the Spice Girls, the thousands
of little girls who had waited and sweated, and waited and sweated
some more, let out the screams they had been saving for what seemed
like an eternity.
</P>
<P>
   If Ginger was missed, it was hard to tell at first. But by
intermission, the little girls gathered in clusters, discussing the
enormity of being the first group in the world to evaluate the
Gingerless Spice Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very pretty,'' Jamie Young, 11, of Delray Beach said.
``It's just different without her.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The concert sounds different, but in in a good way,'' her
friend, Madeline Mowery, 11, said. ``But I don't really care what
they sound like, I just miss Ginger not being in the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginger still appeared in the video images of the group that were
displayed as a backdrop to the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't miss her,'' Jamie and Madeline's friend, Brittany
Westbrook, 11, boldly announced. ``She's probably getting married,
or living off her riches.''
</P>
<P>
   I have my own theory. I believe the former Spice Girl is not
really angry at Scary Spice. And, although I'm not really qualified
to opine about the marriage prospects of Sporty, or whether or not
Baby Spice mooned a member of the Royal Family, I do have an answer
for the Ginger Question.
</P>
<P>
   She's getting out of the music business to fly the Space Shuttle
for NASA. Yep, that's right.
</P>
<P>
   She's even getting her own astronaut name.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Space.
</P>
<P>
   Really?
</P>
<P>
   Um... well, that's what I heard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
