<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Only in obsessive Washington D. C., endlessly
stewing in half-scandals and faux scandals, could the admission by
Kenneth Starr that he and his staff have leaked be heard as some
sort of thunderclap. (Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED. Eds: A bonus
column from Tom Teepen.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Flag Day is old, forgotten stuff, and the
observance of the Fourth of July centers mainly on giant sales of
nothing having to do with patriotism and everything having to do
with the filling of cash registers. Howard Kleinberg is a former
editor of the Miami News. (Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-COMMENTARY _ There was a time _ just a few days ago _
that when asked of my hometown, the talk took a long, explanatory
path. No longer, however, is such a long detailed description
needed of my hometown. For my hometown is Jasper, Texas, and most
have formed their own mental image of that little town buried deep
in the dark, brooding woods of East Texas. (Reetz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/15.
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-COLUMN _ Both white and black are at impasse, like spouses
who have had a falling out, neither wanting to give up the
marriage, both hoping the other will come forward in
reconciliation. Two people can live in the same house without
making a home together. Pulitzer winner Michael Skube's weekly
lifestyle commentary. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
6/15.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ Imagine, a bright and dedicated woman leading a
congregation. The next thing you know, Texas will have a governor
with the forbidden chromosomes. When that happens, Baylor
University will obviously be at fault. Mark these words. (Young,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ In a recent column I had the
temerity to candidly notify Vice President Gore that he was full of
baloney. ``Hooking kids up to the Internet is not the universal
remedy for what ails education,'' I wrote. The mail, both ``e'' and
``snail,'' brought yea-sayers with their own take on the problem.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ For a while that night, I felt what it was
like to hold the answer to the question gripping not only a nation,
but perhaps the entire world. ``Is Ginger Spice here?'' they
repeatedly asked. ``No,'' I answered sagely, knowing for the first
time what it must feel like to be Kenneth Starr. For I had seen the
Spice Girls hours before the recent sold out show at Coral Sky
Amphiteatre in Florida, the opening concert of their world tour,
and I had only counted four girls ... Baby Spice, Scary Spice,
Sneezy and Zeppo. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
