<HEADER>
A1082 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Human contact might be the answer, not computers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Schuett
</P>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. In a recent column I had the temerity to
candidly notify Vice President Gore that he was full of baloney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooking kids up to the Internet is not the universal remedy
for what ails education,'' I wrote. Then I sat back and waited for
Bill Gates,
</P>
<P>
   AOL, or at least the CIA to put a tap on my e-mail and maybe
even set up surveillance on my snail-mailbox. But that's not what
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the mail both ``e'' and ``snail,'' brought yea-sayers
with their own take on the problem. A reader in Spokane writes:
``'Gore hyping
</P>
<P>
   a general protection fault' appearing in our local Spokesman
Review was excellent. I hope a copy went to Gore. I'll send mine.
The 'E-Rate' (the
</P>
<P>
   hidden levy) is what Gore instigated on our phone bills.''
</P>
<P>
   A school board member in Vermont pleads for perspective. ``I
just finished reading your commentary titled `Computers are not
teachers' in
</P>
<P>
   the Rutland Herald. I am a school board member and chairman of
our district school board. I applaud your commentary and only wish
that more
</P>
<P>
   board members, teachers, politicians, parents and taxpayers felt
the way you do. I am fighting a losing battle here in Vermont in
trying to keep
</P>
<P>
   computers in perspective. Whenever I voice my concerns I am
labeled a reactionary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reassuring to find out that I am not alone in thinking
that computers are not going to `fix what's broke' in our schools.
Even
</P>
<P>
   though, I am afraid the train is moving and nothing will stop
it, it is comforting to know that others are as concerned as I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Eaton, a teacher in Snohomish, Wash. e-mails: ``Right on.
After thirty years in the classroom at junior high I learned the
value of
</P>
<P>
   human contact. Computers are a great editing tool and number
organizer, but they offer no `hands in the soil' satisfaction. Who
values the
</P>
<P>
   garden more? Is it the gardener or the person who hires the
gardener?
</P>
<P>
   ``I taught math for sixteen years and came to realize the memory
destroying power of the calculator in a young student's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Calculators are great work savers for those who understand the
math, but they cannot enhance any understanding. Far too many of my
students
</P>
<P>
   became `math crippled' when faced with doing their own
calculations. The students' attitudes became a `let's just get (it)
done' mind set....
</P>
<P>
   Many students cry out for personal interaction and educators
give them a machine. It is no wonder so many students lack the
interpersonal skills
</P>
<P>
   needed for working in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript, Mel admits: ``Spell checkers sure help
borderline spellers like me. I appreciate them because of my
struggle to learn to
</P>
<P>
   spell.'' But he wisely asks, ``Is the real learning in the
struggle as well as the accomplishments?''
</P>
<P>
   Karlheinz Halter in Torrance, Calif. writes thanking me for my
``thoughtful article'' in the Long Beach Press-Telegram. ``Most of
our
</P>
<P>
   so-called leaders are not yet really aware that `The Internet
can't replace a good teacher'. Parents,'' he states, ``have given
up on their
</P>
<P>
   duties (and rights) by using television as a replacement for
nourishing care, and now...educators are replacing `manual labor'
and dedicated
</P>
<P>
   personal attention with yet another electronic gimmick to pacify
curious youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense,'' he warns, ``tells us (and Paine did too) to
think, and to be careful, what we accept as truth, and also to be
sure we
</P>
<P>
   understand its meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   From Manhattan, Kan., John Morrill responds to excerpts from a
teacher's letter I quoted in an earlier column on the built-in
</P>
<P>
   shortcomings of a school system ``teaching to the test
(proficiency).''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the teachers you quote reflect your views,'' he writes,
``then we share in common concerns such as empowering teachers,
(about) raising
</P>
<P>
   standards while avoiding competency testing, (about) teaching to
the tests, and (about) feel-good stuff that administrators and
school
</P>
<P>
   shrinks like to boast of that has turned teaching into a
farce.''
</P>
<P>
   There we have it folks. We're concerned, we care, but too many
of us, I'm thinking, keep quiet about it. That's no way to change
things.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Lucy's advice to Charlie Brown: ``It's the squeaky
wheel that gets the grease.''
</P>
<P>
   So get in there and NAG! Demand your very own squirt of WD-40.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
