<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1083 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Commentary: A woman pastor, heaven forbid
</P>
<P>
   By John Young
</P>
<P>
   C.1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I'd never thought of it before, but I should have
worried about Baylor University's influence on this city when I
first noticed that it had street lights.
</P>
<P>
   I realize that most cities have them, even though there's no
biblical mandate for street lights. But most cities are dens of
wickedness and beyond saving. Waco _ surely Waco could have been
spared these forces of the night.
</P>
<P>
   There are references to ``light'' and ``lamps'' in the Good
Book, but nothing literal and electrified like street lights. And
for good reason. Light streets at night and someone will walk on
them. It is foretold.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for the telephone and electric lines that link our
despoiled city. Link homes with phone lines and you'll have gossip
and plotting. Share electricity and people will be up all night
doing who-knows-what in Waco. And the fact is, gossip aside, we
don't know what. And it's Baylor's fault.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's unfair to blame Baylor for every corrupting influence
in our city. But reading the words of a Southern Baptist Conference
official, to some conclusions we are impelled to jump.
</P>
<P>
   The official is Dr. Richard Land, president of the SBC's Ethics
and Religious Liberty Commission. He was sharing with a (IT)Dallas
Morning News(RO) reporter recently his disappointment that Waco,
specifically Waco's Calvary Baptist Church, was where the first
woman in Texas had been appointed senior pastor _ Julie
Pennington-Russell.
</P>
<P>
   With apparent sadness, Land acknowledged that Waco is a lost
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised that if it's going to happen, it happens in
Waco, because of the influence of Baylor, which I don't think is a
good influence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not one for conspiracy theories, but Land may have something
there. Even I wrote at the time that Baylor's flirtation with its
first-ever campus dance _ temptation to which it would later cave _
was emblematic of creeping Presbyterianization, a condition that
clearly had befallen all of Texas. After all, I'd just paid to see
the Rolling Stones in the Cotton Bowl and, well, who'd have thought
such seepage would ever exceed Austin city limits?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it happened. And so we are wilderness-cast.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, a bright and dedicated woman leading a congregation.
The next thing you know, Texas will have a governor with the
forbidden chromosomes. When that happens, Baylor will be at fault.
Mark these words.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor will try to deflect blame _ try to claim it's a
university with a scriptural soul. But its refusal to be held by
fundamentalist keepers like Dr. Land, and its treating of
moderation as some kind of virtue, will haunt it, and Waco with it.
</P>
<P>
   If you want further evidence of hard-and-fast rules broken in
this city, look no further than another Baptist church _ Spring
Street Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   Once it was an all-white church which died out. Then it became
an all-black church. Now heirs of the all-white flock and members
of the all-black flock are talking about a relationship that would
include both colors.
</P>
<P>
   As flocks go, there would go the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is wrong to pin any of these developments on Baylor.
Maybe Baylor, like Dr. Land, is standing back with jawbone low as
incessant tolerance and deviation have their way on the citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Land should rest assured, however, that not all of Waco is
so ravaged. There's still rigidity in this city we call home.
There's still inerrancy. There are still backs bowed against that
which man must fear above all: change.
</P>
<P>
   But with light posts and phone lines strung everywhere,
vigilance is costing us some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
