suddenly become legitimate. A six-stop professional skiboarding
tour has been organized for next year; Nick's sponsor, Line
Skiboards of Albany, N.Y., instantly doubled its production staff.
And now a host of entrepreneurs are slouching toward San Diego, in
hopes of emulating Line's smashing success.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth annual Summer X Games will open at San Diego's
Mariner's Point Friday, June 19, offering 10 days of manic
athleticism and unceasing commercialism.
</P>
<P>
   In-line skaters and barefoot water-ski jumpers will flail
beneath the banners of Taco Bell and the U.S. Marine Corps, each of
which paid more than a million dollars to become an X Games ``gold
sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   Spectators will sip free Mountain Dew (thanks to its maker's
gold status) and promoters of fledging sports like mountainboarding
(think skateboarding on dirt) will work the sidelines, trying to
garner inclusion in next summer's X.
</P>
<P>
   While high-risk, attitude-laden extreme sports like
skateboarding might have once been about having fun and busting
free of the confining rules of traditional sports, they are now
increasingly about money.
</P>
<P>
   Mini-industries sprout up around each nascent sport the moment
it's born, and the manufacturers, tour promoters and impresarios of
Web sites like www.snakeboarding.com all desperately need ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   The summer and winter X Games, begun in 1995 and 1997, are by
far the world's best-known alternative-sports festivals. And
because the people tuning in to ingest the games' smorgasbord of
street lugeing to bicycle stunt riding are, quite often, young men
willing to risk their own necks, ESPN holds the power to make a
sport chic.
</P>
<P>
   Consider snowmobiling. When snowmobiling made its debut at this
year's winter X, Men's Journal magazine rhapsodized, ``Forget the
old stereotype of dirty-fingered, chain-smoking rural gearheads.
Snowmobiling has gone sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed quite possible that top snowmobilers would soon be
negotiating million-dollar endorsement contracts. After all, Shaun
White, the nation's foremost 11-year-old snowboarder, has a
publicist _ a fact that is emblematic of how far extreme has
strayed.
</P>
<P>
   The genre of extreme sports takes its cues from early 1980s
California skate punk culture, which proved that you could still be
a gnarly athlete even if you had spiky green hair.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a progenitor of extreme, it is Jay Adams, an almost
mythic Venice Beach skate god who had a shaved head and a tattoo
that read ``Team Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said in a magazine article that he smoked marijuana
voraciously, reveled in fistfighting and hopped fences to ride
empty swimming pools. But he rose to prominence at roughly the same
time as MTV, and it was inevitable that the rebel spirit he
exemplified would be co-opted.
</P>
<P>
   It happened finally in 1993, when Ron Semiao, the program
director for ESPN's hipper offshoot, ESPN2, stepped into a
stationery store looking for, as he described it, ``the Sports
Illustrated of extreme sports.'' To his surprise, there was no such
thing.
</P>
<P>
   But there were scores of specialty magazines catering to
everyone from health-conscious rock climbers to corn-dog-eating
skate rats.
</P>
<P>
   Semiao bought every one of the magazines, and then reflected
that AT&AMP;T, Old Spice deodorant and Ricoh copiers were all using
extreme sports images to advertise to twentysomething consumers. If
he could unify the magazines' myriad subcultures ``from the top
down,'' he thought he would strike gold. So he envisioned the X
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Semiao said he favors sports that ``have a whole culture
attached to them, a specific attitude and a group of people who
live and die for that sport.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose skiboarding, he said, because its 20,000 or so American
practitioners are strong rivals of snowboarders.
</P>
<P>
   But it was ESPN's treatment that made the sport sing to viewers.
The network's coverage in January was wonderful eye candy, a
spectacle replete with splashy graphics, lightning-quick interviews
and even stage direction: ESPN's producers had Mike Nick make his
first-ever attempt at a 1440, a quadruple aerial spin, on his last
run. The announcer crowed, ``Expect the spectacular!'' Nick whirled
and crashed.
</P>
<P>
   It was ESPN at its best. Even more than the Olympics, the X
Games are ultimately about theatrics and bathos. And in the spirit
of the best TV dramas, they deliver poignant moments.
</P>
<P>
   The X moment, as it might be called, is soul stirring yet
somehow subversive. At last summer's games, for instance, we saw
skateboarders thumping their boards axelike on a ramp as the fading
skate legend Tony Hawk twisted through what the announcers deemed
``the greatest run of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all enough to make skeptics like Kevin Thatcher feel sick.
Thatcher is the publisher of Thrasher, a San Francisco-based
skateboard magazine founded in 1981, and a friend of Jay Adams (who
has now retreated to Hawaii, where he repairs surfboards for a
living). He was invited to oversee the skateboarding contests at
the first X Games, but declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV flattens skateboarding into one big ad,'' he said. ``You
can't truly capture it unless you take the TV cameras away, close
off a street and just let the kids go at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thatcher might be right, but he's not about to stop Semiao.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these insider magazines feel a moral obligation to
trash the X Games because ESPN is a large corporation,'' Semiao
said. ``But when I see more kids buying skateboards, and more
skaters doing ads for Pepsi and AT&AMP;T, I think, that's a good thing.
There's nothing wrong with it.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Donahue is a Portland, Ore.-based free-lance writer who
has contributed to Outside and George.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
