<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1249 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAR-TREK-HNS &LR;      06-16 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-TREK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR TREK' BOLDLY INSPIRES GENERATIONS OF TERRANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Also filed in ``e'' category)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SAM HURWITT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It's quite possibly the most famous split
infinitive in the English language: ``to boldly go where no man has
gone before.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice-over mandate that introduces the original ``Star
Trek'' television series _ and, with a slight political correction,
``Star Trek: The Next Generation'' as well _ has proven resonant
enough to support four television series, eight feature films, and
tons of tie-in literature and merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Trek'' is now shown in more than 100 countries, finding a
far wider audience than the original cultish Trekkers (don't call
them Trekkies) of old-time fandom. Travel writer Jeff Greenwald of
Oakland, Calif., made it his mission to find out why.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald, whose quests have led him through the spiritual
twists and turns of ``Shopping for Buddhas'' and to circumnavigate
the globe in ``The Size of the World,'' has tired of making the
personal the global, and has turned his eyes to the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said everything I have to say about travel in `The Size of
the World,''' Greenwald says, ``so I'm moving now to writing
science. And it seemed like it would be a wonderful transition to
write a book about `Star Trek' _ which is about traveling to begin
with _ and to go around the world talking to people who are
obsessed with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Future Perfect: How Star Trek Conquered Planet Earth,''
Greenwald talks to fans as well as Trek writers and actors, rocket
scientists and terran luminaries like Kurt Vonnegut, Arthur C.
Clarke and the Dalai Lama, about the show's appeal. He lurks on the
set of ``Star Trek: First Contact'' and attends a Klingon wedding
in Germany, following the warp signature of the Starship Enterprise
to the ends of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked people, `What is it about this American vision that's
so compelling for you?' And what I heard from people in Hungary,
Italy, and even in India, is that this is not an American vision,''
Greenwald reports. ``Now, it's certainly true that the original
`Star Trek,' which was born out of the Cold War Kennedy years, had
a very specific agenda in promoting truth, justice and the American
way. But with `The Next Generation' and later forms of `Star Trek,'
the idea of a global consciousness really took hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that over the last 10 years, the presence of
nonthreatening technologies _ like the Internet, like personal
computers _ have really done a lot to create a global culture. And
everybody began to get this sort of vision of the possibility of
peace on a more global scale. `Star Trek' may have its roots in a
very American vision of the future, but I think that it's a
seductive vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald experienced firsthand the draw of the ``Star Trek''
myth during the filming of ``First Contact,'' when he got to stand
on the ship of his boyhood dreams. ``There's no way to really
convey the emotional rush of being on this mythical ship hich
you've grown up with. I thought it would really deconstruct the
experience to stand in the transporter, to walk onto the main
bridge _ and show me it was all just plywood and plastic _ but it
didn't have that effect. And I think that's a tribute to the depth
to which this show has gotten under our skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transporter has been around for 32 years. The idea of warp
drive, of a phaser _ these things have been around longer than many
of the people watching the story have been alive. They grew up with
them as a part of their culture, and they're no more or less real
than the pyramids, in terms of people having actually seen them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that I was more disappointed visiting the actual
pyramids, and seeing them surrounded by Coca-Cola stands, than I
was visiting the deck of the Starship Enterprise, which was every
bit as fantastic and otherworldly as I'd ever dreamed it would be.
It resonated with me much more deeply. It was my mythology.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons so many people look to _ or at least look at
_ ``Star Trek'' is the shows' relentless optimism; late Trek
creator Gene Roddenberry posited an idyllic future in which
humankind has eradicated war, crime and poverty at home, and has
set off to explore ``space, the final frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the few television shows that cultivates people's
nobility instead of their flaws,'' Greenwald affirms. ``You're
bringing out the whole quest of sentient beings as a noble quest,
and one in many respects that we're all on together.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think that's why `Star Trek' has lasted so long: It
somehow convinced people that this trip is real, that it's not just
positing a possible future. It's a possible future that's in our
reach if we get over certain hurdles in society. And many see it as
a goal: Loads of engineers who now work in NASA are there because
they watched `Star Trek' as kids and want to build these things
they saw on TV. They want to be part of that process of making this
thing come true.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The connection between the space program and ``Star Trek'' is
one that Greenwald makes much of; he sees the series as a kind of
surrogate space program _ which may explain its ho-hum reception
and early demise in 1969. ``At that point we're in the middle of
the Apollo program, Neil Armstrong is about to walk on the moon,''
Greenwald explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``People had the real thing; they didn't need this fanciful
macho vision of this captain in this spaceship. The American space
program was one of the most compelling visions that's ever been
given the human race. Like the Crusades, it just captured the
imagination of a whole civilization; but it wasn't about killing
people or converting them, it was about getting out there and
exploring. That stopped short in 1972, after Apollo 17. We left the
moon. We still haven't been back. No one thought that was going to
happen. So `Star Trek' picked up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is that I think that's coming back. There are
all these companies now that are gearing up to launch tourist
flights in orbit, and even translunar flights. So I think there's
going to be a tremendous surge of interest in getting people into
outer space. I think that was reawakened very, very strongly by the
Mars Rover, Pathfinder.''
</P>
<P>
   Might ``Star Trek,'' then, soon be outliving its use as a
surrogate? ``I would like to see that happen,'' Greenwald says. ``I
would like to see our own space program become so exciting and so
inclusive and so international that `Star Trek' seems a pale
imitation, a silly imitation. But I think that `Star Trek' has a
few good years left.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald points to the remarkable longevity of ``Star Trek,''
which lives on in its two current television incarnations _
``Voyager'' and ``Deep Space Nine'' _ with a ninth feature film on
the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 32 years they've managed to stick to an essential formula,
invented by Gene Roddenberry, that is so durable that nothing seems
able to abrade it or wear it down. And the basic premise, of the
ship and the crew boldly going, continues to capture people's
imagination. Go figure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
