   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-MILOSEVIC (Moscow) _ Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic agrees to resume negotiations with a moderate Kosovo
Albanian leader and to stop harassing ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
He stresses, however, that he will not pull out of the area or stop
pursuing ``terrorists.'' By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-U.S. (Washington) _ Steven Erlanger examines the Clinton
administration's response to the Milosevic-Yeltsin talks.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-HYUNDAI (Tokyo) _ The founder of Hyundai drives 500 cows
across the border into North Korea in an effort to further
reconciliation on the divided peninsula. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-MISSILE (Tokyo) _ North Korea declares that it will
continue to develop missiles and sell them abroad, flatly rejecting
informal U.S. suggestions that it curb its missile program. By
Nicholas Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments in the investigation
by Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr into allegations of wrongdoing
by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   CLARENCE-THOMAS (Washington) _ Supreme Court Justice Clarence
Thomas has been formally disinvited to the annual meeting of the
nation's largest black bar association. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE (Los Angeles) _ After years of halting
steps, the National Park Service is just beginning to develop as a
national historic site the abandoned remains of Manzanar, a
Japanese internment camp that housed 10,000 Japanese-Americans,
most of them U.S. citizens, who were brought here in the hysteria
that followed Pearl Harbor. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   NANNY-VERDICT (Boston) _ Massachusetts' highest court upholds
the reduced conviction and sentence of British au pair Louise
Woodward, clearing the way for her to return to England.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-PAIN-STUDY (Washington) _ As hospital stays grow
shorter, more elderly patients with cancer are spending their final
days in nursing homes. Now, the largest study ever to be conducted
on these patients raises troubling questions about their care,
finding that many are severely undertreated for their pain and more
than quarter of those who complain of pain are not treated for it
at all. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   GRAMMYS (New York) _ The Grammy Awards are moving back to Los
Angeles. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   NY-AUTO-RULING (Albany, N.Y.) _ The State Court of Appeals rules
that an automobile manufacturer is liable in an accident case
because it failed to install air bags in its cars at a time when
the safety devices were available, but not mandated by law. By
Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-PRISON-PORN (Newark, N.J.) _ Hearing in federal court on
judge's order temporarily blocking a New Jersey law that bans
sexually explicit literature and other material from the state
prison housing chronic sex offenders. By Robert Hanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Code f)
</P>
<P>
   VOICE-RECOGNITION-TECH (Undated) _ The spread of
voice-recognition technology will have long-range effects on the
U.S. work force and in how Americans communicate with businesses
and customer-service relations. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-WORKPLACE (Osaka, Japan) _ Ever so gently, corporate Japan
is trying to lessen its reliance on lifetime employment by
tinkering with the rigid, seniority-based salary system that is
standard in Japanese industry. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   GM-LABOR (Detroit) _ Keith Bradsher examines the labor issues
facing General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Hong Kong) _ China has steadfastly refused to
devalue its currency, but the yen's weakness is testing Beijing's
resolve. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-SCIENTIFIC (Undated) _ Boston Scientific buys Pfizer's
cardiovascular-devices unit for $2.1 billion in cash, giving it a
larger piece of the market for devices that keep arteries clear. By
David Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-SURVEY (Undated) _ A survey by the Association of Executive
Search Consultants finds that chief executives and their top
lieutenants are often at odds over issues like succession and
training for the top job. By Adam Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The weekly business travel column.
By Janet Piorko.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was flat
at plus 7 while Nasdaq was up 17. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ At midday, the long bond was down 25/32,
with the yield at 5.64 percent. By Robert Hurtado.
