<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY SOME PARENTS PREFER SCHOOL CHOICE OVER BEDLAM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLONIE, N.Y. _ ``If we could throw them out,'' the teacher was
telling me, ``if they knew we could actually do something to them,
then maybe we could impose some real control in the classroom. But
those kids know that we have to put up with them, and they behave
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   That was only one of more than two dozen calls I received a few
days ago after a column about a kid at Shaker High School who'd
pulled a particularly vile stunt. He'd taken photos of girls in his
suburban Albany school, apparently from the yearbook, used his
computer to graft their faces on shots of naked women in
pornographic poses and put the whole thing on the Internet as a Web
site entitled, ``Shaker Girls at their Best.''
</P>
<P>
   He included false and salacious ``autobiographies'' by the girls
and their e-mail addresses.
</P>
<P>
   The school suspended him for five days and probably will end up
suspending him for the rest of the year. He might also be barred
from extracurricular activities, including graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out in that column that the school can't expel him. By
law, every New Yorker is entitled to a free public education until
age 21. The most any school can do in the face of any offense is
keep the kid out of school for the balance of that school year and
supply the kid with private tutoring at public expense.
</P>
<P>
   If a kid does something criminal, he can be shipped off to state
prison from age 16 on. But, even if a kid commits a felony on
school property and somehow manages to evade the slammer, he can't
be thrown out of school.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason so many people are so much in favor of school
choice. They want tax dollars spent to support their kids in
private schools that do have the authority to throw out
troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's certainly true that a good many people in the school
choice movement have specific and unrelated political agendas _
inflicting pain on teachers unions, for example, or founding
religious schools where other taxpayers would have to pay for the
promulgation of somebody else's personal views concerning God.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also true that a good many people in the school choice
movement _ especially in poorer neighborhoods _ are simply
concerned parents fed up with a system that has as its guiding
principle the proposition that every kid, no matter how disruptive
or resistant to learning, is entitled to a spot in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   That principle is especially repugnant to parents in minority
neighborhoods where education represents a kid's best chance of
escaping poverty and entering the middle class. A poll last year by
the Joint Center for Political Studies, a generally liberal outfit,
shows that African Americans favor school choice by a margin of 56
to 38 percent and that 87 percent of black parents of school-age
children favor it. Latinos favor school choice by 65 to 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Clark, the former high school principal in Paterson, N.J.,
who dealt with disruption simply by ejecting 300 teen-age
troublemakers, told me that he became a hero with the parents of
the other kids _ and a national hero as well _ by flatly rejecting
the idea that the system must save every kid regardless of whatever
damage that kid might inflict on the learning environment.
</P>
<P>
   School choice is scary stuff. Critics say it would destroy the
public school system, and they're probably right. But unless
politicians give public schools the power to expel troublemakers,
school choice will become a more attractive proposition to more
people _ especially the ones who saw ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   And who understand that overloading the lifeboat guarantees that
everybody goes under.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
