<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITING OUT DISHONESTY IN JOURNALISM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: Resending for all needing)   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The perils of the unidentified source made a
splash again last week to the embarrassment of afflicted
publications. Those news media not directly affected should
nevertheless bathe themselves in self-examination.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Glass, a writer for The New Republic, stood publicly
revealed as one who not only made up salient quotes, but entire
persons and even organizations. Fired last month because one of his
articles was run down as fiction by the magazine after an
interested reader probed and complained, Mr. Glass now is said to
have faked wholly or partially more than half of the articles he
wrote for The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he free-lanced for other magazines, all of
which have now severed their connection with him, some having also
found fictive handiwork in what he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Even a news organization, so perfect it could only exist
hypothetically, one where stringent standards were rigidly enforced
without exception, would not be able to protect itself entirely
against a determined fabricator who also has some writing talent.
However, news organizations in real life are not paragons of ideal
thoroughness. Practically speaking, no journalism is error-free
because the system of checking is flawless.
</P>
<P>
   In many places, editing or fact-checking is done on the run and
the result is that a myriad of errors creep into the pages of the
newspapers and magazines, most of them careless, unintentional and
without malice. These don't necessarily wreak lasting harm, unless
sloppiness becomes so pervasive in an organization that consumers
of the work it produces come to doubt its reliability.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of trust. In the real life of a
newspaper, trust frequently hangs in the air, implicitly part of
the dialogue as reporters discuss their reporting with their
supervising editors. So, for example, you would not hire an
applicant for a newspaper job who was not apparently trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Trust is important in getting you in the door. But while trust
is base of the relationship between reporter and editor, it cannot
be permitted to stand in the way of confirming the validity of an
article-in-the-making. It is through this system of check and
balances, that reporters tell their editors and most desirably
their readers, how they came to learn what they write, who their
sources are, and what their sources' self-interest in the
information provided by them might be.
</P>
<P>
   It is at this juncture that journalistic standards most often
don't measure up to the principles that editors fondly offer in
their own defense when enduring public criticism. If editors can't
totally protect their publications against an ambitious liar, we
should do a much better job upholding the rules that are
self-evidently desirable and enforceable.
</P>
<P>
   However, such attention to detail is complicated when the
sources of information are anonymous, as they were in Stephen
Glass's work. Confidentiality of sources is utterly essential to
good journalism. Without it, much of the most serious revelations
that impinge on the public welfare would never see the light of
day. Whistleblowers can suffer great punishment from wrongdoers
they expose.
</P>
<P>
   But sources who are not identified for readers in articles need
to be known by the editors, so that a system of checking can exist
at the point where it is most needed: to determine the plausibility
of assertions made by people, who for apparently good reasons,
decline to have their names associated with the information they
are supplying.
</P>
<P>
   The essentiality of confidential sources does not argue for
their wide use.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons just argued, they should be restricted to those
situations when the issue is serious and there is no other way to
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening now in more and more news media, unnamed
sources are taking an ever larger role in articles that, on their
face, should not require them.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we confront the real problem facing journalism. Even men
and women who are spokesmen for a personage or organization now
appear unnamed in the public prints because they seek to guard
their privacy, an incongruous consideration for a person paid to
take public positions.
</P>
<P>
   Others are permitted to comment on people or their motives
without risking their identity with the public in political and
financial articles especially. Editors should bear down hard on
limiting unnamed sources and on insisting that their reporters
strive to get on-the-record information.
</P>
<P>
   Such insistence would have immediate payback. On-the-record
information, of course, is another important way to check on
information. A named person could attract a response contradicting
an assertion, which may be why some people insist on anonymity. It
is much harder to challenge an account when who said what is not
precisely known.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
