<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BRIDGET JONES'S DIARY &QL; 
 &UR; Helen Fielding (Viking, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   Poor Bridget. Her diary is a rip-roaring success in Great
Britain, but no sooner does it arrive in America than the critics
declare a blood bath. Is it because she's so, like, (begin itals)
shallow? (end itals) Just remember, it's not as if there aren't
lots of women out there just like her. She's thirtyish,
self-absorbed and unlucky in love. This mildly funny novel comes in
the form of a diary (each entry begins with Bridget's weight and
caloric consumption for the day, and proceeds to discuss the length
of her skirts, her family, her vapid social life and her
oft-expressed determination to turn her life around). It got its
start as a weekly newspaper column, became a bestselling book in
England and is soon to be a movie from the makers of ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral.'' A foothold in America has not been so
easy to make, but don't count Bridget out. It's about time
something went her way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PARK CITY &QL; 
 &UR; Ann Beattie (Knopf, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Alison Woodruff is caught in an emotional tornado, with pieces
of her life swirling around her, too dizzying and dangerous for
comfort. There's her boyfriend, who clutches his beer bottles as if
they were grenades and wants her to marry him even though his
fidelity is already in question. There's his 8-year-old son, a
fierce boy whose vulnerability, when it finally surfaces, is a
heart-wrenching thing to see. There's Alison's young student,
Moriko, who starts a fire that forces Alison into a laughable
struggle with Moriko's distressed Japanese uncle. All of this comes
fast and furious in ``Cosmos,'' the first of eight new stories from
Beattie, whose message is that order can and does emerge from
chaos, if only because it has no choice. This book also includes 28
stories selected from Beattie's five earlier collections, many of
them examinations of the precarious and how people learn to live
with it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A BEAUTIFUL MIND &QL; 
 &UR; Sylvia Nasar (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25)
</P>
<P>
   This is a biography of John Forbes Nash Jr., the handsome, aloof
and highly eccentric mathematical genius who went mad at 30,
suffered for three decades with paranoid schizophrenia, then began
a remarkable ``spontaneous recovery'' from his illness and at the
age of 66 won the 1994 Nobel Prize for economics. In the throes of
his illness he had abandoned mathematics and embraced numerology,
religious prophecy and a belief in extraterrestrials. He underwent
drug and shock treatment, dressed oddly, had extramarital
relationships and an illegitimate son and was known to wander the
campus of Princeton University, scribbling bizarre messages on the
blackboards. A bewildered colleague once asked him how he, a man of
reason and logic, could stray so far. ``Because,'' Nash replied,
``the ideas I had about supernatural beings came to me the same way
that my mathematical ideas did. So I took them seriously.'' This is
a wonderful book about brilliance that endured through years of
torment. Nasar, an economics correspondent for The New York Times,
calls it ``a story about the mystery of the human mind, in three
acts: genius, madness, reawakening.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PASS THE BUTTERWORMS: Remote Journeys Oddly Rendered &QL; 
 &UR; Tim Cahill (Vintage, $13)
</P>
<P>
   Tim Cahill once contracted malaria after spending the night in a
stilt house in the swamps of New Guinea among people so primitive
that they used stone tools and were said to practice cannibalism.
He did not get much rest that evening _ sleep does not come easy
when you know your hosts have recently eaten human flesh. Cahill
makes a living doing things like this, and what's more, people
(begin itals) envy (end itals) him. They want his job. They write
and tell him that all the time, but he won't give it up because the
discomfort, the inconvenience and the oddness of it all appeal to
him. Many of the travel essays in this collection (new in
paperback) were written for ``Outside'' magazine, of which Cahill
was a founding editor. They are funny because Cahill passes himself
off as an Everyman, stumbling into exotic places, coming face to
face with cannibals and living to tell the tale. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; G.I. JOE &QL; 
 &UR; John Michlig (Chronicle, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   Don't call him a doll. Even in the beginning, developers of G.I.
Joe found other labels for him because they knew that the president
of Hasbro Toys did (begin itals) not (end itals) want to be in the
doll business. And so the ``d'' word was banished from their
language, even though they used Barbie's boyfriend, Ken, as a model
(he was too soft for a heroic man of action, so they carved baby
fat from his face and beefed up his shoulders and chest until he
looked like a body builder who had seen a bad plastic surgeon). And
the accessories! Ah, the accessories, enough to give even Barbie a
run for her money. But (begin itals) don't call him a doll. (end
itals) Here is the story of the ``action figure'' that would take
hold of the imaginations of a generation of boys and never let go.
With lots of great illustrations and a preface by Don Levine,
former creative director of Hasbro Toys, whose idea the whole thing
was. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
