<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-AUTHOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKERS SUFFER, READERS LAUGH: MISFITS TREK APPALACHIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ On March 9, 1996, Bill Bryson and his friend,
Stephen Katz, set out to hike the length of the Appalachian Trail,
roughly 2,150 miles through 14 states, from Springer Mountain in
northern Georgia to Mount Katahdin in northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson decided to do this for several reasons. For one thing,
the trail went through the town in which he lived, so the idea was
always there, beckoning with deceptive charm. Also, there were
personal advantages to be gained. The trail would make him fit
after years of sloth. He would learn survival skills. He would
become as one with the wilderness. He would be like Daniel Boone,
who, Bryson knew, not only wrestled bears but tried to date their
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he would be manly when he finished, no longer a
cupcake among guys with muscles and Bowie knives. After the trail
he would be able to gaze upon any mountain in the distance and know
with deep satisfaction that it was his for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, none of these things came to pass,'' Bryson says
today from Hanover, N.H., his home since he returned to the United
States after nearly 20 years in England. He was born in Iowa but
traveled in Europe during college and met and married an
Englishwoman. He has been back for three years but still speaks
with a deep British accent, the better to convey the enormity of
the task he and Katz faced together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, we really thought we were just going out for a
pleasant sort of (begin itals) walk,'' (end itals) he says.
``Neither of us had done anything like it before and we had no idea
what we were letting ourselves in for. Everyone else on the trail
was just so much (begin itals) fitter (end itals) than we were.
They didn't seem to have anything like the adjustment that we had
to make, physically or mentally. But I've always suspected that
maybe, deep down, they were feeling the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryson's book, ``A Walk in the Woods,'' is a hilarious account
of his adventures on the Appalachian Trail. It's worth repeating
that salient point: This book is so very funny, and one reason for
it is Stephen Katz. He signed on as Bryson's hiking companion after
the author's solicitations among other friends produced no
volunteers. Bryson and Katz had grown up together in Iowa, but had
pretty much lost touch over the ensuing 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did he come?'' says Bryson. ``There were a number of
reasons. He had just broken up with a long-term girlfriend. He had
been laid off of a job, so he was at loose ends. He was, and is, a
recovering alcoholic, and he thought getting away from temptation
would be a good thing. And then there is the reason anyone goes to
hike the trail. The adventure of it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz, however, was singularly unprepared for the enterprise. He
had traveled with Bryson in Europe one summer when Bryson was in
college (their adventures appear in Bryson's first travel book,
``Neither Here Nor There''), but had returned to Iowa and immersed
himself in drink and drugs, even spending 18 months in prison once
for possession of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   To all appearances he had reformed, but there was still the
little matter of his weight. Like Bryson, he was hopelessly out of
shape, but unlike Bryson he had developed a girth for which all
realistic comparisons were ominous. Zero Mostel, perhaps. Or, as
Bryson suggested to his wife after seeing Katz for the first time,
``Orson Welles after a bad night.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz had never carried a backpack. He had never seen a hiking
trail. And with that, he and Bryson stepped into the woods.
</P>
<P>
   It was hell. It was hell all the way through. At first they
treated each other with a precarious balance of tolerance and
testiness, but later they came to feel mutual affection as they
ventured deeper and deeper into a love-hate relationship with the
Appalachian Trail. Katz displayed a quick, vulgar wit and a
disarming if cantankerous willingness to forge on, hilariously,
through deep adversity. His exploits made great material for
Bryson's book, as Bryson had known from the start that they would.
</P>
<P>
   People ask him all the time if Katz is real, or if he just made
him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to tell you that he's real and I didn't begin to do
him justice,'' Bryson says. ``He truly is one of those
larger-than-life characters. I wrote about him as accurately as I
could but still captured only about 10 percent of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His life and mine had gone in different directions, almost as
opposite as two guys who grew up in the same town can go. I became
a husband and father and wrote books and lived a life of rectitude
and all that. And he led this sort of dissolute life. By the time
we met up again we were, on the face of it, very incompatible. But
he never let me down. That's the finest thing about him. He knew if
he quit he would be abandoning me. We looked out for each other.
The friendship you form with the person you're hiking with,
especially if you have some affection for that person at the start,
deepens in a way that's really quite incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Katz and Bryson walked less than half of the
Appalachian Trail, but came away with strong legs and a deep sense
of what they were capable of doing. Bryson lost 28 pounds, and
while he's not wrestling bears like Daniel Boone, he has enough
confidence to take on one of the celebrities of wilderness lore,
the great Henry David Thoreau himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson calls Thoreau ``inestimably priggish and tiresome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it's true, I think he gets way too much credit, both for
original thought and for having any particular devotion to the
woods,`` he says. ``I mean, his cabin was just like on the edge of
town. He was no closer to the wilderness than I am now, in a town
of 5,000 people. Yes, I think he was a prig. I stand by that.''
</P>
<P>
   He says this with the authority of a manly woodsman, but that is
not the only result of his time on the Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a really good friend,'' he says, ``and I learned a lot
about being a friend, which is important to me. I learned a real
appreciation for the woods and the scale of wilderness, and a lot
about myself and how much I'm capable of doing. I learned how to do
things that really make you feel grown-up. And I can now look at a
big hill or a small mountain, size it up with eyes of chipped
granite, and say, `I can do that.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
