<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS PONDER GIULIANI'S BUNKER MENTALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Has Rudolph Giuliani gone a bridge too far?
</P>
<P>
   During his first term as mayor, Giuliani went after squeegie
men, drug gangs, graffiti vandals, and disorderly criminals
generally _ and the people loved it.
</P>
<P>
   In the first year of his second term, he has, with the same
passion, gone after taxi drivers, jaywalkers, hot dog vendors, and
disorderly behavior generally, and, in New York, where such things
form the fabric of everyday life, that's a different deal
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   With these recent battles in mind, New Yorkers reacted with
mirth or outrage to reports over the weekend that Giuliani has
budgeted $15 million for a 40,000-square-foot, bulletproof,
blast-hardened crisis bunker, stocked with enough food and water to
last a week, and equipped with a secure videophone line between the
mayor and the president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bunker strikes many people as funny because it's the
perfect metaphor for Giuliani,'' observed Fred Siegel, professor of
urban studies at Cooper Union. ``He's in a crisis mode for all
situations, whether it's a crisis or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel is a conservative thinker and, in the past, a strong
supporter of Giuliani and his policies. Now, he is having second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani is one of these politicians, like Clemenceau or
Churchill, who had such outsized personalities that their approach
is inappropriate for ordinary situations,'' Siegel said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among many of Giuliani's allies, Siegel added, ``There's a sense
that his personality is no longer appropriate to the current
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, the mayor has treated every political
dispute as if it constituted a threat to the city _ and has fired
off the rhetorical equivalent of A-bombs in response.
</P>
<P>
   When 1,000 cabdrivers planned to protest new regulations,
Giuliani called them ``taxi terrorists'' and blocked their
demonstration with a police mobilization massive enough to contain
a large riot.
</P>
<P>
   When the speaker of the City Council, Peter Vallone, introduced
an alternative to the mayor's budget, Giuliani didn't just
criticize it _ he mailed a letter to the city's 900,000 homeowners,
warning that if Vallone's budget passes, their property taxes will
go up.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's critics have greeted these tactics with glee. ``I
think he's nuts, or going in that direction,'' chortled former
mayor Edward Koch. ``If he wants to build a bunker only for the
people he trusts, all he needs is a phone booth,'' jabbed Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor and his loyalists view the latest attacks as a
political charade. ``It's a shabby attempt by a group of weak
Democratic candidates to get publicity,'' charged Joseph Mercurio,
a leading Republican consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Giuliani's critics concede the point, to a degree.
Vallone, who is running for governor, is grandstanding way beyond
the norm for a City Council speaker. At least one participant in
the taxi protest did threaten to turn the city into a gigantic
parking lot. And a secure high-tech emergency control center of
some sort might be a good idea for a big city where terrible things
can happen.
</P>
<P>
   However, not just the usual political snipers are raising their
eyebrows. Siegel is one case in point. On a pop-culture level,
Curtis Sliwa, head of the Guardian Angels and normally a
Giuliani-booster, joined his talk-radio co-host, radical lawyer Ron
Kuby, in poking fun at the mayor's bunker for all four hours of
their show last Saturday. They even invited listeners to phone in
ideas for a name-that-shelter contest. (The winner: ``The Nut
Shell.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, this is a combative, activist guy,'' said Myron
Magnet, editor of City Journal, a conservative magazine that
Giuliani frequently cites. ``Sometimes that's good. But we do have
problems with his plan to shut down a lot of hot-dog vendors. We're
big fans of order in public spaces, but we also think the vendors
fill an economic need, for the customers and the entrepreneurs. Any
way that poor, legal immigrants can find a route to the American
dream while filling a necessary economic function _ we ought to
help them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Magnet added, Giuliani has often turned out to be
shrewder than he first appears. ``When he started controlling
pedestrian traffic on 50th Street,'' Magnet recalled, ``I thought,
`Oooh, a bridge too far.' But it worked. I was wrong. He was
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Conn Nugent, director of Citizens' Union, sees the
whole tempest as just another off-Broadway theatrical. ``The fact
that Rudy Giuliani tackles controversies in an idiosyncratic way is
to the taste of New Yorkers,'' Nugent said. ``It's entertaining.
Entertainment has always been a big part of what New York
government is about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS &LR;      06-16 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAY HOME, MICHAEL JORDAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ One and one-tenth second remained in what could
have been the last basketball game of his career. Michael Jordan
was in a position for a finish to top all the other breathtaking,
heart-pounding, mind-blowing finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bulls' ball, at midcourt, late Friday, down two points
to the Utah Jazz in Game 5 of the NBA Finals. After a deflected
pass left less than a second on the clock, the ball _ as it usually
has the good sense to do _ found its way into Jordan's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan took aim from behind the 3-point line and fired a shot at
the jugular of the Jazz. The game, the series, maybe the Bulls'
rollicking romp through the 1990s, would end if the ball went in
the basket. That would make three NBA titles in a row and six in
the decade for the Bulls. America waited to exhale, soaked in
ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   Is anybody other than Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf and general
manager Jerry Krause really ready to say goodbye? Breaking up is
especially hard to do when nothing is broken in the first place.
Still, what a way to go. The gunslinger of all gunslingers,
triumphantly riding off into the night, never to fire another
bullet. Airball. Airball?
</P>
<P>
   There would be no championship celebration for the Bulls that
night. (That would have to wait until Sunday, when the Bulls beat
the Jazz in Game 6 by 87-86.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jordan couldn't seem to stop smiling Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was cute,'' Jordan said, ``just thinking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is 35, and he's still the best player on the planet. He
has only just begun to slow enough for others to occasionally
venture into his stratosphere. On Friday, Karl Malone summoned the
sort of game (39 points, 25 in the second half) that Jordan used to
produce on demand. Jordan, meanwhile, made only nine of 25 shots in
the first 47 minutes and 59 seconds of Game 5. It hadn't been his
night, but that didn't discourage him one bit from trying to seize
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was anticipating a big shot on our side, on their
side,'' Jordan said. ``Everyone thought I could make a shot, and
that's the beauty of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wanted the ball, but no one knew what was going to
happen. That's part of my personality. That's the way things have
happened for me in my career. I was sure everybody was hoping that
would end that way, except for the Utah people. Everybody was
holding their breath.''
</P>
<P>
   To see Jordan embrace the moment, rather than wallow in his
failure, is to understand that he has little choice but to play
again next season.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the fans. Not for his teammates. Not for his coach.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the shoe company with the Swooshtika logo.
</P>
<P>
   Not for more scoring titles, more Most Valuable Player trophies,
more unbreakable records.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the NBA. Not for NBC. Not for Ahmad Rashad.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the fat wallet of Reinsdorf or the fat head of Krause,
who still can't make peace with the notion that Jordan is the alpha
and omega of this empire.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan should come back for Jordan. Jordan owes it to himself to
keep doing this for as long as he can. He owes himself the pleasure
of pushing himself, of creating new challenges for himself. The
next time he walks away from the NBA, it's for keeps. He'll never
find anything that approaches the feeling he gets on a basketball
court, where just about anything still seems possible.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan failed on Friday, failed to deliver the sort of
miracle that he and all earthlings have come to expect, and this is
the first four-letter word that came to his mind:
</P>
<P>
   Cute.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knew what was going to happen _ me, you, no one who was
watching the game,'' Jordan said. ``And that was the cute part
about it. I love those moments. Great players thrive on that in
some respects, because they have an opportunity to decide happiness
and sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happiness was on our side at the time, and sadness was on
Utah's side. Unfortunately, we reversed roles _ sadness in Chicago
and happiness in Utah. That's what you live for.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan should hold on to those moments for as long as he
can. They bring him the sort of happiness that money can't buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
