<HEADLINE>
AN ENLIGHTENING STUDY OF STARR AND THE PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- With too much vehemence, Independent
Counsel-For-Life Kenneth Starr has sought to deny that of which he
was not accused in order to knock over straw men he has himself
erected.
</P>
<P>
   As his ox was being gored last weekend, Starr protested that not
once had he ever leaked so much as a milligram of ``grand jury
material'' and had spoken or authorized prosecutors' conversations
with journalists only to correct misinformation that might
otherwise be disseminated, all for that most noble of purposes, to
``engender public confidence.'' Oh, and what he was doing is not a
crime, and is _ like subpoenas of mothers, bookstores, dead men's
and live clients' attorneys _ par for the course in the
crook-catching game.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, everybody does it, and it's not illegal. I
assume my Clinton-hating friends will note the irony.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to obliterate this nonsense is to spend a couple of
hours with Steve Brill's 30,000-word examination of the press and
Starr in the early weeks of the Monica Lewinsky investigation,
contained in his new magazine about the media, Content.
</P>
<P>
   The meat of the article is definitely not about the leaking of
grand jury material, and the fact that Starr and some of his senior
prosecutors meet with journalists regularly and privately is not
the article's chief focus either. Instead, it is in large part
about the use of the press to put information of dubious veracity
into the public domain without serious double-checking.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, while motive is not a fit subject for speculation, the
timing of these disclosures and their impact clearly worked in
tandem _ investigative information is selectively disclosed close
enough to a grand jury appearance to make it look like the
functional equivalent of it, and it has the effect of adding to the
pressure on Lewinsky to tell the prosecutors what they want to
hear.
</P>
<P>
   Example: While President Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie, was
still a grand jury witness, The New York Times reported
characterizations of what she had to say to ``investigators'' about
supposedly being coached by the president that were disputed by her
lawyers. This was followed by a meeting between two of its
reporters and Starr and his deputy, Jackie Bennett Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Example: A Washington Post story about retired Secret Service
agent Lewis Fox, also at the time of his grand jury appearance, was
hyped to suggest that he could swear Clinton and Lewinsky were once
``alone'' for about 40 minutes. The story ignored other comments in
other venues by Fox that greatly undercut the significance of his
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The practice also extended to unofficial arms of the
prosecutor's office, like New York literary agent Lucianne
Goldberg, the friend and book agent wannabe for Starr's star
witness and secret Lewinsky-taper, Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters were desperate for tidbits from Tripp's tapes
that were being played for Starr's grand jury, Goldberg was one of
the tidbit suppliers. One of her best moves was to tell ABC News of
a Lewinsky dress, allegedly with semen stains on it. Goldberg then
added, out of the blue, that Lewinsky claimed to have saved the
dress.
</P>
<P>
   Brill is one-dimensional in his focus on reporters, neglecting
the unsung and unexamined enablers of modern tabloidization called
editors. He also should have included at least some context, above
all the fact that information-dispensing was routinely practiced to
his shame by Iran-Contra prosecutor Lawrence Walsh, and admitted to
in his memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Brill article is causing the press-prosecutor
wagons to be circled here. The best clue is wildly varied press
coverage (the lead story, for example in yesterday's Los Angeles
Times, with not a word allowed into The Washington Post).
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate context, though, is to be found in the Watergate
analogy Kenneth Starr so valiantly tries to make in his routine
court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Richard Nixon had Archibald Cox fired, the
prosecutor spoke with two members of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, Edward Kennedy and the late Phil Hart, and let slip a
piece of evidence given him months before by a scandal figure,
former Attorney General Richard Kleindienst.
</P>
<P>
   When the information appeared in print, Cox was so appalled he
might have been the indirect source, he turned himself in to the
committee, endured a public thrashing and even a brief bar
association inquiry _ even though he turned out not to have been
the cause of the evidence's disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   That was an ethical man. Today, political investigations so
flout the rules with the press's competitive connivance that they
could not withstand even a moment's scrutiny. That's why the wagons
are circulating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
