<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MONDAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LUXURY TRAIN RIDE TO NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE CARITAS RAIL CAR _ Some things are worth getting up
early for. And that's why my wife and I were at the station before
8 a.m. on a Saturday, waiting to board a luxury rail car that would
take us to and from New York City while serving up relaxation,
scenery, and fine food along the way.
</P>
<P>
   That car was the Caritas, a nicely restored private rail car
that travels 45,000 miles a year, conducting excursions around the
country, some for a day and others for longer periods. Today's trip
was an afternoon and evening in New York, with the Caritas as the
last car on an Amtrak Northeast Direct train.
</P>
<P>
   The train was right on time, meaning that at 7:45 a.m. we
boarded the red-white-and-blue Caritas via its observation platform
for a 4 1/2-hour trip to the city. We were greeted by our host,
Taylor Johnson, who introduced us to the two waiters and cook and
told us a little bit about the 85-foot rail car.
</P>
<P>
   The car began life in 1948 as as the Pierre La Clede, a Pullman
sleeper. Sold to the Canadian National in 1964, it was renamed the
Churchill Falls. Then, in 1983, it was bought by the
Minneapolis-based High Iron Travel Corp. and renamed the Caritas _
a word that sent me scurrying to the dictionary to learn that it
means ``love for all people.'' The new owners transformed the
Caritas into an Art Deco observation car.
</P>
<P>
   The results of that transformation were readily apparent as we
settled into one of the 10 upholstered chairs that line either side
of the lounge area and face large windows. Those side-by-side
chairs are especially appreciated by a tall person: Unlike on some
plane trips, I wouldn't have to travel with my knees forced under
my chin. In addition, there are two glass-topped tables that seat
four people each (usually, the car accommodates 16 passengers on
day trips and eight on overnight journeys). Then comes the
all-important kitchen, followed by versatile rooms in which day
couches convert to upper and lower berths so that the Caritas can
sleep eight guests in three double bedrooms and a master suite.
</P>
<P>
   The overall effect may not have been dazzling, but it was
certainly pleasant. Colorful photos of trains were on the
neutral-colored walls, and there were chrome lighting fixtures and
other Art Deco touches. I especially liked the two vertical glass
etchings, each depicting a maiden in a diaphanous dress holding a
round, bubbling vase, which to my unsophisticated eye appeared to
resemble a frothy cannonball.
</P>
<P>
   But enough glancing around: It was breakfast time. And this
would be no fast food on a plastic tray. We were served fresh
fruit, scrambled eggs, sausages, coffee, and orange juice on tables
set with tablecloths, china, and silverware.
</P>
<P>
   During breakfast and the rest of the trip, we chatted with our
fellow passengers and discovered just who takes such trips. After
all, the cost for this particular journey was $250 _ slightly more
than double what the same trip would cost on Amtrak's express,
reserved coach. So, not surprisingly, many of the Caritas
passengers were lovers of luxury and good food. Others were train
buffs, who seemingly spent the entire trip talking about rail cars
and track systems and other train-related minutiae. (One such
passenger used many feet of videotape photographing the rails
through one of the three circular windows in the door that leads to
the observation car. I occasionally wonder whether he pops up a
batch of popcorn and watches the video nightly.) My favorite
passenger, though, was a man simply trying to decompress. ``I'm
always on the go,'' he said. ``I hope I can take this kind of
slower pace.''
</P>
<P>
   My wife, Linda, and I certainly could. The ride was
exceptionally comfortable, with no sway. We sat and chatted and
read and gazed at surprisingly interesting scenery en route _ swans
(a lot of them) and geese, marshes and marinas, old mills and new
graffiti (including an elaborate drawing of what looked like a
horned snake), and the impressive domed Rhode Island State House in
Providence. In New Haven, we had a 15-minute break while the train
swapped a couple of cars. And although this was the last day of
February, it seemed like a spring break: We were blessed with a
mild, mostly sunny day.
</P>
<P>
   A while later, we got our first view of Manhattan, and, as
always, it was a thrill to see this skyscrapered city. To some, NYC
is simply overwhelming, but to me it is one of the world's most
exciting, vibrant cities. It had been a while since my last visit,
and I was eager to be in the city again.
</P>
<P>
   Some passengers had made plans to catch a matinee at a Broadway
show. But Manhattan is a magnificent show all by itself, and we
spent most of the 5 1/2 hours allotted to us before the return trip
dining, shopping, and mostly just wandering. It was heartening to
see that there is indeed a ``new'' Times Square _ with not a
three-card monte game in sight. Construction seemed to be
everywhere as mini-malls, movies, and other attractions are added
to this revitalized, largely de-sleazed area. ``The Lion King''
musical was sold out at Disney's New Amsterdam Theatre, and the
huge Disney Store next door was filled with people buying items
such as coin banks depicting Minnie Mouse as the Statue of Liberty.
The Virgin Megastore lived up to its name _ it's said to be the
world's largest record store _ and every kind of dining experience
was available, from a big-buck luncheon at an ambience-drenched
restaurant to a hot dog served from a pushcart.
</P>
<P>
   There were so many sights. We wandered down to Grand Central
Terminal to admire its Renaissance-style architecture (our train
had arrived at the less-spectacular Pennsylvania Station, which is
on track to receive a new home at the massive but graceful Farley
Post Office). En route, we paused to watch a pro-Iraq protest march
composed of everyone from college students to aging hippies. We
strolled to the Empire State Building, where I went on the ``New
York Skyride,'' a silly but exciting simulated flight through the
city, while my wife waited and wondered why. Outside, we found
young men selling faux Rolex watches; in days past, they would have
been at Times Square. We strolled through Macy's _ the real Macy's
_ and watched the skaters at Rockefeller Center. The hours passed
pleasantly, even if our feet had begun to protest a bit.
</P>
<P>
   We returned to Penn Station in plenty of time to catch the
Caritas's return trip, which began at 6:05 p.m. Cold drinks
(including cocktails) and light snacks were awaiting us, and so was
a glorious view of New York City at night as the train headed
homeward. Some of us crept out onto the observation platform to
better enjoy the city lights. A line from the musical ``Annie'' _
``I want it to shine like the top of the Chrysler Building'' _ took
on a whole new meaning as we gazed at that illuminated Art Deco
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   Soon it was dinnertime, and we ate in two shifts of eight people
each. The meal was filet mignon, whipped potato, and broccoli in
cheese sauce, served with a good merlot. Dessert was a brownie and
ice cream, or ice cream with chocolate sauce or strawberries, or a
creative combination of all the preceding. Throughout the journey,
in both directions, the always-attentive waitstaff often would ask
if we wanted a drink or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   No one can predict the chemistry of a disparate group of
travelers. This turned out to be a largely quiet group, and most
simply relaxed or conversed for the rest of the trip, which would
end about 11:15 p.m. The Caritas has a stereo aboard (as well as a
public address system, television, and a VCR), and for a while soft
music was played. But to me the real music was the gentle rhythm of
the rails.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CARITIS TRIPS STILL TO COME
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   June 23-24 _ Minneapolis to Chicago, with an overnight stop.
Fare: $995 double occupancy, including the overnight on June 22 and
all meals. Space available for six.
</P>
<P>
   June 29-30 _ Minneapolis to Chicago and return on Amtrak Empire
Builder. Ride on the original route of the Burlington Zephyr and
the Great Northern Empire Builder. Fare: $195 each way. June 29
includes breakfast and lunch; dinner will be served on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   July 2 _ St. Paul-Chicago. The Caritas will be put on the Empire
Builder for a one-way trip. Fare: $195; limit 16.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 29-Sept. 6 _ Explorers' trip. Starts in Spokane and covers
the Blue Mountain Railroad and Palouse River and Coulee City
railroads, with a total of 581 miles. Price to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 9 _ Chicago-Kansas City on Amtrak 303, The Ann Rutledge.
The $395 price includes breakfast, lunch, and dinner as well as
overnight accommodations on Sept. 9 and 10. The cost is $320 for
the trip only.
</P>
<P>
   There are also repositioning trips at lower cost. Prices are per
person/ double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   June 26: Chicago to Minneapolis. $195; includes breakfast and
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   July 5: Minneapolis to Chicago on Amtrak 8, The Empire Builder.
$195; includes breakfast and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   July 11: New Orleans to Chicago behind Amtrak 58, The City of
New Orleans. 12. The $395 cost includes dinner and breakfast and
overnight accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   July 12: Chicago to Minneapolis behind Amtrak 7, The Empire
Builder. $195; includes dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The Caritas is also available for charter _ even for
whistle-stop political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call 612-922-7259, fax: 612-922-8820,
e-mail nona(at)rpcp.mit.edu, or write to High Iron Travel Corp., PO
Box 50116, Minneapolis, MN 55405. In New England, you can also call
781-581-0411. The Internet address is
www.midcoast.com/(tilde)caritas/.
</P>
</TEXT>
