u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNMASKING OF JOE MALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wow! That was some rain.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, my basement was so wet Leonardo DiCaprio was down
there looking for a place to drown. When I finally summoned the
courage to check it, I saw Sigourney Weaver chasing damp aliens.
</P>
<P>
   Man, what a mess.
</P>
<P>
   All over New England people are arguing with insurance agents.
Not me.
</P>
<P>
   What I do is simple: I shut the cellar door and keep it shut
until the end of July. It's bound to dry.
</P>
<P>
   However, I am surprised at the number of residents who are angry
because they feel they didn't get advance warning about the sheer
volume of rain that fell from the sky throughout the weekend. Too
bad they listened to the wrong people: the weather forecasters.
</P>
<P>
   They should have called Joe Malone. He's the formerly amiable
state treasurer now running for the Republican nomination for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   And, it turns out, a major league know-it-all. If we had made an
ordinary phone call to Joe on Friday he absolutely would have told
us to go buy sponges, mops, and wet vacs.
</P>
<P>
   See, there's nothing Joe doesn't know about. Ask him about the
Fells Acres child abuse case getting tossed out last week by a
judge and Joe will immediately tell you it was Scott Harshbarger's
fault.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Joe had barely graduated from high school when
the charges were first brought. Never mind that the sum total of
his legal knowledge comes from watching ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   You got a question? Joe's got an answer.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Joe Malone is a very sad story. His career is proof of
what can happen when political and personal ambition is allowed to
destroy conscience and common sense.
</P>
<P>
   When he started in politics, Malone traded on a nice-guy image.
He had those cute little radio commercials, complete with an
inoffensive jingle, where he'd tell voters he wasn't a career pol,
just a regular fellow who wanted to make things better, serve a
couple of terms, not make a life out of it, just do good, then go
home and mow the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Joe is merely a tool of trash-and-burn consultants. They
get paid a lot of money to turn out slime-ball ads and devise a
sleazy strategy based on the false premise that voters are truly
stupid.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Malone is desperately trying to make Paul
Cellucci's MasterCard bill an issue. Last week, he claimed people
were sick and tired of Cellucci's ``stonewalling'' on the subject
and that the governor's refusal to address his charge-card account
was getting people really mad.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I don't know about you, but it has been a while since I've
seen anyone in the `8 Items or Less' lane at Star Market go
ballistic over how many t-shirts Cellucci charged at the new
Marlboro Mall. But perhaps there is a silent, seething anger out
there that I have not picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Joe clearly decided there is a temporary advantage to be
gained by injecting William Bulger, the president of UMass, into
the campaign. Apparently, his consultants have told Malone he ought
to play off the daily headlines coming out of the hearings in
federal court that revolve around Bulger's brother, the notorious
fugitive who killed JFK, Martin Luther King, invented crack, and
ran the mob in America.
</P>
<P>
   Fire Bulger! That's Joe's stupid pet trick of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger upgraded the university, improved morale, and helped
attract more top high school students to the state system. In other
words _ no matter what you thought of him when he ran the Senate _
the man is doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't matter to the desperate Joe Malone. He's in the
process of a scorched-earth campaign aimed at satisfying his own
Yuppie self-absorption. He wants to be governor and he wants it
now. And if he can't be the guy, nobody else can, either.
</P>
<P>
   How pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, too, because there was a moment in his career when
Malone seemed to have a few of the things essential to success in
politics: personality, charm, a sense of himself, balance and an
awareness that holding office wasn't worth selling your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Yet look at what's happened. Look at what politics and no
beliefs will do to a guy: He has become a mean-spirited, right-wing
know-it-all who is willing to do, or say, just about anything in
order to get what he wants.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding: If you had called on Friday Joe Malone could have
predicted the downpour because he's got an answer for everything.
But I wonder if he would've seen the lifejacket wrapped around his
campaign as it settles in the cellar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
