<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I BOB' WAS ONE FOR THE SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might just be time to bring Marv Albert back to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   He should get his job back on NBC, largely because his
replacement, ``I, Bob Costas,'' has taken the simple game of
basketball and made it his own pulpit to give views on everything
from looming labor problems in the NBA to the off-the court
behavior of Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   It's the world according to me, ``I, Bob.'' His commentary in
the NBA Finals would have been better if he wrapped a laurel wreath
around his head and wore a toga to let everyone know that ``I,
Bob,'' the all-knowing, all-seeing Greek God of Sports, was in the
house. Not that he played the game or anything. He has made his
name by watching.
</P>
<P>
   Once Costas was glib and smart, calling the games, particularly
baseball, without a lot of adjectives and verbs. But sizzle
replaced substance, and nowadays his colleagues in the booth barely
can get a word in, and when they do, they must hurry because they
know ``I, Bob'' needs the microphone back quick.
</P>
<P>
   Next to him, Costas had Isiah Thomas, a two-time NBA champion,
and Doug Collins, a former All-Star who once coached Michael
Jordan. These color commentators have strengths and weaknesses, of
course, but they had great things to say throughout the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Collins used the TelePrompTer superbly, showing viewers, for
instance, how the referees blew the call by disallowing Howard
Eisley's 3-pointer in the first quarter. Collins circled the ball
at least 8 feet away from Eisley's hand with the shot clock clearly
reading one second.
</P>
<P>
   And Thomas had several good points at the end of the game,
questioning, for example, why Jazz guard John Stockton didn't feed
the ball down low to Antoine Carr when the injured Scottie Pippen
was guarding Carr.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas made another good point when he questioned Stockton's
fatigue. Thomas, as many recall, hobbled downcourt during the
Pistons' championship drives and said he wouldn't come out of games
because of fatigue or injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas and Collins were overshadowed by ``I, Bob,'' who
tried to work three jobs _ studio host, play-by-play announcer, and
color commentator _ at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Jordan was playing, or there's no telling how
many viewers would have turned off their sets. Not even ``I, Bob''
can offset Jordan, and not even in Boston, the most provincial of
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 had an overnight rating of 17.6 here, but the number is
deceiving because the last quarter pulled huge numbers. From
10-10:15 p.m., the neck-and-neck game earned a 23.3 rating. The
next 15 minutes did even better, pulling a 25.2.
</P>
<P>
   But ratings for NBC's postgame show dropped quickly and
substantially, to 13, with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   How many times do we have to listen to Ahmad Rashad or other NBC
sycophants ask Jordan, Bulls owner Jerry Reinsdorf, or any player
if the team will remain intact next year?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, Pippen, and coach Phil Jackson have pulled this act
three straight years, and not once has an NBC interviewer asked a
sharp question like, ``Jerry, are you out of your mind to disband
your team?'' or ``Scottie, how much money would it take for you to
stay?'' The Bulls won't answer questions about their future, so why
should NBC stay chummy with guys holding the NBA hostage?
</P>
<P>
   ``I, Bob'' is becoming almost a parody of himself. Just calling
the game is not enough. Not a single moment is spared his
melodrama. When the genuine dramatic moments arise, viewers are too
numb to feel a sensation. Unlike in baseball, when announcers have
time to spin stories because of the pace of play, basketball is
nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   Good announcers let the game come to them.
</P>
<P>
   Not ``I, Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Albert transcended the sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
