<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEMOCRACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN INSTITUTIONS FACE NEW CHALLENGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ An unfettered press, and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
   With all the hardship and strife that Russians have endured in
the stumbling post-Soviet odyssey, the rise of these two democratic
institutions are often cited as the two clear successes of
President Boris N. Yeltsin's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent murder of an investigative reporter in southern
Russia has served as a reminder that Russian journalists are still
free to say what they want only as long as they do not make
powerful political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   And fair elections? A run of recent election victories by
incumbent governors in Russia's regions has revealed strong-arm
tactics reminiscent of the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin, which relies heavily on the political support of
regional leaders, has responded timidly to both challenges to
Yeltsin's democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has ignored a spate of apparent rights violations
surrounding Sunday's election victory by Murtaza Rakhimov, the
incumbent president of Bashkortostan, a largely Muslim region of 4
million people in central Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Election officials said Monday that Rakhimov took 73 percent of
the vote, while his only competitor, Rif Kazakulov, received just
over 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kazakulov, the forestry minister in Rakhimov's Cabinet, actually
suggested that voters would be better off if the incumbent won.
That fueled suspicions that his candidacy was a cynical ploy to
meet the legal requirement in Russia that all elections have at
least two candidates.
</P>
<P>
   All serious opposition candidates were excluded from the vote
for a variety of technicalites, and local election officials
ignored a decision by Russia's Supreme Court last week to reinstate
them. Few voters in Bashkortostan could find out about this,
though, since the region's only independent newspaper and radio
station had already been shut down, and the radio station's
director, Altaf Galeyev, arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that it was a sham election,'' said Laura
Belin, an analyst on Russian politics for Radio Free Europe-Radio
Liberty. ``Outspoken opponents of Rakhimov were systematically
eliminated from the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Rakhimov's victory is not the first time that a Russian governor
was suspected of staging a landslide. Last October, Yegor Stroyev,
the powerful speaker of the upper house of parliament and the
governor of Oryol Region 300 miles south of Moscow, was reelected
with over 95 percent of the vote after election officials excluded
two potential rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Stroyev was outdone this February by Nikolai Merkushin, the
incumbent president of the Russian republic of Mordovia, who won
reelection with 96.6 percent of the vote. In both regions,
opposition candidates were barred by election officials from
running, and the lone challengers were widely alleged to be
supporters of the incumbents, who entered the races to make them
legal.
</P>
<P>
   Far from protesting the apparent violations, Yeltsin
congratulated both Stroyev and Merkushin on their ``convincing''
victories. Analysts said Rakhimov, a longtime backer of Yeltsin,
can expect the same.
</P>
<P>
   But one regional strongman who has enjoyed the Yeltsin
administration's tacit backing until now, Kirsan Ilyumzhinov of
Kalmykia, was feeling some heat from Moscow Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Saying local authorities ``cannot be fully trusted,'' Yeltsin
Monday called for a full inquiry into the slaying last week of
Larisa Yudina, an opposition journalist in the Caspian Sea region.
Before her death, Yudina was frequently harassed by Kalmykian
authorities for her frequent criticism of Ilyumzhinov, and her
allies have suggested the murder was revenge by the man who firmly
controls all political and economic activity in the region.
</P>
<P>
   What remains to be seen is how far the Kremlin will go to prove
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
