<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO KEY _ AN NO CLOTHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We suppose it had to happen: For the first time, a New York
hotel has found that more men than women locked themselves out of
their rooms in various stages of undress.
</P>
<P>
   According to the fifth annual survey from Novotel New York, 197
men and 114 women found themselves standing in the hallways, locked
out. Eighty-four of those guests were at least partly undressed _
but less than 1 percent of them were women, compared with 50
percent the year before. Other findings:
</P>
<P>
   _Also for the first time, housekeepers reported that women keep
a cleaner bathroom than men. Furthermore, women are better tippers,
use the phone more often, and are more apt to take baths, iron, and
use the hotel laundry and pressing services.
</P>
<P>
   _Men, on the other hand, keep their rooms cooler, order more
adult movies, and are more likely to frequent the hotel bar, order
room service, use the fitness center, and bring home a hotel
``souvenir'' such as a towel.
</P>
<P>
   _Men are more likely to leave socks behind, while women leave
nightgowns and hairdryers.
</P>
<P>
   The top complaints by both genders about New York City are that
it's dirty, expensive, and has rude cabbies. The chief compliments
are that NYC has great theaters, shopping, and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  Which New York City building is tallest: The
Woolworth Building, the Metropolitan Life Building, or the Bank of
Manhattan building? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``And you know your fate is/ where the Empire State is./
All you contemplate is/ the view from Miss Liberty's dome./ And the
Hudson River/ makes you start to quiver/ like the latest flivver/
that's simply dripping with chrome.'' _ from ``It's Nice to Go
Trav'ling,'' written by Sammy Cahn and Jimmy Van Heusen for an
irreplaceable singer named Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of Sinatra: &LR;  A walking tour in New York's midtown area
on June 27 will pass Frank Sinatra's favorite restaurants, the
Paramount Theater site where the singer thrilled the bobbysoxers in
the 1940s, and the Friars, a private theatrical club where Sinatra
held the title of ``head abbot.'' The tour will include anecdotes
about the chairman of the board's singing and acting careers, his
wives, and the Rat Pack. And you can be sure there will be Sinatra
music in the background. The cost is just $5 a person. For
reservations or more information, call Adventure on a Shoestring at
212-265-2663.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Triple thanks: &LR;  John F. Kennedy Airport in New York has the
reputation of being confusing and sometimes hostile. We'll vouch
for the confusing part, but we found anything but hostility when we
missed an international flight a while back and found ourselves
stranded in the city for 24 hours. Although another airline was
responsible for our tardiness, three Delta employees were quick to
help arrange lodging and another flight. We don't know their names
but we do know their dispositions: sunny. So thanks, you Delta
three.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Cozy:  &LR; AMC Theaters has included ``love seats'' in plans for a
25-screen, 125,000-square-foot movie megaplex on Times Square's
redeveloped 42nd Street. Couples will have the option of lifting
the arm between the seats for a cozier viewing experience. But the
theater opening is months away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Museum of the month: &LR;  The Lower East Side Tenement Museum looks
like ... well ... a tenement. The six-story worn brick building at
97 Orchard St. takes you to the years between 1880 and 1919, when
more than 23 million Europeans moved to America, many living in
cramped and crowded quarters such as this building. There are
rotating exhibits and snapshots of tenement life. One apartment,
for instance, illustrates the life of a single German Jewish mother
in the 1880s who worked at home as a seamstress. Another depicts a
room during the Great Depression. For more information, call (212)
431-0233.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Mailbag: &LR;  From time to time, we run examples of fractured English.
The other day, we created some of that fractured English ourselves
when we wrote that the nickname Tootsie Tech applies to the ``Ohio
Pediatrics College.'' It, of course, is the Ohio Podiatrics College
(or, officially, the Ohio College of Podiatric Medicine), and we
like to think the misnomer was merely a typing mistake. (With
thanks to Dr. David B. Alper, president of the Massachusetts
Podiatric Medical Society; Cindy Hoover of Londonderry, N.H.; D.
Burgess of Nova Scotia; and D. Post of somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Of the three, the Bank of Manhattan building, at
927 feet, is tallest. The Metropolitan Life Building is 700 feet
and the Woolworth Building _ the city's original skyscraper _ is
792 feet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
