<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KING _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton meets with Coretta
Scott King and three of her children, Martin III, Dexter and
Bernice, to discuss a commission that would take a new look at the
assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   USCHINA _ WASHINGTON _ The House votes Tuesday on the creation
of a special committee to investigate technology transfers to
China. Sherman
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES _ Sen. EdwardKennedy (D-Mass.) joins Sen. Ron Wyden
(D-Ore.), Reps. John Lewis (D-Ga.), Charles Schumer (D-N.Y.) and
John Conyers (D-Mich.) in a news conference to introduce the Hate
Crimes Prevention Act of 1998. The legislation aims to strengthen
the hand of federal law enforcement in the prosecution of hate
crimes. (Carr, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   LATINO-SPONSORS _ WASHINGTON _ Minority organizations have
traditionally welcomed sponsorship aid from the tobacco and alcohol
industry, but the Latino Council on Alcohol and Tobacco is
announcing Tuesday that it will not do so for the Latino Festival
in Washington next month. Does this mark a shift toward a more
protective attitude among minority groups? (Abulhassan, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   TECH-VISAS _ WASHINGTON _ Immigrants and representatives of
business and pro-immigration groups hold a news conference Tuesday
to press for House passage of a bill to increase the number of
highly skilled workers admitted to the United States. Meanwhile,
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who is pushing worker protection
language in his version of the bill, releases a list of
``tech-dependent'' companies he says have laid off workers
recently. (Marselas, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   POLMONEY-DEMS _ WASHINGTON _ The Democratic party exceeded the
legal spending limit for its 1996 convention by more than $700,000,
according to Federal Election Commission auditors. The commission
has delayed consideration of the audit reports, which were obtained
Tuesday by Cox Newspapers. The commission decided earlier this year
that the Republican Party exceeded the limit for its 1996
convention by $1.7 million. In return for $13.4 million in federal
funds, both parties agreed to spend no outside money on their
conventions. If they don't win appeals, the parties will have to
pay the U.S. Treausry penalties equal to the overpayments. The
audit report on Democrats shows that the bulk of its overspeding
consisted of local and long distance phone bills from the
convention that were paid for by the City of Chicago, headed by
Mayor Richard Daley, and a private Chicago host committee
co-chaired by his brother William, who has since become President
Clinton's Secretary of Commerce. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Armed Services Committee
holds a hearing on the nomination of Daryl Jones to be secretary of
the Air Force. (Joyce, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-HEAT _ Florida temperatures continued to break records
with nary a drop of water in the sky, leaving some farmers,
ranchers and water managers thinking about the dreaded ``D'' word:
Drought. Perhaps just in time, meteorologists at the South Florida
Water Management District say they hope for rain. They don't know
how much it will rain or how long, or if it will augur a normal
summer of daily thunderstorms. But they hope it will cool things
off. (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HEAT _ AUSTIN _ Unless you've been hiding in a meat
locker, you've noticed it's steamin', fry-an-egg-on-the-sidewalk
hot. Time to find a cool spot under the front porch and let your
tongue hang out. (Hopper, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
