<HEADER>
A1315 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMOR-BLOUNT-2TAKES-A     06-16 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMOR-BLOUNT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BLOUNT EDGE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Eds.: ``Arli$$,'' is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILL RIVER, Mass. _ Long before Roy Blount Jr. became a
humorist, back when he was just another graduate student in English
uneasily home for the holidays, his parents asked what he wanted
for Christmas. A book, he told them: ``The Most of A.J. Liebling.''
Liebling, The New Yorker's press critic, boxing aficionado, and
trencherman supreme, didn't have much of a readership in Decatur,
Ga., back in 1963. Even so, Blount's parents managed to find a copy
for under the tree.
</P>
<P>
   The gift soon demonstrated its utility. When Blount's mother
took the opportunity to inquire about his plans, her son pointed to
Liebling's photograph on the dustjacket. ``I want to be like this
fat Jewish man here.''
</P>
<P>
   It is but one episode in a history of mutual bewilderment Blount
describes _ often hilariously, sometimes laceratingly _ in his new
memoir, ``Be Sweet: A Conditional Love Story.'' That book is part
of a Blount boomlet that includes the recently published ``If Only
You Knew How Much I Smell You'' (his text accompanies Valerie
Shaff's dog photos), and the reissue of his 1980 book,
``Crackers.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother's understandable consternation notwithstanding, the
56-year-old Blount has gone a long way toward fulfilling his
youthful aspiration. He is only borderline stocky and continues a
lapsed Methodist, but he has lived up to his role model in one key
respect. Liebling liked to brag that he could write faster than
anyone who could write better and better than anyone who could
write faster. Blount's preeminence among contemporary humorists has
for some time allowed him to boast (even if he's too modest to)
that he can write funnier than anyone who can write smarter and
smarter than anyone who can write funnier.
</P>
<P>
   Blount divides his time between an apartment on the Upper West
Side of Manhattan and a comfortably snug house in this hamlet in
the southern Berkshires. Dandelions dot his yard, and a river runs
through it. True, the river isn't all that big, but then neither is
the yard. ``That's the Konkapat,'' Blount announces with a
riparian-directed wave, savoring the syllables. ``I enjoy saying
that, Konkapat, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   How Blount came to Mill River says something about him _ and how
he came to stay here says even more. When he and his first wife
divorced in 1972, she moved to the nearby town of Monterey and
Blount came here to share custody of their two children. Seventeen
years later, when he divorced his second wife, Joan
Ackermann-Blount, a writer for the HBO series ``Arli$$,''
Ackermann-Blount kept their house and he bought this one a few
hundred feet away. ``I still don't quite understand it,'' he muses,
``but we all manage to pretty much get along and still like each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The children are grown (Blount even has two grandsons, which he
finds a source of personal delight and chronological consternation)
so more often than not he's in New York now. ``I've pretty much
become a weekend person,'' he says guiltily. ``I can work better in
the city. When I get up here I just like to piddle around in the
yard and walk outside. Whereas in the city when I'm in my high-rise
building, in order to get outside I have to get in the elevator,
and say hello to the doorman and the concierge, and then if they
see me going back and forth three or four times an hour they begin
to wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia-bred, Vanderbilt-educated Blount has spent more than
half his life away from the South (in fact, he writes a column for
The Oxford American magazine called ``Gone Off Up North''): as a
grad student at Harvard, as an Army lieutenant, and then, after a
stint on The Atlanta Journal as an editorial writer and columnist,
at Sports Illustrated, followed by the move to Mill River. The
incongruity of his expatriate lifestyle provides frequent grist for
his typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be holding forth about something at, oh, say, the New
York Public Library, and whoever's introducing me will incorporate
the word `redneck' into the introduction and it always throws me.
People still tend to think of Southerners as, well, colorful, and a
little slow and not from around here. It's amazing how people laugh
at you when you take issue at being called a redneck. They don't
mean any harm, but I guess it'll never change. I've never belonged
to any kind of category that anybody feels there's anything wrong
with abusing. Men, Southerners. I kept trying to turn juniorhood
into some kind of class-actionable category, but not even other
juniors take that seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount's name rhymes with (itals)bunt(unitals) and
(itals)punt.(unitals) This is as it should be: Two such relatively
feckless acts evoke the character of a former sportswriter and
lifelong versifier (Blount's best-known poem, ``Song Against
Broccoli,'' reads in its entirety, ``The neighborhood stores are
all out of broccoli/Loccoli'') who as ``a jack of various trades
but primarily a fool by profession'' has made affable bafflement
very much a laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Blount calls himself ``a free-range writer'' (which is
presumably like being a freelance writer only the chicken feed is
harder to come by). He's published 14 books and written for 118
publications, a figure that, as such specificity suggests, he takes
pride in. ``I always have two or three magazine pieces that are
overdue,'' Blount says. ``All my life I've been doing 14 things at
once, and I probably always will.'' His works in progress range
from a fairy tale for HBO's animated series ``Happily Ever After''
to an article about going golfing in Ireland with his pal actor
Bill Murray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
