<HEADER>
A1318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUMOR-BLOUNT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     06-16 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMOR-BLOUNT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 MILL RIVER, Mass.: ... Bill Murray.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the tradition of Robert Benchley, a boyhood idol, Blount is a
performer as well as writer. ``Be Sweet'' includes an exhaustive
list of the network talk shows he's been a guest on (Johnny Carson
once whispered to him during a commercial break, ``So often, comedy
is rooted in sadness''). Blount frequently appears on his friend
Garrison Keillor's ``Prairie Home Companion'' and has had cameos in
Jonathan Demme's ``Married to the Mob'' and ``Philadelphia'' and a
regrettably forgettable 1996 comedy, ``Larger than Life''
(regrettable for Blount since he wrote the screenplay). A one-man
show at New York's American Place Theatre, ``Roy Blount's Happy
Hour and a Half,'' earned glowing reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Blount on stage is pretty much the same as Blount in person: an
energetically gestural talker (body English is one thing, but
Blount's has a drawl, to boot) with a guyishly gruff demeanor that
masks a winning cordiality. The temptation is to call him a
Southern gentleman, except that any such compliment would make
Blount howl (or at least growl) _ nor do Southern gentlemen usually
accessorize tweed jackets with baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking thing about Blount is his manner of speech _
or, rather, the manner of his manner of speech. He's always
qualifying what he says, searching for a better way to put
something, polishing it, editing himself. You'd think you were
talking to a politician, except for the fact it's not loopholes
he's after: It's getting the words (itals)right.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   A free-range writer who freely roams, Blount is about as
miscellaneous as an author can be and not suffer from
multiple-personality disorder. What unites all his work, whether
it's country &AMP; western lyrics or a travel piece about getting
chomped by a piranha-like fish in the Amazon or a manifesto for
``The Singing-Impaired'' (a group Blount forthrightly admits
membership in), is a feverish love of all things lexical.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' he says, laughing, when told he could start an
organization called Language-Users Anonymous, and Blount actually
does belong to the usage panel of the American Heritage Dictionary.
S.J. Perelman excepted, no American humorist has pursued le mot
juste _ or at least le mot juiced _ quite so avidly. It's hard to
think of two more contrasting personas than Perelman's
Yiddish-British manneredness and Blount's down-home (itals)homme
moyen sensual(unitals) (or, if you prefer, Flaubertian good ole
boy); but, for both men, in the beginning was the word.
</P>
<P>
   There is this difference, though: for Blount it's the
(itals)spoken(unitals) word. Back in 1989, discussing the longtime
New Yorker film critic Pauline Kael, a friend and Berkshires
neighbor, he praised her for having ``risen to what is the
distinctive American writer's challenge: which is to create an
eloquent prose style that derives from American speech.'' It's a
description that applies equally well to himself. Far more than
just a very funny man _ which he certainly is _ Blount is a shrewd
and wide-ranging observer of our culture who invariably manages, as
he puts it, ``to get something down on the page while it's still
moving around.''
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``About Three Bricks Shy of a Load'' (1974),
describing a year spent in the company of the Pittsburgh Steelers,
may be the single best volume written about football precisely
because it's as much about aging, race, physicality, and much else
besides as it is about the NFL. ``Crackers,'' an extremely witty
book about the world of Jimmy Carter, has a lot more in common with
W.J. Cash's ``The Mind of the South'' than it does with, say, Lewis
Grizzard, an affinity further demonstrated in the lengthy
introduction and notes for ``Roy Blount's Book of Southern Humor''
(1994). Running through the four humor collections he published
during the '80s is one of the most biting (not to mention amusing)
critiques of Reaganism, and beneath the surface of one of them,
``What Men Don't Tell Women'' (1984) is enough truth, and pain,
about the war between the sexes to make James Thurber or Dorothy
Parker blush.
</P>
<P>
   If Blount has a deep dark secret it's that he's something of a
blusher himself: your basic red-blooded American writer made
slightly uncomfortable by the acuity of his intelligence and the
(dare one say it?) sensitive side of his nature. Intelligence and
sensitivity aren't supposed to be guy things, after all, which is
one thing men (itals)do(unitals) tell women.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Blount's working at it. What makes his novel, ``First
Hubby'' (1990), so beguiling is that all the laughs can't disguise
the fact that what it really is is a love story _ one whose
narrator-hero happens to be named Guy, no less. And then there's
``Be Sweet,'' which Blount has been working at off and on for most
of a decade, ``a book I've always been dreading writing.'' He
clears his throat. ``Writing about yourself is enormously
embarrassing _ that's for starters _ and now I have to go and talk
about it on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more than himself, though, it's his mother Blount's writing
about in the book, and that's where the embarrassment comes in. At
least his persona's only literary _ and it's funny. For Louise
Blount, her persona was through and through and not exactly
something to smile about. She was a character out of '50s Broadway:
a Tennessee Williams soul and William Inge personality cinched into
a Rodgers and Hammerstein manner. ``Climb Every Mountain''? ``Climb
Every Wall,'' was more like it. Both Blount and his sister, to whom
``Be Sweet'' is dedicated, are still trying to come to grips with
their mother's spun-sugar balefulness 17 years after her death.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book makes you laugh, and much of it makes you ache.
The former response is very Roy Blount, of course, and the latter
... isn't. That the book is a departure for him, he concedes. That
it might differ in the impact it has had on him, this he's not so
sure about. Exorcised some demons? Done some emotional processing?
The shoulders shrug, the eyes roll. ``The notion that writing is
therapeutic in any kind of lasting way is a delusion.'' He pauses a
moment, the humorist sneaking up on the memoirist. ``I mean, if
writing were psychologically good for you there would be an awful
lot of sane writers walking around _ and I haven't noticed many.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
