<HEADER>
A1320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMMUNITY-BANKS-ART-B     06-16 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNITY-BANKS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BANKS HOPE TO CASH IN ON COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAINTREE, Mass. _ When Donald C. Olson frets about capital
flight, he is not thinking of an exodus of money from troubled
Southeast Asian banks or of Russian investors who whisk cash abroad
to dodge tax inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Olson is worried about men driving their trucks up to
two trailers on a dusty construction site next to the Bugaboo Creek
steak house _ and stealing his new community bank.
</P>
<P>
   As a hedge against such a scenario, Olson, chairman and chief
executive of Horizon Bank &AMP; Trust Co., a new, pint-sized bank just
south of Boston in Braintree, recently placed two boulders at each
end of the trailers.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled side by side and surrounded by sinkholes and gravel, the
trailers are home to a growing trend in the banking industry _
start-up community banks that see opportunity in a world where
bigger banks are laboring to offer the personalized service that
small-town banks have pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole concept of this bank is the result of the
acquisitions and consolidation that have been taking place over the
last couple of years,'' said Olson, who wore wrinkled khaki
trousers and whose executive trailer suite contained a shovel.
``The small business community is underserved because of the
changes. People are very unhappy with the larger banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Some customers,riled by the service disruptions and higher
charges that often accompany bank mergers, are increasingly taking
their business to smaller banks, according to some industry
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, 54 and his senior officers _ small-town bankers who have
spent their careers at tiny financial institutions _ rose to the
top at their banks only to be squeezed out or thrust into a harsh
new world when their companies were taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Olson left UST Corp, a Boston-based supercommunity bank, in
1997, after it took over The Braintree Savings Bank, where Olson
had been president and chief executive. ``I couldn't find a job. So
I started a bank and gave myself one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation sweeping the nation's financial services
sector and creating ever larger banks is intended to help banks cut
costs and boost revenues. But analysts say the merits of size are
not yet proven. In a world where personal service is valued as much
as a network of automated teller machines, community banks are
finding niche opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a better time to start a community
bank,'' said Alex Sheshunoff, head of Alex Sheshunoff &AMP; Co.
Investment Banking, a consulting firm in Austin, Texas. ``But there
has also never been a worse time. The big banks are increasingly
sophisticated in going after the customer and providing service,
which is the one advantage community banks have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with rising stock prices and good prospects for growth,
many community banks are riding high. At a time when the total
number of US banks is shrinking, more than 200 new banks, all
small, were chartered in 1997, a 27 percent rise from 1996,
according to the American Bankers Association, a trade group in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a booming economy with low inflation, it is not unusual for
some community banks with less than $100 million in assets to swell
to $3 billion in several years, thanks to growing loans to small
business owners. Some of these banks have become acquisition
targets, producing a windfall for their shareholders and for
founders who own lucrative stock options
</P>
<P>
   Small banks are minnows in a world where mergers have begat
whale-sized institutions. But the small fry are legion _ there are
nearly 8,500 small banks in the United States, with a total of $785
billion in assets, according to the American Bankers Association.
By comparison, BankAmerica Corp. and NationsBank Corp., which will
create the country's largest bank when they combine, have a
collective $580 billion in assets. In all, small banks account for
80 percent of the nation's total bank assets yet just 16 percent of
its deposits.
</P>
<P>
   Barbieri points out that small town bankers often live in the
communities where they work. ``We live here; we see our
customers,'' said Horizon's president, James R. Barbieri, who
worked alongside Olson at Braintree Savings Bank but declined to
join. ```Heck,'' he said, ``you're on the soccer field for your
kid's game or at the dump in Hingham, and you're selling accounts
and answering questions.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Olson watched a dozen South Shore banks get bought out
in recent years, he sensed an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1996, unsure of his future at US Trust and hankering to
run a bank of his own, he contacted Barbieri and John A. Fanciullo,
who was then president and chief executive of Quincy Savings Bank,
a community bank in the Boston suburb of Quincy. With his
mother-in-law in Florida for the winter, Olson set up camp in her
empty Boston apartment to draw up a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I said, we can't start a bank in my mother-in-law's
apartment _ we need an office,'' he said. The men decamped to a
building where staffers shared chairs and all the furniture was
borrowed. Under state law, they needed at least $8 million to
launch a bank.
</P>
<P>
   By May 1997 Olson had found 23 investors and $3.2 million. He
submitted his application, won approval, and began plotting an
initial public offering for November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called the local golf club and the Rotary Club. We went
through the telephone book _ any list we could get,'' Barbieri, 42,
said. ``We grabbed the Hingham phone book and said, `these people
live on a wealthy street. Let's send them a letter.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then an investment banker from Josepthal &AMP; Co., an investment
bank and brokerage in New York, sounded a warning. Investors, he
said, were jittery about the effect of Asia's economic crisis on
the US economy and market. They were in no mood for a unproven,
tiny community bank whose loan portfolio and lifeblood could be
devastated by an economic downturn or change in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   By December 1997, Olson had promises for $4.5 million. But many
investors got cold feet. By the holidays, Olson, who had just
bought a BMW, had only $1 million on hand. It took until last March
to raise the rest. The three men rewarded themselves with $125,000
each in salaries and benefits _ a princely sum for small-town
bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The bankers opted to move into a building under construction in
a shopping area next to Bugaboo Creek. Then the edifice morphed
into a three-story project and fell months behind schedule, putting
Olson behind the August deadline by which he was legally obligated
to open his bank or scrap the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Olson panicked. Last month he ordered two trailers.
</P>
<P>
   There were other decisions to be made. The men nearly came to
blows over what kind of logo-emblazoned corporate freebies they
would hand out to customers. ``We had to decide, do we want key
chains, refrigerator magnets, or chip clips for the opening?''`
Olson said. (The other options were band-aid holders, 7-day pill
containers for the geriatric set, and paddle balls.)
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day in the back trailer that serves as executive
offices, Fanciullo, 47, Horizon's chief operating officer, beavered
away on a computer. Outside, concrete pipe sections lay piled up _
industrial innards strewn across gravel. Bulldozers and cranes
resembling giant praying mantises sp? stood idle in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't look at this and say, `A monkey could open a bank,'''
Barbieri said, ``because it couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Horizon knows it faces competition for small business customers
in the region, which is also served by Fleet, BankBoston Corp. and
a handful of community banks.
</P>
<P>
   It may do some advertising, but only on the cable channels. For
now, Horizon has only one branch _ in the front trailer. The bank
offers simple passbook savings and checking accounts. It offers
none of the credit cards, mortgages or investment products that
larger, one-stop shopping banks provide, although it plans to sell
those products through other firms.
</P>
<P>
   What it lacks in breadth and, for now, sophistication, it makes
up for in smiles and friendly service. ``Our customer isn't
high-tech, he's high touch,'' Barbieri said. ``He comes into the
bank three times a week for business or emotional reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the times, Horizon has already refashioned itself.
Originally called South Shore Community Bank &AMP; Trust Co., Olson
chose a new moniker last April when two nearby banks merged and
adopted a name almost identical to that of his bank.
</P>
<P>
   And while he decries the effect of mergers on customer service
and winces at the insult of being downsized, Olson knows the
ineluctability of the changes reshaping the banking world.
</P>
<P>
   ``To grow, we have to establish branches or affiliate,'' he
said. ``Yeah, it could be through a merger. We haven't talked to
people yet or identified a candidate. But it's an option.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
