<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY CELEBRATES ITS 100TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York City is having a weekend to remember. After all, you
only celebrate being 100 once in a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   The ``NYC 100: Centennial Weekend'' June 18 through 21 will be
celebrated in every borough and neighborhood as the city marks its
historic consolidation of 1898 into the New York City of today.
There will be hundreds of free events, spectacular fireworks,
walking tours, a parade, and a garden party.
</P>
<P>
   Centennial Weekend will also launch the NYC 100 Walking Tour
Festival with 21 tours that will be offered every weekend through
July 18 in all five boroughs. On June 20, there will be walks of
the political strongholds on both sides of the river sponsored by
The Museum of the City of New York; on June 21, visitors can step
back in time to ``meet'' the congregants at the Eldridge Street
Synagogue in 1898, and at the Richmond Hill Historical Society in
Queens there will be a walking tour of Victorian Vernacular
architecture, followed by a Victorian picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning June 21 and continuing through Aug. 30 (except July 4
weekend), the New York HistoricalSociety will sponsor Central Park
History Walks on Sundays at 2 p.m. For information and
reservations, call 212-873-3400.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, simultaneous fireworks in all five boroughs will be
set off beginning at 9:30 p.m. The display will be 24 miles wide
and is intended to set a new record for the widest geographic
pyrotechnical display. Doing the display will be the famed Grucci
family, who first came to New York through Ellis Island in 1870.
</P>
<P>
   And, ``New York is Free'' on June 21, when more than 100
institutions waive their admission fees or offer special free
events as a gift to the city _ a great opportunity to explore the
cultural and historic treasures of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Centennial Summer will also include Battery 4th of July Blues
Festival at 3:30 p.m.; Music at Castle Clinton with Arlo Guthrie on
July 9; Luna, July 16; John Pizzarelli Trio on July 23; Mavis
Staples with a tribute to Mahalia Jackson on July 30; O'Neill by
the Sea Festival, July 13-24 at 12:30 p.m.; and the Downtown Dance
Festival, Aug. 30-Sept. 3. For information on these events, call
the Conservancy for Historic Battery Park at 212-566-6700.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on all events, call 212-877-8984 or check
www.nyc100.org on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Museum scene
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opening June 25 at the New York Historical Society (2 West 77th
St., telephone 212-873-3400) is Kid City, an interactive exhibition
that simulates the corner of West 82nd Street and Broadway in 1901.
Children can open doors in this Upper West Side neighborhood to
find out about residents, peer inside mailboxes to learn how mail
was sent, and take items from store displays to learn about
shopping in the past. Kid City lets young people learn about the
lives of New Yorkers past and present.
</P>
<P>
   The American Museum of Natural History (Central Park West at
79th Street, telephone 212-769-5800) has just opened a permanent
exhibition devoted to what many scientists believe to be the most
pressing environmental issue of our time _ the need to protect the
variety and interdependence of earth's living things. The new Hall
of Biodiversity features ``The Rainforest: A Diorama for the
Twenty-First Century,'' which immerses visitors into one of earth's
richest ecosystems; ``The Spectrum of Life,'' which depicts the
diversity of life on Earth; and a section that regularly updates
the changing state of biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its 30th anniversary, the Studio Museum in Harlem
(144 West 125th St., telephone 212-864-4500) is offering ``The Fine
Art of Collecting African-American Art,'' which showcases the most
important collection of the art of Black America and the art of the
African Diaspora.
</P>
<P>
   One of the city's jewels is the Dahesh Museum (601 Fifth Ave. at
48th Street), featuring late-19th- and early-20th-century European
academic art. The museum, known for having exhibitions never before
seen in the United States will, beginning June 30, feature ``Image
and Text: Orientalist Works on Paper'' from the Permanent
Collection, which has 80 rare works of art. The museum is free and
near major hotels and tourist sites such as St. Patrick's
Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Opening July 1 at the Museum of the City of New York (1220 Fifth
Ave., telephone 212-534-1672) is ``Half Past Autumn: The Art of
Gordon Parks.'' Having overcome poverty and racism to achieve great
acclaim as an artist, Parks draws greatly on his own life and
experiences in his work. More than 200 photographs ranging from
gang warfare, the Black Muslim movement, to high fashion and New
York City street life are on view.
</P>
<P>
   Through Aug. 30, the Morgan Library (29 East 36th St., telephone
212-685-0008) features ``a.k.a. Lewis Carroll,'' which marks the
centenary of the death of the creator (the Rev. Charles Lutwidge
Dodgson) of ``Alice's Adventures in Wonderland,'' one of the
greatest children's books ever written. The collection includes
early editions of Lewis Carroll's books, art, and personal items.
</P>
<P>
   Now through Oct. 4, the Jewish Museum (1109 Fifth Ave. at 92nd
Street, telephone 212-423-3200) is offering the first major
retrospective of artist George Segal in North America in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Music offerings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center, known for its annual festival, July 7-26, is
also featuring three music festivals this summer. A Midsummer Night
Swing, June 24-July 25, features nights of dancing outdoors to
music ranging from the big band to the tango. Top bands are
featured. Mostly Mozart Festival offers its 32d season July 28
through Aug. 24 in Avery Fisher and Alice Tully halls. And from
Aug. 7 through Aug. 30, Lincoln Center Out-of-Doors, a festival for
all, will include music, dance, and family entertainment, all free.
For information on these events, call 212-875-5108.
</P>
<P>
   The Bard Music Festival on the Bard College campus in the Hudson
River Valley will feaure ``Tchaikovsky &AMP; His World'' on the
weekends of Aug. 14-16 and 21-23. For information, call
914-758-3226.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
