<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE ME HOME, AND BRING ME AN ASPIRIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One afternoon last week, my husband phoned to ask, ``So, when
are you coming home?'' But thanks to the magic of Caller ID, I knew
that he wasn't home _ he was still at his office, too. ``You can't
ask when I'm coming home,'' I told him. ``Unless you're already
there, you mean when am I going home.''
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, his workplace is much closer to home than mine, so
he could be forgiven for considering himself practically there, by
comparison. Still, it struck me as suspicious: Was it an extension
of his nonstandard (in my Midwestern view), New York-bred use of
bring in sentences where take would be my choice?
</P>
<P>
   Come, go, bring, take _ surely we can at least agree on which
way is which? Or maybe not. I dug out a letter from Nancy Sutton,
who wrote months ago to beg for support in the bring/take campaign
she's been waging ``since we moved to New England 40 years ago,''
to no avail: ``Now the misuse is spreading,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing mysterious about the basic rule: Take (like go)
denotes motion away from the person speaking, bring (like come)
motion toward the speaker. (Dog lovers and students of fine
distinctions will want to add fetch to this list: Whereas bring
implies motion from the addressee's location _ ``While you're up,
bring me a drink'' _ fetch asks a person or a pup to go find
something and bring it back.)
</P>
<P>
   While some usage arbiters think the distinctions are clear-cut _
or should be _ others point to a vast middle ground of bring/take
uses where either verb is possible, depending on the point of view
of the speaker. ``Don't forget to bring the umbrella,'' say the
Merriam-Webster usage guide editors, means that the speaker is
already picturing herself at the outdoor concert, needing the
umbrella, so it's bring, not take, from her point of view.
</P>
<P>
   But they may be projecting her imagination further than they
need to. Ten minutes before leaving, she might say ``Shall we take
an umbrella?'' But with one foot out the door, the same person
might ask, ``Shall we bring an umbrella?'' _ not because she's
imagining herself somewhere else, but because she's farther along
on the excursion than the umbrella is, and now must bring it along.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has a problem with what to say to a person at your
destination: ``Shall we bring our swimsuits when we come to see you
Saturday?'' But add a third party, someone neither here nor there,
and we have the most contentious bring of all: ``I'm going to see
my brother in Iowa, and I'm bringing him a live lobster.''
</P>
<P>
   The Merriam-Webster folks, a tolerant bunch, think it's up to
the speaker to posit a point of view, and none of the audience's
concern. They approve of ``he brought his family back to
Stockholm,'' which I think should appear only in a Swedish
publication; they condone ``She brought him to a professional
educator,'' which would mean, in my language, that the writer is at
the same institution as the professional educator. Though I
generally share their get-a-life attitude toward overzealous
parsers, in this case I think they're missing a logical point.
</P>
<P>
   Take those live lobsters: If you're talking to someone in your
brother's general vicinity _ house, city, state, depending on your
perspective _ you might well say, ``I'm coming to Iowa, and I'm
bringing my brother a live lobster.'' But if you're going somewhere
_ from your listener's point of view _ surely you should be taking,
not bringing, the lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I expect language to submit to mere logic; I was
hoping, though, that bring for take would turn out to be a regional
variant we could call a charming idiosyncrasy, like frappe and
tonic. But it's not that simple: The Dictionary of Regional English
surveys, done in the '60s, found the ``bring Mary to the dance''
usage among older interviewees in several Midwestern states as well
as among younger ones in New York and Boston. Now, it's everywhere.
Wordsman James Kilpatrick cites examples from sea to shining sea,
though not to condemn them: He has no problem with ``I brought my
car in for a tuneup last week,'' whether in LA or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if we need a vox-pop sampling of our own. Readers,
please fill in the blank below with the usage that seems normal to
you, and send it my way, along with any comments; names aren't
necessary, but please note where you spent your linguistically
formative years.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a pain-free vacation at the beach, be sure to ----- along
plenty of sunblock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
