<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS MADE QUITE A FINAL STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ We all got a good look at the 1998-99 Chicago
Bulls in Game 6 of the NBA Finals Sunday night. Two minutes worth.
It wasn't a pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan was getting a rest. Scottie Pippen was getting
therapy on his back. Dennis Rodman was watching. The only saving
grace for Chicago was that Utah was resting its big guns, too.
Otherwise it could have been even uglier.
</P>
<P>
   It was a brief look into a future that neither Bulls fans nor
NBC wants to contemplate. The mere thought of, ``Please welcome
Toni Kukoc and your world champion Chicago Bulls ...'' echoing
through the United Center next season is anathema to Chicago fans,
not to mention NBC, the official network of the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, it could happen. Jordan talked a lot in the past
tense after his unforgettable, 45-point performance in the 87-86
clincher. Coach Phil Jackson said he thought only something ``out
of left field'' could change things. (Given that owner Jerry
Reinsdorf's idea of a left fielder is Albert Belle, well, you get
the picture.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it should happen. Can anyone endure another season of the
second-guessing, sniping, waffling, and scrutiny that would surely
envelop the club if it reloaded again? Even this season, especially
in the last two playoff series, the famed Last Dance started to
look more like the Aztec Two-Step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if people realize the kind of stress and tension
that we deal with every day of the year,'' Steve Kerr said.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma, of course, is that it appears to be an
all-or-nothing scenario for Chicago. If they all come back, they'll
be favored again. If Jordan retires, Pippen goes elsewhere, and
Jackson does his rain forest thing, you're looking at Vancouver
East.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan doesn't want to play without the teammate he calls his
``twin brother,'' the valuable Pippen. The feeling is mutual. If
Jordan does go, do you think Reinsdorf would empty the vault for
Pippen, to try to maintain some semblance of the dynasty?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's seasonlong contingency of having Jackson return may be
earnest, but it's also probably not cut in stone. Pippen said he
thought Jordan still had five years left _ that may be a stretch,
but no one thinks he doesn't have at least one _ and Jordan's
desire to compete and accept challenges is well-documented.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would view winning another title without Pippen and
Jackson as a real challenge, Jordan said, ``It would be a pretty
big challenge. The question is, do I want to do that or not? That's
the thing that has to be debated. My answer is that there still are
a lot of unanswered questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinsdorf probably could assure another run or two with the same
crew by doing two main things: writing a lot of checks with a lot
of zeroes and reassigning general manager Jerry Krause. Neither of
those is seen to be feasible, especially the latter. Reinsdorf and
Krause are tight and they are both a bit agitated by the imperious
Jackson, who has taken on almost a Nixonian/Rileyesque persona
lately. (We couldn't wait to see whom he was going to blame for the
Game 6 loss had Jordan not saved the day.)
</P>
<P>
   What better, more fitting way for Jordan to go out than the way
he did in Game 6? Two big hoops, including the game-winner. A steal
from Karl Malone, who, as the reputed greatest power forward to
play the game, allowed himself to be stripped in that critical
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he wouldn't mind going out the way he did, Jordan
said, ``If that's the case, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   We may have to wait several months to see how this unfolds.
Jackson's status wouldn't be affected by a lockout in the NBA; he's
management, although it's easy to forget that sometimes. But all
the key free agents _ Pippen, Rodman, Jordan, Kerr _ will be
affected. By the time the labor situation is resolved, Jordan may
be eligible for the Senior PGA Tour and Rodman may be a
WrestleMania regular.
</P>
<P>
   They have had a remarkable run. They have never lost an NBA
Final series, a truly incredible achievement. They've never even
been extended to a seventh game in their six Finals appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can never see any other team in the future being as dominant
as this ball club has been,'' Pippen said. ``You hate to see it
come to an end. You don't want to see it come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   But it has to sometime. They all seemed to sense that Sunday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
