<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR SHOULD BACK HARSHBARGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On June 25, the Massachusetts AFL-CIO will make a choice _ to
be, or not to be, a force in this year's gubernatorial election.
</P>
<P>
   That is the day when the 400,000-member umbrella organization
for most of the state's major labor unions is expected to endorse
candidates for statewide offices _ including governor. And, based
on some reports, a gubernatorial endorsement by the state AFL-CIO
is not assured.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements will be decided by the group's Committee on
Political Education, which consists of approximately 60 members who
are executive officers.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate needs the vote of two-thirds of the committee. If a
candidate falls short, he or she does not receive this politically
important endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   And that possibility may present a particularly difficult
dilemma for both the state AFL-CIO and the leading Democratic
contender for governor, Attorney General Scott Harshbarger. Despite
his front-runner status and his oft-repeated public pronouncement
that ``labor's agenda is my agenda,'' various sources say he may
not yet have the support of two-thirds of the panel to gain the
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Some committee votes are expected to be cast for the two other
Democratic contenders, former state Senator Patricia McGovern and
former US Representative Brian Donnelly. But it is not likely that
either will get more votes than Harshbarger, who won the
endorsement of the Democratic state convention and has a
significant lead in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is more of a possibility that if the panel fails to
reach a two-thirds majority to endorse Harshbarger, then no
candidate will receive its support. And that could be more of a
problem for the union than for Harshbarger. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some committee members are also officers of unions who have
disagreed &UR;  &LR; with Harshbarger on certain issues and are reportedly
reluctant to support him.
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems a few unions have had with Harshbarger: his
opposition to casinos in New Bedford and Springfield. The unions
saw casinos &UR;  &LR; as &UR;  &LR; job providers, &UR;  &LR;  but Harshbarger felt the economy
should not be based on gambling. Other unions felt Harshbarger did
not move fast enough, or was not tough enough, on firms that
violated wage enforcement laws.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, &UR;  &LR;  a few voting members reportedly may vote not only
for Donnelly or McGovern, but also for Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci. The state's chief executive, along with his GOP rival,
state Treasurer Joseph Malone, declined invitations to attend the
recent AFL-CIO forum organized to help determine labor's strongest
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cellucci has &UR;  &LR;  finally given his support to a raise in
the minimum wage, which had already been endorsed by the Democratic
contenders, most labor officials saw his forum absence as a lack of
support for labor's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Harshbarger gave the strongest endorsement of
labor's agenda, which ranged from better wages for working families
to better education for children.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent poll of union households in the Boston Herald
Harshbarger emerged as the clear favorite among the Democratic
candidates for governor. &UR;  &LR; For example, 46 percent of union
households supported Harshbarger for governor, &UR;  &LR; while 10 percent
went to McGovern.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger received 48 percent support among nonunion
households to &UR;  &LR; McGovern's &UR;  &LR;  17 percent . Overall, Harshbarger
received 47 percent of likely Democratic voters, McGovern 17
percent, and Donnelly 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If Harshbarger does not get the committee's necessary two-thirds
vote, it will not be as much a loss for him as it would be for the
AFL-CIO . If there is no AFL-CIO endorsement for governor, the
group, which has reflected organized labor's growing clout in
recent years, could see its image and strength diminished.
</P>
<P>
   One &UR;  &LR;  way to ensure the AFL-CIO will be a winner in the November
election is to endorse the only Democrat who can win _ Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
