<SLUG> BC-NAFTA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH WILL KILL SAN PEDRO RIVER, REPORT CONCLUDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Without new efforts to manage growth and conserve
water, the San Pedro River will dry up, ruining one of North
America's best bird sanctuaries, an international report concluded
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented study by the Commission for Environmental
Cooperation concluded what environmentalists have warned for a
decade: that excessive pumping of underground water will lower the
river enough to kill trees along Arizona's last major undammed
waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The study, done in connection with the North American Free Trade
Agreement, identified the U.S. Army intelligence post at Fort
Huachuca and the adjacent town of Sierra Vista as two of the
culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that the recharge capacity of the regional aquifer
is now being exceeded due to pumping,'' said the report,
``Sustaining and Enhancing Riparian Migratory Bird Habitat on the
Upper San Pedro River.''
</P>
<P>
   The report calls for cutbacks in water pumping on both sides of
the Arizona-Sonora border, an increase in eco-tourism opportunities
and controlled growth in a region where groundwater pumping has
increased fivefold since 1940.
</P>
<P>
   The report was immediately denounced by local government
officials, who resent the idea of an international group _
representing the U.S., Mexico and Canada _ intruding on the affairs
of their community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report hurts,'' said Sierra Vista City Councilman Harold
Vangilder. ``It doesn't tell any of the story and gives ammunition
to the people who would attack Fort Huachuca and this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the report was released, the Arizona Legislature
voted, earlier this year, for a memorial attacking the San Pedro
River study. It asked Congress to ``refuse to ratify or adopt
future treaties that subject the states to international intrusion
or authority over states' environmental matters.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the commission has no regulatory authority and relies
entirely on voluntary self-regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The report maintains that ``the people of the Upper San Pedro
Basin . . . will . . . largely define the future of the riparian
bird habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are also the ones with the most at stake and the most to
lose if this extraordinary habitat is lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Pedro between the Mexico border and Benson was protected
by Congress in 1988 as the nation's first riparian conservation
area. In 1995, it was recognized by the American Bird Conservancy
as the Western Hemisphere's first ``Globally Important Bird Area.''
</P>
<P>
   The report found that it is home to 390 bird species, including
250 Neotropical migratory birds, which move between the United
States and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The report praised water conservation, recycling and recharge
efforts already undertaken by the Army and throughout Cochise
County. However, it warns that these measures are not enough, and
the local citizenry needs to be open to additional actions.
</P>
<P>
   Without local support, a solution is doubtful, the report
stated, ``and over time demand fueled by uncontrolled growth could
overwhelm other measures (already) adopted to address the water
budget deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Block, director of the Montreal-based commission, said his
organization's objective was to develop ways for groups in Arizona
and Mexico to cooperate and find solutions that will keep the San
Pedro flowing, without substantially harming the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It currently is on an unsustainable course,'' Block said.
``Unless a growth management strategy is put in place, (further
expansion) could lock in the water deficits.''
</P>
<P>
   Kieran Suckling, executive director of the Tucson-based
Southwest Center for Biological Diversity, said the report backs up
what environmentalists have said all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report, hopefully, will have settled once and for all the
fact that the San Pedro River is being killed by development,''
said Suckling, whose organization petitioned the commission last
year to do the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficult work is ahead of us now to solve this problem.
Whether any of the local county supervisors and City Council
naysayers will accept any of this is the real question.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Hansen, spokeswoman for Sierra Vista, said the city
government did not support doing the report but will attempt to
circulate it to as many people as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Public meetings are planned next month to solicit public
comment. The report will be formally delivered to a panel of local
and state government officials in September.
</P>
<P>
   The commission was formed under an environmental side agreement
required before NAFTA was signed by President Clinton and ratified
by Congress in 1993. &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
