<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHARM' LACKING AT CHURCHILL DOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything was set up nicely for Silver Charm in Saturday's
Stephen Foster Handicap at Churchill Downs, but then he lost the
race.
</P>
<P>
   Reality, in the form of the victorious Awesome Again, intruded
on the best-laid plans of Churchill officials, who raised the purse
of the Foster from $500,000 to $750,000 to attract last year's
3-year-old champion, and of Silver Charm's trainer, Bob Baffert,
who chose the Foster over the Massachusetts Handicap May 30 and the
Hollywood Gold Cup June 28. Both of those races were spots to face
handicap champion Skip Away.
</P>
<P>
   Off as the 2-5 choice under Gary Stevens, Silver Charm could not
handle Awesome Again, who was getting 14 pounds (127 to 113), in
late stretch, losing by a length to the 5-1 shot ($13.80 to win)
and Pat Day in the time of 1:48 3/5 for 1 1/8 miles. Semoran,
Silver Charm's stablemate, set the pace to the eighth-pole and
managed to finish third under Kent Desormeaux despite bowing a
tendon in the final yards. Semoran was retired Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do enough with Silver Charm before the Foster,'' said
Baffert, who had not started the 1997 Kentucky Derby and Preakness
winner since capturing the Dubai World Cup March 28. ``If I had
known I was going to give away 14 pounds to a good horse, I would
have done more.''
</P>
<P>
   Awesome Again, a 4-year-old son of Deputy Minister, had started
only once this year, winning an allowance race by 7 lengths at
Churchill May 22. However, he was a serious player last year,
winning the Queen's Plate at Woodbine and the Jim Dandy at Saratoga
before running third as the favorite in the Travers. He then
finished fifth in the Super Derby at Louisiana Downs Sept. 28 and
was laid up for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always sorry to see Silver Charm and horses of his caliber
lose, but if we were going to beat him I thought it might be when
he was coming off a layoff,'' said trainer Pat Byrne, who this year
took over Awesome Again from David Hofmans. ``Our horse was fresh
and he had a good race under his belt over the track. We'll
definitely go to Saratoga with this horse. We want to get a Grade I
(the Whitney) for him now.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news for racing fans is that Silver Charm's loss
dropped him behind Skip Away in the race for Horse of the Year and
now Baffert, who has been taunted by Sonny Hine, Skip Away's
trainer, for ducking him, is going to have to stop playing it cute
and come out to fight. Now, Baffert not only is pointing Silver
Charm to a meeting with Skip Away in the Pacific Classic at Del Mar
Aug. 15 but also wants to give his popular gray star, who has never
been worse than second in his career (14-8-6-0), a race before that
as a prep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to find something for him,'' said Baffert, who said
Silver Charm was ``big and heavy'' following his loss. ``I'm
looking everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Matchmaker misses
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the Foster, Baffert turned thumbs down on a $2 million
match race between Silver Charm and Skip Away in late July at
Laurel. The proposal was made by Joe DeFrancis, president of the
Maryland Jockey Club. ``I've talked casually to the connections of
both horses about it and I think that the Skip Away people are very
interested in it, but trainer Bob Baffert is concerned about
running Silver Charm in the heat in the summertime,'' said
DeFrancis. ``At this stage, I don't think there's much likelihood
that it's going to happen.'' ... Semoran, who almost came to the
MassCap before Baffert opted to run him in the Foster, will
recover, but the 5-year-old son of Phone Trick is too valuable to
return to racing. ``He'll be all right,'' said Baffert. ``There was
no bone damage but he will be retired. He'd need a year off to be
able to come back.'' Semoran won the Cornhusker Handicap at Prairie
Meadows and the Kentucky Cup Classic at Turfway Park last year, and
retires with a record of eight wins from 22 starts and more than
$860,000 in earnings ... Byrne also trains Touch Gold, who stopped
Silver Charm's Triple Crown bid in last year's Belmont Stakes when
he was trained by Hofmans, and he's counting on Awesome Again and
Touch Gold to form a powerful 1-2 punch by the fall. Byrne gave up
2-year-old champion and Horse of the Year Favorite Trick and
2-year-old filly champion Countess Diana, both of whom went to Bill
Mott, to become private trainer for Frank Stronach, who owns
Awesome Again and Touch Gold. ``You can tell them that Touch Gold's
trainer will have two for the (Breeders' Cup) Classic,'' said Byrne
after the Foster. Touch Gold, who has not raced since finishing
ninth and last in last year's Breeders' Cup Classic at Hollywood
Park, is working forwardly at Churchill and Byrne expects to get
him a start in July at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Gold' watch time
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Formal Gold, owned by Jack Murphy of Quincy and trained by Bill
Perry, will enter stud at Gainsway Farm in Lexington, Ky., in 1999.
A son of Black Tie Affair, Formal Gold engaged in a memorable
series of duels with Skip Away last year, defeating him in the Donn
Handicap at Gulfstream, the Iselin Handicap at Monmouth, and the
Woodward Stakes at Belmont, while Skip Away turned the tables in
the MassCap and the Suburban at Belmont. Formal Gold suffered a
fracture of the right hind leg while training for the Breeders' Cup
Classic, which Skip Away won, then injured his right front ankle in
April and was retired with a record of 16-8-4-1 and more than $1.5
million in purses. ``Formal Gold is very special to me and we took
our time finding the right farm that will give him every
opportunity to prove himself as a stallion,'' said Murphy. ``We are
very pleased he will stand at Gainsway.'' ... Deputy Commander, who
won the Travers and Super Derby last year, has been retired. The
son of Deputy Minister suffered a small tear in the suspensory
ligament of his right front leg while competing in the Californian
at Hollywood Park May 31. ``It was a great run,'' said trainer
Wally Dollase. ``He was a hell of a horse.'' Deputy Commander, who
also was second in the Breeders' Cup Classic, goes to the breeding
shed with four wins from 13 starts and nearly $2 million in
earnings ... Free House, who was third in last year's Kentucky
Derby, second in the Preakness, and third in the Belmont Stakes, is
training well at Hollywood for his return to the races. Trained by
Paco Gonzalez, Free House, who won the Swaps Stakes at Hollywood
last July but has not raced since finishing sixth in the Super
Derby, will make his '98 debut in either the Triple Bend Handicap
on the Hollywood Gold Cup undercard or in the Bel Air Handicap July
11.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
