<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSAGE TO MICHAEL: BOW OUT NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ He shouldn't come back.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan should walk away for good, leaving us with the
perfect closing line, like Humphrey Bogart talking about the
beginning of a beautiful friendship, or Clark Gable not giving a
damn. Would ``Gone With the Wind'' or ``Casablanca'' be better
movies if the directors had added another scene?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan left on top on the mountain in Salt Lake City Sunday
night. He scored 45 points, carrying an old, wounded team to a
sixth championship in eight years. With his team trailing by 3
points and 41.9 seconds to play, he: 1. scored on a driving layup;
2. stole the ball from Karl Malone; and 3. faked Bryon Russell into
the next century, then swished a 17-foot textbook jumper from out
top.
</P>
<P>
   On what might have been the final shot of his career, Jordan
looked a little like a ballet dancer, extending his right arm and
leaving it out there long after the ball had ripped through the
net. His basket put the Bulls ahead by 1 and shocked the Utah
crowd. I expected lightbulbs to explode all over the scoreboards,
like in the final scene from ``The Natural.''
</P>
<P>
   What more can be achieved if Jordan returns? Scottie Pippen is
as good as gone, and that goes double for coach Phil Jackson. Does
Michael really want to spend his final year(s) trying to carry a
mediocre team all by himself? He did that already. Remember when he
scored 63 against the Celtics in the '86 playoffs _ and lost the
game?
</P>
<P>
   Those early days of Michael seem so far away. He was the third
pick in the 1984 draft. Houston taking Hakeem Olajuwon was
understandable, but Portland's selection of Sam Bowie at No. 2 is
still worthy of a class-action lawsuit by Blazer fans.
</P>
<P>
   There were some doubters and detractors in the early years.
Young Michael could jump out of the gym and had enormous hands
(like Julius Erving) that made the game easier for him. Some
veterans scoffed when he played wearing his own line of sneakers
and Isiah Thomas was one of the East All-Stars who ``froze'' rookie
Jordan out of the action at the 1985 All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Bird's '86 Celtics handed off to Magic's '87-88 Lakers, who
dished it to Isiah's '89-90 Pistons. Then came Michael's time. And
what a time it was.
</P>
<P>
   The ``best ever'' argument is pretty much over. Bird was one of
the last to concede. As late as 1990, he still said, ``People talk
about me and Magic and now Michael. I can tell you who the best
ever was. It's Bill Russell and Wilt Chamberlain. Hell, it's right
there in the book. Look it up. Russell won 11 championships.
Chamberlain averaged 50 points a game over a whole season!''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan didn't win 11 championships, but he won six in eight
years and would have had eight if he hadn't taken two years off for
baseball (or a commissioner-ordered silent suspension for his
gambling debts and associates). Winning six in eight years in a
29-team league (there were 27 when the Chicago run started in
'90-91) seems almost as impressive as 11 in 13 years in an eight-
to 14-team league.
</P>
<P>
   But the absolute best thing about Jordan is his wonderful merger
of hunger and talent. Some guys want the ball but don't have the
skills. There are plenty of players with the ability who don't want
the ball. Jordan always gave us both.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being Phil Jackson. Your most talented player is also
the one who works hardest, plays the best defense, and wants the
ball in the last two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan may go down as the last great American athlete who played
just to win championships. Larry and Magic were like that, but
Shaquille O'Neal isn't. Neither is Antoine Walker. And there's not
a baseball player on the planet who'd choose to win a World Series
if if meant making Donald Fehr unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Michael had a chance to win Title VI in Chicago last Friday but
his buzzer-beating prayer missed everything. This is what he said
after the game: ``I was sitting there, thinking about the whole
thing. I knew I wanted the ball, but no one knew what was going to
happen. Me, you, and no one who was watching the game. I love those
moments. Great players thrive on that because they have an
opportunity to decide happiness and sadness. That's what you live
for. That's the fun part about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the comment of a true champion, and two days after making
the statement, Jordan put himself back in the same position and
delivered the goods like no one before him.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice if Jordan were a tad more political, speaking
out against the high price of Nike shoes and the low price of Nike
wages. It would be powerful if Jordan made gun control his life's
work after his father was murdered with a handgun. But not every
person is political. It was never Michael's way.
</P>
<P>
   To the finish, he gave us a true American sports hero. We didn't
have to know about his private life or tell our kids to be like
Mike. But it was always OK to tell them to play like Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Playing like Mike doesn't mean you have to jump the highest or
be the best. It means you play every day, and get the most out of
what you've got. It means you play for fun, without fear of
failure. And it means you play to win championships.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing more to say and no more ball for Michael to
play. I hope he walks, and leaves us with the perfect finish from
the best there ever was.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
