<SLUG> BC-BOMB-HUNTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRPORT USES MECHANICAL `POOCH' TO SNIFF FOR BOMBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Security officers at the San Francisco
International Airport are using a computerized canine to sniff for
explosives inside luggage.
</P>
<P>
   The airport's ``explosive trace detector'' doesn't look like the
robotic pooches of science-fiction films. Rather, the trace
detector is as drab as its name _ a squarish, blandly colored box
the size of a medium-sized television set. It is so inconspicuous
that passengers ignore it as they stream past security checkpoints
toward aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   All passenger luggage is X-rayed inside standard X-ray machines.
But since late last year, some luggage also has been checked for
organic molecules wafting from any nitroglycerine or other
explosives that might be concealed in luggage.
</P>
<P>
   A security officer sniff-tests luggage by taking a clean,
circular slip of paper and wiping it over the luggage. Then the
paper is inserted into a hole in the explosive trace detector.
</P>
<P>
   Usually within seconds, a light on the computer screen declares:
NO ALARM. That means the luggage is safe.
</P>
<P>
   But occasionally, the computer flashes the word ``NITRO.'' That
means it has detected organic molecules _ chains of carbon atoms
with other atoms attached, such as nitrogen _ characteristic of the
explosive nitroglycerine.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, in all such cases to date at the San Francisco
airport, the passenger has proven to be innocent of evil intent. He
or she is really transporting nitroglycerine, but it's the kind
used in trace amounts to treat heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the device sometimes flags innocent passengers who have
been exposed to organic molecules used for legitimate purposes, as
in farming or construction work, airport spokesman Ron Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The device, manufactured by Lockheed Martin in Manassas, Va.,
also can identify TNT and other common explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it's looking for is any of the atoms given off by an
explosive material. It's like being around an orange: You know the
orange is there because you can smell it a little bit,'' said Bob
Collins, president of the Aviation Crime Prevention Institute in
Hagerstown, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Not all luggage is selected for ``sniffing.'' Airport security
personnel say that passengers are ``randomly'' selected for
sniffing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will not detect a knife,'' said Romila Deo, operations
manager for the checkpoint at the San Francisco airport's Concourse
E.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco airport was the first in the nation to test
the explosive trace detector, Wilson said. The devices cost from
$50,000 to $60,000 each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
