   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COOKING (Undated) _ China, like France, also has a
venerable tradition of haute cuisine. And while expensive French
restaurants in New York can hold their own against many places in
Paris, if you want to move beyond steamed dumplings and stirfrys to
experience the complexity of Chinese banquet cuisine, the
possibilities grow dimmer every year. Critic's Notebook by Ruth
Reichl.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebars:
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-COOKING-MAVEN (Undated) _ Dining with someone who is
Chinese is one way to be served food that is truly superb.
Otherwise, it takes time and effort. But it can be done. Chinese
food mavens have offered suggestions to increase your chances. By
Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HAUTE-CUISINE (Undated) _ During a banquet of whole shark
fin, abalone with goose web and fish maw, scallops and sea conch in
brandy sauce, and minced lobster in lettuce cups, Ken Hom, the man
who tried to put a wok in every American home, was supposed to
discuss the reasons Americans aren't interested in Chinese haute
cuisine_ and in a way he did. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MARKETS (New York) _ New York's dirty little secret is its
dirty little supermarkets. by Alex Witchel.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-ZAGAT-GUIDE (Paris) _ Zagat Survey's first Paris
Restaurant Guide has arrived in newsstands and bookstores here,
introducing French readers to the novel idea that customers can
rate restaurants themselves just as well as Michelin and Gault
Millau's authoritative inspectors. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   BRAILLE-WINE-LABELS (Undated) _ Michel Chapoutier, a well-known
maker and shipper of Rhone wines, has put Braille labels on all his
premium wines, including appellations like Hermitage,
Crozes-Hermitage, Condrieu, St.-Joseph, Cote Rotie and
Chateauneuf-du-Pape. By William Grimes.
</P>
