<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ONE TOLD THE FISH THAT EL NINO'S OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Everybody's been chanting ``Adios to El Nino,''
but the fish in San Francisco Bay and along the Pacific Coast have
been speaking another language.
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions of the end of El Nino by the end of June,
the continuing saga of the biggest ocean temperature tantrum in
history turned up several new bizarre episodes in the past week.
The consequences are making this the story of the 1990s for
California outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The latest series of events started in San Francisco Bay earlier
this month when the bait trawler Johnny T out of Fisherman's Wharf
set its huge net around what appeared to be an acre of schooling
anchovies. When the net was tightened and drawn in, it turned out
that the fish were not anchovies, but adult sardines in numbers
that haven't been seen in the Bay in generations.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, another swirling horde of sardines was spotted
just 100 yards off the beach at Pacifica, another anomaly, and a
pod of 40-foot gray whales moved in right behind them, targeting
the baitfish like giant torpedoes, scooping, breaching and playing
for hours.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, off the Marin coast along the Point Reyes National
Seashore, I've seen the same thing in the past month, the whales
are feeding and frolicking so close to the beach that you could hit
them by skipping a sand dollar across the ocean surface.
</P>
<P>
   When there is something to eat, everybody in town with an
appetite can show up. And so it is now for striped bass, rockfish,
and believe it or not, even albacore and tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Striped bass? Fishing for striped bass has been generally poor
for years. With the sardines in the Bay, though, the bass are
schooling up and corralling them, just like the best days ever of
Bay fishing in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Art Roby was one of the first to find them, at the reefs
just west of Alcatraz, and he took 20 people out on his boat New
Huck Finn. They caught 40 striped bass (2-fish limits) to 21
pounds, 17 halibut to 24 pounds, 3 lingcod and 9 rockfish.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Armand Castagna of the Imagine heard that several San
Francisco Giants were injured, so he called Giants manager Dusty
Baker to go fishing and salved the week by catching 13 stripers to
18 pounds in three hours. Yeah, it's like living in a time machine.
</P>
<P>
   On the beach at Pacifica, there have also been stripers and a
sprinkling of salmon chasing the sardines just north of the pier at
Sharp Park, trapping the baitfish against the back of the surf
wall, complete with hovering, diving and feeding birds.
</P>
<P>
   Well, when it comes to fishing, a lot of people have difficulty
with the truth, but birds never lie. Evenings have seen anglers who
have seen those birds out on the beach, then reaching the fish with
long casts with Worm-Tail jigs and Hair Raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the feed has also drawn huge numbers of rockfish and
lingcod to inshore waters on the San Mateo County coast, especially
between Pescadero and Pigeon Point. This is just in 100 feet of
water on in, a wonderful and crazy scenario for anglers who have
been able to use light tackle and fish as if in a lake.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been eye-popping. In four trips, a total of 60
people caught 900 rockfish (15-fish limits), 67 lingcod to 27
pounds and 127 cabezone to 12 pounds, all in less than 100 feet of
water. That's just plain unheard of, but it's now the daily deal.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more, maybe the stunner of all: Fieldscout Bob
Franco on his boat Fishing Machine left from Half Moon Bay last
weekend and caught a bluefin tuna at Guide Seamount. What? Tuna?
Yep, the fish don't know, apparently, that El Nino is supposed to
be about over and they should be down off San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the sea surface temperature anomaly is still
in force, an average of three to four degrees above normal along
the California coast and as much as nine degrees above normal 100
miles offshore. That is why albacore have been discovered at two
spots, 15 miles offshore of Point Reyes between Cordell Bank and
Soap Bank, and out of Half Moon Bay at Guide Seamount.
</P>
<P>
   Is this for real? You decide. Generally, the prospects for
albacore off the Bay-area coast can be predicted by early-summer
scores out of Morro Bay in central California, fish that are
usually migrating north. So get this: A half dozen commercial boats
out of Morro Bay all had 100-fish days on albacore recently.
</P>
<P>
   It sure sounds like El Nino, but hey, the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, the official source on the matter, says
it's the tail end of the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modelers predict that equatorial El Nino Sea Surface
Temperature conditions will return to normal by June-July.'' That's
the word from NOAA's special El Nino site on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   They better start consulting with the fish. Sardines in the Bay?
Whales in the surf? Stripers, rockfish, marauding like the good old
days? Rockfish biting like a guard dogs getting hold of a burglar's
rear end?
</P>
<P>
   That's right, and, thanks to El Nino, it's happening here and
now. There's nothing else like this anywhere across the rest of
North America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
