<HEADER>
A1379 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTIST-MERILEE-STERN-     06-16 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTIST-MERILEE-STERN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OUTSIDER COMES IN FROM THE COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By REGINA HACKETT  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Here's a story that never happens:
</P>
<P>
   After seeing photographs of paintings, top Manhattan art dealer
Phyllis Kind flies to Seattle solely to see a painter who has never
exhibited before. Not anywhere. Nor has this painter shown her work
to anyone even remotely associated with art, meaning she had no
track record and no contacts.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Kind suggests a solo show. When it takes place seven
months later, it generates feverish sales and avid reviews,
including a long one in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The story that never happens happened to Marilee Stiles Stern of
Seattle, who had her first show at Phyllis Kind Gallery in January.
</P>
<P>
   Still unknown locally, she is rapidly developing a following in
New York, and this isn't her first foray into the spotlight there.
</P>
<P>
   At 18, she joined the New York City Ballet Company under the
direction of George Balanchine. He had discovered her when she was
14 and chose her to dance in the newly formed Ballet of Los Angeles
under his direction.
</P>
<P>
   A dancer all her life, she began painting eight years ago as
part of therapy. She is recovering from dissociative identity
disorder, previously known as multiple personality disorder.
</P>
<P>
   None of the inner chaos that has plagued her is evident when
meeting her. At 48, she is gracious, soft-spoken but articulate and
full of quiet self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   The assurance is hard won. Stern eventually painted a portrait
of the teenage dancer who charmed Balanchine. Standing artfully en
pointe and possessing a long, supple body, the dancer, whose body
is in profile, turns her face over her shoulder to the audience,
and her head is full of monstrous things.
</P>
<P>
   Stern has mixed memories of herself as a dancer. While she
thinks of Balanchine as a genius and cherishes her time working
with him, the day-to-day life in the company was a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers taking Ex-Lax and throwing up with the other
dancers to stay thin, but back then, she said, ``those things
didn't have a name and we didn't realize anything was wrong with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   In her view, Balanchine saved her, rescuing her from an abusive
family and giving her the art of dance to concentrate on.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an abusive family, the child is the parent's tool,'' she
said. ``In a dance company, the dancer is the tool of the
choreographer. I was used to being a tool, but in dance it makes
sense and serves a larger good.''
</P>
<P>
   Concentrating is key in dance, but it's hard work for a multiple
personality. Stern remembers walking in the city saying the names
of the streets to herself, the stores she passed, the number of
people waiting for a light _ anything to keep her mind focused on
the present and in control of the voices in her head.
</P>
<P>
   Just as throwing up seemed OK, she wasn't aware there was
anything wrong with having voices.
</P>
<P>
   The necessity of maintaining rigid control both helped and
hampered her as a dancer. While she could follow rules beautifully,
she could never let go and merge with the music.
</P>
<P>
   After she had been with the company six years and failed to
secure major roles, she met with Balanchine to ask about her
future. ``He told me some dancers mature early and some late, and
that I was one of the late. He said he needed a dancer to be able
to do batterie, or fast beats, something I didn't do well. Instead
of hurrying to the studio to practice, I decided that he hated me
and left the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly under pressure from the voices in her head, she
danced with the Los Angeles Ballet for two years, the Zurich Opera
Ballet for one and taught ballet in Los Angeles and later Seattle
through the Pacific Northwest Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Helping her through tough moments was her husband, screenwriter
Stewart Stern, whom she married in 1980. His credits give him
legendary status, including ``Rebel Without a Cause,'' ``Rachel,
Rachel,'' ``Summer Wishes, Winter Dreams'' and the TV miniseries
``Sybil.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, she suffered a breakdown and entered intensive therapy
with Brian J. Moss, in whose office she began to draw with black,
red and yellow felt-tip pens on Bristol lined paper.
</P>
<P>
   What emerged was extraordinary by anyone's measure. Stern
brought her formidable ability to focus to the task of filling
thousands of little grids with patterned shapes. The shapes lock
into place, gain force through repetition and then open up again
with fluid grace.
</P>
<P>
   The power to merge with the music that eluded her as a dancer
became hers through drawing. Stern's patterns enclose living
worlds, places where predatory monsters enter small people and
occupy their souls.
</P>
<P>
   When English writer E.M. Forster said his goal was to ``only
connect,'' he couldn't have been thinking about the kind of
connection Stern depicts. The connections she makes are prison
grids that both contain and describe the figures within them.
Drawings 22 inches high by 28 inches wide connect to other
drawings. Shift the drawings and the pattern changes but the sense
of imploding disaster remains inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   During the past two years, Stern has introduced more colors:
pinks, purples and a variety of greens. While the horror of the
early work is missing, the intensity of experience delivered
remains the same. Instead of larger figures enveloping smaller
ones, the figures in Stern's new work are whole and entire.
</P>
<P>
   While she started painting as a necessary therapy, helping her
give voice to what she was otherwise powerless to express, her new
work proves that her gifts as an artist do not depend on
nightmarish content.
</P>
<P>
   Stern found the Phyllis Kind Gallery through her therapist. Moss
happened on a magazine titled ``Raw Vision'' and showed it to her.
``I knew I didn't belong in the regular art world,'' she said,
``but I had hopes I might belong here, in the world of outsider
art.'' Seeing ads for Phyllis Kind and liking the artists she
showed, Stern and her husband went to the Outsider Art Fair in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent Stewart to talk to her,'' said Stern. ``I was too
afraid to approach her myself.'' Kind agreed to look at the photos
but failed to do so for a week. Finally, her gallery assistant,
Chris Wyrick, insisted, because he'd taken a look when Stern
brought them in. One look was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have Stewart, I wonder if I could have made
connection with her,'' Marilee Stern said, looking at him as he
busied himself in the kitchen, making dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Stern continues to make art and wants to show it not only in New
York but in Seattle. This time, she says, when she presents her
work, she'll be the one to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
