<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO LAWMAKER SEEKS TO EXPAND DOMESTIC PARTNER LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A city supervisor is proposing an ordinance that
would require all rental car agencies, health clubs and insurance
companies that offer discounts to married couples to extend the
same rates to registered domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mark Leno seeks to expand the city's
anti-discrimination law and would apply to all San Francisco
businesses offering discounted goods, services or privileges to
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Under the ordinance, residential hotels that only allow spouses
to share rooms would have to extend that privilege to domestic
partners who register with the city. Domestic partners in San
Francisco include homosexuals and non-married heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banning discrimination is no new concept. ... We're talking
about inalienable rights here,'' Leno said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, businesses with offices or stores outside
the city would have to adhere to the domestic partners requirement
only in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many businesses would be required to change
their policies if the proposal were approved. Leno noted that many
businesses already comply with the equal-benefits concept.
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce is taking a wait-and-see approach to the
proposal. But spokeswoman Carol Piasente said the organization was
``strongly opposed to any form of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   If Leno's plan is adopted, a business found in violation of the
law could face a civil lawsuit. However, the city's Human Rights
Commission would be brought in first to try to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the proposed ordinance, among them Supervisors Tom
Ammiano and Leslie Katz, said it's the natural progression to the
city's equal-benefits ordinance. That year-old law requires
companies that do business with the city to provide the same
benefits to their workers with domestic partners as they do to
married couples.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies are challenging the ordinance in federal
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
