<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO THE BOTTOM OF A MEDICAL PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A philosopher once said that man is nothing but a digestive tube
open on both ends, at which point the science of gastroenterology
was born.
</P>
<P>
   As a practitionee of the science, I am impressed with the amount
of ground it covers. Everything from the lips to the lap and beyond
. . . but not far.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas, dentistry or ophthalmology seldom strays from the mouth
or eyes, respectively, gastroenterology ranges from our tops to our
bottoms.
</P>
<P>
   Some gastroenterologists, for reasons known only to them and
their accountants, gravitate toward the lower end . . . near your
wallet. These are known as proctologists.
</P>
<P>
   As an aside, I note that while studies have reported high
suicide rates among dentists, no one has discovered any such
correlation among proctologists or gastroenterologists in general.
If there is a psychological effect from looking into people's
mouths every day, and being generally feared, as the suicide
studies indicate, then one would think that the proctologists and
gastroenterologists would be lined up on both sides of the Aurora
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Happy to report, however, that my personal (and how much more
personal can one be) gastroenterologist is a fellow of high spirit
and pleasant demeanor. So, too, is the Heir Apparent's
father-in-law, who practices this same top-to-bottom science in
Helena, the cultural center of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   I noted above that I am intimately familiar with this science as
a practitionee, more plainly, one upon whom, or into whom the good
doctors do their scientific snooping. Some several years ago, I was
introduced to this field of medicine by way of a sigmoidoscopic
examination.
</P>
<P>
   All middle-age men should have one, not only because it's deemed
a medical necessity for anyone at or beyond the age of 50, but
because it gives you the right to exchange knowing ``Oh, yeah ...
I've been there and done that!'' commiserations with someone on the
brink of his or her first such exam.
</P>
<P>
   The sigmoidoscope, thought mistakenly to have been invented by
the Marquis de Sade, is truly nowhere as uncomfortable as a trip to
your local physical therapist. And upon the latter we will dwell in
a later discussion of my recent rotator cuff surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But I have strayed _ by a good meter or so _ from the
application of gastroenterology to this 58-year-old body. Having
those several years ago passed the sigmoidoscopy with good marks
and been pronounced clean as a whistle _ a gastroenterologist's
phrase if ever there was one _ I went merrily on my way through
midlife until a recent annual physical.
</P>
<P>
   Traces of blood _ which might have come from as far away as my
rather large nose _ showed up in tests down under. And the
gastroenterologist suggested we start at the top and look down,
thereby enlarging my passive study of his science as well as my
gullet. We did an ``upper G.I. endoscopy.''
</P>
<P>
   As the term implies, the doctor and his team in
color-coordinated surgical scrubs get you all comfy on an exam
table and then stick a long camera-and-light tube down your throat
and into your stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Braver folks than I tell their dentists to hold the Novocain and
their gastroenterologists to hold the sedative and pain-killing
sprays. But if someone's gonna push a spotlight and camera past
your molars and into the duodenal distance of your stomach exit, I
recommend the sedated trip.
</P>
<P>
   That means not watching the closed-circuit pictures of your
esophagus, but you don't want to be watching if the doctor strays
off course like that tunneling machine under Eastlake Avenue.
Besides, they offer you suitable-for-framing still shots, which you
can put in your journal.
</P>
<P>
   There is a built-in good news/bad news to the upper G.I.
endoscopy: If your upper tubes look clean, as mine apparently do,
they circle around and attack from behind, so to speak. Another one
of those ``someone your age'' things: the colonoscopy.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas, the sigmoidoscopy makes only a few basic turns, sort of
like the Renton ``S'' curves on I-405, the colonoscopy goes all the
way to the Canadian border. It is not, like the upper G.I.
endoscopy, a simple in-and-out procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But since we are still learning to endure the biweekly trips to
the physical therapist's chamber of arcane mechanical devices _
part of the shoulder surgery recovery route _ we are backing off
the recommended colonoscopy until we feel better able to bend to
that task.
</P>
<P>
   If you are the least bit squeamish about reading this sort of
thing _ now's a fine time to be asking _ you have my permission to
turn instead to the news columns dealing with murder, genocide,
global warming and the proposal to sell naming rights of the state
ferries to a Tacoma-based pickle and condiment producer.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
