<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1416 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-AWAITS-COX- &UR; -$A     06-16 1608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-AWAITS-COX- </SLUG>
   -$ADV21-1000&AMP;ADD 
 &HT;     CHINA PREPARES ``RE-EDUCATION'' FOR CLINTON AND HIS MIGHTY
ENTOURAGE
 &HT;     With CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV21.
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     For Use Sunday, June 21 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ China's movers and shakers will activate a global
re-education campaign when President Bill Clinton reaches the
country on Thursday with an entourage expected here to number more
than 1,000 aides, congressmen, journalists, industrialists and
think-tankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The images of China in the United States are not yet
adequate,'' said Zhou Mingwei, director general of Shanghai's
foreign affairs department, a branch of the Chinese foreign
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most important opportunity at this moment, at the
end of this century and the beginning of the new century, for
America to have a better idea about China.''
</P>
<P>
   Image _ that was the word most-repeated by a range of Chinese
interviewed about the importance to their country of Clinton's
unprecedented nine-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   This trip is China's hope for blotting out the image of a
monolithic, unyielding communist power, the image freeze-framed in
millions of Western minds in the shape of a man standing defiantly
alone in the path of a tank during the bloody crackdown that ended
the Tiananmen Square democracy movement in 1989. It happened three
months after then-U.S. President George Bush walked on Chinese
soil, but assured that nearly a decade would lapse before another
president dared to return.
</P>
<P>
   In full concert with the White House, China is orchestrating a
tour competitive with Madison Avenue's deftest ad campaigns, one
aimed at reforming Western views of China on a scale grander than
the ``re-education'' of urbanites dispatched to learn from the
peasants in the harrowing 1966-1976 Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   From the glories of ancient culture to the high-tech marvels of
tomorrow, the president will discover China.
</P>
<P>
   But images are cast in two directions, and Chinese intellectuals
who believe America has wrongly snubbed their country for a decade
are warning Clinton to beware that the impression he leaves does
not come across as arrogant and preachy to China's 1.2 billion
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton should not say America is the beacon of democracy in
the world, and China should follow. That's finished,'' said Yang
Jiemian, director of American studies at the Shanghai Institute of
International Studies, a think tank that advises the nation's
leaders. ``You have to have new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese business leaders expect the presidential visit to
build investor confidence, or even to yield new deals like the $4.2
billion worth of contracts announced when China's President Jiang
Zemin visited America last October.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for Clinton to ring the opening gong on the Shanghai
Stock Exchange elated Yang Guoping, general manager of the Shanghai
Dazhong Taxi Co., Ltd., a booming transportation, hotel and biotech
conglomerate listed on the exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mr. Jiang rang the opening bell at the New York Stock
Exchange, the stocks in the United States soared 20 percent,'' he
said, ``so we think this will be helpful for the stocks in
Shanghai. Though maybe not so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he joined other Chinese in assessing that deals and
communiques take a backseat to ending what one academic called
``the abnormal situation'' characterized by a decade of tension,
continuing sanctions and irregular top-level exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese will do their best to depict a nation that is
jumping a time warp, advancing through generations worth of
technological and economic development in an atmosphere freer than
ever before. And they are expecting to have a broad audience of
Americans who will take home the official snapshot of changing
China.
</P>
<P>
   The exact numbers in the Clinton entourage may never be added
up, but the Chinese are ready for a friendly invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total numbers that will accompany the president are
different every day,'' said Yang Jiemian, the American studies
expert. ``The minimum I think is 1,200 and the most I heard is
about 3,000.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shanghai foreign affairs office, tasked with keeping track
of such visitors, at last count was expecting 1,400 people,
including the press corps, to arrive in the wake of the first
couple and daughter Chelsea. Another 300 aides and U.S. Secret
Service agents were due here early to finish last-minute advance
work.
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House is declining to give an estimate, that
number will far exceed the body count of the official delegation.
Ancillary visitors will include aides to Cabinet officials,
journalists outside the tent of the White House press corps,
business executives eying a new locus of world economic growth and
academic China specialists drawn to the summit as a magnet that
well may set the compass of U.S.-Sino relations for coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   Shanghai is the broadest stroke of the new sketch China wants to
beam out to the world via the scores of opinion-molding visitors
and through the television clips and news stories that will fill
media across the continents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will spend two days and three nights in this showcase
city of 13 million people, the metropolis that China's leaders
calculated only six years ago should become the preeminent
financial and high-tech center of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Meticulous plotting of how and where to grow the city has
created a skyline studded with skyscrapers and a smart lifestyle
totally alien to China just a decade ago. Nearly $20 billion of
infrastructure investment has produced elegant new bridges,
elevated cross-city highways and a central public square lined by
City Hall, an extraordinary Shanghai Museum and a new Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   Development of the Pudong New Area, where multinational industry
and financial institutions are enticed by liberal export policies,
helped Shanghai's gross domestic product reach $41 billion in 1997
after six years of annual double-digit growth rates. Since 1991,
retail sales have grown an average of 21.8 percent a year, and
industrial output value 17.1 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty years ago, we didn't know what the stock market is,''
said Tu Guangshao, the 40-year-old president of the Shanghai Stock
Exchange. ``The only thing we knew is that the stock market was a
product of capitalism, and that is something we must resist.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Tu said the financial community is hoping Clinton
will trail along a group of American chief executives to engage in
more ``cooperative relationships'' with their Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet below the surface of this new China lie some of the same old
approaches and sticky issues that have frustrated good relations
with Americans.
</P>
<P>
   An example is the soon-to-open General Motors plant, a joint
venture with Shanghai's government-run car company that will
produce a variant of the Buick Regal.
</P>
<P>
   GM tried mightily to lure Clinton to the factory, but the big
U.S. strike this month _ based largely on workers' protests against
GM's cheap, non-domestic operations, just like this one _ seems to
have sunk hopes for a presidential drop-in. Celebrated as a pride
of Shanghai, the plant is a potential embarrassment to an American
president.
</P>
<P>
   The entire super-structure of economic development here is a
different animal from Western capitalism, one carefully controlled
and still dominated by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The stock exchange, in most countries the herald of free
enterprise, lists almost exclusively state-run companies. Set up to
draw capital to state enterprises, it shuts out the most daring of
China's fledgling capitalists.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign companies hoping to manufacture goods for sale within
China had better find a Chinese partner, and that means a
government-run company, with which they will share the profits and
more importantly the technology they are required to hand over.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the most important bases of China's new great
leap into the 21st Century: the technology Westerners are bringing
to the building of everything from cars to computers to nuclear
power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction of Shanghai itself has been approached in the
typical command-plan manner of a one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people living where skyscrapers should rise? One
million people were forced to move from the center city to the
suburbs. Shanghai Vice Mayor Zhou Mu Yao, who said another million
families have yet to be relocated, emphasized that they are moving
from substandard to bigger, better housing.
</P>
<P>
   That is surely the case, yet stories abound of Shanghai
residents awakened at 5 a.m. by construction workers who bundle
them out to a truck and start whacking down the walls.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the visions President Clinton and the attendant
world audience will absorb beginning this week.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean the sharp young students, ambitious farmers
and savvy business executives Clinton will meet on his China tour
are unrepresentative. But they won't tell the whole story of a
nation still stretching out of old ways and means.
</P>
<P>
   ``The importance is to realize how we who have different
concepts can live together, can work together,'' said Zhou Mingwei
of the Chinese Foreign Affairs Department. ``I think China is not a
place for limited imagination. It is especially not a place for
limited imagining of China-U.S. relations.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
