A1496 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-16 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YIP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS' VOLATILITY GIVE BONDS APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By PAMELA YIP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's time for a reality check.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrials dropped by more than 200 points last
week because of worries over Asia's worsening financial crisis and
concern that U.S. corporations may be hard-pressed to sustain
strong profits.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of thing that makes the fixed income of a bond
look appealing.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're seeking shelter in bonds, consider the possible
perils, because the solution isn't so clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   Bonds have performed rather well over the past year. In the year
ended last Thursday, general bond mutual funds soared an average
10.8 percent, according to Lipper Analytical Services in New York,
which tracks fund performance.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the falling interest rates that have pushed
up the value of bonds may mean an encore will be hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, yields on the benchmark 30-year U.S. Treasury
bond are at their lowest levels. Yields move in the opposite
direction from bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, 30-year yields briefly fell to 5.64 percent _ the
lowest level since the Treasury began regular sales of the
securities in 1977 _ and closed at 5.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at an all-time low,'' said Meggan Walsh, vice president
and a portfolio manager at Aim Management Group in Houston, a
mutual fund company.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT INVESTORS ARE LOOKING FOR
</P>
<P>
   Bonds have done well lately for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation is virtually nonexistent. Inflation is the archenemy
of bonds because it erodes the value of fixed-income securities.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. dollar has shown lots of muscle against foreign
currencies, which ups the value of dollar-denominated investments.
</P>
<P>
   There's also been a flight to quality by foreign investors
fearful of turbulent foreign markets and eager to buy
dollar-denominated bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking to invest in bonds now for income, this
isn't good news because of the inverse relationship between bond
prices and yields.
</P>
<P>
   Consider going to shorter maturities that offer nearly the same
rate without the interest risk.
</P>
<P>
   There's minimal difference between long-term and short-term
interest rates. A tight interest rate spread ``more than anything
else indicates that investors don't expect interest rates to rise
dramatically,'' said Leslie Fox, senior portfolio manager at Dain
Rauscher in Houston, an investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Fox recommended going with treasury bonds with two- and
three-year maturities, which are yielding 5.45 to 5.46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the best choice right now in the trade-off between
interest rate risk and current yield,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the 30-year bond at 5.65 percent, you're not being
compensated enough for tying up your money that long.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries due in 10 years and under are all yielding below 5.5
percent _ the Federal Reserve Board's target for overnight loans
between banks. For yields to go much lower, many investors said
they'd need evidence that the Fed might consider cutting rates _
which many consider unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   More price gains by bonds are still possible but the momentum
will be slower than that of the last year, Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH EXPENSES
</P>
<P>
   Tighter spreads between short-term and long-term bonds make it
more imperative that you watch your pennies when shopping for a
bond fund.
</P>
<P>
   Find a fund whose expense ratio is less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For investors, a narrower range of returns simply means it's
necessary to dig deeper to find the best funds, and that expenses
matter more than ever,'' said Alice Lowenstein, fixed-income editor
at Morningstar Mutual Funds in Chicago, an investment newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that with bonds, you have interest rate risk, as well
as credit risk, which is the chance you take that the bond issuer
will default.
</P>
<P>
   In these times, don't look to bonds to provide you income, but
to diversify your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Investors ``should not focus nearly so much on the income aspect
because the yields just aren't very satisfactory across the
board,'' Fox said. ``They should buy bonds just on the need to
reduce volatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonds are good for diversifying your portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really are an extraordinary diversifier to a stock
portfolio,'' said John Merrill, a money manager at Tanglewood
Capital Management in Houston and author of the books Beyond Stocks
and Outperforming the Market. ``The total return of bonds tends to
go in the opposite of the total return of stocks just when you want
them to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
To voice comments, telephone 713-220-2000 and dial in code 1003.
Send e-mail to pamela.yipchron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
