</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TO IGNORE THE MOM ALARMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to what we've led our children to believe, there are a
number of things that parents fear. There's the letter from the IRS
that contains anything but a check. The personal phone call from
your physician. A flat tire on a deserted road at night and, well,
telephone conversations like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi sweetie. It's mom,'' I say to my youngest son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi Mom! Where are you? Are you coming to get us?''
</P>
<P>
   His voice gladdens my heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``No honey,'' I sigh. ``We'll be home tomorrow. Remember? I said
two days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Friday and Saturday. That's two days.''
</P>
<P>
   `` ... OK, 48 hours. I meant 48 hours.'' Kids are so literal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So you'll be home in 24 hours right?'' Clearly, he'll do well
in math next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, 27 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But you said...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sweetie, we'll be home in time for dinner. I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   I wink at my husband across the restaurant. He is irritated. He
didn't want me to call so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you being a good boy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure am! I ate a spoonful of peas for Grandpa last night so
he let me have cake for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   The first mommie alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, did you have anything else with the cake?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. Cold pizza and milk.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nutrition there I think.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caleb, when we left yesterday, you were wearing blue shorts
and a white T-shirt. What are you wearing today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue shorts and a purple and white T-shirt,'' he answers
proudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't pack a purple and white T-shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it was white before I spilled grape juice on it. Grandpa
said it was a waste of time to wash it 'cause grape juice don't
never come out anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm at two mommie alarms and looking for a safe subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you remember to brush your teeth before bed?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. Calvin said if we brushed for 10 minutes, we wouldn't
have to do it again this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is Calvin?'' I hear loud voices and screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's watching wrestling with Grandpa. You know that show you
won't let us watch? It's really good. Hey, Mom, where are our gym
bags, anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably by the front door where your father left
them. How did you brush your teeth without a toothbrush?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I found one in Grandpa's toolbox. Guess what, Mom. We're going
fishing when it gets dark and Grandpa says I can shine the
flashlight and make the fish come.''
</P>
<P>
   We are now at three alarms and my husband is frowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Grandmother, Caleb?''
</P>
<P>
   ``She called and said the church bus broke down in Arkansas. She
won't be back 'til tomorrow. Oh, Mom! Killer is strangling Mr.
Wonderful with a crowbar. See ya!''
</P>
<P>
   The line goes dead. I weigh my options and slowly walk back to
the table where my food is getting cold.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are the kids?'' my husband asks over chicken teriyaki.
</P>
<P>
   I douse fretful fire with a cold sip and reply like any working
mother on a much-needed vacation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Great. They're having a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist, Write in
care of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
