<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE SOUTHERN BAPTIST COUP HAD ITS BEGINNINGS IN HOUSTON
SKYBOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ When Paige Patterson, a Texas native and an
icon to conservatives in his denomination, became president of the
Southern Baptist Convention last week, I was drawn back in time to
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, then practically anonymous in the nation's largest
Protestant group, was in a plush skybox of Houston's Astrodome,
along with Houston Judge Paul Pressler, orchestrating the beginning
of what became one of the most dramatic takeovers of a major
denomination in this century.
</P>
<P>
   I was there in the Astrodome skybox, too, along with
then-Houston Chronicle religion editor Louis Moore, reporting on
the first shot fired in a bitterly fought conservative campaign
that won control of the august Protestant group.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates didn't realize what had hit them.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, moderates dominated the giant denomination, and
they were basking in the glow of fresh national attention brought
on by the election of President Jimmy Carter, a born-again Southern
Baptist.
</P>
<P>
   But working in the background were conservatives such as
Patterson and Pressler, who thought Baptists were on a liberal path
to destruction.
</P>
<P>
   At that Southern Baptist Convention in Houston, the
conservatives shocked everyone by winning the presidency. The Rev.
Adrian Rogers of Memphis, a biblical inerrantist with much
charisma, was elected over moderate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first in a series of hard-fought presidential
victories that within 10 years put conservatives in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Moderates were at first angry, then demoralized.
</P>
<P>
   At the Houston convention, moderates approved resolutions
condemning the blatant, secular-style politicking of Patterson and
Pressler.
</P>
<P>
   But the two revolutionists were undeterred. They had discovered
a little-known way to seize the denomination from moderates. All
they had to do was get enough people to come to the convention to
elect a conservative president.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist presidents, until then, were considered
symbolic figureheads and not very powerful. What Patterson and
Pressler learned was that Baptist presidents had more power over
appointments of agency heads of Baptist seminaries, mission boards,
publishing houses and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Each conservative president used his power to name unbending
conservatives as trustees of those powerful Baptist agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative revolution was completed in 10 years. It was
dramatic, and painful.
</P>
<P>
   Two friends, Dan Martin and Al Shackleford, highly competent
journalists who had dedicated their lives to religious work, were
fired from their Baptist news service jobs in Nashville, mainly
because they were moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives acknowledged the brilliance and effectiveness of
Russell Dilday as president of Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary in Fort Worth but fired him because he was deemed
sympathetic toward moderates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed we would be so successful,'' Patterson told
reporters during an interview in Salt Lake City last week. Now he
is president of Southeastern Baptist Theological Seminary in Wake
Forest, N.C. The seminary, once the most liberal of Baptist
seminaries, has become one of the most conservative under
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Southern Baptists have gone their separate ways and
have formed their own group, called the Cooperative Baptist
Fellowship, which has its own headquarters in Atlanta and sends out
missionaries and other church workers.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson, an interesting mixture of brashness and Southern
friendliness, believes Southern Baptists are better off with their
new conservative bent.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old Patterson said his entire focus as president
will be to encourage his fellow religionists to rededicate
themselves to reaching out to the unsaved millions.
</P>
<P>
   No plans are in the works, though, to reach out to Southern
Baptist moderates.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's religion editor.
E-mail him at jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
