<HEADLINE>
U.S. WORLD CUP COACH CONTEMPLATES CHANGES  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A day after a humbling 2-0 loss to Germany in the World
Cup, the United States began looking toward Sunday's match with
Iran while contemplating new personnel and a new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   At least three lineup changes were being discussed on a day when
coach Steve Sampson seemed to second-guess himself and his players
second-guessed everything from the lineup, to the 3-6-1 formation,
to the isolated chateau where the team is staying outside of Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   Tab Ramos said he had been told by Sampson that he would start
against Iran. He would most likely play as an attacking midfielder,
replacing Ernie Stewart, who was all but invisible against Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie Hejduk, who provided the only real U.S. threat to score
Monday, seems certain to replace Mike Burns on the right wing in
midfield. And Sampson appears to be considering replacing Eric
Wynalda at forward with Roy Wegerle.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sampson would not discuss his intended lineup, he said
he was ``absolutely'' considering changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need personality on the field,'' Sampson said. ``We need
players who give 1,000 percent of themselves from the first
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson and his players could agree on one thing. Another timid
start, like Monday's, and the Americans might find it impossible to
beat Iran, which seemed fearless and hard tackling in a 1-0 loss to
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be a lot more aggressive and have the confidence to
go forward,'' Ramos said. ``When we're as timid as we were in the
first half, we don't give ourselves a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the Iranians could appear more aggressive than the
Americans in their opening match, when they are playing in their
first World Cup in 20 years, Ramos said: ``Maybe they have a lot of
confidence. They had two difficult playoff games in qualifying;
they got a tie in Australia. They're used to pressure. They have
15,000 people at training every day. The World Cup is almost like a
relief to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Without really bickering, the U.S. players Tuesday wondered
whether the right lineup was on the field against Germany. Ramos
said it was ``hard to believe'' when he saw such mainstays as Alexi
Lalas, Marcelo Balboa and Jeff Agoos on the bench. Claudio Reyna
pointed out that Germany started seven players who have won a World
Cup title while the Americans started seven players who had never
started a World Cup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience was a factor and it showed, especially in the first
half,'' Reyna said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Wynalda: ``Some guys were questioning their own
abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, though, inexperience did not let the Americans down so
much as the failures of some of their most experienced stars. Reyna
was knocked off the ball repeatedly. Wynalda did not seem
aggressive coming back for the ball. Burns, a natural defender, was
overmatched in the midfield and reluctant to go forward in attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of confidence and willingness to get in
position behind the defense,'' Sampson said of Burns. ``I begged
him to put himself in position to make them work to defend him.''
</P>
<P>
   After halftime, Sampson replaced Burns with the fleet Hejduk who
knows no direction but forward. And Ramos should add some
creativity and goal-scoring chances in midfield while removing some
of the playmaking pressure from Reyna.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson was clearly not happy with Wynalda's effort at the lone
forward spot. ``I was very happy with the energy Roy Wegerle
brought to us in the second half,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos said that he preferred a 4-4-2 formation with two forwards
and that Wynalda seemed to tire himself chasing after the Germans
while they played ball control in the first half. Wegerle has said
that the lone forward formation means playing with ``half the help
and twice the work.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda pointed out that he did not have trouble finishing his
shots because he took no shots. Asked about the inability of his
teammates to service him with the ball, Wynalda said, ``That would
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Lalas wondered whether the isolated vineyard living of the
Americans had been counterproductive. ``We were in the middle of
nowhere, then suddenly we were plopped in Paris,'' Lalas said. ``It
was like a big circus. A lot of guys didn't have the experience for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, one thing is clear now. While Sunday's match
against Iran may present a political sideshow for the Americans,
they simply need a victory for victory's sake if they hope to
advance to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need to be concentrating on that,'' Wynalda
said of the political interest surrounding the Iran match. ``We're
in enough trouble as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
