<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A debate over homosexuality erupts
in Congress when House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, a
conservative Republican, says it's a sin. Later Sen. Paul
Wellstone, a liberal Democrat, says it's something that's
genetically determined. He urges Senate leaders to bring the
ambassadorial nomination of gay rights advocate James Hormel to the
floor for a vote. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-MERGERS (Washington) _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan cautions Congress and government regulators against
intervening too quickly in the current wave of mergers sweeping
many U.S. industries. By MARK HELM. (Story also will be filed in
the FINANCIAL NEWS, or ``f,'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-SENATE (Washington) _ The Senate is scheduled to vote on
an amendment that would cap the fees of lawyers who litigate
lawsuits against the tobacco industry at between $500 and $4,000 an
hour, depending on the duration of the cases. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING-EXTRADITION (Washington) _ Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla.,
calls for renegotiation of the U.S.-Mexico extradition treaty as
the husband of a slain San Antonio woman picketed at the Mexican
Embassy, saying his wife ``is screaming from the grave'' for her
killer's immediate return. The prime suspect in the shooting, which
took place in Florida, is in custody in Mexico. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ Several members of Congress propose
the Hate Crimes Prevention Act of 1998, legislation that would
``strengthen the hand of federal law enforcement in the prosecution
of hate crimes.'' By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   LATINOS-FINANCE (Washington) _ Hispanic groups complain about
amendments to a bill that would overhaul the campaign finance
system, a bill that is being taken up by the House. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   YIP-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Dow Jones industrials dropped by more
than 200 points last week because of worries over Asia's worsening
financial crisis and concern that U.S. corporations may be
hard-pressed to sustain strong profits. It's the sort of thing that
makes the fixed income of a bond look appealing. But if you're
seeking shelter in bonds, consider the possible perils, because the
solution isn't so clear-cut. By PAMELA YIP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Low-income families are getting the
shaft this year. The Supreme Court's assault on legal services
programs for the poor compounds the impact of congressional efforts
to cut other programs, such as Medicaid, which are also aimed at
helping the poor. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-McGWIRE (Houston) _ The show begins about 90 minutes before
the game. Eager fans, young and old, stream into the Astrodome
hoping to catch _ literally, with their gloves at their sides _ a
piece of history as Mark McGwire steps in for his daily batting
practice ritual. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-US-OPEN (San Francisco) _ Nearly four months after beating
the PGA Tour in a courtroom, Casey Martin gets his first chance to
test his game on the golf course against the best the PGA Tour has
to offer in this week's U.S. Open golf championship. But the week
has gotten off to an auspicious start for Martin, who encountered
all kinds of mechanical problems during his practice round Monday.
By JAYNE CUSTRED.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WORLD-CUP (Nantes, France) _ In World Cup action, Brazil
takes on Morocco. By JOHN P. LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-IRAN (Paris, France) _ We look at the Iran soccer team,
which played surprisingly well in its opening match against
Yugoslavia and now turns its attention toward Sunday's match
against the United States. By JOHN P. LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-STANLEY-CUP (Washington) _ In the Stanley Cup Finals, the
defending champion Detroit Red Wings try to finish off a four-game
sweep of the Washington Capitals. If Detroit wins, this would mark
the fourth consecutive season that the NHL championship series has
ended in a sweep. By NEIL HOHLFELD.
</P>
</TEXT>
