<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-SCOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTS TIE RAGGED NORWAY, 1-1  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BORDEAUX, France _ Scotland's ``tartan army'' came back from the
dead Tuesday to keep its World Cup soccer chances alive with a 1-1
draw against a ragged Norwegian team.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the opening match of the tournament to champions
Brazil, Scotland looked doomed after Havard Flo headed Norway into
the lead in the 46th minute. Even the massive, kilted Scottish
crowd, whose encounter with Bordeaux wine had helped keep it in
fine voice, was silenced.
</P>
<P>
   But running onto a magnificent 40-yard pass from substitute
David Weir, Scottish midfielder Craig Burley brought the crowd back
to life in the 66th minute with a precise lob over the advancing
Norwegian goalkeeper into an empty net. Scotland then pressed
furiously for a winner, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   It was a game of Anglo-Saxon bustle, rather than Latin finesse,
with the ball spending much of the time high in the air, thumped
forward in the vague hope that it would land on a friendly head.
Despite its impressive results in qualifying matches _ winning six
games and drawing two while scoring 21 goals _ Norway looked
thoroughly mediocre for most of the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we were the better team and we are bitterly
disappointed that we did not win,'' Craig Brown, the Scottish coach
said. Scotland did indeed dominate the game for long periods, but
regularly ran out of ideas and precision in front of goal.
</P>
<P>
   The result left the two sides' group, which also includes
Morocco and Brazil, wide open. Norway, having drawn its opening
game against Morocco, has one more point than Scotland, but still
has to play Brazil. The identity of at least the second team to go
through will now not be known until the final group matches next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux, an elegant and conservative city, had never seen
anything quite like the invasion of bagpipe-playing Scots and
Norwegians sporting mock Viking helmets with horns. ``Alouette,
we're going to find the net,'' the Scots chanted, outsinging the
Norwegians decisively, and in the opening minutes it seemed they
might be right.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Dailly, the Scottish leftwinger, headed wide in the
fourth minute from point-blank range. Then, eight minutes later,
striker Gordon Durie's looping header went inches wide. When the
same striker was brought down as he raced into the penalty box in
the 15th minute, a penalty seemed inevitable, but the Hungarian
referee, Laszlo Vagner, ruled that the foul was committed just
outside the box. The free kick was squandered by the Scots.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian side, having changed three players after its 2-2
draw with Morocco in the opening match, was in disarray. Its
midfield appeared to have disappeared into some endless
Scandinavian night. But as Scotland squandered chance after chance,
Norway gradually came into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after halftime, with the Scots apparently
day-dreaming about their missed opportunities, Norway's
left-winger, Vidar Riseth, swung over a long cross and Havard Flo,
alone at the far post, nodded in.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland crumbled and it seemed that yet again, in its eighth
World Cup, the team would make an early exit, failing to get beyond
the first round. At last, the Norwegians seemed to have found some
cohesion and were coasting toward victory. But then Burley burst
through the middle, and Scotland could dream again as the Norwegian
goalkeeper, Frode Grodas, watched the ball loop over his head for
the equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Those dreams almost became reality when Burley's 75th minute
drive from the edge of the box brought a fine save from Grodas.
``We were lucky not to lose,'' said the Norwegian manager, Egil
Olsen. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
