<HEADLINE>
WITH MY LUCK, IT'LL BE THE PAT TRULY MEMORIAL POTHOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAT TRULY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In this day and age, it is a chancy proposition to pick names
for highways, bridges, airports, schools and such.
</P>
<P>
   This has been on my mind ever since a recent road trip. I was
motoring through Dayton, Ohio, with The Lady Who Shares Her Tuna
Salad with Me when I noticed an exit from Interstate 75 to the
Edwin Moses Expressway.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about that!'' I marveled. ``They named a freeway for Edwin
Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who?'' asked TLWSHTSWM.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edwin Moses,'' I said. ``Great hurdler. Dominated the
400-meter hurdles back in the 1970s and 1980s. Would have won three
straight gold medals if Carter hadn't pulled us out of the 1980
Olympics. By golly, I think Dayton was his home town.''
</P>
<P>
   By then she had dozed off, and I started thinking about the
people whose names go up on expressways and such. In Cincinnati
there is (I guess there still is) a Pete Rose Way, down close to
Riverfront Stadium. Rose may never make baseball's Hall of Fame (he
gambled and went to jail, you see), but he's still a notable in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Every time some author writes a new and unflattering biography
of Lyndon B. Johnson, I half expect Dallas to change the name of
the LBJ Freeway (otherwise known as Interstate 635).
</P>
<P>
   The safest idea is to name freeways by direction or destination
(West Freeway, Eastex Freeway, Santa Monica Freeway, Broken Arrow
Expressway). But I figure that Dayton's Edwin Moses Expressway is
safe enough, once you get your steps down (that's an old hurdling
expression, for the uninitiated).
</P>
<P>
   Some names of things I really like. I have previously written
about the thrill of unexpectedly coming upon the Alvin C. York
bridge over the Tennessee River (on Highway 412, as I recall).
</P>
<P>
   I am sure that Detroit is the only city with freeways named for
(1) labor leader Walter Reuther and (2) Edsel Ford. Those whose
memories extend to the Ford Co.'s union-busting activities in the
1930s will see the irony.
</P>
<P>
   I find it excellent that the District of Columbia named a
parkway for a nurse, Clara Barton, while ignoring all the politicos
who have crossed its portals.
</P>
<P>
   I have to take my hat off to Louisville, Ky., which must be the
only place in America to name an expressway for a newspaperman:
Henry Watterson.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago took a politically neutral stance, naming interstate
expressways for John F. Kennedy, Dwight Eisenhower and Adlai
Stevenson. But the thoroughfare I like most in Chicago is Cermak
Road, honoring the mayor who was killed in 1933 by an assassin who
was shooting at Franklin D. Roosevelt. Fortunately for America, but
unfortunately for Cermak, the guy's aim was poor.
</P>
<P>
   The woods are full of schoolhouses and roads named for various
ex-presidents and congresspersons and other notables, including
many of purely local fame. Some double-dip. There is a Daniel Boone
Parkway in Kentucky (where he trailblazed) and a Daniel Boone
Expressway in St. Louis (he lived his last years in Missouri).
</P>
<P>
   My real point is that you have to be careful, naming freeways,
airports and public buildings for folks whose reputations might
later suffer. It is safest to wait until the honoree is deceased.
It is even safer to wait until he or she has passed from actual
memory into the realm of mythology.
</P>
<P>
   Even with revisionist historians on the loose, it's OK to name
stuff for Washington, Jefferson, Lincoln, Franklin and other
Founding Fathers. After all, their peccadilloes were committed 200
years ago or more. (Did Jefferson dally with a slave? Do we care
that Franklin was a randy old guy and that Lincoln told smutty
stories?) There's a sort of statute of limitations on these things.
</P>
<P>
   Yet anything named for J. Edgar Hoover would run the risk of
becoming a cross-dressing joke. And can you imagine what sort of
edifice might be named in the future for Bill Clinton, Newt
Gingrich or a lot of other contemporary folk?
</P>
<P>
   I mean, you have to be careful what you name for a village idiot
like Rep. Dan Burton or a bad boy like Sen. Ted Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Thinking up something appropriate to bear Clinton's name reminds
me of a scene in ``That Touch of Mink,'' an otherwise negligible
Doris Day-Cary Grant movie. Grant is writing a big check to a home
for single mothers or wayward girls or some such, just as Day
appears in his office wearing only a bathrobe (it was all quite
innocent; we won't go into the silly details). The proper ladies
collecting the money agree, as they leave, that anyone who gives so
generously to the upkeep of fallen women ``deserves to use the
facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, write your own Clinton punchline.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Truly is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7751. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
