<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Tuesday, June 16. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-MILOSEVIC (MOSCOW) _ The Yugoslav President, Slobodan
Milosevic, promised to make a series of small concessions toward
ending the crackdown in Kosovo to forestall military action by the
West but stopped short of meeting the key condition: the withdrawal
of Serbian security forces from the province, which is
predominantly ethnic Albanian. The Yugoslav leader announced his
promises in a joint statement with President Boris Yelstin after a
day of closed-door meetings with top-level Russian officials. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.) TOBACCO-CONGRESS (WASHINGTON) _
On the third try and by the narrowest of margins, the Senate found
a way today to limit lawyers' fees in suits against tobacco
companies. Under the amendment to the massive tobacco bill now in
its fourth week before the Senate, lawyers who took the greatest
risk and were involved in cases before 1995 could collect as much
as $4,000 an hour. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NANNY-VERDICT (BOSTON) _ The highest court in Massachusetts left
Louise Woodward, the plump-faced au pair convicted last year of
killing the baby in her care, free to go home to England _ but not
free of the taint and trauma of her sensational trial. The three
dissenting justices said in their non-binding opinion that they
believed Woodward, 20, should be re-sentenced, and that a new judge
should consider two special conditions: that she be barred from
earning money from her story, and that, ``as a felon convicted of a
grave act of child abuse,'' she be barred from caring for children.
By Carey Goldberg. &QL; 
MANZANAR-NATIONAL-SITE (LONE PINE, Calif.) &UR;  &LR; _ The stone sentry
posts stand empty and silent now at Manzanar, their graceful pagoda
shapes a haunting reminder in the desolate high desert here on the
eastern slope of the Sierra Nevada. In World War II, this lonely
stretch of scrub off Highway 395 was the largest outpost between
Los Angeles and Reno, the place where 10,000 Japanese-Americans,
most of them United States citizens, were brought from their homes
and businesses along the West Coast against their will in the mass
hysteria that followed Pearl Harbor. By Todd Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   ELDERLY-PAIN-STUDY (WASHINGTON) _ Researchers studying elderly
cancer patients in nursing homes have found that many are severely
undertreated for their pain and more than a quarter of those who
complain of pain _ especially minorities and the oldest of the old
_ are given no pain medication at all. The study, the largest of
its kind, is all the more troubling, experts say, because as
hospital stays grow shorter and the elderly population increases,
more and more old people with cancer are living out the end of
their lives in nursing homes. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VOICE-RECOGNITION-TECH (Undated) _ When any of the 90,000
employees of United Airlines need to make a flight reservation,
they routinely pick up the telephone and speak to a computer that
is programmed to respond to them as a human reservationist would.
Scheduled to be available to all United customers later this year
as a flight information system, the computer asks questions to find
out when the caller wishes to travel, looks up answers in a data
base and uses synthesized speech to converse with the caller. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   GM-LABOR (DETROIT) _ The strikes now crippling General Motors,
while partly about short-term job security and workplace safety
disputes, reflect a larger struggle over whether America's auto
industry will become more like Brazil's. General Motors' operations
in Brazil have copied Japanese manufacturing practices on a huge
scale, and have become the company's most profitable, efficient and
flexible. When General Motors introduced new mid-size sedans in the
United States and Brazil two years ago, a Kansas factory took seven
months to make the switch while the Brazilian factory reached full
production in just three months. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
</TEXT>
