<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-BOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESSERTS THAT COULD BE BY ARMANI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SUZANNE HAMLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In their homes, Italians refuse to budge on the issue of
desserts. The guiding principle is so brilliantly simple: whatever
follows a meal should be pure, fresh and, preferably, seasonal _ an
aid to digestion, an inducement to further conversation. It's an
Armani way of eating: the elegance of restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Viana La Place, an Italian-cookbook author, has compiled a
lovely collection of intense pleasures in ``Dessert and Sweet
Snacks: Rustic Italian Style'' (William Morrow, $23). With its
delectable, natural-looking photographs and instructions for homey,
easy ways to finish a meal, the book seems made for summer.
</P>
<P>
   s. La Place, who lives in San Francisco and is the daughter of
Italian immigrants, is the author or co-author of seven books on
rustic Italian cooking. For those who know her books, they are like
a series of conversations, a running translation of the Italian
sensibility. ``Desserts and Sweet Snacks'' is a provocative
continuation.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, her desserts celebrate pure fruit, with all
its refreshing, palate-cleansing sweetness. But the collection
includes many different kinds of deeply flavorful moments _
puddings and gelatins, cakes, crostatas, cookies, ice creams and
cheese desserts. (Surprisingly, there's only one ice.)
</P>
<P>
   Many require no cooking, and none require special equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To make Peaches in a Glass of Red Wine, for example, just dice
an unpeeled peach into a tall glass and pour in enough chilled
light red wine or rose to cover it. Then you add two or three sugar
cubes, crush the cubes against the side of the glass with a spoon
and stir.
</P>
<P>
   To dress up seeded watermelon cubes a bit, serve them with their
juices in chilled goblets and sprinkle bittersweet chocolate
shavings on top. Or, now that raspberries have reappeared, you can
take a couple of baskets, sprinkle on a tablespoon or two of sugar,
mound them into four dessert goblets and pour on a half cup of
chilled Moscato di Pantelleria, a dessert wine with a honeyed
flavor and a flowery orange blossom bouquet. The author comes
through on her promise: ``Its effect on raspberries is magical.''
</P>
<P>
   Higher up the preparation ladder, there are perfect little
no-flour cakes like an Italian rice cake, a semolina cake and a
chocolate and espresso cake. The elegantly flat cake of carrots and
almonds _ a perfect blend if ever there was one _ could be the
highlight of a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet olive oil quick bread is as good for breakfast as it
is with a glass of dessert wine.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked in with the ice creams and ice cream confections is an
Italian-style open-face ice cream sandwich: you spread lemon
marmalade on slices of crusty bread and cover with soft vanilla ice
cream. Or you can just stuff fresh figs with goat cheese and mint,
or drizzle honey over whole-milk ricotta and sprinkle with toasted
almonds.
</P>
<P>
   This is a book full of reasons to linger at the table these long
summer evenings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CARROT AND ALMOND CAKE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Desserts and Sweet Snacks'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unsalted butter and flour for pan
</P>
<P>
   2 cups whole unpeeled almonds
</P>
<P>
   { cup crushed amaretti cookies
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Few drops almond extract
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups carrots (about 5 medium), peeled and coarsely grated
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar for dusting. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter and flour a 9-inch
springform pan. Finely grind the almonds in a nut grinder, coffee
grinder or blender.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large mixing bowl, stir together the ground almonds,
amaretti and baking powder. In another bowl, beat the egg yolks
with the sugar until pale yellow and creamy, and then stir in the
lemon zest and almond extract. Add yolk mixture to the almond
mixture, along with the grated carrots, and stir just until
combined.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large, clean mixing bowl, beat the egg whites until
stiff and gently fold them into the egg mixture. Pour into the
prepared pan, and bake on the middle level of the oven for 50 to 60
minutes, or until a skewer inserted into the center comes out
clean. Remove from oven and let cool on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   4. Run a knife around the sides of the pan, release and transfer
cake to a dish. Dust with confectioners' sugar, and serve at room
temperature. (It keeps well at room temperature, wrapped in
aluminum foil.)
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 9-inch round cake (8 servings).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
