<SLUG> BC-SNOW-PARKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINTER THAT WON'T GO AWAY TAKES TOLL ON PARKS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A winter that won't go away has caused
summertime travelers to think twice about venturing into some
national parks in California.
</P>
<P>
   Roads and campgrounds that normally are filling up at this time
of year remain shrouded in a blanket of white stuff. Meanwhile,
some state parks are trying to restore trails and repair damage
caused by heavy rains and snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Storms are just kicking our teeth in,'' said Marilyn Parris,
superintendent of the Lassen Volcanic National Park in Northern
California park.
</P>
<P>
   Many areas of Lassen are accessible only by skis, snowshoes or
snowmobile. Some campgrounds remain snowbound.
</P>
<P>
   From Crater Lake, Ore., to Mammoth Mountain, the story is the
same _ warm skies over snow, snow, snow. The weather phenomenon
known as El Nino is to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Old timers do not recall a heavier snowfall at Lassen.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of Highway 89, which bisects the park north to
south, ``the snow measured 46 feet, and that was with a straight
tape,'' Dan Jones, the park's maintenance chief.
</P>
<P>
   ``The week after Memorial Day we gt over nine feet of snow.
That's worse than Tioga Pass. We're working in 25-plus feet of
snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas all park roads are normally open in early June, ``we're
hoping to get them open by July 4 this year, but whether we do is
up to the weather,'' Parris said.
</P>
<P>
   Lassen, established in 1916, is one of the least used, most
scenic of national parks. At 160,933 acres, it contains 40 glacial
lakes, hot springs, lava beds, mud geysers and majestic Lassen
Peak, which at 10,457 feet affords one of the grandest vistas in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   Snow removal started on March 23, ``and we've been going 10
hours a day, seven days a week'' and just barely holding even,
Parris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to secure some money and more equipment _ we even
got a plow from Death Valley _ and people from other parks have
come to help. We've done all we can do. Mother Nature is going to
have to give us a break,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 of the 175 campsites in the park's Manzanita campground
are open, as is the Crags campground.
</P>
<P>
   Drakesbad, the family resort in the park, won't be open until
Friday, more than a week late, Parris said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the heavy snow, ``some people are turning away. We've
had about a 25 percent turnaround'' _ that is, people who drive up
to the park entrance, then decide not to drive in, Parris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't interested in paying a $10 entry fee for one
mile of road.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is much the same in other parks affected by El Nino,
which spawned heavy snowfalls during the winter and well into the
spring.
</P>
<P>
   At Sequoia National Park, spokeswoman Malinee Crapsey said there
was ``virtually no (snow) melting going on above 9,000 feet.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main highways through Yosemite National Park remains
closed because of deep snow.
</P>
<P>
   California's state parks suffered $14.8 million in damage over
the winter. Eight-seven parks were affected, and 25 percent of the
system's trails were damaged, said William Berry, chief of the
department's park services division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that most of it (damage) won't be cleared up until
toward the end of fall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hardest-hit coastal parks are among the state's most
popular, such as Gaviota and Refugio in Santa Barbara County, which
are usually full all summer. Gaviota's campground is closed, and
Refugio's water system was washed out, Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   Other coastal campgrounds that suffered extensive damage causing
reduced visitor accommodations are Prairie Creek Redwoods and
Cardiff Beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
