<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARGAINS IN THE LAP OF BORDEAUX LUXURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't give up on Bordeaux. Prices are going through the roof and
in recent weeks there has been some unpleasantness at one of the
chateaus, Giscours, over alleged shortcuts in the winemaking. But
keep in mind that there are two Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The first and best known is the Bordeaux of the great chateaus
and their often rare and always expensive wines. This is the elite
world of titled owners, wealthy buyers, spectacular cellars and
lots of money.
</P>
<P>
   The other Bordeaux is an immense region, much of it beautiful
country and picture-perfect villages that visitors rarely see.
Blaye, Bourg, Fronsac, Moulis, Listrac and other towns produce 800
million bottles of wine a year. Not all of it is memorable, but a
lot of it is extremely good.
</P>
<P>
   It is not necessary to range far afield in Bordeaux to find
bargains. Nestled in among the monarchs of the Medoc, which include
Margaux, Latour and the two Rothschilds, Lafite and Mouton, are
lesser lights, not royalty but not peasants, either.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Lanessan, whose history goes back to at least the 14th
century, sits on the southern border of St.-Julien and regularly
produces big elegant clarets that compare favorably with many of
the classified growths. Louis Delbos, who owned the place in 1855,
refused to submit his wine for the famous classification made that
year, regarding it as bureaucratic nonsense. The 1995 is selling
for about $25.
</P>
<P>
   Way up north on the Medoc peninsula, in the town of Begadan, is
Chateau Patache d'Aux, which makes a wine I used to enjoy in
magnums. The wine tends to be lighter than some but without a loss
of flavor or intensity. It used to be quite abrasive in its youth;
no more, at least not in the 1995 vintage. It is about $13.
</P>
<P>
   Also in Begadan is Chateau Vieux Robin, the producer of a
smooth, elegant wine with considerable complexity, which means an
intriguing combination of oak and fruit, nicely balanced. It sells
for $15 to $20.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Fourcas-Dupre is in Listrac, a town inland from the more
famous wine communes of the Medoc like Margaux and Pauillac.
Fourcas-Dupre has stood in the shadow of its better-known neighbor,
Fourcas-Hosten, but in 1995 it turned out a most attractive wine.
It is hardly one for the ages, but it has character and a nice
finish. Under $15.
</P>
<P>
   Two old standbys in the Medoc are Chateaux Larose-Trintaudon and
Greysac. Larose, owned for many years by the Forner family from
Spain, is the largest vineyard in the Medoc. The wine can be
one-dimensional at times, but it is pleasant to drink and
reasonably priced.
</P>
<P>
   Greysac is well known in the United States, probably because of
its high merlot content. In fact, if it were made in California or
on Long Island, in some years it would easily be mistaken for a
merlot. Both of these wines sell for about $11.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best buys among the lesser Medoc chateaus is La
Cardonne, in the commune of Blaignan. From 1973 to 1990, it was
owned by members of the Rothschild family, who virtually rebuilt
both the winery and the vineyards. Thanks to their efforts,
Cardonne is a deeply colored, fruity wine that is at its best after
three or four years. La Cardonne usually sells for $10 or less.
</P>
<P>
   The Graves region, south and west of the city of Bordeaux, was
split up a few years ago, with some famous properties falling in
the area just beyond the city limits known as Pessac-Leognan.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau La Louviere, one of the most beautiful chateaus in the
Bordeaux region, also makes a delightful wine in the best tradition
of the Graves, rich and opulent but with considerable elegance.
About $25. La Louviere also makes an impressive white wine.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Segonzac is in Blaye, across the Gironde River from
St.-Julien. The best wines of Blaye come from the Premieres Cotes
de Blaye, and Segonzac is one of the better-known properties in
that appellation. The wine is not particularly complex but it has
delicious fruit and, in the 1995 vintage, surprising intensity.
Also around $10.
</P>
<P>
   St.-Emilion is one of the two most famous wine communities in
the country east of the city of Bordeaux; the other is Pomerol.
St.-Emilion chateaus like Cheval Blanc and Ausone _ whose 1995
sells for more than $300 a bottle _ are among the glories of
Bordeaux.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also good, lesser-known estates like Chateau Haut
Corbin that offer classic St.-Emilion depth and are often ready to
drink a few years after the harvest and at much lower prices. Like
many St.-Emilion wines, it is made principally from merlot grapes.
About $15.
</P>
<P>
   Is $30 a lot to spend on a bottle of wine? Given the prices of
wines like Ausone, no; considering what most people in the real
world can afford, yes. But for anyone interested in venturing into
that pricier category, Chateaux d'Armailhac and d'Angludet are
worth the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Angludet was the home of Peter Sichel, who died a few months
ago. He converted Angludet into one of the most promising of the
second-tier wines in the commune of Margaux. His 1995, deep and
intense, is a fitting memorial to his work, and I am told the 1996
is even better. It is $24 to $28.
</P>
<P>
   Chateau Armailhac adjoins Mouton-Rothschild in Pauillac and is
owned by Baroness Philippine de Rothschild. Its wine is made with
all the care invested in Mouton-Rothschild, and its 1995 displays
much of the brawny power associated with Mouton. This is a wine to
put down for another five years. Or break open a bottle to welcome
in the next millennium. It is $25 to $30.
</P>
<P>
   If you give Bordeaux a chance, in the company of one or two of
these wines, you just might be glad you did. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
