<HEADLINE>
A SICILIAN BLEND 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Planeta La Segreta Rosso 1996, Sicily. About $15.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of exciting, reasonably priced wines from Italy
continues. One importer, Vias Imports, offers a substantial
selection of attractive wines from the Alps to Sicily, which just
happens to be the source of La Segreta Rosso.
</P>
<P>
   The Planeta family has been making wines near Menfi on the
southwest coast of Sicily for more than three centuries. La Segreta
is named for the vineyard from whose grapes the wine is made.
</P>
<P>
   And those grapes are cabernet sauvignon, merlot and nero
d'Avola, a much respected local variety, which may have come from
the mainland because it is also known as Calabrese. The blend is 20
percent cabernet and 40 percent for each of the other two
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   The wine has considerable body, a garnet color and a
fruit-filled taste. There is no oak aging here; none is needed. Why
the vineyard is called La Segreta remains just that _ a secret.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
