A1650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-COOKING-MAVEN-N     06-16 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COOKING-MAVEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RESTAURANTS, DOING AS THE CHINESE DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I will never forget that narrow storefront on East
Broadway in Chinatown, where many years ago a Chinese business
acquaintance of my husband's once took us to dinner. There were
little pans of dried seafood in the window. The dishes were
plastic, the napkins paper, and the food, including my first taste
of Shanghai soup dumplings, was delicious.
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I returned there on our own (the place is no
longer in business), but it didn't measure up to that first visit.
</P>
<P>
   Dining with someone who is Chinese is one way to be served food
that is truly superb. ``The restaurants treat Chinese people
differently _ they take more care and send out special dishes,''
said Judy Wong, the catering manager of Balthazar. ``When I dine
out with my father, he always asks what is the best and the
freshest.''
</P>
<P>
   For Westerners, dining the way the Chinese do may be the best
approach. Chinese-food mavens all recommend large parties of eight
or 10, so that it's easier to share more dishes. And it's wise to
develop a palate willing to forego the orange beef and give fish
heads, dried eel and water spinach a try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never look at a menu,'' said Leonard Lopate, the host of ``New
York and Company'' on WNYC-AM and a Chinese-food enthusiast.
``Decide how much you want to spend per person, and ask the waiter
or manager to propose a meal.'' Unlike some, he said advance
arrangements are not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the possibility that you may get something you
don't like or that someone at the table will freak out when they
bring the live shrimp,'' he said. ``But it's the only way you'll
get interesting food you may never have had before.''
</P>
<P>
   He raved about the buffalo carp at Joe's Shanghai in Chinatown.
Also in Chinatown, he likes Oriental Garden, Lin's Dumpling House
and Evergreen, a new Shanghai spot on Mott Street. For a small
party, he prefers Shanghai restaurants over Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jacqueline Newman, a professor of nutrition at Queens
College and the editor of Flavor and Fortune, a Chinese-food
magazine, said she never asks a waiter or restaurant owner to
suggest the food. ``I know people who think that's the best way,
but I don't,'' she said. ``They'll only give you what they think
Westerners will like.''
</P>
<P>
   But she also has little use for menus. ``My husband walks around
the dining room looking at what other people are eating and chooses
that way,'' she said. She said organ meats and unusual seafood are
less likely to be Westernized.
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, you might be surprised how delicious an
appetizer of thin-sliced kidneys in a cold spicy sauce can be.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Schoenfeld, a restaurant consultant who has long been
involved with Chinese restaurants, recommends ordering a banquet in
advance. ``That way you know the head chef will be involved in the
planning and the cooking,'' Schoenfeld said. ``Most restaurants
have two separate systems, one for a la carte and one for banquets.
The head chef never gets involved in the regular menu.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chinatown, he likes Golden Unicorn, Mandarin Court and 20
Mott Street.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Ferretti, a contributing editor of Gourmet, whose wife,
Eileen Yin-Fei Lo, is Chinese and a cookbook author, said that top
restaurants will cook well from the menu but that they, too, need
to be nudged in the direction of authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in a place like 20 Mott or Shun Lee, you can talk to the
owner or manager and say you want the food cooked Chinese style,''
he said. As an example, he said to request that the Peking duck be
done in traditional fashion, in three courses, or to ask for live
shrimp steamed with garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Other good bets, he said, are simple Cantonese steamed fish,
home-style pork belly with preserved mustard greens or Shanghai
red-cooked pork shoulder. He also said to stay away from fried
foods, which tend to be prepared for Western tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is dim sum, which levels the playing field because
everybody is offered the same dishes. The best tactic here? Head
for the least desirable table, as close to the kitchen door as
possible, especially in large dim sum palaces. That way the food
will be hot and fresh when it comes rolling your way. Glazed
chicken feet are delicious, but not when they're cold. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
