<SLUG> BC-BRAILLE-WINE-LABELS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABELS FOR RHONE WINES COMMUNICATE IN BRAILLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(th) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there are bumps on the label, it must be Chapoutier.
Reasoning that blind customers want the same information that other
wine lovers look for on a bottle, Michel Chapoutier, a well-known
maker and shipper of Rhone wines, has put Braille labels on all his
premium wines, including appellations like Hermitage,
Crozes-Hermitage, Condrieu, St.-Joseph, Cote Rotie and
Chateauneuf-du-Pape. That adds up to nearly two million bottles
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the Braille, customers can learn the type and name of
the wine, the vintage date, the name of the winery (Chapoutier),
the town where the wine was made and the color of the wine, a vital
piece of information, since some of the appellations come in both
red and white.
</P>
<P>
   Chapoutier, who for years has run a wine auction to raise money
for the Bone Marrow Fund in France, came up with the idea of
Braille labels in 1994. Working with the French Association for the
Blind, he developed a Braille label for his Monier de la Sizeranne
Hermitage, a dense, smoky, long-lived red wine from the northern
Rhone.
</P>
<P>
   The wine was a fitting choice for the new label: the Association
for the Blind was founded by Maurice de la Sizeranne, whose family
once owned the vineyard that gives the wine its name. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPER-SUPERMARKET-2TA     06-16 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPER-SUPERMARKET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FOOD SHOPPER'S ESCAPE TO A SUPERMARKET DISNEYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDITORS: budgeted earlier as NY-MARKETS. Change reflects story
angle more accurately )  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By ALEX WITCHEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS: FIRST 5 GRAFS CAN BE CUT)
</P>
<P>
   I have just returned from the ballet. Not the one starring Darci
Kistler at Lincoln Center, the one starring me at Gristede's. My
co-star was the pathetic excuse for a cart that refused to dance
along.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, today was something of a victory; out of 15 items on
my list the store had 13 in stock, which may be a record. But I
still didn't get my eggs.
</P>
<P>
   There they were, right behind the hand truck piled with
Tropicana boxes that completely blocked the way. I backed up, into
two other dancers and their laissez-faire carts, and pushed down an
aisle that was clear, or at least I thought it was, until the Alpo
bags leaning against the shelves caught in the wheels and started
coming with me.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I love New York. But the town's dirty little secret is its
dirty little supermarkets. Sure, sure, they're not ALL dirty and
they're not ALL little. After all, there are places like the Food
Emporium at 68th and Broadway, quite large and if not dirty, just
messy.
</P>
<P>
   And if I'm lucky enough to want to see a movie playing at
Lincoln Square across the street, I might actually be able to
finish off one entire shopping list in only seven days _ before
it's time to start again. (And no, I'm not interested in paying
double at the corner deli).
</P>
<P>
   So, when I started hearing about Draeger's in the last year, I
suspected it might just be the supermarket of my dreams. Draeger's
opened a year ago in San Mateo, 15 miles south of San Francisco,
and occupies an entire city block. It is so spectacular, it was
even photographed for Town &AMP; Country. I knew it was only a matter
of time before destiny brought us together. And it did.
</P>
<P>
   Right on the edge of Silicon Valley, Draeger's is a veritable
supermarket Disneyland, measuring in at 60,000 square feet. It is
designed around a two-story atrium (Sunlight! Indoors!) where baby
moguls of the computer industry try mightily to dent their bank
accounts, and they may have met their match.
</P>
<P>
   This ``market'' is a grocery, butcher shop with its own
smokehouse, fishmonger with its own sushi chef, delicatessen,
cheese cave, bakery, florist, 30,000-bottle wine shop, candy store,
housewares emporium, food library and cooking school.
</P>
<P>
   On the top floor, there is a restaurant run by the former chef
at the Ritz-Carlton in San Francisco. Though this Draeger's is the
third supermarket of the same name to open in the area (of the
other two, one is in Menlo Park and the other in Los Altos), it is
by far the grandest.
</P>
<P>
   My day finally arrived. When the front doors opened and I
stepped into the enormous expanse of light and space, I saw on the
right a profusion of colors where the walls were covered with
flowering plants. To the left were glass cases filled with fresh
fruit tarts glittering with sugar syrup, homemade chocolates and
Black Forest cakes dotted with vivid red cherries. Everything was
there but the yellow brick road.
</P>
<P>
   I floated in, accompanied by two friends, Bob MacDonald and Ron
Valentino, who had moved to San Francisco from New York a few years
ago. It was noon.
</P>
<P>
   We started with lunch at Viognier, which means ``great variety''
in French. The chef is Gary Danko, who was named Best California
Chef by the James Beard Foundation in 1995. Though I haven't kept
track of who's won since, he or she would be hard-pressed to do
improve on the pancetta-wrapped prawns from the wood burning grill,
the gratin of polenta with roasted garlic cream or the chocolate
peanut brownie with caramel sauce. So much for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   After we were done, I ran into Diana Kennedy, the authority on
Mexican cooking. (Funny how I never see her at Gristede's pondering
the Goya selection). She was at Draeger's to teach two classes and
was busily perusing the Food Library _ 4,000 titles, including
hard-to-find cookbooks from Europe and the Far East. (Though the
books are available for reference, they are also for sale.)
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Ron were more interested in the Cooks Tools department.
Bob had been to Draeger's once before and was eager to come again.
Ron was more suspicious. Though an excellent cook, he keeps a sharp
eye on the bottom line. When Bob and I considered the merits of
buying a Bagel Block _ that wooden contraption that holds the bagel
so you slice IT in half, not your hand _ for $15.50, Ron muttered,
``Suckers.''
</P>
<P>
   But even his reserve quickly subsided, surrounded as we were by
bounty, bounty everywhere. Rosenthal china, lobster bibs, ravioli
forms, cookie cutters in the shapes of ducks and penguins. Room
followed room filled with Italian pottery, table linens, napkin
rings. (But no decent potholders, the one thing I actually needed.)
</P>
<P>
   Sated with things, we were ready for more food, and headed
downstairs to the massive produce department. Five varieties of
apples, all polished. Seedless watermelon. Emperor red grapes, each
one the size of a walnut. Mango, papaya, kumquats, limequats. The
mushroom section featured golden chanterelles, portobello,
shiitake, oyster and crimini. The tomatoes were astonishing, so
deep red and round that if Eve had only seen them she would have
skipped the apple altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking as I do for the three men in my life, whose motto is
``the spicier the better,'' I was impressed by the fresh chili
selection: Anaheim, Thai, pasilla, red Fresno, jalapeno, habanero,
serrano. Underneath them, the okra were lined up straight, like
soldiers, next to vibrant yellow peppers, shining zucchini and pale
ears of fresh white corn.
</P>
<P>
   The wine department was next, with 2,500 labels on dislay,
representing the 30,000 bottles in the cellar. For Francophiles
there is an extensive selection of Bordeaux and Burgundy. A locked
display case featured a Grande Fine Champagne Cognac, La Fontaine
de la Poyade for $799, and a Glenlivet Scotch, aged 50 years, for
$1,100.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There were also aisles filled with ready-to-drink California
wines and gallon bottles of liquor. (The freezer held Absolut,
Ketel One and Stolichnaya, all ready for the party.)
</P>
<P>
   Two women walked past us. ``This is so much fun!'' one
exclaimed, while the other nodded, filling her cart. Forget fun.
It's an orgy. Directly across the aisle from the wine and liquor
were Pez dispensers and Oreo ice cream cones. Life and all its
undiscovered opportunities started to glow like a sunrise. I looked
over at my friends. At that moment, I knew that we would live
forever.
</P>
<P>
   The three of us were drawn to the full aisle of beers, most from
microbreweries, including our favorite, He'Brew: The Chosen Beer.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the aisle was the 100-foot-long butcher counter,
which sells every meat imaginable, and 25 varieties of house-made
sausages. From the on-site smokehouse come freshly smoked chicken,
turkey, ham and trout. In the display case before us was a side of
pepper bacon, lamb curry sausage and pork sausage with porcini,
black olives and roasted peppers.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing standing between me and bankruptcy was the fact
that my hotel room did not have a kitchen, let alone a freezer.
</P>
<P>
   I started to feel drunk. Shelves of biscotti rolled by.
Sourdough walnut bread, sourdough cheese bread, olive and rosemary
and cinnamon raisin bread.
</P>
<P>
   Ron appeared with a bag of organic coffee beans. We smelled
them. Mmmmm. I looked in his cart. ``No sausages?'' I asked,
disappointed, and he started to lecture on low fat, which I found
hilarious after the polenta with garlic cream we all just ate. He
had a package of Martha's Low Fat Swedish Oatmeal Pancake Mix in
the cart, instead. I shook my head. If youth is wasted on the
young, California is wasted on the Californians.
</P>
<P>
   The fish section was beautiful, but no more so, to be fair, than
Citarella's. Though Draeger's has a full-time sushi chef and a
dozen varieties of fresh caviar.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese and charcuterie counter was astonishing. Draeger's
has a Halior aging case with three humidity chambers that can
simultaneously age different types of cheese, which means you can
request that a cheese be aged to the exact degree of ripeness you
want.
</P>
<P>
   The prepared-food counter seemed to go on forever. A pizza oven,
a meat carving station and a charbroiler for freshly made
sandwiches. That day there were three kinds of rotisserie chicken:
barbecue, rosemary and mesquite.
</P>
<P>
   Bob, the responsible one, was suddenly pointing to his watch. It
was 4 o'clock. Ron and I were amazed. ``The afternoon just flew
by,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't get to make much of a dent in the 100 varieties of
mustard, 90 types of vinegar or 130 brands of olive oil. But the
cans of snails and cans of rendered goose fat displayed nearby
certainly stopped us in our tracks.
</P>
<P>
   We got on the checkout line. ``Do you get a discount?'' I asked
the cashier. She laughed. ``No, I'd be in worse trouble if I did,''
she said. ``I buy enough stuff here already.''
</P>
<P>
   And who could blame her, I thought, for the thousandth time, on
my way home today from Gristede's, yet again. Each time I have
shopped there since Draeger's, I have thought back on it fondly and
dreamily, like a boyfriend from junior year abroad you'll never see
again.
</P>
<P>
   Once home, I unpacked my groceries and reviewed the receipt.
Five Snapple iced teas at 99 cents apiece. I checked. I had bought
only four. One box of onion matzoh, $3.09. I checked. The label
said $3.19.
</P>
<P>
   OK. For my day's efforts, I had 13 out of 15 items, no eggs, and
was only down 89 cents. In New York, that's the good news. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1644EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
