A1661 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV21-     06-16 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE AND NOVA SCOTIA: MOVING CLOSER TOGETHER  
 NORTHWEST AND DELTA RAISE BABY-SITTING FEES  
 NEW HORIZONS FOR FREQUENT FLIERS  
 TRAVELS WITH STEINBECK, ON VIEW IN SALINAS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Planning a trip between Nova Scotia and Maine? Once the choices
were a 10-hour car journey or a six-hour ferry ride. It's still 10
hours by car, but the ferry trip has been cut to two and a half
hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bluenose service, which carried people and cars across the
Bay of Fundy for 42 years, has been replaced by the Cat. The new
high-speed catamaran travels from Bar Harbor, Maine, to Yarmouth,
Nova Scotia, at speeds up to 54 miles an hour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Australian-built Cat accommodates 900 passengers, a third
more than the old ferry. Its capacity of 240 cars is almost the
same as that of the Bluenose. It has two passenger levels, five
parking ramps, airline-style seating, four passenger lounges, a
cafeteria, a casino, a duty-free shop, a sundeck and an arcade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Cat was scheduled to begin its summer schedule of
two round trips a day. On Oct. 3 it will revert to the off-peak
schedule of one trip a day until Oct. 31. The summer fare is $45
each way, $20 ages 5 to 16 and $40 over 64. Children under 5 are
not charged. The one-way fare for a car and driver is $100. Special
day trips and overnight packages to Yarmouth are available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cat is operated by Bay Ferries, a Prince Edward Island
company that runs ferries throughout the Maritime Provinces of
Canada. Call (207) 288-3395. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airline officials say the number of children flying alone has
risen significantly over the past few years, and this month two
U.S. carriers increased the fee they charge to chaperon
unaccompanied children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines and Delta Airlines have doubled the extra fee
charged for unaccompanied children traveling on connecting flights,
and Delta has added a charge for children flying alone on direct
flights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both airlines now charge $30 for an unaccompanied child aged 5
to 11 on a nonstop flight. And both charge $60 for children
traveling alone on a flight with connections. Delta does not permit
children under 8 to fly unaccompanied on connecting flights. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airline employees supervise children from the time of departure
to the time of arrival at the final destination, where they are
turned over to a designated adult. The service is mandatory for
children under 12, but can be requested for those ages 12 to 17. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other major domestic airlines have no plans to raise their fees.
Most charge $30 for an unaccompanied child on a flight with
connections. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Airlines has begun a new frequent-flier program,
called Aviators, to replace its Frequent Flight Bonus program.
Mileage from the old program has been transferred to Aviators. The
new program offers benefits based on money spent as well as miles
flown, quicker access to higher program levels and changes in award
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Members are awarded one bonus Aviator mile for each dollar spent
on full fares in first class, business or coach. Flights between
cities less than 750 miles apart require only 15,000 miles for
coach or 30,000 miles for first class. Longer domestic flights cost
25,000 miles for a coach ticket and 40,000 miles for first class.
More information: (800) 325-4815. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airtran, formerly Valujet, inaugurated its A-Plus Rewards
program in March. Airtran customers earn free travel through the
end of the year, redeemable on Airtran and several other airlines
(America West, American, American Trans Air, Continental, Delta,
Eastwind, Midway, Midwest Express, Northwest, Reno, Southwest, TWA,
United and US Airways).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All travel must be either to or from Atlanta, Orlando or
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Participants collect flight credit vouchers before departure.
Those traveling in coach class receive one voucher for each one-way
trip, those in business class receive two. Twelve vouchers are
needed for a travel-reward certificate. One travel-reward
certificate is required for a free round-trip ticket on any Airtran
flight, and two certificates are required for a round-trip economy
class ticket on another airline. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free tickets on other airlines are available only for nonstop or
direct round-trip flights to cities that Airtran does not serve
within the United States (except Hawaii and Alaska) or to the
Bahamas from Atlanta. Thirty days' notice and a Saturday-night
stopover are required. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Redemption of a reward certificate for an Airtran flight does
not require the Saturday-night stopover or 30-day advance notice.
All credit vouchers must be redeemed for certificates by March 31,
1999. Certificates may be used for travel through December 2000.
More information: (888) 327-5878. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Steinbeck Center, a $10.3 million museum, gallery
and archive devoted to the life and work of John Steinbeck, will
open on Saturday in Salinas, Calif. Steinbeck, a winner of the
Nobel Prize, was born there in 1902 and brought up in a house that
still stands, about two blocks from the center.
</P>
<P>
   The town and its namesake agricultural valley _ the 85-mile-long
``Salad Bowl of the World'' _ figured prominently in Steinbeck's
writing, and he is buried less than two miles from the center. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 37,000-square-foot center houses permanent interactive
exhibits that recreate places from Steinbeck's life and writings,
including Cannery Row and a plaza that reflects the author's
interest in the people, history and culture of Mexico. Rocinante,
the camper used by Steinbeck for ``Travels With Charley'' (1962),
is part of the collection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition gallery will open with ``This Side of Eden:
Images From Steinbeck's California,'' paintings and prints from
California artists of the 1930s and 40s, through Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   In the archive and library, researchers will have access to
first editions, a Steinbeck journal, typescripts, photographs and
audiotapes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Aug. 6 to 9, the center will be host to the 18th Steinbeck
Festival, a series of lectures, films and tours. This year's theme
is ``Travels With Charley: Beyond Steinbeck.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Steinbeck Center, 1 Main Street, is in the historic
Oldtown district of Salinas, a 20-mile drive inland from Monterey.
It is open daily, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is $7, $6 for seniors
and students. Information: (408) 753-6411. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
