<P>
   ALASKA -- TOBACCO. A proposed $1.10 increase in the federal tax
on a pack of cigarettes contained in the Senate tobacco bill would
hit Alaska smokers hard, because they already pay a higher tax than
any other state. But Alaska lawmakers and state health officials
are split over whether it will really cut down on smoking in
Alaska. (Working.) Gorman
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA -- BORDER. The Immigration and Naturalization Service
is announcing a safety program for migrants traveling across the
2,000-mile U.S.-Mexico border. (Possible.) Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO -- PARKS. Half of the Denver Service Center's workers
will lose their jobs and 90 percent of the center's park design
role will be contracted out under a plan to streamline the
government agency responsible for building a $334,000 toilet. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- BULLETPROOF. The president is signing into law a bill by Sen.
Ben Nighthorse Campbell that would establish a $25 million federal
matching grant to assist police departments in buying bulletproof
vests. Campbell and Arapahoe County Sheriff Pat Sullivan will be at
the White House ceremony. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   CONNECTICUT -- KIDS. President Clinton is expected to endorse
Rep. James H. Maloney's juvenile crime bill at a White House
ceremony today. Maggi
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA -- CANADY. Legislation aimed at protecting Americans'
right to free exercise of religion is based on faulty legal
doctrines and will never hold up in court, two law professors told
a House panel Tuesday. Williams
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA -- SPEND. The House Appropriations Committee is expected
to vote late today on the 1999 energy and water spending bill,
which includes funding for the Savannah River Site and several
projects on the Savannah River. (Working.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS -- BRIEFS. Column for Sunday. (Working.) Wallison
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA -- VESTS. Congressman Pete Visclosky (D-Ind.) joined
President Clinton at the White House today, as the president signed
into law Visclosky's Bulletproof Vest Partnership Grant Act.
Stebbins
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND -- DEF. Working on project. Biers
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN -- TEAMSTERS. Two financial auditors told a
congressional panel that the Teamsters did nothing wrong when they
stopped paying into a pension fund that was renowned as a personal
kitty for Teamster elites. Wolfberg
</P>
<P>
   OHIO -- MUSKINGUM. The fate of the Muskingum River's possible
American Heritage Rivers designation may be decided today in St.
Louis when the initiative's advisory committee meets to come up
with the names of 20 rivers to recommend to President Clinton.
Congressman Bob Ney's opposition to the designation may jeopardize
the river's chances for a recommendation, which has sparked the
criticism of Ney's opponent, Robert Burch. (The committee has yet
to decide if they will disclose their recommendation.) Hurt
</P>
<P>
   -- NEWARK. Looking into the revitalization of a city. What
federal resources are available? How important is a city planner or
manager? What have other cities done? The National Trust for
Historic Preservation has a main streets program in small towns to
show communities the resources they have to revitalize. The SBA has
a Hubzone program very much like the Empowerment Zones for rural
and urban areas. HUD has a program too. Herard and Barton
</P>
<P>
   -- REGULA-PARKS. Today Rep. Ralph Regula, R-Navarre, received
the report he had commissioned on privatizing National Park Service
Functions. Story will focus on the report. Zaret
</P>
<P>
   -- BOEHNER-LAWSUIT-STARR. (Working, for Wed. or Thurs.)
Comparing the allegation that Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr
illegally leaked information to reporters WITH the claim that Rep.
Jim McDermott, D-Wash., illegally leaked information to reporters.
Why do Boehner and Gingrich think this is different? Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- SENATE-POLL. (RE-sent). The latest Ohio poll was released
Monday. Voinovich is up 57 percent to 34 percent. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   -- KASICH-FOR-PRESIDENT. (RE-sent) A wrap-up of Rep. John
Kasich's activities at the Iowa GOP Gala this weekend. Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH CAROLINA -- SMOKE. The Senate today MAY take up competing
proposals to compensate tobacco farmers for the impact of the
proposed tobacco bill. (Possible.) Williams
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS -- BORDER. The Immigration and Naturalization Service
(INS) today announced a public safety initiative that will combine
the existing efforts of both governments into a single system to
monitor the 2,000-mile U.S.-Mexican border. Brown
</P>
<P>
   -- FINANCE. Reps. Ortiz and Hinijosa are doing well financially
outside of the $130,000-plus they make as members of Congress.
Hinojosa is really pulling in a lot of extra money. Marlin
</P>
