<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL BANKS HOPE TO CASH IN ON A SENSE OF COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects circumstances of President Henry Givray's departure from
Giga.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is this Gideon Gartner's last chance?
</P>
<P>
   Gartner, the cantankerous pioneer of the technology consulting
world, is trying for a second time to launch an initial public
stock offering for Giga Information Group Inc., his Norwell, Mass.
company.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: raise as much as $46 million.
</P>
<P>
   Giga tried to jump into a hot IPO market late in 1996 as a very
young company with less than two years' history, a product line
under development, and nothing resembling a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Now Gartner, 62, is pushing to bring Giga public again. Sales
are growing rapidly, the company's research products and delivery
system are recognized as a distinctly new model, and Gartner
himself remains a powerful draw to clients.
</P>
<P>
   But there is trouble too. The small service company has lost a
staggering amount of money, $54.7 million in just three years, and
is running out of cash. Giga's new IPO underwriter, Friedman,
Billings, Ramsey &AMP; Co., has given the company a $10 million bridge
loan to help carry it through the stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Early venture investors have been diluted by the financing
requirements of rapid expansion and Giga's working capital deficit
has grown to $13.8 million by March 31. Executive defections and
firings have created a revolving-door management team below
Gartner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is bleeding red ink from every orifice and has been
for a while,'' said Howard Anderson, president of the competing
Yankee Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is no Gartner fan and there are many others in the
information technology consulting business who feel the same way.
But Gartner has been a powerful draw with consulting clients and
institutional investors for years. Critics may scoff, but others
don't hesitate to call Gartner a legend in his field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has demonstrated tremendous instincts over the years
about what customers really want,'' said Jeffrey Swartz, a former
senior vice president of marketing at Giga. ``I think the market
will eventually decide'' how to assess Gartner's impact.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that file documents to sell public stock usually are
not permitted to discuss their business except in investor road
show meetings. Calls to Gartner and other Giga executives were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner, routinely characterized by a powerful intellect and
personality to match, has led a high-profile professional and
personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Tel Aviv and raised in America, Gartner made a name for
himself as a young classical pianist but left music for an
education in engineering and business at MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Recently divorced, Gartner's former wife was featured in People
magazine this year making the case that she, not Tipper Gore or
anyone else, was the inspiration for the novel and movie ``Love
Story,'' the product of her years growing up in Brooklyn when both
author Erich Segal and Gartner were friends.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner started his career at IBM Corp. but later went to Wall
Street to become a star stock analyst at E.F. Hutton and
Oppenheimer. It was those years, in the 1970s, when Gartner
developed a strong following among investors and built a reputation
that continues to serve him today.
</P>
<P>
   He formed the Gartner Group in 1979, selling research and advice
to companies using technology instead of investors. His years of
experience at IBM were especially valuable and the company became a
star in a fledgling business.
</P>
<P>
   The Gartner Group went public in 1986 and was sold to Saatchi
and Saatchi Group two years later. He came back to the company,
which went public again, this time as its chairman for a few years,
but left for good in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the Gartner Group has since soared, to about $3.2
billion today. Other companies in the industry he helped create
also blossomed, either in their own IPOs or in sales to larger
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research Inc., based in Cambridge, went public in 1996
and now has a stock market value of about $300 million. Meta Group
Inc., another publicly traded research company, is worth $261
million today.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gartner himself is clearly a rich man, it is unlikely he
achieved fabulous wealth comparable with the technology research
industry itself. People who know Gartner say he had discussed his
own personal wealth as being in the range of $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner sat on the sidelines from his home in Aspen for two
years before forming Giga, named after the first two letters of his
names, in 1995. Today, he still owns 31.9 percent of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Giga had a big idea: providing customers access to blanket
technology coverage instead of pigeon-holed research based on
narrow categories of interest. Giga offered its customers access to
lots of analysts with different specialties. Now it distributes
information even more broadly to clients via the Internet for
annual fees of $20,000 to $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner had no problem raising money for Giga, going back to the
investors who had made money on his advice years ago. Among its
largest investors was a partnership led by James D. Robinson III,
the former American Express Co. chief.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner was thinking big from the beginning. He had to spend
heavily on research up front and employed a strategy that worked
well at the Gartner Group: building a very large sales force that
could cover a lot of territory.
</P>
<P>
   But that sales force, now about 100 representatives, was another
huge expense. The cost of sales and marketing last year, about $19
million, equalled all of Giga's revenues in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the research actually sold by Giga has won mixed
reviews. A survey of all technology research firms, conducted last
year by Information Week magazine, placed Giga well into the middle
of the pack in all categories.
</P>
<P>
   Giga has managed to retain about two-thirds of its clients year
to year, a figure below many other research firms' retention rates.
New Giga documents suggest its figure isn't directly comparable to
the rates of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Giga first saw its chance to jump into a hot IPO market in 1996.
An offering led by Lehman Brothers tried to raise $40 million.
Initially, the underwriters estimated an offering at $9 to $11 per
share and favorable reviews during the company's road show led to
hopes of a higher price. But the market began to cool as Giga's
offering drew near and executives pulled the plug at the last
minute, when it appeared they would receive only $6 or $7 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Giga's president, Ken Marshall, left a short time later and
nearly all of the company's senior executives went on to other
jobs. Management turnover became a regular feature at Giga.
</P>
<P>
   The company's top technology officer, Jacques Bouvard, was fired
last October. A month later, new Giga president Henry Givray
resigned. Cofounder David Gilmour gave up his top research post to
start a new company in February, three months before Giga's latest
IPO filing. Gilmour remains a Giga director and works as a
non-employee consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Giga's latest IPO effort may succeed or Gartner could raise more
private money. But the company is still expected to lose money in
the immediate future and has limited cash.
</P>
<P>
   Swartz, the former Giga marketing executive, said it would be a
mistake to count Gartner out now. ``Gideon has an incredible
reputation on Wall Street,'' said Swartz. ``He's proven again and
again that he can pull a rabbit out of his hat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
