<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRILLED-FISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERING THE ART OF THE PERFECTLY GRILLED FISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: recipes at end of article) 
 (bl)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grilling a whole fish is to outdoor cookery what a triple axel
is to figure skating: the apex of the skill pyramid, daunting
enough to turn back many challengers. As such, accomplishing it
provides a sense of mastery.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other such pursuits, though, a perfectly grilled whole
fish is within reach of any backyard cook. Admittedly, it takes
some practice, so it is best to try it in private, revealing your
skills to outsiders only when fully developed. To take a short cut
around the learning period, we recommend the following simple
steps.
</P>
<P>
   First comes the fire. Seafood is best cooked over a medium-hot
fire, rather than a hot one. To reach this point, the fire must
build to a peak and then die down; try grilling on the way up and
the fish will almost certainly end up incinerated. A fire is
medium-hot when you can hold your hand about five inches above the
cooking surface for three to four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure the grill grid is very clean and very hot. An easy way
to accomplish both of these simultaneously is to set the grid over
the coals just as the fire is lighted, wait till any flames die
down, scrub the grid well with a wire brush and then leave it on as
the fire heats up.
</P>
<P>
   It is also very important to choose the proper candidate for the
grill: a super-fresh fish of the right size. If you are grilling
one whole fish per person (which is the best plan), look for a fish
that weighs between 12 ounces and 2 pounds; if it is any larger
than that, you'll have trouble flipping it; any smaller, there will
be too many bones.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the fish, coat it very lightly with oil, and make
several horizontal slashes on each side, about two-thirds of the
way down to the bone. The slits will help the fish cook more evenly
and make it easier to tell when the fish is cooked properly.
</P>
<P>
   When introducing fish to flame, gentleness is a critical factor.
Carefully lay the fish down over the fire, and _ here is a crucial
point _ don't fool with it for four or five minutes. One's natural
instinct is to lift the fish and check to see if it is sticking,
but you should resist that impulse. It is important for a good sear
to form between the fish and grill so that the fish is easier to
turn when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
   After four or five minutes, use your tongs to sort of worry the
fish free of the grill surface. Don't turn it at this point;
separate it from the grill, and then let it cook for three or four
more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the second decisive moment: turning the fish. Do not
flip the fish like a pancake or pick it up like a burger. Instead,
roll the fish over very gently. There is no reason for the fish
ever to leave the grill completely during this process.
</P>
<P>
   Despite your best intentions, sometimes the fish will rip apart
at this point. If so, bail out. Get a spatula, lift the pieces onto
a baking sheet, and finish cooking it in a 350-degree oven. The
presentation will suffer, but the fish will still taste great.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the fish does not rip, though, you're almost home. All
you have to do now is to let it finish cooking. To assess when you
have reached that point, simply push apart the flesh around those
slits and peer into the center. With a whole fish, you should leave
a trace of translucency at the middle, since residual heat will do
the final bit of cooking after you remove the fish from the grill
with your tongs.
</P>
<P>
   That's all there is to it. You are now ready to bear your
trophies to the table and receive the plaudits of your guests.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is also the option of grilling your fish inside
the wire mesh grilling baskets that have achieved a degree of
popularity. Some are fish-shaped, others are more versatile
rectangles. If you choose to use them, follow all of the
instructions above except for those involving turning and lifting.
</P>
<P>
   In our opinion, though, a wire basket does not really make the
process much easier, and it definitely blunts the glory. For full
satisfaction, there's nothing like facing the grill with only your
tongs, your skill and the fish you now know you can cook perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED WHOLE RED SNAPPER WITH AVOCADO-CORN SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 ears of corn, husked, with silk removed (about 2 cups kernels)
</P>
<P>
   3 ripe but firm avocados, peeled, pitted and diced large
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, diced small
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, diced small
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   \ cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   6 dashes Tabasco, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   { cup lime juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 1\-pound whole red snappers, scaled and gutted (or substitute
with ocean perch, bluefish or hybrid striped bass)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Build a fire in your grill, placing most of the coals on one
side of grill basin so that the fire has hot and cooler sections.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make salsa: Blanch corn in boiling water for 3 minutes,
drain, and cool under cold water. Cut kernels off cobs, and mix in
medium-size bowl with avocados, red onion, bell pepper, olive oil,
vinegar, garlic, Tabasco sauce, cumin, chili powder, chopped
oregano, lime juice and salt and pepper to taste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Make three diagonal slashes about two-thirds of the way down
to the bone along both sides of each fish. Rub fish lightly with
vegetable oil, and sprinkle generously with salt and pepper inside
and out.
</P>
<P>
   4. Make sure grill grid is very clean, and place it on the fire
at least 10 minutes before beginning to cook.
</P>
<P>
   5. Gently place fish on grill over hot part of fire, and cook
for 4 minutes without moving. Then use tongs to gently free the
fish from the grill grid, but don't turn them. Instead, gently move
them to the cooler part of the fire, and continue to cook until the
down side is nicely charred, about 5 more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   6. Roll fish over gently, without lifting from grill. Continue
to cook for another 10 minutes or until a peek inside the fish
shows that they are opaque throughout and just a trace translucent
near the center.
</P>
<P>
   7. Remove fish from grill. Top each one with several tablespoons
of Avocado-Corn Salsa, and serve immediately, accompanied by
remaining salsa.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED WHOLE TROUT WITH ASIAN-FLAVORED SLAW
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shredded Napa cabbage
</P>
<P>
   { cup radish or alfalfa sprouts
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber, peeled, seeded and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   \ cup rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno or other fresh chili pepper of your choice, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons roughly chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   4 12-ounce whole trout, scaled and gutted (or substitute with
hybrid striped bass or ocean perch)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly cracked black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Build a fire in your grill, placing most of the coals on one
side of grill basin so that the fire has hot and cooler sections.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make slaw: In medium bowl, combine cabbage, sprouts and
cucumbers. In small bowl, combine soy sauce, vinegar, ginger,
garlic, chili, sugar and basil, and whisk together well. Add just
enough of this dressing to the cabbage-cucumber mixture to moisten
ingredients well, toss gently, and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Follow steps 3 through 6 in recipe for Grilled Whole Red
Snapper, cooking fish for about 2 minutes less on each side. When
fish are fully cooked, remove them from grill, and serve at once,
accompanied by Asian-Flavored Slaw.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
