<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK FOOD NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ripe Strawberries, Ripe, At the Greenmarkets
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Quarts of ripe, luscious strawberries from local
farms were lined up at stands at the Union Square Greenmarket last
week, and they should be available through early July. They were
being sold for $3 a quart by Caradonna Farm of Marlboro, N.Y.,
Sycamore Farm of Middletown, N.Y., and Hodgson Farms of Newburgh,
N.Y. Caradonna Farm offered two quarts for $5. Most of the other
Greenmarkets in the city also have strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Farm stands and some markets in the region are also selling
locally grown strawberries for $3 to $5 a quart. They are more
perishable than the California variety but have sweeter flavor and
a lovely perfume. They are sold at Grace's Marketplace, 1237 Third
Ave. (71st Street), for $2.49 a quart, at Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560
Broadway (Prince Street), for $3 a quart, and at Fairway, 2127
Broadway (74th Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132d Street), for
$3.89 a quart.
</P>
<P>
   This promises to be a banner year for Greenmarkets, with 27, up
from 24 a year ago. The three new ones will begin in mid-July, on
Wednesdays in Elmhurst, Queens, and on Saturdays in Greenpoint and
Bedford-Stuyvesant, Brooklyn. Exact sites have not been determined.
For Greenmarket schedule information: (212) 477-3220.
</P>
<P>
   Bread Marches On
</P>
<P>
   Ecce Panis is moving two doors up at the end of the summer, to
1126 Third Ave. (66th Street). The bakery, which is also at Madison
Avenue and 91st Street and Columbus Avenue and 74th Street, is
opening two new branches in September, at 434 Avenue of the
Americas (10th Street) and 4 World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   And with new plans come new products, including a dark and
savory onion pumpernickel and a rye bread ($2.50), assorted rolls
with flavorings like olives or chocolate (75 cents to $1.75) and
traditional Italian grilled panini sandwiches ($5.25 to $6.50).
</P>
<P>
   Hazardous to Waistlines
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate cigars may not be the newest idea for Father's Day.
But a man with a child's palate still might like the new filling of
crunchy peanut butter and chocolate being sold at all Starbucks.
And the $2.95 price makes for a gift that a child's allowance could
handle. But who can open the cellophane casing that wraps the
treat?
</P>
<P>
   Downsized Chocolate
</P>
<P>
   When John Scharffenberger's excellent chocolate was introduced
in the New York area in February, it was available only in bulk or
in hefty 3.3-pound bars designed for commercial use. Now it is also
being sold in a 9.7-ounce size, which is more convenient for home
bakers, and a 3-ounce candy-bar size. Both sizes are made from the
San Francisco company's fruity, bittersweet dark chocolate, which
is 70 percent cacao. The 9.7-ounce bars also come in 99 percent
cacao, which makes them about the best unsweetened baking chocolate
available.
</P>
<P>
   The large bar costs around $9 and the candy bar $4 at Dean &AMP;
DeLuca, 560 Broadway (Prince Street); the Gourmet Garage stores,
453 Broome St. (Mercer Street), 301 East 64th St. and 2567 Broadway
(96th Street), and Fresh Fields markets.
</P>
<P>
   Newman's Steak Sauce
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to actor Paul Newman's line of products is
serious stuff. Newman's Own Steak Sauce, one of his best products,
is spiced with enough mustard, horseradish, pepper and
Worcestershire sauce to give the taste buds a workout and stand up
to whatever flavors the charcoal grill can deliver. It has no nasty
preservatives to affect its clean, sharp flavor, and the
consistency is pourable yet thick enough to coat and glaze the
food. An 11.5-ounce bottle is about $4.25. All profits go to
charity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
