<SLUG> BC-DINING-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TURKEY'S FREEZER LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I placed a fresh-killed turkey into the freezer in November.
Is it still good? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: If the turkey was properly wrapped, you may serve it without
qualms _ even to your guests this coming Thanksgiving. Fresh turkey
that has been wrapped well has an indefinite freezer life, as far
as food safety is concerned, according to the Agriculture
Department's Meat and Poultry Hotline. But the meat's texture and
flavor will gradually decline as it loses moisture.
</P>
<P>
   These changes are subtle during the first year and detectable
only to people with keen palates, so the roasted bird would
probably make a perfectly acceptable meal. After a year, though,
you may not want to serve it to guests you especially want to
impress.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can compensate for the loss of taste and the
dryer texture by using marinades or spice rubs or by cooking the
meat in casseroles or similar dishes in which it is one of many
flavorful ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to insure maximum freezer life for turkey and other
foods is to double-wrap it. The layer closest to the bird should be
a plastic wrap that clings as tightly as possible, to dispel air.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure that the wrap does not tear and that the ends are ample
enough to be turned for securing. For the outer wrap, use a heavy
foil, pressing it tightly to conform to the shape of the food. As a
second layer, you could also use another layer of plastic wrap, a
layer of freezer paper or a large freezer bag.
</P>
<P>
   If not wrapped properly, meat will be damaged by freezer burn,
meaning it will dry out and acquire a discolored or whitish cast.
It may also take on the flavors of other foods in the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Trim away these dried, undesirable parts until you reach flesh
that is unaffected, and use it in soups and casseroles.
</P>
<P>
   More information is available at the Meat and Poultry Hotline,
at (800) 535-4555. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
