<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      06-16 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ASPARAGUS CLAFOUTIS THAT'S ALMOST A QUICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., this is the last of eight columns by Daniel Boulud, the chef
and owner of Restaurant Daniel in Manhattan. His collaborator has
been Dorie Greenspan. Next week: the first of eight columns by
Deborah Madison, the founding chef at Greens in San Francisco and
the author of ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone''; from Broadway
Books, 1997.) 
 (HLW)  
 By DANIEL BOULUD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The clafoutis has a long and controversial history.
The mother of all clafoutis is the one with sweet black cherries
that put the Limousin region of France on the gastronomic map. But
even as it was winning admirers, it was causing a rift between the
Academie Francaise, the guardians of the French language, who
defined it as a flan, and the Limousins, who insisted it was a
cake. The Limousins prevailed, as it is officially considered a
cake.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine what either would say about this clafoutis,
which celebrates one of my favorite vegetables, asparagus. My
rendition is savory, baked in a crust, and harks back to the
quiche, a recipe that is at least a half-sister to the clafoutis.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional clafoutis batter is a direct descendant of the
one used to make a crepe, but for this version I have replaced the
flour with a puree of asparagus and ramps, the garlicky wild spring
onions. (If you can't find ramps, garlic can be used.) I mix the
puree with eggs and heavy cream, season it well and then bake it
slowly so that the filling retains its spring-green color and
custardy texture, the better to contrast with the crumbly, buttery
crust and the slightly firm sauteed mushrooms, Texas onions and
thin slices of blanched asparagus, which are scattered over the
bottom of the tart.
</P>
<P>
   In order to get the most flavor out of the puree, it is
important to make sure that after you blanch the asparagus and
ramps, you dry them very well. It is not overkill to wrap the
vegetables in several changes of paper towels and allow them to
dry.
</P>
<P>
   I serve this with a salad of blanched asparagus spears, sliced
mushrooms and purslane, dressed with nut oil and sherry vinegar.
For me, this is not a garnish, but a part of the dish. It
complements the tart's lightness and adds a touch of coldness. It's
the yang to the yin of the clafoutis.
</P>
<P>
   ASPARAGUS CLAFOUTIS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours plus 1 hour chilling.
</P>
<P>
   7 tablespoons cold unsalted butter, plus more for greasing pan
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plus 3 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt and fresh ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Dried beans or rice for weighting crust
</P>
<P>
   22 jumbo asparagus stalks, peeled
</P>
<P>
   6 ramps, washed and trimmed, leaves and bulbs reserved, or 4
cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 Texas or Vidalia onions, trimmed and very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon finely minced fresh rosemary leaves
</P>
<P>
   4 large very firm porcini or white mushrooms, very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   \ pound purslane leaves, optional
</P>
<P>
   Hazelnut or walnut oil
</P>
<P>
   Sherry vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut 6 tablespoons of the butter into 6 pieces. Lightly beat 1
egg. Using a food processor with a metal blade, pulse the flour,
butter pieces and [ teaspoon salt until the mixture is crumbly. Add
the beaten egg and pulse until the dough forms moist curds. Shape
the dough into a {-inch-thick disk. Wrap in plastic and chill for
at least one hour.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Separate 1 egg, lightly beating
the white and reserving the yolk for the filling. Butter a
9{-by-1-inch-high round fluted tart pan with a removable bottom. On
a lightly floured surface, roll the dough to a thickness of [ inch.
Fit the dough into the pan, taking care not to stretch it. Cover
the crust with aluminum foil or parchment paper, and weight with
dried beans or rice. Bake for 15 minutes. Reduce temperature to 300
degrees, remove the foil and beans, and bake 5 minutes more. Brush
the inside of the crust with the egg white, bake 1 minute, then
transfer to a rack to cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   3. While crust is cooling, prepare the filling. In a large pot
over high heat, combine 2 quarts of water and 2 tablespoons salt.
Fill a bowl with ice water and set aside. Starting from the tip,
cut a 4-inch-long piece from each asparagus stalk. Cut the next 3
inches of stalk into \-inch-thick slices; discard the rest. Boil
the spears for 5 minutes, then transfer the spears to the ice water
to cool. Add the ramp bulbs or garlic to the pot, and boil for 5
minutes. Add the asparagus slices and ramp leaves, boil another 2
minutes, and transfer to the ice water. Drain vegetables, and set
asparagus spears aside separately. Squeeze the excess moisture from
the ramp leaves, and pat everything dry using several changes of
paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a medium skillet over medium heat, melt the remaining
tablespoon of butter and add the onions and rosemary. Saute until
softened but not colored, about 5 minutes. Add half of the mushroom
slices, and season with salt and black pepper to taste. Saute
another 5 minutes, then set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   5. Preheat oven to 275 degrees. In the work bowl of a small food
processor or blender, combine the ramps, ramp leaves and half the
asparagus slices. Pulse to chop. Add the cream, remaining 2 eggs,
reserved egg yolk and salt, black pepper and cayenne to taste.
Process until smooth. Spread the onion mixture on the bottom of the
crust, and scatter the remaining asparagus slices over it. Pour in
the egg mixture almost to the edge of the crust; discard any
excess. Arrange 5 asparagus spears in a pinwheel in the center of
the tart, and sprinkle over the Parmesan. Bake until the custard is
set in the center, about 40 to 45 minutes. Cool on a rack for 10
minutes before cutting into 6 wedges.
</P>
<P>
   6. While clafoutis is cooling, prepare salad. In a mixing bowl,
combine remaining mushroom slices, remaining asparagus spears and
purslane. Add hazelnut or walnut oil, sherry vinegar, and salt and
pepper to taste. To serve, arrange a slice of clafoutis and some
salad on individual serving plates.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-COOKING-ART-2TA     06-16 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COOKING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY GREAT CHINESE COOKING REMAINS RARE IN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ja) 
 By RUTH REICHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Chinese chefs are much more skilled than French
chefs,'' Ching Yun Pu said. And then he added, ``Although we do not
brag the way French chefs do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1981, and Pu, a master chef trained in pre-revolutionary
China, was working in a restaurant in San Francisco's Chinatown. I
was working at a magazine there, trying to find the best Chinese
restaurants in the state. I couldn't do it on my own, so I enlisted
the help of Chinese friends (among them, Wayne Wang, then an
unknown filmmaker).
</P>
<P>
   They read the ads in Chinese-language newspapers, talked to
their parents and consulted employment agencies that placed cooks.
And then we started eating; before we were done we had found 50
astonishingly good restaurants cooking regional Chinese food and
catering almost exclusively to a Chinese clientele.
</P>
<P>
   I had been to China the year before, but working on that guide
gave me a new respect for Chinese food in America. As I ate Sichuan
minced squab soup, Shanghai lion's head, Chiu Chow crab roll and
Hakka stuffed bean curd, I learned about the enormous impact
politics and immigration laws have had on the Chinese restaurants
of America. It was not an accident that regional Chinese cooking
became a craze during the late 1960s; the Hart-Celler Act of 1965
allowed many more Chinese people into the country and brought new
chefs to our shores.
</P>
<P>
   America got Chiu Chow food as a result of turmoil in Southeast
Asia. The first wave of Hong Kong cooking was due to the Cultural
Revolution, which drove many people out of South China to Hong Kong
and from there to the United States. The second wave came courtesy
of the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, which increased
the Hong Kong immigration quota.
</P>
<P>
   Tasting the flavors these new immigrants brought with them was
exciting, and I became convinced that America was about to
experience an explosion of Chinese cooking. I was positive that
before long the country would have as many notable Chinese
restaurants as French ones.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 20 years later, I have to admit that I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It is still possible to find a good Chinese meal in the United
States. As more Chinese people have come into the country, the
number and quality of small, regional restaurants have certainly
increased. If you want the Chinese equivalent of French bistro
cooking, you can easily find it.
</P>
<P>
   But China, like France, also has a venerable tradition of haute
cuisine. While expensive French restaurants in New York can hold
their own against many places in Paris, if you want to move beyond
steamed dumplings and stir-fries to experience the complexity of
Chinese banquet cuisine, the possibilities grow dimmer each year.
Why?
</P>
<P>
   Chinese food experts in this country contemplate this culinary
disappointment with deep sadness. The reasons, they say, range from
the apathy and lack of sophistication of American diners to a
shortage of great Chinese chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, San Francisco had the benefit of master chefs
like Pu. New York's Chinese restaurants of that period also showed
the influence of T.T. Wang, who opened the original Shun Lee
restaurants; Uncle Lou, a renowned banquet chef, and the chefs from
mainland China who opened Sichuan Pavilion. They had all been
classically trained, a process that can take years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our training was very hard,'' said Pu, who served a formal
apprenticeship in Beijing in the 1940s with one of China's most
powerful families. ``We were sometimes beaten when we made
mistakes. And we had to prepare each dish according to the classic
method, no matter what the conditions. In the winter we had to peel
shrimps, washing them with cold water because warm would have
changed their taste. No matter that our hands were burning from
cuts and stinging from the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   The revolution, of course, put an end to all that. ``Who wanted
to be a chef in China from 1949 to 1985?'' said Michael Tong, the
owner of Shun Lee Palace and Shun Lee West, both in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But today's China is a different place. Tourism is booming,
along with national wealth. Hotels are being built. Restaurants are
opening. The market, Tong says, is getting bigger, and there are
not enough chefs. ``Over the years we must have had 500 chefs
coming and going at Shun Lee Palace,'' he said, ``and only 5
percent were trained in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Tong, also talks of the old system of apprenticeship, in which
young people who worked for famous chefs lived behind the kitchen
and did everything from making their beds to heating their wine.
But prosperity has changed that, as well. ``China has never thought
of being a chef as a high profession, and there is no tradition of
celebrity chefs,'' Tong said. ``Young people aren't being trained
as they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is intense global competition for top Chinese chefs.
And rising salaries.
</P>
<P>
   A good chef in Hong Kong, says Philip Chiang, the owner of the
Mandarin Restaurant in Beverly Hills, Calif., can make more than
$100,000 a year. After taxes. If a restaurant in the United States
wants a chef of that caliber, it has to match those dollars. Few
chefs in the United States, no matter what their style of cuisine,
are paid that much money. ``Chinese chefs are better paid than
French ones,'' Chiang said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese, though, with their growing tourist economy and new
freedom to enjoy luxuries in public, are increasingly willing to
pay whatever it takes to hire great chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Most Chinese experts are too tactful to say so, but money is
only one part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should Chinese cooks come here?'' asked Bruce Cost, the
restaurateur and author of several Chinese cookbooks. Cost, who is
not Chinese, was the chef and an owner of Monsoon in San Francisco.
He is now an owner of Big Bowl in Chicago. ``Anybody who can cook
can make a good living in Asia,'' he said. ``And if you're a
Chinese chef, you want to feed Chinese people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nina Simonds, a cookbook author and another non-Chinese expert
in Asian cooking, agrees. ``The best Chinese chefs,'' she said,
``don't cater to Westerners.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true that many Chinese are convinced that Americans do not
value Chinese food. Tong is among them. ``Americans appreciate
French culture more than Chinese culture,'' he said. ``And
Americans have much more knowledge of French food.'' He noted,
rather heatedly, that he sometimes goes to Restaurant Daniel in
Manhattan and watches incredulously as people devour squabs. ``They
even eat them rare!'' he added. ``I used to put squab on the menu;
maybe I would sell two or three. And if I put eel, duck webs or
sliced kidneys on the menu, nobody orders that.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Cost said: ``There is a difference in what people like to eat.
The Chinese eat bones and innards. Americans don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Ms. Simonds said, ``In this country the audience is not
there to appreciate really great Chinese food.''
</P>
<P>
   Tong blames himself. ``In the '70s we invented all these dishes:
orange beef and crispy sea bass. There's no such thing in classic
Chinese cooking. When Americans eat Chinese food now, they want
crispness. They want sweetness. They want spicy. If I try to give
them red-cooked dishes, they don't understand or want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a shame. Red-cooking is a classic Chinese technique
that involves searing meat or fish in oil and then slowly stewing
it in a mixture of soy, sherry, rock sugar and spices like star
anise. The result is a glistening sauce with a complex flavor that
is simultaneously salty, sweet and rich.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, I was invited to an elaborate banquet at Shun Lee
West, given by a friend eager to prove that Chinese food can be as
impressive as anything produced by the French. It was testimony to
the fact that when Shun Lee wants to pull out all the stops, the
kitchen is equal to the task.
</P>
<P>
   The meal began with cold hors d'oeuvres surrounding an edible
landscape, in which pandas carved out of vegetables cavorted around
a gelatin lake. Eight cold plates were set around it: crisp slices
of pig's ear in hot oil crunched pleasantly when you ate them.
Dried bean curd was cut into noodles and tossed with fava beans.
Pork kidneys had been soaked in many changes of water until they
were pure texture, little clouds under a hailstorm of Sichuan
peppercorns. Fish was richly smoked. Jellied pate rivaled anything
on the Champs-Elysees. ``They just don't sell,'' Tong said. ``We
sell one cold hors d'oeuvre for every 30 hot ones like egg rolls,
dumplings or spare ribs.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, Pu was already lamenting what had become of
his native food in American hands. Speaking of the Hunan food that
was then the rage in San Francisco, he said: ``What is often called
Hunanese food is something made up to please the American palate.
Once the pattern of spiciness and the overuse of garlic was
established, nothing could change it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another attitude that nothing seems to be able to
change, either. Drew Nieporent, the restaurateur and an owner of
Nobu, TriBeCa Grill and Montrachet in Manhattan, has been
considering opening a Chinese restaurant. But he said: ``One thing
worries me _ price. There's a certain conditioning about Chinese
restaurants that they shouldn't be expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Tong said flatly, ``American people won't come if you charge
more than $75'' per person.
</P>
<P>
   Cost said: ``Think about Hong Kong, where a single abalone dish
can cost $1,100. &UR;  &LR; And then ask why the restaurants here aren't as
good.''
</P>
<P>
   It is true: the most expensive meal I have ever had was in a
Hong Kong restaurant where dinner for two, without alcohol, was
almost $1,000, in American dollars. The crabs alone, with delicious
fat down to the end of their claws, cost $400. Would Americans be
willing to pay those prices?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, they would not,'' said Cost, who still becomes angry when
he thinks about the reviews of his now-defunct San Francisco
restaurant, Monsoon. ``One review called it Asian food at European
prices. I was buying the same raw ingredients as Chez Panisse, but
there was an attitude that Chinese food had to be cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a prejudice that extends even to cookbooks, Ms. Simonds
maintains. ``Publishers tell me that people will pay more for an
Italian or French cookbook than a Chinese one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Prejudice, however, goes both ways, and even if you were willing
to spend a fortune on a Chinese meal, you might not succeed. There
are many small restaurants serving good regional Chinese food, and
they will feed you well. But when you get to the next level, eating
well becomes more difficult. Consider the Chinese food palaces that
opened when Hong Kong money was flooding into the United States in
the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong money is only invested in Chinatown and Flushing,''
Tong said. ``They only want to cater to Chinese people. They have
no interest in taking care of Caucasians.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are mainly pragmatic. ``The Chinese spend more
money,'' he said. ``They eat more quickly. Caucasians come in, just
a few of them, and they want to have a drink first. Then, when you
want them to order, they say, `Don't rush me.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese also arrive in bigger numbers, he said. ``Look
around,'' he said. ``The Chinese go in groups. It's a cuisine of
sharing. In a Chinese restaurant there are no tables for two or
four; there are only big tables and private rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese people, Tong said, even order differently when they go
out to eat. ``They always,'' he said, ``order ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Haas, a Boston food writer, recently had a meal at one of
that city's best Chinese restaurants, New Shanghai. Julia Child and
Ms. Simonds were seated nearby, and he noted that their food looked
much more appealing than what was on his own table. When he asked
C.K. Sau, the chef and an owner of the restaurant, the reason for
it, Sau replied: ``When Julia and Nina come in, they don't order.
They call me the day before and say `C.K., go to the market, get
something fresh, get something that's in season.' They never order
from the menu.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the culture gap unbridgeable? Probably not. Americans
could certainly become more knowledgeable consumers of Chinese
cuisine. Chinese restaurateurs could learn to trust American
customers.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be too late. Ed Schoenfeld, one of the first
non-Chinese to take Chinese food seriously, recalls that when he
was a manager at Uncle Tai's Hunan Yuan in Manhattan in 1973, the
chefs were extraordinary. ``The three top chefs each had 25 years'
experience,'' he said. ``The No. 10 chef had 10 years' experience.
The rest had learned in Hong Kong and Taiwan. The food was
wonderful. There aren't so many Chinese chefs of that caliber in
New York anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There may not, in fact, be many chefs of that caliber anyplace
anymore. Ms. Simonds has just returned from Asia. She said that
although she ate splendidly in Taiwan and Hong Kong, it was getting
harder to find good food there, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mentor, T.C. Lai, becomes very upset when he starts talking
about the general level of cooking there,'' she said. ``He is one
of the most knowledgeable people about Chinese food, and he thinks
the standard has gone down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
