<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-HAUTE-CUISINE-A     06-16 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-HAUTE-CUISINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: ARIZ.)  
 THE FORGOTTEN MAN OF CHINESE CUISINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During a banquet of whole shark fin, abalone with goose web and
fish maw, scallops and sea conch in brandy sauce, and minced
lobster in lettuce cups, Ken Hom, the man who tried to put a wok in
every American home, was supposed to discuss the reasons Americans
aren't interested in Chinese haute cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   And in a way he did.
</P>
<P>
   But Hom, impeccably attired in a gray Chinese-style suit with a
mandarin collar, spent most of the three hours at the Harbour
Village in San Francisco _ and several hours the next day as he
cooked in the kitchen of his blue Victorian house in Berkeley _
talking about why he was leaving the United States to live in
France.
</P>
<P>
   There is a connection.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, he said, have never given Chinese food the respect it
deserves and consequently he has never had the celebrity that might
be open to him had his field been French cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   This state of affairs is not true everywhere. In England, for
example, Hom, 49, is a star. ``I made my career outside the United
States,'' he said. ``I'm known here only to a small group of foodie
people. I'm a cult figure. I can't be a Richard Simmons type. The
country is so big people like me get lost.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, however, his books are best sellers and his popular
cooking shows on the BBC network have kept him consistently in
front of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.K., I'm known like Julia Child is here,'' he said.
``The cachet of BBC is amazing worldwide. My programs are seen in
prime time. You've been on BBC and people lay their bodies before
you.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his books, ``Ken Hom's Chinese Cookery,'' was published
only in England and sold 350,000 copies. He has a line of
ready-to-eat foods sold in British supermarkets; his line of
Chinese cooking equipment and sauces is available in 44 countries.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain alone he has sold more than 2 million woks. Which
means that Ken Hom woks grace the kitchens of roughly one in every
27 citizens. In America, 4,455 have been sold (even in Slovenia
they have sold more _ 5,701). His books have been published in
German, Dutch and Spanish. On German shop-at-home television, he
said, his equipment sold out in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   And he has a fan at 10 Downing Street. ``It's interesting that I
was asked by Tony Blair to cook for a heads-of-state summit,'' he
said, ``but when the White House has a Chinese state dinner it
doesn't even ask me for advice on what to serve. I'd have done it
for free.''
</P>
<P>
   Hom's catalog of slights might seem like sour grapes. But he is
so charmingly hospitable and so disarmingly open as he describes
his hurt that it is easy to sympathize with him. Besides, his eyes
crinkle when he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   So he is decamping to Europe _ following his cash flow.
Logically, he should be moving to England; but it's too expensive,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is heading for France, where his companion of many
years still has family. They have a 13th-century stone house with a
tower in the village of Catus, outside of Cahors, south of
Perigord. And a flat in Paris. ``We've always wanted to go back,
but financially it wasn't possible,'' he said. ``Now most of my
work is there. I like living in France because it is a food
culture. I love the life in a small village.''
</P>
<P>
   And his restored manor is far grander than the tiny house in
Berkeley that has been his home for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, judging from the photo album anyway, the kitchen in
France is far more expansive than the one in Berkeley, which is
packed stem to stern, up the walls and down, with jars of spices
and Western and Chinese cooking equipment _ including a wok stove,
a Western stove and an oven just for Peking duck. An island in the
middle of the kitchen has a chopping board and a couple of sinks.
It is surrounded on three sides with director's chairs, just the
right height for eating at the counter, which is what most people
want to do so they can watch Hom cook.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Hom hasn't spent that much time in California in
years. He is on the road 60 percent of the time. This year's
schedule, from April to the beginning of July, includes England,
Bora-Bora, Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, Australia and
Thailand as well as Berkeley and France.
</P>
<P>
   In his ideal world, he explained, he would live part time in
France and part time in Hong Kong, a city he loves because, he
said, people look like him and speak Cantonese, the language he
spoke until he was 6.
</P>
<P>
   Hom was born in Tucson, Ariz. When his father died eight months
later, his Canton-born mother took him to join relatives in
Chicago. He remembers his uncle's restaurant where there was one
menu for Americans and another, untranslated, for Chinese. In
Chinese restaurants, this is still the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese people are really adaptable,'' he said, ``and if they
didn't sell enough of their own kind of food they would go to the
lowest common denominator and give the customers what they wanted _
heavy stuffed egg rolls, sticky sweet-and-sour pork, stir-fried
beef dishes and plenty of soy sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   The only difference today is that chop suey has given way to
sesame noodles. A steamed whole fish with ginger, scallions and soy
sauce, a classic Cantonese dish, doesn't travel well in one of
those white cardboard carry-out containers.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent book, part memoir, part cookbook, ``Easy
Family Recipes From a Chinese-American Childhood'' (Alfred A.
Knopf, 1997), Hom quotes one historian who calls Chinese-American
food a ``distinctive species'' that was adapted by restaurateurs
``to suit the `lo fan''' (``barbarians'').
</P>
<P>
   Behind his gentle manner, charming smile and warm laugh, Hom is
expert at skewering American tastes. ``Americans don't appreciate
Chinese food,'' he said. ``They have dumbed it down. The perception
is that Chinese food is cheap grub.''
</P>
<P>
   Our banquet, at $636 for two, was hardly cheap grub. He pointed
his chopsticks at the perfectly cooked dish of scallops and conch
and commented that most people would say: ``What's the big deal? It
doesn't taste like Chinese food.''
</P>
<P>
   Hom's view is that so many of those woks eagerly bought in the
1970s are rusting in the far corners of American kitchens because
people chose to make such elaborate recipes that they tired of
them. ``They made 10-course Chinese meals and were exhausted,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the last book, an effort to entice Americans back to their
woks, Hom returns to the easy recipes of home cooking with readily
available ingredients and simple techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The book was Hom's final effort to get Americans to pay
attention to Chinese food and, by extension, to him. It has sold
10,000 copies, his publishing house said.
</P>
<P>
   He described it as an attempt to make unfancy home-style Chinese
cooking accessible to Americans. ``The type of food Americans eat
is not the type of food Chinese would eat,'' he said as he cooked
several of the recipes. ``In my latest book I've tried to come to
grips with this.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, Hom has found his niche. Recently he had his picture
taken by Patrick Litchfield, a celebrity photographer and an earl,
no less (he's the Queen's cousin). It was for the British Tourist
Authority, which is promoting the country by featuring those who
are changing the face of British life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stranger than fiction,'' said Hom with a laugh, but also with
a sense of having arrived _ somewhere, if not here. ``Here I am, a
Chinese-American, becoming this sort of icon in another country.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALMOND CHICKEN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Easy Family Recipes From a Chinese-American
Childhood'' by Ken Hom (Alfred Knopf, 1997) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces (a scant { cup) whole almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boneless, skinless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg white
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 cup peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Shaoxing rice wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped scallions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Bake almonds on a baking sheet
until lightly browned, about 5 to 10 minutes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut chicken into 1-inch cubes. In a medium bowl, combine
chicken, egg white, salt and cornstarch. Refrigerate for at least
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place a wok or large skillet over high heat. When wok is hot,
add the oil, coating bottom of pan. When oil is very hot, remove
from heat and immediately add chicken pieces; stir vigorously to
keep them from sticking to pan. When chicken pieces turn white, in
about 2 minutes, drain all but 1 tablespoon of oil from pan.
</P>
<P>
   4. Return wok to high heat, and add soy sauce and rice wine to
chicken. Stir-fry for 2 minutes, then add scallions and almonds.
Stir to combine, transfer to a platter and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINATOWN STIR-FRIED ASPARAGUS WITH OYSTER SAUCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Easy Family Recipes From a Chinese-American
Childhood''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds fresh thick asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely sliced garlic
</P>
<P>
   { cup homemade chicken stock or reduced-salt canned broth
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Shaoxing rice wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons oyster sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Asian sesame oil. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Remove hard ends of the asparagus, then slice diagonally into
1-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a wok or large skillet over high heat. Add peanut oil
to coat bottom, and allow to heat until slightly smoking. Add salt,
pepper and garlic, and stir-fry for 30 seconds. Add asparagus, and
stir-fry for 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add chicken stock, rice wine and oyster sauce. Continue to
stir-fry until asparagus is tender, about 5 minutes. Stir in the
sesame oil. Transfer asparagus to a platter and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOME-STYLE PORK AND EGG CUSTARD LOAF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Easy Family Recipes From a Chinese-American
Childhood''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ pound ground pork
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons light soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon plus 1 tablespoon Shaoxing rice wine or dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut oil, plus more to coat baking dish
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups homemade chicken stock or reduced-salt canned broth
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped scallions, white part only
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons oyster sauce. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium bowl, combine pork, soy sauce, 1 teaspoon of the
rice wine, { teaspoon salt, black pepper, sesame oil and
cornstarch. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place a wok or small skillet over high heat. Add 1 tablespoon
of the peanut oil to coat the pan, and allow to heat until slightly
smoking. Add pork and stir-fry until meat is broken up and lightly
browned, about 2 minutes. Drain pork in a heat-proof colander,
discarding excess fat and oil, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a medium bowl, combine eggs, chicken stock, 1 tablespoon
rice wine, white pepper and remaining { teaspoon salt. Mix well.
Add cooked pork, and stir to combine.
</P>
<P>
   4. Set up a large steamer, or place a rack in the bottom of a
large wok or deep pan. Fill with just enough water to sit below the
rack, and bring to a boil. Lightly oil a 9-inch glass pie plate or
other shallow baking dish. Pour egg mixture into dish, and
carefully set it on rack. Reduce heat to low, and place lid on
steamer, or cover wok tightly with a lid or foil. Steam gently
until the custard has barely set, about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, remove plate of custard from the steamer, and
sprinkle with scallions. Heat remaining tablespoon of peanut oil in
a small pan until it begins to smoke, and pour over the custard.
Drizzle on the oyster sauce, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
