<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-VISAS-COX &UR;  &UR; TECHC     06-16 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-VISAS-COX </SLUG>
     TECH COMPANIES SEEKING FOREIGN WORKERS
REPORTEDLY LAYING OFF AMERICANS
 &HT;     By CHRISTI HARLAN and KIMBERLY MARSELAS 
 &HT;     Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some of the high-tech companies that are lobbying
to hire more foreign workers are also announcing layoffs of
thousands of U.S. workers, Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, chairman of the House immigration subcommittee, is using
the layoff numbers to bolster his insistence that companies
employing foreign workers take specific steps to protect the jobs
of U.S. workers _ steps that companies are strenuously fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is so wrong with asking companies to advertise jobs and
hire qualified American workers?'' Smith asked in a news release in
which he listed 21 ``high-tech dependent'' companies that have
announced layoffs in the past six months. The list includes
Motorola Inc., which announced layoffs of 15,000 workers June 4, as
well as consumer-products companies such as Sunbeam Corp., which
announced 6,400 layoffs last month.
</P>
<P>
   The companies and their trade associations said Smith is making
a connection where there is none. Jerry Jasinowski, president of
the National Association of Manufacturers, said the layoff numbers
have little to do with a shortage of qualified U.S. technical
workers and the companies' desire to hire the best workers, no
matter where they come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people who get laid off and rehired every day,''
Jasinowski said. ``Even with that, we'll have this shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement is the latest skirmish in what is becoming an
increasingly entrenched battle between Smith and the business
community over H-1B visas, which enable highly skilled foreign
workers to hold jobs with U.S. companies for up to six years.
</P>
<P>
   This year's allotment of 65,000 visas ran out almost six weeks
ago, and companies and their would-be employees are anxious for
Congress to make more visas available immediately and to boost the
number of H-1Bs available in coming years. The Senate has passed
legislation that would increase the visas, but the House version _
written by Smith _ is stalled because of corporate opposition to
the requirements he would impose on companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I don't know what I should do,'' said Valentina Videva, a
foreign student who worked as a manufacturing engineer at Texas
Instruments Inc. in Massachusetts until her student visa expired in
May. The H-1B visas were gone before she got one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I pack my belongings and return to Macedonia?'' she
asked. ``Or will the H-1B cap be increased so that I can stay
here?''
</P>
<P>
   Videva spoke Tuesday at a Capitol Hill press conference
sponsored by business and pro-immigration groups that are anxious
to see the House approve more visas. Outside the conference,
Smith's spokesman, Allen Kay, distributed the congressman's news
release questioning corporate layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which was not represented at the news conference in
Washington, does not see ``a direct connection'' between the
layoffs it has announced and the company's desire to hire H-1B
workers, said spokesman Lonny Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see a direct relationship between one or the other,''
Hurst said. The company is hoping early retirements and natural
attrition will trim its work force to cure a short-term business
downturn, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long term, we are always looking for the most qualified
people,'' including foreign workers, Hurst said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's legislation would require companies to attest that they
made ``good faith, timely and significant steps'' to hire U.S.
workers for the jobs and that no U.S. workers were laid off from
the jobs being filled by foreign workers. Employers say the
requirements sound simple. but could turn into bureaucratic
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Kay said Smith believes that U.S. businesses should retrain U.S.
workers instead of hiring foreign workers for technical positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an industry where people are trainable and
retrainable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jasinowski, with the National Association of Manufacturers, said
the need for highly skilled workers is immediate: ``We're doing
everything we can to improve the training and education of American
workers,'' he said, ``but that's not going to be enough, soon
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
