<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: `X-FILES' FILM; TNT WRESTLING MOVIE; `MONEYLINE WITH LOU
DOBBS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: bylines at end of articles)  
 (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `X-FILES' MOVIE SEEKS NEW FANS
</P>
<P>
   David Duchovny believed that he was taking part in a first when
he filmed the ``X-Files'' movie last summer: starring in a
big-budget Hollywood film, playing the same character he plays in a
continuing television series.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then somebody told me there had been a `Beverly
Hillbillies' movie one year while that show was on, and then there
was a `Munsters' movie while it was on the air,'' Duchovny said.
``So maybe we're just the first  &UR; drama &LR;  that's made a movie while
on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, ``The X-Files'' movie, which opens Friday, is the
first film to be dropped into the middle of a television series
with a continuing story line. Duchovny, who is in New York this
week to promote the movie, admitted that recreating his Fox Mulder
character _ the FBI agent exposed to alien invaders, monsters of
all descriptions and government conspirators on every side _ posed
a few challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie is all about storytelling,'' Duchovny said, ``which
leads to slight differences in how you play the character. On TV,
it's been five years. People know Mulder. In the movie, you have to
play him for people who are seeing him for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   What this means in the movie is a subtle shift in Mulder's sense
of the events surrounding him. ``In the TV show, we have so many
different types of episodes: monster shows, the mythology shows,
satiric-type shows,'' Duchovny said. ``We couldn't be all of that
in the movie. So there are some aspects of Mulder from the show
that you don't see in the movie. What happens is you see some
things that Mulder doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files'' has a steady audience of 20 million every week
on the Fox network. But Chris Carter, the creator of the series and
the film, said he had to open the movie up to nonfans.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's episodes of the series were being shot after the
movie's filming was completed. All Duchovny knew going into the
film, he said, was that the X-Files division of the FBI was going
to ``be closed down in the final episode of the season, when my
office burns down.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the starting point for the film. ``But I didn't want
Mulder to be moping around depressed when the movie started,'' he
said. ``That's no way to introduce a character to people. So I
talked it over with Chris.''
</P>
<P>
   They came up with an approach that included a touch of humor in
the early scenes of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that was really a risk,'' Duchovny said. ``We're
taking plenty of other risks with this movie, but I don't think my
characterization is a big one. The biggest gamble we're taking is
doing the movie at all. If the movie were not to work, it might
tarnish the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny said that he was very happy with how the film turned
out and that he expected to make another film if this one is a
success. Whatever happens, he said, ``I'm on board for this coming
year in the series.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   A WRESTLER'S OTHER SIDE
</P>
<P>
   When Judson Vaughn, an independent filmmaker in Atlanta, cast
Steve Borden as a lead character in his first feature, he had no
idea about Borden's alter ego.
</P>
<P>
   In his day job, so to speak, Borden plays the silent and
menacing Sting, one of the most feared and therefore most popular
characters in World Championship Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   But without his frightening black-and-white face paint, Borden
is just another good-looking young actor learning his craft,
perfect for a role in Vaughn's romantic comedy ``The Real Reason,''
which focuses on five men who commit assorted crimes out of
devotion to beautiful women (hence the title).
</P>
<P>
   It includes some foreign-language wooing (with subtitles), an
oenophilia theme and some high-flown discussion of the philosophies
of Aristotle, Schopenauer and Kant.
</P>
<P>
   But because of Borden's other, more notorious identity, Vaughn
was able to sell his film's distribution rights to what he
described as ``a division of Turner.'' That division turned out to
be World Championship Wrestling, which promotes professional
wrestling matches, both as weekly fare on Turner's cable network
TNT and as enormously lucrative pay-per-view events. Sting is one
of its biggest celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn's movie is being sold as a pay-per-view film this month;
the ads for it feature a fearsome photo of Sting, and this
headline: ``Warrior. Vigilante. Lover?! See Sting as You've Never
Seen Him Before.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is flattered that Turner thinks the more than 30 million
people who watch pro wrestling every week on cable television might
want to watch his film. But he's a tad concerned that wrestling
fans may sense a bait-and-switch tactic, while film buffs who might
enjoy his movie will skip it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smart romantic comedy in the vein of `Metropolitan' or
`Barcelona,''' he said. ``It was in the Peachtree Film Festival
last fall. Now it's being marketed as a wrestling movie.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I'm no elitist, and I didn't make the movie for
intellectuals or wine snobs. It's just that I think it's a pretty
good little romantic comedy, and I wouldn't mind if some
nonwrestling fans saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Turner pointed out that more than 36 million
people a week watch wrestling matches on cable: not a bad potential
audience for earning a producer some money from a pay-per-view
movie.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   DOUBLING `MONEYLINE'
</P>
<P>
   Trying to build audiences by capitalizing on one of its
better-known names, the Cable News Network is expected to announce
Wednesday that the financial news program ``Moneyline With Lou
Dobbs'' will be expanded to one hour from a half-hour, starting
next week, and will change its name to reflect a broader approach.
</P>
<P>
   The new show, ``Moneyline News Hour with Lou Dobbs,'' will
appear from 6:30 to 7:30 p.m. weekdays, following CNN's ``World
News'' at 6. The name has been changed to enable Dobbs to present a
wider range of news reports, usually, but not always, with business
or financial ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   The move is another attempt by Richard Kaplan, president of CNN
in the United States, to generate ``appointment viewing,'' meaning
a program people will tune to regardless of whether they were
already watching that network or not. Currently, when Dobbs' show
comes on at 7 p.m., CNN's viewership usually increases by 20
percent, a network spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
