<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: FRESH LAURELS FOR COMPOSER; COUNTRY MUSIC AWARDS;
RUSSIAN EXHIBIT EXTENDED; MEXICAN CONTEMPORARY ART;   STONES CANCEL
AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 BY LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Already the recipient of the gold medal for music from the
National Institute of Arts and Letters, the National Medal of Arts
and two Pulitzer Prizes, the composer Elliott Carter is the
recipient of another honor. The latest is the Prince Pierre
Foundation Music Award, bestowed by the Principality of Monaco and
carrying a prize of 100,000 francs or about $16,500. Carter, who
turns 90 in December, was given the award for his composition
``Allegro Scorrevole,'' commissioned by the Cleveland Orchestra,
which gave it its premiere last year. The Prince Pierre foundation
was created more than 30 years ago by Prince Rainier III in memory
of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Vox Populi
</P>
<P>
   Accolades will do a lot for an achy breaky heart. Six years
after his hit song of that title, Billy Ray Cyrus left the TNN
Music City News Country Awards in Nashville on Monday night laden
with honors for best single, video, song, album and male vocalist.
The only one of his nominations that failed to translate into an
award was the one for Entertainer of the Year, which went to Neal
McCoy, who also triumphed over Garth Brooks, Alan Jackson and
George Strait. The winners are chosen by fans. At the ceremonies,
Reba McEntire won the Minnie Pearl Award for her charity work, and
Porter Wagoner was named a Living Legend.
</P>
<P>
   Second Chance
</P>
<P>
   Time eventually runs out on procrastinators, but those who have
been thinking about paying a visit to the Brooklyn Museum of Art to
see the 200 exquisite works from five major Russian museum
collections in ``Jewels of the Romanovs'' are getting an extended
chance to mend their ways. The display of priceless crown jewels,
imperial portraits and court costumes is prolonging its stay by a
week, until July 12.
</P>
<P>
   New Look
</P>
<P>
   Mention 20th-century Mexican art, and names like Diego Rivera
and David Siqueiros may come to mind. But much has happened since
their heyday. On Saturday, an exhibition showcasing a new
generation of contemporary Mexican artists opens opens at the
Chicago Cultural Center. Running until Aug. 23, it is titled
``Mexico Ahora: Punto de Partida/Mexico Now: Point of Departure.''
Featuring the works of 13 innovative artists, the show comprises
sculpture, photography, installations and paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Silent Night
</P>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones canceled their concert in Milan, Italy,
Tuesday after Mick Jagger came down with laryngitis. The concert
had already been rescheduled from May 30, when the guitarist Keith
Richards was unable to perform. Organizers said they were trying to
reschedule the performance for September.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1841 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOHLS-COLUMN17-COX     06-16 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOHLS-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Texas defensive genius Campbell critically ill
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Mike Campbell was about to make his biggest comeback,
perhaps his best contribution, if two decades too late. This was to
be no formal coming out of retirement, no full-time return to a
calling that had been his life's work for nearly 30 of his 76
highly productive years.
</P>
<P>
   The former longtime defensive coordinator under Darrell Royal
had been invited back into the Longhorns fold to impart his advice
in the formidable task of rebuilding the once-proud University of
Texas defense.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Campbell was wanted again.
</P>
<P>
   And he couldn't have been happier.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, life is playing one of its cruelest tricks on
this most honorable of men. At a time when new UT head fooball
coach Mack Brown and defensive coordinator Carl Reese were
petitioning him to share the brilliance that was Campbell's
defensive intellect, he is lying critically ill in a hospital bed
at Seton Medical Center, a victim of lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell has called his room at Seton home for the better part
of two weeks, a staph infection robbing him of the precious white
blood cells needed for the fight. It is one of the few times in
this man's life that his defense has let him down.
</P>
<P>
   The man who drew up some of the finest defenses this program has
ever seen devised, who stopped threats from Roger Staubach to Joe
Theismann, could not concoct a defense to fight this final battle.
</P>
<P>
   Let it be said there has been no finer man who has coached at
Texas. There might have been those with better credentials _ if so,
it would be a short list _ and there are those who were called to
greater glory.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell was never about winning percentages or coaching
honors or silver hardware that gathered dust in a too-soon
forgotten trophy case. That's why he turned down head coaching
offers from Baylor and Texas Christian, preferring to remain loyal
to Texas, a trust that would hardly be returned in kind years
later.
</P>
<P>
   He was always about the kids _ pushing them, goading them,
inspiring them to be better players, stronger people. He worked
them hard and he worked them long. Three of those people were his
sons, twins Mike and Tom, and Rusty. It would be Tom who would hang
on to Bill Montgomery's final pass to turn back Arkansas in 1969
and give Texas its last undisputed national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Mike wasn't always soothing. He could holler and scream with
the best of them. But he always found a way to brag on the guilty
player to avoid any lasting emotional wounds. The coach never
forgot that he was a father as well.
</P>
<P>
   As a coach, he was nothing short of genius, able to sit in a
dark room armed with nothing more than a yellow pad and a clanky
projector and magically produce that week's defensive game plan
before the lights came on. Texas fans still marvel at the defense
that shut down a vaunted 1976 Oklahoma squad and, but for an Ivey
Suber fumble, would have brought Texas another win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so simple,'' said David McWilliams, a former pupil and
colleague of Campbell's. ``I always asked myself, `Why couldn't I
see that?'''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious was lost on a lot of people back then when coaching
was less about shoe contracts and personal agents and more about
team and championships. It wasn't enough about loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be all too true, Mike Campbell might have been the
greatest head football coach Texas never hired.
</P>
<P>
   For all that Campbell did to elevate Longhorns football over 20
wildly successful years, he will also be remembered for the job he
wasn't allowed to do. When Royal resigned in 1976, worn out by the
cheating ways of Barry Switzer and others, the line of succession
clearly pointed to Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   There was no good reason Campbell shouldn't have replaced Royal,
but the first telltale sign he wouldn't was a formal interview. He
and fellow assistant Ken Dabbs drove to the University of Texas
Tower in a heavy rainstorm. When they arrived, a gust of wind
hyperextended Campbell's umbrella, leaving him drenched and very
much distraught.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he was as respected a football coach as there was in the
nation. He was a true gentleman in every respect. He was
media-friendly and had a wit drier than a West Texas breeze. And,
above all, he had Royal's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the assistant coaches on Royal's first Texas staff in
1957 later became head coaches, Jim Pittman and Charley Shira among
them. Another, T Jones, became Texas Tech's athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 15, 1976, the heir apparent seemed such a foregone
conclusion that the city's ill-fated afternoon newspaper, the
Austin Citizen, printed a front- page story with the bold headline,
``It's Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   President Lorene Rogers and Board of Regents chairman, former
Gov. Allan Shivers, instead, turned to another former Royal
assistant, 38-year-old Fred Akers, who had the necessary
prerequisites. Turnaround season at Wyoming. Southwestern roots.
Deadly charm. Defiant chin.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Smith can name Bill Guthridge his successor in 1997, but
Darrell Royal wasn't afforded that privilege in 1976. The
54-year-old Campbell was out faster than yesterday's trash.
Secretaries openly cried. Staff members stoicly cleaned out their
desks. Royal assistant Spike Dykes called passing over Campbell
``the greatest injustice that's ever been done.'' Dabbs said it was
``like breaking up a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell deserved so much better. What followed was a decade of
acrimony that, along with the deterioration and eventual ruin of
the Southwest Conference, served to kick the underpinnings out of a
once-great, once-feared dynasty that was one of the bedrocks of
college football.
</P>
<P>
   Akers' teams competed hard and won big until the lingering
bitterness between the Royal and Akers camps completely engulfed
UT. Some 10 years later, Akers was dismissed despite flattering
numbers, and so, too, in turn were McWilliams and John Mackovic.
Their inability to return Texas to the ranks of the nation's elite
came partly as a result of weaker staffs, the antithesis of Royal's
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Campbell wouldn't have won enough either, this
legend-following being a rather dicey proposition. But when it came
to trusted, respected assistants and decent men, one clearly stood
out.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
