<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Just for Fun: Drawing tool is pressure-sensitive
 &HT;    By Yusuf Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ PenPartner, from Wacom, is a pressure-sensitive pen
and graphics tablet that can turn your computer into an art studio
_ or a devil's workshop.
</P>
<P>
   An easy way to point, click, draw, edit photos and personalize
projects, PenPartner can be used to create original works of art or
draw a mustache on your boss's computerized photo.
</P>
<P>
   Users can draw freehand, edit or trace images, and add their own
handwriting to almost anything. It can be used with a computer
mouse, or it can replace the mouse and be used to drag, drop,
double-click and zoom around the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's pressure-sensitive, this drawing tool responds to
every hand movement. Press harder for thicker and darker lines, or
lighter for thinner and more opaque lines.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like what you've drawn, turn the pen over and use
the eraser. The software automatically recognizes the eraser and
removes what you don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Bundled with Corel Print &AMP; Photo House, PenPartner has a
suggested retail price of $99.95.
</P>
<P>
   Stop those surges
</P>
<P>
   The SurgeArrest Notebook protector is a travel-size
surge-suppression device, designed to protect portable computers
from spikes and surges of electricity, which can cause hardware
damage and loss of data.
</P>
<P>
   Its maker, American Power Conversion, claims that sensitive
modem connections, such as PCMCIA cards, make laptops even more
susceptible to damaging power surges than their desktop cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Because the device is equipped with jacks for computer, modem
and telephone, users can retain the use of the phone without having
to unhook the notebook.
</P>
<P>
   The lightweight and compact suppressor can be easily carried in
a notebook carrying case or briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteed for life, the UL-approved unit also has a three-year
equipment-protection warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to begin shipping Monday, the Notebook protector has a
suggested retail price of $29.95. It can be seen at
http://www.apcc.com.
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme Tripmate
</P>
<P>
   The DeLorme Tripmate is an easy-to-use navigational device that
will help travelers find their location and directions anywhere in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A useful gadget for anyone with a portable computer, this
hand-held receiver links to the satellite navigational technology
of the Global Positioning System, developed by the U.S. military.
It can track your location in a city or on a deserted country road,
day or night.
</P>
<P>
   With this handy tool, there's no need to stop to ask for
directions or wonder if the exit or street you passed was where you
should have turned. The unit shows your position on a street-level
map and moves as you travel, displaying speed, direction of travel
and altitude.
</P>
<P>
   Tripmate, which operates on AA batteries or an optional
cigarette lighter adapter, retails for about $200 and is bundled
with a copy of Street Atlas USA.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the company's Web site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .delorme.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
