<HEADER>
A1845 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNLAP-SIDE17-COX     06-16 0310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNLAP-SIDE17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cloudy days for Sunbeam?
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ With Al Dunlap gone, will Sunbeam Corp.
stay?
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap's removal as chairman and CEO chief executive officer of
Sunbeam raises questions about the company's future in Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   But people familiar with the situation say Sunbeam, which
employs about 110 at its Delray Beach headquarters, is not likely
to leave. ``Why go through the pain and expense of relocating the
headquarters again,'' said Larry Pelton, president of the Business
Development Board of Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap moved Sunbeam's headquarters to Delray Beach from Fort
Lauderdale after he took over in 1996. He announced plans in April
to move Sunbeam to a new complex site in Boca Raton that would
house operations from the three companies Sunbeam bought in March.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam signed a 15-year lease for nearly 150,000 square feet at
Peninsula Executive Center, a two-building complex under
construction off Butts Road. The builder, CarrAmerica Realty Corp.,
said Monday that Dunlap's departure won't affect the project.
</P>
<P>
   But newly named CEO Jerry Levin indicated Monday that he may
pull back from Dunlap's plan to centralize all operations. ``My
feeling is that for Sunbeam, it won't work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean Sunbeam may not need to triple the 50,000 square
feet it now occupies in Delray Beach. In that case, the company
could stay in Delray Beach or move and use only part of the space
it's rented in Boca Raton. In either case, Sunbeam would need to
find a tenant for part or all of the Boca Raton space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lease is already fully executed and in place,'' said Jim
Peterson, CarrAmerica's regional vice president of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1846 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUNLAP-SUNBEAM17-COX     06-16 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNLAP-SUNBEAM17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunbeam gives 'Chain Saw Al' the ax
 &HT;    By Julie Waresh
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELRAY BEACH _ Al Dunlap, best known for laying off tens of
thousands in a ruthless formula for cutting costs, has himself been
fired as chairman and chief executive officer of Sunbeam Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Citing continued operating losses and the company's inability to
meet its own earnings forecasts, Sunbeam's board of directors said
recently it has lost confidence in Dunlap's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to restore Sunbeam's credibility,'' Director
Peter A. Langerman said from the appliance maker's Delray Beach
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap's ouster brings to a close a saga that began here in
1995, when the boisterous corporate gunslinger rode into town
dragging Scott Paper Co. and loudly proclaimed ``a great day for
Boca Raton.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Dunlap sold the stripped-down paper company after
eliminating 11,000 jobs, and its Boca Raton headquarters was
closed. Not long after that, he joined Sunbeam and moved it to
Delray Beach from Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   But what was to be Dunlap's crowning achievement _ the creation
of a consumer product powerhouse through the consolidation of
Sunbeam and three newly acquired companies _ has ended in failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``With what happened today, I don't think he'll ever work
again,'' one former employee of Sunbeam said Monday. ``He's
humiliated.''
</P>
<P>
   Langerman, who represents Sunbeam's largest shareholder,
investor Michael Price, will replace Dunlap as chairman. Jerry W.
Levin, former chairman and CEO of Revlon Inc. and Coleman Co., will
serve as CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Levin represents financier Ronald Perelman, the part-time Palm
Beach resident who in March became Sunbeam's second-largest
shareholder when he sold the company his interest in Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Sunbeam has reported a first-quarter loss of $44.6
million and warned that the red ink will spill into the second
quarter. And despite assurances from Dunlap that his plan will work
given time, the stock (NYSE: SOC) has tumbled 70 percent from a
12-month high of $52 in early March.
</P>
<P>
   It closed Monday at $15.75, down $2.31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine that Ron Perelman was happy,'' said Connie
Maneaty, an analyst with Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. in New York. ``Even
though he didn't have board representation at the time, he's a
force to be reckoned with.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dunlap met his match in Perelman, whom he reportedly
clashed with when the two met at Perelman's Palm Beach home late
last year during the initial negotiations on the Coleman deal.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Dunlap struck the $2.5 billion deal to buy Coleman,
along with smoke alarm maker First Alert and Mr. Coffee maker
Signature Brands USA, when he couldn't find a buyer for Sunbeam.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street had driven Sunbeam stock so high on faith in
Dunlap's record of richly rewarding shareholders that the company
was seen by prospective buyers as too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   So Dunlap, who acquired the nicknames ``Chain Saw Al'' and
``Rambo in Pin Stripes'' for his ruthless cost-cutting tactics,
decided to take a different approach: He would build the company
instead of dismantling it.
</P>
<P>
   But things quickly began to unravel. In April, Dunlap fired
consumer products chief Don Uzzi and said he expected to report
lower-than-expected sales as well as a loss for the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Monday at his Boca Raton home, Uzzi, a veteran of Quaker
Oats, PepsiCo and Procter &AMP; Gamble, said the board's decision
improves Sunbeam's prospects for success ``exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap unveiled a far-reaching cost-cutting plan on May 11 that
called for slashing the total three-company work force by more than
6,400 jobs to 9,500 and closing numerous plants, warehouses and
sales offices.
</P>
<P>
   But in a news release Monday, Sunbeam's board said it does not
expect the company to meet even the revised earnings forecasts
Dunlap released at that time: 5 to 10 cents a share for the quarter
that ends this month and $1 a share for the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think it was the earnings (that spurred Dunlap's
firing),'' said William Steele, an analyst with Buckingham Research
Group in San Francisco. ``The board must have felt uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Sunbeam's five independent directors met Saturday in New
York and set up a conference call with the two absent board
members: Dunlap and Sunbeam Chief Financial Officer Russell Kersh.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Charles M. Elson, a law professor at Stetson
University in St. Petersburgcq, made the motion to fire Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the motion, but it was a sentiment shared by everyone
on the board,'' Elson said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap did not return calls Monday to his Boca Raton home.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the company say Dunlap knew things were not
working, but refused to acknowledge the problems.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, two senior executives sent Dunlap a memo outlining
the dim outlook for sales and second-quarter earnings, according to
a source close to the company. But Dunlap refused to meet with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was known in the organization that you can't go to Al with
a problem,'' one former Sunbeam employee said. ``He just wanted
solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, it seems, was overconfident to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, Sunbeam's new CEO, said Monday that many of Sunbeam's
employees are working on compensation incentive systems that are
dependent on earnings-per-share targets.
</P>
<P>
   Because the company hasn't met the lofty financial goals, many
workers haven't been making much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a big morale booster,'' said Levin, who added that
he expects to work to ``set some realistic targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin, Sunbeam's new CEO, also said he will be working with
Sunbeam's major customers, which include discount chains Wal-Mart
and Kmart, to sort out the bloated inventories they have
accumulated. He declined to promise a quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of you who've worked with me before know I can be a
little slow to declare success,'' said Levin, who engineered
Revlon's turnaround for Perelman.
</P>
<P>
   The board denied Dunlap's removal was tied to concern over the
company's 1997 financial statements. A report by Barron's last week
said that 1997 profits were based largely on accounting tricks, a
charge denied by both Dunlap and company auditor Arthur Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   Steele, the Buckingham Research Group analysts, said he believes
there is no underlying problem with Sunbeam's business or its
brands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business just has to be run on a consistent long-term
viable strategic plan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Langerman, Sunbeam's new chairman, said Monday the board has
given Dunlap no severance pay and issues related to his employment
contract have been referred to the company's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Dunlap signed a lucrative three-year employment
deal with Sunbeam, which gives him $2 million a year in salary, a
grant of 300,000 shares of common stock and options to buy 3.75
million shares at $36.85 a share.
</P>
<P>
   That contract states that if Dunlap is fired for cause, he will
have the right to exercise the vested portion of his latest option
award, as well as all previous options, for 90 days after his
firing. If Sunbeam's stock doesn't rebound in that time, the
options from his new contract will be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunlap, who walked away from Scott Paper $100 million
richer, won't be hurting for money. He'll still feel the sting of
losing a job, however.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good thing, says J.E. Smith, mayor of Bay Springs,
Miss., a town of 2,200 that lost 350 jobs when Dunlap closed its
two Sunbeam plants in 1996 and early this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he won't wonder where he's going to get his next
meal, like a lot of my people,'' Smith said. ``I thought about
calling him and asking if he needed any work. I need someone over
here to mow the parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Michael Utley contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
