<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1852 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-RUSSIA-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-16 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RUSSIA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VISION OF RUSSIA'S FUTURE: ART VS. DESPOTISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toward the end of his tour of Russian culture, James Billington
suggests that Russia's future will be decided by a clash between
art and despotism. That conventional coda does not do justice to
the more complex if less wishful history that he tells, which
demonstrates that art can be in the service of despotism as well as
at war with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Face of Russia'' begins Wednesday night with the
mysteriously beautiful icons, the oldest and perhaps deepest
expressions of Russian culture, which symbolized a religion that
served many generations of czars and resisted assaults by several
generations of Communists.
</P>
<P>
   And it ends with the movie classics of Sergei Eisenstein, which
served the Communist cause until they ran afoul of Joseph Stalin.
If anything, this series resists the conventional worship of art as
liberator and confirms that the relation between art and power
remains ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   It's a visually rich tour. Billington, the Librarian of Congress
and an eminent historian of Russian culture (as well as the author
of a companion book to this series), ranges from 10th-century
religious art up to today's moviemakers, with pauses along the way
at lovingly photographed onion-domed cathedrals and baroque
palaces, musical masterpieces in performance and great novels in
intriguing adaptations.
</P>
<P>
   He is in search of connections, between the works of art and the
larger culture, between Russia and the West, between power and
creation.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable and energetic though he is, as a television
personality and critic, Billington lacks the forceful individuality
of such masters of the tube as Kenneth Clark and Robert Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   His observations are never less than informed and informative _
he is especially interesting about the origins and enduring
significance of the icons _ but rarely exciting. His performance
and language smack of the lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The contemporaries whom he calls on to lend grand meanings to
the proceedings tend to settle for art-appreciation cliches:
Mstislav Rostropovich, the cellist and conductor, says Mussorgsky
gives us the Russian soul; Vladimir Mirzoev, a theater director,
says Gogol helps readers understand their own motivations.
</P>
<P>
   The result is edifying in an easy-to-take way, but references to
the continuing power struggle in Russia often seem to be straining
for relevance.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is much here to be savored, one craves to be
unsettled. I was grateful for what is probably an overwrought
assessment by a theater director who, by way of both tribute and
condemnation, calls Eisenstein's films ``a gigantic advertising
agency of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that without the ``false memory of events'' they
imposed, ``the Bolsheviks would never have succeeded.'' His
conclusion: ``We owe to the cinema the entire Communist regime.''
Now there's a claim for the power of art to delude that ought to
trouble its worshipers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE FACE OF RUSSIA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Wednesday night, June 24 and July 1 at 10. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WETA Washington, D.C., Library of Congress and Malone Gill
Productions in association with Public Media Inc. and Media-Most,
producers. Michael Gill, producer. Phylis Geller, WETA executive
producer. Murray Grigor, director. Dr. James Billington, writer.
Karen Kenton, WETA associate producer. &QL; 
WITH: Dr. Billington. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
