<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAYLONJENNINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUMORS ABOUT WAYLON JENNINGS' RETIREMENT HAVE BEEN GREATLY
EXAGGERATED
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-WAYLONJENNINGS-CD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps it was just because Waylon Jennings' contemporaries
seemed to be in decline during the past two years: Carl Perkins
died, Johnny Cash was found to have Parkinson's disease, Merle
Haggard had heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   So where was Waylon?
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, doctors suggested he take some time off due to
health issues including diabetes and heart bypass surgery, both
dating to the '80s. So he did. And suddenly, the outlaw legend and
Buddy Holly protege became the object of speculation. Would he
retire? Was he dying?
</P>
<P>
   The talk is the only thing that's bothering him now, he says. He
has a new album, ``Closing in on the Fire,'' released Tuesday. He
turned 61 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hanging in there,'' Jennings said during an interview last
week from his Nashville office, miffed at the mention of that
R-word, ``retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, to borrow a line from an earlier Jennings hit,
``Maybe I'm used, but baby, I ain't used up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennings still intends to do the occasional show. But with the
new album; a voice-over for a Nickelodeon children's series, ``The
Angry Beavers''; the re-release of his '93 kids' album, ``Cowboys,
Sisters, Rascals &AMP; Dirt''; an appearance in a new
``Highwaymen''-based movie; and a collaboration with Jerry Reed,
Bobby Bare and Mel Tillis, Jennings isn't lacking for things to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a lot busier than I intended to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings is on Ark 21, an independent, eclectic-format label
based in Sherman Oaks, Calif., after years on RCA Records and
shorter stints on other labels, including MCA and CBS/Epic.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Copeland, Ark 21 chairman, said Jennings is ``as vital and
interesting today as when he first started,'' and praised his new
album as ``one of the best he's ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   It includes collaborations with Sheryl Crow, Travis Tritt, Marty
Stuart, Sting, Mark Knopfler and Jennings' longtime friend, Carl
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, too, seemed pleased with the project, which includes
five songs he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   His other projects are quite eclectic:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Old Dogs'' with Jerry Reed, Bobby Bare and Mel Tillis, which
will be telemarketed: ``That could set music back 20 years. Shel
Silverstein wrote all the songs, so they're great songs, but I
wasn't there when they passed out the songs, so I got all the dirty
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Highwaymen'' movie project, called ``The Long Kill,''
isn't a true ``Highwaymen,'' Jennings said, because Johnny Cash
didn't participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get killed early, and then do the narration,'' he said.
``Willie started in on me about five or six years ago about this. I
did a great dying scene _ just kerplunk, and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Cowboys, Sisters, Rascals &AMP; Dirt'': ``A lot of that stuff is
about myself, and a lot of it is about kids I've known.''
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins covers country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
