<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-COX </SLUG>
     SENATE PANEL DELAYS DECISION ON AIR FORCE
SECRETARY NOMINATION
 &HT;     By SHANNON JOYCE 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Armed Services Committee will meet in a
rare executive session this month to discuss whether or not Daryl
Jones, nominated as Air Force secretary, has been cleared of
wrongdoing in a Florida bond sale inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a Florida state senator, answered the committee's
questions for two hours Tuesday but failed to provide proof that he
is no longer subject of an inquiry into a $200 million bond sale
last October by a Florida securities firm to finance an expansion
of Miami International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   No decision will be made on Jones's nomination until after the
committee meets in the private session, said John DeCrosta, a
spokesman for the panel. He said that would take place before the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Securities and Exchange Commission is conducting an
inquiry into the airport bond sale, and the Miami New Times, a
weekly newspaper, questioned whether Jones worked as a unsalaried
employee or a paid consultant for Douglas James Securities, Inc..
</P>
<P>
   Jones said someone from the Securities and Exchange Commission
told him he had been cleared in the inquiry, but would not give the
person's name during his public conformation hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he worked as an investment banker for Douglas James
Securities, one of several Miami firms that help the city with bond
issues, but left to pursue other interests. When the city wanted to
remove Douglas James from the list of firms doing bond work, Jones
said he came back as a municipal finance professional to help the
firm keep its relationship with the city.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the firm did keep its contract with city, and as part
of a usual rotation, oversaw the sale of the airport bonds.
</P>
<P>
   A 1977 graduate of the Air Force Academy, Jones served for seven
years as an F-4 fighter pilot before entering the reserves. He was
elected to Florida's House of Representatives in 1990 and to its
Senate in 1992. President Clinton nominated Jones for the Air
Force's top civilian slot in October.
</P>
<P>
   While other senators at the hearing asked Jones to simply
explain what happened in connection with the bond sale, Sen. John
Warner, R-Va., questioned Jones about his duties at the firm, what
kind of benefits he received, and how he was paid.
</P>
<P>
   Warner and other committee members questioned Jones on
professional problems such as an incorrect line on his resume
saying he still is a reserve fighter pilot and press reports that
his former colleagues called him ``an unsafe pilot with attitude
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always tried to conduct myself in a way that treats
everyone with dignity and respect,'' Jones said. ``I can't even
begin to venture into the minds of other people as to why they
would do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he chose to stop flying several years ago when a
state congressional election, a new law practice and a growing
family made it too difficult to devote a week each month to flight
training _ not because his superior officer threatened to yank his
flight status. As for the outdated line on his resume, he said it
was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also outlined his vision for the Air Force during the
hearing, calling the F-22 stealth fighter one of the service's top
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delicate battle between readiness and modernization is our
biggest challenge,'' Jones said. ``We can support modernization
only if we reduce the cost of doing business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said two of the biggest problems facing the Air Force are
cost overruns and delays in the development of the F-22 and a
bloated infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have that plane as soon as possible,'' Jones
said. ``It shouldn't take 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he supported consolidating bases to make more money
available for research, acquisitions, and personnel and ``get the
optimum use of our resources.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
