</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-MERGERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SAYS MERGER WAVE WON'T HURT ECONOMY OR CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``w'' and ``f'' categories.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned
Congress and government regulators Tuesday not to intervene too
quickly in the current wave of multibillion dollar mergers sweeping
some U.S. industries.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan told the Senate Judiciary Committee that the mergers
should have little impact on the overall U.S. economy and on
American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., who asked, ``What
happens to the people in these mergers?'' the Fed chairman admitted
that job losses would result. But he added that the nation's
growing economy should be able to handle the displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that 300,000 U.S. workers lose their jobs each week but
said that with the creation of new jobs the unemployment rate
stands at a 28-year low of 4.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effects of the present merger wave on concentration have
yet to be determined, but there is little reason to expect their
influence will differ substantially from the merger wave of the
early 1980s, which produced at most a slight increase in
manufacturing concentration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was joined by several top antitrust officials at the
committee's hearing on what impact the recent mergers could have on
the economy. He noted that the nation is now experiencing its fifth
wave of mergers since 1900, the others having occurred at the turn
of the century, in the 1920s, 1960s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Justice Department, the United States is
expected to see $1.75 trillion dollars worth of mergers this year,
more than the combined value of mergers in all of the years between
1990 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have expressed concern that a number of big bank
mergers could force consumers to pay higher bank fees because of
reduced competition.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said that while the mergers had reduced the overall
number of banks nationally, the number competing in any given
region remained about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also criticized government antitrust regulators for
trying to prevent mergers based on sketchy industry forecasts. ``At
the end of the day, I would have a lot of problems with preventing
mergers based on the predictions of how a market will evolve,''
Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Congress and government antitrust officials should wait
to see how mergers affect the economy before attempting to break up
any of them.
</P>
<P>
   But Joel Klein, antitrust chief at the Justice Department, and
Robert Pitofsky, chairman of the Federal Trade Commission, argued
against waiting until after a merger occurs to determine whether it
was a good or bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I radically disagree with waiting,'' Pitofsky said. ``If you
wait until after the companies have come together and the employees
have been fired, it is very difficult and expensive to break them
up again.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who challenged 31 mergers in 1997, told the committee
that the growing number and size of mergers ``can be expected to
have long-term effects on markets and on the future of our
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said his division would challenge only those mergers
that regulators believed would raise prices or limit competition.
``The key to what we do is that we focus on competition, not
size,'' Klein said. ``Our economy is the most powerful in the
world, and that is due in large part to our belief as a country in
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan attributed the growing number of mergers to the
increasing use of computers and other high-tech equipment in many
American firms.
</P>
<P>
   He said technology has allowed companies in many industries to
expand nationally and globally, which has led them to look for ways
to enter new markets. Instead of trying to push their way into the
new markets, many companies simply buy or merge with established
firms in the areas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent weeks, banking giant Citicorp announced a megamerger
with brokerage-insurer Travelers Group that valued each company at
$68.9 billion, the biggest merger in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NationsBank Corp. and BankAmerica Corp. announced a
$57.2 billion marriage to create a coast-to-coast banking giant.
</P>
<P>
   Banc One Corp. and First Chicago NBD Corp. announced a $57.2
billion merger to form the dominant bank in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., unveiled a bill that
would toughen the conditions that large regional telephone
companies must meet to merge. The bill would require approval by
the U.S. attorney general of any merger of a large local company _
one that serves more than 5 percent of the nation's telephones _
with a similar firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
