<HEADLINE>
THE WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 17, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It will be unsettled over much of the Northeast again on
Wednesday, as a large dip in the jet stream persists. Bands of
showers will sweep across northern New England, buoyed by a flow of
moist air from the Atlantic. Eastward-moving showers and
thunderstorms will ignite over the Appalachians, as the mountains
act as an elevated source of heat for rising parcels of warm air.
Meanwhile, a few stronger storms will accompany a cold front
approaching the coast as it dislodges the sultry mass that is in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Although a front lay draped from the Carolina coast to the
Tennessee valley, sinking air currents and ample sunshine will
bring little risk for rain from the Deep South. It will stay hot.
Florida will remain parched, with brush ires continuing. North of
the front, weak high pressure will prompt sunshine in the parts of
the Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous low pressure for the season will crawl northward
through the Plains states. Clusters of showers and thunderstorms
will precede a surge of hot air in the central Plains. Meanwhile,
isolated severe storms will fire up in Texas and Oklahoma, where
dry air east of the southern Rockies meets with humid Gulf of
Mexico air.
</P>
<P>
   A stalled front will be the focus for frequent rains from the
northern Plains to the northern and central Rockies. Downpours will
locally produce more than two inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Over the far West, sunshine will be abundant with seasonal
temperatures in most places. However, patches of morning fog and
low clouds will interfere with sunshine along parts of the Pacific
coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Carolina Ice
</P>
<P>
   Ice has been falling from the sky with unusual frequency around
Wilmington, N.C. During the past 40 days, four days with hail have
been recorded at Wilmington, tying the record for the most days
with hail in any year since records began there 127 year ago.
Indeed, only 94 days have had hail in the record that spans over
46,000 days. Hail is a ball of ice that forms when rain drops
collect and freeze onto partially melted snow flakes high in a
thunderstorm. Strong updrafts can prolong the time hail remains
aloft, allowing it to grow further as additional rain drops freeze
onto it.
</P>
</TEXT>
