A1905 &Cx1f; kan-z
a f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CASINO-VOTE-2ND-TAKE-     06-16 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-VOTE-2ND-TAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI ANTI-GAMBLING FORCES GEAR UP FOR VOTE ON SLOT MACHINES ON
`BOATS IN MOATS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia: The tangled case affects 10 of the state's 16
riverboat casinos.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, only the Argosy Riverside is not
threatened by judicial or Missouri Gaming Commission sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   In a worst-case scenario _ defeat in court and at the polls in
November _ the offending casinos would be forced to unplug their
slots. That would slash revenues by as much 70 percent and almost
certainly force the closing of some boats.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign spokesman Don Poston said the boats' strategy is
simple: ``Let the people decide, and take it out of the courts'
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry won at the polls four years ago when 54 percent of
voters approved slot machines and other games of chance, such as
roulette.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, St. Louis-area gambling foes argued
successfully before the Supreme Court that under the constitutional
language approved by voters in 1994, games of chance could be
played only on boats floating ``upon'' the main channels of the
Missouri and Mississippi rivers _ not moored behind floodgates or
in off-river, man-made ponds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skill'' games, such as craps and blackjack, were not affected.
</P>
<P>
   After months of legal sparring, the Gaming Commission is
expected to set hearings later this month to determine which boats
comply with the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Any adverse decisions are certain to be appealed to the state
courts and ultimately to federal court _ unless voters
short-circuit the legal conflict on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Fridkin, a Kansas City lawyer for Harrah's four Missouri
casinos, said the central issue is unfair treatment. The boats, he
said, rigorously obeyed the Gaming Commission's licensing rules and
spent more than a billion dollars on their casinos. Then the rules
were changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fairness issue...that is a federal question,'' Fridkin
said. ``That's a substantial part of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also at the heart of the appeal the casinos will make to
voters.
</P>
<P>
   But not all casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Missouri Riverboat Gaming Association and the American
Gaming Association are sitting this one out.
</P>
<P>
   Some casinos, such as the Argosy, stand to gain if their
off-river competitors are put at a disadvantage or forced to close.
Such bottom-line considerations have neutralized the state and
national industry groups on many issues.
</P>
<P>
   Only four casino companies, Harrah's, Station Casinos, Players
International and the Flamingo Hilton, are paying the tab for the
Winner/Wagner political consulting group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a states' rights issue,'' said Frank J. Fahrenkopf Jr.,
president of the national industry group. ``The people of Missouri
are entitled to not have gaming. If that's what they decide, so be
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Poston said the campaign's strategy and slogans were still
taking shape and he wouldn't discuss details.
</P>
<P>
   But a flier being distributed by Station Casinos in Kansas City
offers a glimpse at what voters can expect to see in ads and on
television commercials:
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaming has invested more than $1.3 billion in Missouri's
riverboat properties...Changing the rules now is totally unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help us save your favorite games. Help us save our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   If the riverboats lose in court and at the polls, operators
would be left with almost no choice but to offer only games of
skill, as they did before the 1994 vote. Or they could opt to make
costly physical changes to their buildings and riverfront land to
meet the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The latter would certainly trigger a new round of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The `Ohio plan'
</P>
<P>
   For six years Grey has criss-crossed the country campaigning
against legalized gambling on behalf of his church and as spokesman
for the National Coalition Against Legalized Gambling, which he
helped found four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He's lost plenty of elections. But his movement has also won its
share. Grey takes credit for the crushing defeat of a riverboat
gambling measure in Ohio two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   That campaign spawned a strategy that Grey has since dubbed
``the Ohio plan,'' which he's putting into effect in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Grey was in Columbia on two recent weekends for annual
conferences of the state's United Methodist Church, where he began
organizing grass-roots workers for the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in 1994 loose-knit anti-casino volunteers still
attracted more than 46 percent of the vote against a professionally
managed campaign that cost the casinos millions.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with that 46 percent, Grey boldly predicts a 60 percent
victory this year.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri is a showdown, Grey said, laden with national
implications about whether Americans are becoming weary of hometown
gambling parlors and are willing to shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   A loss, he said, ``would be a crippling blow to our argument
that there is a backlash out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Victory, however, would send a message to gambling's nerve
centers in Las Vegas and on Wall Street that an era of casino
expansion is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom's been saying that for years,'' Fahrenkopf said. ``He
needs to get some new material.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
