<SLUG> BC-CASINO-VOTE-1ST-TAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI ANTI-GAMBLING FORCES GEAR UP FOR VOTE ON SLOT MACHINES ON
`BOATS IN MOATS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA _ Many in Missouri's religious community are itching
for a ballot-box rematch against the casinos. They're going to get
one.
</P>
<P>
   But this time _ in November when Missourians are expected to
vote on retroactively legalizing slot machines on ``boats in
moats'' _ church leaders say the gloves are coming off.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are bitterly opposed to gambling and will do all we can as
a church to see that this referendum in November is defeated,''
said Ann Brookshire Sherer, resident bishop of the statewide United
Methodist Church, 190,000 members strong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, an underfunded and mostly church-driven coalition came
close to defeating a casino-sponsored ballot measure to legalize
slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   What's different this time is that Missouri's anti-gambling
establishment appears to be organized as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Under a strategy unfolded at meetings on two recent weekends in
a Columbia Holiday Inn, the Methodist church is training hundreds
of its members to serve as the campaign's ``precinct captains.''
</P>
<P>
   They will go home and recruit other church, business and civic
leaders to stage public debates, distribute literature, raise money
and get out the vote on Nov. 3. The first volunteer training
sessions already are set for June 29 and 30 at Methodist churches
in Kansas City and Lee's Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Other religion-based groups are signing on, including early
support from leaders of the multidenominational Missouri Christian
Leadership Forum and the Christian Civic Foundation of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we didn't have last time was a campaign from the bottom
up,'' said Tom Grey, a Hanover, Ill., Methodist clergyman and icon
of the anti-gambling movement. His presence alone invigorates the
Missouri campaign and forces it into the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Off-river gambling facilities _ boats in moats _ have been
licensed by state regulators since 1995. But they were outlawed by
the Missouri Supreme Court last fall in a decision that stunned the
gaming industry.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting back, the casinos are now close to gathering the
109,000 signatures they need to force a question onto the fall
ballot that would nullify the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gambling industry tries to portray us as narrow-minded
moralists,'' Sherer said. ``But legalized gambling is not a
personal morality issue. It is a community justice issue....
Gambling preys on the poor, the old and the lonely.... It hurts our
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry has well-practiced answers ready for its critics _
symbolized in the name of its 1998 campaign committee:
``Missourians for Fairness &AMP; Jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry also has its own cadre of precinct captains _ more
than 8,000 employees whose jobs are at stake. Earlier this month
casino workers in St. Louis announced formation of a statewide,
pro-gambling citizens' political action committee _ called AFFIRM _
that will work for passage of the moat measure this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos also will tout industry-financed studies that
attempt to debunk critics' claims that they hurt the economy and
foster compulsive gambling.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside City Administrator Ann Daniels is one of many public
officials whose jurisdictions are reaping millions in new tax
dollars from the casinos and who side with them.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago last month to testify before a congressional panel
studying gambling, she said, ``I would share our problems with you
now, but there have been no problems'' since the Argosy casino
opened for business four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were prepared (for) prostitution, robberies, domestic
violence, bankruptcy and on and on,'' Daniels testified. ``No
increases in any of these problem areas have occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Academic studies and news organization investigations, including
one last year by The Kansas City Star, have found pockets of
increased crime and other social problems _ but not uniformly in
every casino city, and certainly not to the dire straits that some
critics claim.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsements such as Daniels' will be crafted into ads by the
same national political consulting group _ Winner/Wagner &AMP;
Mandabach Campaigns _ the industry used in 1994 to persuade
Missouri voters to legalize slots.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is survival for the casinos,'' Grey said. ``It's
winner-take-all in Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   Slots at stake
</P>
<P>
   The gambling industry has suffered a setback in the ongoing
court battle over boats in moats. The tangled case affects 10 of
the state's 16 riverboat casinos.
MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
