<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-HARVEST-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS WHEAT HARVEST WILL BE BIG, BUT IT MAY BE DIFFICULT TO DEAL
WITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is expected to be the 10th-largest wheat harvest in Kansas
history is roaring to life.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state agricultural statisticians reported Monday
that, despite rain delays over many fields, about 2 percent of an
estimated 394 million-bushel crop has been harvested, mostly in the
far southeastern and south-central part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   That 2 percent represents more than twice the progress farmers
made through mid-June last year, but it trails a longer-term 3
percent average.
</P>
<P>
   The harvest may be an awkward one for farmers and Kansas to deal
with, some observers predict.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a promising start, reduced plantings and earlier weather
losses are going to leave many Kansas farmers with much less wheat
to sell than they became used to the nine times the harvest topped
400 million bushels.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bad news, because prices are low, and it means they
can't simply sell a little extra wheat'' to improve their cash
flows, said Mark Nelson, a Kansas Farm Bureau economist in
Manhattan. ``Plus, we've got transportation and storage problems,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Grain-hauling rail cars and elevator storage space are expected
to be scarcer than normal this season. If those expectations are
accurate, extra costs could push grain prices below even the
extremely low levels that federal economists recently projected.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Kansas, farmer or otherwise, would be immune from a
disappointing harvest, said Jim Ragan, a Kansas State University
economics professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wheat prices are an important indicator of how much the entire
state's economy will grow,'' Ragan said.
</P>
<P>
   And while wheat prices aren't yet low enough to tip the state's
economy downward, they have been a drag on potential statewide
economic expansion for several months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Look for that to continue, at least until Asia's economies
improve, which isn't expected any time soon, said Karen Fegley, a
trade specialist with the National Association of Wheat Growers in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not an optimistic picture,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asian countries buy about 40 percent of the farm goods U.S.
producers export, Fegley said. Turmoil in Asian economies has
chilled that buying a lot and helped push U.S. wheat prices to
their lowest level in seven years, Fegley said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Agriculture economists estimate that Kansas
farmers will receive no more than $3 a bushel for their wheat
during the coming marketing year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, there is Pakistan,'' Fegley said.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan is the third-largest international buyer, after Egypt
and Japan, for the wheat raised by American farmers. But wheat
sales to Pakistan this year may be shut off because of trade
sanctions being imposed after last month's nuclear tests in that
country.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is proposing legislation that would allow the sales.
But Pakistan's own crop is larger than usual, and the country is
expected to buy less wheat from all its suppliers, Fegley said.
</P>
<P>
   At midday Monday back in Kansas, combines and trucks and the
crews that run them were busily harvesting fields scattered across
a broad wedge of southern Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The northern edge of the most active harvesting runs across the
state from near Liberal (400 miles southwest of Kansas City near
the Oklahoma border) to Hutchinson (about 200 miles nearer to
Kansas City) to Chanute (about 100 miles south of Lawrence), say
crop watchers at the Kansas Association of Wheat Growers in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Hit-or-miss thundershowers across the state and pockets of grain
still not ripe enough to harvest lend a spatter-painted texture to
progress in many areas, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But give us another good day and we'll be more than 50 percent
done around here,'' said Martin Hampel, a state wheat harvest
coordinator in Kingman, near the center of the harvest surge.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the first fields to be harvested have yielded beautiful
wheat by industry standards.
</P>
<P>
   Yields per acre reportedly have ranged from near the 39-bushel
average projected for Kansas to almost twice that much. Test
weights, which measure how much potentially usable wheat is in each
bushel, have been running at or above a federally specified
60-pound standard. Protein and moisture levels, which are two other
important indicators of quality, also are described as being close
to ideal in many places.
</P>
<P>
   But this harvest perfection seems unlikely to last much longer,
crop watchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers haven't yet done much cutting in fields farther north
and west where frost devastated a federally estimated 100,000 acres
of wheat over the Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And Kansas Agricultural Statistics, the agency that issued the
harvest progress estimate Monday, also reported that 2 percent less
of the wheat still standing was in the same good-to-excellent
pre-harvest growing condition as a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, about 65 percent of the state's wheat crop still is
rated in good or excellent condition, the statisticians estimated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1801EDT &QL; 
