<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAYLONJENNINGS-CD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD WAYLON, FRESH NEW CUTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies WAYLON JENNINGS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SHIRLEY JINKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Waylon Jennings sets out to unite country, rock and blues, as
well as reclaim his territory as an innovator, on his first new
album in two years, ``Closing in on the Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Give him the first objective hands down: Few artists can cross
those three genres so easily. As for innovation, Is he really a
groundbreaker, or does it just sound that way next to the
pop-country stuff on the radio?
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way: He's perhaps one of the few country artists
who would think to collaborate with Sheryl Crow, Travis Tritt,
Marty Stuart, Sting and Mark Knopfler, all on one album.
</P>
<P>
   The title cut, by steamy bluesman Tony Joe White, has sinewy
electric guitar work that draws listeners in on a harmonica's
breath. Jennings' vocals sound like a shadow of himself, a nasty
blues whisper.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings and Travis Tritt trade tempos and vocals on the
Kostas-Kelly Willis-penned ``I Know About Me, Don't Know About
You,'' a roadhouse duet.
</P>
<P>
   Willis isn't the only Texas singer-songwriter represented on the
album. Kimmie Rhodes' sweet ``Be Mine,'' garnished with Mark
Knopfler's guitar solo, is a simple delight.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings' own incisive work is represented on five of the 12
cuts, including the companionable ``Best Friends of Mine,'' written
about his buds ranging from Hank Williams Jr. to Buddy Holly.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most tender songs Jennings has ever done is the waltz
``Just Watch Your Mama and Me,'' which he said took all of an hour
to write, so deeply personal is the message.
</P>
<P>
   Other Jennings originals include the autobiographical ``Back
Home Where I Come From''; a lighthearted ``Easy Money'' and ``The
Blues Don't Care,'' written by Jennings and Gary Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing in on the Fire'' has its flaws, though. Most glaring
is the Sting cut, ``She's Too Good for Me.'' If only Sting would
stay away from country music. (Remember the Toby Keith-Sting
collaboration?) Perhaps Sheryl Crow should, too, if the best she
can do is the '60s pop chorus on that clunker.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness for the Mick Jagger-Keith Richards-penned cut
``No Expectations,'' a 1968 song with a true honky-tonk feel and no
awkward guest stars. Marty Stuart contributes guitar.
</P>
<P>
   The rockabilly veteran Carl Smith is anything but awkward when
he vocalizes with Jennings on Kevin Welch's ``Untitled Waltz,''
with the fun line ``We all got where we are as fast as we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Audio liner notes are offered on track 12, and it's just as
interesting to hear a purring Jennings tell stories about the album
and its cuts, as it is to hear them performed:
</P>
<P>
   ``My life hasn't been without humor,'' he drawls, amid
background laughter, ``and I've tried to be sexy the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, ``Closing in on the Fire'' is a true Jennings
sampler, and should allay any fears about the state of his health
or musical commitment. He sounds fit and motivated, and laudably
has achieved the right balance: enough familiarity to be
recognizably and reliably Waylon Jennings, and enough innovation to
be fresh.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Artist: Waylon Jennings
</P>
<P>
   CD: ``Closing in on the Fire''
</P>
<P>
   Label: Ark 21 Records
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 stars
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Shirley Jinkins covers country music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
