<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING ON MITSUBISHI TOOK COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I know a lot of lawyers. I'm married to one. So I'm not naive
about lawsuits. They're usually tedious, time-consuming and
unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes they're necessary. A case in point is the suit the
Equal Employment Opportunity Commission brought against Mitsubishi
Motors in April 1996 and won last week.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, women and men are harassed at work. Most suffer in
silence because they don't know their rights or because they fear
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   It takes courage to file a harassment complaint with the EEOC.
It takes strength to withstand the depositions, the denials and in
many cases the retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders what was more difficult for the women working at the
Mitsubishi plant in Normal, Ill. _ to tolerate the repeated
harassment or to withstand the criticism and death threats they
received after the federal agency sued Mitsubishi.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Mitsubishi management initially denied the
allegations and even tried to convince workers and the community
that the women were a threat to their high-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Employees responded by defending the company. You know they
said, ``Boys will be boys.'' They ignored the fact that male
workers and supervisors kissed and fondled the women, called them
``whores'' and worse, demanded sexual acts, and retaliated against
women who refused.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi even persuaded thousands of workers to attend a
company-sponsored picnic with free buses and free lunches to
protest at the Chicago EEOC office.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Mitsubishi isn't denying anything anymore. Last week the
company agreed to pay a record $34 million to settle the claims of
repeated harassment. It is by far the largest sexual harassment
settlement for the EEOC and covers women who have worked at the
plant since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The consent decree, which is subject to federal court approval,
also requires the company to provide mandatory sexual harassment
training to employees and investigate allegations of harassment
within three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   EEOC Chairman Paul M. Igasaki warned other companies that ``the
Mitsubishi situation is not unique, and no employer should assume
that it can't happen in my company.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week's settlement is not only a victory for the women at
Mitsubishi but for all of us. Sexual harassment isn't just illegal,
it's intolerable. No one should have to experience such horrendous
working conditions to support their families.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it usually takes courageous women such as those
at Mitsubishi to file lawsuits and multimillion-dollar settlements
to persuade businesses to change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1918 &Cx1f; kan-z
a k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      06-16 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY'S END IS NO TIME TO BE ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wind fell and the pond, stirred to a chop in afternoon, lay
perfectly still as the long evening came on.
</P>
<P>
   Red-winged blackbirds whistled from the reeds. A handsome little
snake, green as emerald, etched his sinuous way across the surface
just ahead.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a better way to spend a quiet hour or two than in a
boat, on a piece of water you know as well as you know that face in
the mirror. But if there is, it doesn't come readily to mind.
</P>
<P>
   A cool front had dipped down from the northern plains, bringing
with it a badly needed rain. Even as I'd pushed the little johnboat
out from the bank and through the cattails there had come a last
pelting of big drops.
</P>
<P>
   Then that shower blew on past as well, and the sky began showing
broken patches of blue. Except for birdsong and the creaking of the
oarlocks, the silence was absolute.
</P>
<P>
   It's an old pond, that one _ built most of 30 years ago, where
the corner of a field dips down toward the next man's land. Because
it lies in the open, unshaded by bordering trees, it comes awake
earlier in the season than other waters on the place.
</P>
<P>
   Deep and clear, fed by runoff from untilled grassland, it has
been wonderfully productive. I have fished it with my daughters
through all their ages, and with a good many friends.
</P>
<P>
   Even when I'm by myself those memories are with me in the boat.
</P>
<P>
   I had come to the country on other business. Somehow the day had
gotten away, and I'd considered not going to the pond at all. But
then I remembered what a man once said about hunting: that a day
when you might have followed the dog, but didn't, was a day you'd
never see again.
</P>
<P>
   So there I was, rod in hand, dropping the bass bug close against
the reeds. There'd be time for two, maybe three circuits of the
shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   It's curious, how little the excitement of it changes through
the years. The skipped heartbeat when the fish's weight is first
felt and line is stripped from the reel in that initial bullish
run. The thrill's no different today than it was in boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   What's changed is that the catching matters less, especially
since nearly all those brought to boat are freed to grow and give
battle another day. It's enough to be attached for a while _ to
feel that wildness at the tippet's end.
</P>
<P>
   This one was a female largemouth, heavy-bodied, a wonder of a
fish. I grasped her lower lip and slipped the hook free without
lifting her from the water. Released, she sank away and vanished
with a flash.
</P>
<P>
   One like that is enough. I put down the rod and took up my
coffee, gone cold in the cup.
</P>
<P>
   The late sun had dropped below what remained of clouds, and
threw long shadows of the cattails dark across the glassy pond. The
color of the water changed with the sky, deepening finally to
purple.
</P>
<P>
   A bullfrog boomed from the near shore. From across the way a
rival answered.
</P>
<P>
   That's a fine hour, just before the light goes out, but also a
melancholy one. You think of everything and everyone, happy things
and sad _ of times gone, and people gone, and mistakes made, and
chances of one kind or other let slip away.
</P>
<P>
   And it's always then, with darkness closing, that one would be
most grateful for a little company. But there wasn't any. So, not
lingering longer, I rowed ashore, pulled the boat up and hurried to
the car.
</P>
<P>
   One ought to fish in the early mornings, when the first light is
just coming and the whole day lies bright ahead, I was thinking
then.
</P>
<P>
   Or else not fish alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
