A1932 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-MSKUBE18-COX     06-16 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-MSKUBE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Kolsches prove perfect for sipping in the summertime
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 18: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In France, law requires a winemaker's pledge of honesty. The
appellation controlee not only assures the buyer that the grapes
are from the region claimed, but also prohibits outsiders from
claiming to produce the same wine.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the ancient German city of Cologne does a similar
practice exist in brewing. In a country that enjoys dozens of
regional beer styles, each different from the next, the only place
you'll find a Kolschbier is Koln (Cologne in German) and
surrounding towns.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the darker Altbiers of nearby Dusseldorf and the
spritzy white beers of Berlin, Kolsch is the least familiar of
German styles in the United States. For one thing, it's an ale,
top-fermented, and not a bottom-fermenting lager like most German
beer. But it's a different kind of ale (an English word Germans
never use), light as a sister's kiss, pale as summer corn, served
in a cylindrical 7-ounce glass with no ornamentation.
</P>
<P>
   In Cologne, you don't drink a Kolschbier from a mug, a stein or
a conical pilsner glass; you drink from what looks like a tall
juice glass. The size and simplicity of the glass, like the color
of the beer, suggest lightness. ``I have on more than one occasion
seen a waiter help himself to a glass in one swallow,'' Michael
Jackson writes in his ``Beer Companion.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolsch is drunk year-round in Cologne, even during the
Rhineland's cold, wet winters, when other palates (mine, at least)
might hope for something more robust.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is a different matter, and now Atlantans have the
opportunity to sample a German style that's light but not Lite.
Thunder Head, an enterprising upstart among the area's beer
distributors, has brought H.C. Berger's Mountain Kolsch to retail
shelves, and a Kolsch also went on tap last week at Phoenix Brewing
Company in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   H.C. Berger, based in Fort Collins, Colo., is one of the few
American craft brewers that offer a Kolsch _ and the proprietary
name isn't the only reason. This is a style whose delicacy is hard
to bring off. Some, in deference to the Cologne Association of
Brewers, call theirs Kalsch rather than Kolsch; others,
Kolsch-style.
</P>
<P>
   Berger's Mountain Kolsch is a reasonable approximation of the
real thing, its gentle malt flavor up front and its finish so soft
and dry it vanishes from the tongue. This isn't a beer to set
alongside a plate of nachos, although Jackson notes that Cologners
accompany it with a snack of smoked sausage (called mettwurst) or
the local blood sausage called Cologne caviar.
</P>
<P>
   With or without the caviar, it's an easy, light-bodied beer to
sip on a summer evening. I might have liked a touch more hop aroma
and flavor, but a Kolsch isn't a hoppy beer to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix's interpretation of the style is more complex than
Berger's, a beer you might well have been served in Cologne. On
Monday night, at a Brewmaster's Dinner, Phoenix is serving it as an
aperitif with soft-shell crab on Asian vegetable slaw. Not for
caviar alone is Kolsch made, even in Cologne. A true pilsner would
be too assertive with a dish so light (Phoenix's superb pilsner
will be served later, with smoked black angus beef carpaccio), and
a Munich-style lager too rounded and malty (the Seven Sisters
Munchener will accompany a grilled veal chop and mushroom gratin).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the accompaniment _ or with none at all _ a Kolsch is a
summer beer that was never designed as one. In fact, between the
two world wars, Cologne's brewers refined the top-fermented beer
they'd been brewing to compete with the bottom-fermented golden
pilsners that were becoming more popular in Germany. They liked
what they had, and weren't about to embrace bottom fermentation.
</P>
<P>
   They liked it so much they got the government to decree it
theirs and no one else's. You know people take their beer seriously
when they get the government involved. Many Atlantans _ tasting
either of these locally available Kolsches without fear of a legal
imbroglio _ will understand why.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
