<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-TUSCUMBIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DON'T MISS: Hometown remembers Helen Keller
 &HT;    By Alan Patureau
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Country star Ronnie Milsap will headline the entertainment at
the 20th annual Helen Keller Festival, June 25-28 in the quaint
Tennessee River town of Tuscumbia, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Milsap, who was invited because his career has soared despite
his blindness, will give a free concert at 8 p.m. June 27 in Spring
Park, site of the festival's arts and crafts fair and other musical
events.
</P>
<P>
   The nostalgic center of the celebration will be Ivy Green, the
plantation cottage where Keller was born June 27, 1880. ``The
Miracle Worker,'' William Gibson's drama about the blind legend's
life, will be performed on the grounds at 8:15 p.m. every Friday
and Saturday through July 25. (Tickets are $8.) Included is the
actual water pump where young Helen learned her first word:
``water.''
</P>
<P>
   Hourly tours of Ivy Green, at 300 West North Commons in
Tuscumbia, feature Keller's grandparents' original furniture, her
Braille books and typewriter, and the ``whistle path'' that leads
to a well-preserved outdoor kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $3 for adults, $1 for children, from 9 a.m. to 4
p.m. Monday through Saturday and 1 to 4 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Another festival highlight, on the Colbert County Courthouse
lawn, is nightly music and dance by regional groups such as T.
Graham Brown, the Midnighters and the Kerry Gilbert Band. A
one-hour parade down Main Street began at 10 a.m. June 26. A
26-mile bicycle race and seven-mile family bicycle ride starts at 6
p.m. June 26. An antique car show will be staged on downtown
streets June 27, and the Full Moon Ensemble folk band will close
the festival with a free concert at 3 p.m. June 28.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Miracle Worker'' tickets or festival information, call
256-383-4066.
</P>
<P>
   -- Just for kids: With Keller's perseverance in mind, the
festival will offer schoolchildren a free ``Keller Kids'' program
June 25 at the Tuscumbia Multi-Purpose Center, teaching them
Braille, sign language and games that stress overcoming sensory
handicaps. A ``Keller Art for Kids'' course will be June 26 at the
Tennessee Valley Art Center (cost is $30 per child; call
256-383-0533). Children will learn watercolor painting and will
sketch the famous water pump.
</P>
<P>
   -- Famous musicmakers: Tuscumbia is also the home of the Alabama
Music Hall of Fame, on U.S. 72, featuring artifacts of W.C. Handy,
Hank Williams Sr., Nat King Cole, Lionel Richie and other
Alabamians. 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Mondays through Saturdays, 1-5 p.m.
Sundays. Adults $6, children $3.
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: It's a 280-mile drive from Atlanta, via I-20
west to Birmingham, I-65 north to Cullman and Ala. 157 to
Tuscumbia.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
