<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:Remembering Ellen Bryan: Skinning dipping to Press
Association meetings
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was out of town earlier this month, one of the most
charming women Atlanta has yet produced died.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Bryan _ Mrs. Wright Bryan _ died at the age of 93 years.
When I got the word from Jim Bryant, Mercer University(Ga.)'s
historian, I sat long moments thinking about Ellen, and feeling an
odd sense of loss for a woman I really didn't know well. It's funny
the things that stick in your mind about a person you don't know
well, but cherish like you cherish unexpected laughter and a crazy,
odd meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bryan's husband was editor of The Atlanta Journal, a
newspaper we on The Atlanta Constitution considered our unlikely,
unloved competition. But we did like the Bryans and rejoice in
Ellen's humor and goodwill.
</P>
<P>
   I had not met her when she first spoke to me on a parade route
celebrating Gen. Lucius Clay's homecoming from Europe at the end of
World War II. His hometown, Marietta, Ga., had staged a wingding of
a celebration, and I borrowed a country expression in describing
it. They had, I wrote, ``put on the big pot and the little pot,
too.'' Our young city editor regarded it as an obscure and
meaningless expression, but let it go. Ellen Bryan walked up to me
on the parade route and said, ``I know exactly what you meant by
that old expression and it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   I was relieved and grateful that this long-time and stylish
Atlantan knew what I was talking about, and thereafter delighted
when I saw her. She always accompanied her husband to the Georgia
Press Association meetings in Athens, and she was a charmer at the
after-banquet gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bryant, author of a history of the Druid Hills golf club,
wrote that he was greatly helped by Mrs. Bryan, whose father,
Alfred C. Newell, joined the club in 1914. Her father played golf
there with Ernest Woodruff, father of the famous Robert Woodruff,
and Ellen rode her horse on the golf course. Her family dwelled in
a Neil Reid house on Clifton road, the home of Col. and Mrs. Z. D.
Harrison ``whose pond she sometimes fished and swam in in her
birthday suit with her sister,'' Jim wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He added a wonderful Ellen Bryan note: ``One day a dignified
butler knocked on the Newells' door carrying a small silver tray
with a note on it, which read: 'Dear Mrs. Newell, Would you please
keep your children out of my pond? It is our drinking water. Thank
you. Mrs. Z.D. Harrison.'
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bryant wrote of Ellen's social activities, which were more
important in the 1920s than they are today _ debut, founder of the
Girls Cotillion Club, vice president of the Junior League and an
elegant wedding at which Enrico Leide, conductor of the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra, led a stringed orchestra in nuptial music.
</P>
<P>
   I was interested to learn that her great-grandfather was Georgia
Gov. Alfred Hope Colquitt and that she and her husband took the
first all-day flight to New York on their honeymoon when air
service was inaugurated Atlanta-to-New York.
</P>
<P>
   I am sorry I wasn't here to say goodbye to Ellen Bryan, blithe
spirit. Jim said it for many of us when he wrote that her ``genteel
manner and quick wit, sparkling eyes and charming stories''
embellished his history of Druid Hills and ``will remain part of my
own experience for the rest of my days.'' He added: ``Many of us
feel richer and are thankful for having known Ellen Newell Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
