<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECPSWAP18-COX     06-16 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECPSWAP18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mixer cake still a favorite after 50 years
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 18: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know that place in your kitchen where loose recipes, old
grocery lists and instruction manuals seem to collect. Every once
in a while, you go through and sort it all out, tossing most of it.
Then, within days, you remember that recipe that would be perfect
for the upcoming family get-together. Now where could it be?
</P>
<P>
   Frances Bowie recently e-mailed Recipe Swap looking for the
Mix-Easy Two Egg Cake recipe from the cookbook and manual that came
with her Dormeyer mixer in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, there were a handful of pack rats out there who pulled
out their Dormeyer mixer manuals from around the same time and
found the recipe. And readers Dorothy Barr and Ruth Eunice, both of
Atlanta, reported their mixers were still working.
</P>
<P>
   We offer the recipe here, which is indeed easy. The cookbook
suggested a chocolate frosting for the cake or this ``Creole
Topping.''
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mix-Easy
</P>
<P>
   Two Egg Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4cups cake flour, sifted
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup shortening, softened
</P>
<P>
   2eggs, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Grease 9-by-13-by-2-inch baking
pan. Set aside. In a measuring cup or small bowl, combine milk and
vanilla. Set aside. In a large bowl, combine flour, baking powder,
salt and sugar. Mix well. Cut in shortening using pastry blender
and mix well. Add 3/4 cup of the milk-vanilla mixture. Beat 2
minutes at medium speed. Add eggs and remaining milk mixture. Beat
1 minute on low speed. Pour batter into prepared baking pan and
bake about 30 minutes. Remove from oven. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 267 calories, 3 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 41 grams carbohydrates, 38
milligrams cholesterol, 358 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Creole Topping
</P>
<P>
   Makes topping for one 9-by-13-inch cake (12 servings)
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup firmly packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup melted butter
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup finely chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine brown sugar, cake flour, melted butter,
water and chopped nuts. Mix well. Spread over baked cake and bake
additional 5 minutes at 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 112 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 66), 123 grams carbohydrates, 124
milligrams cholesterol, 502 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Patricia Gardner of Clarkston is looking for a recipe for
Anadama Bread, which once was popular in middle Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
Include a daytime telephone number. E-mail: rwalker(at)ajc.com.
</P>
