<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN stands behind story as military advisor resigns
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A military adviser to CNN has resigned in protest over a recent
report that U.S. armed forces used deadly nerve gas on U.S.
defectors in Laos in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   CNN is standing by its story.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Perry Smith quit his position as
military adviser, stating that he had tried and failed to get CNN
to issue a retraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had tried very hard for a week to convince (executives) to
do a major retraction, but to no avail,'' Smith told WorldNetDaily,
a politically conservative website that has previously been
critical of the CNN story.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly stand by the accuracy of the reporting, which was
done over eight months and included talking to more than 200 people
up and down the chain of command,'' CNN spokesman Steve Haworth
said Tuesday. Tom Johnson, CEO of CNN Newsgroup, and Richard
Kaplan, president of CNN/U.S., were both traveling Tuesday and
unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN report, which originally aired June 7 on the debut of
``NewsStand: CNN &AMP; Time,'' has caused a firestorm of controversy.
Correspondent Peter Arnett reported that a secret U.S. military
operation, ``Operation Tailwind,'' used sarin nerve gas to kill
American defectors during the Vietnam War. Among those interviewed
who appeared to support the charge (although stating they did not
have direct knowledge) were former Secretary of Defense Melvin
Laird and former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman Admiral Thomas
Moorer. Maj. Gen. Smith was on retainer to CNN, and occiasonally
appeared on air as a military expert. He received most of his air
time during the Persian Gulf War, when he was a regular presence.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the CNN report have also cited the version that
appeared in Time magazine, written by Arnett and CNN producer April
Oliver. Time turned the main headline into a question: ``Did the
U.S. Drop Nerve Gas?'' But the Time story was as emphatic in its
assertion as the CNN report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
