<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XFILES-INTERVIEWS-COX     06-16 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XFILES-INTERVIEWS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Once a cult series, X-Files now a major motion picture
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beverly Hills, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   On and on came the beast, relentlessly. Mulder and Scully were
exhausted, but knew they could not give up.
</P>
<P>
   In one hotel suite, Mulder, in his civilian guise as actor David
Duchovny, was sprawled on a couch, barely able to get up. He'd
kicked off his shoes, stripped to a white T-shirt over khakis,
describing himself as ``pretty whipped.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the hall in an identical room, Scully, aka Gillian
Anderson, sagged wearily into a high-backed chair, her eyes heavy
as she sipped hot tea. ``Beaten to a pulp,'' she called herself.
</P>
<P>
   The lives of Duchovny/Mulder and Anderson/Scully have been
dominated by the hydra-headed media beast (including Entertainment
Weekly, Newsweek and TV Guide) in the days leading up to the Friday
premiere of their movie ``The X-Files: Fight the Future.'' Trapped
in a luxury hotel, they have endured the endless probes of
journalists who come to their rooms seeking the truth, or at least
a juicy tidbit.
</P>
<P>
   For five seasons, FBI agents Mulder and Scully have been
professional soulmates on television's ``The X-Files,'' forever on
the trail of aliens, vampires, shape-shifters, evil goverment
agents and the occasional demonic substitute teacher.
</P>
<P>
   They've evolved from polar opposites (he spooky and obsessed,
she rational and skeptical) to partners in sync in all but the
sexual sense, Fred and Ginger in trenchcoats, searching for truth
rather than facing the music, with cell phones and flashlights to
pierce the all-encompassing darkness of conspiracies and cover-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same five years, the Fox series has mutated from
cult-object to Top 10 Nielsen favorite, Internet obsession, and now
the movie, an attempt to appeal to both the 15 million-or-so
hard-core fans, as well as those who've never tuned in to the
show's eerie wavelength.
</P>
<P>
   The actors behind the roles are nowhere near as close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We show up and do the work, and in the process we might have
some laughs, but our relationship is basically within the realm of
the show and doesn't extend beyond that,'' says Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're not as close as Mulder and Scully,'' agrees
Duchovny. ``But we've got a good working relationship. The fact
that we're still doing the show speaks for itself. You don't have
other examples of a two-person show that comes back for five
seasons. The two-person hows explode 'cause it's tough to get
thrown together in an arranged marriage like that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Indeed, the two-character drama series is a volatile form,
littered with four-year marriages like ``Moonlighting'' and ``Lois
&AMP; Clark.'' ``Cagney &AMP; Lacey'' is the notable exception for
longevity.)
</P>
<P>
   There is, Anderson says, more intimacy between Mulder and Scully
than between her and Duchovny, which is ironic, given that the
level of intimacy between the two FBI agents has always been an
issue for the show's fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Files'' creator Chris Carter used to say that there would
never be any romance between the agents, that simply having two
attractive, intelligent people working in close quarters created
its own chemistry. Some fans buy that, while others passionately
wish the two would get together, filling the Internet with romantic
``fan fiction'' scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makes an effort to please both groups. In a scene that
has been widely shown in trailers and ads, they come very close to
a kiss, and there is a level of emotional closeness in the film
unknown in the TV series.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I was most struck by is that the movie is a
love story,'' says Anderson. ``There's a heightened level of
intimacy and respect and care that you don't get in the show. I'm
curious as to how the relationship is going to shift in the
series.'' (The series returns in the fall for its sixth season.)
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny admits that early on, he was one of those pushing
Carter to get the agents romantically involved. ``I used to say,
'Let's get 'em together, 'cause selfishly as an actor then I get to
play the boyfriend, or love, or jealousy, or the things they play
on ``NYPD Blue.'' ' As an actor you say, 'Hey! I want an Emmy!'
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you grow up, and realize you're servicing a piece,
and what may be more fun for or better for you as an actor may not
be better for the show.''
</P>
<P>
   But the actors' stories diverge at a key point in the
interrogations. Anderson will own up to be occasionally tiring of
playing Scully for the past five years, while Duchovny gets
downright riled over devoting his prime years to Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulder's a very needy guy,'' he says. ``It's all that I do, is
be Mulder. And when I'm not doing that, I'm talking about Mulder or
preparing to be Mulder. It's really human to be tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   He catches himself, knowing how he sounds; that without the role
of Mulder, he might still be little more than the narrator of
Showtime's soft-porn series ``Red Shoe Diaries.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you allow yourself to talk like that, people see it as
being ungrateful to the show, or not liking the people you're
working with, when in fact it's a reaction against something that's
consuming all your time.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he says, he's never tried to get ouf of his contract, which
runs for two more TV seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of the show,'' he says. ``To try to destroy it that
way, even if it would be helpful to me, is not the right thing to
do in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bored with Scully,'' Anderson counters. ``I am, at
times, frustrated with not having the freedom to do other projects.
But I've never regretted being a part of it. I'm constantly
grateful for the gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Both actors, and Carter, creator of the characters that rule
their lives, see the series extending for two more seasons, then
possibly morphing into a series of movies, a la ``Star Trek.''
</P>
<P>
   That will depend largely on how successful this first movie is,
which may depend largely on what fans think of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine the die-hard fans are gonna be upset about
something,'' says Duchovny, aware how picky and contentious the
sensibilities can be of those who love the show the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they're die-hard fans. That's why we love 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   And the beast, sated, retreated.
</P>
<P>
   The Duchovny File
</P>
<P>
   David William Duchovny
</P>
<P>
   Plays: Fox Mulder, an FBI agent obsessed by the alien abduction
of his sister, forever seeking the truth about the paranormal.
Nicknamed ``Spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   Age: 37
</P>
<P>
   Youth: Very bright. Attended Princeton University on academic
scholarship (he played junior varsity basketball and was nicknamed
``Scruff'' for his appearance). Senior thesis: ``The Schizophrenic
Critique of Pure Reason in (Samuel) Beckett's Early Novels.''
Master's degree in English lit from Yale. Dropped out of the Yale
PhD. program when he got a Lowenbrau beer commercial and decided to
be an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married one year to actress Tea Leoni (``Deep Impact'').
No children so far, but ``I think that'll happen sometime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad movie history: ``Playing God.'' ``I had six weeks to do a
film,'' he says. ``Because I'm a big TV star, people wanted to make
it my breakout attempt. So much for perception.''
</P>
<P>
   Other roles: Co-starred with Brad Pitt in ``Kalifornia,'' played
a transvestite FBI agent on ``Twin Peaks'' and the bad guy in the
doggie movie ``Beethoven.''
</P>
<P>
   Awards: Golden Globe for role as Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   Spare time: Writes poetry, plays basketball, recently started
golf lessons.
</P>
<P>
   On Mulder: ``He appears to be a rational person, but he's
completely insane. Isn't the definition of insanity doing the same
thing over and over and expecting different results? By that
definition, he's insane.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anderson File
</P>
<P>
   Gillian Leigh Anderson (the G is soft)
</P>
<P>
   Plays: Dana Scully. Physician, scientist, skeptic, partnered
with FBI agent Fox Mulder.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 29
</P>
<P>
   Youth: A wild teen, she went through a punk phase that included
a multicolored mohawk. Once handcuffed herself to high school
doors.
</P>
<P>
   What she says: ``Despite how low things got for a while, there
was always a sense that there were two options: I was either gonna
kill myself or I would pull out if it.''
</P>
<P>
   Education: Classical theater training at DePaul University.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Divorced from Clyde Klotz, father of her daughter Piper,
3 1/2. ``People think she's 5. She's constantly asking really
interesting questions, like `what's inside trees?'''
</P>
<P>
   Distinguishing marks: Pierced navel, tattoo on ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Bad movie history: The straight-to-video ``The Turning.''
</P>
<P>
   Awards: One Emmy, two Golden Globes, two Screen Actors Guild
Awards, all for Scully.
</P>
<P>
   Spare time: Fund-raising for Neurofibromatosis, Inc., which
fights the affliction also known as ``Elephant Man's disease.'' Her
brother has it.
</P>
<P>
   On Scully: ``She's very responsible, very adult, very mature,
smart, compassionate, kind. She has a lot of qualities that I
haven't been but always wished I could be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
