<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1956 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICIAN-REALWORLD-2T     06-16 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICIAN-REALWORLD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIS ARTIST, LIVE AND ELECTRONIC MUSIC BLEND IN VARIED CAREER  
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Wis., Ohio)   By ANN POWERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mimi Goese lives in one of those old New York City
apartments whose rooms are so tiny that they feel like a complex of
cages. Yet Ms. Goese, a 38-year-old performing artist, has
transformed this standard walk-up into enchanted chambers.
</P>
<P>
   A vast window she cut into the wall between the kitchen and the
living room opens up an unexpected vista. A manual typewriter hangs
by invisible cords in the air above her desk. Clear threads also
cover the living room ceiling, blanketing white stucco with sheets
of parchment-colored paper filled with seemingly random sentences _
samples of the speed-writing that sometimes inspires the lyrics to
her pop songs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she gazes at her ceiling for musical inspiration, Ms.
Goese laughed. ``There's a big hole,'' she said. ``I was basically
covering up.''
</P>
<P>
   Renewing the worn-out stuff of urban life is a requirement for
artists like Ms. Goese (pronounced GAY-zee), who survive and thrive
on the borders of New York City's art worlds. While stars dodge
paparazzi and high-culture careerists hobnob uptown, a quiet
assemblage of experimentalists and virtuosos brightens the city's
corners, their innovations filtering out to feed the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Famous to a few, these inconspicuous originals fortify New
York's artistic communities, which open onto one another like the
rooms linked by Ms. Goese's makeshift kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   Mimi Goese belongs to this shadow pantheon. She has
choreographed or danced in dozens of programs, starred in
independent films, composed all varieties of experimental music and
appeared at spaces ranging from the Kitchen to the Central Park
Bandshell. As the singer for Hugo Largo, she helped define
1980's-style art rock. In 1995, she was the co-writer of two songs
that she sang on ``Everything Is Wrong,'' the eclectic album by the
groundbreaking New York techno artist Moby. Now, with a new album,
``Soak,'' on Luaka Bop, the record label run by the veteran musical
genre-hopper David Byrne, she is aiming to reach her largest
audience yet.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate the release of ``Soak,'' Ms. Goese is performing
every Wednesday this month at Fez, in the East Village, with her
band, Mimi, and a list of guest stars that connects the dots of her
musical history. Collaborators include Lloop, a founding member of
two electronic art-and-music collectives, We and Multipolyomni;
Elliot Sharp, a multi-instrumentalist; Ben Neill, the inventor of
the ``mutantrumpet'', and Mark Mulcahy and Syd Straw,
singer-songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I should have this tree with all these branches,''
Ms. Goese said, discussing her network of musical allies. ``Or
something more like a hexagon, like the chemical symbol for
helium.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goese, born in Milwaukee, came to New York in 1982 and dived
into the fertile mayhem of the performance-art scene. She
collaborated with old friends, like the choreographer and filmmaker
Jo Andres, and new ones, like Tom Murran, the Alien Comic. She
joined a Butoh troupe, studying the stark, morbid style of Japanese
dance, and learned to keep her eyes open for 40 minutes at a time.
For other shows, she would convincingly camouflage herself as a
burly man or a young boy. Sometimes she worked with two fellow
graduates of Ohio University, Anne Iobst and Lucy Sexton, known as
Dancenoise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Tim Sommer, who was then Ms. Sexton's boyfriend, formed
a band and recruited both women to sing. The band was Hugo Largo;
Ms. Goese was the vocalist who lasted. Her voice, which vividly
blends warmth with melodrama, suited the daring, arty atmosphere of
post-punk New York and proved a revelation to her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something about Mimi that blew my mind,'' said Ms.
Andres, who recently directed Ms. Goese's first music video for
``Soak.'' ``I knew her for years; then she joined this band. All of
a sudden we all realized she could sing. No one knew! I think she
figured she didn't need to use singing in her performance before
then.''
</P>
<P>
   With spookily desolate songs, a deliberately strange
instrumental lineup _ two basses and a violinist, no guitar or
drums _ and Ms. Goese's visceral presence at its center, Hugo Largo
immediately became a talked-about band, loved by some and despised
by others, who found its antics unbearably pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the fear, the heightened awareness of performance,''
she said. ``I would drag a butcher knife across my face. I had
little lines on my neck for every show. One time, I threw the knife
out into the audience.'' She shook her head at the memory. ``What
was I thinking?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goese explored pop music's terrain without being attached to
its myths. But Sommer wanted Hugo Largo to become a successful rock
band. Tensions mounted after the group recorded a critically
acclaimed EP, ``Drum,'' produced by Michael Stipe of R.E.M. for
Brian Eno's label, Opal. A full-length album, ``Mettle,'' and a
European tour followed. Success only heightened the differences
within the band. ``It did spontaneously combust,'' Ms. Goese said.
</P>
<P>
   Sommer went to work for Atlantic Records, where he realized his
goal of getting rich before age 30 by signing Hootie and the
Blowfish. Ms. Goese entered a fallow period. Cuts to arts financing
had severely damaged the dance and performance communities; what
arts jobs she got were brief and usually took her to Europe. At
home, she baby-sat and cleaned out people's closets for a fee.
</P>
<P>
   Realizations And Reflections
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hugo Largo there was always this attitude of we're not
going to sell out,'' Ms. Goese said. ``I was the one behind that; I
was the  &UR; artiste &LR; . But then I realized _ and this was eye-opening _
that even though nobody wants you to sell out, nobody's handing out
medals when you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after sharing these reflections, Ms. Goese ascended
the rickety staircase of a converted warehouse near the Gowanus
Canal in Brooklyn. She found Hahn Rowe, the former violinist in
Hugo Largo, in his darkened closet of a practice space, busily
charting electronic samples on his Powerbook. Over a lunch break,
he shared his thoughts on the making of ``Soak.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowe, whose quick smile enlivens his shy demeanor, has been Ms.
Goese's main musical collaborator since Hugo Largo's demise. A
guitarist and D.J. as well as a violinist, he represents the bridge
between Ms. Goese's old musical style and her current incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   The drifting compositions of the electronic music world
preoccupy Rowe, but frustrate him too. ``It's very easy to come up
with something that sounds cutting edge, but is really very
shallow, just a diagram of originality,'' he said. ``It's funny,
because three years ago, if I'd heard anybody say, `It's all about
the songs, man,' it would make me reach for my revolver. But now I
see both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Rowe was immersed in dance music, recording
solo and with various collaborators and frequenting underground
gatherings, sponsored by collectives like Soundlab and Unity Gain.
Like many of Ms. Goese's friends, including most of her Fez guests,
he had caught the electronic bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were people who had not been excited in years,'' Ms.
Goese said. ``There's something intrinsic in the beat. In the
energy of the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing the Live And the Electronic
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goese was thrilled by electronic music, too, but she
disliked its lack of focus on performers. What partly persuaded her
to collaborate with Moby was his onstage charisma. Rowe agrees that
the human spark of live performance is a key to the band Mimi's
success.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goese's ``singing and even her melodies are very involved
with the way she is physically,'' he said. ``Hopefully, watching us
is like watching music.''
</P>
<P>
   Mimi, the band, wasn't always so well balanced between
electronic and live elements. The demo tape that David Byrne heard
while getting his hair cut at a salon run by Ms. Goese's friend
Valerie Ohms, was mostly electronic. At Byrne's suggestion, Ms.
Goese tried a more organic approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urged her to perform, so that when the record came out
there would be a real thing there,'' Byrne said. ``Then at some
point we all felt that that approach was making some stuff a little
more conventional. I suggested she work with Hector Zazou. They met
and got along really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowe had long admired Zazou, an Algerian-born ambient musician
and producer based in Paris, and agreed to share production on
``Soak'' with him. The two traded material via the Internet.
Although the process sounds like cut-and-paste when described,
``Soak'' is a remarkably cohesive suite grounded in Ms. Goese's
dramatic vocals.
</P>
<P>
   The live Mimi band has also gone from traditional to electronic
to a blend. ``We're incorporating what's available to us now _ the
sampler, and the large sonic palette,'' Rowe said. ``But we're
still also trying to have the feeling we had in Hugo Largo, which
was almost like being in a chamber music group.''
</P>
<P>
   The chamber group, rehearsing at Fez for Mimi's first
appearance, was having trouble fitting onto the stage. Lloop, the
dreadlocked auteur whose pseudonym describes his technique of
looping samples together to make sonic collages, stood,
disgruntled, behind his bank of machines, now banished to the front
row of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Metaphors for Art In the Surroundings
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goese's surroundings often suggest metaphors for her art,
and here was another one: two banks of samplers, two turntables and
the instruments of three traditional musicians had created an
overflow akin to her intense new songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life's a piece of cake,'' Ms. Goese sang as the band crashed
through the first single from ``Soak.'' ``Except with Lloop, where
everything's difficult,'' she improvised.
</P>
<P>
   As the band got going, with Lloop finding the rhythm of his
synthetically created and found sounds, Ms. Goese rocked and
gestured in synch with the increasing noise. Vocally, she sparred
with the jerky rhythms of the music, her movements adding a third
dimension to the shifting tableaux engendered by her words and the
players' shifts between tunefulness and clamor. Later, Lloop said
he enjoyed rising to the group's challenges. A prime mover in the
local electronic music scene, he belongs to the younger generation
of artists that Mimi's new songs take from and give back to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future will be hybrid,'' Lloop predicted. ``There won't be
a distinction between electronic and traditional artists. If they
were two different religions, it would be a good idea for them to
intermingle anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloop's prophecy seems likely, and such events could bring
greater success to artists like Ms. Goese. These days, musical
undergrounds often infiltrate the mainstream more easily than they
survive in their own environments. Ms. Goese's talent for leaping
boundaries may help her take some missives from those subterranean
scenes into pop's great beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, where I teach, very often I've have a group of 10
people and every one is from a different country,'' she said. ``So
you get down to your pidgin English and hold on for dear life. You
find the very important words that you need to communicate. That's
what I hope for in writing the songs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
