<HEADER>
A1962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIGHTINGALES-THEATER-     06-16 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIGHTINGALES-THEATER-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOT ABOUT NIGHTINGALES': TENNESSEE WILLIAMS, A YOUTH CONFINED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Pa., Mo.)  (Eitors: production notes at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``Now is the time to make a break _ get away _ away.''
The words, hopeful and desperate, appear in the private journal of
the 27-year-old Thomas Lanier Williams III, who was soon to adopt
the first name of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was then living, most unhappily, with his parents in
St. Louis. His older sister, Rose, who people said might as well be
his twin, had recently been institutionalized for mental illness,
and the young man found himself ``pinning pictures of wild birds on
my lavatory screen.'' The idea of flight, of escape, saturated a
life that was becoming more and more claustrophobic.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1938, the same year that Williams wrote a play that
is only now receiving its American premiere. Called ``Not About
Nightingales,'' it was shaped with the aim of getting the attention
of the politically minded Group Theater in New York, and it is
directly topical in a way that Williams' plays would never be
again.
</P>
<P>
   But its subject, inspired by newspaper accounts of four brutal
deaths in Philadelphia, matched its author's state of mind all too
well: it is a drama about a prison and the toll that incarceration
takes on the human spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The fine, searing production of ``Not About Nightingales'' that
can be seen at the Alley Theater here owes its inception to Vanessa
Redgrave, who became curious about the play while researching her
role in Williams' ``Orpheus Descending'' and tracked down the
manuscripts. It has been brought to life as a collaboration by Ms.
Redgrave's Moving Theater, the Alley and the Royal National Theater
in London, where it was first staged, under the direction of Trevor
Nunn, to excited hosannas in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not About Nightingales'' is by no stretch of the imagination a
mature piece of craftsmanship. Williams, who was aching to have his
work produced, was clearly cutting the play's design according to
polemical patterns of theater made popular by Clifford Odets. But
the emotional cloth of the drama, and much of its imagery, is pure
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   As a cry of social protest for prison reform, it can seem as
much of an artifact as the ``big house'' movies of the 1930s. As an
anguished cry of empathy for fellow souls in captivity, it is a
full-strength heartbreaker.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional tide that sweeps through ``Nightingales'' and that
makes it so strangely compelling isn't as much righteous anger as
corrosive fear: fear of losing all connection with the fast-passing
stream of life; of madness; of sexual loneliness; of entombment,
real and metaphorical. From the beginning of ``Nightingales,''
which traces the battle of wills between a sadistic warden, Boss
Whalen (Corin Redgrave), and a group of prisoners on a hunger
strike, there hovers the threat of an ungodly punishment:
consignment to ``Klondike,'' a subterranean chamber lined with
steam radiators. In the events that inspired this play, four men
were cooked to death in such a room.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of excruciating death in a locked room figures in
Williams' work as early as a short story (set in ancient Egypt) he
wrote for a pulp magazine when he was a teen-ager. Here, it becomes
the conclusive symbol in a chain of images of isolation and
confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Nunn and his excellent cast and production team admirably
refrain from overemphasizing this pattern. They are clearly aware
of the work's difficult status as the previously unseen product of
a master, and they don't overload it with interpretive quirks or
shadings. They present ``Nightingales,'' as they should, as a
story, not a poem, and give full due to the sensational thrust and
tension of a play Williams himself identified as a melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   But the wholesale commitment of the actors, a mixture of British
and American performers, to their roles gives the evening both an
urgency and an organic-seeming lyricism that overrides its clunkier
lines and speechifying.
</P>
<P>
   The drama begins in darkness with the amplified voice of a guide
on a tour ship called the Lorelei. (Williams' affinity for
ironically grand names is already in evidence.) It's a siren call
that can't be heeded by the prison inmates who hear the teasing
voice of a world of motion to which they no longer belong. Richard
Hoover's set and Chris Parry's lighting, which ply Expressionist
techniques with commendable delicacy, create a bleak, stranded
environment so bleached of color that even the American flag in the
warden's office is rendered in shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   Redgrave, the brother of Vanessa and a co-founder of the Moving
Theater, plays the corrupt, lusty Boss Whalen with an outsize
satanic gusto that is as unnerving as it is entertaining. He
becomes the embodiment of the element in which the prisoners exist.
He's the oppressive, tyrannical God in their circumscribed
universe, holding the power of life and death.
</P>
<P>
   As is always true in Williams' plays, there are those who are
strong enough to survive in this context and those who are crushed
by it. Williams admires the former; he loves the latter.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the characters can be broken into a familiar
lineup of the stereotypes that show up in everything from the
prison dramas to the war movies of the period. There's the
inevitable sensitive young man, here named Jim Allison (Finbar
Lynch in a piercing, sharp-edged performance), a prisoner who works
in the warden's office and a writer in the making, and his sworn
enemy, Butch O'Fallon (James Black), who is all swagger and
testosterone.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The good-hearted inmate (Dion Graham) is in prison for stealing
a box of canned food to feed his starving family, is liked by all
and is destined to die early; the cocky new boy (Mark Dexter)
swears he doesn't belong in prison, and the appropriately named
Queen (Jude Akuwudike) utters a line that anticipates the Almas and
Blanches to come: ``All my life I've been persecuted by people
because I'm refined.'' For love interest, there is the warden's
alluring but honorable young secretary, Eva Crane (Sherri Parker
Lee).
</P>
<P>
   You've seen all these characters, with only slight variations,
before, right? But if their outlines come from cookie cutters,
their uneasy souls are their own. Even the robust Butch, given
vigorous credibility by Black, is haunted by the shadows of an
unlived life. Jim, whose anxious moral ambivalence beams steadily
from Lynch's glittering eyes, has developed trembling hands from
years of self-disgusted compromise and sexual repression.
</P>
<P>
   Before all the men looms the warning figure of Sailor Jack
(Richard Leaf), who has gone ``stirbugs,'' reduced to babbling
incoherence by his time in solitary confinement. The official
diagnosis is dementia praecox, a phrase, for the record, with which
doctors had recently described the condition of Williams' sister.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Crane, too, suffers from frayed nerves, an aspect that Ms.
Lee has the good sense not to exaggerate, and though she is
repulsed by the warden's sexual overtures, she also admits she is
hypnotized by them. The overall climate, as Whalen notes with
remarkable understatement as the play reaches its horrific climax,
is one in which ``we're all just nervous, strained, overwrought,''
a phrase he repeats like a seductive litany. The setting may be a
prison, but it is also the same ``suburb of hell'' inhabited by
Williams' great later characters.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch's character, by the way, is derisively called Canary Jim
by his fellow inmates, and the motifs of birds in cages and
feelings of flightlessness pervade the play. The work's title comes
from Jim's declaration that he will portray only the raw truth in
his writing and not the pretty creatures of nature of Romantic
odes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a way, this drama IS about nightingales, precursors to
the fluttering, fragile life seekers whom Williams would write
about until he died. They are always doomed to extinction, but they
can sing like nobody else. This tender act of resurrection by the
Redgraves, Nunn and company shows the songbirds just beginning to
find their voices.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NOT ABOUT NIGHTINGALES'
</P>
<P>
   By Tennessee Williams; directed by Trevor Nunn; director's
associate, Stephen Rayne; set by Richard Hoover; costumes by Karyl
Newman; lighting by Chris Parry; music arranged by Steven Edis;
sound by Christopher Shutt; dialect coach, Joan Washington; company
voice work, Patsy Rodenburg; fights, Malcolm Ranson; stage manager,
Christa Chapman; assistant stage manager, Kristin Fox; dramaturge,
Travis Mader; general manager, Harold Wolpert. Presented by Alley
Theater, Gregory Boyd, artistic director; Paul R. Tetreault,
managing director. A co-production of the Royal National Theater
and Moving Theater, in association with Alley Theater. In Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Sherri Parker Lee (Eva Crane), Finbar Lynch (Jim Allison),
Corin Redgrave (Boss Whalen), Richard Leaf (Sailor Jack), James
Black (Butch O'Fallon), Jude Akuwudike (The Queen), Alex Giannini
(Joe), Dion Graham (Oliver Armsted), Joel Leffert (Shapiro), Mark
Dexter (Jeremy Trout), Chico Andrade (Mex), Tom Hodgkins
(Chaplain), Noble Shropshire (the Reverend Hooker) and Sandra
Dickinson (Goldie).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
