<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1984 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     06-16 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO JOB QUESTIONS ARE `STUPID'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior. Send
e-mail to LloydOnJob(at)aol.com, or mail to P.O. Box 260057,
Encino, CA 91426. Names will be withheld upon request. 
BY KEN LLOYD, PH.D.  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We were having a staff meeting and I asked a basic question.
After the meeting, my manager told me that he didn't want to
embarrass me in front of the others, but my question was stupid. He
feels he's a hero because he reprimanded me in private, but I'm
annoyed over the criticism itself. What do you think? E.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: In Management 101, your manager gets half credit. He gets an
A for providing negative feedback in private, and an F for the
feedback itself.
</P>
<P>
   The best managers today adhere to the adage that there is no
such thing as a stupid question. It is not as if managers should be
seeking so-called stupid questions, but it is through the
opportunity to ask any question that innovation and creativity are
fostered.
</P>
<P>
   Your manager's actions can totally extinguish the employees'
desire to think, take some mental risks, and approach problems in
new and different ways. Even if you ask the most ridiculous
question in the world, it is entirely possible that your question
will generate some related ideas that can truly lead to more
effective problem-solving. After all, some of the greatest ideas,
concepts and inventions started as arguably stupid questions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, even if your question made absolutely no sense, the
way that you were treated is ultimately going to prevent your
associates from asking their own risky questions, and who is to say
what creative ideas may be lost forever as a result? It's time for
your manager to go back to Management 101.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So much of what I've been reading lately advises job-seekers
to wear a tie to a job interview. Many of the companies I'm looking
at are very casual, and I wonder if I'm going to look out of place
wearing a tie. What do you think? J.E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Although work has definitely become more casual in many
sectors, being too casual in the interview process can cause a
casualty. In general, it makes sense to wear a tie to a job
interview, even if the people you meet at the company seem to
wonder why you are wearing a piece of colorful fabric around your
neck. The fact is that many interviewers expect applicants to wear
ties, and you can send an unintentionally smug or lackadaisical
message by arriving without one.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there are many work environments and jobs in
which it is the tie that sends the wrong message. In such settings,
a tie can cause the applicant to look too stodgy or self-important.
</P>
<P>
   If you look carefully at the industry, the company, and the
specific job you are seeking, you should be able to gather some
insight as to whether you need to wear a tie. And, if you know
people who work for the company, you can check with them. If all
else fails, you can always call the company, mention that you are
going to be coming in for an interview, and ask if it is a
tie-optional affair.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Upon receiving my college degree, I returned home to find a
tough job market for my field. Consequently, I took a temporary,
full-time position while continuing my job search. I am being
bombarded with lectures and advice by numerous co-workers who think
they have the answers to my job-search woes. I wish these
know-it-alls would understand that not all college grads have a
choice of where they want to work. What do you suggest? K.P.
</P>
<P>
   A: The most important step for you to take is to stop focusing
on your co-workers and start focusing on your career. Your
co-workers probably feel badly that you spent four years in
college, only to have to settle for a stopgap job until you find
something better. In fact, it sounds like all they really want to
do is help you.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you need to look at what you are doing for
yourself. If you have a real strategy to get your career on track,
it will be much easier for you to listen to what your co-workers
may be saying. However, if you feel stuck, then all of their
comments are going to be that much more annoying.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, something about your behavior is calling for
help, and your co-workers are responding to it. In terms of getting
real help, there are career placement centers, job counselors,
industrial psychologists, employment agencies and search firms, and
university programs that can help you either find a more satisfying
position, or slightly redirect your career path toward an equally
fulfilling objective. There are many outstanding opportunities for
recent college graduates, but you need to give yourself the
opportunity to pursue them.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1823EDT &QL; 
