<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-SPONSORS-COX </SLUG>
   440&AMP;ADD  LATINO GROUP URGES MINORITY
COMMUNITY TO SHUN ALCOHOL, TOBACCO MONEY
 &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When it comes to funding cultural events,
cash-strapped minority groups have often depended on the Marlboro
Man to ride to their rescue.
</P>
<P>
   But the non-profit Latino Council on Alcohol and Tobacco (LCAT),
which has persuaded Washington's annual Latino Festival to kick the
habit of accepting tobacco and alcohol sponsors, wants minority
organizations to rethink the consequences of accepting these gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The council said at a news conference Tuesday it hoped the
Latino festival, expected to draw half a million people from across
the nation to the national capital July 25 and 26, would ``set a
precedent'' of shunning tobacco and alcohol money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, we are sending a loud, clear message to the alcohol
and tobacco industries to stop selling poison to our children,''
Richard Levinson, spokesman for the American Public Health
Association, said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Huerta, director of cancer prevention at Washington
Hospital Center, noted that 440,000 Americans die of
tobacco-related illnesses each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (tobacco companies) are killing 1,200 people every day.
They need a new crop _ that's our community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most large Latino organizations, as well as major
African-American groups, accept financial support from the tobacco
and alcohol industries.
</P>
<P>
   Doing so has put minority groups in a bind, said Rev. Alpha
Estes Brown of the American Cancer Society. They ``inadvertently
contribute to the demise of their communities through silence or
indifference, not wanting to offend the generosity of their
benefactors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Daphne Kwok, executive director of the Organization of Chinese
Americans, admitted there was ``tremendous pressure'' to take
tobacco and alcohol money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken the funds, but have used it appropriately,'' she
said. The organization recently accepted $35,000 over two years to
put out a directory of Asian Pacific American organizations that
was largely funded by Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kamasaki, senior vice president of the National Council
of La Raza, the largest Latino civil rights organization, said La
Raza receives about 2 percent of its roughly $13 million budget
from tobacco and alcohol sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is undeniably true there are other sources of money,'' he
said. ``My point is, a lot of that money comes with strings
attached.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the freedom granted by tobacco and alcohol companies for
use of the money makes it hard to turn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't carry out other people's agenda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Carraro, spokeswoman for Philip Morris U.S.A., said that
the industry's marketing techniques are simply tailored to each
community's preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Latinos are just as capable of making life decisions
as any other group,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that Hispanic males are more likely to
experience drinking problems than African-Americans or whites.
Also, chronic liver disease and cirrhosis are leading causes of
death among Latinos, according to LCAT.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Chairman Jeannette Noltenius, is why LCAT wants to
curb the ``systematic targeting'' of minorities by the tobacco and
alcohol industries.
</P>
<P>
   Noltenius said the council's purpose was ``not to criticize
Latino and other minority groups,'' but to encourage them to probe
new sources of funding to cover the cost of their events.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hoped comprehensive national tobacco legislation
pending in the Senate would allocate funds for minority
organizations to help them cut dependence on the tobacco and
alcohol money.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
