<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 NEW DIRECTOR FOR LINCOLN CENTER FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The general director of the Spoleto Festival U.S.A.
was named Tuesday as the new director of the Lincoln Center
Festival on the eve of the summer program's third season.
</P>
<P>
   The new director, Nigel Redden, 47, who served as executive
producer of the Lincoln Center Festival in 1995 and has been
running it since January, replaces John Rockwell, who left at that
time to return to The New York Times as editor of the Arts and
Leisure section. The appointment places Redden at the helm of two
of the United States' leading arts festivals. He will remain as
general director of the Spoleto Festival in Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are complementary in a lot of ways,'' Redden said. He
said he saw no conflict between Spoleto, an offshoot of the
original Italian ``Two Worlds'' festival, taking place in May and
June, and the Lincoln Center Festival, in July.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a special tie to Lincoln Center. His wife, Arlene
Shuler, is the center's senior vice president for planning and
external affairs.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's Lincoln Center program, which Redden inherits
essentially from Rockwell, consists of 111 performances of 36
events, from a 19-hour Chinese Kunju opera, ``The Peony Pavilion,''
to a cyberworld ``Faust'' by La Fura dels Baus of Barcelona, Spain;
a tribute to Leonard Bernstein; two plays by the Gesher Theater of
Tel Aviv, Israel, with simultaneous translation from the Hebrew;
and the complete organ works of Bach. The festival runs from July 7
to 26.
</P>
<P>
   The programs are budgeted at about $9 million a season, with
about $6 million to be raised from benefactors. Last season,
however, cost $10.6 million, Lincoln Center officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Redden said he was already working on the 1999 and 2000 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Leventhal, president of Lincoln Center, and Beverly
Sills, the chairwoman, praised Redden's understanding of the arts
and his ``practical know-how.'' He has also worked at the Santa Fe
Opera and the National Endowment for the Arts in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Redden marks another act in an unusual pas de deux
that has taken him back and forth between Spoleto and Lincoln
Center. He was Spoleto's general manager from 1986 to 1991, when he
left following a dispute with the organizer of the festival, the
composer Gian Carlo Menotti. Menotti himself left Charleston in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Redden was named consultant and several months later
executive producer of the Lincoln Center Festival, then being
planned under the direction of Rockwell, who had been European
cultural correspondent when he left The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Redden left Lincoln Center in late 1995 to return to Spoleto in
Charleston as general director. He returned to Lincoln Center in
January as artistic consultant to lead the festival after
Rockwell's return to The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a bad penny,'' Redden said Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
