<HEADLINE>
RONALDO DISPATCHES MOROCCO, 3-0 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Ronaldo took a step toward fulfilling his
ambition Tuesday, a week after the start of the World Cup finals
and more than two months after his previous goal for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   The planet's most famous 21-year-old finally converted his first
World Cup goal to spark the Brazilians to a 3-0 victory over
Morocco, clinching a berth in the second round as the top team in
Group A. They will meet the second-place team in Group B in Paris
June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Before the World Cup started, Ronaldo had talked of challenging
the tournament record of 13 goals set by France's Just Fontaine in
1958. But he was seldom involved in the action during Brazil's
opening 2-1 victory over Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Things changed suddenly in this match. Possibly Ronaldo was
inspired by the arrival at Stade de la Beaujoire of his girlfriend
Susana Werner, an aspiring model/soccer player known as Ronaldinha.
More likely, Ronaldo's success is attributable to the improved
understanding among his teammates, the ineffective defending and
inexperienced goalkeeping of Morocco, plus his dynamic bursts of
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil entered the field with a different attitude,'' Brazil
coach Mario Zagallo said. ``We played a more joyful game. I was
glad to see a smaller team like Morocco play an interesting, joyful
game also. We are especially satisfied to be in first place in our
group _ that was the first objective.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilians were able to penetrate early with quick
combinations. They dislodged the defense with enterprising runs and
adventurous, unpredictable passes. Leonardo had an offside goal in
the opening minutes. The Moroccan defenders became spread. And
Rivaldo nearly caught goalkeeper Driss Ben Zekri out of the goal
with a 45-yard blast from the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo had possession in a similar position less than a minute
later. This time, Ben Zekri held his line, instead of taking the
necessary risk of cutting the attacking angle. That allowed Ronaldo
room to speed past the offside trap and take a perfect, angled
through ball from Rivaldo to score.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco continued to battle, though. Ronaldo retreated quickly
into defense to stop Abdeliha Saber seconds after the goal. Said
Chiba then left an 8-inch cleat gash on Ronaldo's left thigh with a
reckless challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco had few chances as Brazil's defense concentrated on
stopping Mustafa Hadji, and Ronaldo helped set the tone by
retreating into defending positions. But in the final minutes of
the first half, Youssef Chippo broke through the midfield and fell
while attempting to shoot from the edge of the penalty arc. Russian
referee Nikolai Levnikov issued a caution to Cesar Sampaio for a
foul, prompting a strong protest from Dunga. With Dunga
gesticulating wildly, Bebeto entered the conflict, leading Leonardo
to step between his teammates like a boxing referee.
</P>
<P>
   Levnikov added two minutes of injury time, and allowed the
Brazilians a final possession, which they converted as Bebeto and
Cafu set up Rivaldo for a 2-0 edge.
</P>
<P>
   The next score came five minutes into the second half as
defender Abdeliha Saber slipped under token pressure from Ronaldo,
who then went past a defender and Ben Zekri and centered for
Bebeto.
</P>
<P>
   The predominantly Brazilian crowd began calling for substitutes
Denilson and Edmundo in the first half. But Zagallo waited until
midway through the second half to make his first change _ Doriva
for Sampaio, who is disqualified for the Norway match in Marseille
Tuesday. Edmundo replaced Bebeto soon after. Denilson finally
entered for Rivaldo with three minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Zagallo avoided debating with Egil Olsen, the Norway coach who
guided his team to a 4-2 win over Brazil in Oslo last year and
recently said that if he coached the Brazilians they would never
lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything about the other team,'' Zagallo
said. ``I don't want to know about the other team, only about my
team. For me, it was not a surprise that we improved. In my
experience, Brazil is capable of doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won anything, yet. We've only finished first in the
group. Until we win the championship, we haven't done anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
