u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KATYA-OPERA-REVIEW-49     06-16 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KATYA-OPERA-REVIEW-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KATYA KABANOVA': A JANACEK REPRISE AT GLYNDEBOURNE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLYNDEBOURNE, England _ Britain is wet. The uncloned sheep on
the hills and meadows around the garden do not seem to mind, but
chalky mud from the paths of Glyndebourne clings to the black shoes
of the gentlemen in evening clothes at 4 in the afternoon, and
ladies pick up their long skirts to run from the next shower.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere matches the uncertainty that hangs over the
place, with the coming departure both of the opera festival's music
director, Andrew Davis, and of its chief executive, Anthony
Whitworth-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   But the show goes on. One of Glyndebourne's big successes in the
last decade has been its sequence of Janacek performances, achieved
with outstanding singers, excellent conductors and a fine
production team, headed throughout by the director Nikolaus
Lehnhoff, whose emphatic groupings and heightened realism suit this
composer. ``Katya Kabanova'' was being played again Sunday evening,
and again hit home.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias Hoheisel's designs and Wolfgang Goebbel's lighting put
drably dressed people inside lurid landscapes and interiors: The
Kabanov home has violent magenta wallpaper, while the evening love
scene takes place against a sky that turns from orange through
tangerine to purplish gray. The inanimate world proclaims what most
of the characters dare not reveal: how much heat and vividness they
contain.
</P>
<P>
   The coloring also fits well with the music, especially with
Yakov Kreizberg in the pit to enforce the score's power and
determination. The best singers can stand up to his orchestra's
precise onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Amanda Roocroft is consistently vital and warm as
Katya, the one person in the drama who does reveal herself, and
pays the consequences. Kudrjas' emotionalism is more ironical, and
is captured beautifully by Timothy Robinson, a young lyric tenor
who sings with ease, elegance and a smile. Impressively acted
performances come from Helga Dernesch as the dominating Kabanicha,
Katya's mother-in-law, and Neill Archer as her weakling son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cosi Fan Tutte,'' the other opening production this year, is
altogether more disappointing, and especially so when it comes as
the first installment in a Mozart-da Ponte triptych to be conducted
by Davis and staged by Graham Vick.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' contribution, two nights ago, was rough at the edges.
Maybe this was because there is a lot of roughness, as well, in
Vick's production. Set in a rehearsal room, the work loses a lot of
its dramatic interest, quite apart from the fact that it looks
lifeless and bare.
</P>
<P>
   Because what we see is a semiperformance by modern young people,
the shades and ambiguities of characters playing roles are ironed
out and the corsets of courtliness untied. Games and moments of
passion alike are overplayed; points are made brutally and
physically. Vick has some nice ideas about the long-term damage of
pretense, but they need a more sophisticated production around
them.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The singers, too, might have been coarsened by all the activity
they had to indulge in. Barbara Frittoli gave, nevertheless, a fine
account of Fiordiligi's big second-act aria, and Katarina Karneus
as Dorabella kept alive the sisterly relationship by playfulness
and deferral. Given the opportunity to stand aside from the
rambunctiousness, Alan Opie was a marvelous Don Alfonso: wise,
good-humored, entertained and entertaining, his singing as light as
a feather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Katya'' closes on Sunday, but performances of ``Cosi'' go on
until the beginning of July, alternating with Handel's
``Rodelinda.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
