<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAGUERREOTYPE-$ADV21-     06-16 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAGUERREOTYPE-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTY DAGUERREOTYPE EXHIBIT: TINY WINDOWS, ON THE PAST, SHUTTERS
OPEN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes groundbreaking inventions come along when
the world is not quite ready for them, and then they languish a
while.
</P>
<P>
   When the transistor was developed in 1947, it was thought to
have only a few technical applications; The New York Times stuck
its announcement of the discovery in a radio column. Within 10
years, the inventors were awarded a Nobel prize, and commercial
applications _ transistor radios for one _ were ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   The man who developed the mini-computer, which was smaller than
a mainframe and cost a mere several hundred thousand dollars, said
when the first reports of the PC came out that there would never be
any use for an individual computer in the home.
</P>
<P>
   But other discoveries are so immediately recognized, accepted,
and applied that it seems like the world had been waiting for them
all along. The daguerreotype is the archetypal case: it was perhaps
the most rapidly accepted and disseminated invention in history. In
1839, shortly after his process was announced to the world, Louis
J.M. Daguerre wrote an instruction manual. Within three months, 29
editions were published in six languages.
</P>
<P>
   Now, through July 12, the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles,
which owns one of the most important daguerreotype collections in
the world, has more than 125 examples from its holdings on view, as
well as a display of studio and darkroom equipment from the
collection of Matthew Isenburg. The show was organized by Weston
Naef, curator of photographs, with Julian Cox, Michael Hargraves,
and Jill Finsten, of the Getty.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the daguerreotypes, small black-and-white photographs on
polished silver plates, have never been shown before, and a fair
number are brilliant and/or historic. The museum has also published
a book about its collection and the history of daguerreotypes,
``The Silver Canvas,'' by Bates Lowry and Isabel Barrett Lowry, who
are husband and wife.
</P>
<P>
   On view is a gripping, anonymous portrait of Edgar Allan Poe
that prompted Poe to say on seeing it: ``My life seems wasted. The
future looks like a dreary blank.'' Seldom does a personality so
indelibly inscribe itself on a surface; seldom does a sitter allow
pain, perplexity, and defeat to register so clearly. Racked by
drugs and alcohol, Poe died four months after the picture was
taken.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, is John Jabez Edwin Mayall's mammoth-plate image
(about 12 by 10 inches) of London's Crystal Palace in 1851, a grand
record of the first structure to enclose so large a space in glass
and metal. The building's size is made clear not just by a couple
of people in it but by one of the elm trees that soared beneath its
arched glass vault. At a time when technological advances flew so
fast that they jostled one another, this engineering feat so
impressed Prince Albert that he commanded Joseph Paxton, the
designer, to lead the opening procession, the only time anyone ever
preceded the queen.
</P>
<P>
   The Crystal Palace no longer exists. At the moment of its
demolition in 1941, this photograph acquired a new historic
importance. And as to history, photographers were already recording
what they knew to be important occasions _ in short, news _ on the
little slices of silver-coated copper that Daguerre prescribed.
Witness a picture at the Getty of a convention in Cazenovia, N.Y.,
in 1850, attended by Frederick Douglass, to protest the proposed
Fugitive Slave Law.
</P>
<P>
   Or a photograph taken in 1847 by Southworth and Hawes, the
Boston daguerreotypists, of one of the earliest operations using
ether. Eight doctors and an anesthetist in frock coats and vests
stand about an unconscious patient, their hands bare because the
transmission of disease and infection was not yet understood. The
daguerreotype, used primarily for portraits and requiring long
exposures and lots of light, was nonetheless pressed into service
for one of photography's great enterprises, the recording of events
the moment, or close to the moment, they happen.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Photography leaped into history just as the writing of history
was changing, and the new medium made a significant contribution to
that change. Historians in the 19th century increasingly relied on
primary documents, the lives of people from less-than-aristocratic
classes and direct observation. By the third quarter of the century
it was clear that eye-witness newspaper reporters had forever
altered a profession once modeled on Thucydides, Tacitus, and oral
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs were another reminder that drawings and written
accounts of the past were not necessarily accurate. Even history
painting as an idealized, generic summary of a major event, a genre
once the most revered of artistic categories, was giving way by
mid-century to more specific scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Photography in fact inaugurated a new kind of history, the
family history in picture form. Oh, royalty and the aristocracy had
had personal, rather limited pictorial histories _ a couple of
centuries of forebears looking cossetted and imperial on the walls
of the family manse. Photography gave the middle classes the family
album, but not until the late 1850s, when smaller and cheaper
photographs, like the cartes des visites, drove the
daguerreotypists out of business.
</P>
<P>
   The Getty has an unusual collection of 92 daguerreotypes (29 are
on display) by a wealthy amateur, one Jean-Gabriel Eynard, who made
what amounted to a family album without an album. His servants
posed, his worldly goods and evidence of his achievements sat still
beside him when he took self-portraits, and children grew up before
his lens.
</P>
<P>
   Daguerre regarded the medium as an art, a claim disputed at the
time but hard to deny now in the face of the Getty exhibition. One
of its most artful images is a splendid bit of pornography entitled
``Two Nude Women Embracing'' by an unknown French photographer.
These full-frontal nudes, arranged with voluptuous grace, caress
and regard each other lovingly before a mirror that reflects the
back of one of them. The photograph belongs to the same realm of
erotica as Gustave Courbet's later painting of two intertwined
women, a triumph of fleshy luxury.
</P>
<P>
   In one respect, daguerreotypes can be more ``artistically''
displayed in museums today than ever before; certainly the public
can view them in a way unanticipated by their makers. In their
heyday, in the 1840s and 1850s, there was both an intimacy and a
prologue attached to viewing daguerreotypes. Most plates, enclosed
in cases, were small enough to be readily held in the hand. The
viewer had to open the case, then turn the mirrored surface until
the light struck it at the proper angle, when the image
miraculously appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber optic technology has changed all that. Daguerreotypes can
now be temporarily removed from their cases and hung or propped in
glass display cases like small paintings, their images fully and
instantly visible. The only drawback is that they must sit a
certain distance behind the glass front of the case, making it is
impossible to scrutinize them through a magnifying glass as
19th-century viewers loved to do.
</P>
<P>
   When the daguerreotype was invented, it was one of those
discoveries that the world had indeed been unknowingly waiting for.
Lithography had already accustomed people to an abundance of
printed images. Science was depending ever more heavily on visual
evidence. Art was striving for the most exact realism possible.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences in Europe were enamored of illusionistic spectacles.
Daguerre, a painter and set designer before he succeeded in his
photographic research, had made an enormous reputation with his
Diorama, a theater that presented his large, elaborately devised
paintings. Through ingenious use of paint and light, these seemed
to change from day to night, from unpeopled to crowded.
</P>
<P>
   The daguerreotype, though smaller, devoid of color and reversed
(unless the lens was fitted with a reversing prism), was an even
more convincing illusion of reality. A pre-modern populace, already
yearning for a semblance of the world, rushed to embrace the new
invention.
</P>
<P>
   And embrace it the public did, in enormous numbers. Human beings
have reacted strongly to approximations of reality since an image
was first drawn on the wall of a cave, but by the time photography
became a practical matter, philosophy, culture, and technology had
combined to boost reaction to fever level. A burning need for the
kind of redactions of the world the new medium offered was
discovered as soon as the medium was. Image hunger is rather like a
tapeworm: once it gets into the system, it demands constant
feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Before the new process of photography was fully understood, some
thought it must be magic. ``The Silver Canvas'' quotes an American
poet who, in 1840, longed to see the daguerreotypes that he thought
the sun had been taking since the dawn of the world, including
pictures of Adam and Eve strolling about the garden. He was doomed
to disappointment, and yet the sun would bring him amazing sights
he never would have seen by other means.
</P>
<P>
   It would bring them to us too, and with the aid of fiber optics
_ invention does go on _ some of those still appear in all their
miniature glory at the Getty right this minute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
