<SLUG> BC-VILLA-VILLA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VILLA VILLA': HAPPINESS IS TO FLY AND SWING AND SLAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN.: Argentina)  (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(HLW) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the members of De la Guarda aren't hanging
around, they're yelling and bouncing off the wall. Literally. Most
of De la Guarda's ``Villa Villa,'' which opened on Tuesday at the
Daryl Roth Theater on Union Square, takes place with the performers
overhead, swinging from the ceiling while harnessed to long
tethers. First they appear as speeding shadows behind a ceiling
scrim, like celestial messengers whizzing across a fluorescent
firmament. Then dangling heads break through from above, and the
true mayhem begins.
</P>
<P>
   If the cast of ``Stomp'' reworked Cirque de Soleil in a mosh
pit, it might turn out something like ``Villa Villa,'' which was
first performed by De la Guarda in its home city, Buenos Aires. The
65-minute work is staged without a stage, as the audience stands in
a room like a crowd at a rock club; the music makes its way up to
rock-concert volume, moving from pearly New-Age prettiness to hints
of gamelans and African thumb pianos to pounding drums and howling
voices.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the cast joins the audience on the floor, dancing
to a big beat as if the space were a disco; women from the cast
also surf the crowd, held overhead like teen-agers at a
Lollapalooza Festival. Now and then, De la Guarda's crew herds
spectators out of the way to make room for a flying performer or
movable platforms, where water pours onto the performers (sometimes
spilling onto the audience) and cast members fling their bodies
against noisy sheet-metal floors as if they were on trampolines.
</P>
<P>
   With the tethers, the cast ignores gravity. Two women chase each
other up and around a vertical wall; two men race around a balcony
with their bodies parallel to the floor. A man and a woman, on
separate tethers, pursue each other in midair, finally holding
hands as their momentum carries them into a spinning circle; groups
mesh and metamorphose overhead. Troupe members are indefatigable
and apparently feel no pain. In one segment, a suspended woman is
slammed repeatedly into a wall of fabric, moaning a satisfied
``ah'' after each impact.
</P>
<P>
   If there's an underlying theme in ``Villa Villa,'' it's about
resilience. Most of the performers are dressed in business clothes,
and they're acting out high-speed, stylized, dimensionally skewed
versions of daily events: pursuit and cooperation, romance and
domination. And all it takes to survive in their whiz-bang universe
is the determination to get up afterward and keep on moving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
