<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BONDS DROP A FULL POINT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Giving back much of its previous day's gains, the
Treasury market on Tuesday posted one of its biggest one-day losses
in nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar weakened and overseas equity markets improved their
tone, so some traders moved from Treasuries into shares abroad.
However, domestically, equity prices were still under pressure, and
longer term, analysts expect Treasuries to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond dropped a full point to a price of 106 26/32,
sending its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, up to
5.65 percent, from 5.58 percent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Economic statistics released Tuesday point to a still vibrant
business advance and a lift in trend rate inflation, according to
Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management.
Indeed, the 0.3 percent May rise in consumer prices unnerved many
market participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But while 0.3 percent may be an overstatement of the average
monthly increase in the CPI over the remainder of the year,'' he
said, ``at the same time, inflation is not likely to be as
favorable as the very tame 0.1 percent average of the last six
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bond yields are now in a new, lower range, but there is a
growing debate as to whether the long Treasury bond could move
below 5.50 percent on a sustainable basis with monetary policy on
hold and the Fed having a bias toward tightening, and yet without
any clear-cut evidence of a long-lasting slowdown in economic
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Industrial production was up 0.5 percent in May, and coupled
with some upward revisions to the prior two months it produced the
first rise in capacity utilization since November. Housing in May
remained healthy, although the level fell modestly from April.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate bond calendar is heavy. Among the large issues in
the pipeline is a $3.45 billion, eight-part offering Wednesday from
Niagara Mohawk Corp. that is rated speculative and is the largest
junk deal of the decade, second only to RJR Nabisco's $4 billion
plus in the 1980s, according to MCM Corporatewatch's Data Services.
</P>
<P>
   Price talk ahead of Niagara's megadeal has the yield spread over
Treasury securities with similar maturities ranging from 125 basis
points, or hundredths of a percentage point, for a one-year issue
to about 287.5 basis points for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Proceeds are expected to be used to help pay for a restructuring
plan for the Syracuse-based utility; the plan was approved earlier
this year by New York state regulators.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
