u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-N     06-16 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, June 21,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (New York) _ The Drama Dept.'s quite enchanting
resurrection of ``As Thousands Cheer,'' the 1933 Irving Berlin-Moss
Hart topical revue, which is at the Greenwich House Theater. A
topical revue that is still funny. By Vincent Canby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SIDE-MAN-THEATER (Undated) _ After toiling for 20 years not
exactly anonymously but far from the bright lights of fame as a
freelance journalist, stand-up comic, playwright, screenwriter and
movie director, nobody is more surprised to see ``Side Man,'' a
memory play about jazz performers, land on Broadway than its
author, Warren Leight, 41. In jazz parlance, sideman refers to a
musician who works for hire on band jobs, who knows the standards
by heart and who can solo dazzlingly but also blend in with an
orchestra's sound. By Steven Drukman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FILMS4KIDS (Undated) _ Brief reviews of some films and their
suitability for children. This week: ``The X-Files''; ``Mulan'';
``Six Days, Seven Nights''; ``Can't Hardly Wait'' and ``Dirty
Work.''
</P>
<P>
   SODERBERGH-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ When Lady Luck smiles on a
26-year-old first-time director, she doesn't take it kindly that he
ignores her and heads out on his own path. But now, at 35, after
five well-crafted bleak flops, Steven Soderbergh has returned to
knock on her door with ``Out of Sight,'' an upbeat romantic film
starring George Clooney and Jennifer Lopez. By Jamie Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE-SIGNALS-FILM (Sliammon Indian Reserve, British Columbia) _
The new movie in which Evan Adams, 31, an American Indian actor is
a co-star, ``Smoke Signals,'' opens Friday. It is funny and
complex, as well as poignant, casting a new light on the Indian
sensibility. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINIAN-DANCE (New York) _ The last time the Virsky Ukranian
National Dance Company visited New York, in 1988, Ukraine was part
of the Soviet Union and the troupe was beholden to its Moscow
sponsors. That is, it was strongly encouraged to perform Russian
dances along with Ukranian ones. This week Virsky, one of the
world's premiere professional folk troupes, returns to New York for
three performances at City Center, on Tuesday, Friday and Saturday
as part of a 38-city North American tour. And this time all the
dances are Ukranian. By Terry Trucco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PHYLLIS-CURTIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Phyllis Curtin, the estimable
American soprano, is a singer who has achieved notable success and
respect throughout the field but never quite the recognition she
deserves. This neglect is even more striking in light of two new
releases from Video Artists International featuring Ms. Curtin
recorded live during her prime years, in the 1960s. By Anthony
Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   GENEVA-OPERA-HOUSE (Geneva, Switzerland) _ While other cities
have lost their beloved 19th-century opera houses in the wave of
overgrown performing-arts centers, the board of the opera company
here bucked the tide. At the same time that it took necessary steps
to preserve the Grand Theatre, Geneva's elegant opera house from
1882, it developed a second house in many ways as good as the old
one. By Paula Deitz.
</P>
<P>
   GABRIEL-FAURE-MUSIC (New York) _ Music tells no stories, but it
is a sign of human behavior. John Philip Sousa tells the world that
Americans want to make friends. The music of Gabriel Faure tells us
that the French are private, lonely, tender, furtive, wistful. Five
concerts of Faure's music at the Kaye Playhouse recently were
generously American, just as the music remained elusively French.
By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   PROKOFIEV-MUSIC (Undated) _ Today, as composers are being told
to be more popular, Sergei Prokofiev may re-emerge as a role model
for the young and ambitious. The composer of the ``Classical''
Symphony, ``Peter and the Wolf,'' ``Lieutenant Kije'' and ``Romeo
and Juliet'' knew a thing or two about popularity. By David Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RINGO-STARR-MUSIC (Undated) _ For a musician who was once part
of the most influential band in pop, spending more than a decade
rekindling a career must be an intensely frustrating business. But
listening to ``Vertical Man,'' Ringo Starr's 12th post-Beatles
studio album, one has to admire the cheerful industriousness with
which he has tried to recapture the success of his early hits,
``Ringo'' (1973) and ``Goodnight Vienna'' (1974). By Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DAGUERREOTYPE (Undated) _ The daguerreotype is perhaps the most
rapidly accepted and disseminated invention in history. In 1839,
shortly after his process was announced to the world, Louis J.M.
Daguerre wrote an instruction manual. Within three months, 29
editions were published in six languages. Now, through July 12, the
J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, which owns one of the most
important daguerreotype collections in the world, has more than 125
examples from its holdings on view, as well as a display of studio
and darkroom equipment from the collection of Matthew Isenburg. By
Vicki Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY (Undated) _ Even though Rafael Vinoly is the
most elegant architect now practicing in the United States, he
probably doesn't want to hear about it. The elegance of his work is
ascetic as well as esthetic. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SUNVALLEY (Undated) _ A summer of double axels. By Linda
Greenhouse. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PRAGUE (Undated) _ Prague: The immersion course. By
Judith H. Dobrzynski. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-JAMAICA (Undated) _ Jamaica sweeps off its welcome mat.
By Edwin McDowell. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CYBER-TRAVEL (Undated) _ Surfing the net. By L.R. Shannon.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Boarding passes take a nosedive.
By Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Travel notes and news: Maine and Nova
Scotia: Moving closer together; Northwest and Delta raise
baby-sitting fees; New horizons for frequent fliers; Travels with
Steinbeck, on view in Salinas. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Taking a car to Europe; On Hans Brinker's
heels; Civil War tours. (Moved).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1836EDT &QL; 
