A2014 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     06-16 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANDPARENTS HAVE IMPORTANT `WORK' TO DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mama Ruby died suddenly the year I moved to Sacramento. She was
84 and had lived a full life. But growing up, I never imagined
living out my own life without her.
</P>
<P>
   I think about her now, remembering those thick signature braids
on her head, her sense of humor, her heart, and I wonder how I ever
got this far without her.
</P>
<P>
   Never a day passes that I don't remember her, but I was reminded
recently of the important role she played in my life, the important
role all grandparents play. I've wished a thousand times we could
just sit and talk like old times. I wished my own daughters, Asha
and Jamila, could know such moments.
</P>
<P>
   They have only one grandparent, their father's mother, and she
lives miles away in Illinois. Although they talk by phone on a
regular basis and exchange gifts through the mail, they've seen her
only four, maybe five times in the nine years since Jamila was
born.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many children, their grandparents are either dead or
live too far away for regular visits.
</P>
<P>
   And so I was delighted to read that the Texas Department of
Protective and Regulatory Services recently launched a program to
fill that void.
</P>
<P>
   Young at Heart matches residents 55 and older to act as
surrogate grandparents to children at Tarrant County day-care
centers. They provide a wide range of services, including rocking
infants, reading stories, gardening and creating art and music.
</P>
<P>
   At ages 7 and 9, my daughters are too old to benefit from such a
program, but officials estimate that there are more than 265,000
Texas children in child-care facilities who can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to realize that children not only need homes
and good families, studies show that when an adult gives a child
one-on-one attention, it makes a huge difference in the way that
child grows,'' said Jennifer Clark, Tarrant County's project
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   By providing children with surrogate grandparents, officials
hope to enhance their self-esteem and promote healthy brain
development. They also believe that simple physical contact like
recognition, touching, hugging or a pat on the head gives a child a
sense of comfort and feeling of acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of Young at Heart also extend to its volunteers,
providing them the opportunity to feel needed, to the child-care
facility and even to the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I'm just trying to do a little good, if I can,'' said
88-year-old Inetta Schnitzer. ``I love the youngsters, and they
seem to respond to the way I help them.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnitzer, who spends her time reading to 4-year-olds, is one of
two seniors who volunteer at Children's World in Arlington, said
director Sylvia Dougharty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children love her, and the parents just go crazy about
her,'' Dougharty said of Schnitzer, who has two grown grandchildren
of her own. ``We couldn't have asked for a sweeter person.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clark said that more seniors like Schnitzer are needed. To
date, only 10 have signed on with the program. There are about 90
child-care centers across Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to have at least two volunteers at each
center,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for the program, interested seniors must undergo a
criminal background check and attend a 1 1/2-hour-long orientation.
Seniors interested in volunteering may contact Clark at 640-9600,
Ext. 2014.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
