</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLLUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS CALIFORNIA STUDENTS FACE POLLUTION THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Industrial air pollutants expose half of
California's schoolchildren, including many in the San Francisco
Bay area, to chemicals known to cause cancer, respiratory illness
and other diseases, according to a new study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay-area refineries operated by Tosco Oil Corp. and Shell
Oil Co. have the largest amounts of particulate and gaseous
emissions in the state, and are within a mile of five Martinez
schools, according to ``School Haze: Air Pollution Near California
Schools'' prepared by the Environmental Working Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Working Group, a national organization,
analyzed 1995 reports to the Environmental Protection Agency and
school attendance records in doing its research.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that in Fremont, the New United Motor
Manufacturing Co. (NUMMI), which emits carcinogens, reproductive
toxins and heavy metals, is within a mile of nine schools. NUMMI is
jointly owned by the General Motors Corp. and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Both NUMMI and Tosco say the emission reports are correct but
question the number of schools listed as within a mile of their
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have continuously reduced our toxic air emissions,'' said
Stuart Rupp, manager of environmental affairs at NUMMI. ``We're
building a new paint shop, which is going to be using new
state-of-the-art equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it would reduce the emissions at one of two shops by 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our models show that the risk at our fence line from toxic
chemicals is less than 1 in 1 million,'' Rupp said.
</P>
<P>
   A Shell spokesman, Mark Hughes, called the study ``a contrived
report targeting Martinez.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 2.8 million California children were enrolled in 4,293
schools within one mile of an industrial emitter of the chemicals,
the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of children represented more than half of the
enrollment in some 9,700 public and private schools in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say children are more susceptible than adults to
environmental contaminants. Their bodies are growing rapidly and
sensitive organs and tissues are developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children eat proportionately more food, drink more fluids and
breathe more air per pound of body weight. They play outside more,
and are more exposed to environmental threats ... They crawl on the
ground and floor and expose themselves to different hazards,'' the
study said.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental organization said the state has failed to
adequately monitor pollution near schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few children _ about one in 25 _ attended schools covered
by the existing network of air pollution monitors,'' the study
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The existing network of 189 state monitors misses the great
majority of schools where proximity to known pollution sources puts
students at increased risk of exposure to air pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   The group surveyed six different types of pollutants:
carcinogens, heavy metals, reproductive toxins, particulate matter,
nitrogen oxide and sulfur dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   It posted the list of schools within one mile of 1995 emissions
on the Internet at www.ewg.org/risk.
</P>
<P>
   Tosco's refinery near Martinez is the largest source of nitrogen
oxide, sulfur dioxide and other particulates in the state, and, the
study said, is within a mile of an elementary and high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report said how much is emitted, but it doesn't address
the risk of what is a safe level. The federal EPA and the state Air
Resources Board are currently developing a nitrogen oxide rule
right now. They're doing air modeling and studying the data and
trying to determine the health effects of nitrogen oxides.'' Tosco
spokesman David Kory said.
</P>
<P>
   Kory said one listed in the study is 4 miles away from the
Martinez refinery, not a mile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
