<HEADLINE>
FILM FESTIVAL EXPLORES THE BANALITY OF EVIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JIM YARDLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Movies perform all sorts of back flips to shock
people these days, which makes an early scene in the documentary
``Gerrie and Louise'' notable for its understated horror. The
film's central figure, Gerrie Hugo, once a commander of a South
African hit squad, is discussing torture.
</P>
<P>
   It is late at night, and Hugo is talking to the camera. He has
exposed atrocities of the old South African government and married
a crusading reporter, Louise Flanagan. Dragging on a cigarette, a
little woozy from beer, Hugo is a charming rogue, and he knows it.
What is less clear is whether he is a man whose conversion can be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Seduced by the camera, he cannot help but laugh as he describes
his old life, how he once attached electrical wires to the teeth of
a black prisoner. Every jolt of electricity triggered a small
explosion in the man's mouth. The power, Hugo admits, was
intoxicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person was so submissive,'' he says with an incredulous
smile, ``that I could do that with him and still talk to him
afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Films often trivialize evil. What makes ``Gerrie and Louise''
and many of the other films shown at the Human Rights Watch
International Film Festival distinctive is how they often manage to
shock by depicting only human complexity and its ragged, sometimes
awful edges.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, which is in its ninth year, began on Thursday and
runs until June 25 at the Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln Center in
Manhattan. Featuring 33 films from 19 countries, the festival
offers documentaries, dramas and satires of wildly different scope.
``Rezistans,'' a sweeping political history of Haiti, lasts 156
minutes; ``Two and a Half Weeks in Paradise,'' about the
dispossessed in Siberia, lasts 10.
</P>
<P>
   Because its ambitions are artistic and political, the festival
suffers inherent burdens. How can you truly measure success? If, as
Abraham Lincoln suggested, ``Uncle Tom's Cabin'' helped trigger the
Civil War, what should be expected of a movie like ``An Ordinary
President,'' a wicked satire of the current president of Belarus?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it can be measured with a measuring cup: whether
a dictator has been felled,'' said Bruni Burres, the festival
director. ``What we've said all along is that these films
inspire.'' Some of them ``get lost,'' Ms. Burres conceded. ``Some
sit on shelves. But a lot don't.''
</P>
<P>
   One that did not was ``Calling the Ghost: A Story About Rape,
War and Women,'' which had its premiere at the 1996 festival and
earned the top award, the Nestor Almendros Prize. The film,
produced and directed by Mandy Jacobson, is the story of two
Bosnian women, a lawyer and a judge, who were raped at Omarska, the
Serbian concentration camp, in 1991. It was not the sort of film
destined for movie houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We constantly have this struggle between those of us who are
making these movies and those who are controlling the outlets over
what it is people want to see,'' said Ms. Jacobson, who lives in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   But after its festival premiere, the film attracted the
attention of Home Box Office, which showed it on Cinemax. The two
women, Jadranka Cigelj and Nusreta Sivac, accompanied the film on a
25-city U.S tour and showed it at the Council on Foreign Relations
to an audience that included Richard Holbrooke, the former Clinton
administration envoy to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
