<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIGHTS-FILM-FESTIVAL-     06-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIGHTS-FILM-FESTIVAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: to Bosnia. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``These women were basically able to confront the politicians on
why they were not doing anything,'' said Ms. Jacobson. Eventually,
British forces patrolling Bosnia under auspices of the United
Nations captured two men accused of rape and other war crimes at
the camp.
</P>
<P>
   This year, ``An Ordinary President'' and its ebullient director,
Yuri Khashchevatsky, won the festival's Almendros Prize. It, too,
is enjoying an unusual influence at home. A humorous but pointed
satire of President Alexandr Lukaschenko of Belarus, the film
exposes his hypocrisy in promising to root out corruption as he
profits from it. By flashing images of Stalin, Khashchevatsky makes
clear what sort of president he considers Lukaschenko to be.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the film has been seen in Belarus only once. In
January 1997, a small cable station in a remote town showed a
bootleg copy. As the final credits were rolling, local and national
police kicked open the locked doors of the television station and
seized the movie. Lukaschenko promptly banned it. Several months
later, two men broke into Khashchevatsky's studio and beat him
unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't take anything except my scripts,'' said
Khashchevatsky, speaking through a translator during an interview
in Manhattan. He believes his attackers were sent by the
government, he said, adding, ``I have no other hypothesis.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ban, Khashchevatsky said, the extensive black market
in Belarus, developed during the Soviet era, has allowed him to
distribute about 150,000 video copies of the film. He estimated
that 800,000 of the 10 million people in Belarus have seen it.
Street vendors, he said, often hugged him and gave him free
bananas. He said he had made the film as a rejoinder to what he
called the misleading propaganda disseminated by the government on
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this duel, they chose their weapons,'' Khashchevatsky said.
``So I decided that my response would be through a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Khashchevatsky, who obviously enjoyed tweaking the president,
nonetheless described the political impact of ``An Ordinary
President'' as limited. Its success, he said, may come in helping
people in Belarus ``have the feeling of opposition, even if it is
unformed,'' but no more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to be able to say that this film is leading
Belarus to a new era,'' he said. ``But it is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Sturla Gunnarsson, the Canadian who made ``Gerrie and Louise,''
had not produced a documentary in 10 years when he was drawn to
South Africa in 1996 by the wrenching spectacle of the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission. Charged with unearthing the facts about
government-sponsored murders of black activists, the commission,
which is still operating, promised immunity from prosecution for
anyone who came forward.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued with ``the bad guys'' and fascinated with exploring
the depth of forgiveness in South Africa, Gunnarsson said, he
interviewed several former soldiers in the South African Defense
Force before realizing that Gerrie Hugo was his story. Hugo had
violated the sacred creed of covert soldiers by going public,
revealing the complicity of the white government in operations
against blacks. He had also married Ms. Flanagan, who had written a
litany of exposes about government-sponsored killings.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Flanagan's ability to love and forgive Hugo, and Hugo's
ambivalent feelings about his own past, drew Gunnarsson to them, he
said. ``He would tell me stories that would make me an
accomplice,'' Gunnarsson said of Hugo. ``He would make me laugh,
and then I would stop because he was telling me things that were
gross human-rights violations.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Khashchevatsky, whose film was aimed at his native
Belarus, Gunnarsson said he did not make his film for South Africa.
``Gerrie and Louise'' has been shown on Canadian national
television and on CNN. The film is to be shown in 30 countries, he
said, but not South Africa, because of disarray at the national
broadcasting agency.
</P>
<P>
   Although political change has already occurred in South Africa,
Gunnarsson said he hoped his film would continue to draw attention
to what Hannah Arendt called ``the banality of evil.''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``We all know these kinds of human rights violations go
on. We all know apartheid is an evil thing. There's no news there.
But I wanted to know how these things happen. How do ordinary
people get involved?''
</P>
<P>
   He felt that through Hugo, ``you could begin to understand these
horrors and how people could do them, and that they're not
monsters,'' Gunnarsson said. ``They're just like you and me. It
leads you to the conclusion that evil is part of the human
condition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
