<HEADLINE>
ALIENS, A COVER-UP: YES, A JOB FOR MULDER AND SCULLY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE X-FILES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Bowman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David Duchovny, Gillian Anderson, Martin Landau, William B.
Davis &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 121 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cigarette Smoking Man (Davis) and his co-conspirators are up
to no good _ in Dallas, Washington, London and Antarctica. Fox
Mulder (Duchovny) and Dana Scully (Ms. Anderson), television's
favorite lonely, intense FBI agents, transfer their search for the
truth to the big screen. A terrorist bombing leads them to a
government cover-up (what else?) of a new form of alien life and
``a plague to end all plagues.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Exploding buildings and cars, deadly attacks by aliens.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A dozen or so curses or vulgarities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 No. Some of the action is so loud and sudden that
children this age would be terrified. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 9-12 If they're fans of the series, they can probably
handle the film. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Please. They're already in the ticket-holders'
line.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Gates &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MULAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking voices of Ming-Na Wen, Eddie Murphy, B.D. Wong, Miguel
Ferrer, Pat Morita, Harvey Fierstein, Soon-Tek Oh, June Foray;
singing voices of Lea Salonga, Donny Osmond &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Barry Cook and Tony Bancroft &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 86 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese teen-ager disguises herself as a boy to take her frail
father's place in the Emperor's ragtag army and save her country
from the rampaging Huns. Based on a legend from the Northern Wei
dynasty (A.D. 386-534), this animated feature is part
``Pocahontas,'' part ``The Mighty Ducks'' and mostly ``Yentl.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE The leader of the Huns looks scary, but no scarier than
any Saturday morning cartoon villain. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None, but Mulan finds herself accidentally skinny-dipping
with the guys, and there are gentle jokes about cross-dressing.
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 Even if they don't understand all the intricacies,
they'll be rooting for Mulan and may learn something about China. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-11 This age group will enjoy the movie, but girls
particularly will adore the spunky heroine and get the message that
girls are as good as boys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP They'll love it, too, but because it's a Disney
film, they may pretend they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Higbie &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SIX DAYS, SEVEN NIGHTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Ford, Anne Heche, David Schwimmer, Jacqueline Obradors &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Ivan Reitman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   146 minutes PG-13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On a South Seas vacation with her boyfriend (Schwimmer), a New
York magazine editor (Ms. Heche) is called to Tahiti for a photo
shoot. Hiring a puddle-jumper of an aircraft and its raffish pilot
(Ford), she sets off, but the two run into a storm and crash-land
on a gorgeous but remote outcropping. There, remarkably well
outfitted on such short notice, they battle pirates, dine on
peacock, jump off a cliff and take a shine to each other. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Pirates gun down a yacht owner and assault the
castaways, but the film is more a comedy than a thriller. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Some of the outfits qualify as near nudity. Ford and Ms.
Heche's romantic attraction, aside from a smooch in the surf,
doesn't progress beyond talk. Schwimmer's character, on the other
hand, has an all-night tryst with a resort ``it'' girl (Ms.
Obradors), though this, too, is only alluded to and not shown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY A little. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 Inappropriate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 Parents should be aware of the profanity and sexual
situations, but nothing is extreme. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP There's nothing in the film that would offend the
sensibilities of teen-agers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peter M. Nichols &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T HARDLY WAIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
