<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROKOFIEV-MUSIC-$ADV2     06-16 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROKOFIEV-MUSIC-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE CASE FOR PROKOFIEV AS HEAVYWEIGHT CONTENDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)  (David Schiff is a composer on the faculty of Reed College in
Portland, Ore.)  
 (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, as composers are being told to be more popular, Sergei
Prokofiev may re-emerge as a role model for the young and
ambitious. The composer of the ``Classical'' Symphony, ``Peter and
the Wolf,'' ``Lieutenant Kije'' and ``Romeo and Juliet'' knew a
thing or two about popularity. His innate sense of how to please an
audience brought him early fame and allowed his music to reach
millions for whom classical music, let alone most of its
20th-century varieties, was a closed book.
</P>
<P>
   His popular touch was also a curse, an unaccountable and
unreliable resource that enslaved Prokofiev to the adulation of
audiences and the whims of critics and commissars who could shape
an audience's opinions. Yet despite a half-century of overexposure,
at least of the warhorses, and critical condescension, much of
Prokofiev's large body of work continues to attract performers and
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Now, an eardrum-shattering recording of the five piano
concertos, with Alexander Toradze as soloist and the Kirov
Orchestra conducted by Valery Gergiev (Philips 289 462 048-2; two
CDs), reveals unsuspected depth and passion in a composer who has
been either loved or despised for his facility, charm and
unmistakable melodic flair.
</P>
<P>
   In many accounts of his life and work, Prokofiev appears like a
sleepwalker in a minefield, semiconscious about art and politics.
Contemporaries described him as both unintellectual and
unemotional. His judgments about other music were philistine and
self-serving. Like other composers who achieved early success,
Prokofiev could not deal with failure, and he disowned fine works,
like the Second Symphony and the Fifth Piano Concerto, which failed
to please critics.
</P>
<P>
   This apparent lack of artistic integrity was paralleled by
character flaws in his personal and political life, which continue
to shadow his reputation, if not his popularity.
</P>
<P>
   The music, too, has a somnambulistic quality. The first five
symphonies, for example, seem to have been written by five
different composers unfamiliar with one another's works. At the
same time, all of his music possesses a strong personality, which
is clearly audible even in his earliest works. But personality,
like popularity, was an unearned gift that seemed to mystify the
composer.
</P>
<P>
   In a strange act of pre-emptive self-deconstruction, Prokofiev
enumerated the content of his small yet potent bag of tricks:
Classicism, motorism, lyricism and grotesquerie. To these may be
added three Prokofiev trademarks: the mocking march, the ironic
gavotte and the sour waltz. He returned to these formulas
throughout his life, as if they were talismans. But his writings
about his own music rarely touch on more complex issues of musical
construction or expression.
</P>
<P>
   Such symptoms of superficiality have hurt Prokofiev's critical
standing, which has declined sharply while Shostakovich's has
soared. In Richard Taruskin's book ``Defining Russia Musically,''
which brilliantly re-evaluates Russian music from Glinka to
Schnittke, Prokofiev is blown away in a couple of lines of
surprisingly conventional wisdom: ``It is utterly characteristic of
Prokofiev that beneath the clangorous surface there always lay a
simple harmonic design and a stereotyped formal pattern straight
out of the textbook.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, Prokofiev was an insincere hack. He lacked the
inventiveness and finesse of Stravinsky, the tragic sense of
Shostakovich.
</P>
<P>
   The unflattering comparisons are hard to counter. Where
Stravinsky's music can turn on a kopeck, Prokofiev clumsily inserts
an eight-bar vamp to get from one idea to another, or just bring
the music to a full stop. And instead of the gut-wrenching
bleakness so often evoked by Shostakovich, Prokofiev's music, when
it is emotionally effective, tends to be poignant, as in the close
of the ballet ``The Prodigal Son,'' rather than cathartic.
</P>
<P>
   Today Prokofiev stands as an erratic lightweight, perhaps the
greatest second-rate composer of the century but second-rate
nonetheless, with a gift for narrative and mood that gave him
pre-eminence in the forms of the concerto, ballet and movie music,
where broad strokes count for more than finesse or profundity.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze and Gergiev clearly intend to challenge that image.
Particularly in the first two concertos here, Prokofiev emerges as
a heavyweight, a contender.
</P>
<P>
   This recording has been long awaited, or long dreaded, ever
since Toradze won second prize at the Van Cliburn Competition in
1977, apparently over the dead bodies of many jurors. In Joseph
Horowitz's 1990 book about the competition, ``The Ivory Trade,''
Toradze appeared as an anti-establishment hero. Horowitz praised in
particular the ``traumatic intensity'' of Toradze's performances of
Prokofiev's Second Concerto, and the aptness of that phrase is
borne out here.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze's controversial status has only grown since Horowitz's
book appeared. Many musicians roll their eyes at the mention of his
name; for others, he is the real thing, a performer who goes beyond
the notes. While Horowitz's praise may not have swayed critical
opinion, Toradze's close alliance with Gergiev, the hottest
conductor of the day, may force even those who have dismissed him
out of hand to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   In a typically cannibalistic feat of marketing strategy,
Polygram Classics has released the Toradze set almost
simultaneously with a bargain reissue of the highly praised 1975
recording of the five concertos by Vladimir Ashkenazy, with the
London Symphony conducted by Andre Previn (London 452 588-2; two
CDs).
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two sets can be put simply by noting
that for Ashkenazy the Third Concerto seems like the centerpiece of
the five, but Toradze, in his own booklet note, gives the Second
the highest rank. These two works are like biblical brothers: one
light, the other dark; one smooth, the other hairy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Third, Prokofiev sleekly updated the Romantic concerto.
The soloist is no longer a brooding poet weighed down by yearnings
and dreams but an Olympic athlete leaping over hurdles ever higher.
In the two recordings of the Third, Ashkenazy still wins a gold
medal, and Toradze fails even to place, or else seems to be staging
a counter-Olympics with different rules.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the welter of notes in the Third, Ashkenazy always finds
the music with limitless resources of touch and expression.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
