<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SCIENTIFIC TO BUY PFIZER VASCULAR UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Scientific Corp. will spend $2.1 billion in cash to buy
the vascular devices unit of Pfizer Inc., outbidding several
competitors to gain a major market position in products used to
clear clogged arteries.
</P>
<P>
   The sale follows Pfizer's decision in February to sell or spin
off its medical products businesses &UR;  &LR; and focus on its
pharmaceutical products, which include Viagra, the best-selling
male impotence drug.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The unit, Schneider Worldwide, sells surgical stents, the
scaffolding used by physicans to prop open arteries, and
artery-clearing devices used in a procedure known as balloon
angioplasty. Such products are gaining in popularity because they
are used in minimally invasive procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is Boston Scientific's largest since early 1995,
when it began buying smaller marketers &UR;  &LR; of minimally invasive
surgical devices. With Tuesday's purchase, Boston Scientific has
spent $5.6 billion on 11 companies since early 1995, said Lawrence
C. Best, the Natick, Mass. company's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to like the deal. Boston Scientific shares
closed at 62 3/4, up 1 3/4, while Pfizer shares also rose 1 3/4 to
close at 109 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Schneider Worldwide had sales of $330 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Some Wall Street analysts said that Boston Scientific was
paying a steep price _ more than six times sales _ to expand into
the stent market, but that the move was worth it. The stent market
is growing quickly, with a variety of American and foreign
competitors, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston Scientific had a choice: either pay more or get left
behind, so they had to suck it up and pay what looks like a big
price for Schneider,'' said Daniel T. Lemaitre, managing director
and medical device analyst at Cowen &AMP; Co. ``I think they did the
right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For Boston Scientific, which hopes to get government &UR;  &LR; approval
of an internally developed stent next month, the Schneider purchase
provides a new technology, more than a dozen patents, and entry
into the growing cardiovascular stent market.  &UR;  &LR;  A key Schneider
product, called the Wallstent, &UR;  &LR; accounts for more than $100 million
of the unit's annual revenue. It is a tube inserted into patients
with clogged arteries in areas such as the groin, neck, and
kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Best said he expects Schneider's sales to jump to $500 million a
year in 1999, with 30 percent operating margins.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that Boston Scientific outbid rivals, but
declined to name them. Earlier this month, several Wall Street
analysts said Boston Scientific was competing against several
companies including Arterial Vascular Engineering Inc. of Santa
Rosa, Calif., a leading stent developer.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider &UR;  &LR; employs about 2,200 worldwide, including 1,200 in the
United States. &UR;  &LR; Its global headquarters are near Zurich, with US
operations based in Plymouth, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can bring costs in the overall stent market down
and help bring the product costs of the medical procedure down,''
said Best.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, he added, will be dilutive to Boston
Scientific's 1999 earnings by as much as five cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boston Scientific earned $139.3 million, or 72 cents
a share, on revenue of $1.87 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To finance the $2.1 billion purchase, Best said, Boston
Scientific will borrow about half the total, with the balance split
equally between a forthcoming convertible debt offering and a
common stock sale planned later this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2043 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROKOFIEV-MUSIC-$ADV2     06-16 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROKOFIEV-MUSIC-$ADV21-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and expression.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toradze's Third often sounds like a willful parody. Everything
is exaggerated. Passages marked forte or even mezzo forte are
pounded out fortissimo, and climactic moments threaten to split the
soundboard if not the keyboard. Allegro passages are played presto;
andante seems to mean adagio. Much of the passage work, so
carefully articulated by Ashkenazy without in any way damaging the
propulsive energy of the music, is either blurred or crassly
unshaped.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze seems to be giving a lesson in how not to play the
piece, or he is suggesting, unconvincingly, that the piece is not
the genial fingerfest that audiences usually take it for.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze's frantic travesty of the Third Concerto becomes more
comprehensible in light of his account of the Second, a work better
suited to his Romantic personality. In his notes, he explains that
the Second Concerto commemorates Prokofiev's friend Maximilian
Shmitgoff, the object of one of the composer's few profound human
attachments, who killed himself in 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze describes the piece as a tone poem that follows
Shmitgoff from the cradle to the grave. In this work Prokofiev not
only memorialized his friend but also, according to Toradze,
revealed a passionate and tormented soul, which he kept hidden in
most of his other music.
</P>
<P>
   This reading may seem naive, but it points to strengths in the
music that are often ignored. Prokofiev may not have constructed
music with Stravinskian precision, but he knew how to tell a story.
Whether or not the Second is a portrait of Shmitgoff, it turns its
soloist into a tragic protagonist who traces an emotional arc from
brooding melancholy to rage and finally to acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   In Toradze's hands the music is an epic shriek, which Prokofiev
amplifies in two huge piano solos that build up to the outer limit
of what a performer and an instrument can project, and beyond.
Typical of Prokofiev, these solos are not carefully nuanced. They
owe their power to sheer relentlessness, pushing performer and
listeners to the breaking point.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze does nothing to disguise the music's cruelty; he
embraces its excesses with an over-the-top performance of an
over-the-edge concerto. The Second here seems to witness a horror
larger and fiercer even than the death of a dear friend; it earns a
place among the great tragic utterances of the century, like
Mahler's Sixth Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Toradze and Ashkenazy shed contrasting lights on the other
concertos as well. Prokofiev wrote his First Piano Concerto when he
was just 21. Its audacity made him famous overnight. In Toradze's
hands the work is not just impetuous but also visionary. As he does
with the Second Concerto, he exploits the work's apparent weakness,
its obsessive restatements of its main theme, and turns it into a
strength, a statement of youthful fervor.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, both Toradze and Gergiev snooze through the Fourth
Concerto, a work for left hand only, written, like Ravel's Concerto
in D, for Paul Wittgenstein, who refused to play it. Toradze's
unfocused reading seems to confirm Wittgenstein's judgment, but in
Ashkenazy's recording, with its greater sense of line, the piece
seems richer in emotional contrasts and far more adroit in
construction than any of its predecessors. Here Prokofiev was
already far along a path that took him beyond the bad-boy pose that
sparked the first three concertos.
</P>
<P>
   The later, Soviet, Prokofiev, is an even greater mystery than
the fledgling composer. Suddenly the crass young charmer began to
compose profound music, like the first Violin Sonata and the Sixth
Symphony. But these works were strewn, as if randomly, among more
typical crowd-pleasers like the Second Violin Concerto, the Fifth
Symphony, and a long list of Stalinist potboilers, the terra
blessedly incognita of the composer's output.
</P>
<P>
   Although critics today may wonder whether the heavier late works
are only superficially deep, the greatest Soviet artists took them
most seriously. While both Toradze and Ashkenazy reveal appealing
aspects of the Fifth Concerto, you have to hear the recently
reissued recording by Sviatoslav Richter, with the Warsaw National
Philharmonic conducted by Witold Rowicki (also from Polygram, on
Deutsche Grammophon 449 744-2; CD), to appreciate the much greater
economy, inventiveness and emotional complexity that Prokofiev
achieved as he turned 40. The awakened sleepwalker now commands
every second of the music.
</P>
<P>
   On the same disk, Richter performs the Eighth Piano Sonata, an
artistic peak before which every critical reservation you might
have about Prokofiev simply collapses.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hazards of being popular is the illusion of intimacy.
Balletomanes and basketball fans put themselves on a first-name
basis with stars they have never met. Because Prokofiev was
popular, we may think we know him, but like Gershwin, he was a
master of disguise, even when he appeared to be most forthright.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes he gave away for his own work, the naive belief in
Classical forms, the apologies for stylistic sins may all have been
smoke screens, designed to make him look like a sleepwalker when he
was, in fact, a great chess player whose next move no one could
predict. We have not yet taken the full measure of the man or his
music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
