<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US LOSS NO EMBARRASSMENT, BUT A LETDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It wasn't anywhere near as bad as it was the last time
the US men's soccer team played a World Cup opener in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Czechoslovakia in 1990 was a complete embarrassment,''
recalled midfielder Tab Ramos Tuesday. ``We got hammered. It was
5-1 and it could have been worse.''
</P>
<P>
   This time it was only 2-0 against a team of Germans who could be
holding the Cup over their heads next month. But what bothered the
Americans after they'd slept on Monday night's loss at the Parc des
Princes was (itals)how(unitals) they'd lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing to Germany in itself isn't a disgrace,'' said Alexi
Lalas. ``Lots of great teams have lost to the Germans. But the way
we lost, we feel we let ourselves down.''
</P>
<P>
   Up against the seasoned European champions, who've won three
Cups and reached five of the last eight finals, the Americans came
out timid and tentative. When Andreas Moeller squeezed a header
between Mike Burns and the goalpost in the ninth minute, they were
in shock. By the time the US began coming forward and creating
chances in the second half, the Germans were well in command.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks didn't cave and they didn't quit, but they didn't show
the world what they wanted _ that their second-round effort last
time wasn't just a matter of California home cookin'.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to win the World Cup, because we know that's
not going to happen,'' said Ramos. ``But we wanted to show we've
improved, and I don't think we did a good job of that. We looked
more like the 1990 team than the 1994 team _ and that's not
acceptable. I'll be honest with you: If we don't play better
against Iran, we're not going to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans can't beat the Iranians in Lyon Sunday, they're
finished and they admit it. And unless they win by at least two
goals, they could lose out on goal differential if they tie the
Yugoslavs in the group finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play for 3 points from the first second,'' said
coach Steve Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   So he's shaking up his lineup to get more scoring punch,
starting at least two of the three men he brought off the bench
against the Germans. Ramos, finally back in peak form after tearing
up the same knee twice in less than a year, will replace Ernie
Stewart in the midfield. And midfielder Frankie Hejduk, who had the
Americans' only serious scoring chance against the Germans with a
diving header, will step in for Burns.
</P>
<P>
   And though Sampson wouldn't say so Tuesday (``Nothing is for
sure yet''), odds are he'll start Roy Wegerle instead of Eric
Wynalda at striker in his 3-6-1 formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against Iran, we have to put people on the field who will
attack and get behind their defense,'' said Sampson, who yanked
Wynalda in the 64th minute after he'd failed to strike sparks.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans have never lit up the scoreboard (they produced
only one goal from the run of play in the 1994 Cup), but they've
been barren since their 3-0 demolition of Austria in April,
suffering shutouts in three of their last four matches.
</P>
<P>
   They had no illusions about beating the Germans, but what
bothered the Americans Tuesday was that they'd sat back until they
were in extremis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we started out playing for a 0-0 tie,'' said
midfielder Chad Deering. ``The first 15 or 20 minutes, we were
asleep out there. We put ourselves back on our heels and punished
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Moeller's goal had much to do with that. ``It changed the entire
dynamics of the game,'' said Sampson. But so did the mugging that
man-marker Jens Jeremies did on US playmaker Claudio Reyna all
night.
</P>
<P>
   After kneeing Reyna in the kidneys in the first 30 seconds to
leave a calling card, Jeremies knocked him off the ball every time
Reyna touched it. When none of his mates stepped up to take over
(until Ramos came in 20 minutes from time), the US attack went
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you watch Eurosport and they say, `Here's the best
scoring chance for the Americans in the first half,' and it's like
a cross from 30 yards out,'' mused Ramos, ``you know you've got a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   While they would have liked to produce some decent film
highlights, the Americans are still where they figured they'd be
after one game _ 0-1 and probably needing to beat Iran, 2-0, and
tie Yugoslavia to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of us talked about it ... and said, `You know, we
could have played well and still lost, 3-0,''' said Ramos. ``We
lost to the Germans. So what? Everybody loses to the Germans. Let's
forget about it and think about Iran.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
