<SLUG> BC-MA-CHILDREN-POVERTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL SHOWS BAY STATE ECONOMY OVERSHADOWING CHILD POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A recent public opinion poll has found that
Massachusetts residents seriously underestimate the number of
children who are living in poverty in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In a survey of 408 residents, only 24 percent correctly placed
the number of poor children under age 18 here at 200,000. Forty-one
percent guessed the number was much lower.
</P>
<P>
   Jetta Bernier, executive director of the Massachusetts Committee
for Children and Youth, said the overall optimism created by the
robust economy seems to be obscuring public awareness of the extent
of child poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has a sense we are all doing pretty well,'' said
Bernier. ``But there is a population of children being left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted for the Massachusetts Committee for
Children and Youth's Campaign for Children, a grassroots advocacy
organization, to gauge public attitudes on issues of child welfare.
The poll was conducted in March by DiNatale and Hock Research and
has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also measured public sentiment toward various proposals
for improving children's well-being.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; When it comes to child sex abuse, most residents polled
favored tougher punishment _ the death penalty, longer prison
sentences and lifetime parole _ for both adult and adolescent
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   But a significant portion, 40 percent, still saw comprehensive
treatment as the best way to stop children from sexually abusing
other children. By contrast, only 20 percent believe treatment
would be effective for adult offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Latham, a forensic psychologist who works with violent
juveniles and child sex offenders, said the tendency by politicians
in recent years has been to emphasize punishment over treatment for
juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the poll shows, as previous studies have, that a large
portion of the public believes that the younger an offender is, the
more effective treatment tends to be, Latham said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents surveyed said that they favored other measures that
could improve the lives of poor children and their families, even
if it meant the state or businesses would have to spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four percent indicated that they would be very supportive
of a law increasing the minimum wage by 50 cents per hour and
indexing the minimum wage to inflation; 62 percent favor a law
expanding after-school care for children from low- and middle-
income families; and 60 percent support a law guaranteeing child
care for all low-income families with at least one person working.
</P>
<P>
   There was less enthusiasm for other proposals. Fifty-five
percent said they would strongly back a law guaranteeing home
visits for all newborns of parents under age 21; 51 percent
supported a law that would require companies to pay the same
salaries to permanent and temporary workers who do the same job;
and 21 percent indicated strong support for a law providing public
assistance to families who pay more than 10 percent of their income
on property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Kay Khan (D-Newton), a member of a legislative
group pushing these and other proposals as part of a ``working
families agenda,'' said the poll results will unlikely sway any
votes in the Legislature, but were nevertheless heartening because
``it seems that people are becoming more sympathetic'' to the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
