<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2061 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-16 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDENING THE GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the Supreme Court to Congress, 'tis the season
to pick on the poor _ legally, economically and politically.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of the current governmental retreat from major
efforts to help those Americans left behind in an affluent society
will be painful, both for individuals and the country.
</P>
<P>
   The morality and decency for which politicians crusade so loudly
these days should include public compassion for the least
advantaged among us. But that quality seems to be in distressingly
short supply.
</P>
<P>
   In this conservative era, extending a state-sanctioned helping
hand has become an unfashionable concept, except in President
Clinton's small progressive inner circle. Instead, poor folks are
supposed to learn responsibility by helping themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When a majority of the nine Supreme Court justices ruled Monday
that states can no longer finance legal services for the poor their
customary way, the clear suggestion was that the next step may be
to declare the programs themselves unconstitutional. A lower court
was left to deal with this prospect for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its inconclusive nature, the ruling is a serious blow to
lower-income families who cannot afford a lawyer to help with
common legal questions, from figuring out complicated Social
Security forms to disputes with landlords. Access denied is
inevitably justice denied.
</P>
<P>
   Through the now-discredited system, state programs annually
generated $100 million nationwide toward legal assistance for poor
clients. The money was supplemented at the federal level by the
Legal Services Corp, which has a budget of $283 million _ peanuts
on the scale of most government spending.
</P>
<P>
   If the state programs go, LSC is likely to go too. It is
something of a political miracle that it is still breathing at all.
Conservatives have been trying for two decades to kill it off. At
every opportunity they slash its budget further.
</P>
<P>
   The LSC got in trouble because its original goal of giving
indigent individuals access to the judicial process sometimes
segued into class-action suits seeking to transform public policy
affecting the poor in general. And some of the powerless people it
sought to help with taxpayer-financed legal advice, such as
undocumented immigrants, were not popular with those who like the
established order.
</P>
<P>
   From Capitol Hill, there is bad news for low-income families as
well. Senate and House Republicans are espousing tax revisions that
benefit the rich at the expense of the poor, targeting for budget
cuts major programs aimed at the poor and proposing to repeal
altogether certain benefits, such as some food stamp entitlements.
</P>
<P>
   This assault on the weakest Americans is cloaked in language
pandering to the strongest Americans, those with ample money to buy
advantages for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There are differences in the Senate and House budget resolutions
that remain to be reconciled, and the president's veto threat hangs
in the air. Some proposals are still the whims of conservative
presidential and congressional candidates. But the trend is clear.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed flat tax would greatly lower the burden on the
wealthiest folks but increase proportionately that on middle- and
lower-income families. It is described as merely a desirable
simplification of the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Block grants passing along to the states the governmental duty
to provide for the public good _ for programs such as
welfare-to-work _ are being funded at lower levels than when the
programs were a federal responsibility. The House budget projects
$10 billion over five years in Medicaid cuts, to be achieved under
cover of converting Medicaid, formerly a federal-state
responsibility, to block grants administered by the states.
Cost-cutting, however, is not acknowledged as the goal. Returning
power to local government is the theme.
</P>
<P>
   A move to slash food stamps for legal immigrants was defeated,
but other cuts in those benefits for the poor in different
categories are included in the new federal budget passed by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Estate and capital gains tax cuts in both House and Senate
budgets would primarily benefit only the very richest folks.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, in the House budget the earned income tax credit
for low-income working families would be reduced for those with
children and totally eliminated for those without children.
</P>
<P>
   This is in addition to the heavy hits that programs for
low-income individuals and families have already taken. According
to a Center on Budget and Policy Priorities analysis, 93 percent of
the mandatory program reductions enacted in the last Congress were
in those for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   To counter this tilt against low-income families, Congress is
peddling some legislative alternatives that are supposed to
compensate a bit. The favorite is to create vouchers so poor
parents can send their children to private and parochial schools, a
constitutionally questionable notion that Republicans keep trying
to slip into legislation in various guises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLMONEY-DEMS-COX &UR; 1ST     06-16 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLMONEY-DEMS-COX </SLUG>
   1STLEDE-310&AMP;ADD  AUDIT SAYS 1996 DEMOCRATIC
CONVENTION BROKE LEGAL LIMITS
 &HT;     Restores dropped word to make it ``$1.7 million'' in graf 9.
 &HT;     By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Democratic Party exceeded the legal spending
limit for its 1996 convention in Chicago by roughly $700,000,
according to federal audit reports released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In return for taking $12.4 million in public funds, the
Democratic and Republican parties each promised not to spend any
other money on operating expenses for their national conventions to
nominate presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Staff auditors for the Federal Election Commission (FEC)
reported that the Democrats went over the limit when they charged
the convention's long-distance and local phone bills to the city of
Chicago and a privately funded host committee.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors found documents indicating that city's taxpayers
paid $126,510 and the host committee funded by Chicago-area
companies and executives paid $600,325 in phone bills run up by the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The host committee was co-chaired by Chicago Mayor Richard
Daley's brother, William Daley, a first-rate fund-raiser who was
later chosen by President Clinton to be secretary of commerce for
Clinton's second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll need some time to study the report before we can
comment,'' said Kip Kolkmeier, an attorney for the host committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll contest the assertions of the audit before the full
FEC,'' said Tony Wyche, spokesman for the Democratic National
Committee. ``We believe the expenses were properly paid for by the
Chicago host committee.''
</P>
<P>
   If the FEC approves the report, the debt-laden DNC _ which has
already returned $120,000 of the taxpayer funds it received for the
1996 convention _ would have to repay another $565,000 to the U.S.
Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, after reviewing a similar audit, the commission
voted to require the Republican Party to repay $1.7 million for
similar spending overruns during its 1996 convention in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Both political parties disputed the auditors' findings, and they
have numerous chances for appeals to the commission and the courts.
Campaign expert Anthony Corrado of Colby College said the process
may take years.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Why have spending limits, if they are meaningless?'' asked
another analyst, Herbert Alexander of Silver Spring, Md., who has
been studying convention financing since 1960. ``This time both
parties got caught on the question of limits by FEC auditors, and
that is unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   The limit was designed to minimize the chances that big donors
to convention funding could corrupt presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But the auditors said that at both 1996 conventions, the host
cities and host committees, which legally spent millions of dollars
to prepare and equip the convention halls, also paid some of their
operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   Any action on the report by the commission would require four
votes. Because one seat is vacant, the commission currently
consists of three Democrats and two Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting scheduled for Thursday to discuss the audits was
canceled because not all the commissioners would be present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither party wants to pay off, because both parties have
debts,'' Alexander said. In the end, ``there will probably be a
stalemate'' on the commission, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corrado said today's ``extravaganza-oriented'' conventions aimed
at a television audience cost more than the old-fashioned
conventions, which were conducted for the benefit of party
activists within the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1980, conventions didn't have a wall of video monitors or
interactive capabilities or satellite linkages that let people at
the conventions be interviewed live by their home-town TV
stations,'' Corrado said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
