<SLUG> BC-STITH-HEARING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STITH FACES SENATE PANEL ON AMBASSADORSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ESTELLA DURAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Rev. Charles R. Stith, the Boston civil rights
activist, moved a step closer Tuesday to becoming US ambassador to
Tanzania after appearing before the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Stith and 14 other ambassadorial nominees must wait for the
official committee vote on the nominations and for final Senate
approval. The next committee meeting has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, it looks good. President Clinton nominated Stith for
the diplomatic post in March, and Senators John F. Kerry, a member
of the Foreign Relations Committee, and Edward M. Kennedy said
Stith is well-suited for the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverend Stith has been dedicated to working for the
betterment of the dispossessed and disenfranchised in Boston, where
he ministered with spirit,'' Kerry said. ``It is most appropriate
that the president has nominated him to go to a country where he
can use his skills to help the people of Tanzania.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who introduced Stith at the hearing, also applauded
Stith's community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reverend Stith has worked tirelessly to develop ties between
Boston's African-American community and the city's business
leaders,'' he said. ``Boston is proud of him, and so am I.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith said he is eager to begin working to help Tanzania raise
its standing in the world market. Tanzania, which has a population
of about 29 million, is one of the world's poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tanzania is a valuable part of the administration's efforts to
forge new partnerships in Africa,'' Stith told the committee. ``It
is one of the most respected states in Africa and a longtime leader
in the international Non-Aligned Movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostonians know Stith for his flair in sermons and for his
leadership in civil rights issues. Stith was pastor of the Union
United Methodist Church in Boston for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Stith, who is national president for the Organization for a New
Equality, has said that if he becomes an ambassador he will resign
from the national nonprofit group, which helps economically
disadvantaged people. He also plans to step down as an advisory
board member of Fleet Financial Services Corp. and as director of
West Insurance Agency, both in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am new to the foreign service of the United States, but I am
familiar with the world of personal diplomacy and public service,''
Stith said. ``With the assistance of the United States and the
international community, I believe Tanzania can break the cycle of
poverty, which ensnares most of its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Stith, who helped build churches in Kenya as a college student,
said what he learned about African people when he lived there would
help him as ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by the many commonalities between Africans and
Americans, and I was inspired to enter the clergy as a means of
unlocking the human potential, which all people carry inside,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   If the nomination goes through as expected, Stith said he plans
to move to Tanzania's capital of Dar es Salaam by Labor Day. His
wife, Dr. Deborah Prothrow-Stith, an associate dean at the Harvard
School of Public Health, will also move but said she will probably
travel between the United States and Africa the first year.
</P>
<P>
   Stith said his children, Percy and Mimi, will attend college in
Tanzania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
