u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNEDY-WAGE-BOS &LR;      06-16 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-WAGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY WEIGHING MOVE TO HIKE MINIMUM WAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Senator Edward M. Kennedy has his way, the
bankruptcy bill rolling through Congress that would make it harder
for cash-strapped consumers to walk away from their debt will also
come with an increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is strongly considering attaching an amendment that
would raise the minimum wage by $1 over the next two years when the
Senate considers the bankruptcy legislation next month, his aides
said this week.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said President Clinton would support
Kennedy's effort, although he thinks the bankruptcy bill already
adopted by the House is ``rigid and arbitrary'' because it
establishes a means test to determine who could purge their debt
and who must repay it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president strongly supports an increase in the minimum
wage, so he'll certainly support the senator's efforts to move that
in a way that he thinks makes sense legislatively,'' said White
House spokesman Barry Toiv.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's maneuver could eliminate the possibility of a
presidential veto and perhaps stimulate broader Democrat support
for the first major overhaul of the nation's bankruptcy laws in 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is a high priority for Republicans in both the
House and Senate. Last week, 84 Democrats joined all the House
Republicans to adopt the bankruptcy bill by a 306-118 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Among the bill's Democratic supporters were Representative
Barney Frank of Massachusetts, who broke ranks with the
Massachusetts delegation to vote in favor of the bankruptcy
measure.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said he voted for the bill because ``people who can afford
to pay their debts ought to pay them.'' He also said he was
satisfied with changes made to the bill that would allow child
support and alimony payments to be given priority over credit-card
debt.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would prevent individuals earning more than the
national median income ($50,000 for a family of four) from
declaring personal bankruptcy under Chapter 7 liquidation, which
erases most debts. Those earning above that cap would have to file
under Chapter 13 laws, which would require them to reorganize their
debts and establish a repayment plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate version would place fewer restrictions on those
filing for bankruptcy but would give creditors greater power to
recoup what they are owed. Unlike the House bill, the Senate bill
would not require those with higher incomes to undergo a means test
to determine whether they can file under Chapters 7 or 13
bankruptcy laws, but leave that to bankruptcy trustees.
</P>
<P>
   That bill was approved by the Senate Judiciary Committee last
month and is awaiting consideration by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Shaw, a spokeswoman for Senate majority leader Trent
Lott, said he is very interested in the bill and would bring it to
the Senate floor after the July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   She refused to speculate about what might happen if Kennedy
tries to attach his proposal to raise the current federal minimum
wage of $5.15 by 50 cents each year for two years beginning Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy spokesman Jim Manly said the senator opposes the
bankruptcy legislation, but if Republicans are intent on passing
it, then he wanted the minimum wage increase in exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain symmetry here in a bill many suggest will
have an adverse impact on low-wage workers and workers' families
providing a useful vehicle for Senator Kennedy to try to provide
for a further increase in the minimum wage,'' Manly said.
</P>
<P>
   Ranit Schmelzer, a spokeswoman for Senate minority leader Thomas
A. Daschle, said the minimum wage amendment was contingent on first
finding legislation to attach a proposal to protect the rights of
patients enrolled in Health Maintenance Organizations, a chief
Democratic legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   Frank predicted that Kennedy's amendment ``would probably not
kill the bankruptcy bill.'' Instead, he said it could shore up
Democratic support for bankruptcy reform or force Republicans to
consider the minimum-wage hike separately. ``I'm for both of
them,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
