s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-$ADV21-     06-16 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ENCHANTING REVIVAL OF TOPICAL SKETCHES FROM 1933
</HEADLINE>
  (For release on Sunday, June 21.) 
 (ja) 
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The setting is Washington in March 1933: the economy
is deep into the Depression, the stock market is a wasteland, bread
lines are long and banks are closing. The nation totters.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert and Lou Hoover, the 31st president of the United States
and his wife, are rattling around the White House on the eve of the
day they must vacate the premises for the incoming Roosevelt
family. Herbert faces the move with equanimity, but Lou wants
revenge. She is planning to steal some White House silver and a
portrait of George Washington _ it's not as if there aren't plenty
more around the place.
</P>
<P>
   Herbert tries to cheer her: ``It could be worse _ I could have
been re-elected.'' She goads him. This being their last night, she
says, isn't there something he'd like to do that is not entirely
proper? There is, which leads to the rude, gleefully childish
blackout that ends the sketch titled ``Franklin D. Roosevelt to Be
Inaugurated Tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of the numbers in the Drama Dept.'s quite
enchanting resurrection of ``As Thousands Cheer,'' the 1933 Irving
Berlin-Moss Hart topical revue, which is at the Greenwich House
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   A 1933 topical revue that's still funny? Yes. One of the
marvelous things about intelligently written, skillfully performed
revue material is that the humor can shine through in front of
audiences for whom the original associations have grown dim or,
perhaps, never existed at all. Watch children watching a sketch
whose point is utterly beyond them and they laugh at the right
places. Such comedy has a rhythm that can be as infectiously comic
as content, even when the subjects might be John D. Rockefeller
Sr., the five-and-dime heiress Barbara Hutton, Mahatma Gandhi,
Hollywood's morals czar Will Hays, unemployment and thievery at the
Automat.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder here is that you can delight in both the content and
the rhythm of ``As Thousands Cheer,'' which is presented with nutty
enthusiasm and sometimes vitriol as it sends up the American scene
at one of the darkest moments in the country's history. Directed as
a series of collegial, go-for-broke turns by Christopher Ashley,
whose credits include ``Jeffrey'' and the recent Encores production
of ``Li'l Abner,'' the show is a kind of tabloid version of the
original Broadway hit. It has been cut to run a breezy 75 minutes,
played without an intermission by a cast of six acting and singing
clowns, accompanied by a piano and a bass.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Atlantic Theater Company, which recently revived ``Once
in a Lifetime,'' the classic 1930 George S. Kaufman-Moss Hart
comedy, the Drama Dept. possesses an awareness of the theater's
historical past that deepens and illuminates the company's present
work. This was apparent six months ago in its ebullient, witty,
very original deconstruction of Harriet Beecher Stowe's ``Uncle
Tom's Cabin or Life Among the Lowly.''
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to search for the life within ``As Thousands
Cheer,'' the Drama Dept. is rediscovering the art of the revue as
it has evolved in the American theater from the days of minstrel
shows. Spawned in its present form in the years before World War I,
the intimate revue took over during the Depression, when soaring
budgets made the elaborate, Ziegfeld-type spectacles too risky to
produce. Revues have existed in all sizes and shapes from the
teens, '20s, '30s and '40s into the '50s: a glorious grab-bag kind
of theater, brainy beyond the aspirations of burlesque and
vaudeville, composed of sketches, songs and dances, sometimes with
a common theme and, most important, with a consistently skeptical
point of view.
</P>
<P>
   I think of London in 1947 and the first revue I ever saw,
``Sweetest and Lowest,'' a hilarious, very jaundiced look at life
in grimly austere, postwar Britain, starring an almost youthful
Hermione Gingold. A highlight: a sendup of Noel Coward's role as a
goodwill ambassador during the war (``While disguised as Mr.
Eden/He was smuggled into Sweden/Where he cleverly put on `Private
Lives'''). The cheeky effrontery of undergraduate humor, which I
then knew best, had been transformed into art.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1950s, television had already appropriated the
variety-show format of revues, and Sid Caesar and Imogene Coca
briefly made the entire country sketch comedy-conscious on ``Your
Show of Shows.'' Yet producers of theatrical revues persisted: Ben
Bagley with his ``Shoestring Revue of 1957,'' Julius Monk with his
brilliant, mini-scaled shows in whatever nightclubs were available,
and the indefatigable Leonard Sillman, whose ``New Faces of 1952''
was the most successful of all the ``New Faces'' shows he had been
producing since the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the discoveries of the 1952 edition were Ronny Graham,
Alice Ghostley, Paul Lynde and Eartha Kitt. As this show introduced
Ms. Kitt, she introduced what was to become one of her signature
songs, ``Monotonous.'' The most memorable production number,
choreographed for frenzy by Richard Barstow, was Michael Brown's
exuberant hoedown, ``Lizzie Borden,'' which has the refrain: ``Oh
you can't chop your papa up in/Massachusetts/Massachusetts is a
long way from New York!''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the priceless sketches: a Paul Lynde monologue in which
a man with a Rotarian's desire to please, though still heavily
bandaged and on crutches, relates what happened on the Trip of the
Month Club's African safari he took with his late wife; a vignette
about the Loman family in which Willy's frail, worried wife
implores her sons to pay attention, to become bank robbers like
their exhausted dad; and Ronny Graham's takeoff on Truman Capote,
who is lying in a hammock and talking (if I remember correctly)
about moss.
</P>
<P>
   Gorgeous material, some of it written by a writer then billed as
Melvin Brooks. He, of course, was also one of the contributors to
``Your Show of Shows,'' which used a platoon of talents that
included Neil Simon, Carl Reiner, Larry Gelbart and many others.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   What is it about these revues that makes them so irresistible?
</P>
<P>
   When they work, they capture the temper of the times with
brevity, with an accuracy that sometimes shocks and with a gift for
parody that restores sacred cows to human dimension. A blending of
first-rate sketches laced with songs as funny and melodic as
Berlin's for ``As Thousands Cheer,'' can be among the most bracing
of theatrical entertainments. We have let the genre go to seed.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it seemed as if television would meet the demand
for sketch comedy, but then not even Sid Caesar could stick it out.
Television eats up material like an office shredder. The
incomparable Carol Burnett endured for 11 seasons and kept the
quality way, way up. ``Saturday Night Live'' has had its golden
moments, most of them many years ago. I think of an Edward R.
Murrow ``Person to Person'' sort of parody in which the
self-absorbed interviewer has his back to the television screen on
which his guest, who looks like Elizabeth Taylor, starts choking to
death on the chicken leg that has had her ravenous attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Live'' produced some great sketch actors: John
Belushi, Dan Aykroyd and the best of them all, the grandly and
subtly gifted Eddie Murphy. Remember his sketch about how white
folks behave on the bus to work when black folks aren't around?
Bells go off, music suddenly blares, saucily dressed waitresses
appear, to serve martinis and canapes. The imagined merriment is
nonstop and strictly segregated.
</P>
<P>
   The show still introduces good new performers but, in what could
be an attempt to affect a 1990s sort of cool, the sketches tend to
be resolutely without point. The idea is that to express passion,
even in a satirical way, is definitely un-cool.
</P>
<P>
   There have been suggestions that the revue sketch is dated
today, that audiences (especially television's) are not interested
in it and much prefer shows that feature stand-up comics. Yet the
range of subjects covered in stand-up is limited. It is usually so
self-referential (dating, the difference between men and women,
terrible sexual performance, parents, looks, weight) you might
suspect that the comics and their audiences have turned their backs
on the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, it's no wonder so few people bother to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The time may have come for the theater to reclaim the topical
revue. There is no shortage of writing talent available. Tick off
the names: Larry Gelbart, Neil Simon, Betty Comden and Adolph
Green, Terrence McNally, Wendy Wasserstein, A.R. Gurney,
Christopher Durang, Whoopi Goldberg, Paul Rudnick, Nicky Silver,
David Ives, Jane Wagner, Jon Robin Baitz, Douglas Carter Beane,
David and Amy Sedaris, John Leguizamo _ and they are just some of
the people we know about.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you can see what a hit 1933 revue looks like as put
on by people whose parents might not even have been born when the
original production opened. ``As Thousands Cheer'' is a theme show,
each sketch or song supposedly torn from a newspaper headline of
the day. In this way it was something of a prescient parody of the
Living Newspapers that were to be put on under the sponsorship of
the Federal Theater Project, which was established by the Works
Progress Administration in 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Living Newspapers, however, which examined housing,
health care, labor unions and the like, ``As Thousands Cheer''
mostly examines such issues as why a man might bite a dog and the
private personas of public people, usually behaving badly. The
Berlin score includes the steamy and funny ``Heat Wave'' and, for
an abrupt change of mood, the poignant ``Supper Time,'' which is
cued by a headline about a lynching and was sung in the original
show by Ethel Waters.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the Drama Dept. cast are a delight. Some
highlights: B.D. Wong (Gandhi and the man who bites a dog), Kevin
Chamberlin (hilarious as the dog that's bitten and Hoover), Judy
Kuhn (Joan Crawford, Barbara Hutton), Howard McGillin (John D.
Rockefeller Sr., Douglas Fairbanks Jr.), Mary Beth Peil (Aimee
Semple McPherson, Mrs. Hoover), and Paula Newsome, who plays and
sings up a storm. Among her numbers are Berlin's superb ``Harlem on
My Mind'' and ``Supper Time.'' David Evans is on piano, Lou Bruno
on bass. This is a very good crew.
</P>
<P>
   Footnote to history: In her book, ``Irving Berlin: A Daughter's
Memoir,'' Mary Ellin Barrett reports that when ``As Thousands
Cheer'' was trying out io Philadelphia, Clifton Webb, Marilyn
Miller and Helen Broderick, the show's three white stars, refused
to share the curtain call with Ethel Waters. Berlin's reaction was
to suggest that this wasn't a show in need of curtain calls anyway,
and that they should be cut. At the next performance the cast took
its bows together.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `The Dying Gaul': &QL; 
 &LR;  Craig Lucas' fascinating new play, ``The Dying Gaul,'' closed
last Sunday night after a limited engagement at the Vineyard
Theater, where a scheduling conflict made any extension impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad, but there are hopes that it will reopen in the fall for
the unlimited run it deserves. Or, to put it another way: ``The
Dying Gaul'' is even more theatrically imaginative and engaging
than Lucas' ``Prelude to a Kiss,'' the quirky fairy tale of a
modern love story seen on Broadway in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dying Gaul'' is quite different. It is also a love story
of sorts, but one in which anger and lust take a terrible toll, at
least in part through the magic of Internet technology.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is Hollywood and the principal characters are
Robert, an aspiring screenwriter of mystical bent, in mourning for
his lover who has recently died of AIDS; Jeffrey, a bisexual
producer who buys Robert's first script and seduces him into a
mutually satisfying, supposedly no-strings-attached affair, and
Elaine, Jeffrey's wife, an intelligent, loving woman whose patience
runs out.
</P>
<P>
   The Vineyard production, staged by Mark Brokaw, was just about
flawless, with Tim Hopper as Robert, Tony Goldwyn as Jeffrey, Linda
Emond as Elaine and Robert Emmet Lunney as Robert's psychiatrist,
who is as important to Lucas' intricate plotting as the existence
of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   If Goldwyn appeared to stand out, it was because the role is so
scarily flamboyant; his colleagues were equally centered in their
performances. Adding to the classiness of the production: Allen
Moyer's serenely handsome, vaguely Japanese unit set, which
suggested Hollywood glitz as interpreted by a very expensive
decorator in a minimalist mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dying Gaul'' indicates that Lucas is writing better than
ever these days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
