<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RINGO-STARR-MUSIC-$AD     06-16 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RINGO-STARR-MUSIC-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RINGO OUTDISTANCES HIS PAST, FINALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a musician who was once part of the most influential band in
pop, spending more than a decade rekindling a career must be an
intensely frustrating business.
</P>
<P>
   But listening to ``Vertical Man,'' Ringo Starr's 12th
post-Beatles studio album, one has to admire the cheerful
industriousness with which he has tried to recapture the success of
his early hit albums, ``Ringo'' (1973) and ``Goodnight Vienna''
(1974).
</P>
<P>
   His last effort, ``Time Takes Time'' (1992), should have done
the trick: it was bright, energetic and pleasantly Beatlesque, but
it disappeared without hitting the charts.
</P>
<P>
   In sound and spirit, ``Vertical Man'' (Mercury) has much in
common with ``Time Takes Time.'' There are Beatles references, both
overt (a remake of ``Love Me Do'') and oblique (the combination
mellotron sounds, a la ``Strawberry Fields Forever,'' and sliding
strings, in the style of ``I Am the Walrus,'' on the otherwise
bluesy ``King of Broken Hearts'').
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both of Starr's surviving former band mates play on the
record: The crying slide guitar sound that has been George
Harrison's post-Beatles signature adorns a few tracks, and Paul
McCartney contributes bass and backing vocals to others. ``I'm
Yours,'' the closing ballad, has a George Martin string arrangement
reminiscent of ``Good Night,'' the song Starr sings at the end of
the Beatles' White Album.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Vertical Man'' is not merely a retread of Beatles' styles.
There is a grittiness, a density and a fluid eclecticism that is of
the '90s, not the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a consistency that has been lacking in Starr's work
until now. Typically, his recordings have been parties of guest
appearances, with different ensembles on each selection, and with a
few of Starr's modest creations mingling with songs written for him
by more compositionally accomplished friends.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the guest vocal and instrumental contributions are
plentiful: in addition to Harrison and McCartney, the roster
includes Joe Walsh, Alanis Morissette, Steve Tyler, Ozzy Osbourne,
Tom Petty, Steve Cropper and Brian Wilson. But the guest shots are
rarely the focus; mainly, they embellish performances by a core
band that includes Starr on drums (solid and unostentatious as
ever), Mark Hudson and Steve Dudas on guitars and bass, and Jim Cox
on keyboards.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also collaborated in the writing of 11 of the album's 13
songs with Hudson, Dudas, Dean Grakal and, in one case, Mark
Nevins.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly they have catchy melodies that tiptoe around Starr's
vocal limitations and cater to the slightly nasal quality and good
humored phrasing that give his singing its distinctive, homey
charm. Peace, love and understanding, in both personal terms (``I'm
Yours'' and ``What in the World'' are straightforward love songs)
and with a mildly political undercurrent (in the pacifist
``Mindfield,'' for example).
</P>
<P>
   The idea of taking life in stride _ the impulse that drives ``La
De Da,'' a folksy singalong with the refrain, ``que sera, whatever,
la de dah'' _ threads through several songs as well.
</P>
<P>
   All told, this is a tightly crafted, appealingly upbeat album,
and clearly meant as entertainment rather than innovation. That
said, the new songs are immeasurably more sophisticated than ``Love
Me Do,'' which Starr included partly to redress the fact that a
session drummer had replaced him on a 1962 Beatles recording and
partly to assert his right to sing Lennon-McCartney songs beyond
the few he sang with the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's straightforward rocking version pulls the song away from
its blues roots, but that is a far more pleasing approach than
McCartney's 1989 remake, the disco-tinged medley ``P.S. Love Me
Do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1917EDT &QL; 
