</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-LIQUOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERMARKETS SUE TO EASE LIQUOR LICENSE LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts' supermarket industry Tuesday promised
more competitive prices for beer and liquor if its court challenge
to a state law prohibiting anyone from owning more than three
liquor stores is successful.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Stop &AMP; Shop, Roche Bros., and BJ's Wholesale Club, the
supermarkets said a Prohibition-era law restricting how many liquor
licenses a company can hold violates the Sherman antitrust law and
means retailers have little leverage in negotiating deals with
liquor wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now retailers have no buying power and no clout,'' said
Christopher Flynn, executive director of the Massachusetts Food
Association.
</P>
<P>
   The US District Court suit, which follows an unsuccessful effort
by former Governor William F. Weld to eliminate the liquor license
cap, would dramatically change the way liquor is sold in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, wholesalers sell their products to about 3,000
package store owners across the state, none of whom can operate
more than three stores. The overall number of liquor licenses
permitted in the state is also tightly restricted, with licenses
allotted in each community using a population formula.
</P>
<P>
   The supermarket suit does not challenge the state's authority to
limit the overall number of liquor licenses, only a store's right
to acquire more than three of them. In other words, the number of
individual liquor store competitors would probably decrease, not
increase, if the suit were successful and chain stores buy up
licenses for their outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Hurley, the owner of Canterbury Liquors in Sandwich and a
prominent figure in state package store associations, said he
doubted the court challenge will prevail. If it does, he said,
consumers would ultimately be the losers.
</P>
<P>
   In Sandwich, for example, there are currently five liquor
licenses. If the supermarket suit is successful, Hurley said the
local Stop &AMP; Shop and A&AMP;P would probably each buy licenses from one
of the existing liquor stores and then use their deep pockets to
drive the remaining package stores out of business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they gain control, they will raise prices,'' he
predicted. ``And this example would be duplicated throughout the
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley said supermarkets also tend to carry only the most
popular beers and wines, so selection would suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, of the Massachusetts Food Association, said Massachusetts
has some of the highest prices in the nation for beers and wines,
in part because of the archaic restrictions on liquor license
ownership. He said supermarket chains and warehouse clubs, if
allowed to acquire more liquor licenses, would have more clout in
negotiating lower prices with wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley said the power of wholesalers to restrict price
competition was dramatically curbed in January when a federal judge
struck down on antitrust grounds a law regulating the way
wholesalers set prices.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called price posting law required wholesalers to announce
their prices each month and allowed them to match, but not beat,
the prices of competitors. Hurley, who filed the lawsuit, said
wholesalers can now adjust their prices at any time and undercut
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Since the verdict, Hurley said the price of Gordon's Vodka and
Baccardi Rum have dropped about $1 per 1.75-liter bottle. He said
jug wines have also dropped about a $1 per bottle. Beer prices have
not fallen because beer wholesalers have strict franchise
agreements that tend to restrict competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Stasiowsky, president of the Massachusetts Wholesalers of
Malt Beverages, said his group supports the three-store limit
because smaller package stores do a better job of regulating
alcohol sales than supermarket chains that sell a wide variety of
products.
</P>
<P>
   He also disputed Flynn's statement that beer prices in
Massachusetts are among the highest in the nation. Stasiowsky said
prices here are higher because of the state's bottle deposit law.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Sullivan, chairman of the Alcoholic Beverages Control
Commission, the state agency sued by the supermarkets, said it is
his job to enforce the laws on the books until those laws are
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the state limits retailers to only three liquor
licenses, he said it was done ``to protect the public safety and
common good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
