<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2090 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KERRY-TENURE-BOS &LR;      06-16 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERRY-TENURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY OFFERS PROPOSAL ON TEACHER TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BY JORDANA HART AND BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ National and state education leaders Tuesday embraced
many of US Senator John F. Kerry's proposals to grant public school
principals more authority to hire and fire teachers, though teacher
union officials warned he was scapegoating their members even as
they fostered school reform.
</P>
<P>
   Those union officials said they would join Kerry in pushing the
many states that still have cumbersome tenure and
teacher-certification processes to join the reform movement,
provided that teachers get a proper method to appeal unjust
firings.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's ideas on education were outlined in a 45-minute speech
Tuesday to some 125 educators, state legislators and college
students at Northeastern University. The speech, which was national
in scope, was intended to be Kerry's first major address to set the
tone for a possible presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The speech called for dismantling both the seniority systems
that protect unqualified teachers, and certification procedures
that prevent teaching by people without an education degree.
</P>
<P>
   State reform advocates said the senator's proposals may have
raised eyebrows in states just launching their own reform efforts,
but not in about a dozen states at the front line in education.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the firing of teachers no longer has to go
through the time-consuming process of a school committee vote. Now,
principals and superintendents have greater power to remove them.
In most cases, firings then go to binding arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry ``was really articulating many of the initiatives in
Massachusetts as models for the rest of the country,'' said state
Senator David Magnani, a Democrat who is former co-chair of the
Massachusetts legislature's education committee and attended
Kerry's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is in the midst of a billion-dollar education
overhaul launched in 1993. It has made hiring and firing of
teachers easier, and allows professionals without teaching degrees
into classrooms _ so long as they get a waiver from the state Board
of Education and work toward teacher certification.
</P>
<P>
   National teacher union leaders said that a majority of states
have alternative certification processes for professionals to
become teachers. But they also acknowledged that many of those
programs are cluttered with red tape.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials also applauded Kerry's decision not to support a
school-voucher program that many Republicans back. They said they
would help work instead toward a widespread system of public school
choice.
</P>
<P>
   But James Peyser, a Massachusetts Board of Education member who
supports vouchers as well as charter schools, said he was
disappointed that Kerry didn't support a voucher system like the
one that won court approval in Milwaukee last week. The Wisconsin
plan allows students to choose private and parochial schools at
public cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not even willing to go as far as a limited system for
poor children or children stuck in failing schools,'' Peyser said.
``He was basically saying, `Give us more time to get public
education right.' What he fails to realize is that there are
children in schools who are not being served and who will be lost
unless something is done for them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry met with a series of education leaders in the past several
months as he prepared his speech, including Boston Public Schools
Superintendent Thomas Payzant and heads of the state and national
teachers unions.
</P>
<P>
   It was those union leaders who felt their organizations were
cast in a villianous light in many parts of Kerry's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would look very favorably to the fact that he has tried to
be creative in his thinking on improving public schools,'' said
Mary Elizabeth Teasley, director of government relations for the
National Education Association, the nation's largest teacher union.
</P>
<P>
   ``But on the other side of the coin, we are not pleased with his
swipes at teachers unions,'' she said. ``The NEA and our new
president, Bob Chase, has embraced new unionism and cooperation
instead of conflict. We did not understand the broad-brush swipes
at teachers unions. It surprised us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
