<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2091 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-EXTRADITION-     06-16 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-EXTRADITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOWER URGES MEXICO TO EXTRADITE MAN WANTED IN FLORIDA KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A U.S. congressman called Tuesday for renegotiation
of the U.S.-Mexico extradition treaty as the husband of a slain
Florida woman picketed the Mexican Embassy, saying his wife
``screams out from the grave'' for her alleged killer's return to
the United States to face trial.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said they were sympathetic to the concerns of
James Bellush, who held a news conference on the embassy steps. But
Mexican officials said they could not interfere with the due
process of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this person to be tried fairly,'' said Jose Antonio
Zabalgoitia, a Mexican Embassy spokesman. ``The Mexican government
has no interest whatsoever in protecting a criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   But an angry Bellush countered: ``Talk is all the Mexican
government does.''
</P>
<P>
   A former Marine, Bellush urged Americans to boycott Mexican
goods until Jose Luis Del Toro Jr., 22, is returned to Florida to
face a first-degree murder charge in the death of Sheila Bellush,
who was shot and slashed to death at her home in Sarasota, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man needs to be on a plane today. I'm tired of waiting,''
Bellush said. ``My wife, she screams out from the grave for him to
be extradited immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Bellush gave birth to quadruplets in 1995, when she lived
in San Antonio. She was killed Nov. 7, 1997, in Sarasota, just
weeks after the family had left Texas for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, an American citizen from San Antonio, was captured in
Mexico after the slaying. Two other San Antonio men, Samuel
Gonzales, 27, and Daniel Rocha, 29, also were charged in Florida
with in connection with the Bullush murder.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the motive in the brutal killing was a
complex murder-for-hire scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales pleaded guilty to solicitation to commit murder. He was
sentenced to 19 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Rocha has implicated Sheila Bellush's first husband, Allen
Blackthorne, in the death. Blackthorne, through an attorney, has
denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Florida prosecutors dropped their intent to seek the death
penalty in their case against Del Toro last year in exchange for
Mexico's cooperation in extradition. Mexico does not recognize
capital punishment on moral grounds.
</P>
<P>
   But once Mexico's Foreign Ministry agreed to extradite Del Toro,
he appealed the decision, claiming his constitutional rights in
Mexico were being violated.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials said the appeal could take weeks or months to
resolve, although they expressed confidence that Del Toro's capture
and incarceration in Mexico City will pass judicial review.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the delays have prompted spirited conversations
among Mexican officials, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., and Rep.
Dan Miller, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Miller _ who represents the Sarasota area _ called on the
Clinton administration to renegotiate the U.S.-Mexico extradition
treaty ``so that the possibility of capital punishment will not
interfere with the timely extradition of criminal suspects from
Mexico to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller has filed a resolution in the House seeking a
renegotiation of the 1978 treaty signed in Mexico City by former
President Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro is being held in the East Jail in Mexico City until his
appeal is heard and a decision is rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Bellush, who was 35 at the time of her death, was the
mother of six children, including two daughters from her previous
marriage to Blackthorne. James Bellush has since moved the children
to Sussex County, N.J., to be with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Bellush's body was found in her Sarasota home by one of
her daughters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rocha, a golfing partner of Blackthorne's, sought a plea bargain
with Florida prosecutors. He released a statement from Gonzales
that implicates Blackthorne in his former wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales' statement accused Blackthorne, a San Antonio
businessman, of hatching the murder-for-hire scheme following a
bitter divorce and child custody battle.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Bellush family's move from Texas to Florida,
Gonzales told Texas Rangers, Rocha offered a $10,000 bounty for the
return of Blackthorne's daughters ``with no questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales told Rangers he repeated the offer to his cousin, Del
Toro, during a meeting in which Rocha was present.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Bellush's death prompted an international manhunt for Del
Toro, who was featured on the television program, ``America's Most
Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   His abandoned car was found in Austin, Texas, just days after
the slaying. Among the items investigators found in the car were a
.45-caliber handgun, a Sarasota hotel receipt and written
directions to Bellush's Florida home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
