<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-GABRE2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIKRETE GABRE, ENTREPRENEUR AND ETHIOPIAN ACTIVIST; AT 42 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: W-Maryan Ayemo is cq)  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fikrete Gabre, 42, an innovative Ethiopian entrepreneur and
community activist who had been living in Amherst, Mass., died June
9 while staying with family members in California. Her death was
attributed to complications from hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Zato, a village in southwestern Ethiopia, Ms. Gabre was
best-known for developing Siljo Sauce _ a traditional African blend
of ginger, garlic, and other spices which she made and marketed to
raise funds to create the first water system in her
drought-stricken hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Donating 20 percent of profits, she raised thousands of dollars
and generated considerable publicity for her village before a
severe case of hepatitis forced her to reduce her efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; From a family of 14, Ms. Gabre came to the United States in
1974. A military dictator had closed all the local schools and she
wanted to get a college education. She eventually earned bachelor's
and master's degrees in labor relations at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst and a second master's degree, in social
work, at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   In California, she also organized the first multicultural,
multilingual Ethiopian Community Resource Center in Oakland, which
she directed from 1983 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   With help from many Massachusetts residents, she launched her
Siljo Sauce project in 1991. Drought had devastated her village and
social progress, particularly for women, was being blocked by the
all-consuming search for water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water,'' she observed, ``is the lifeline for every living
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves her mother, W-Maryan Ayemo of Zato, Ethiopia; four
sisters, Boge of Los Angeles, and Ceebo, Zenebeh, and Sheyae, all
of Addis Ababa; and four brothers, Tsedek of Nova Scotia, Berhanu
of Addis Ababa, and Abera and Solomon, both of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fikrete talked her mind. She was a ball of energy, constantly
doing things, creating things. She had such a huge heart for
everybody,'' said her sister Boge. ``We will carry her dreams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
