<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVE ME A GAME I CAN PUT MY HANDS AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now seems as good a time as any for all red-blooded Americans to
take the pledge. So please rise, stand at attention, and place your
hand over your red card:
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) I, (state your name), as American as an episode of
Springer
</P>
<P>
   Do hereby swear loyalty to the sports that made my country great
</P>
<P>
   And promise from this day forward to never utter the word nil
</P>
<P>
   And while I will always encourage my children to play any sport
that pleases them, be it indigenous to our country or something
imported
</P>
<P>
   I will forever remind them that it is the birthright of all
Americans
</P>
<P>
   To pick up a ball, any size and any shape, with their hands (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   About now, the dozens of soccer fans in this audience have
already reached for the yellow card in their pocket and are holding
it up to my face.
</P>
<P>
   I do not blame them. They are the Sons of Pele and Maradona, and
every minority group deserves to be treated with respect. They are
harmless cult members, and one should seek to understand the root
of their obsession in the course of avoiding it.
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup began in France a week ago and will continue on
into July, with the whole world allegedly watching the biggest
sporting spectacle on the planet. An asteroid the size of Macedonia
could hit the earth today, and one feels certain that the world's
soc-ocracy would insist the tournament go on for the greater good
of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   The point here has less to do with those we've angered than the
uncounted millions of Americans who go through life never thinking
very seriously about soccer.
</P>
<P>
   It is galling that those locked up in soccermania look upon
those of us who aren't as heathen. They cluck at us for being
narrow-minded, xenophoboic or just plain stupid for not getting
caught up in this event.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer is a fine sport. It's great for kids to play, because it
emphasizes fitness and does not discriminate. I enjoy watching
World Cup games, because I know that the teams involved, with one
or two exceptions like the Etats-Unis, represent the best players
in the world. It's great theatre.
</P>
<P>
   But I do not want to be upbraided if my attention span is short
and I decline to get caught up in the hysteria. Neither the sport
nor the World Cup requires the presence or enrollment of the United
States of Apathy for its worldwide success.
</P>
<P>
   Americans did not grow up playing soccer the way other countries
did, which is the most obvious reason why many of us do not care.
In Brazil, Europe and elsewhere, children were given a ball at the
age of 3 and encouraged to kick it.
</P>
<P>
   America's children took to other things and made them their own.
The country imported cricket and turned it into baseball. It felt a
country bristling with energy would find it more entertaining and
physical if players ran the ball more often than they kicked it,
giving birth to our version and obsession of football.
</P>
<P>
   (It is telling that a country as large as ours can not field a
team that's competitive with a country, Germany, that's roughly the
size of Massachusetts. Let me be the latest to also note that the
big U.S. win in the '94 World Cup, against Colombia, came as a
result of an own goal, and the poor lad who scored it was
assassinated.)
</P>
<P>
   In the process of baseball or football taking root, no one in
America felt the need to call foreigners stupid for not caring
about baseball or football. But the opposite is true; we're
considered dullards for not embracing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America is part of the soc-ocracy, because corporate
America -- Coke, Nike, Fedex, Master Card, ABC/ESPN -- never misses
a chance to co-opt an event and turn it into cash. In their own
way, they are the worst practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   For example: An ad for Master Card Tuesday during ESPN's
coverage used fleeting images of soccer fans dressed in party
regalia and the words ``faith, hope and glory'' to get its message
across. The spot ended with an aside that the company is a
``supporter of the beautiful game.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom-line message: soccer beauty, and shame on all of us
who aren't smart enough to have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Next time someone says TV is benign, slap his antennae.
</P>
<P>
   I can see a day when America gets excited about soccer -- 1999,
when the Women's World Cup is played on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the birth of gender equity in the '70s and the
opportunities afforded women, every sports-inclined daughter has
probably played soccer at some stage of her life. With baseball and
football essentially prohibited, soccer was given a chance to
become part of a female athlete's foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. soccer team stands on even terms internationally, too,
since the organization of women's play is relatively young.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond that, there isn't anything soccer offers that a
red-blooded American can't find somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Low-scoring games? We've got hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime shootouts? We've got extra innings and sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   International talent? We've got Toni Kukoc, Chan Ho Park and
Junior Seau.
</P>
<P>
   Hooligans? We've got Dennis Rodman and base brawls.
</P>
<P>
   And at last check, there hasn't been a single murder of an
athlete as a result of a baseball, football or basketball game.
</P>
<P>
   We're a hands-on country, and I see no reason to apologize for
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
