<SLUG> BC-BYRD-HATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MURDER MAY NOT FALL UNDER US HATE STATUTE, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As hateful as the brutal murder of James Byrd Jr.
was last week in Jasper, Texas, federal authorities may not be able
to prosecute the slaying as a hate crime, lawmakers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law on hate crimes requires prosecutors to prove
not only that a crime was racially motivated but also that the
victim was engaged in an activity specifically protected under the
statute, such as going to school or work, serving on a jury or
using public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy and the other lawmakers said the short
list of activities protected under the law has prevented hate crime
prosecutions in many racially motivated crimes in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the limitations, federal prosecutors are fighting
bigotry with one hand tied behind their backs,'' Kennedy said at a
news conference as he called on Congress to pass a stronger hate
crimes law.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper police said Byrd, 49, a disabled grandfather and amateur
musician, was walking home from a family party when he accepted a
ride from three white supremacists in a pickup truck. The three men
allegedly beat Byrd, chained him to the back of the truck and
dragged him more than two miles on a paved country road, tearing
him to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   All the evidence indicates the murder was racially motivated,
Jasper police said. But the county prosecutor, Guy Adam Gray, who
wants to seek the death penalty in the case, said the killing may
not qualify as a capital crime under Texas law.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Jasper police summoned the FBI to investigate the
slaying as a possible hate crime, which could be punishable by the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kennedy and several other lawmakers said the current
law is so restrictive that Byrd, by accepting a ride from the white
supremacists, may not have been engaging in an activity that is
specifically protected under the federal hate crime statute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be no federal jurisdiction to prosecute those
responsible'' for Byrd's murder, said Representative John Conyers
Jr. of Michigan, the highest-ranking Democrat on the House
Judiciary Committee. ``And the fact is, there should be federal
jurisdiction over crimes so hateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Legislation that Kennedy, Conyers and others filed last year
would permit federal prosecutors to pursue hate crime charges if
they believe cases are motivated by the victim's race, color,
national origin or religion. The list of protected activities would
be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which is scheduled for a hearing July 8 before the
Senate Judiciary Committee, would also expand the hate crimes law
to cover crimes motivated by a victim's gender, sexual orientation
or disability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
