<SLUG> BC-SOC-POSTCARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAILY FRENCH IN FRANCE POSTCARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paris is many things, right? Like what?
</P>
<P>
   City of light? OK, I'll buy that. The sun, when it peeks through
the imposing clouds, doesn't set until nearly 10 p.m. But we seem
to get much more rain than sunshine, so maybe ``city of falling
water'' is more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   City of romance? Previous trips tell me this is true, but I can
assure you there is very little romance in the press center at
Porte de Versailles or in my hotel room at Gare de L'est, where I
seem to spend the vast majority of my time. Lots of, uh, romantic
fare on TV, when every channel isn't devoted to soccer.
</P>
<P>
   City of arrogance? The Parisian attitude, well documented ---
and believe me, I can tell you tales --- seems to have disappeared
for the World Cup. People are helpful, friendly, and my refrain of
``Parlez vous Anglais?'' gets a far more positive response than it
has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   City of fine cuisine? I'm not so sure about this. The crepes are
great, and I do like the Chinese restaurant next to my hotel, but
the French fare seems to rely a little too heavily on undercooked
--- or even raw --- beef and heavy, heavy sauces. The baguettes are
wonderful, oui, but is there such a thing as sit-down dining for
less than $25?
</P>
<P>
   City of monuments? The French, it is said, hated the Tour
d'Eiffel when it was unveiled, but I never get tired of looking at
it. The Arc d'Triomphe, when lit up in gold after dark, is a
beautiful site. Sacre Coeur on Montmarte, which reminds the Gauls
of a big, fluffy marshmallow, is beautiful from afar. The Palais
Royale and the Louvre make the Rue de Rivoli one of the world's
great thoroughfares. Throw in the Hotel Invalides (where Napolean's
tomb, among other things, resides), Notre Dame (the most famous of
gothic cathedrals, although inferior to Chartres), Ste. Chapelle
(nothing on the outside, but incredible stained glass indoors), La
Defense (a wonderful, modern structure, sort of a huge, hollow
square meant as a counterpoint to the Arc d'Triomphe) and dozens of
other imposing structures, and you could spend weeks just looking
at buildings.
</P>
<P>
   City of shopping? I suppose, but it's not like I've got the time
or the cash (or the room in my luggage) to acquire more stuff. I'll
leave this one for someone else to decide.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing about Paris, I've found, is how easy it is to
get around. The Metro is Europe's most comprehensive subway
(although it would be nice if it ran after 1 a.m.), the bus system
is easy to use (and offers an inexpensive way to see the town), and
the taxis are relatively inexpensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
