<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTISIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB LEADER PLEDGES TO HOLD TALKS ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin, his country teetering on the
brink of economic meltdown, needs cash. And Yugoslavian strongman
Slobodan Milosevic, waging a brutal crackdown in Kosovo but wary of
Western military intervention, needs time.
</P>
<P>
   As the conflict in the mainly Albanian southern Serbian province
intensified, both leaders Tuesday made strides toward getting what
they need, but appeared to make little headway on ending the crisis
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a Kremlin meeting with Yeltsin, Milosevic promised to hold
talks with moderate Albanian leaders in Kosovo and accepted other
conditions set by the US and other Western nations to head off
military intervention by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement may buy Milosevic some time. But the Serbian
leader flatly refused the West's main demand, the withdrawal of
Serbian security forces who have been conducting what Western
nations say is ethnic cleansing in Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians
make up 90 percent of the population of around two million.
</P>
<P>
   Russian leaders hailed as a breakthrough the results of the
meeting, held one day after NATO staged a massive show of force in
the skies over Kosovo's borders with Albania and Macedonia. That
brought angry protests from Moscow, which opposes the use of force
against Serbia, and which has loudly protested NATO's eastward
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   But while maintaining its prickly opposition to the West's
military alliance, Russia badly needs a bailout from Western
lending organizations to help stem a financial crisis that has seen
stocks dive 60 percent since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Russian analysts, like Georgy Bovt of the newspaper Segodnya,
have wondered how long the Kremlin can keep up a foreign policy
that appears to fly in the face of Western objectives while at the
same time negotiating for a reported $10 billion loan from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting helped answer that question. Nominally, it was
called so that Yeltsin, acting on behalf of Moscow's Western
allies, could exert some of the influence Russia is said to hold
over its fellow Slavic, Orthodox Christian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Russia's influence over the Serbs has been widely
recognized as minimal since the outbreak of violence in the former
Yugoslavia in 1991, the same year of the Soviet Union's collapse.
Instead, a more plausible reason for Tuesday's Kremlin meeting with
Milosevic was to allow the embattled Yeltsin to raise the tattered
banner of Russia's status as a great power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Russia, the Kosovo problem cannot be solved,'' Yeltsin
said on Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   A Kremlin spokesman said President Clinton had called Yeltsin to
congratulate him on the successful negotiations with Milosevic. But
in Washington, US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, was more
cautious, and suggested that the option of a Western military
intervention was ``still on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some progress but (Milosevic) did not meet the
primary points that the Contact Group raised,'' Albright said,
referring to the grouping of Russia, the US and other European
nations who are trying to regulate the Yugoslavia crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic promised to allow international aid agencies access to
Kosovo villages cut off by the fighting, and agreed to resume
negotiations with a moderate Kosovo Albanian leader. But Milosevic
said that his troops were targeting ``terrorists,'' not civilians,
and ruled out a withdrawal from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no reasons or grounds for the Yugoslav army not to
be on the territory of Yugoslavia,'' he told reporters in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   That stance, unacceptable to the West, is strongly supported in
Russia's parliament, which will likely issue a statement condemning
NATO's show of strength in the Balkans when it convenes Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But is far from clear how widespread popular indignation over
Kosovo is in Russia. Domestic economic matters, rather than foreign
policy, is what makes Russian blood boil these days.
</P>
<P>
   The Western nightmare about Russia is that an economic collapse
could bring to power ultranationalists who would reverse years of
post-Cold War cooperation with the West.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why, despite the Yeltsin administration's
uncomfortable political stance on Kosovo, economic assistance is
still in the cards. As Gordon Brown, British Chancellor of the
Exchequer, said last week: ``Russia's economic stability is vitally
important to all our interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
