<HEADER>
A2115 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-HATE-CRIMES-0616-C     06-16 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-HATE-CRIMES-0616-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS MEMBERS CALL FOR STRENGTHENING FEDERAL HATE CRIMES LAW
 &HT;    By REBECCA CARR
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A group of Congress members called Tuesday for
passing legislation that would strengthen the federal government's
authority to prosecute hate crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The members held a news conference following news reports of a
black man being dragged to death behind a truck near Jasper, Texas,
a black man in New Orleans reporting that a group of whites dragged
him for 2 1/2 blocks before setting him free, and a black teenager
in Belleville, Ill., reporting that three white youths dragged him
by his shirt until the cloth ripped and he went under the wheels of
a car they were driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the events near Jasper, Texas, have made all too clear,
racism and racial violence continue to plague our nation,'' said
Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., who appeared with Sens. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and Ron Wyden, D-Ore., and Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich. ``As
a nation and as a people, we must renounce violence and embrace the
teachings of non-violence. We must renounce racism and embrace
diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation, which lawmakers said would be
considered in the House and Senate Judiciary Committees as soon as
next month, would remove several obstacles in prosecuting hate
crimes, said Michael Lieberman, counsel for the Anti-Defamation
League, a Washington-based civil rights advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Current federal law requires that prosecutors prove a victim was
chosen due to race, religion or nationality. Under the proposed
legislation, this definition would be expanded to include victims
who were selected because of gender, sexual orientation or
disability.
</P>
<P>
   And under the proposed legislation, prosecutors would no longer
have to prove that the victim of a hate crime was engaged in a
federally protected act such as voting at the time of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   The need for a new law is not just in the recent attacks, but in
the rising number of crimes committed based on someone's race,
Wyden said. In 1996, there were 8,759 such crimes reported to the
FBI, a 9 percent increase over the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate and bias have left an ugly mark on society,'' said Wyden.
``We're trying to close the loopholes in the federal law. It just
seems to be that if you beat a woman or attack a disabled person or
bash a gay person, you ought to face the federal government. This
is intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a longtime champion of legislation that would expand
the federal authority to combat hate crimes, said he expected an
uphill fight to pass legislation. He predicted that some members
would oppose it on a constitutional basis, and others would oppose
it because it protects groups such as homosexuals who some
lawmakers believe should not be given special protection.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always those who will find something to oppose,''
Kennedy said, following the press conference. But he said that he
hoped that the recent racial attacks in Texas, Illinois, and
Louisiana would persuade both chambers that the time has come to
pass a strong measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate crimes tear at the heart and soul of our country, and we
need to do all we can to combat them,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation would go a long way toward plugging the
holes in the current law, said Christopher Edley, professor of law
at Harvard University. Strengthening the law would make it easier
for the federal government to step in an prosecute cases like the
one in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government issued indictments in only 40 out of the
8,759 incidents of hate crime in 1996, in large part because of the
restrictions placed on federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, racist groups have opted to operate in a more
clandestine manner, Edley said. The proposed legislation would
remove barriers keeping federal and state law enforcement officials
from working together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racial hatred and related violence is like a cancer without
visible tumors; you can't always see where its going,'' Edley said.
``That's why this legislation is so important.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis sees it, the legislation is important because it taking
a step toward recognizing that ``racial hatred threatens not just
the victims of hate crime, but each and every one of us.''
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
