<SLUG> BC-COX-CABLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tuscon cable buy solidifies Cox strength in Southwest
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In its second major purchase in the past two months,
Cox Communications has bought several cable TV systems in Arizona,
including one in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based company is buying the systems, which have a
total of 115,000 subscribers, from Tele-Communications Inc. The
other systems are in Sierra Vista and Pima County, which includes
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The deal closed late Monday evening, with approval of the change
in ownership by the Tucson City Council. The council's approval
came on the last day the deal could go through.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications is buying the Tucson system with proceeds
from another sale and needed to close the purchase Monday to take
advantage of tax credits associated with those proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase makes Cox Communications the largest cable operator
in Arizona, where it already owns the Phoenix system. With 578,000
subscribers, the Phoenix system is the company's largest.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also anchors Cox Communications' position as the
largest operator in the Southwest. It has 1.4 million subscribers
in the region now, including 484,000 in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   That number will swell to more than 1.8 million with the
addition of Tucson and Las Vegas, a $1.33 billion deal announced in
May. It's expected to close at the end of the year, giving Cox
Communications an additional 319,000 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Las Vegas will bump Cox Communications up to
fifth place from sixth among the largest cable TV operators.
</P>
<P>
   The Tucson purchase is part of a Cox Communications strategy to
concentrate subscribers in large clusters. Other clusters are in
Virginia, including Hampton Roads and Roanoke, and New England. The
Southwest is the company's biggest play.
</P>
<P>
   The many of the cities in this region are considered among the
fastest-growing in the region. They include Las Vegas, Phoenix and
Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The region has tremendous residential and commercial growth,
which makes it very attractive to us,'' said company spokeswoman
Ellen East. ``This deal strengthens our presence in the Southwest,
where the majority of our customers are.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications plans to begin immediately upgrading Tucson
to a digital system, said East. That will enable the company to
offer, at an additional price, Cox Digital TV. The service enables
the transmission of many more channels and a sharper picture, among
other things.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications has named Gretchen Shine to oversee its new
systems in the Southern tier of Arizona. A 14-year veteran of Cox
Communications, she most recently managed the company's system in
Roanoke, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
