<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUCOM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two public utility groups oppose federal appointment
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Two Washington-based public utility groups are
opposing the impending appointment of an attorney with Southern
Co.'s law firm to two federal commissions charged with working out
longstanding water disputes between Georgia, Florida and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rural Electric Cooperative Association and the
American Public Power Association wrote the White House recently to
raise conflict-of-interest questions about Thomas Jensen's
appointment as alternate federal commissioner for the two panels.
</P>
<P>
   The Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint and
Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa river basin compact commissions were
created by Congress last year to reach agreements on allocation of
water from those river basins among Florida, Alabama and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The NRECA and the APPA said Jensen should not be appointed
because he is a registered lobbyist for Atlanta-based Southern Co.
and the Alliance for Power Privatization, a Washington-based
advocacy group formed by investor-owned utilities, the two groups
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen, an attorney with the Washington office of Atlanta-based
Troutman Sanders, dismissed the charges Tuesday. ``It's regrettable
that they did not check their facts prior to sending their
letter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jensen said he is registered as a lobbyist for Southern and the
Alliance for Power Privatization only because his law firm
represents and lobbies for them. But he added, ``I have never
lobbied for either of them and have never represented them on the
types of issues that will come before the commissions.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Rural Electric Cooperative Association and the
American Public Power Association, which are lobbying organizations
and often at cross-purposes with Southern, noted the utility
holding company has nine hydroelectric projects under the
jurisdiction of the new commissions, and the alliance ``continues
to advocate the sale of the federal power facilities, including
those facilities on these river systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The groups are against such sales because they would jeopardize
power supply arrangements or the very existence of their member
utilities. Former U.S. Rep. Lindsay Thomas (D-Ga.), now president
of the Georgia Chamber of Commerce, recently was named to the
Apalachicola-Chattahoochee-Flint and the Alabama-Coosa-Tallapoosa
river basin compact commissions. He said the controversy over
Jensen may indicate the importance of the commissions, which will
attempt to sort out environmental, transportation, irrigation and
electric power issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody and their brother is concerned about this,'' said
Thomas, who will attend his first commission meeting June 29-30 in
Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
