<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KING-COX </SLUG>
     CLINTON TELLS MRS. KING HE CAN'T CREATE
PANEL TO PROBE ASSASSINATION
 &HT;     By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton told the widow of the Rev. Martin
Luther King Jr. on Tuesday that he could not create a panel to
reopen the inquiry into the civil rights leader's assassination 30
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton told Coretta Scott King that the question of
whether to reopen the case would remain under review at the Justice
Department and that the administration would act on the advice of
Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we are awaiting the response of the Justice
Department,'' said Minyon Moore, deputy assistant to the president
for political affairs, who attended Tuesday's 45-minute Oval Office
meeting between Clinton and Mrs. King.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nothing else, I think it has given her the opportunity to
speak directly to the president about her concerns, unfiltered, and
we'll just have to see where we go from here,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King said after the meeting that she would continue to
press for a new investigation into her husband's death, saying she
did not believe convicted assassin James Earl Ray acted alone in
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to ignore this thing for years, but it didn't go
away,'' said Mrs. King, flanked by three of her children _ Martin
Luther King III, Dexter Scott King and the Rev. Bernice King _ who
accompanied her to the meeting with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a family that believes in truth and we believe in, also,
forgiveness,'' said Mrs. King. ``And we believe that there is a
moral order and that somehow, in the long run, that the truth will
win out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King said she had hoped the president would consider
empaneling a federal commission to investigate new evidence she
claims supports the theory that Ray, who died in prison this year,
did not act alone in the murder of King and possibly wasn't even
the killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult for me to appreciate the fact that one lone
person could engineer what he did, in terms of his escape and what
I know about him not being a good shooter ... and the fact that he
was able to get out of the country and all that,'' Mrs. King said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Clinton believed in a conspiracy theory, she
replied, ``We didn't discuss that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, gave no indication that he would empanel a
commission, as Mrs. King has sought, modeled after the South
African Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which is reviewing
apartheid-era human rights abuses in exchange for immunity for
perpetrators who come forward to tell their stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president just said he would have to see what his options
are,'' Mrs. King said. ``There are such things as laws, and,
legally, what is possible to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she was satisfied with the pace of the Justice
Department inquiry _ which began after she met in April with Reno _
Mrs. King said ``I know these things take time and my assumption is
that we will be hearing something in the not-too-distant-future.
... That's about what we can expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who died in April at age 70, pleaded guilty in 1969 to
King's assassination at a Memphis hotel on April 4, 1968. Ray later
recanted his confession.
</P>
<P>
   The King family went to the White House bearing gifts for
Clinton _ the book ``A Knock at Midnight,'' inspired by the late
King's work; an audio tape of his speeches, and a video of sermons
preached by his daughter, Bernice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shared with the president a very intimate look at who
they were as a family and what this tragedy has done to them,''
said Moore. ``He was certainly very attentive and listened very
carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
