<HEADER>
A2134 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONORAIL-COX     06-16 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONORAIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monorail hasn't had a smooth ride to success
 &HT;    By Matt Kempner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The little Marietta company with a funky computer and
a unique way of doing business won lots of national media
attention.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half since the debut of Monorail the computer and
Monorail the company, the executives have kept up the marketing
chutzpah, but the market didn't buy in as planned.
</P>
<P>
   Monorail Chairman Doug Johns _ a former chief of Compaq
Computer's PC division who populated his start-up with industry
veterans _ predicted he would sell an astounding 1 million
computers last year.
</P>
<P>
   Monorail was a ``virtual company.'' Fewer than 50 people work at
its Marietta headquarters. Most of the basic parts of doing
business _ computer assembly, delivery, phone-in technical support,
on-site support and accounts receivable _ are contracted to other
companies in other cities. The company hit the market with an
all-in-one desktop unit that took up a fifth the space of most
systems, offered acceptable power and cost a smidgen under $1,000.
Best of all, it got its bargain box to stores months before the
industry's giants could break the same price ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   But Monorail's advantages of timing were fleeting. Competitors
stormed the under-$1,000 computer market, and the overall industry
began a brutal wave of price slashing.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Phelps, the CEO of Monorail's original assembly contractor,
said he produced only about 20,000 units before his own Kansas
City, Mo.-based company went bankrupt. Monorail disputes Phelps'
figures as too low, but declined to say how close sales compared to
Johns' projection.
</P>
<P>
   Not close at all, said Phelps. ``They hit the market and
basically fell flat on their face ... They couldn't sell the thing.
Here they were supposed to be marketing gurus.''
</P>
<P>
   James Chatz, an attorney representing unsecured creditors of
Phelps Technologies, says his clients are struggling to unload
leftover Monorail components _ a difficult task because some of the
equipment is customized. ``We have about 100,000 pink keyboards
that we never could sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Monorail, meanwhile, says it was Phelps Technologies that
repeatedly left it without enough computers to put on store
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Monorail lost what had been one of its biggest
breaks: a foothold with major national retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We committed a few cardinal sins,'' said Monorail marketing
chief Andrew Watson. He recalled Sunday advertising circulars that
pitched Monorail computers when there were no units available.
Monorail officials found themselves apologizing over and over again
to some of the nation's biggest retailers and distributors for not
coming through.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part about it,'' Watson said, ``was that we had
millions of dollars in orders from the biggest, most powerful, most
influential channels in the PC distribution business, and we
couldn't fulfill them.''
</P>
<P>
   CompUSA hasn't carried the brand on its store shelves for
months. Neither has Circuit City. But Watson said relationships
remain intact.
</P>
<P>
   A Circuit City spokesman declined to comment. CompUSA's Carol
Elfstrom said Monorail officials ``are focused on being more
competitive, and they are focused on their manufacturing process. I
think that slowed them down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   While Monorail computers were aimed at first-time computer
owners, businesses and schools were more likely to want the
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Watson said, ``Don't get the wrong idea. We had a good
year in '97.'' He declined to release the private company's
financial results, but said Monorail's sales exceeded the top
figure posted by any of the hot growth companies highlighted in a
recent report by Business Week magazine. That would put its sales
over $145 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Monorail is bulling forward in an attempt to tackle perhaps
the most competitive and crowded segment of the PC world:
mini-tower desktop systems.
</P>
<P>
   This time Monorail and its distributors are targeting
businesses, abandoning the company's niche for desktop units
costing under $1,000. Monorail officials say the original
all-in-one design isn't big enough to handle more powerful innards
and bigger displays now demanded by customers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Monorail announced two new additions to its line of
full-sized mini-towers, with suggested retail prices of $1,499 and
$1,799.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we are structured to do,'' Watson says. ``We _
unlike anybody else in this business _ are structured to play in a
market that is deteriorating so fast that nobody else is making any
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson says the new Monorail mini-towers are 20 percent cheaper
than units of comparable quality offered by giants such as Compaq
and Dell. The computers will be assembled by Monorail's new
assembly contractor _ its third in 18 months _ Huntsville,
Ala.-based SCI Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Once dramatically unique in price and look, the new Monorails
are neither, analysts say. And in an industry where prices are in
free fall, ``it is really hard to use price as a strategy,'' says
Cameron Duncan, a hardware analyst with ARS in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not in a good spot,'' says Stephen Baker of PC Data,
a market research firm based in Reston, Va. Computer markets are
consolidating into a few dominant suppliers with broad product
lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult in this environment to be a small PC
manufacturer with high aspirations,'' Baker says. ``It's nice to be
new and different, but if you don't get to be new and different and
real big real quick, you are in trouble, because the rest of the
market targets what you are doing and blows it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
