u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-16 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETS POST MODEST GAINS AS INVESTORS GO BARGAIN HUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major stock market indexes were modestly higher
Tuesday as investors looked for bargains but shunned many
multinational companies with exposure to Asian markets. Instead,
they sought technology issues, which have been battered recently by
some of the same concerns that are now hurting the conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Nasdaq composite index rose 37.37 points _
erasing Monday's 29.30 point decline, to 1,753.12. The 2.18 percent
gain was the largest percentage increase in the technology-heavy
barometer since March 6.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom and Microsoft were the leading gainers in the index.
</P>
<P>
   One of the day's most active issues, Dell Computer, rose 5.9
percent, or 4 23/32 points, to 84 31/32. The stock has fallen
almost 14 percent from its recent closing high of 98 1/4 on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   Oil stocks were also higher as oil prices rose on news that
several leading oil producers again agreed to cut production to
lighten worldwide oversupply.
</P>
<P>
   After a 207-point plunge Monday, the Dow Jones industrial
average, which seesawed between gains and losses throughout the
session, closed up 37.36 points, at 8,665.29.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble, Merck and Chevron led the index higher, as
buyers selected stocks with positive news _ such as the oil shares
_ or which they believed would not be severely hurt by the turmoil
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index was up 10.58 points, to
1,087.59.
</P>
<P>
   Calmer overseas markets helped stave off further declines,
analysts said. In Asia, the dollar fell sharply against the yen
after Japan's central bank indicated it might enter the market to
support the currency.
</P>
<P>
   No intervention took place, however, and the American currency
made up some of its lost ground, closing at 143.47.
</P>
<P>
   While the benchmark Japanese Nikkei 225 index fell 0.71 percent,
most Asian stock markets were higher. European markets rose as
well.
</P>
<P>
   But after Monday's sharp selloff, some analysts were unimpressed
by the market's limited gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an attempt at a rally, but it was very uninspiring,''
said Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.
``It doesn't appear there's much confidence coming back to the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I ask, `Does it appear the stock market has reached a
near-term bottom?' The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM proved the biggest drag on the Dow, pulling 8.97 points out
of the blue-chip index. IBM closed at 110, down 2 1/4. Merrill
Lynch analyst Steven Milunovich on Tuesday lowered second-quarter
earnings estimates for the personal computer maker, citing concerns
about weak computer sales, declining revenue in Asia and the strong
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   This year IBM, like many other technology companies, has been
plagued by weakening demand and Asia's worsening economic problems.
</P>
<P>
   IBM warned in January that first-quarter profits would take a
hit due to the strength of the dollar and slowing Asian demand for
its products.
</P>
<P>
   And when Coca-Cola reported first-quarter earnings in April, it
attributed a 13.2 percent drop in earnings to the negative effect
of Far Eastern currency fluctuations and warned that similar
currency problems would affect second-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the dollar's recent strength caused Merrill Lynch
analyst Douglas Lane to reduce his earnings estimates for the
beverage company, which derives about 80 percent of its profits
from outside of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, as the Asian financial crisis was unfolding, shares
of a number of multinational companies, including Coca-Cola,
Gillette, Eastman Kodak and Polaroid, fell on fears that the
dollar's strength would hurt earnings. Each of those issues closed
lower Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
