<HEADLINE>
DEBATE OVER HOMOSEXUALITY ERUPTS OVER GOP LEADERS' COMMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey touched off
new debate over homosexuality Tuesday when he said the Bible ``is
very clear'' in holding that it is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Republican was asked if he agreed with remarks made
Monday by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., likening
homosexuals to people who have problems with alcoholism, sex
addiction or kleptomania. Armey was also asked if he thinks
homosexuality is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   Replying that he does, Armey said, ``The Bible is very clear on
this. In fact, I can give you a reference if you like _ one of many
_ but it is very clear on this. Now, both myself and Senator Lott
believe very strongly in the Bible. ... I abide by the instructions
that are given to me in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited what he said were several references to the
homosexuality in the New Testament books of Romans, Timothy and
First Corinthians.
</P>
<P>
   The conservatives' comments prompted Sen. Paul Wellstone, a
liberal Democrat of Minnesota, to fire back on the Senate floor
Tuesday, saying being gay or lesbian is genetically predetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone added that in light of the Republican leaders'
remarks, the Senate should debate the issue and vote on the
languishing nomination of gay rights advocate James C. Hormel to be
ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative senators blocking the nomination of Hormel, 64, a
San Francisco philanthropist and Democratic Party donor, have
accused him of being a gay activist who would try to carry out a
homosexual agenda in Luxembourg, a predominantly Catholic nation.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone asked that Lott's comments on homosexuality be
included in the public record and said the statement ``takes us
back quite a ways from where we are. We ought to bring it to the
floor so we can have an honest discussion,'' Wellstone said. ``The
Majority Leader is entitled to his opinion... and he is entitled to
his vote. But the rest of us are entitled to our opinions and our
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute quickly moved to the White House when President
Clinton's press secretary, Mike McCurry. said Lott and other
conservatives who have kept Hormel's nomination from going to the
Senate floor for seven months are doing so because they are
``backward in their thinking ... because they have views that are,
to put it charitably, quite out of date. ... They're refusing to
move forward on that nomination because he's gay.''.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott has refused to bring Hormel's nomination up for a vote,
saying it would take too much time. Hormel was approved, 16 to 2,
in November by the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, but his
appointment has been put on hold since then by conservatives
including Sens. James M. Inhofe, R-Okla., Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark.,
and Robert C. Smith, R-N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's comments came in an interview on ``The Armstrong Williams
Show'' on the America's Voice cable television network.
</P>
<P>
   Williams asked Lott whether he considers homosexuality a sin and
the senator replied, ``Yeah, it is.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``You should still love that person. You should not
try to mistreat them or treat them as outcasts. You should try to
show them a way to deal with that problem, just like alcohol ... or
sex addiction ... or kleptomaniacs. There are all kinds of
problems, addictions, difficulties, experiences of things that are
wrong, but you should try to work with that person to learn to
control that problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that ``in America right now there's an element that
wants to make that alternative life style acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Stachelberg, political director of the Human Rights
Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian organization which
Hormel help to found, said Lott's and Armey's comments are
``another sign that the extreme right wing has a stranglehold on
the Senate and now the House leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Stachelberg said the comments are an indication that the
politics of Gary Bauer, who heads the conservative Family Research
Council, and James Dobson, who has a conservative Christian radio
show, are rubbing off on the Senate and House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   She added that Lott's comments ``seem to suggest'' that his
beliefs about homosexuality are what's holding up Hormel's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's not a sign of the direction of the Republican
party,'' Stachelberg said. ``I hope it's not open season on gay
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott spokeswoman Susan Irby declined to comment on Stachelberg's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of the American Psychiatric Association, the
American Psychological Association declared in 1975 that it no
longer considered homosexuality a mental disorder. Some scientific
studies have found differences between the genes and brain
structures of homosexual and heterosexual people.
</P>
</TEXT>
