<SLUG> BC-LATINO-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN ATTEMPT TO BAN BILINGUAL VOTING MATERIALS DENOUNCED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican attempts to enact voter identification
laws and ban bilingual voting materials were denounced Tuesday by
the League of Women Voters as nothing more than an effort to keep
ethnic and racial minority voters away from the polls.
</P>
<P>
   In a blistering critique of GOP-sponsored amendments likely to
be offered during House consideration of campaign finance reform
legislation this summer, the league said the measures would only
``promote discrimination'' against Hispanic, Asian and other
minority voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the proposed . . . amendments would discourage voter
participation, create obstacles for new citizens and citizens with
disabilities, and encourage discrimination against ethnic and
racial minorities,'' said League of Women Voters' senior lobbyist
Mary Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   She said some of the amendments had already been rejected at
least twice by Congress, but keep coming back again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems to never end,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks made the comments in a news conference with Democratic
Party leaders and various Hispanic and Asian groups that also
condemned the amendments as ``a crass political attempt'' to
prevent minority citizens from participating in the elections
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the amendments are a calculated strategy on the part of
the Republican Party to prevent people from registering to vote,''
said Colorado Gov. and Democratic National Committee Chairman Roy
Romer.
</P>
<P>
   The amendments drawing the most fire would set up a federal
office to ``verify'' voter citizenship through Social Security and
immigration records, ban bilingual materials at polling places,
require photo identification of voters at the polls, allow states
to drop voters from the rolls for not voting, and repeal the
mail-in voter registration provision known as the motor voter law.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, Brooks said the amendments would in effect abolish
Voting Rights Act protections and violate privacy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders plan to offer the restrictions as amendments
to campaign finance reform legislation now being debated in the
House, although opponents of the amendments say they have nothing
to do with the issue of changing the way candidates raise and spend
money in elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about campaign reform, free and fair elections . . .
and honest elections. It's as much about voter registration as it
is campaigns,'' said Michelle Davis, press secretary to House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've spent all this time calling for a fair and open debate
(on campaign finance legislation) and now that they've got it, they
don't want it,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   But supporters of campaign finance reform, said the amendments
are designed to kill any attempt at overhauling the laws that
govern political contributions and are aimed as well at
``suppressing the Hispanic and Asian vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want us to be informed, they don't want us to be
registered, and they certainly don't want us to come out and
vote,'' said Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J. ``Instead of trying to
proselytize voters in the Latino and Asian communities, they are
trying to intimidate them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
