<SLUG> BC-HABITAT-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HABITAT WORKERS BATTLE TEXAS HEAT, AIM AT 100-HOUSE EFFORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA M. CHMIOLA 
and BRENDA TAVAKOLI 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As Wade and Shalina Gibson watched their dream house
materialize before their eyes, they found it hard to put their
emotions into words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a dream and when it's there . . . it's like you're
in shock. I really can't describe it,'' said Shalina Gibson, a
25-year-old mother of two who is seven months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting. It's a blessing. It's unbelievable,'' Wade
Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gibsons joined approximately 6,000 volunteers in Habitat for
Humanity's Jimmy Carter Work Project. Building began at dawn Monday
on 100 homes at several sites in Houston's Second and Fifth Wards,
which will be completed by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Carter project, the largest attempted in the United
States, is enormous compared to the project's first year in 1984,
when 42 volunteers labored to renovate an apartment building in New
York. For each project, Carter and wife, Rosalynn, work
side-by-side with volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working with tools ever since I was a small boy on
the farm,'' Carter said Monday on a site where 35 homes are being
constructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a sacrifice for me to come here. It's a real
pleasure,'' said Carter, clad in a straw hat and tool belt while on
a break from construction.
</P>
<P>
   Tasks included framing, installing windows and doors and
beginning the roofing, said the Rev. Michael Shirl, executive
director of Houston Habitat for Humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers work in two shifts: 7 a.m. to 4 p.m., or 4 p.m. to 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Daytime shift volunteer Art Moser of Mishawaka, Ind., led a
group of college students from a Habitat group in the South Bend,
Ind., area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a satisfaction that you've helped somebody out. I hope
someday if any of my grandchildren or great-grandchildren need any
help, there will be someone to help them. I think we need to give
back to our fellow man,'' said Moser, who has helped build more
than 25 houses in his 12 years with Habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Group member Julie Duba, a junior at St. Mary's College in Notre
Dame, Ind., heard about the project while writing a paper for class
on Habitat for Humanity, an ecumenical organization that builds
affordable housing for low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see how it would be done in such a short time,''
said Duba, who worked on her first Habitat house last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The day had minor glitches. Some volunteers boarded the wrong
bus en route to construction sites. A short-lived power outage
slowed progress on a few houses. One woman bumped her head while
putting up a wall and was taken to a hospital for examination. And
the Houston heat took its toll on some workers, especially those
who are not from this area.
</P>
<P>
   Some volunteers were not surprised at Tuesday's high of 98
degrees, with a heat index of 103 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretty much knew it was going to be hot,'' Moser said.
</P>
<P>
   Duba of St. Mary's College agreed. ``It's a bit warmer than I
thought (it would be), but it's beautiful, so I'm not
complaining,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Miller, the project's medical director, said: ``A lot
of people are having a lot of trouble with the heat. With the
humidity, they are getting overheated.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical personnel and volunteers made aggressive efforts to keep
heat-related illnesses at bay, Miller said. The more intensive
construction work, like framing and shingling the houses, occurred
early in the day. The preparation paid off the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not had any unanticipated events, no surprises,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Workers drank water, misted it onto themselves with spray
bottles, and soaked towels and handkerchiefs in an effort to keep
cool. Not all managed to beat dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a little dehydrated,'' said volunteer Bruce
Hollenbeck of Garden Grove, Calif., as he sat in the first aid
trailer's air-conditioned comfort. ``I just didn't drink enough
water fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Difficult as the work proved for some, the volunteers maintained
a can-do spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a second wind,'' said volunteer Betsy Chamberlain.
``I'm out of shape. I don't hammer and nail all day. The
combination of the heat and humidity is very tiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chamberlain and others said they enjoyed the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fascinating to see (houses) go up,'' she said, glancing
at the house she was helping build. ``This morning, there was
nothing but concrete here. I think it's a wonderful effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said, ``What I find absolutely amazing is the intensity
and enthusiasm with which people are working.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of glitches, project construction is running smoothly,
according to Shirl. ``We're on schedule. I feel good about where we
are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping to talk after installing a window, Wade Gibson told why
he and his wife wanted to own a home so badly. The family rents an
apartment, and it is nearly impossible to obtain repairs on it.
Drug dealers frequent the streets, and there is no security, making
it impossible for the Gibsons to allow their 7- and 2-year-old
daughters to play outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he will own a home, Wade Gibson said he can wash his
car in the driveway and play outside with his children. His wife,
Shalina Gibson, also has plans for their new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much I want to do. I really want to start working
on my yard, put some plants out there, some flowers. I want to make
it really pretty,'' she said. ``I'm ready to move in.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
