r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-COACH-LADN     06-16 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-COACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN BOXMEER INTERESTED IN DUCKS' JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Mighty Ducks begin their search for a new head coach,
they might want to look in their own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Ice Dog coach and general manager John Van Boxmeer said Tuesday
he is very interested in speaking to Mighty Duck general manager
Jack Ferreira about the vacancy created by the Monday firing of
Pierre Page.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize this is a tough decision for Jack,'' Van Boxmeer
said. ``No, I haven't been a head coach in the NHL. But I have been
an associate coach in the NHL (from 1990-92 with the Buffalo
Sabres). My record of wins and losses speaks for itself. I think I
have an excellent track record with star players, No. 1, and No. 2,
with European players. I think those are two big factors in today's
NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   And clearly, they are two big factors for the Ducks, who have
superstar wingers in Paul Kariya and Finland's Teemu Selanne.
Ferreira, attending NHL general managers meetings in Washington,
could not be reached for the comment he probably wouldn't have
given in response to questions about prospective candidates. But at
Monday's news conference announcing Page's firing, Ferreira who has
not set a timetable for making a decision did not rule out hiring a
coach lacking NHL experience.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira said, ``We want what every team in the NHL is looking
for in a hockey coach: respect from the players, someone who is
strategically sound, someone who will show consistent improvement
in the club and someone who develops young players. All of this
adds up to one thing: winning. We want to win and get back to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, after the Ducks reached the playoffs for the only
time in their five-year history, Coach Ron Wilson was fired with
little explanation. This season, Wilson led the Washington Capitals
to the Stanley Cup finals for the first time in their history, and
Page coached a problem-plagued Duck team to a 26-43-13 record, 13
points out of the last playoff spot in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Van Boxmeer, meanwhile, has a sparkling record
in 12 years as a minor-league head coach. In three seasons with the
Ice Dogs, his record is 139-75-32, and the last two years, he has
led them deep into the IHL playoffs. He won the IHL's Coach of the
Year award with the Ice Dogs in 1996-97, a decade after coaching
the Rochester Americans to the AHL championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Duck job has special appeal for Van Boxmeer because his
wife, Judy, is from Orange County, and he is not interested in
moving her and the couple's children Ashley, 13, and Henry, 10 to
another city in pursuit of an NHL opportunity. Van Boxmeer lives in
Orange, a quarter-mile from Ferreira and a 15-minute drive from the
Pond, and he said he feels quite worthy of consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Listing current and past NHL coaches, Van Boxmeer said, ``I've
coached against Pat Burns, Barry Melrose, Marc Crawford, Terry
Murray, Colin Campbell, Terry Crisp and Pierre Page. My teams have
beaten all these guys. It's not like I haven't coached against guys
in the NHL. I have, and I've had success against them. The fact
that I've never gone out and marketed myself for a job has kept me
at the position I'm at. I'm still not marketing myself, but this is
the job I'm interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   But will Ferreira be interested in Van Boxmeer? It remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer said he was planning to notify Ice Dog owner Barry
Kemp of his interest in the Ducks' job (Kemp has said he expects to
eventually lose Van Boxmeer to an NHL team), and then to contact
Ferreira. Van Boxmeer said he did not contact the Ducks about their
opening a year ago, the one that was filled by Page.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons to believe Van Boxmeer could have a shot at
the Ducks' job. And there are reasons to believe he might not.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side is his winning record, the relationship he
developed with Ferreira a year ago when the Ice Dogs and Mighty
Ducks had a limited affiliation, his role developing numerous young
players at the minor-league level, and the fact that Van Boxmeer
would be willing to work at a salary that Disney would find more
palatable than what it would cost to hire available big-ticket
items such as former Colorado coach Crawford and former Buffalo
coach Ted Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, for instance, earned $800,000 this season at Colorado,
and is believed destined to be hired by the Toronto Maple Leafs.
Page was fired after one year of a three-year deal that paid him
$500,000 a season, and unless he is hired elsewhere will receive $1
million more from the Ducks over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Van Boxmeer, who recently signed a two-year extension with the
Ice Dogs, has three years remaining on his contract and is believed
to earn about $175,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing against Van Boxmeer, however, is the fact that Ferreira
the only general manager in the Mighty Ducks' history may be down
to his last coaching hire, and may not view Van Boxmeer as the
safest possible choice because he hasn't been an NHL head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just like an interview,'' Van Boxmeer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
