<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR LASHES OUT OVER MAGAZINE ARTICLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the defensive for the third day, independent
counsel Kenneth Starr lashed back Tuesday at a magazine editor,
saying his article ``borders on the libelous'' when it accuses the
prosecutor of illegally leaking grand jury information about the
Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a 19-page letter, Starr ``categorically and unequivocally''
denies any legal or ethical breaches and accused Steven Brill of
``a fundamental misunderstanding of the law and a misrepresentation
of the facts'' surrounding the prosecutor's discussions with
reporters about the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``You challenge this office at a fundamental level _ alleging
that we would commit crimes to uncover crime,'' Starr wrote. ``I
categorically and unequivocally reject the charge.''
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the inaugural issue of his media affairs
magazine Brill's Content, Brill, a lawyer and donor to Democratic
candidates, accuses Starr of violating a federal law prohibiting
disclosure of evidence gathered by a grand jury or information
gained from persons who are potential witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your reckless and irresponsible attack borders on the
libelous,'' Starr wrote to Brill.
</P>
<P>
   The special prosecutor is quoted in the article justifying
discussions he and top deputy Jackie M. Bennett had with reporters
about the investigation into whether President Clinton or his aides
engaged in a cover-up of his alleged sexual relationship with
Lewinsky or an encounter with Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton's private attorney, David Kendall, fired off
his own letter, this one to Starr repeating earlier accusations
that the prosecution team have violated laws and ignored ethical
rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caught flat-footed by the Brill article, you've attempted to
shift your ground,'' Kendall wrote to Starr. ``You accuse Mr. Brill
of misinterpreting, but not misquoting, and that's highly
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar point was made by Brill after he read Starr's letter.
``I am pleased that Judge Starr again does not dispute any of the
quotes attributed by me to him,'' the lawyer-editor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure that Judge Starr sincerely believes in his view of
the law, just as I believe that other lawyers and judges have and
will continue to disagree with him,'' Brill said.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall has asked U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson to
sanction Starr and his deputies for violating her order barring
grand jury leaks. Monday night, Johnson summoned members of Starr's
staff, the president's legal team and lawyers for Lewinsky for a
half-hour, closed-door discussion about leaks in the case.
</P>
<P>
   As Starr, Brill and Kendall swapped correspondence, two top
aides to President Clinton made return appearances before the grand
jury investigating allegations of a presidential affair and
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   John Podesta, Clinton's deputy chief of staff, was questioned
for two hours. Podesta was involved in efforts to help Lewinsky _ a
former White House intern who later worked at the Pentagon _ find a
job outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying Tuesday was Nancy Hernreich, chief of Oval
Office operations, who spent almost four hours behind closed doors
with the grand jury. Hernreich has been summoned for questioning at
least four other times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
