<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2156 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-IRAN-HNS &LR;      06-16 1287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-IRAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NANTES, France _ The nation of Iran recently made an emphatic
statement to the rest of the world: It is dangerous, unpredictable
and explosive.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're talking soccer, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the whole point to this Iranian World Cup
expedition, an intriguing trip to a different kind of international
spotlight and, many Iranians here hope, a different kind of
perspective about their enigmatic and controversial country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to play good, fair soccer, strong soccer,'' Iranian
coach Jalel Talebi said. ``Every game here for us has special
meaning. We want to be sportsmen.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will be difficult separating sports and politics
for this embattled nation, particularly Sunday when Iran faces the
United States, a nation with which it has had no economic or
political relations for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that is the great hope for many Iranian players and a
large contingent of followers who have made the trip to France for
Iran's first World Cup appearance since 1978. A hope for peaceful
soccer solutions to a longtime problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans think of us as animals,'' said Hedayaed Azim, an
Iranian soccer fan who traveled with the team to Paris. ``Why?
There is too much thinking around the world that we cannot coexist
with other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, particularly in the West, there seems to remain a widely
held belief that Iran is a nation of radical fundamentalists,
religious fanatics and terrorist sympathizers. It is, of course, a
sentiment founded in Iran's political history, which might have
been defined in 1979 when Islamic revolutionaries took 52 Americans
hostage in Tehran and held them for 444 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Iran's players all were either children or young teens when
the hostage crisis took place and now say they wish Iran's image
could be different as they progress through France '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do nothing about what has happened in the past,''
Iranian midfielder Alireza Mansourian said. ``But it is there.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, what was there for the Iranian World Cup team
was an impressive if ultimately unrewarded effort against
Yugoslavia. It was a small step toward at least giving the world a
different kind of image about its country.
</P>
<P>
   A soccer image.
</P>
<P>
   Iran is a soccer-loving nation without a doubt. Thousands of
Iranians have descended upon France this month, wearing the colors,
chanting the cheers and scooping up tickets at a feverish pace.
</P>
<P>
   On Paris streets and in Lyon cafes, Iranians are happily
intermingling with all others, including Americans. The most
popular tourist site among the Iranians: Euro-Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket brokers quoted in L'Equipe, a French daily sports
newspaper, were asked in Sunday's editions about the best customers
they have come across thus far at the World Cup. Brazilian and
English fans were considered the front-runners. Iranian fans ranked
third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tickets? Tickets?'' they can be heard asking strangers along
the Champs Elysees in Paris, the Bellecour plaza in Lyon and the
Grand Station in Saint-Etienne.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no outlaws here,'' Azim said. ``Just football
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the hostage crisis, Iran was in fact considered the best
of all the Asian and Middle Eastern soccer countries. It was a
1970s power on the world level, winning three consecutive Asian
Championships, beating Brazil in the 1972 Olympics and qualifying
for the World Cup in 1978. And its fans were widely considered
among the world's most enthusiastic and loyal.
</P>
<P>
   After 1978, however, the Iran-Iraq war brought the game to a
virtual standstill in Iran. Then came the hostage crisis and a
U.S.-led diplomatic blockade of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Iran became a great villain to much of the world.
</P>
<P>
   With so many political issues at stake, it did not attempt to
qualify for the 1982 World Cup. It then was not allowed to play any
home qualifying games for the 1986 World Cup and was eliminated
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the game again dominates nearly every sidewalk
conversation as the team has returned to prominence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is so huge in Iran, and everyone is excited about the
World Cup,'' said Aras Nouamouz, a former Houston Hotshots player
and Iranian national-team member still living in Houston.
Nouamouz's father, Nasser, is Iran's 1998 World Cup team manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the players and to my mother (Monday), and they
said everything about the World Cup is being covered,'' Nouamouz
said. ``People are staying at home to watch every game. There is no
business, no activity anywhere, just the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   There are five daily sports newspapers in Iran, and all sent
numerous reporters to France. The national television network also
is broadcasting every World Cup game, not just those involving
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   And before the team departed Tehran for France, there was a
send-off rally for the players that drew more than 70,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what kind of team we would have, because there
is not any World Cup experience on the team,'' Nouamouz said. ``But
there is talent, and there is emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran played a fast, furious game in its opener against
Yugoslavia, a team many expect to move deep into the tournament.
The Iranians pressed the ball offensively and played tough
straight-up defense against the creative Yugoslavian goal-scorers.
</P>
<P>
   The statement made was clear. This is a dangerous team again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a difficult team to get through,'' Yugoslavia's
Sinisa Mihajlovic said of Iran. ``They were tough and faster than
we expected to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran had at least three legitimate scoring opportunities slip
away in the 1-0 loss, and when it was over, the Iranian players
shook hands with their opponents, smiled and waved to the crowd at
Stade Geoffrey in Saint-Etienne.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to know that we are humans, like everyone
else,'' Mansourian said. ``We love soccer, and we play soccer for
the sport of it. It is our national game. We want to prove that
this is a friendly game and that we love to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Iran is one of the last remaining enemies of the
American government. Relations are anything but friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's USA-Iran match in Lyon will have huge political
overtones, for sure. It figures to be one of the most watched games
of the World Cup's first round, if not the entire tournament.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. players have been saying for months that they will approach
the match only as a game and let others discuss the political
issues. After Sunday's nice effort against Yugoslavia, the Iranian
players were saying the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it will be a good game,'' said Kohodad Azizi, the
Asian soccer Player of the Year in 1997 and arguably Iran's best
player. ``We want it to be like any other game, well-played and not
looked at from a political view.''
</P>
<P>
   But Azizi later added, ``Our people are sensitive to the team
that we are playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian government will be involved in the game against the
U.S., too, whether the players like it or not. Already, Iranian
government officials reportedly have accounted for the majority of
tickets allocated to the nation for Sunday's game. Thus, there is
great demand for black-market tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Iranian soccer federation also made clear
the importance of the game recently when he announced, ``We cannot
lose to the Americans. We are better than they are, and we will not
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Azizi: ``Maybe the government says that but not the
players. We want to have fun and play a good game. We do not want
to shame ourselves or our country. But we want it to be about
soccer, not politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
