<HEADER>
A2157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERCK-MARKETPLACE-NYT     06-16 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCK-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: RUMORS ABOUND ABOUT A MERCK MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Merck &AMP; Co. is close to a $4 billion windfall that has the
pharmaceuticals industry buzzing.
</P>
<P>
   Astra AB, the Swedish drug giant, is expected to announce within
days that it is buying Merck's share of the joint venture formed by
the two companies in 1994, according to people close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, Astra-Merck, is primarily a marketing vehicle
created to sell Astra's ulcer drug, Prilosec, in the United States.
Successful though the unit has been _ last year Prilosec was the
nation's best-selling drug, with revenue of $2.3 billion _ Astra is
more interested in finding a full-fledged merger partner as the
patent for Prilosec approaches expiration.
</P>
<P>
   Haakan Mogren, Astra's chief executive, announced in March that
he wanted to merge his company, which is about a fifth the size of
Merck in market capitalization, with one of equal size. But before
starting a new relationship, he needs to split with Merck, since
their joint venture has the right to sell Astra's drugs in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Merck's next move is less certain. According to stock analysts
and others close to the deal, Astra will pay Merck about $1.5
billion up front and $12 billion more over 10 years for its 50
percent stake in the venture. In a separate deal, DuPont agreed
last month to pay Merck $2.6 billion in July for its stake in their
joint venture, DuPont Merck Pharmaceutical Co.
</P>
<P>
   So even without the billions to come in over the next decade
from Astra, Merck will soon have $4 billion in mad money.
</P>
<P>
   While theories about what it will do are about as numerous as
the pills Merck makes, Merck has said only that it is in
discussions with Astra and that it intends to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   Merck could stay the course and sink the $4 billion into
research and development, on which it spent $1.68 billion last
year. This strategy, albeit dull, would be true to the company's
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Merck, it will be business as usual,'' said Stephen Scala,
a pharmaceutical-stock analyst with Cowen &AMP; Co. ``I definitely
can't see the company making a merger or acquisition. Merck is very
insular.''
</P>
<P>
   A second theory is more intriguing. Patents on several Merck
drugs, generating $5 billion in annual revenue, will expire in 2000
and 2001, leaving the company vulnerable to generic knock-offs. The
company could use its $4 billion bounty to buy drugs still under
development and market them as its own.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of a revenue fall-off, Merck has added four
drugs this year: Propecia, for baldness; Singulair, an asthma
medication; Aggrastat for acute angina, and Cosopt, a glaucoma
drug. Maxalt, a drug for migraine headaches, is expected to be
released during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is far from convinced these five drugs will be the
sales miracle Merck predicts. CIBC Oppenheimer estimates that they
will have combined sales next year of $835 million, several billion
short of the drugs they will replace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Merck could use the money to buy back shares as
part of its buy-back program, but the company has enough cash for
that,'' said Neil Sweig, who tracks pharmaceutical stocks for
Southeast Research Partners. ``More than likely, they will buy
products from other companies and shepherd them through the Food
and Drug Administration to bolster their product pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be good news for capital-hungry biotechnology
companies with promising compounds under development.
</P>
<P>
   A third notion has the whole industry salivating. Merck, with a
Marine-like sales force, could merge with another U.S. drug
company.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Gilmartin, Merck's chief executive, is not known for
razzle-dazzle. Merck, with $23.6 billion in sales, posted an
earnings gain of 19 percent, to $4.6 billion, last year. With
numbers like that, Merck's stock should be the envy of Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   But its shares have gained 29 percent in the last 12 months,
underperforming a number of other drug makers. Lofted by Viagra,
its popular impotence pill, Pfizer has seen its share price
increase 95.3 percent in the same period. Four other drug stocks _
Warner-Lambert, Schering-Plough, Bristol-Myers Squibb and Alza
Corp. _ have all jumped more than 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. drug industry lacks a dominant player. After American
Home Products acquires Monsanto, the merged company will be the
leader, but will control only 6.9 percent of the domestic market
for prescription drugs, according to IMS Health, an industry
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Merck could create a King Kong in the industry, though it might
have to make several acquisitions to do it. Analysts mention
Johnson &AMP; Johnson as a possible merger partner for Merck, noting
they have similar shares of the U.S. prescription-drug market and
similar corporate cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the companies would have U.S. pharmaceutical sales of
$11.3 billion, nearly double that of American Home Products and
Monsanto. Johnson &AMP; Johnson, along with its popular consumer-health
products Tylenol and Neutrogena shampoo and soap, has Risperdal, an
anti-psychotic, and Propulsid, a gastrointestinal drug, each of
which is expected to generate more than $1 billion in sales
worldwide this year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this particular combination appears to be a long shot, as
does the entire merger theory. Gilmartin firmly denies that he
intends to merge, saying that he expects his company to outperform
the industry without any help.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing to note is that we don't know how Gilmartin views
the industry,'' Scala of Cowen said. ``He may believe it is going
to perform bleaker than we do. If he believes the industry will
grow mid-to-high single digits each year, then Merck could
outperform it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
