u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-HMOS-330&AMP;ADD-NY     06-16 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HMOS-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR-OWNED MANAGED CARE PLAN COLLAPSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., Pa., La., Kan., N.Y.)   (bl)  
 By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a sobering blow to the many doctors who want to recapture
control of their patients' care, the California Medical Association
is shutting down the managed care company that it and 7,500 of its
member physicians created to take on the state's big health
maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half frustrating years, three chief executives
and $11 million in losses, the CMA's managed care company,
California Advantage, will file for bankruptcy Wednesday, said
Steven Fleisher, a lawyer for the CMA. The business will be slowly
liquidated while the company's insurer fulfills the terms of its
existing contracts for patient care, some extending until next May.
</P>
<P>
   California Advantage never came close to enrolling the 10
percent of the state's population, or 3.3 million people, that its
management set as a 10-year goal early last year, or even the
40,000 it said it needed to break even. It is going out of business
with about 6,000 subscribers _ less than one for each physician
investor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a noble and worthy venture,'' said Dr. Jack Lewin, a
family practitioner who is executive vice president of the
28,000-member association. ``Everybody liked the philosophy of
putting patients first and profits second.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort failed, Lewin said, in part because doctors would not
invest enough to sustain it and because, offering subscribers easy
access to thousands of specialists throughout the state, it tended
to attract those who were the sickest and costliest to treat.
</P>
<P>
   But unrealistic expectations and poor planning were factors,
too, said Peter Boland, a health care consultant in Oakland, where
California Advantage had its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a very well intentioned and very naive strategy,''
Boland said of California Advantage's effort to go after the
state's entire market at once on an investment of just a few
million dollars. ``It's a sobering event: one of the country's
biggest medical organizations fails miserably.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alarmed at HMOs' usurping doctors' prerogatives and cutting
their fees, the medical societies of at least a dozen states, and
tens of thousands of their member physicians, have been forming
organizations like California Advantage to manage patient care.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ventures have just begun operating and are too new
to have proved themselves. One that became a prototype, MD Health
Plan, was established in Connecticut in 1986 on an investment of
$6.9 million by the Connecticut State Medical Society and 3,000
physicians.
</P>
<P>
   In time, MD Health Plan became the state's second-biggest
managed care company, with 161,000 subscribers. But in 1995 its
physician owners sold it to a conventional HMO for $101 million,
nearly 15 times the original investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physicians were criticized for being greedy,'' said
Timothy Norbeck, executive director of the State Medical Society.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason for the sale, Norbeck said, was a shortage of
capital _ $10 million to $30 million _ that he said MD Health Plan
had needed to expand and remain competitive with the big HMOs then
crowding into the state.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, insufficient capital was a factor in the demise
of California Advantage. The California Medical Association created
the organization in January 1996 with $7.5 million: $1,000 from
each of 7,500 physician investors. CMA officials say in hindsight
that this was half of what they needed, and some experts say that
even that may be an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Gary Brown, chairman of a similar organization in
Pennsylvania that began enrolling members late last year, said
4,000 physicians had invested $5,500 each, or $22 million.
Investing a third as much, the California doctors tried to tackle a
much larger state.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate for more money as the shortage became apparent, the
California Medical Association hit a wall of indifference among its
member physicians, many of whom worked for HMO competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you invest $1,000?'' Dr. Robert Reid, the association's
president, asked in letters to the 35,000 active and retired
members.
</P>
<P>
   The request was largely futile. ``We had only 2,000 responses to
that,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   The association also turned to big corporate investors, but it
did not want to sell a majority interest in the plan and yield
physician control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't find one that would come in with a minority
interest,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   There were other blows. Early last year, for example, California
Advantage began competing against a score of managed care
organizations for the state-sponsored pooled coverage of
small-business employees. Offering easier access to specialists
than most HMOs, it succeeded in capturing about 6,500 subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   But those subscribers were generally older and sicker than
others, and their premiums did not cover the cost of their care.
Within a few months, the plan's insurance company, which was liable
for the added cost, terminated its policy, and California Advantage
dropped out of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians in other states, including Pennsylvania, Louisiana
and Kansas, are investing more in new doctor-owned plans than the
California doctors did, and face less acute competition from
established HMOs. So their medical societies expect better luck.
</P>
<P>
   But physicians of another big state, New York, have decided that
the stakes are too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told we would have to raise on the order of $60
million to create an HMO,'' said Dr. Charles Aswad, chief executive
of the State Medical Society. ``That makes it a bit too risky for
physicians to get into.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
