<SLUG> BC-BORDER-CROSSING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., MEXICO ANNOUNCES PLAN TO RESCUE ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS FROM
DANGER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Acknowledging that illegal immigrants are risking
their lives to get across the border, U.S. and Mexican officials
Tuesday announced a plan to steer illegals away from danger, rescue
them if they get into trouble and better identify them in case of
death.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, said Immigration and Naturalization Service
Commissioner Doris Meissner, speaking in Washington, D.C., ``will
enable us to work together with the Mexican government to make the
border safer for both migrants and law enforcement officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement comes at a time of record-high
temperatures in Texas, the kind of heat that contributed to the
deaths nearly 1,200 illegal immigrants between 1993 and 1996,
according to a University of Houston study released last summer.
More than 800 of those perished along the Texas-Mexico border.
</P>
<P>
   Four areas will be given immediate attention, including Kenedy
County in South Texas, a stretch of heavily traveled brush country
that has proved deadly to immigrants in recent years. Two perilous
crossing spots were identified in Southern California and one in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it is the INS crackdown along the U.S.-Mexico border
that in large part has caused the problem U.S. officials now seek
to address. More manpower, from Brownsville to San Diego, Calif.,
has forced illegal immigrants to seek alternative, often unsafe
routes.
</P>
<P>
   The UH study found that two-thirds of the victims drowned, most
in the Tijuana River and the Rio Grande. But stretches of desert
and brush country such as the terrain found in Kenedy County have
been plenty inhospitable. Two years ago, 19 people died of exposure
there trying to evade a Border Patrol checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   While Mexican officials have criticized the United States for
initiatives such as Operation Rio Grande, which provides more
border enforcement in South Texas, ambassador to the United States
Jesus Reyes-Heroles said the latest effort will ``protect the
rights and safety of immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activists, who only weeks ago criticized the INS
amid an Amnesty International report that accused the agency of
sexually assaulting migrants and denying them medical treatment,
were generally supportive. Still, some remained wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement sounds nice coming from Washington, D.C.,''
said Nicholas Rizza, national refugee coordinator for Amnesty
International. ``But often, these things don't translate in the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   Though certain border locales have previously launched public
service efforts to discourage illegal immigrants from swimming
dangerous channels or trekking vast deserts, Tuesday's announcement
is the first bi-national effort and the first one to be coordinated
from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to naming a border safety coordinator, the INS
intends to use the Civil Air Patrol to fly over the unforgiving
stretches of California, Arizona and Texas where immigrants
sometimes cross. The agency will also install lights along the All
American Canal near El Centro, Calif., where so far this year 27
immigrants have drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Border Patrol intends to train its agents in land
and water rescue and stock its trademark vehicles with drinking
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``This effort will enable us to make the protection of human
life the highest priority of our border activities,'' said Gus de
la Vina, chief of the U.S. Border Patrol. He added that the
initiative will make safety a priority for law enforcement officers
as well.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Mexico intends to set up a toll-free hot line for
its citizens who fear their friends or relatives might have
encountered danger crossing the border. Hot line officials would
then contact U.S. authorities.
</P>
<P>
   As dangerous as rivers and deserts can be, unscrupulous
smugglers are often the biggest problem facing illegal immigrants.
Recognizing this, Mexico has posted warnings at heavily trafficked
areas along the international boundary.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is offering up to $5,000 for information
leading to the arrest and indictment of traffickers who steer their
clients around checkpoints such as the one in Kenedy County along
U.S. 77 and into dangerous terrain, such as the area where the 19
people died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since last October in the McAllen, Texas, sector, the Border
Patrol reports 21 immigrant deaths, mostly from drowning and
dehydration, and more than 100 rescues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these people are women and children,'' said Joe Garza,
chief of the McAllen Border Patrol sector. ``They're not equipped
to be in the brush. They're not in condition.''
</P>
<P>
   The identities of illegal immigrants who perish along the border
have long been a source of mystery for U.S. authorities, who
sometimes bury them in anonymous graves. But U.S. and Mexican
officials Tuesday agreed to cooperate in trying to identify the
dead and notify their families.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
