<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Speed techniques of Seagrave keep players on, and off, toes
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The Falcons have hired Loren Seagrave's Atlanta-based
company, Speed Dynamics, in an effort to improve the team's speed.
</P>
<P>
   Seagrave has worked with some of track's best athletes,
including 1996 Olympic 100-meter gold medalist and world
record-holder Donovan Bailey of Canada and sprinters Ben Johnson,
Andre Cason, Gwen Torrence and Sandra Farmer-Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   Seagrave and his wife, former world-class 400-meter hurdler
Kathy Freeman Seagrave, teach running technique and use a variety
of methods to improve speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, coaches have been saying run on your toes; athletes
interpret that to mean point your toes (down),'' Seagrave said.
``If you can point your toes up (as the foot strides forward), then
you can cock your ankle, and it serves more as a spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reprogramming their nervous systems to take the strength
they get in the weight room and apply it more efficiently.''
</P>
<P>
   Seagrave began working with the Falcons 14 weeks ago. He'll be
on board at least through training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a half-step, maybe a full step faster,'' wide receiver
Terance Mathis said. ``We're learning to get our feet under us for
more explosion. It's helped me.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   First-round draft choice Keith Brooking made his first
appearance at passing camp and recovered a fumble from rookie
running back Ken Oxendine on his first play of 11-on-11 drills.
Brooking was working at weakside linebacker. ... Jeff Hullinger and
Jeff Van Note, who will be the radio voices of the Falcons on 640
AM and 105.7 FM, were at practice. ... Fullback Bob Christian
practiced a little for the first time since Thursday's knee injury.
Receiver Todd Kinchen (back muscle) missed his second straight
practice. ... Falcons president Taylor Smith and head coach Dan
Reeves, who also holds the title of executive vice president of
football operations, were involved in meetings Tuesday morning with
another group of developers. They will meet with more developers
today. Team officials are listening to ideas on how to proceed with
the Falcon Inn Motel, which will close on Sept. 1, and about 15
acres around it. Ultimately, the decision could affect next year's
training camp. A one-year move might be necessary if there is
construction on the grounds. Several possible scenarios include the
sale of the motel and surrounding property. No decision is
imminent, however, as the family of late Falcons owner Rankin Smith
awaits the appraisal of his Suwanee property. That's not expected
for a few weeks. ... Local free agents dot the roster. Wide
receiver Corey Allen of Georgia said, ``So far, it's pretty much
what I expected, except there's no way you could be prepared for
all this running (in post-practice conditioning).'' Valdosta State
defensive end Richard ``Schad'' Freeman, who had 14 sacks and 71
tackles last season, has been working with the linebackers.
Freeman's former college teammate, safety Brad Trout, has been
practicing with deep snappers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
