<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notes
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheely
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traditional cart for Martin
</P>
<P>
   Because of handling difficulties and safety concerns with the
one-seater vehicle that Casey Martin had been experimenting with in
U.S. Open practice rounds, the USGA decided Tuesday to allow him
use of a traditional golf cart through the conclusion of the
tournament. He may drive the cart on the fairway, the same as the
one-seater. ``I'm not going to be doing curly-Q's in the rough or
anything,'' Martin said. ``Although I'd like to mat it down a
little.'' During a practice round Monday, two varieties of the
smaller, lighter cart broke down and were ineffective on slopes of
the Olympic Club. ``I think the single-rider cart is the right idea
, but I don't think it's there yet,'' said Martin, who suffers from
a circulatory disease in his right leg and won a lawsuit for the
right to ride in competition. ``I'm excited that we're going with
the regular cart. (The one-seater cart) was definitely a (safety)
issue on severe terrain.'' ... Martin not only hung in there
Tuesday during a practice round with his former Stanford teammate,
Tiger Woods, he won 12 skins to Woods' six. ``Yeah, I was taken for
some cash today,'' Woods admitted. Joking on the range afterward,
Martin said, ``Tiger didn't know what hit him. Now he says I've got
an advantage (with a cart) since I beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Par could be a good score
</P>
<P>
   Scott Simpson, the 1987 champion at Olympic, said he would take
3-under par again for 72 holes and be quite thankful. Tom Watson is
predicting that the winning score in the U.S. Open, where par is
70, will be over that. Defending champion Ernie Els won't go that
far, but suggests that maybe 4 or 5 under will win. Said Watson,
who finished a stroke behind Simpson in 1987, ``It's going to be
difficult to shoot around par here.'' The main reason? Watson said
Olympic's rough, which is grotesquely thick and up to seven inches
long, is ``the most difficult I've ever seen in a U.S. Open. ...
When you hit the ball in the rough at Colonial (where Watson won
last month), you could still get the ball on the green. You hit the
ball in the rough here, you're lucky to move it 50 or 60 yards.''
Chipping or flopping from the heavy stuff, Watson generally is
recognized as the best in the world, and he's not hoping for
anything closer than a 15-foot putt.
</P>
<P>
   From across the pond
</P>
<P>
   England's Lee Westwood, who won at New Orleans on the PGA Tour
this spring, and Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, are Europe's top
U.S. Open contenders. It's an annual occurrence for Montgomerie,
who has come close three times and failed. It's the first serious
contention for Westwood, 25, after back-to-back wins on the
European Tour earlier this year. ``I think the way I'm playing, if
I play well this week, then I can win it,'' he said. ... Atlanta's
Danny Yates, 48, has been named captain of the 1999 U.S. Walker Cup
in matches against Great Britain and Ireland on Sept. 11-12. ``I'd
hoped if I lived long enough something like this would happen one
day,'' said Yates, who plays out of Atlanta's Peachtree Golf Club.
``This is such a humbling honor when I think about the people who
have been captain in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
