<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAPORTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGI names Gittens its regional director
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Angela Gittens has landed on her feet.
</P>
<P>
   The former general manager of Hartsfield International Airport,
who was ousted by Mayor Bill Campbell when he chose not to
reappoint her, is joining Airport Group International as its
regional director of North America. She will be based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   AGI, known until 1995 as Lockheed Air Terminal, performs airport
services for airlines, such as fueling, ground handling and cargo
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This achieves several things,'' said Gittens, whose departure
sparked criticism of the mayor's office. ``I get to stay in the
business, I get to stay in Atlanta and I also can get involved in
an early trend in the corporatization of airports.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, AGI has been buying airports internationally as part
of a privatization trend. It owns five airports in Australia, three
in Bolivia and soon one in London. In the United States, AGI
manages several airports including those in Columbus, Ohio; Albany,
N.Y.; and Burbank, Calif. AGI's major competitor worldwide is the
British Airports Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Bullock, AGI's senior vice president of operations, said
Gittens was hired as part of a company effort to recruit top
aviation managers. He got to know Gittens when he was executive
director of the Orlando airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angela has significant leadership experience at two of the
largest and best-run airports in the country, Atlanta and San
Francisco,'' he said. ``She is extremely well-respected in the
industry, and she has tremendous interpersonal skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Gittens said her management will exclude Atlanta for one year. A
city ordinance prevents former employees from doing business with
the city for a year. Once that year is up, she said her
jurisdiction would include Hartsfield, where AGI has several
contracts to run two ramp control towers and provide ground
services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
