<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USOPEN-FEATURE-COX     06-16 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPEN-FEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aching back holds Els back
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Ernie Els is known for making it all look so
easy. The swing is long and graceful and repeats so effortlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Throw out all those observations this week. Instead of peaking
into the U.S Open as defending champion, Els is creaking. Lower
back spasms that pushed him out of the Buick Classic last week have
clouded his status for the Olympic Club. The affable South African
might contend. He might convulse. Each day is unsettled. He
slouches slightly in an interview room chair, admitting that
sitting is the worst part and, sorry, but the discussion might have
to be brief.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, he's miserable. After playing a practice round
Tuesday _ his first 18 holes since the previous Tuesday _ Els could
not hit balls for fear of inflaming his lower back. He has gone
from contender to question mark, and it's killing him to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's the wrong timing for me to get this kind of
injury,'' Els said.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the parade of players who have sought treatment from
Columbus physical therapist Tom Boers, Els is in less pain than
last week, when the left side of his lower back ``kind of seized up
a little and went into spasm,'' but hardly able to play with his
normal confidence. Boers put him on a strengthening and exercise
program similar to those of his other patients, Davis Love III and
Fred Couples. Now it's wait-and-watch and hopefully not wince.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the healing process now,'' Els said. ``I know I have
the right guy working on it, and if I can just get through the next
couple of weeks without doing too much damage to it, I'll be all
right. ... Last Thursday I could barely swing through the ball.
Today I could feel it, but the pain was a lot less.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully for Els, this is Olympic and not Oakland Hills.
Although monster-length holes exist, like the 609-yard, par-5 16th
and the 468-yard, par-4 17th, long hitters such as Els will use a
driver on perhaps five holes. Els is hoping that being able to hit
long irons on several occasions off the tee might reduce his
chances of reinjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to put the ball in play and take it from there,''
he said, ``and it might work to my advantage, you never know.
Beware of injured golfers, as they say sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, who travels worldwide as much as anyone in golf, might have
to reduce his schedule beyond the majors. Fitting his 6-foot-3 body
into an airplane seat is hardly ideal for his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom said it's from traveling,'' Els said. ``The golf swing
isn't all that bad for you if you don't overwork it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
