<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-ANALYSIS-BOS     06-16 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL OUTCOME ERASED LEGAL ERRORS IN WOODWARD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG   AND JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It wasn't pretty and mistakes were made, but the trial
of Louise Woodward ultimately ended with a decision that was
legally justified, Massachusetts' highest court ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court's 46-page decision is a dissertation
on what went wrong with the trial, but in the final analysis the
justices determined that any errors of law were rendered harmless
by the final outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court correctly evaluated a case where there was plenty of
error to go around,'' said Boston lawyer Morris Goldings. ``The
system has a way of correcting its own errors, sometimes
fitfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The SJC said Superior Court Judge Hiller Zobel erred when he
granted a defense request that the jury be barred from considering
the less serious charge of manslaughter. The jury found Woodward
guilty of second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Zobel, the high court ruled, was able to right his own wrong by
later reducing the jury verdict to manslaughter _ which the SJC
suggested was the appropriate verdict because there was no evidence
of prior abuse by Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there was no evidence in this case of repeated caretaker
abuse, the judge did not abuse his discretion in concluding that
the jury verdict of murder was not proportionate with convictions
in other cases,'' Justice Margaret H. Marshall wrote for the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Woodward and her lawyers last year to ask Zobel
to prevent the jury from considering the manslaughter option was a
moment of high legal drama.
</P>
<P>
   That so-called ``all or nothing strategy'' was based on the
belief the prosecution didn't present enough evidence to warrant a
murder conviction. Without the manslaughter option, the defense
gambled that the jury would be forced to return a not guilty
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC, however, said it has historically ``declined to
penalize defendants who adopt an all-or-nothing strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, one of Woodward's lawyers Tuesday said he would
reconsider the strategy if given a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We engaged in a strategy that resulted in conviction of
second-degree murder,'' said Harvey Silverglate. ``If you ask me,
`Would I do it the same way again?' I would have to have my head
examined, wouldn't I? ... I doubt very much we would do it the same
way again.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the SJC determined that the manslaughter conviction was
appropriate, the court made it clear it was not exonerating
Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not view the judgment against Woodward as a light
matter,'' Marshall wrote. ``She stands guilty of causing an
infant's violent death. The outcome of this criminal trial most
assuredly was not an acquittal.''
</P>
<P>
   The SJC decision also was seen as a strong endorsement of the
broad and powerful discretion given to trial judges in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A trial judge has lots of discretion to basically do the right
thing,'' said Boston College Law School professor Robert Bloom, who
wrote ``Constitutional Criminal Procedure.'' ``The judge has a
responsibility in every criminal case, regardless of the jury's
decision, to seek justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, challenges to cases in which a judge reduces a verdict
in Massachusetts are rare. Since 1979, 10 reductions were appealed
and seven of those were upheld.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC decision Tuesday was not without its detractors,
including three of the court's seven justices who issued a
dissenting opinion on whether or not the sentence for Woodward was
too lenient. Zobel sentenced Woodward to the 279 days she had
already spent in prison awaiting the outcome of her trial.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John M. Greaney, writing for the dissenters, said Zobel
moved too quickly to sentence Woodward after throwing out the
jury's verdict, ``resulting in a sense of unease that permeated the
proceedings that followed.''
</P>
<P>
   The dissenters also concluded it appeared that Zobel
``identified himself with Woodward's cause, compromising the
public's confidence in the integrity and impartiality of our
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William H. Doherty of the Globe staff contributed to this
article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
