<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: U S AIRWAYS CUTS FARES; FAXING BETWEEN FLIGHTS;
TRAVEL-AGENCY FEES; AIRPORT VAN SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Ohio, Fla., N.H., R.I., Wash., Ga., N.J.)  (Eds: Also moved in ``t'' category.) 
(lb) 
 By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the introduction earlier this month of Metro Jet, a
low-fare service, U S Airways is trying to beat Southwest Airlines
at its own game. Metro Jet is competing with Southwest on routes
between Baltimore and four cities: Cleveland; Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.; Manchester, N.H., and Providence, R.I. None of the routes
overlap with U S Airways' regular service.
</P>
<P>
   A ticket on Metro Jet between Baltimore and Fort Lauderdale
starts at $163 one way with no restrictions, or $194 round trip
with a seven-day advance purchase and one-day stay. There are
several flights daily on each route.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, not surprisingly, expressed some skepticism about the
venture. ``We have one of the lowest cost structures in the
industry, and US Airways has one of the highest,'' said Linda
Rutherford, a spokeswoman for the airline. ``It will be interesting
to watch how successful the airline is at not only providing the
service but also remaining profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 6, Metro Jet plans to add flights between Baltimore and
Miami, Tampa-St. Petersburg, Fla., and Jacksonville, Fla. On Aug.
3, Orlando, Fla., is scheduled to follow. The all-coach flights use
Boeing 737-200s, with seat assignments made on the day of
departure.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers who are members of U S Airways' frequent-flier
program will get one free round-trip Metro Jet ticket when they
take eight round-trip or 16 one-way Metro Jet flights, in addition
to earning miles. Those who do not want the free ticket can get
double miles instead. U S Airways expects to have 20 planes
dedicated to the service by the end of the year and 54 by the end
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Faxing Between Flights
</P>
<P>
   Laptop Lane, a new company operating office centers at airports,
is preparing to open at Seattle-Tacoma Airport on June 25. SEA-TAC
is the second location for the Seattle-based company. The first, at
Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport, opened in May,
and an Atlanta center is planned for this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Open daily from 6 a.m. to 10 p.m., the centers contain private,
individual offices, each equipped with a Micron desktop computer;
connections for a traveler's laptop; access to a high-speed
Internet line; a laser printer; a plain-paper fax machine, and a
multiline phone.
</P>
<P>
   Each office has a glass door that can be locked. The cost is
$8.95 a half-hour, with extra fees for long-distance calls or
long-distance faxes. (Local calls and faxes are free.) Additional
services, for a charge, include black-and-white or color copying
and a color laser printer. For now, the service is on a first-come,
first-served basis.
</P>
<P>
   Travel-Agency Fees
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of member agencies responding to a recent
survey by the American Society of Travel Agents are now charging
fees for their services. In a 1995 survey, the ratio was just 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most (84 percent) of the agents charging fees said they began
doing so after the major airlines cut their commissions last fall.
Some of the services for which fees are most often charged are
transactions involving special coupons and promotions; refunds or
exchanges; issue of at least some airline tickets; cancellations,
and trip planning or research. Of the agencies charging service
fees for airline tickets, the average fee is $10.37.
</P>
<P>
   Though the society did not break down the survey results by
agency clientele, James Ashurst, a spokesman for the American
Society of Travel Agents, said the organization believed the survey
reflected the average member agency, for which business travelers
make up 30 percent to 40 percent of sales. Smaller agencies are
less likely to charge fees _ 53 percent of those with sales under
$1 million said they did so, compared with 68 percent of those with
sales of $1 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Door to Terminal Door
</P>
<P>
   Super Shuttle, the door-to-door van service that began carrying
passengers last month on shared rides in New York between Manhattan
and Kennedy International Airport and La Guardia Airport, plans to
start serving Newark International Airport in New Jersey on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company's seven-passenger vans pick up and drop off
passengers between 23rd and 126th streets in New York City. Average
fares are $14 to La Guardia, $15 to Kennedy and $17 to Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix-based company serves more than a dozen other regions
around the United States, including Los Angeles, San Francisco,
Dallas-Fort Worth, Denver and Philadelphia. The toll-free
reservation number is (800) 258-3826.
</P>
<P>
   Super Shuttle says pick-up requests need to be made at least
three hours in advance. No reservations are taken for airport
arrivals; passengers go to the ground transportation desk and catch
the next available van.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0358 </DOCNO>
