<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2179 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-1STL     06-16 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC-1STLD-WRITETHRU-410&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV LEADER MAKES CONCESSIONS ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (subs to expand 5th graf)  (Eds.: budgeted earlier as BOSNIA-MILOSEVIC; see also KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(BL) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic promised
Tuesday to make a series of concessions over Kosovo to forestall
military action by the West. But he stopped short of meeting one
key demand: the withdrawal of Serbian security forces accused of
attacking ethnic Albanians in the province.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of closed-door meetings here with top Russian
officials, the Yugoslav leader announced his promises _ including
access for relief groups and international monitors as well as
arrangements for refugees to return _ in a joint statement with
President Boris Yelstin.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials, who are also eager to head off NATO air
strikes, were quick to cast Milosevic's promises as an important
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from clear, however, whether Milosevic's pledges were
merely tactical or whether he was genuinely prepared to ease the
repression in Kosovo, whose population is predominantly ethnic
Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said that Milosevic had only met NATO part
way. Western diplomats at NATO headquarters said the alliance was
continuing to work on military options. But the threat of military
action has, in effect, been deferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some progress,'' Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said. But she added that that Milosevic ``did not meet the
primary points that the Contact Group raised.'' Western diplomats
at NATO headquarters said that the alliance was continuing to work
on military options. But the threat of military action has, in
effect, been deferred. The Contact Group, which monitors events in
the Balkans, includes Britain, Germany, France and Italy as well as
the United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In a defiant press conference in an ornate Russian Foreign
Ministry mansion, Milosevic denied that Serbian forces had ever
harmed ethnic Albanians. ``There was no kind of ethnic cleansing,''
Milosevic said. ``In the latest actions it was declared by the
security forces there were no civilian victims at all.''
</P>
<P>
   International observers have painted a very different picture.
They say that at least 250 ethnic Albanians have been killed in the
fighting and at least 65,000 have been forced to abandon their
homes in the separatist province.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan has condemned the Serbian
crackdown as ``ethnically driven violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's talks took place a day after NATO conducted air
exercises over the Balkans in an effort to pressure him to end the
crackdown in Kosovo.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He met with Yeltsin on Tuesday and then engaged in several hours
of talks with Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov, Defense Minister
Igor Sergeyev and other top Russian aides as the two sides sought
to cobble together a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Kosovo crisis, the Kremlin has had conflicting
motivations.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, Yeltsin has an interest in maintaining good
relations with the West, especially since Moscow wants billions of
dollars in Western loans to help overcome its financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian officials also acknowledge that Milosevic has gone
too far in Kosovo. Primakov, for example, went along last week with
the demand by his fellow foreign ministers in the so-called
``Contact Group'' on the Balkans who insisted that Milosevic
withdraw security forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russians see solidarity with their fellow Slavs in
Yugoslavia as a useful card to play in Russian domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians also believe that Milosevic is defending an
important principle when he says that he is entitled to take firm
steps to insure that Kosovo remains part of Serbia. Russia has its
own regions of ethnic tension and is not eager to invite
international scrutiny or intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Primakov enjoys playing a pivotal role in world affairs
and is no friend of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   NATO countries have threatened measures including military
intervention if Milosevic does not stop the Serbian offensive
against ethnic Albanians. And the newspaper Izvestiya bluntly
outlined one of the main purposes of Tuesday's meeting: ``Russia is
trying to save the Serbs from NATO bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   After a day of lengthy negotiations, Primakov claimed a major
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this opens up a real possibility to resolve the
situation,'' Primakov said at a joint news conference with
Milosevic. ``In many ways, the ball is now in the court of the
Kosovo Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Western officials will be monitoring the situation in Kosovo for
the next several weeks to see if the Serbs keep their promises.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has, in fact, promised to take some noteworthy steps.
In the joint statement, he agreed there would be no restrictions on
the work of international organizations, such as the International
Committee of the Red Cross, or on international monitors. And he
promised to allow refugees who had fled Kosovo to return.
</P>
<P>
   He also agreed to continue talks with ethnic Albanians on
``forms of autonomy,'' though he spurned the idea of doing so with
the help of international mediators. Western officials are worried
that any talks will stall without international supervision.
</P>
<P>
   The Western-dominated ``Contact Group'' had demanded that
Milosevic recall intelligence and army units sent to Kosovo for the
crackdown. Security forces inside Kosovo, they insisted, should be
confined to their bases.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, however, Milosevic refused to take the initiative and
instead put the onus on the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``As terrorist activities subside, security forces will reduce
their presence outside the areas of their permanent deployment,''
Milosevic's joint statement with Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees crossing into Albania from Kosovo on Tuesday reported
attacks on mountain refugee camps by Yugoslav army helicopters, but
there was no independent confirmation of those reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav president told reporters Tuesday that his position
was intended to protect the principle of Serbian sovereignty over
the Kosovo region. He revoked Kosovo's autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no reasons or grounds for the Yugoslav army not to
be on the territory of Yugoslavia,'' Milosevic said. ``Any
withdrawal of units of the Yugoslav army from any part of
Yugoslavia is out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's statement also showed some of the contradictions in
the Russian stance.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov, who sat at Milosevic's side throughout the press
conference, joined the ``Contact Group's'' call for the withdrawal
of Serbian security forces. But the Russian foreign minister then
endorsed the far weaker measure Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic seemed to enjoy his verbal jousts with the press
Tuesday. To the obvious discomfort of his Russian hosts, he
occasionally lapsed into English to respond to Western reporters.
</P>
<P>
   When Western reporters pressed Milosevic about the violence in
Kosovo, he shot back that Albanian ``terrorist groups'' had
launched reprisals against ethnic Albanians who refused to support
them.
</P>
<P>
   As Milosevic ended his remarks, Primakov cut off the session,
reminding the Yugoslav president that he was late for a visit with
the patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic seemed ready for another round of sparring and
wrapped up the news conference with an invitation to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, next time, if you want longer talks, you
come to Belgrade,'' Milosevic said. ``You are invited, all of
you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
