A2193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NETWORKS-AD-COLUMN     06-16 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NETWORKS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NETWORKS EXULT OVER FLAT SALES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That loud sound you may have heard in recent days was
a collective sigh emanating from the top executives of the four
major broadcast television networks, who have been able to sell
about as much advance commercial time for the 1998-99 prime-time
season as they did for 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Four _ ABC, CBS, Fox and NBC _ have sold an estimated
$6.05 billion to $6.1 billion worth of commercial time during the
up-front market, so called because the time is peddled to
advertisers before a season begins. That compares with $6 billion
to $6.05 billion sold ahead of the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   And if the definition of broadcast TV is expanded to include the
two new ``weblets'' _ the UPN and the WB _ the up-front market rose
to approximately $6.4 billion to $6.5 billion, compared with $6.25
billion to $6.3 billion in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a year where everybody walked away from the table
happy,'' said Paul Schulman, president of the Paul Schulman Company
division of Advanswers Media Programming in New York, a unit of
Omnicom Group that buys broadcast TV time for marketers. ``It was a
good up-front for all.''
</P>
<P>
   In many industries, of course, flattish sales would be cause for
concern rather than celebration. But broadcast television, besieged
by viewer defections and beset by competition from cable networks
and even the Internet, is happy to have won by not losing, escaping
the steep declines that had been forecast before the start of the
up-front selling period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much better story for the network business than we had
thought,'' said Joseph Abruzzese, president for network sales at
the CBS unit of CBS Corp. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``To keep the money in network television after a banner year
last year is important,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Nesvig, president for sales at the Fox Broadcasting Co. unit
of the News Corp. in New York, had a one-word response when asked
his feelings about how broadcasters fared in the up-front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phew!'' he said, laughing, then continued: ``Maybe we
shouldn't be breaking out the party hats and the champagne. We're
all looking for ways to improve our business. But given what's
happening, the erosion in audiences, it's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Agency media executives, who face Abruzzese, Nesvig and their
counterparts across the negotiating table, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the networks would have liked to have seen better
numbers because neutral is not generally where you want to stay,''
said Michael Kassan, president and chief operating officer at the
Western International Media unit of the Interpublic Group of
Companies in Los Angeles, a significant buyer of TV time. ``But
it's better than reverse.''
</P>
<P>
   And given the myriad difficulties confronted by broadcast TV,
said Steve Sternberg, senior partner at TN Media in New York, a
unit of True North Communications, ``stability equals growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the up-front market began, there had been widespread
predictions _ many from agency media executives hoping to jawbone
prices lower _ that sales would decline significantly from 1997-98,
perhaps by as much as $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into this marketplace, the broadcast networks were
supposed to be hit with a major correction,'' said Joe Mandese,
editor of The Myers Report, a media newsletter. ``But it didn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcing the perception that broadcasters would suffer was
the strength of demand for commercial time on the cable networks,
whose up-front market continues this week. Mandese is projecting
that cable will have ``its greatest up-front sales season ever,''
racking up as much as $2.7 billion, a gain of 15 to 20 percent from
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   That cable boom is fueled in part by sophisticated new
computerized media plans, known as optimizers, used by agencies and
media services to buy TV time more efficiently and effectively. The
conventional wisdom was that the optimization process would draw ad
dollars from the broadcast networks to cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Optimizers gave buyers a slight edge in the negotiations this
year,'' said Kassan of Western. ``But at the end of the day, they
helped the broadcast networks demonstrate that they still have the
biggest reach of any media.''
</P>
<P>
   So if TV is good, to quote the slogan used last season by ABC,
broadcast TV may not be so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates are that ABC, a unit of the Walt Disney Co., sold
about $1.5 billion in the 1998-99 up-front market, on par with last
season despite the network ending 1997-98 with the largest ratings
falloff of any major broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' sales totaled about $1.2 billion to $1.25 billion, roughly
even with last year _ also a good showing given CBS's problems with
developing hits to attract younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the stage set for a good scatter,'' Abruzzese said,
referring to the sale of commercial time that occurs during the
season, and ``there are huge opportunities in the fourth quarter''
as CBS resumes broadcasting National Football League games and its
coming prime-time schedule is promoted far more prominently to male
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   NBC, the General Electric Co. unit that sold the most commercial
time in the 1997-98 up-front market, repeated that feat for 1998-99
with a total of $2.15 billion, compared with $2.1 billion last
season. Sternberg of TN Media predicted that the NBC drama ``E.R.''
may be the only series during the 1998-99 season to get a 30 share
in the Nielsen ratings _ that is, 30 percent of the TV sets in use
when ``E.R.'' is on will be tuned to ``E.R.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox sold $1.15 billion in the up-front market versus $1.1
billion in the up-front last season. Fox finished the 1997-98
season behind only NBC in ratings among viewers ages 18 to 49, the
demographic group most prized by advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The best showing in the 1998-99 up-front was made by the WB,
owned by Time Warner Inc. and the Tribune Co. Thanks to the ability
of WB hits like ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Dawson's Creek''
to appeal to teen-age viewers _ ``an audience that's hard to reach
everywhere else,'' Sternberg said _ WB sold $250 million to $300
million in commercial time for the coming season, compared with
$125 million to $150 million last season.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates for the UPN, a unit of Viacom Inc., varied the most
for any network, ranging from a low of $100 million to a high of
$180 million. UPN is overhauling its schedule for 1998-99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
