<HEADLINE>
RULING DISMAYS WOODWARD JURORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Jurors who served on the Louise Woodward case expressed
bitterness and frustration about a Supreme Judicial Court decision
Tuesday which upheld a reduced verdict and sentence for the former
British au pair.
</P>
<P>
   One juror, who says she has received dozens of threats from all
over the country, asked not to be identified, but read a statement,
expressing her anger toward the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A jury of 12 individuals, of whom I was one, found Louise
Woodward directly and solely responsible for the death of
8-month-old Matthew Eappen on Feb. 4, 1997,'' she said. ``I am
repulsed by the many people, Judge Hiller Zobel included, who were
more concerned with the prospect of Ms. Woodward's temporary loss
of freedom, than they were with an innocent baby's loss of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The juror would later say during a telephone interview that
``nothing about this case makes me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   During Woodward's trial last year, the defense instructed the
12-person jury to either find Woodward guilty of first- or
second-degree murder and not to consider manslaughter, believing
jurors would be hard-pressed to find the then 18-year-old guilty.
But the jury came back with a guilty verdict, sending shockwaves
around two continents.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Zobel reduced the jury's second-degree murder
conviction to manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Colwell, another juror in the case, said he still
strongly believes Woodward is guilty of the child's death but feels
comfortable that the Supreme Judicial Court in its opinion upheld
her guilt and responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the punishment may be less than what she deserved,'' he
said. ``The fact that she only spent 279 days (in jail), in my
opinion, is not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   One alternate juror, who also asked not to be identified, said
he was happy with Tuesday's decision and always thought jurors made
the wrong decision in convicting Woodward of murder.
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the alternates, who he described as
analytical-minded people _ some engineers and one attorney, would
have fought for a not guilty verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Alternates were designated after all the testimony and before
the start of deliberations. ``There was a lot of pressure,'' he
said. ``I will never, and I mean never, serve on a jury again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
