<SLUG> BC-KOREA-MISSILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA SAYS IT WILL CONTINUE TO DEVELOP AND EXPORT MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ North Korea declared Tuesday that it would continue to
develop missiles and sell them abroad, rejecting U.S. suggestions
that it curb its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue developing, testing and deploying missiles,''
the official Korean Central News Agency said in a dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Japan and other countries have long been
concerned by the North Korean missile program. North Korean
missiles deployed at home can already strike much of Japan, and
officials say the recent Indian and Pakistani nuclear tests have
highlighted the risks of the spread of missiles that might be
fitted to carry nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and South Korean officials are scheduled to meet next month
to discuss proposals to ease the economic embargo against the
Communist government of North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea has urged that the
American sanctions be lifted. But the United States has been
cautious and has hinted that one criterion for easing sanctions
might be a North Korean willingness to curtail its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday North Korea rejected that idea, saying that it might
freeze its program, but only after the United States had lifted the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States really wants to prevent our missile
export,'' the news agency said, ``it should lift the economic
embargo as early as possible and make a compensation for the losses
to be caused by discontinued missile export.''
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to be its most public acknowledgment of its
willingness to export missiles, the agency added, ``Our missile
export is aimed at obtaining foreign money we need at present.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea said that its missiles were defensive, intended to
protect the country from U.S. missiles, and that because of the
embargo it has few ways of earning currency other than exporting
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Rodong missiles developed by North Korea are similar to the
Soviet Scuds and can apparently reach much of Japan, although
probably not Tokyo, and could in theory carry a nuclear warhead,
military experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Western experts disagree about whether the missiles are accurate
enough to pose much of a military threat. But Japanese civilians
are not much reassured by the possibility that the missiles might
miss the military bases that they are presumably aimed at.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has also been developing a missile, the Taepodong,
that would have a much greater range, of 2,000 to 3,000 miles. But
some experts said they believed the missile would need years of
development before it could be deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has held periodic talks with North Korea,
trying to work out an agreement under which the North would curb
its missiles program. But the talks have not proceeded very far,
and some diplomats said the North would be willing to give up the
program only for a far greater economic and diplomatic price than
Washington is willing to pay. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
