<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2200 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBERALS-SOCSEC-475&AMP;A     06-16 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERALS-SOCSEC-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERALS SCRAMBLE TO COUNTER PRIVATIZATION OF SOCIAL SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Concerned that conservatives and Wall Street are
winning the ideological battle over Social Security's future,
liberal Democrats, unions and left-leaning interest groups are
scrambling to reverse the momentum toward the adoption of private
investment accounts and come up with politically appealing
proposals of their own.
</P>
<P>
   No longer able to assume that Social Security is so sacrosanct
that to fiddle with it would be political suicide, Democrats and
liberal advocacy groups said they intended to offer detailed
alternatives and become more aggressive in pointing out the risks
and drawbacks of moving from a collective to a more individualized
system.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and Rep. Earl
Pomeroy of North Dakota, among others, are drafting legislation
intended to address Social Security's long-term financing problems
without resorting to private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Pomeroy, who has been designated by the House Democratic
leadership to develop their position, has settled on a plan that
would allow the Social Security system itself to invest in the
markets, allowing beneficiaries to reap the presumed benefits
available on Wall Street without shifting the risks or potential
payoffs directly to individuals. Kennedy is considering a similar
approach but has not yet made a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO is planning a grass-roots effort to educate its
members about the issue and battle against both private accounts
and proposals to increase the retirement age as part of any fix.
</P>
<P>
   And liberal research groups and lobbying organizations _
including some that have not so far been heard from on the issue _
are stepping up their efforts to make their positions known. The
National Organization for Women, for example, plans to make defense
of the Social Security system a priority this year because women
are particularly dependent on the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a major push by well-funded organizations who
are getting money from Wall Street and elsewhere to promote Social
Security privatization and are doing so by promoting an exaggerated
sense of crisis,'' said Roger Hickey, the co-director of the
Institute for America's Future, an advocacy organization that is
trying to coordinate a liberal response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you have liberal groups who are pretty satisfied with
Social Security, who don't perceive major problems and who have
been slow to recognize a major threat,'' Hickey said. ``It does
appear that the privatizers have a jump on the debate. But that
won't last for long.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Liberals have been on the defensive almost since the moment that
President Clinton called in January for a year-long national debate
on how to prepare Social Security for the looming retirement of the
baby-boom generation, which by 2032 will leave the retirement
program short of the money needed to pay all promised benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The calls to look for a solution in the financial markets come
at a time when Americans have grown increasingly sophisticated
about and comfortable with investing, either on their own or
through employer-sponsored retirement programs like 401(k) plans.
With the market booming and the economy humming along, placing some
portion of Social Security taxes into stocks and bonds clearly
seemed attractive to many people.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Democrats said, the conservative approach holds out
the promise of specific rewards for individuals. The liberal
approach is a tougher sell, they said, calling for a commitment to
a more generalized good, that of providing retirement security _ as
well as disability and death benefits _ to everyone no matter what
unexpected circumstances befall them or what happens in the
markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the political environment also created challenges for
liberal Democrats. Because Clinton adopted the role of honest
broker in the debate, precluding the White House from taking any
position, many Democrats were hesitant to appear too partisan over
an issue that will ultimately require support from both parties to
address. Groups like the American Association of Retired Persons,
perhaps the most powerful grass-roots force for maintaining Social
Security's basic structure, also took their cue from Clinton and
went to great lengths not to bash any potential solutions,
including private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, conservative groups were mounting an all-out campaign
in favor of private accounts. On Capitol Hill, Republicans endorsed
a variety of proposals _ and jubilantly watched the Democratic
ranks fracture as Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, Bob
Kerrey of Nebraska, and others said they would back limited private
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of private accounts said their approach was winning
on the merits and had increasingly broad support. But opponents
said early enthusiasm for the concept in general terms would give
way to a realization that the specific tradeoffs necessary to bring
about such a change would be controversial and result in a
substantial drop in support for the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of private accounts are highlighting the potential
risks of a sustained market downturn and the substantial costs of
administering millions of individual accounts. And they are
increasingly rallying around the idea of having the Social Security
system rather than individuals invest in the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach is supported by the American Association of
Retired Persons and by unions, among other groups, and it will be
the centerpiece of the plan that Pomeroy hopes to introduce in a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the approach's advantages is that it avoids one of the
biggest problems associated with moving to private accounts _ the
need to make up for the money that would be diverted from payroll
taxes into the personal accounts. Because the payroll taxes levied
on current workers are needed to pay benefits to current retirees,
diverting a portion of them into private accounts requires
privatization proposals to rely on some combination of additional
benefit cuts and new sources of revenue such as projected federal
budget surpluses to fill the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Collective investment would avoid that problem, thereby
requiring less in the way of benefit cuts. Although it would create
the potential for other problems, including the possibility that
the government's investment decisions would have a huge effect on
the financial markets and even on individual stocks, supporters of
the approach said it was far superior to private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll achieve higher investment returns,'' Pomeroy said,
``without the downside of imposing on Social Security beneficiaries
the individual risks that come with investing in markets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
