</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUTO-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BROADENS SUITS ALLOWED OVER AIR BAGS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's highest court ruled Tuesday that a
person injured in a traffic accident may sue the automobile
manufacturer for not installing air bags, even if the car was made
before the safety devices were required by law.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision by the State Court of Appeals, New York leaps
into a growing and controversial legal arena with broad
implications not just for the auto industry but also for all areas
of product liability. Auto makers and industry groups say the
standard set by the Court of Appeals and by courts in other states
could prompt a torrent of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The decision involves a lawsuit filed by Jason Drattel over
injuries suffered by his wife, Caryn, in an accident in Matawan,
N.J., on Nov. 19, 1991. She was driving her 1991 Toyota Tercel when
it was struck head on by another car.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Drattel, an accountant who was then 29 years old and the
mother of a 4-month-old boy, suffered permanent brain damage, her
lawyers said. They contended that she would be unable to work or to
care for herself or her son for the rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's ruling sends the case back for trial to State Supreme
Court in Brooklyn, where it was originally dismissed. It will be up
to a trial jury to determine whether Toyota knew that air bags
would make its cars safer, and reasonably could have been expected
to install them before they were mandated by law.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Tetherow, a spokesman for Toyota, said, ``We are
confident that Toyota will prevail at the trial of the action and
that the jury will find the Tercel automobile, without an air bag,
was a proper and safe vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of lawsuits over the absence of air bags have
ever gone to trial, with at least two producing out-of-court
settlements. Only one such suit, in New Hampshire, has gone to
trial since that state's high court dealt with the issue, and in
that case, the jury decided for the car maker.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the ninth state whose highest court has ruled on
whether auto makers can be held liable for the absence of air
bags.The first such case was decided three years ago, when New
Hampshire ruled against auto makers, according to lawyers who track
the issue, and since then, top courts in New York and four other
states _ Ohio, Arizona, Indiana and Texas _ have permitted lawsuits
over the absence of air bags. Pennsylvania, Mississippi and Idaho
have rejected such complaints.
</P>
<P>
   That disagreement among the courts and the national significance
of the dispute could make the issue ripe for review by the U.S
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question this issue will go to the
Supreme Court to resolve the discrepancies,'' said Arthur Bryant,
the appellate lawyer for Ms. Drattel. ``The prestige of New York's
court adds impetus to that because it will influence other states'
courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The Drattels lived in New Jersey at the time of the accident,
and bought the car in New Jersey, but later moved to Brooklyn,
where they still reside. Under New York's law venue rules, they
were able to bring the case against the Toyota Motor Corp. before a
New York court because they lived in the state when they filed
suit.
</P>
<P>
   At issue in the New York case is the scope of the federal Motor
Vehicle Safety Act, the law that sets standards for vehicles sold
in the United States. The act specifically pre-empts states from
enacting a law on any aspect of auto safety ``which is not
identical to the federal standard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals, in a 6-1 decision, concluded Tuesday
that the pre-emption did not prevent lawsuits in state court that
are based on a claim that auto makers should have adhered to a
higher safety standard than is required by the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until 1993 that federal law mandated air bags in all
new cars sold in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's very significant because automobiles are
one of the most widely used products, and one that probably causes
more injury than any other product,'' said Mark Geistfeld, a law
professor at New York University who specializes in product
liability.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority in Tuesday's ruling, Judge Joseph
Bellacosa said, ``Toyota could have installed an air bag even
though it was not required to do so by federal law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, this injured plaintiff should not be deprived of
the opportunity to establish in an appropriate court of law,'' he
continued, ``that Toyota should have included a driver's-side air
bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Judge Judith Kaye, and Judges Vito Titone, George Bundy
Smith, Carmen Beauchamp Ciparick and Richard Wesley concurred.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Howard Levine, the sole dissenter, wrote, ``Federal
standards are `minimum' standards only in the sense that they
present a floor (and not a ceiling) of product safety performance
for automobile manufacturers, but are in fact both a ceiling and a
floor as to a state's power to impose safety standards.''
</P>
<P>
   In the safety act, he wrote, Congress intended to set uniform,
nationwide standards for auto safety, knowing that state-by-state
variations would harm the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
