<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2203 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENEVA-OPERA-HOUSE-$A     06-16 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENEVA-OPERA-HOUSE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAKESHIFT OPERA HOUSE COMES TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ While other cities have lost their beloved
19th-century opera houses in the wave of overgrown performing-arts
centers, the board of the opera company here bucked the tide. At
the same time that it took necessary steps to preserve the Grand
Theatre, Geneva's elegant opera house from 1882, it developed a
second house in many ways as good as the old one, and for that
matter, almost as old.
</P>
<P>
   When the stage machinery of the Grand Theatre developed
dangerous cable problems in 1996, the administration was forced to
close the house for a year to make repairs. ``Not only were we
faced with depriving our audience of an entire opera season, but
250 people would have been out of work,'' said Guy Demole, the
president of the theater's board. Opera, as anyone who knows of the
accomplished performances and innovative productions here will
realize, is integral to the social and cultural fabric of the city.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, an ingenious solution suggested itself. The
Canton of Geneva had acquired an unused power plant, a Beaux-Arts
structure from 1886 on an island in the Rhone River, which runs
through the city, and officials offered it as a possible location
for a temporary opera house. Within 13 months, and in time for the
current season, Bernard Picenni, a 42-year-old Geneva architect,
transformed the old building into a gem of a new opera house, which
exudes youth and gaiety.
</P>
<P>
   Without disguising the building's original purpose _ two blue
turbines are left as decoration in the grand foyer _ Picenni
inserted an auditorium of simple, serviceable materials. It feels
magically aloft on the river, which shimmers with reflected light
outside the tall arched windows until, just before the opera
begins, red velvet shades are lowered to block it out.
</P>
<P>
   The Batiment des Forces Motrices, as the power plant is called,
was long important to the city as an inexpensive and ecologically
sound source of hydraulic energy, derived from regulating both the
level and the force of Lake Geneva as it narrows into the Rhone. In
its heyday, the plant was responsible for channeling drinking water
throughout the canton and providing energy to factories and
workshops, notably those of the many watchmakers. The city's
symbol, the Jet d'Eau, a 460-foot plume of water that graces the
harbor, originated in the 100-foot geyser that discharged excess
energy next to the plant after hours and on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Situated at the end of a tree-lined promenade in the middle of
the Rhone, the plant is a long L-shaped structure of rusticated
stone, with the short segment of the L forming a bridge to the city
square, which serves as the entrance plaza to the building. Stage
scenery is delivered across a small bridge through the rear
entrance on the island. The high, arched facade on this side,
facing the lake, is appropriately crested with a statue of Neptune,
the god of the sea, and ornately decorated with stone reliefs of
wheels, gears and pistons, symbolic of its former life.
</P>
<P>
   With a flock of swans swirling around its edges, the building,
with its Baroque-revival character, actually seems more suitable to
an opera house than to a power plant, especially when it is
illuminated at night, with the arched windows and water-level
vaults reflected in the water.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed in the 1880s by Theodore Turrettini, an engineer
whose passion for electricity led him on several occasions to call
on Thomas Edison. In his honor, the 985-seat performance space in
the plant, has been named Theodore Turrettini Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Although Picenni left the entrance areas and the grand foyer in
their original condition, with rough concrete floors and cranes
positioned overhead, Turrettini Hall was constructed of beech and
mahogany as meticulously as if it were a violin resting in its
case. The contemporary freshness of pale woods and red velour seats
is reinforced by the industrial shell, including the original steel
trusses overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Picenni said he purposely selected inexpensive materials, so the
procedure could be reversed in the future, though that appears to
be an unlikely scenario in view of the hall's popularity and
surprisingly good acoustics.
</P>
<P>
   At a performance of Offenbach's ``Orphee aux Enfers'' this
season, the complexity of scaffolding in the set for the underworld
scene, with multiple stairways and slides, demonstrated the new
house's capacity for elaborate mechanical scenery. The orchestra
pit, like the one Wagner designed at Bayreuth, has been placed
partially under the stage, and seats 65 musicians from the
Orchestre de la Suisse Romande, which plays as the opera orchestra.
On a tour backstage, a visitor could see how cleverly dressing
rooms and costume storage areas were arranged on the lower levels.
</P>
<P>
   The grand foyer, with its long, sleek bar of sheet metal and
wood, has become a fashionable place on its own, not only at
intermission but for banquets and balls and other civic occasions.
Standing in this immense space next to the remaining turbines
washed in blue light gives one the impression of being in the
engine room of a glamorous ocean liner at sea as the river outside
flows swiftly by.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of the project has raised the morale of the whole
city by creating a new confidence in its future,'' said Demole. The
conversion, he explained, was achieved without opposition and with
two-thirds of the financing coming from private sources.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this development, the surrounding neighborhood was
known chiefly as a center of countercultural arts programs,
particularly those located in a building across the square from the
main entrance, called the Factory. The presence of the opera house
has introduced an interesting mix, enlivening the area and its
night life in new ways. Cafes and bistros on slightly run-down
streets, for example, have suddenly become trendy spots for dining
after performances.
</P>
<P>
   The season ends this month, and the company returns to the
1,500-seat Grand Theatre in the fall. But it will continue to use
Turrettini Hall and will produce about 40 evenings of opera,
concert and ballet next season. The hall has worked too well to be
abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest, Demole envisions performances by the Comedie
Francaise, theater groups, dance companies, soloists, chamber music
groups and jazz ensembles. This dynamic new performance space has
quickly recovered the particular grandeur and charm associated with
traditional 19th-century opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Opera Takes a Plunge,'' a headline in the Journal de
Geneve read at the opening, but Renee Auphan, the company's general
director, got it just right when she called the outcome ``a genuine
coup de theatre.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
