<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2204 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GABRIEL-FAURE-MUSIC-$     06-16 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GABRIEL-FAURE-MUSIC-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GABRIEL FAURE: DO THESE PIECES WANT TO BE HEARD? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore.)   (For release Sunday, June 21)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS: FIRST FOUR GRAFS CAN BE CUT)
</P>
<P>
   The Americans and the French have a good time disliking each
other these days. We push too hard and eat processed cheese. They
are arrogant, with little to be arrogant about, and have bad
symphony orchestras. Our movies are vulgar, theirs boring.
</P>
<P>
   Witnessed here are two separate ideas of what makes human
behavior decent and worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are big on rectitude and moral fiber, or like to think
they are, and are offended when the French regularly cut in line in
front of them. The French live largely for how things look, feel,
smell and sound; they are morally distressed by fish sticks.
</P>
<P>
   This sensuousness extends to the mind. For if a lot of their
daily philosophizing adds up to little, there is the elegance of
the argument even when the premises are pure foolishness. The
French are good at finding faultlessly reasoned justifications for
behaving badly, while we just blunder into sin.
</P>
<P>
   Music tells no stories, but it is a sign of human behavior. John
Philip Sousa tells the world that Americans want to make friends.
The music of Gabriel Faure tells us that the French are private,
lonely, tender, furtive, wistful. The guarded eloquence of Faure's
pieces is not that far away from the spirit of French daily life
and what is most touching about it: touching, that is, once we get
past our own values and begin to enter other people's minds.
</P>
<P>
   Five concerts of Faure's music at the Kaye Playhouse recently
were generously American, just as the music remained elusively
French. I heard the last two: one, an evening of songs; the other,
a collection of piano pieces and the Piano Quintet in D minor.
Chamber music, instrumental pieces and more songs occupied the
other events. The crowds I saw were respectable: not big yet larger
than I expected them to be.
</P>
<P>
   During a long life (from 1845 to 1924), Faure wrote few big
pieces. He seemed almost embarrassed by the riches of symphonic
sound. The composer worried about his public reputation and gained
a big one later in life, but much of his music sounds as if it did
not want to be heard at all. It retreats from the listener. It does
not present itself; we apprehend it.
</P>
<P>
   Listening on a Monday evening to Kurt Ollmann and Margaret
Lattimore sing the collections, ``Mirages,'' ``La Chanson d'Eve''
and ``Le Jardin Clos,'' one's ear kept turning to Steven Blier's
piano parts. In them, Faure creates a paradox: teeming harmonic
adventure wedded to a studied monotony. Patterns played at the
beginning of a song tend to persist to the end. The rhythms do not
change much.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere, indeed, is a sense of calm, a curious kind of
musical domesticity, an assurance that this music, and we with it,
are at home and will not stray far. For if sonata form is a
traveler's art, thriving on structured changes of scene, Faure's
constructions are like the proverbial drop of water seen through a
microscope: stationary but filled with life. In refutation to
Beethoven, Brahms and other great voyagers, Faure offers us the
variety of sitting still.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside this serenity is the life of Faure's harmony, which
seems to change directions at almost every measure. We continually
ask two questions of it: Where are you going? How are you going to
get back? Yet somehow it remains upright, a cat turning a dangerous
fall into a four-point landing. The vocal part, as Blier suggested
between songs, is not necessarily the star of a Faure song; rather,
it looks down on the piano from its higher perch, acting as
commentator and observer.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersing songs by Roussel, Debussy and Ravel on the Monday
provided powerful commentary on Faure's lonely art. Roussel offered
cheerful entertainment. Ravel's ``Peacock'' radiated delicately
with show business. ``Le Promenoir de deux amants'' was pure
seduction; in it, Debussy is private but not lonely. He talks to
the objects of his desire; Faure talks to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Never effusive, he became even more reclusive in old age. In
``Mirages,'' the String Quartet and the Piano Trio, any traces of
hazy sensuousness are burned away. The absence of extreme highs and
lows had at least something to do with the composer's increasing
hearing problems, which left only the middle ranges of sound fully
comprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Faure's music intrigue us? In part, it is its
flirtatiousness. If Aretha Franklin gets unequivocally to the
point, Faure's music never lets us forget that powerful musical
passions, however secretive, are there. Revealing a little and
hiding the rest has always been the best aphrodisiac, and we should
never forget that the composer is remembered in life as an
attractive and amorous man.
</P>
<P>
   Ollmann's lightly carried baritone found the right balance for
Faure's songs. Ms. Lattimore's mezzo-soprano is fundamentally too
big and bright for this music, but she reined herself in as best
she could and worked admirably to do the right thing. Leon Bates'
piano-playing on the next evening was discretion itself and acted
always in Faure's best interests, even though his collection of
nocturnes, barcarolles, preludes, and smaller pieces made quite an
earful for a single sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Bates, the Portland String Quartet worked ardently at
the D minor Quintet, a wonderful piece previously unknown to me.
The Portland players were a little undone by the physical
challenges of the finale and tended everywhere to be effusive to a
fault. Their heart-on-sleeve approach might have made this retiring
Frenchman a little uncomfortable, but then we Americans are like
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
