<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-EAPPEN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-EAPPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAPPEN SUIT SEEKS TO BLOCK WOODWARD PROFIT IN TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTY NEALON AND BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seventy eight minutes after the state's highest court
ruled that Louise Woodward faces no further criminal consequences
in the death of Matthew Eappen, a discouraged but resolved Sunil
Eappen filed a wrongful death suit in Boston's US District Court
against the former au pair.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fredric L. Ellis, the Eappen family lawyer, the
primary reason for filing lawsuit was to prevent the British
citizen from profiting from the tragic events. The 20-year-old
reportedly has had numerous of book offers, and the civil suit
specifically requests that a judge prevent Woodward from spending
any money she makes.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks compensatory damages and unspecified
punitive damages for the wrongful death of Matthew. A hearing on a
request for an injunction will be held this afternoon before US
District Judge William G. Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is right and there is wrong,'' said Deborah Eappen
Tuesday. ``It is wrong for her to profit in any way from what she
did to Matty. What she did was so wrong, for her to benefit
financially would be so wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a criminal case where the prosecution must prove the
charge beyond a reasonable doubt, the plaintiffs in a civil case
need only show by ``preponerance of evidence'' that Louise was
responsible for Matthew Eappen's death. In a civil case, only 51
percent of the evidence is needed to win, in a criminal there must
be proof ``beyond a reasonable doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if the Eappen lawyers win, there is no guarantee that
Woodward would be forced to obey an award because British courts do
not always honor the decisions of other countries' courts. They
would still have to go before an English court, according to law
professors consulted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, family members said the Eappens were intent on filing the
case to take all steps necessary that Woodward does not profit from
the story, and if money was made, it would go to child abuse
prevention. The formation of a Matty Eappen Foundation was
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do all we can so this never happens again,'' said
Deborah Eappen. ``If there is any financial gain from this case it
should all go toward educating people about child abuse, about
shaken baby syndrome. There is so much denial we need to get over.
I hope the foundation can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their claim that Woodward has, or will, peddle the
story of her arrest and imprisonment, lawyers for the Eappens
included copies of newspaper stories from here and abroad
describing possible book and movie deals Woodward and her mother
were negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   One of Woodward's lawyers, Andrew Good, denied Tuesday that
Woodward had made any deals to sell her story. Last fall, after
being freed from prison by Middlesex Superior Court Judge Hiller
Zobel, Woodward said selling her story would be ``distasteful and
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   And to drive home the point that the market for Woodward's story
is vast, the lawyers included a fat footote listing some two dozen
books spawned by another infamous criminal trial: the O.J. Simpson
murder case.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Simpson wrongful death suit _ which followed
Simpson's acquittal on criminal charges that he murdered his
ex-wife and a friend _ the Eappen suit would be much easier to win,
legal experts say, because Woodward has been convicted of
involuntary manslaughter. Thus, unlike the Simpson case, the issue
of who is responsible for Matthew Eappen's death would not need to
be relitigated.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's lawsuit was prepared in advance, the Eappen's lawyers
said, awaiting the SJC decision. They said they wanted to wait
until a decision was made so it would not interfere with the SJC
appeal. The suit does not name the EF Au Pair agency, which helped
pay for Woodward's defense.
</P>
<P>
   Neither does the lawsuit try to retrieve a significant asset of
Woodward's: the estimated $200,000 collected by supporters in
England. Ellis said he was not going to pursue the trust fund ``for
strategic reasons'' saying only ``it does raise some complexities
to do that.'' Hours after the civil suit was filed, Woodward was
served with a summons naming her as the defendent in the suit while
at a friend's home in Marblehead.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction and civil lawsuit are the Eappens' best chance at
preventing Woodward from profiting from her story by selling movie
or book rights. A Massachusetts law prohibiting such a move was
repealed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In England, newspapers and television stations are barred from
paying convicted felons for the rights to their stories, except
when there is overriding public interest. But Massachusetts, like
the majority of states, does not have a law barring convicted
felons from profiting from their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the US Supreme Court struck down New York's so-called
``Son of Sam'' law as an unconstitutional infringement on the right
of free speech. The law was written to stop serial killer David
Berkowitz from selling his story to a publisher. Massachusetts
modeled its version of the law after New York's. In the wake of the
SJC decision, Britain's Press Complaints Commission, said it is
``now up to editors to decide whether to pay Louis Woodward for her
story after considering the ... code of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Doreen Iudica Vigue of the Globe staff contributed to this
article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2214 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-EAPPEN-BOS &LR;      06-16 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-EAPPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAPPEN SUIT SEEKS TO BLOCK WOODWARD PROFIT IN TRAGEDY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
