<P>
   Neither does the lawsuit try to retrieve a significant asset of
Woodward's: the estimated $200,000 collected by supporters in
England. Ellis said he was not going to pursue the trust fund ``for
strategic reasons'' saying only ``it does raise some complexities
to do that.'' Hours after the civil suit was filed, Woodward was
served with a summons naming her as the defendent in the suit while
at a friend's home in Marblehead.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction and civil lawsuit are the Eappens' best chance at
preventing Woodward from profiting from her story by selling movie
or book rights. A Massachusetts law prohibiting such a move was
repealed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In England, newspapers and television stations are barred from
paying convicted felons for the rights to their stories, except
when there is overriding public interest. But Massachusetts, like
the majority of states, does not have a law barring convicted
felons from profiting from their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, the US Supreme Court struck down New York's so-called
``Son of Sam'' law as an unconstitutional infringement on the right
of free speech. The law was written to stop serial killer David
Berkowitz from selling his story to a publisher. Massachusetts
modeled its version of the law after New York's. In the wake of the
SJC decision, Britain's Press Complaints Commission, said it is
``now up to editors to decide whether to pay Louis Woodward for her
story after considering the ... code of practice.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Doreen Iudica Vigue of the Globe staff contributed to this
article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
