<HEADER>
A2216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ISLANDS-ART-NYT     06-16 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ISLANDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAPAN'S NORTH, HARD TIMES ARE THE BLEAKEST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: a map and a photo are being sent to NYT graphics and
photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 212-556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAPPORO, Japan _ Kimihiko Shimada's footsteps echo against the
marble floors as he crosses the hall of the Therme International
Hotel, a grand resort with everything from fake palm trees reaching
up 11 stories to a roller coaster water slide.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing the hotel does not have is guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult time for us,'' said Shimada, a
manager who will soon have to start looking for a job, as 240
former employees at Therme did. ``Of all the employees, only half
have found new jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The resort complex is a casualty of Japan's growing economic
troubles, which are nowhere more stark than here on the northern
island of Hokkaido. The city of Sapporo, home to the 1972 Winter
Olympics, is one of the most pleasant in Japan, and the entire
island is an invigorating kaleidoscope of woods, mountains, and
fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   But the unemployment rate of 4.7 percent _ compared with a
national average of 4.1 percent _ is the highest in Japan and
indeed a record in the country's postwar era. So some people are
wondering if its problems will drift south to the rest of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, we can't deny that the same thing could happen
in other regions of Japan,'' said Yasuyuki Hamada, an economics
professor at Hokkaido University. ``For now, though, Hokkaido is
facing a special phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   The special problems arise in part because Hokkaido is a symbol
not only of Japan's economic troubles, but also of the reasons for
them. More than other parts of the country, economists say, it
epitomizes the traditional Japanese distaste for entrepreneurship
and fondness for government spending and regulation.
</P>
<P>
   A manufacturing backwater, Hokkaido has relied on government
handouts, and it is full of smoothly paved but barely used roads,
bridges and tunnels whose main purpose seems to have been keeping
the construction industry plump. Hokkaido is also one of the
regions of Japan that has been the slowest to modernize and link up
with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   So it is a far cry from the pioneering mentality that
characterized the island a century ago, when Hokkaido was Japan's
new frontier. Now it is a prime example of what Japanese refer to
as nareai, the incestuous ties that link politicians and
businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The walls between the local government and private companies
here are thin, and there isn't much of a competitive spirit,'' said
Akihiro Fujimura, who runs the corporate data department at Tokyo
Shoko Research, an investment research company. ``People here
always say that when the snow melts away, the national government
budget money comes to Hokkaido.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hokkaido's main plan for dealing with the current
recession is not reassuring, at least for those who believe that
Japan must undergo a painful economic restructuring to regain
competitiveness. Hokkaido's plan seems to be to hold out until
money starts rolling in this month from the central government's
$114-billion fiscal stimulus package.
</P>
<P>
   Tadakazu Kobayashi, executive director of the government's
economic policy planning office in Sapporo, treats the central
government stimulus package as the centerpiece of the region's
revival plan. The money, he said, should come to Hokkaido as soon
as Parliament passes the legislation in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are already preparing the bidding and the ordering, and if
necessary we will pay the bill before the project is finished,'' he
said. ``At the time of contract, we can make a down payment for the
entire price.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobayashi seemed much less concerned with figuring out what
projects to spend the money on than with the fact that the money
was in the pipeline. He said the government would be able to pay in
advance to get the money moving, and he added, ``I think the cash
will start circulating and the companies will start paying
salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Hokkaido has been devastated ever since the collapse last fall
of its main bank, Hokkaido Takushoku Bank, the island's largest
employer and formerly one of Japan's 20 largest banks. That
bankruptcy led to a chain of failures at large companies that had
been kept alive by sympathetic financing from the bank, known as
Takugin.
</P>
<P>
   Takugin's efforts to support the local community in thick and
thin are typical of banks across the country, which are
contributing to their own demise by supporting dying industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main bank system, with the peculiar role of banks which
support industries, has to go,'' said Akio Mikuni, who runs his own
credit rating company.
</P>
<P>
   As in the rest of Japan, the government in Hokkaido is trying to
spread the recessionary pain very thinly. Bonuses are being shaved
to save jobs, and the result is that there are no corners crowded
with the homeless, no vast layoffs, no streets marked by boarded-up
storefronts. Here in Hokkaido, as elsewhere, the Japanese people
seem to be taking their recession with relative aplomb, at least
for now.
</P>
<P>
   But some signs of distress are hard to disguise. The nation's
currency is tumbling. New construction around Japan has virtually
stopped, so cement mixers sit idle together in parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   Some workers are being edged out of unproductive posts, others
keep moving from job to job as the companies around them fold, and
most college graduates are not getting offers for work. Companies
are also toppling at an alarming rate.
</P>
<P>
   Few in Japan have faced the challenge of looking for a job in a
recessionary economy. And only now is the realization setting in
for people like Nobutaka Suzuki, 24, a construction worker who has
been looking for work for two months in Sapporo. His challenge is
even more pressing because he and his wife have one toddler and
another child due in August, so that his job search has become a
family mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be fooling around anymore,'' Suzuki said, holding his
toddler, as his wife turned away in shame. ``It's very bleak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
