<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANNY-VERDICT-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT RULING BRITISH AU PAIR FREE TO RETURN HOME
</HEADLINE>
   (ps) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The highest court in Massachusetts upheld a reduced
sentence for British au pair Louise Woodward on Tuesday, handing
down a 4-3 decision that effectively ends the criminal case
followed by millions on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling left Ms. Woodward, who was convicted last fall of
killing a baby boy in her care, finally free to go home, though not
free of the pain of her case.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of the infant, Matthew Eappen, immediately filed a
civil suit against Ms. Woodward in federal court, seeking
unspecified damages and asking that she be prevented from making
deals for interviews or books that would let her profit from their
child's death.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction from both sides was as sharp and divergent as it
has been throughout the case, with her attorneys and supporters
declaring the young woman had finally been vindicated and
prosecutors lamenting what they viewed as a miscarriage of justice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward, in seclusion in a house in Boston, had no comment
but is believed to be planning to return to her home in within
days.
</P>
<P>
   The state Supreme Court took up Ms. Woodward's case last fall
after prosecutors appealed a decision by Judge Hiller B. Zobel of
superior court to alter a jury's verdict that convicted the au pair
of second-degree murder and sentenced her to life. Declaring that
the penalty was too harsh, the judge reduced the conviction to
manslaughter and the life sentence to the time already served, 279
days.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the judge declared that he was seeking a
``compassionate conclusion'' to the case and that the initial
sentence had been too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors immediately appealed, seeking reinstatement of
the original verdict and arguing that Ms. Woodward had received a
fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling Tuesday, the justices were unanimous in their
view that Judge Zobel had acted within the discretion allowed him
by law to reduce the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   But the dissenting minority contended that her sentence should
be reconsidered. The three justices argued that Judge Zobel had
acted too hastily by issuing the sentence on the same day in which
he reduced her conviction. The minority opinion also said that a
new judge should consider barring Ms. Woodward from earning money
from her story, and from caring for children.
</P>
<P>
   Though the high court's decision left Ms. Woodward relieved that
she could finally go home, her lawyers said, it also left her
disappointed because it rejected her appeal for her conviction to
be thrown out altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louise Woodward maintains her innocence, as she always has and
always will, `` said Andrew Good, one of her lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Though civil action may continue for months if not years, the
criminal side of the case ``is now over,'' said Thomas Reilly,
Middlesex County district attorney, adding: ``One thing is clear.
The truth is clear. The truth about what happened to Mattie Eappen
and who is responsible for his death. The truth of this case is,
always will be, that Louise Woodward killed Mattie Eappen. Twelve
jurors said so. The trial judge said so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward was initially charged with assault after she made
an emergency call to report the injury to Matthew Eappen in Newton,
Mass., on Feb. 4, 1997. The charge was upgraded to murder after the
infant died five days later at Children's Hospital in Boston. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward's defense team continues to assert, however, that
the scientific evidence in the case indicates that the infant was
killed by the sudden re-bleeding of an old head wound and that his
death could have been accidental. They plan to pursue the creation
of an independent scientific tribunal to examine the medical
evidence, defense lawyer Harvey Silverglate said.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``The Nanny Murder Trial'' by Court TV, the Woodward case
had riveted viewers in both the United States and England as it
wended its way forward last fall, seeming to tap into the deep
anxiety that working parents feel when they commend their child to
a virtual stranger's care; and when the jury found Ms. Woodward
guilty of second-degree murder on Oct. 30, it became provoked
outrage in England.
</P>
<P>
   When the verdict was reduced to manslaughter by Zobel, he said
that he believed Ms. Woodward had acted out of ``confusion,
inexperience, frustration, immaturity and some anger, but not
malice,'' in the legal sense.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court ruling said Zobel made a serious
error of law, but then affirmed that he had acted well within his
rights when he sought to correct it. That error was his decision to
accede to the go-for-broke request of Ms. Woodward's lawyers that
the jury be allowed to consider only whether she was guilty of
murder, not manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   The gambit failed, and Ms. Woodward was convicted of murder and
sentenced to life in prison, with the possibility of parole only
after 15 years. But then Zobel overturned that verdict, and that
was his right, the high court said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The minority opinion savaged Zobel for his actions, however,
saying. ``It appears that the judge identified himself with
Woodward's cause, compromising the public's confidence in the
integrity and impartiality of our courts.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, supporters of Ms. Woodward in Elton, her hometown in
northwest England, said they were delighted at the news she was
returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long wait is over,'' said the Rev. Ken Davey, chairman of
the trustees of the fund that raised $490,000 for Ms. Woodward's
appeal. ``I am sure Louise will be very pleased with the verdict
and she will be longing to get back and get her life back to
normal, or as normal as possible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But not everyone felt the way Davey did. Many people in Britain,
originally swayed by the vociferous campaigns several tabloids
waged on Ms. Woodward's behalf during her trial, began to change
their minds about the case when they saw television clips showing
the people of Elton drunkenly celebrating at the local pub when she
was released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   And in Elton itself, stung by the criticism, there have been
recent murmurings of dissent against Ms. Woodward and her family.
Earlier this week, Jean Jones, a longtime family friend and an
early leader in the campaign to free Ms. Woodward, said that the au
pair's mother, Sue, ``rode roughshod'' over those trying to help
her family and became increasingly obsessed with the money being
raised.
</P>
<P>
   `The money became God,'' Ms. Jones told Sky News there. ``She
was the most ungracious person I ever met in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' remarks came soon after Elaine Whitfield Sharp, a
former member of Ms. Woodward's defense team, accused the Woodwards
of falsifying a $15,000 invoice purporting to show that Ms.
Whitfield Sharp had charged the au pair room and board at her house
in a Boston suburb. According to Ms. Whitfield Sharp, however, Ms.
Woodward had stayed free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Miller, the member of Parliament who represents Elton,
said that the Woodwards had been unfairly subjected to
trans-Atlantic `'smear stories'' in recent weeks. `'The people
opposed to Louise in the U.S. were undoubtedly behind some of
these,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the question of whether Ms. Woodward plans to make money
off the tremendous publicity surrounding the case, rumors have been
swirling, particularly in the British media, of impending deals for
interviews and books. But Ms. Woodward's lawyer, Andrew Good, said
Tuesday that as far as he was aware _ ``and I am very aware'' _ she
had made no such deals.
</P>
<P>
   In the months since Ms. Woodward was released, something else
has changed as well: Deborah Eappen, the mother of the late Matthew
and an older boy, Brendan, became pregnant again and, in late May,
gave birth to another son, Kevin Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   The Eappens have also established a foundation in Matthew's
name, based in Chicago and overseen by Ms. Eappen's brother, to
educate the public about child abuse, focusing in particular on
``shaken baby syndrome,'' the set of injuries that experts say
afflicted Matthew and result from extremely rough handling and
shaking.
</P>
<P>
   The civil suit against Ms. Woodward, filed by Matthew Eappen's
father, Sunil, is seeking unspecified damages, said John O. Mirick,
the lawyer handling it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Louise goes home, publishes a book and makes millions out
of the situation, that's a factor a jury can take into account,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Woodward is expected to leave for home within days, as soon
as the outcome of her case is finalized and she receives her
passport back from state officials. District Attorney Thomas Reilly
said his office would do nothing to delay her departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her out of the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She returns home both a trial-television star and a convicted
killer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court decision noted: ``We do not view the
judgment against Woodward as a light matter. She stands guilty of
causing an infant's violent death. The outcome of this criminal
trial most assuredly was not an `acquittal.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
