<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2224 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EOYEOY-COX     06-16 1440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EOYEOY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    They took their shot and built successful companies
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The winners in this year's Ernst &AMP; Young's
Entrepreneur of the Year regional contest prove that gambling pays
off. Some left cushy jobs to go solo. Two went without salaries for
nearly a year. They manage everything from medical information to
prisons to child care, and they supply a range of products. The 10
winners, from eight companies in metro Atlanta and Nashville, were
honored Tuesday at a dinner in Buckhead. Six of the eight are from
Georgia. ``The thing that struck me in all of these cases were the
personal sacrifices and the personal risk everyone takes. That was
probably more important than the financial status,'' said Joseph
Sansone, a judge in the contest and chairman of Norcross-based
Pediatric Services of America, a national winner in last year's
contest. ``Anybody can run a business that's successful, but to
take a new idea and to sell it under some adverse conditions and a
lot of skepticism and stick with it ... is a true measure of an
individual's entrepreneurship.''
</P>
<P>
   Such awards do not guarantee immunity from problems. One winner,
Premiere Technologies of Atlanta, saw its stock plunge 28 percent
last week after company officials told investors to expect a
quarterly loss. Another winner, Corrections Corp. of America, is
fending off a lawsuit from shareholders attempting to block its
merger wtih Prison Realty Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Profiles of the winners
</P>
<P>
   The regional winners are ``a very diverse group this year in
terms of the types of industry, the stage of development,'' said
Gerry Wilson, Southeast area director of Entrepreneurial Services
at Ernst &AMP; Young. ``Some were fairly young and some were more
mature. All of them are highly successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs of the year
</P>
<P>
   Overall
</P>
<P>
   Doctor R. Crants
</P>
<P>
   Doctor R. Crants was helping television stations get their
federal broadcasting licenses when a former West Point roommate
suggested an unheard-of idea: running prisons like a business. The
idea led to Corrections Corporation of America, a $463
million-a-year business that has 11,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Crants, who has a law degree from Harvard, was raised on a
Seneca Indian reservation in upstate New York. CCA, of Nashville,
has had its share of controversy. It also has had its share of
firsts: It built the world's first private juvenile center in 1996.
The company manages prisons throughout the United States,
Australia, Puerto Rico and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging
</P>
<P>
   Sean and Scott Smith
</P>
<P>
   Identical twins Sean and Scott Smith went eight months without
pay and worked from their three-bedroom apartment to launch
Coalition America Inc. They say their Atlanta-based health-care
information management company is a high-tech cure for
administrative bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very dynamic industry, but a very low-tech
industry,'' said President Sean Smith. ``There's a lot of paper
that gets pushed from one side of the desk to the other. I want to
bring efficiency to the entire industry through technology.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the brothers' thinking three years ago when they left
Medical Review Systems, a medical bill review company.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition America helps employers find the best preferred
provider organization, then creates and manages that plan for its
clients.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old pair built a business that has 50 employees and
$7.6 million in revenues. Clients include Corning, Jeld-Wen and
Western Southern Life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're evolving into an information and technology company,''
Sean Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Going into business with his twin was a logical choice, he said.
``We share the same ideals. If you're going to go into business,
it's nice to have a partner you know well.'' Scott Smith is vice
president of the company. Sean Smith is the point person on
strategies and managed care contracting; Scott Smith knows computer
systems.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to take the company public by 2000 or become part of a
larger high-tech firm through an acquisition, Sean Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Health care/family services
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Penninger Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Harold J. Tenoso
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Penninger Jr. founded Serologicals Corp. in 1971 in
Pensacola, Fla., as a network of plasma donation centers for the
collection of anti-D antibodies. The antibodies help Rh-negative
women have healthy pregnancies and healthy babies.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-D remains the Clarkston-based firm's flagship product. The
company also collects and produces antibodies used to test for and
to treat such diseases and infections as AIDS, rabies, rheumatoid
arthritis and hepatitis. During the 1980s, Penninger foresaw two
trends: the need to develop a range of anti-D vaccines and to
remain a big player in the blood-typing diagnostics business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Penninger acquired a company that could clone and
produce antibodies. Anti-D and the cloned antibodies now account
for about 42 percent of sales and 65 percent of gross profits.
</P>
<P>
   Penninger brought in cellular immunologist Harold Tenoso and
Russ Plumb, vice president of finance. As president and chief
executive, Tenoso moved the company to Atlanta, completed an
initial public offering and increased revenues fivefold. The firm
has grown from eight to 63 donor centers.
</P>
<P>
   Retail/Wholesale
</P>
<P>
   Howard Halpern
</P>
<P>
   When Buckhead Beef opened in 1983, 16 other companies were
cutting meat for Atlanta restaurants and businesses. Buckhead Beef
is the only one left. One of Atlanta's Top 100 privately held
companies, it is a $300 million-a-year family-owned firm headed by
Howard Halpern, president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasing people with food is instant gratification,'' said
Halpern, who grew up in the hospitality industry and ran a gourmet
grocery in Atlanta before opening Buckhead Beef.
</P>
<P>
   The company developed the latest technology in its aging and
dry-aging facilities, working with Kansas State University.
</P>
<P>
   Buckhead Beef management includes Halpern's wife, Lynne, the
accounts-receivable manager, and a son, Kirk, who is in operations
management.
</P>
<P>
   Technology/Communication/Entertainment
</P>
<P>
   Boland T. Jones
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Premiere Technologies corralled its 2,300 employees
for a conference call to brief them on its recent problems: sagging
stock and a lack of payment from two key customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question they asked was, 'When can we buy the
stock?','' Premiere spokesperson Marcia Scott said. ``They're eager
to fight back and prove the critics wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The setback is the first for the Atlanta-based communications
services firm, which has grown mostly through acquisitions.
Chairman is Boland T. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1991 as a telephone calling-card service, Premiere
now offers technology linking voice mail, e-mail, fax and
conference calling via the Internet or telephone. That wizardry
once earned Premiere praise on Wall Street and helped to snare
Olympic chief Billy Payne.
</P>
<P>
   Business services
</P>
<P>
   Monroe J. Carell Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe J. Carell Jr. left an electrical engineering job to join
his father in a parking company 30 years ago. Today, Central
Parking of Nashville is on the New York Stock Exchange and controls
nearly 1 million parking spaces worldwide. It has become one of the
world's foremost authorities on managing parking facilities. Sales
have grown at a compounded annual rate of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Health care/Family services
</P>
<P>
   Marguerite Sallee
</P>
<P>
   CorporateFamily Solutions is a co-winner with Serologicals Corp.
The Nashville-based company is an industry leader in
employer-sponsored child care centers and offers family and
consulting services. As a single parent, Chief Executive Marguerite
Sallee, 52, saw the need for child care for working parents.
Sallee, former Tennessee commissioner of human services, has
received numerous awards and sits on several national boards,
including The Committee of 200, a group of top businesswomen.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing:
</P>
<P>
   Milton Grief
</P>
<P>
   American Fabricators in Nashville makes custom precision sheet
metal used in industrial products. It also supplies stainless steel
industrial kitchen tables and exhaust hoods for a major restaurant
chain. Milton Grief, 51, left his job as a certified public
accountant in 1984 to start the business.
</P>
<P>
   _This year's sponsors are the NASDAQ stock market and the
Kauffman Foundation. Local sponsors are SouthTrust Bank, Holland &AMP;
Knight law firm, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta
executive search firm SpencerStuart and Hamilton Dorsey Alston
insurance brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
