<SLUG> BC-GA-FLORIDA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dog plays one more for Florida
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- When the Georgia and Florida all-star football teams
gathered for a welcome dinner on the roof of the Metro Atlanta
Chamber of Commerce on Sunday night, only one player received a
gracious reception from the opposing squad.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, William Witherspoon of Panama City, Fla., was a welcome
sight for several Georgia players, who will join him this fall in
Athens as University of Georgia freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Witherspoon is one of just two Florida players in Saturday's
Georgia-Florida All-Star Game in the Georgia Dome who will return
to the Peach State to play college football. Six Georgia all-stars
will play at schools in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of Florida and Florida State fans in Panama
City,'' Witherspoon said. ``So there was some (flak) for choosing
Georgia, but they all understood that it was my choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Witherspoon, a 6-foot-3, 215-pound inside linebacker, chose the
Bulldogs over Florida, Florida State, Tennessee, Duke and Notre
Dame. He was a key in Georgia's nationally ranked recruiting class,
after the Bulldogs lost starting linebackers Brandon Tolbert and
Greg Bright to graduation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Steve Hardin, his coach at Rutherford High,
Witherspoonis a lot like former Florida All-American Kevin Carter,
who plays with the NFL's St. Louis Rams. Hardin, who coached Carter
at Tallahassee's Lincoln High nearly seven years ago, says both
players were outstanding defensive ends before he moved them inside
before their senior seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the exact same makeup,'' Hardin said, ``and I'm not
just talking about as a player. I'm talking about a young man who
was president of the student body, homecoming king, prom king ...
and probably the best all-around athlete in the state of Florida,
hands down.''
</P>
<P>
   Witherspoon, who also played tight end, earned state
player-of-the-year honors from USA Today. On defense, he had 125
tackles with four interceptions. On offense, Witherspoon added 15
receptions for 356 yards and 10 touchdowns. He probably will play
on both sides of the ball Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   His skills transcend football. This spring, after placing in the
top three in four events at a district track meet in Jacksonville,
Witherspoon traveled to Daytona Beach for the state weightlifting
championships the next day. He lost nine pounds in 12 hours to
qualify for the 199-pound weight division, then won the state title
by benching 375 pounds and lifting 285 in the clean and jerk.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, Witherspoon appears ready to help at Georgia this
fall, although he concedes that he probably needs to add 15 pounds
before freshmen report on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind taking a redshirt year if I had to,''
Witherspoon said. ``I wouldn't mind playing my freshman year if I
was really needed. But there's that inexperienced feeling you have
moving up to the college level from high school. I think I'm a
pretty adaptable person.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
