<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GM and UAW at a stand still
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio -- General Motors Corp. and the United Auto Workers
are making no progress in settling two Michigan parts-plant
strikes, which have now erased 60 percent of the company's vehicle
production and idled 4,500 workers in the Dayton area.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes in Flint by 9,200 UAW members at a metal-stamping
plant and a Delphi instrument panel and engine parts plant have
caused GM to close or partially shut down 17 of its 29 North
American assembly plants. Parts shortages from the Flint strikes
have forced nearly 71,000 GM workers to be laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, about 4,500 GM employees in are out of work at five
area plants. The local layoffs include about 3,900 workers at the
Moraine truck assembly plant; 323 at two Dayton brake plants; 158
workers at GM's Vandalia air bag plant; 73 hourly employees at the
Kettering suspension parts plant; and 27 workers at GM's Delphi
Chassis plant on Home Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   GM on Tuesday also informed 470 hourly workers at the Moraine
Engine plant that they would be working half-days due to the Flint
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   More plant closures and layoffs in the Dayton area and across
the nation are expected today. Analysts estimate the strike is
costing GM at least $40 million a day.
</P>
<P>
   With negotiators exchanging barbs at the metal plant Monday
night and union leaders expected to leave in a day or two for a UAW
convention, a settlement seems unlikely by Friday. By then, 95
percent of the automaker's car and truck output would be halted,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a long summer for those strikers,'' said Michael
Robinet, an auto industry consultant with CSM Forecasting in
Farmington Hills, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Union and company officials said Monday the walkout appears
likely to last into July. If the Flint strikes aren't settled by
June 26 U.S. workers, idled by the walkouts, will not get their
union-won ``holiday pay'' for the first week of GM's annual
two-week plant shutdown, which starts June 29.
</P>
<P>
   GM's UAW contract classifies the second week of the break as
mandatory vacation, for which workers received pay in a lump sum
earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of auto workers from other U.S. plants, including 200
UAW members from the Dayton brake plants, are expected today to
joint the striking Flint workers on the picket lines.
</P>
<P>
   Union negotiators walked out of discussions at the Flint Metal
Center Monday after a GM representative suggested striking workers'
support would weaken on a steady diet of $150-a-week strike pay,
said President Duane Zuckschwerdt of UAW Local 659.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took major exception to that remark,'' he said. ``That was
just a total slap in our face. Obviously, the company isn't trying
to look for a quick resolution to this thing. They think they can
win their case by holding our members hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest automaker released a statement saying the
union's account of the meeting was ``completely fabricated.''
</P>
<P>
   GM says the union has blocked plans to make the Flint factories
more efficient. The union claims GM has failed to invest in the
plants and has ignored long-standing grievances and run roughshod
over union contracts in its zeal to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW is determined to protect jobs in Flint in light of
company plans to slash 15,000 of its 34,000 Flint jobs over two
years
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
