</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANSON-FUTURE-805&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRANSON FIGHTS TO CHANGE LAW ON AIRLINE OWNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Ohio, Britain)  (lb) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Branson, the golden-haired British entrepreneur whose
Virgin Group's holdings range from airlines and high-speed trains
to retail stores and soft drinks, was close to a deal to start a
new low-cost airline at New York's Kennedy International Airport
earlier this month but backed away because of federal restrictions
that prevent foreigners from controlling domestic airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Branson said in an interview last week that he was still
committed to starting the new discount carrier, tentatively called
Virgin America, and was willing to invest his own money in the
venture, which would concentrate initially on the Eastern United
States. He is lobbying in London and Washington to get the
72-year-old ownership restrictions lifted.
</P>
<P>
   That will not be easy, according to airline analysts,
congressional staff members and experts in aviation law. The
restrictions, which originated in maritime law, are considered so
entrenched that they have never been seriously challenged.
</P>
<P>
   The rules protect the vast U.S. air-traffic market from foreign
competition, an advantage the major domestic airlines will not give
up easily without getting something in return, such as increased
access to overseas markets, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
   But Branson, who has been told often in the past that many of
his ventures would fail, predicted he would succeed because of the
current concern in Congress and the Clinton administration about
the lack of domestic airline competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``When low-fare players come into a market it stimulates the
marketplace and I would think that the U.S. government would
welcome that,'' Branson said. ``We believe we are knocking on an
open door.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Branson entered into talks to start Virgin
America with David Neeleman, the former president of Morris Air, a
Utah-based discount carrier bought by Southwest Airlines in 1993.
The carrier would have begun flying from Kennedy early next year,
according to two people familiar with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Branson declined to confirm that the airline would fly from
Kennedy. He said that it would have started with about 20 planes,
with plans to expand to 15 cities mainly in the East, the region
least served by Southwest, the country's dominant low-cost airline.
</P>
<P>
   The new carrier would have complemented Virgin Atlantic,
Branson's London-based international carrier, and Virgin Express,
its European discount carrier based in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   He said the service was to have been modeled after Virgin
Express, featuring new single-aisle jets, leather seats and ``very
good value for money.'' Though there would be limited food service
on flights shorter than an hour, longer flights would be ``fully
frilled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The airline was to be capitalized at about $200 million, mostly
from U.S. investors, making it one of the best-funded airline
start-ups ever. But Branson was concerned that the federal
ownership restrictions would deny him ultimate control over a
business carrying the Virgin name.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficulty is that our Virgin brand is so important to
us,'' Branson said. ``We would be reluctant to go ahead unless we
could have direct control.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law states that 75 percent of the voting interest in a
domestic airline must be owned or controlled by U.S. citizens.
Regulators have at times allowed foreigners to own more than half
the equity in a domestic airline as long as their voting rights
remain below 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Branson and his advisers met with officials at the Department of
Transportation in the last month to see whether the rules could be
relaxed. They concluded that they could not live with the current
restrictions. At that point, Branson and Neeleman decided to part
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to control something in the U.S.,'' Neeleman said.
``We don't think that is in the cards, at least in the time frame
we are operating in.''
</P>
<P>
   But Branson's timing may be ripe. Many lawmakers in Congress are
upset about the rising cost of air travel in recent years and the
lack of competition at many of the country's major airports. In
April, the Clinton administration proposed rules designed to
discourage major airlines from driving low-cost competitors out of
their home markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Congress, such as Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of
the Senate Commerce Committee, have already proposed allowing
foreigners to control as much as 49 percent of a domestic carrier.
In 1993, a national commission appointed by President Clinton to
look at the airline industry also recommended raising the limit on
voting rights to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should look at ways to increase competition instead of
looking at more regulation from the Department of Transportation,''
said Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, chairman of the Judiciary
Committee's antitrust subcommittee.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Any change in the rules could still take years. Relaxing the
restrictions would likely require an act of Congress, a process
that easily could get bogged down as a result of opposition from
the major airlines and organized labor. National security issues
would also be raised because the Pentagon relies on airlines to
make passenger planes available in national emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is further complicated by the friction between
London and Washington over aviation issues. Washington considers
Britain one of the most restrictive countries because the British
allow only two U.S. carriers to serve London's Heathrow Airport.
</P>
<P>
   AMR's American Airlines and British Airways have been waiting
two years for authorities on both sides of the Atlantic to approve
their proposed alliance, a deal that Washington says will come
about only after London agrees to open its market to more U.S.
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Branson, whose Virgin Atlantic competes with British Airways,
has vehemently opposed the alliance. He is now pressing British
authorities to pressure Washington to lift its foreign-ownership
restrictions as a condition for Britain to open its market.
</P>
<P>
   Many think that if anyone can focus a spotlight on an arcane
aviation regulation that few people even know exists, it is
Branson, who was recently willing to mount a vintage German tank in
New York's Times Square to herald the arrival of Virgin Cola in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans complain about the Japanese and their
protectionism,'' he said. ``Yet you still have these archaic rules
that have no rational reason to exist in this day and age.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
