</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINIAN-DANCE-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS STRINGS TO MOSCOW SEVERED, DANCE COMPANY CAN BE ITSELF  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The last time the Virsky Ukrainian National Dance
Company visited New York, in 1988, Ukraine was part of the Soviet
Union and the troupe was beholden to its Moscow sponsors. That is,
it was strongly encouraged to perform Russian dances along with
Ukrainian ones.
</P>
<P>
   The company eventually lost that support with the breakup of the
Soviet Union, in 1991, but in the process it gained its artistic
independence. This week Virsky, one of the world's premiere
professional folk troupes, returns to New York for three
performances at City Center, on Tuesday, Friday and Saturday as
part of a 38-city North American tour. And this time all the dances
are Ukrainian.
</P>
<P>
   For Myroslav Vantukh, the company's artistic director since
1980, the opportunity to present American audiences with an evening
of purely Ukrainian dance is sweet. ``Russian and Ukrainian dances
reflect different histories and cultures and result in very
different types of dances,'' he said through an interpreter in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Folk dance as performed by Virsky's 90 dancers and musicians is
an exhilarating display of athleticism and bravura technique
showcased in timeless dances that exude the culture, humor and
heart of Ukraine. The dancers look like a ballet troupe dressed in
folk gear; in vivid, hand-embroidered costumes and leather boots,
the women perform swift, precise footwork while the men demonstrate
a breathtaking repertory of barrel turns, air turns, butterfly
leaps, scissor jumps, squatting dances and toplike spins.
</P>
<P>
   The company has visited New York four times in the last 35
years, but never with lighting and theatrical effects as polished
and dramatic as they are in the current tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at Riverdance and knew we could do a very
professional, Broadway type of dance presentation based on the
roots of a culture,'' said the tour's executive producer, Donald
Baker, a Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   Virsky has in fact presented a highly dramatized style of folk
dance since it was formed in 1937. Its founder, Pavel Virsky, a
ballet dancer and choreographer from the Black Sea city of Odessa _
he died in 1975 _ used folk steps and a ballet base to create his
hybrid style, elevating folk dance to theatrical dance.
</P>
<P>
   These days the company's 66 dancers _ 38 men and 28 women, most
of them 18 to 25 years old _ take a two-hour ballet class each day
as part of their training. Nearly all graduated from the Virsky
company school in the Ukrainian capital, Kiev, where most were
students from the age of 7 (and where the troupe continues to
receive state financial support).
</P>
<P>
   The years of training no doubt account for the apparent
effortlessness with which the men perform their signature feats
like triple turns in the air and powerful jumps from a deep knee
bend (Ukrainian choreography has traditionally been showier for men
than for women).
</P>
<P>
   Like the best of today's ballet dancers, Virsky's virtuosos are
more technically skilled than their predecessors. ``The tricks they
perform are based on the traditional steps but are more difficult
than they once were,'' said Myroslav Vantukh, Vantukh's son and a
member of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere on the program are the tricks more thrilling than in
``Hopak,'' the company's rhythmic show stopper in which almost the
entire troupe, dressed in brilliant primary colors, fills the
stage. But the company has quieter moods as well, as in the lyrical
``Tree Dance,'' performed by women holding branches, and in a
joyous ``Marriage Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What our dances have in common is a love of Ukraine,'' said
the senior Vantukh. ``Without that love, there is no dance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
