<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-TRIPLEA-LADN     06-16 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-TRIPLEA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASADENA PART OF TRIPLE-A FOOTBALL LEAGUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB MIECH  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Reinholz might have discovered an original Pasadena
Pachyderm on a recent jaunt to the Atlanta area, where he conducted
research for a novel he's writing about telemarketing scams.
</P>
<P>
   Reinholz turned, and a 22-year-old man who stood 6-foot-11 and
weighed 425 pounds loomed before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like a giant Bob Lilly,'' Reinholz said. ``But he
was dumb as a skunk. Only made it through the eighth grade. I
almost had a hair to become a wrestling promoter. He was fast and
big, he just never could make it in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtesy of the hair Reinholz and four minor partners got about
two years ago, such fringe figures might soon find themselves with
an avenue, however long or rocky, to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The Triple-A Football League -- of which Reinholz serves as
president, commissioner and 51-percent owner -- plans to develop
such talent for the professional ranks. Pasadena is slated to be
one of 10 cities that will field teams in the fall of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always interested in getting tenants,'' said Rose Bowl
events manager Sally Roach. ``We have not really researched the
viability of the whole thing, but we will listen to everyone and
work with them as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the young giant in Atlanta will even find himself
playing football in the Rose Bowl with an elephant on the side of
his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics and cynics abound, especially since Triple-A football
has no coaches, players, uniforms or logos yet. Reinholz and his
group, however, have a dream, and a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Games will take place on Wednesday nights, player contracts will
start at $30,000 and include many incentives, and Reinholz says a
cable network has shown interest in securing television rights.
</P>
<P>
   Field goals of at least 50 yards will be worth four points,
kickoffs will take place at the 25-yard line to induce action, and
certain players will don microphones while one referee will be
outfitted with a camera.
</P>
<P>
   AAA football could be the stage for players with fringe academic
pasts and potential crossover athletes from other sports who might
possess some football potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like (Reinholz) has a program in place, with some
pretty good ideas how to run it. And we will listen,'' Roach said.
``But it's a tough, tough road to put a new league together, no
matter if it's baseball, football or basketball. It isn't an easy
thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes time, and a whole lotta money.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Reinholz, he and his group will have sunk $10
million into the league by the opening kickoff in October 1999. He
also said the first season will take place even without sponsors or
a television deal.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, the group hopes to have its team logos,
uniform designs and coaches, with NFL ties, in place. Training
camps will open next spring, and applications can be obtained from
AAA Football, 2828 University Ave., Suite 301-201, San Diego,
Calif., 92104.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to people who just don't get it,'' Reinholz said.
``Some people aren't convinced. But most of the time, they can
understand where we're coming from. We didn't start working on this
three weeks ago. We started two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've laid the foundation. Now, we're getting ready to put up
the framing of the house. More and more people are walking by,
saying, `Hey, what's this?' We'll get the house built.''
</P>
<P>
   The league will own its 10 teams, which will also play in San
Jose, Sacramento, Reno, Fresno, Bakersfield, Anaheim, Tucson,
Albuquerque and Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Reinholz's group has been in contact with Michael Chan, the
NFL's director of player personnel, who said AAA football is not a
new concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many, many semi-pro leagues throughout the
country,'' Chan said, ``and this will probably be one of those
semi-pro leagues which is more regional than national. And they've
been successful. They continue to play.''
</P>
<P>
   And of the possibility of AAA football attracting a cable
television audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask me, honestly, my personal opinion? I don't think
so, because it's based in California and Las Vegas,'' Chan said.
``(Cable stations) ... would want a wider audience than
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the recent NBC-TNT announcement of an imminent, alternative
pro league, Reinholz said he was excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to play them in a championship game,'' he said.
``Let me be the first to issue that challenge. We know our guys
wouldn't be good enough to play in the NFL, otherwise they'd be in
the NFL. I'm delighted. It's a perfect opening.''
</P>
<P>
   For Reinholz's next piece of fiction?
</P>
<P>
   Reinholz, who said he made his fortune in a Northern California
import business in the '70s and Southern California real estate in
the '80s, envisions a Triple-A team for each NFL franchise one day.
</P>
<P>
   An introductory brochure package, which Chan glanced at Friday
in his New York office for the first time, describes Triple-A
football as the future of pro football in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate malcontents, `goof offs,' head cases and
law breakers,'' Reinholz wrote. ``We will not have any one
individual distract us from our mission ... (and) the coaches don't
have to be baby sitters, security guards and psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Or roll, as in down the drain, which many football leagues have
done in the past. But Reinholz said the difference with Triple-A is
that it will be a feeder system to the NFL, not a competitor
against the established league.
</P>
<P>
   Reinholz and his group will not seek financial support from the
NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike the CFL, which had to borrow $3 million from (the
NFL),'' Reinholz said, ``we wanted to go to them without our hands
out. We want to do it the way we want to, and they're very excited
over the concept. Hey, it looks good to us.''
</P>
<P>
   It will look even better when Reinholz finally sees a Pasadena
Pachyderm uniform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
