</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-ART-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV PROMISES ARE JUST FIRST STEP, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., N.Y.)  (sidebar with KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and its allies said Tuesday that
pledges by Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic did not go far
enough to meet the demands of the West that he end his crackdown in
Kosovo, and that planning for possible NATO military intervention
was continuing.
</P>
<P>
   But Western officials also said that Milosevic's promises, made
to Russian President Boris Yeltsin, in their meeting in Moscow on
Tuesday, were a first step toward halting the Serbian offensive
against the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo, the southernmost
province of Serbia. They emphasized that the West would carefully
monitor Serbian compliance with Milosevic's promises in the coming
days.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told
Congress on Tuesday that Milosevic had rejected a key demand for an
immediate withdrawal of Serbian special police and military forces
from Kosovo. Instead, Milosevic said that as ethnic Albanians
fighting for independence stopped their ``terrorist activities,''
Serbian forces would increasingly stay in their barracks.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Department spokesman Kenneth Bacon said: ``We don't
think that there should be any linkage between an immediate
withdrawal of forces by the Yugoslavs, on the one hand, and
stopping terrorist activities, on the other. There ought to be
complete withdrawal of military forces so that negotiations can
begin.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's spokesman, Mike McCurry, said: ``That's a
linkage that would appear to be a loophole. There's no
justification for continuation of the brutal campaign of violence
by Serb security forces, and the withdrawal of Serb security forces
is fundamental.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCurry said that the Yeltsin-Milosevic meeting, in
Clinton's view, ``moves us in the right direction.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to Yeltsin by telephone after the Russian leader
met with Milosevic in Moscow. Yeltsin hailed the meeting as a
breakthrough, and said that ``the most important thing is that
Milosevic agreed to sit at the negotiating table with the Kosovo
Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic has already done so once, in May, at U.S. urging,
before beginning the latest chapter of his crackdown in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As Albright said Tuesday, ``It is insufficient to say that
dialogue could go forward, if the killing of civilians and
depopulating of villages continues.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that Milosevic's promises _ if carried out _
would constitute progress, U.S. officials said they were not eager
to let Milosevic off the hook, particularly given his history of
doing just enough to stave off tough action against him.
</P>
<P>
   But they also acknowledged that Milosevic had relented enough
for now to make it highly unlikely that Moscow would agree to a
Security Council resolution authorizing the use of force to stop
the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The officials emphasized that it would take some time to
evaluate what Milosevic does to put his pledges into effect. They
said that no use of U.S. force is imminent, that planning for
possible NATO military strikes is being done at a rapid pace, and
that no unilateral U.S. military action is currently being
contemplated, although they did not rule it out in the longer term.
</P>
<P>
   But if Milosevic continues his crackdown and his
disproportionate use of force in Kosovo, a senior Western diplomat
said, ``then the Russian effort will have failed, and one can only
hope that Yeltsin sees that more pressure of another kind is
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., strongly urged the administration
to act with strength in Kosovo. Rep. Eliot Engel, D-N.Y., continues
to gather signatures for a letter urging the White House to move
now to attack Serbian positions in Kosovo and to order a no-flight
zone for Serbian aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said the Bush administration was correct to warn
Milosevic in 1992 that the United States could act unilaterally
with military force to prevent a conflict in Kosovo ``with the
potential to suck in Greece, Macedonia, Turkey and Albania and
strike at the heart of NATO unity.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel called for U.S. action before the situation worsens.
``This deal with Yeltsin is insincere and a sham and we shouldn't
be conned by it,'' he said in an interview. ``The lesson of Bosnia
is that Milosevic will never change his policies unless he knows
there's a resolve on the part of the United States and the West to
stop him. He will only do what he needs to do to stop sanctions or
action against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Engel also said that he was disturbed by the possibility that
the Russians, by vetoing any Security Council resolution
authorizing NATO to use force in Kosovo, could also restrict NATO
from doing what it wants, since the European Union has already
taken the position that military force in Kosovo, a part of
Yugoslavia, would require United Nations authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Albright and Defense Secretary William Cohen have said that
Washington would act alone and without a resolution, if necessary.
But Washington would prefer action through NATO, backed by the
United Nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
