<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG12-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG 12 IS NOT IN DANGER OF BREAKUP, OFFICIALS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No commissioner. A testy television renegotiation looming.
Continuing rumors and predictions of dissolvement.
</P>
<P>
   So, there's panic in the streets of the Big 12 Conference's
neighborhood, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big 12 is healthy and stable,'' Texas athletic director
DeLoss Dodds said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard no expressions of dissatisfaction from anyone,''
said Texas A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen, chairman of the Big 12
presidents. ``I only hear that from members of the media.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past six weeks, commissioner Steve Hatchell has resigned,
the Big 12 held spring meetings at which negotiations for extending
the conference's football television contracts produced no
progress, and the Western Athletic Conference announced it was
breaking up. All three events produced rumors of rifts in the Big
12 and the league's impending doom.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short term, the conference business is moving forward
in a very normal way,'' said Missouri athletic director Joe
Castiglione, who will take over as Oklahoma's athletic director in
a few weeks. ``Contrary to what some might believe, the Big 12 is
alive and well and getting stronger every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 presidents are in Dallas for meetings yesterday and today
to select a committee that will begin the search for a new
commissioner. Hatchell resigned the position in early May, and Dave
Martin, hired as the Big 12's chief operating officer six weeks
ago, is the de facto commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen describes the hiring of a new commissioner as ``important
but not critical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to move in a deliberate fashion without rushing,'' he
said. ``The consensus is that Dave Martin is doing a great job and
that we do no harm under his leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowen's guess is that a new commissioner won't be in place until
around the first of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the right person's out there, I think we need to move as
quickly as we can,'' Kansas athletic director Bob Frederick said.
``Ideally, in my mind, we need someone in place for the beginning
of football season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12, which is entering its third season of competition,
was formed primarily for television benefits. Adding Texas, Texas
A&AMP;M, Texas Tech and Baylor to the Big Eight gave the Big 12 clout _
and more television sets _ in negotiating TV deals.
</P>
<P>
   And Hatchell produced lucrative deals with ABC and Fox. The ABC
deal, which includes the Big 12 championship game, pays the league
$16 million a year. The Fox agreement is an escalating one that
paid the conference $8.5 million last year and will pay an
estimated $11.5 million this year. Both agreements run through
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, however, the Big Ten, Pacific-10 and Atlantic Coast
conferences all renegotiated their television deals, extending them
to 2006 with significant rights increases.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers maintained that the lack of progress on the TV
contract during the spring meetings signaled that the Big 12 family
was bickering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're talking strategy,'' Dodds said. ``We're
deciding what course to take. When we decide that, then we'll start
talking dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   When the WAC broke up last month, the rumor mill started
spinning about the Big 12's future. Baylor, some speculated, might
be interested in joining former Southwest Conference schools SMU
and TCU in a new league.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is totally, completely and without a doubt not true,''
said Grant Teaff, executive director of the American Football
Coaches Association and former football coach and athletic director
at Baylor. ``Everybody at Baylor is in complete agreement that the
Big 12 is the place for them.''
</P>
<P>
   And one other fact speaks against a Big 12 breakup: The
conference generated more than $45 million for its members in
1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a lot of speculation about schools leaving
when I was in the Big Eight at Oklahoma State,'' Bowen said. ``At
Texas A&AMP;M, one of the schools people continue to speculate about
leaving, it's simply not a topic of discussion. We're committed to
the league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS &LR;      06-16 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL MADE TO EXPAND HATE CRIMES LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two leading congressional Democrats, reacting to
the brutal killing of a black man in Jasper, Texas, introduced
legislation Tuesday aimed at expanding federal civil rights law to
make it easier to prosecute attacks based on race, religion, gender
or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed measure would remove a restriction in U.S. law that
outlaws attacks based on race or religion only if the victim was
exercising a federally protected right _ such as freedom of speech
_ at the time of the violence.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would also broaden the scope of the law to
protect not only racial and religious minorities, but also
homosexuals, women and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government should be a full partner with the
states'' in prosecuting hate crimes, said Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., the bill's chief Senate sponsor. The current law's
protected-right limitation ``makes it very difficult to charge a
federal offense, and in many instances it may make a federal
prosecution impossible,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The measure's introduction followed the June 7 killing in Texas
of James Byrd Jr., allegedly by three white supremacists. Byrd's
head and right arm were wrenched from his body when he was dragged
for about three miles from the back of a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested in connection with the killing were John William
``Bill'' King, 23, of Jasper; Shawn Berry, 23, of Jasper; and
Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs. Federal agents
are assisting local law enforcement in investigating the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is considering whether to file federal
civil rights charges in the case, Attorney General Janet Reno has
said. It is unclear whether the Byrd incident will meet the
standards of the current law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dragging death of James Byrd is a vivid and shocking
reminder that even in a civilized society there are those motivated
by blinding hate,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., the
measure's chief House sponsor. ``For those in Congress who believe
that hate crimes are overblown or that the Hate Crimes Act is
unnecessary, let the brutal torture and murder of this innocent man
be a wake-up call. We have to seize the moment and pass a tougher
law, or else the brutal death of James Byrd will have been in
vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, noting that the Ku Klux Klan on Tuesday received a
permit to hold a march in Jasper, urged his colleagues to pass the
legislation and ``send a message to those who use hate as a
vocation that we are going to prosecute crimes of violent bigotry
to the fullest extent possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the legislation is not intended to undermine state
investigations and prosecutions of hate crimes. He praised Texas
law enforcement authorities for their ``immediate, vigorous and
effective response'' to Byrd's killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hate crimes tear at the heart and soul of our country, and we
need to do all we can to combat them,'' Kennedy said. ``As a
nation, we cannot afford to ignore such vicious acts of hate.
Public officials and citizens alike, at every level _ federal,
state and local _ have a moral obligation to root out hate crimes
and the hateful conditions that encourage them.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, although identical, has different names in the
Senate and House.
</P>
<P>
   Principal co-sponsors of the Senate version, the proposed Hate
Crimes Prevention Act, are Sens. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., and Ron
Wyden, D-Ore. In the House, the leading co-sponsor of the proposed
Hate Crimes Prosecution Act is Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
