<HEADLINE>
KKK TO HOLD RALLY IN JASPER, TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ City officials here were notified Tuesday that
members of the Ku Klux Klan will be in town on June 27 to hold a
two-hour rally in the aftermath of the recent racially motivated
murder of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking forward to it,'' said City Manager Terry
Lacy, ``but it is their constitutional right. The can do whatever
they want as long as they don't obstruct traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the murder of James Byrd Jr. and the arrest of three
white men _ two with possible ties to white supremacy groups _
there were rumors that the Klan was coming to Jasper to confront
the militant black groups that arrived on Saturday, the day of
Byrd's funeral. The Klan did not show.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lowe, regional director of the Knights of the Ku Klux
Klan, later said that he would accompany 15 to 20 members of
another, Vidor-based Klan faction to Jasper for a parade, which
would require a permit from the city, to condemn the violence. A
notice posted on the Knights of the White Kamellia website states
that the KKK group will be on hand ``to provide assistance to the
White residents of Jasper County.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the group apparently now plans to hold a rally on public
property, instead of a parade, no permit is required.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not have to have our blessing for that,'' said City
Attorney Gary Gatlin. He said Lowe contacted city officials as a
``courtesy'' to let them know the rally would be held from noon to
2 p.m. on June 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said they want to make a statement that the two men (in
custody) are not part of their organization and that they do not
condone murder,'' Gatlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men arrested for the Byrd murder _ Lawrence Russell
Brewer Jr., and John William ``Bill'' King _ may have been
affiliated with white supremacy groups while they were in prison.
The third suspect, Shawn Berry, has denied any such affiliation and
has given a statement to the authorities, blaming the murder on the
other two men.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
