<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN TEAM HAS CRISIS OF CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A crisis of confidence threatens to undermine the United
States' World Cup campaign, with players second-guessing Coach
Steve Sampson's personnel decisions in the wake of Monday's
lopsided loss to Germany in a Group F opener.
</P>
<P>
   With many of the Americans' most experienced players relegated
to the bench, or worse, a timid squad of World Cup first-timers
took a 2-0 defeat to the Germans at Parc des Princes, raising
questions about whether the Yanks might have been better served by
guys who have been there and done that.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the 11 U.S. starters, plus second-half substitute
Frankie Hejduk, had never seen action in the sport's most important
event, and their paucity of experience contributed to the naivete
the Americans displayed on the field, especially during the
critical first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a little hesitant,'' admitted playmaker Claudio Reyna,
a debutante whom the Germans targeted in disrupting the American
game plan. ``They had seven (1990) world champions on the field,
and we have seven guys playing in their first World Cup. That
showed in the first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyna's numbers might be a bit off the Germans have five
veterans of their '90 title-winning team but his point is well
taken. And while few of his teammates disagreed with his logic, not
many of them wanted to speak publicly about who should they thought
should be playing in place of the players Sampson selected.
</P>
<P>
   One willing to address it was Tab Ramos, one of three three-time
World Cup veterans on the U.S. roster and one of two of them who
started Monday's match on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to believe when you can look down the bench and see
guys like Alexi Lalas and Marcelo Balboa, and then you have guys
(on the field) who have never played in the World Cup before,''
said Ramos. ``I don't have to agree, and I don't, but I respect the
fact that it's Steve's decision to put those guys in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another: ``You die with the guys who got you there.''
</P>
<P>
   That would include Balboa, the Americans' all-time appearances
leader with 126, and Lalas, who teamed with Balboa to form a solid
central defense during the 1994 Cup. Neither appears likely to see
action in '98.
</P>
<P>
   Their experience, and that of ousted captain John Harkes and
several others, might have provided the Americans the wherewithal
to challenge the Germans, who got an eighth-minute goal and then
closed up shop, making it virtually impossible for the U.S. squad
to overcome the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who know how to react (in the World Cup), who know
what to do, they weren't on the field last night,'' said forward
Eric Wynalda, another three-time Cup choice who did start on
Monday. ``You don't know how to react in a World Cup until you've
been in one. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience is such a hard thing to explain. You don't know
what it is until you have it. And it's all the little things that
come to play in a game like that, all the little things that can
snowball and turn into something really bad and ruin your day. It's
the ability to stay calm and be completely intense at the same
time. I don't think experienced players get nervous; I think they
get intense. Nervousness can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Cup sideshow might have played a role in that. After
spending a week secluded at the Chateau de Pizay in Saint-Jean
d'Ardieres, the Yanks arrived Saturday in Paris; some of the
younger players were a bit overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were isolated in the middle of nowhere,'' said Lalas, ``and
then we were plopped in the middle of Paris. It was like a circus,
and a lot of the guys didn't have the experience for it.''
</P>
<P>
   They're eyes were still wide open by game time Monday, which
begs the question: Were the Americans ill-served by leaving so many
experienced players, guys such as Lalas and Balboa and Roy Wegerle
and Preki Radosavljevic, on the bench?
</P>
<P>
   ``You think it showed?'' Wynalda asked a media throng Tuesday.
``What do you think? I think it's pretty clear. I think you guys
know what to write, but you're not going to get a quote out of me
in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to help the team. There's no sense in
slighting the guys. I'm not Tab, I'm not Tab. I've already spoken
to Tab about it. I think it's very important we stay positive right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, who played in his U.S. record eighth World Cup game, has
been told he'll start on Sunday against Kuwait, likely in place of
'94 veteran Ernie Stewart in the attacking midfield slot. As many
as eight starters will be making their second Cup appearance.
</P>
<P>
   If they approach the match, and the June 25 first-round finale
against Yugoslavia, with the right demeanor, things could work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough experience on this team to realize this can be
a very long tournament,'' Wynalda said. ``Or this can be a very
short one if we don't have the right attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW THE US PLAYERS FARED AGAINST GERMANY
</P>
<P>
   By SCOTT FRENCH
</P>
<P>
   U.S. RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES VS. GERMANY
</P>
