 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
COMPAQ SERVICE TO HELP BUSINESSES SET UP ONLINE STOREFRONTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN &QL; 
1998c. Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Compaq Computer Corp. on Tuesday launched another
product designed to generate cash through online transactions, this
time taking aim at the burgeoning small- and medium-business
market.
</P>
<P>
   During his keynote address to the PC Expo trade show, Chief
Executive Eckhard Pfeiffer said Compaq will offer an easy way for
small businesses to offer products and services on the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq Online Services is a software package _ to be included on
Deskpro computers _ that lets businesses set up and configure
online storefronts, sign up with an Internet provider, back up
critical data offsite and even buy postage via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This global initiative is designed to meet the needs of small
and medium businesses for quicker access to online sales
opportunities and more efficient ways of doing business,'' Pfeiffer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The product is the second one Compaq has announced in two weeks
that will give the Houston-based PC maker extra revenue every time
a customer uses it. Businesses will use one of the services offered
in the package, and the service provider in turn will pay a fee to
Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Also in New York last week, Compaq announced an agreement with
GTE's Internet services and America Online in which they would pay
Compaq every time a new Presario owner subscribed to their
services.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Kurtzmann, vice president for Compaq's small- and
medium-business division, estimated Compaq Online Services has a
potential revenue stream of $3 billion over 18 months, and
realistically ``it means at least tens of millions of dollars to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The product is a companion to Compaq's Club Web, a kind of
interactive yellow pages on the World Wide Web that lets businesses
find providers of various kinds of online services.
</P>
<P>
   One of the products being offered is 24-hour backup-and-restore
service from NovaStor. Marius Haas, a manager in the small and
medium business division, said a set of powerful computers operated
by the recently acquired Digital Equipment Corp. will be used to
hold customers' data.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we went to Digital to talk about this, they said they had
massive amounts of storage sitting around idle, just waiting for
something like this,'' Haas said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pfeiffer's speech, delivered to a nearly full auditorium
at the Jacob Javitz Convention Center, focused on Compaq's role on
the Net.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, Compaq and its resellers today sell more than $6
million a day over the Internet _ and that is more than Dell,''
Pfeiffer said.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech at PC Expo Monday, Pfeiffer again sought to
allay the fears of Digital's longtime customers. Some have
expressed concern that Compaq's $9 billion acquisition of the
Massachusetts company means support for Digital's older systems
will go away.
</P>
<P>
   Since the acquisition was completed last week, Pfeiffer has used
each public appearance to proclaim that Compaq will continue to
develop Digital's core technologies, including its own version of
Unix and its high-powered Alpha microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those in the audience who are Digital customers, I want to
assure you that we are not taking your business for granted,'' he
said. ``We intend to earn your trust and confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The integration of Compaq and Digital was evident on the PC Expo
show floor, where Digital's products were shown side-by-side with
Compaq's. Long before the two companies began talking, both rented
booths that coincidentally were next to each other. After the
acquisition, the two were merged into 18,000 feet of contiguous
floor space, one of the largest displays at PC Expo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
