<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSY SPAWNED BY MAGAZNINE ARTICLE ON LEAKS CONTINUES TO
GROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An article in a new media magazine about leaks of
sensitive information to reporters covering the Lewinsky
investigation ignited a new round of accusations and rebuttals on
Tuesday, from the independent counsel, President Clinton's personal
lawyer and journalists who said their reputations had been
maligned.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in four days, Kenneth Starr, who is
investigating the relationship between Clinton and Monica Lewinsky,
sharply questioned the veracity of the article in the magazine
Brill's Content, as well as the integrity of its author, Steven
Brill.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's latest response came in a 19-page letter to Brill, the
magazine's editor and publisher, in which he said the article was
replete with errors and rested on a fundamental misrepresentation
of the law. ``More disappointing, however, is that your reckless
and irresponsible attack borders on the libelous,'' Starr added.
</P>
<P>
   The lengthy article entitled ``Pressgate,'' written for the
magazine's inaugural issue, alleged that Starr or his office was
the source of much of the information reporters used in stories
about witnesses who were to testify before the grand jury
investigating the Lewinsky matter. In the article, Starr
acknowledged briefing reporters but said that what he told them was
not a violation of federal law, Justice Department guidelines or
bar association ethics.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over leaks of information about the investigation
rekindled charges by Clinton's lawyer, David Kendall, that Starr
and his aides have improperly, and possibly illegally, tried to
influence the course of the investigation by disclosing potentially
damaging information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your statements in the Brill article are at breathtaking
variance with your previous public statements about your duties and
actions,'' Kendall wrote. ``Your statements consistently have led
the public to believe you would tolerate no leaks of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the charges and countercharges, Starr's investigation
proceeded, with testimony from two White House officials before a
federal grand jury. Nancy Hernreich, who determines who sees the
president, made her seventh appearance there and answered questions
for more than three hours. John Podesta, deputy White House chief
of staff, who played a role in helping Ms. Lewinsky find a job, was
questioned for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's letter, which reads much like a legal brief, is a
detailed attempt to dispute point-by-point many _ though not all _
of Brill's charges of improper conduct. He said discussions with
reporters about such issues as the time frame of the investigation
or office staffing were perfectly legitimate subjects to share with
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we must avoid, and what we do avoid, is discussion of
information sought from or provided by witnesses _ whether in the
form of investigative interviews, grand jury appearances, or
documents provided to this Office,'' Starr wrote. ``We have not
disclosed this information to the media and your claim that I have
admitted doing so is false.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter, however, does not dispute the quotes attributed to
Starr in the Brill article, which said that he and his principal
lieutenant have provided reporters information on a
not-for-attribution basis. In that article Starr was quoted as
saying it was entirely proper to provide information such as what a
potential witness told an FBI agent, so long as that witness had
not been called before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The question of what was disclosed to reporters by Starr's
office could be critical if it was found to violate federal law,
Justice Department guidelines or rules of ethics forbidding
disclosure of grand jury information. But Kendall and Starr have
offered different interpretations of what information those laws
and rules cover.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, on Monday, Judge Norma Holloway Johnson, who is
overseeing the grand jury investigation, called both sides into her
courtroom and admonished them for the leaks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
