u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEST-FILMS-HNS &LR;      06-16 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-FILMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBARGOED UNTIL 11 P.M. EST 
 
AMERICAN FILM INSTITUTE PICKS TOP 100 FILMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Editors note: please see BEST-FILMS-LIST 
 
By LOUIS B. PARKS 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 57-year-old black-and-white movie most Americans have never
seen is the best American movie of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' is a better science-fiction movie than ``2001: A
Space Odyssey'', ``E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial'' and ``Close
Encounters of the Third Kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Character actor Ward Bond was in more great movies than Humphrey
Bogart, Katharine Hepburn and Marlon Brando.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Graduate'' is the best American comedy of all time, ``High
Noon'' the best western, ``The Wizard of Oz'' the best musical.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than ending debate, the American Film Institute's
18-month effort to select the 100 Greatest American Movies of All
Time is sure to create endless arguments.
</P>
<P>
   And that is brilliant. Because the idea behind the Greatest 100
list, which was to be revealed Tuesday night, is to boost interest
in America's rich and wonderful film heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The list also serves as a nice contrast to the common rankings
of top moneymakers that prove more about marketing than quality or
art.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's only a list, reflecting the experiences, prejudices
and ages of those who voted on it. People tend to be most impressed
by films they saw when they were young and first aware of the
artistry and power of movies. Since most voters were past that age,
they were less likely to vote for recent movies.
</P>
<P>
   The results of voting by as many as 1,500 Americans _
film-industry insiders plus a few others _ were to be announced
Tuesday night on ``AFI's 100 Years . . . 100 Movies'' on CBS. The
movies were made during the first century of American filmmaking,
1896-1996. (So don't get upset if you think ``Titanic'' should be
on the list: It came out too late.)
</P>
<P>
   It will be no surprise to any student of film that, as on many
best-film lists, ``Citizen Kane'' came out on top.
</P>
<P>
   The masterful Orson Welles film, a thinly disguised and
unflattering pastiche based on the life of newspaper publisher
William Randolph Hearst, has long and widely been considered among
the best movies ever crafted.
</P>
<P>
   It can be hard for modern viewers, trained to care about big
scenes and wild plots, to spot what makes this film so important.
That's partly because so much of what Welles and cinematographer
Gregg Toland accomplished has become the standard language of film.
Understanding the film's significance requires knowing what was
usual before ``Citizen Kane'' came along.
</P>
<P>
   Far more popular are other films in the list's Top 10, including
the perennial favorites ``Casablanca'', ``Gone With the Wind'' (the
all-time top moneymaker when figures are adjusted for inflation),
``The Wizard of Oz,'' ``The Graduate'' and ``Singin' in the Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Few movies on the list can be considered total surprises, though
plenty will debate the inclusion of ``Dances With Wolves'', ``Dr.
Zhivago'', ``Giant'', ``Pulp Fiction'', ``Unforgiven'', ``Platoon''
or ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   More surprising are some of the pictures that didn't make the
list. Among the 400 finalists that failed to make the final cut are
``Adam's Rib,'' ``All the President's Men'', ``The Big Chill'',
``The Big Sleep'', ``Cabaret'', ``The Conversation'', ``The
General'', ``His Girl Friday'', ``In Cold Blood'', ``The Killing
Fields'', ``The Last Picture Show'', ``Last Tango in Paris'',
``Mary Poppins'', ``El Norte'', ``Reds'', ``Red River'', ``Tom
Jones'' and ``Goldfinger''.
</P>
<P>
   Film writers and fans will analyze the significance of the list
and its oddities for some time to come. Here are a few to get you
started:
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg, who had to wait until 1993 to get a
best-director Academy Award for ``Schindler's List'' (ranked No.
9), directed five movies on the list. The other four are ``E.T.''
(25), ``Jaws'' (48), ``Raiders of the Lost Ark'' (60) and ``Close
Encounters'' (64). He beat out Alfred Hitchcock and Billy Wilder,
who directed four each.
</P>
<P>
   Katharine Hepburn is the leading lady with the most films: ``The
African Queen'' (17), ``The Philadelphia Story'' (51), ``Bringing
Up Baby'' (97) and ``Guess Who's Coming to Dinner'' (99). Natalie
Wood, Diane Keaton and Faye Dunaway had three each.
</P>
<P>
   James Stewart and Robert De Niro lead all leading men with five
films each. De Niro's are Raging Bull (24), The Godfather Part II
(32), Taxi Driver (47), The Deer Hunter (79) and Goodfellas (94).
Stewart's five are It's a Wonderful Life (11), Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington (29), Rear Window (42), The Philadelphia Story (51) and
Vertigo (61).
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most popular actors of all time, Humphrey Bogart and
John Wayne, had good representation. Bogart is the star of four,
all in the Top 30: ``Casablanca'' (2), ``The African Queen'' (17),
``The Maltese Falcon'' (23) and ``The Treasure of the Sierra
Madre'' (30). Wayne's films are ``Stagecoach'' (63) and ``The
Searchers'' (96).
</P>
<P>
   Beating all actors was Ward Bond, one of the most popular and
prolific character actors in Hollywood history. He had supporting
roles in seven movies on the list: ``It Happened One Night'' (35),
``Bringing Up Baby'' (97), ``Gone With the Wind'' (4), ``The Grapes
of Wrath'' (21), ``The Maltese Falcon'' (23), ``It's a Wonderful
Life'' (11) and ``The Searchers'' (96).
</P>
<P>
   The list includes 11 comedies, eight musicals, nine war films,
eight westerns, four science fiction, four horror and two animated.
Most of the rest are, no surprise, drama. Of course, many also
overlap each other. ``From Here to Eternity'' could be called
either drama or war. ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid'' (50) is
both comedy and western,
</P>
<P>
   Voters seemed to agree with the popular notion that 1939 was the
best year in American movie history, with five films on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s, often considered a relatively fallow period of
American film making, had the most films on the list: 20.
</P>
<P>
   The only sequel on the list is ``The Godfather Part II.'' It's
one of the few sequels often noted as better than its original,
``The Godfather'' (3).
</P>
<P>
   The oldest film on the list is ``The Birth of a Nation'' (1915).
The most recent is ``Fargo'' (1996).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
