<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST SIGNATURE OF ALL? PEROT'S ON A CHECK  
 GOVERNOR'S BOOK AT ISSUE IN ARKANSAS  
 VIRGINIA TOBACCO TIES GOP AND LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., S.C., Tenn., Texas, Va., Ark.)   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost from the day it was founded, Ross Perot's Reform Party
has been complaining about the difficulty that third parties have
in gaining official recognition and getting on state and federal
ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The other day the party even failed to gain access to the 1998
ballot in Texas, the founder's home state. It needed the signatures
of some 44,000 Texans on ballot petitions _ or 1 percent of the
state's electorate _ but it came up with fewer than half that many.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas failure was the party's fourth this year. It also fell
short of gathering the required number of signatures to win ballot
access in North Carolina, South Carolina and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements for gaining a ballot line vary widely by state
and can be daunting. In many states, a party's performance in the
previous election determines whether it will automatically be on
the ballot in the next election or has to circulate petitions again
to demonstrate its political viability.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its recent failures, the Reform Party remains on at
least 30 state ballots as a result of the 1996 election returns.
Still, what of the rest of the states?
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the party has demonstrated that it can prevail in
just about any ballot access fight _ if Perot weighs in.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential election years of 1992 and 1996, when Perot
was a candidate, he saw to it that the party had the petitioning
manpower, money, legal advice and leadership to overcome state
rules and obstacles. The party won position almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in 1998, with no presidential contest
scheduled, Perot has not seen fit to come to the aid of those
seeking ballot access in any state, not even his own, despite
pledges at the party's national convention last year that he and
other party leaders would wage an all-out effort to field
candidates at all levels in all coming elections, presidential and
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of being realistic,'' Reform Party chairman
Russell Verney explained in the aftermath of the Texas failure.
``We've decided we're not going to go for ballot access everywhere
and we're not going to field candidates at every level unless we
can see reasonable results down the road for all that effort and
money. Texas and the other states had to face that reality.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the party does not run lots of candidates and make a
showing in the 1998 elections, particularly in states where it
already has ballot access, will it not find itself off the ballot
again in 2000 and once again facing a huge petitioning challenge?
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done twice, we can do a third time,'' Verney said.
</P>
<P>
   Governor's Book At Issue in Arkansas
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing new about political candidates writing books
about themselves or public issues or both, and then having their
selectively crafted works hit stores just as the campaign season
heats up. Most of the tomes are then routinely greeted for what
they are _ self-serving political advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   But the political reviews have been anything but routine for a
new paperback by Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee, a Republican up for
re-election. His 180-page book, ``Kids Who Kill'' (Broadman &AMP;
Holman), explores violence among American youth, and its opening
lines describe the March 24 incident in Jonesboro, Ark., in which
two middle-school students are accused of fatally shooting a
teacher and four fellow students.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's Democratic opponent, Bill Bristow, and a number
of the state's Democratic leaders contend that the book is not just
a political screed but greedy ``exploitation'' of tragedy by a
public servant. They say the governor owes an apology to the
survivors of the shooting victims and should donate his $25,000
advance from the publisher to a scholarship fund.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, who leads Bristow, a Jonesboro lawyer, by a 2-to-1
margin in the polls, counters that his critics are ``utterly
ridiculous'' and accuses them of political hypocrisy. Last year he
published a book called ``Character Is the Issue,'' and he says he
planned to write the book on violence well before the Jonesboro
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Once the shooting occurred, he argues, there was no literary way
he could ignore it, given that violence in American society was the
new work's subject. In any event, he said, the Jonesboro incident
takes up only a few pages in the $11.99 paperback.
</P>
<P>
   As for donating his advance to a scholarship fund, the governor
has plans somewhat along that line. He said he would use the money
to send his children to college.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tobacco Ties GOP and Labor
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco makes strange political bedfellows.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday in Richmond, one of the country's major tobacco
processing centers, Republican Gov. James Gilmore and Virginia
AFL-CIO president Daniel LeBlanc put aside decades of ideological
antagonism and, standing shoulder to brotherly shoulder at a
``Tobacco Workers Summit,'' pledged unity in the fight to save the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as most people can remember, Virginia Republicans
have been at odds with Virginia's Democrat-dominated unions. Or, as
LeBlanc put it, there was a time when ``the governor of Virginia
wouldn't dare be in the same room as the president of the Virginia
AFL-CIO.''
</P>
<P>
   But the threat that the tobacco bill now before Congress poses
to the state's biggest cash crop looms larger than all that, if the
Gilmore-LeBlanc unity pledge is any indicator.
</P>
<P>
   In the Old Dominion, tobacco is a $2.5 billion industry,
providing livelihood for 120,000 farmers and other workers. That is
a lot of union jobs and a lot of votes.
</P>
<P>
   Before Gilmore's meeting with LeBlanc, some Virginia labor
leaders had complained that the state's Democratic legislators in
Washington were mouthing support for the tobacco industry but
otherwise doing little out of fear that the White House might
retaliate. The Democrats had countered that they were doing all
possible, and some subsequently showed up at the Gilmore summit and
signed the unity pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been on a roll in Virginia in recent years,
after decades of Democratic hegemony that was attributable in part
to solid union support. If they could steal away some of that
support, the state Republican Party could gain even more momentum.
</P>
<P>
   LeBlanc praised both the Republicans and Democrats who gathered
to hear union concerns. But he added pointedly, even portentously,
that in the future big labor's goal in the tobacco fight would be
to have its voice ``not only heard but heeded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
