<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HOMOSEXUALS-SIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY SUPPORTS LOTT'S VIEWS OF HOMOSEXUALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Miss., Minn.)  (th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress unexpectedly became embroiled in a
controversy over homosexuality Tuesday as a senior House Republican
defended the assertion that it is a sin and as the White House
declared that such ``backward'' thinking was holding up
confirmation of its nominee as the ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute came a day after Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss., likened homosexuality to alcoholism, kleptomania and ``sex
addiction'' in a television interview. When Armstrong Williams, a
conservative talk show host, asked him whether homosexuality was a
sin, Lott replied, ``Yes, it is.''
</P>
<P>
   With leaders of gay rights groups condemning Lott's remarks,
Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the House majority leader, Tuesday cited
Scripture to support Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bible is very clear on this,'' Armey said at his weekly
news conference, adding that ``both myself and Senator Lott believe
very strongly in the Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey cited I Corinthians 6:9, 11, 18 and 20. In the King James
version of the Bible, I Corinthians 6:9, for example, says that
``neither fornicators, nor idolaters, nor adulterers, nor
effeminate, nor abusers of themselves with mankind'' shall inherit
the kingdom of God.
</P>
<P>
   The White House and Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., seized upon
Lott's remarks to call for President Clinton's nomination of James
Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg to be brought to the Senate
floor. Hormel, who is gay, was approved by the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee on a 16-2 vote last fall. But Lott, at the
behest of a number of conservative senators, has refused to move
the nomination to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone told the Senate: ``We ought to bring it to the floor
so we can have an honest discussion. The majority leader is
entitled to his opinion. He is entitled to his opinion and his
vote. But the rest of us are entitled to our opinion and our
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, said Lott's
comments showed ``how difficult it is to get business done in
Washington sometimes when you're dealing with people who are so
backward in their thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   McCurry added, ``For over 25 years, it's been quite clear that
sexual orientation is not an affliction, it's not a disease, it is
something that is part of defining one's sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Irby, a spokeswoman for Lott, said that what McCurry
considered backward ``are the views and values of the great
majority of Americans who understand and are concerned about the
grave social and ethical questions our country faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The political dispute set off by Lott comes at a time of intense
debate in religious circles, especially within Protestant churches,
over whether certain verses of the Bible should still be read as
condemning homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Several recent events have fueled that controversy. Among them
are the decision by Southern Baptists to continue their boycott of
Walt Disney Co., which they accuse of condoning homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry attributed Lott's comments to the growing influence of
social conservatives and the religious right in the Republican
Party as it prepares for the midterm elections. He said they were
drawing Republican leaders toward ``the extreme point of view in
American political life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay and lesbian
political group, sent letters to Lott and Armey asking to meet with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These comments are out of step with the American people and
prevailing medical and mental health opinion and in step with James
Dobson and his extreme right-wing rhetoric,'' said Winnie
Stachelberg, the group's political director. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
