<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-MATHIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY'S MATHIS IS ROOKIE OF YEAR FAVORITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  Clint Mathis. His name alone sounds Hollywood made. You
immediately think of a Clint Eastwood or Johnny Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   But little do people know that Clint Mathis is no more the
Sunset Boulevard type than a tourist on holiday.
</P>
<P>
   However, the soft spoken Georgia boy is an enormous soccer
talent whose humble family approach to life was evident following a
recent Galaxy victory when he was seen dancing with his mother at
an Old Town Pasadena restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   And Mother's Day had already past.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old midfielder, far and away the leading candidate
for Major League Soccer's rookie of the year, just wants to let
life shuffle the cards and see what hand he's been dealt at the
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell the future,'' Mathis said. ``I just have to worry
about now and keep my head on straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis played his first game of cards back in November, which
seemed to Galaxy officials like a scary game of high-card,
low-card.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of many big decisions in his young career,
following a sensational college career at South Carolina, Mathis
opted for the MLS instead of taking his career to Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis was a three-time Hermann Award finalist, men's soccer's
equivalent to college football's Heisman Trophy. He was named to
Soccer America's team of the week four times, and was a first-team
All-South selection and Soccer News All-South player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   During last November's MLS college draft, Galaxy president and
general manager Daniel Villanueva, along with coach Octavio
Zambrano, couldn't believe Mathis was available when it came time
for the team to use its first-round pick (No. 6 overall).
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a guy (Mathis) that was not clearly filling anybody's
mold, but he was an outstanding athlete,'' Villanueva said. ``I
said before the draft we were looking at depth for central
defender, but when he was still available, you have to be able to
change gears and get the best athlete with the most skill and leave
behind the whole positional issue.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a big surprise, Mathis delayed his trip to the Galaxy
camp. Rumors immediately spread that Mathis would develop his
talents overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if he entered the draft, he was an automatic,''
Zambrano remembered. ``As he delayed his trip to come into camp I
got a little worried and then I got a couple phone calls from his
advisor and things really didn't look good.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a joint effort from Villanueva, Zambrano and assistant
coach Ralph Perez to convince Mathis to move to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano and Perez got Mathis on the phone, and wouldn't hang
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph and I were going back and forth handing the phone to
each other,'' Zambrano said. ``I would talk for 10 minutes and
Ralph would pick it up for another 10 minutes. Finally, we figured
out the issue bothering Clint. He didn't know how much of an impact
he would be on this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he understood that when we picked him, we picked
him with the idea he would see a lot of playing time. Once he had
that in his mind and I had that conversation with him that I
expected him to really contribute, then I think he understood he
was coming into a situation where he wasn't just going to be one of
the guys who would get in every now and then. Rather, he was going
to be expected to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   And produce he has.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis has started in nine of the Galaxy's first 14 games and is
currently fifth on the team in scoring with 15 points on two goals
and seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   He started the season a little shaky and nervous, but now a
third of the way through he looks like a seasoned veteran.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've picked up the game a little bit and I believe I can play
with these guys now,'' Mathis said. ``The level of play is much
different than college, but the players on this team have shown
trust in me and that's giving me a lot of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that his coach has praised him at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt, he's the leading candidate (for rookie of
the year) as far as I'm concerned,'' Zambrano said. ``And knowing
his character, he is going to keep his head on straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a smart kid, this is just the beginning in a career that
has a lot of rewards ahead. You can dream, but you need to keep
your head on the ground and he understands that. That is why I
don't mind praising his efforts because he takes them for what it's
worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambrano says Mathis' best attribute is that he reads the game
well beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   ``American players are not known as players that have an above
average technique, or that have flair,'' Zambrano said. ``He
understands the game like a young South American player who has
grown up with this game. Sometimes that's just good instinct, but
it's those kind of special intangible talents that make him
different.''
</P>
<P>
   While Zambrano's watches the World Cup, he can picture Mathis in
a different uniform down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the U.S. national team is in his future, no
question.'' Zambrano said. ``Everyone has different opinions about
talent, but I think he would bring something new. He's national
team material without a doubt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
