<SLUG> BC-BKN-BULLS-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS BID THE BULLS HAIL (AND FAREWELL?) 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BILL DEDMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Chicago threw a bittersweet celebration Tuesday, with
300,000 fans filling Grant Park to thank the Chicago Bulls for
winning their sixth National Basketball Association championship on
Sunday but fearing that it was a goodbye party.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls may have been the only team to hold a public victory
celebration without any player saying, ``We're going to try to do
it again next year!''
</P>
<P>
   It's been the longest-running soap opera in Chicago, with more
fighting than a Jerry Springer show. Will Michael Jordan retire?
Will Scottie Pippen go elsewhere for more money? Will Phil Jackson
coach or take a year off? Would any other team put up with Dennis
Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was tentative, chanting ``One More Year!'' and
listening for any word of encouragement. They heard none, and not
only because the sound system broke down.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has said that he does not want to play for any coach but
Jackson, or with any sidekick but Pippen. He left the crowd in
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows if we're going to be in Grant Park next year,''
he said. ``But the one thing I do know, no matter what happens, my
heart and my soul and my love will still be in the City of
Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson said he has already cleaned out his desk (as
has the assistant coach Jimmy Rodgers, who resigned Tuesday), and
made a point of telling the crowd, ``This was our last dance; it
was a wonderful waltz.'' (This was cheered and booed.)
</P>
<P>
   He thanked Jerry Krause, the Bulls' general manager, who fans
believe is pushing the breakup of the team, for ``giving us the
opportunity to do it.'' (This was loudly booed.) Jackson then
dropped a bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the crowd thought it heard Jackson say that Jerry
Reinsdorf, the Bulls' owner, asked him if he would stay another
year, ``and I said yes.'' (This was cheered.) In fact, Jackson was
merely describing what he told Reinsdorf last year.
</P>
<P>
   It all may depend on Pippen, one of the 50 best players in NBA
history, but 122nd this past season on the league's salary scale.
Early in the season, when he was injured, the 32-year-old forward
said he would never play again for the Bulls, then said he wouldn't
stay unless he got a long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Tribune reported Tuesday that Pippen will be offered
a two-year contract for $35 million to $40 million, and Jordan said
Pippen ``should take it.'' To the fans, Pippen offered only this
genuine goodbye, or a bargaining position: ``Thank you for our last
dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's sixth title pushed further into Chicago history the
memory of Al Capone and John Dillinger and the Cubs, who are
uncharacteristically near first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Grant Park crowd more accurately reflected the city than did
the moneyed bunch that filled the $1,500 seats for the NBA finals.
And the crowd mirrored the team, a gritty bunch with a mix of races
and cultures. The Australian, the Croatian, the Flake, His Airness.
</P>
<P>
   The fans started lining up at 3 a.m. to greet the champions.
Mayor Richard Daley sat between Jordan and Jackson on the stage,
flanked by the Luvabulls cheerleaders. Krause stayed in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the real Rodman, on stage, age 37 and still less
housebroken than Jed. He offered a profanity, then closed with
this: ``I've always told myself I would never ever get married,
right? I would never have another wife. If I had to marry anybody,
it'd be these 12 guys right here.''
</P>
<P>
   The champions repeated their annual ritual. This year's bauble
left as it arrived, strapped into the passenger seat of guard Ron
Harper's car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have a safe trip home, folks,'' a Chicago police officer named
Gomez told the departing crowd through a megaphone. ``See you in 30
years, when the Bulls win again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
