u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROWN-COX     06-16 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two more Guatemalan bodies recovered
 &HT;    By Joe Brogan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The bodies of two more Guatemalan
landscape workers whose screams for help in Spanish went unheeded
Monday night by other beachgoers were recovered from the Jupiter
Inlet Tuesday by sheriff's divers.
</P>
<P>
   Another Guatemalan's body was found about 6:30 p.m. Monday night
by a fisherman just after the three non-swimmers disappeared in
swift currents at DuBois Park on the inlet's south side.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said Tuesday they believed it was the first
time three swimmers had drowned simultaneously in a county park.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach County sheriff's Sgt. Jack Courtney said parkgoers
paid little attention to their plight, thinking they were engaging
in loud horseplay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since they spoke Spanish, no one understood they were yelling
for help,'' Courtney said. ``Some were upset they were making so
much noise.''
</P>
<P>
   The men, who lived at 1600 Center St., and are believed to be
under 30, had gone into the water off a rocky point outside of
buoys marking safe swimming areas.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguards, who had been on duty about 200 feet away, left about
an hour before the drownings at the end of their scheduled shift
about 5:30 p.m., a county official said.
</P>
<P>
   The park is guarded by the county's beach patrol from 9 a.m. to
5:20 p.m. seven days a week from Memorial Day to Labor Day and on
weekends and holidays in the cooler season, said David Lill,
director of the county's aquatics division.
</P>
<P>
   DuBois also had the highest number of swimmer rescues in any
north county park from June through August last year because of
swift currents beyond designated swimming areas, county records
showed.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the county would consider extending summer
lifeguard hours beyond 5:20 p.m. in light of the tragedy, Lill said
money for that isn't budgeted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had more money, we could guard from sunrise to sunset,
but for the hours we're there, I believe we meet the needs of the
greatest amount of people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DuBois, like most county parks, is closed from sunrise to sunset
by sheriff's deputies.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's Det. Brian Jacques said Tuesday he is unsure of the
names of the victims and is seeking documents to prove their
identities.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Rev. Felipe Jimenez, pastor of the Iglesia
Evangelical De Sandidad in Hobe Sound, where the men attended
church, said they are David Lopez, about 30, and brothers Antonio
Guzman, 16, and Roberto Guzman, 18.
</P>
<P>
   The three were regular churchgoers who had dedicated their lives
to God, Jimenez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their main goal was to support their families,'' Jimenez said.
``They were sending money back to Guatemala and were working very
hard to help their parents. They eventually planned to return
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
