<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY-$     06-16 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-VINOLY-$ADV21-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ARCHITECT WITH THE SPARE, SINEWY GRACE OF AN ATHLETE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note that last week's architecture article should have
been slugged ARCHITECTURE-GLASS)  
 af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though Rafael Vinoly is the most elegant architect now
practicing in the United States, he probably doesn't want to hear
about it. The elegance of his work is ascetic as well as esthetic.
It has everything to do with integrity and nothing to do with airs.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly's new Princeton University Stadium, now nearing
completion for an official opening in September, would make a great
location for a fashion shoot. But the fashions would have to be of
a kind worn by those who understand the beauty of service to an
ideal.
</P>
<P>
   This trim, understated building arrives at an opportune moment.
In the last decade, with places like Denver's Coors Field, the
sports stadium has emerged as America's most diseased building
type, an expression of arrested development in the innocent guise
of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly's design delivers the architectural equivalent of sports
medicine: it's not whether you win or lose, but where you play the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The new 30,000-seat football stadium replaces Princeton's Palmer
Memorial Stadium, a deteriorated campus landmark judged by
university officials to be beyond repair. The new stadium is on the
eastern edge of the campus, set on an axis with Jadwin gymnasium
(designed by Walker O. Cain), the school's main sports complex.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the stadium, the project includes a new track
field, with its own seating, situated between the stadium and the
gym. The project architect was Chen-Li Lin.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly has conceived of the stadium as a kind of Roman aqueduct:
a tall, arched concrete structure, curved into a U-shape and lined
with seats. The aqueduct is a self-contained building. On the top
level, behind thin ribbon windows, it houses classrooms, offices, a
rehearsal hall for the marching band, rooms for social and other
functions. The ground floor will hold concessions and restrooms in
deep, recessed alcoves.
</P>
<P>
   The structure is unusual. What appears at first glance to be
cladding material _ panels of earth-colored concrete aggregate _ is
the surface of the load-bearing, structural blocks of which the
building is constructed. Besides supporting their own weight, the
hollow blocks (U-shape, like the stadium) provide bracing for the
grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   The seating is arranged on two tiers, the lower level organized
in the conventional way, in the form of a squared-off bowl. The
upper tier is more dramatic. Rather than continuous rows, the
concrete bleachers are divided into three flat, sloping,
trapezoidal slabs. These are propped up by steel, V-shape struts.
The slant and the trapezoidal shape create a forced perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The tiers are vertiginous to look at, exhilarating to sit in,
even without a game going on. The playing field is pitched below
grade, which heightens the sense of enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of seating, the corners of the U are voids _ tall,
rectangular arches that allow peripheral views of the stadium's
parklike surroundings. The tops of the arches slant inward,
creating the illusion of two-dimensional frames. Landscaping is a
prominent feature throughout the design. The park spills through
the arches into the stadium itself. Two raised plazas, set into the
corners, are planted with trees.
</P>
<P>
   Walkways, bordered on one side with sloping planting beds, pass
through the stadium, beneath the upper bleachers; these remain
accessible even when the stadium is closed. Sunlight passes through
slits between the rows of seats, casting bold stripes of brightness
and shade, though the paths may prove more popular when its
raining.
</P>
<P>
   The palette is on the raw side. The aggregate is not a pretty
color. The bleachers are bare concrete, with strips of aluminum
stretched along the seats. The bleacher stairs evoke classical
ruins. The overall image, in fact, is classical, further proof, if
more were needed, that the classical idea in architecture
gravitated long ago to structural expression and has stayed there.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly practices architecture as if it were a form of gestalt
therapy. Many architects do. The dynamic whole was the animating
principle behind Frank Lloyd Wright's gospel of organic
architecture.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Wright would feed a building's requirements into his
imagination, pull out his pencils and sketch his way toward unity
of structure, image, space, and surroundings. Vinoly's classical
symmetry is poles apart from Wright's romantic tension. But his
approach to design is organic, perhaps to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium's arches might be more impressive _ scarier _ if the
tops were straight instead of slanted, but the slant provides
structural bracing. It also enhances the views, and echoes the
slope of the bleachers. But Vinoly wouldn't slant them simply to
create a scenographic effect. At either end of the U there are two
diagonal slots, openings for the ramps that lead from the ground
level to the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Though the slots help reveal the structure, they also look
dismayingly like notches cut in a piece of cardboard with an X-acto
knife. Vinoly would rather risk such an impression than entertain
the extraneous visual gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The architect has a weakness for dull walls. The rear of his
gymnasium for Lehman College in the Bronx is as glum as the front
is radiant. The main facade of the theaters at the Tokyo Forum is
bleak. Beyond Vinoly's walls there is always something sparkling.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense the wall functions as a curtain. It's a relief that
Vinoly doesn't try to make these walls interesting. Their
uncompromising intelligence is clear enough. Yet you may find
yourself wishing that the visual matched the philosophical appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly once memorably called architecture an art of dealing with
heaviness. A stadium is an ideal place to see this idea put into
practice: the relationship between building and body is an ancient
classical theme. This is the second sports center Vinoly has built
in the metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The Lehman gymnasium, with its curving metal roof, which evokes
the grace of divers in its Olympic-size pools, is a ravishingly
fluid design. The Princeton Stadium is more stolid _ more
block-that-pass than jack-knife dive. Both put one in mind of
Balanchine dancers. They are thoroughbred, stripped-down, in the
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Vinoly's athletic spring contrasts sharply with the
ponderousness of recent stadium design. The new generation of
sports architecture started out well enough in 1992 with
Baltimore's Camden Yards, a first-rate synthesis of architecture,
planning and urban design by Hellmuth Obata &AMP; Kassabaum.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture had something valuable to say: traditional
stadiums like Wrigley Field were lean, functional pieces of
architecture, modern in everything but name. In subsequent
stadiums, designed by the same firm for Cleveland, San Antonio and
Denver, this point was lost. The retro subtext of Camden Yards took
over the field.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of locker room talk in New York right now. A new
Yankee Stadium. A rebuilt Ebbets Field for the Mets. But the
discussion has yet to engage architecture on a serious level. Let's
hope that the Yankees stay in the Bronx. But the architectural
victory goes to New Jersey for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
