<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE OKS FEE CAPS FOR LAWYERS IN TOBACCO SUITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
1998c. Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Tuesday narrowly approved capping
fees for plaintiff's attorneys in tobacco lawsuits, a move that
could have major financial consequences for Texas lawyers who
spearheaded a state suit against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   After two unsuccessful efforts to limit fees, the Senate voted
49-48 to cap attorneys' compensation based on a sliding scale from
$4,000 an hour to $500 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum fees would be determined by what year the attorneys
filed suit, based on the premise that those lawyers who were
involved early on took greater risks and laid the groundwork for
attorneys who filed lawsuits later.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, sponsored by Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., would
apply to attorneys involved in all pending state lawsuits and to
lawyers in states such as Texas that have reached agreements. Only
fees that have been paid to attorneys as of June 15 would be
excluded from the limitations.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, plaintiff's attorneys are scheduled to get $2.3
billion as part of the $15 billion settlement.
</P>
<P>
   It has been estimated that the five top attorneys who initially
took the Texas case on a contingency basis would receive fees
equivalent to $100,000 an hour over 25 years. Those lawyers would
have to pay as many as 100 more attorneys who worked with them on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Under the amendment approved by the Senate, Texas lawyers would
be limited to a maximum compensation of $2,000 an hour. The fee is
based on the fact that the Texas suit was filed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation provides that plaintiff's lawyers who
participated in suits filed before 1995 would be entitled to the
maximum of $4,000 an hour while those who filed after June 15 of
this year would get the minimum of $500.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was condemned by Richard Hailey, the president of
the Association of Trial Lawyers of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Congress limits what consumer attorneys, but not corporate
lawyers, may earn, it can cap the wage of every hourly worker in
America, of every profession, every professional sports figure,
every movie star, and every corporate executive,'' Hailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, a spokeswoman for Gov. George W. Bush, who has
challenged the Texas lawyers' fees in court, said the provision
adopted by the Senate represented a ``a more reasonable way'' to
determine the compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the governor has not lobbied senators for
restrictions on fees.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys' fees issue was resolved as lawmakers try to
finish work on the complicated and controversial tobacco
legislation, which would raise cigarette prices and give the
federal government broad authority to regulate tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, lawmakers have added provisions that would also
tap revenue generated by tobacco price increases to pay for a tax
cut for married couples and fund anti-drug programs.
</P>
<P>
   Republican senators are scheduled to meet Wednesday to determine
how to proceed on the bill which has badly split their caucus
between conservatives, who oppose the tobacco measure as containing
too much government intervention, and moderates, who support the
effort to crack down on teen smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the fee cap was clearly important to the Senate
Republican leadership, who view the limit on lawyers as necessary
to get conservative members on board.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that the amendment was initially going to be
defeated by one vote. But the Senate leaders extended the time for
voting and convinced Republican Sen. Gordon Smith of Oregon to
change his vote.
</P>
<P>
   Four Democrats joined 45 Republicans, including Texans Phil
Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison in voting for the fee limits.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Texas lawyers, Tom Banning, declined to
comment on the impact of the Senate action. He claimed, however
that the tobacco industry has already paid $40 million in expenses
and $50 million in fees to the plaintiff's lawyers involved in the
Texas case.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill. said that it was unfair that attorneys
challenging the tobacco companies would have their fees limited
while the lawyers working for the tobacco companies would have no
limits on their remuneration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our anger for lawyers is reserved only for those who sue
tobacco companies not for those who defend tobacco companies,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But defenders contended that because Congress has been asked to
regulate the tobacco industry and impose a tax on their products,
they should be able to determine how that money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can regulate everything with respect to tobacco but we dare
not touch attorneys fees. I think that is a difficult argument to
make,'' said Gorton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
