<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-2NDTAKE     06-16 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the leaks. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brill's article has prompted a buzz in Washington, in part
because it also raised serious questions about the methods and
integrity of many in the city's press corps, an institution as
important to the nation's capital as legislators, bureaucrats and
lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Brill said on Tuesday that what is being lost in the emphasis on
whether Starr had improper contact with reporters is how reporters
treated information allegedly provided by Starr in the first few
weeks after the Lewinsky story broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors will always leak,'' rill said in an interview.
``There are always going to be leakers. The question is what do
guys like you and me do about them. Do we just take stenography or
do we go and check them out?''
</P>
<P>
   But while Brill questioned the professionalism of some in the
Washington press corps, and the accuracy of some of their stories
in the early days of the Lewinsky coverage, several reporters have
said he mischaracterized comments they made to him. In the last two
days, the affirmation ``We stand by our story,'' has been heard all
over town.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Brill's article chastised Jackie Judd, an ABC
reporter, for saying on air that eye witnesses had apparently seen
the president and Ms. Lewinsky in a compromising position. So far,
no such witnesses have been identified.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ms. Judd disputed Brill's version of how she handled
that story. ``He mischaracterized my point of view on this story,''
Ms. Judd said. ``In my conversations with him, I told him that ABC
has not had to retract any report we put on the air, including the
eye witness story.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brill-Starr dispute has, in fact, laid bare some potentially
embarrassing aspects of the hotly competitive contest for
information. In making his case that Time Magazine could not have
been the recipient of leaks from his office, Starr, in his reply to
Brill, quotes from a letter written to Jackie Bennett, his
principal deputy, by Michael Weisskopf, a Time Magazine
correspondent. Weisskopf is seeking to ``open lines of
communication'' with the prosecutor's office in order to establish
an ``off the record relationship,'' Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, we went pretty far to cast doubt on the charges of
Starr leaks,'' Weisskopf wrote, in what appears to be an effort to
get in Bennett's good graces.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Duffy, Time's Washington bureau chief, confirmed the
accuracy of the letter, but declined to discuss it further.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
