<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-(2TAKES)-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENEATH THE SURFACE CALM, CONCERNS ABOUT HONG KONG PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RON REDMOND  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite its smooth reversion to Chinese rule, some worrisome
political and social undercurrents are rippling Hong Kong's surface
calm, analysts and politicians said Tuesday on the second and final
day of a Seattle conference looking at the transition.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of generally optimistic assessments on Monday of
the former British colony's first year under Beijing's control,
speakers at the ``Hong Kong One Year After Transition'' conference
yesterday expressed several concerns over the future, many of them
political.
</P>
<P>
   They cited:
</P>
<P>
   _An electoral system aimed at ``containing'' democracy and
promoting ``rule by tycoon.''
</P>
<P>
   _Moves toward a Singapore-style authoritarian system that
provides for economic liberty while curtailing some freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   _A reluctance by the Hong Kong government to take steps toward a
constitutional convention and universal sufferage;
</P>
<P>
   _Increasing polarization between big business and the rest of
Hong Kong's 6.4 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Davis, a constitution expert and law professor at the
Chinese University of Hong Kong, said business in the territory has
fared much better than in most of the rest of Asia during the
financial crisis that has swept the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the political side has not done as well, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the handover, on a superficial level, things have not
changed,'' Davis said. ``Political demonstrations still occur, the
press still operates freely and elections are held. But this is a
sameness with a difference. One democrat likens the situation to a
war, where one side (China) has seized the high ground but not yet
fired a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the 1984 Sino-British Joint Declaration that promised
Hong Kong a high degree of autonomy under the one country, two
systems concept was based on the political separation of capitalist
Hong Kong and the socialist mainland. But that basic ideological
division _ capitalism vs. communism _ is no longer so distinct, he
said, because of the sweeping, market-oriented economic reforms
that have transformed China. Today, the difference is primarily
between a politically authoritarian mainland and a Hong Kong that
has been promised liberal democracy and the rule of law. The
result, he said, is a framework ``loaded with tension.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy in Hong Kong is viewed as a worrisome threat to the
authoritarian center and much of China's Hong Kong policy aims at
its containment,'' Davis said in a paper prepared for the
conference.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Basic Law now governing Hong Kong provides an
elaborate electoral formula that basically gives the government
two-thirds of the legislative seats and could keep the opposition
in the minority indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese fear of democracy in Hong Kong has become
paramount,'' Davis said. ``This is evident in a wide range of
policies, including, for example ... the promotion of rule by
tycoon; the watering down of democracy, making it impossible for
democrats to win; the promotion of national security concerns in
post-handover laws on public order and ... attacks on human rights
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's pro-business leadership has shown some affinity for
certain aspects of Singapore's authoritarian model, Davis said. The
support of big business is evident in a range of Hong Kong's
post-handover policies, including the scuttling of proposed labor
laws and proposals to import workers from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger is that heavily pro-business forces ... will ride
roughshod over other political, social and economic concerns,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said attempts to characterize Hong Kong's opposition
democrats as radicals are unfair. The outspokeness of the democrats
``is a product of a system designed to keep them a minority and,
quite frankly, I'm concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By passing laws and creating a system where the democrats have
no chance of succeeding, the people in power are being
confrontational and I think it is unnecessary. I don't see any
radicals in Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment was shared by Christine Loh, the 42-year-old
chairwoman of the Citizens Party, considered one of the democratic
parties within the Legislative Council. Loh was re-elected to the
legislature in May 24 elections that saw democrats take 18 of 20
seats up for direct election.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Hong Kong, the democratic camp is about as responsible as
they come,'' Loh said. ``We are mild. We are moderate. We don't
have revolutionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the business and professional elite in Hong Kong enjoy
an undue advantage under the current electoral system and
challenged them to show their support for democracy by running for
direct election.
</P>
<P>
   Loh also urged Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa to begin
preparations for a constitutional convention that will determine
the region's political future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I don't see any enthusiasm yet in that
direction,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But another politician, pro-Beijing legislator Yok Sing Tsang,
said the current electoral timetable allowing for consideration of
universal sufferage in 2007 was the most prudent approach in a city
that prizes stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should look at the decisions we have made, but we should
not rush to change the timetable,'' declared Tsang. He said elected
executive and legislative branches could bring to an end some of
the advantages of living and doing business in Hong Kong, including
small government and low taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take some time to work out the right chemistry
between the executive and the legislature,'' Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
   Eden Woon, director of The Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce
and former head of the Seattle-based Washington State China
Relations Council, said the economic uncertainties facing the
territory and the increasingly vocal political debate threatens to
lead to further polarization between big business and the rest of
the community.
</P>
<P>
   Woon said there are increasing signs of resentment toward
successful business people, who are often categorized as being
pro-Beijing and insensitive to the concerns of the common person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
