<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Webcams Turn the Internet Into One Big `Truman Show'   By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The woman who broadcast her birth over the Internet yesterday isn't
alone in letting strangers peek into life's private moments.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thousands of people the world over have set up ``Webcams,''
small cameras that broadcast digital snapshots or video over the
Web. In essence, they act like electronic eyes, letting anyone on
the Internet peer into homes and offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, 20 or 30 people submit new Webcam sites,'' said
Thomas Rene, an Albuquerque man who keeps an online list at
 &LR; www.rt66.com/ozone/ &LR;   &LR; cam.htm. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Most Webcams overlook bridges or highways. But the most
intriguing sites are those that invite Web surfers to spy on their
creators.
</P>
<P>
   It's like a different twist on Jim Carrey's role in ``The Truman
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the voyeur's paradise come to life,'' said Ken Showalter
of Alexandria, Va., who maintains another Webcam list
( &LR; www.whatsonthe.net/webcamks.htm) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Apple software engineer John Kullmann  &LR; (www.mae.apple.com/jk) &LR; 
perched a Webcam in his Cupertino office three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I know someone is looking is when the flash on
the camera goes off,'' Kullmann said. ``I get no warning. If I
happen to be picking my nose, they catch me.''
</P>
<P>
   And just what thrill does Kullmann get out of the 76,000
anonymous visitors that have flashed into his office so far?
</P>
<P>
   ``The thought of taking a picture and spying on people is
something that appeals to the general public,'' he said. ``I get a
sort of pleasure out of catering to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Office Webcams are comparatively tame, but if you hunt around
the lists long enough, you're bound to point and click to one of
the racy sites, where cameras in bathrooms or bedrooms yield the
odd glimpse of someone in the raw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have an exhibitionist side,'' said Howard Besser,
a professor at the University of California at Berkeley's School of
Information Management and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us manifest this in low-tech ways. Perhaps we're good at
telling jokes or stories, or we move well on the dance floor or on
skis. Putting up a Webcam is just a high-tech way of getting people
to pay attention, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's society, the media seem to say the only people who
matter are the ones who appear on TV or movies,'' Besser said.
``Normal people are separate from that. Maybe by letting others
look at them or parts of their life, they feel like they've had
some impact.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Hardly Trumanesque: &LR;  Andrew Jones was annoyed when he got two
unsolicited e-mails from ``Sylvia'' at the ``Truman Liberation
Front.'' The spams directed him to a Web site
 &LR; (www.freetruman.com) &LR;  that seemed to take a political stand
against OmniCam, the fictional company that made a TV show out of
the life of Jim Carrey's Truman Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who is the Web master at Humboldt State University in
Arcata (Humboldt County), checked to see who owned the Free Truman
online address. When he discovered that it belonged to Paramount
Pictures, which produced ``The Truman Show,'' he became irate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw `Truman' and enjoyed it,'' Jones said. ``But I take
issue with the fact that a major motion picture studio apparently
used spam to promote the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Paramount officials did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Worrywarts? &LR;  While making small talk at a reception, I ran
into Lee Hamilton, worldwide risk manager for Bay Networks, which
telecom titan Nortel acquired on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Her title intrigued me, and in response to some ribbing,
Hamilton explained that she and fellow risk managers worry about
everything from lawsuits to the Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But that's not all they do. ``We're supposed to take care of
it, too,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The risk managers at 50 Silicon Valley firms get together on a
regular basis to share their professional concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to be known as the person who worries about
everything,'' said Leanne Johnson of 3Com Corp., who heads the
local risk manager's association.
</P>
<P>
   But she admitted, ``It's not easy for me to say in one word what
I do at a cocktail party.''
</P>
<P>
   Got a tip, gripe or brainstorm? Tom Abate wants to hear it by
phone (650-961-2689), fax (650-961-5023) or e-mail (abate(at
sign)sfgate.com). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
