<SLUG> BC-INSULIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Breathing In Insulin Works as Well as Shots, Study Says   By Carl T. Hall  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Inhaling a powdered form of insulin appears to work as well as
standard injections in controlling diabetes, a study revealed
yesterday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inhale Therapeutic Systems, a San Carlos-based drug delivery
company, reported the results of the first major clinical trials of
lung-delivered insulin during the annual meeting of the American
Diabetes Association in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of mid-stage, or Phase II, studies tracked 121 patients
with both major forms of diabetes _ juvenile- and adult-onset _ for
three months. Half used standard injections, half the new aerosol
delivery method.
</P>
<P>
   The new insulin-delivery system is designed to disperse a cloud
of fine-powdered insulin into a clear chamber. The drug is given at
the start of a slow, deep inhalation in order to ensure the insulin
reaches the deep lung, where it's quickly absorbed into the
bloodstream.
</P>
<P>
   Blood-sugar control for those using the inhaled delivery method
was comparable to that with injections for both forms of the
disease, researchers said. Follow-up studies extending as long as
18 months showed no sign of lung impairment or other safety
problems, they added.
</P>
<P>
   The results pave the way for a much larger clinical study,
expected to track about 1,000 patients for six months or more. That
study is planned to begin late this year.
</P>
<P>
   If the pivotal results are as favorable as those reported
yesterday, the new system could be before the Food and Drug
Administration by 2000 and ready for commercial launch by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Inhale Therapeutic stock rose $1, or 3.7 percent, on the news to
close at $27.75 yesterday. Shares in drugmaker Pfizer Inc., the
biotech company's New York-based marketing partner, rose $1.75, or
1.6 percent, to close at $109.75.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Chess, chief executive of Inhale, noted that patients
much preferred the lung-delivered insulin.
</P>
<P>
   Even among study participants with lifelong experience with
insulin injections, the vast majority _ 80 percent _ asked to
continue using the aerosol system after the clinical trial ended.
About 92 percent of the adult-onset cases prefered the new method.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not prove that injections can be eliminated
altogether. Patients given the aerosol system continued to take a
slow-acting form of insulin by injection before bedtime. ``Our
focus was on the rapid-acting, regular insulin because a lot more
people need that,'' said Ajit Gill, chief operating officer at
Inhale Therapeutic.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetics might also continue to endure frequent finger-stick
blood draws in order to gauge how much insulin to take, although
less-invasive methods are being developed.
</P>
<P>
   About 3.5 million people in the United States now take regular
insulin injections out of about 16 million total cases of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts said there's a potentially huge market for a
convenient lung-delivered system that proves safe and effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inhaled insulin could be used in the great majority of
patients,'' said Peter Ginsberg at Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis,
who estimates sales along the order of $500 million to $1 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of insulin and syringes for diabetes run about $3 billion
a year worldwide. The market for all the so-called macromolecule
drugs _ including hormones like insulin and other proteins that
generally cannot be given in pill form _ totals about $10 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Besides insulin, Inhale has lung-delivery systems for five other
drugs in the clinical stage of development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
