<HEADER>
A2290 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-SFCHRON &LR;      06-16 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Spending Plenty of Green at U.S. Open   By Jon Swartz and Kenneth Howe  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
   
   
 Somewhere Near the 16th Fairway of the Olympic Club  
 
Phil Ressler is about to make the most important pitch of his life
here at the U.S. Open golf tournament. But it's not a golf shot
he's lining up, it's a business deal.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mere 7-iron from where Tiger Woods will tee up tomorrow,
scores of companies are shelling out millions of dollars for
hospitality tents. Within these green-and-white-striped pavilions,
they will woo clients at one of the world's most prestigious golf
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of corporations _ ranging from BankAmerica, Transamerica,
Pacific Bell and NationsBank to Callidus Software, PeopleSoft and
Hartmann Studios _ have plopped down more than $120,000 each for
the rights to host elaborate soirees at the week-long event.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 152 companies are spending an estimated $11 million just
to rent space at the Open _ and that doesn't include food and
alcohol. Tent-rent fees all go to the United States Golf
Association, which puts on the event.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have arrayed themselves within four fenced and
closely guarded tent villages, each covering several acres.
</P>
<P>
   Inside air-conditioned, carpeted 40-foot-by-40-foot tents,
company executives booze and schmooze important customers with
catered meals, alcohol and all the comforts of home.
</P>
<P>
   And what parties they are _ in some cases, waiters in tuxes
serve five-course French dinners in settings that could double for
four-star restaurants. The goal: scoring lucrative business deals
and rewarding overachieving employees. It's also a great excuse to
watch golfing icons Woods, Davis Love III and Ernie Els compete in
a major tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good opportunity to keep customers happy and foster
deals,'' Carolyn Flinchum, a spokeswoman for NationsBank, whose
spellbinding tent could pass for a small-scale version of the
Fairmont Hotel's Tonga Room. The South Pacific decor is festooned
with exotic palm plants, thatched roof, wicker chairs and a
Polynesian-style bar.
</P>
<P>
   Ressler, the senior vice president of marketing for Callidus,
said his company is spending more than $160,000 during the week of
golf to bring his San Jose start-up software company to the
attention of Fortune 1000 executives.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``This is a marketing play for us,'' said Ressler, whose
company sells a half-million-dollar computer system to help
companies track sales and bonus incentive plans. ``I need to reach
an audience of executives and the best way to get them is at an
event like golf that interests them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ressler said he could have launched his marketing campaign at
New York's PC Expo this week at a cost of about $80,000. ``Trouble
is that everybody else in the corporate software business is there
too,'' he said. Getting a busy chief financial officer to sit down
in a cramped booth for an hour's pitch would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But for golf-loving executives, the U.S. Open, whose tickets are
hard to come by, is an irresistible lure. Many are willing to spend
60 minutes or so in Ressler's tent when they know they can spend
the rest of the day following their favorite golfer.
</P>
<P>
   Ressler said the 50 admission tickets a day that came with his
tent are virtually all spoken for, meaning that he has booked as
many prospective customers as guests as he can.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan bought a half of a tent for $65,000 for the week and
is splitting the cost among four divisions in the company, said
spokeswoman Melissa Freidman, who sat behind the white picket fence
that surrounded the tent's entryway.
</P>
<P>
   The bank had invited Johnny Miller, the golfer and broadcaster,
to speak to a crowd of favored customers yesterday evening. Other
units of J.P. Morgan were using their tickets to reward
high-performance employees.
</P>
<P>
   The tents for each company range from the plush to the opulent.
</P>
<P>
   BankAmerica's luxurious digs are &UR;  &LR; modeled after the TV series
``Cheers.'' A dartboard, framed sports photos on wood-paneled
walls, a popcorn machine and plenty of good grubb ``make people
feel cozy,'' says Connie Colladay, vice president and general
manager of BofA's client marketing. Tomorrow afternoon, Masters
champion Mark O'Meara is scheduled to speak to a select group of
VIP customers.
</P>
<P>
   Golf has been an important part of Transamerica's marketing mix
for at least 10 years, spokesman Bill McClave said. In addition to
renting a hospitality suite at the Olympic Club, the venerable
insurance company is one of this year's U.S. Open sponsors and puts
on a senior golf tournament in Napa in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many executives get quality face time with clients in a
setting like this,'' BankAmerica's Colladay said. ``They normally
enjoy playing the sport and building relationships on a golf
course. So why not extend that relationship at a prestigious event
like the U.S. Open?''
</P>
<P>
   For more than $120,000 a company can &UR;  &LR; get a pavilion tent for a
week, more than 100 tickets for the U.S. Open, at least 40 parking
passes, a telephone, a computerized scoring system, a 32-inch color
TV with cable, a kitchen in the back, a storage locker and
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   But that's only a portion of the tab. Companies fork over more
for catered food and drinks or interior decorating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Super Bowl. Everyone wants something different,
something special,'' said Susan Lacz Gersten, partner of
Ridgewells, the Washington, D.C., catering service that has worked
exclusively with the U.S. Open since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgewells offers companies a menu of more than 100 selections.
</P>
<P>
   The choices run the gamut from the 49er breakfast grinder
(``fluffy scrambled eggs topped with smoked ham slices, shredded
pepper jack cheese, grilled onions and peppers tucked into a
sourdough pocket''), which costs $7.50 per person, to a $110 French
feast of beef cho cho, roasted loin of veal with shitake mushroom
sauce and a chocolate logo box with chocolate bourbon mint.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, silverware costs $750 a day to rent.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, Ridgewells will feed 55,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The high-rent district is Olympic Village, perched atop a hill
overlooking the entire course at $135,000 per tent. Its dozen or so
corporate tenants include Pacific Bell, BankAmerica and
Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Lakeside Village, nestled behind the 16th hole, is a tad more
egalitarian _ or as egalitarian as one can get for $120,000. The
sprawling 40-company compound is populated with the likes of
NationsBank, Compaq Computer, Cisco Systems and Goldman Sachs. An
extension of the village, called Winged O, was hastily created to
handle more companies that wanted tents.
</P>
<P>
   Even the rest rooms are elegant. Spectators who trod the
fairways of the U.S. Open will have to make do with Porta-Potties.
</P>
<P>
   But guests of the hospitality tents enter large portable
air-conditioned restrooms where the atmosphere is enhanced by
recorded music and prints of impressionist paintings hung about the
walls. Running water flows into brass sinks, where at the touch of
a dispenser, mouthwash, body lotion and aloe vera gel is available.
The latter presumably for those who have seen a touch more sun than
is good for them. An electric shoe polisher stands by the door.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between a dirt parking lot and a grove of trees is
the bargain basement Champions Pavilion, where some 80 companies,
such as KCBS radio, Electronics Arts and Miller Brewing have taken
up residence. For $27,500, a firm can get a table in a festive big
top with unlimited food and drink. There's even a life-sized cable
car and faux street signs labeled ``Nob Hill'' and ``Chinatown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
