<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2291 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-16 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: ALL BRILL ALL THE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the wonderful word ``oleaginous'' didn't exist, someone would
have to invent it to describe Rahm Emanuel, the White House spin
artist who has set the Washington news agenda for this entire week.
</P>
<P>
   It was Emanuel, with downcast eyes and a noble tremor in his
voice, who took to TV on Sunday to herald the cover story of the
new magazine Brill's Content as a ``bombshell'' with implications
not only ``grave'' but also ``serious.'' His was a performance
self-righteous enough to make one shout, ``Bring back Sidney
Blumenthal!''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel's ``bombshell'' was the news that Ken Starr and company
had been talking to reporters _ and that Starr had admitted so in
an interview with Steven Brill, the magazine's editor and the cover
story's author.
</P>
<P>
   Bombshell? As Brill himself said during one of his nonstop TV
appearances, ``It's no revelation to anyone that Ken Starr has been
leaking material.'' Nor is it a revelation to anyone that Starr
would confess to what Emanuel and Brill (but as yet no judge) call
a misdeed: Starr long ago proved himself the most self-destructive
hunter of gargantuan prey to come our way since Ahab.
</P>
<P>
   But Emanuel is no fool. With his ``bombshell,'' he deflected
attention from his own appearance in the Brill article, which
describes how he ``cynically'' tried to discredit a damaging and
still undisputed New York Times story about Betty Currie's
revelations to Starr investigators.
</P>
<P>
   And he knew the media would take the bait _ even as they faulted
the White House for ``changing the subject'' to Starr _ because
they welcomed the opportunity to avoid the real subject of Brill's
24,000-word piece. The Brill article is called ``Pressgate,'' not
``Starrgate,'' and the bulk of it is about the press's behavior,
not the independent counsel's, during the first three weeks of its
All Monica orgy.
</P>
<P>
   You'd hardly know this from much of the coverage that Brill's
Content is getting. You wouldn't know, for instance, that Brill
tracks down exactly how a false ``one-source story from a
fifth-hand source,'' about a Secret Service agent's supposed
witnessing of a Monica-Clinton tryst, was spread as fact by all too
many of the country's major news operations.
</P>
<P>
   Or that he unearths the genesis of the illusory semen-stained
dress and details just how it morphed into the holy grail of
scandal coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue in ``Pressgate'' is not that many reporters
talked to prosecutors _ as is their right _ but that a small
minority of them wrote erroneous stories that were then amplified
by the echo chamber of a feeding frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Since the new, Brill-fed frenzy began, most of the press
criticism has been directed at Brill himself _ some of it well
deserved. He should have disclosed his contributions to Democratic
campaigns, including Clinton-Gore, and he should have avoided an
appearance of partisanship by keeping his checkbook shut to start
with.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hard to argue that Brill, who at The American Lawyer
magazine published the Stuart Taylor Jr. article that rekindled the
Paula Jones case, is a Clinton lackey. Nor is he single-mindedly
anti-press. His article names the names of those who resisted the
stained dress and other unfortunate multimedia pileups.
</P>
<P>
   And at least Brill has said he will admit mistakes _ though
perhaps to a fault, given that his first issue contains a
correction about a prototype issue not seen by the general public.
(He'll probably even run Starr's 19-page letter to the editor.)
</P>
<P>
   What's been remarkable this week is how few in the thin-skinned
media have been willing to concede any errors and how many just
duck Brill's questions altogether.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday ABC News' ``World News Tonight'' ran ``A Closer Look''
about the Brill piece in which Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts
sounded off without so much as acknowledging that their own Sunday
show figures in it at length. On Tuesday a Wall Street Journal
editorial trashed the Brill piece as ``Tabloid Criticism'' without
disclosing that it reports on The Journal's retracted account of a
White House steward and stained tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Only on Wednesday is Brill's Content actually available to
civilian readers. The difference between the cover story they find
there and the one spun by the media and Emanuel could be a future
cover story in itself _ though not, heaven help us, at 24,000
words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
