r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUVENIRS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-16 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUVENIRS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 
 Pricey Souvenirs Don't Tee Off Fans   By Steve Rubenstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
A plastic cup is a plastic cup anywhere except San Francisco, where
a plastic cup is $17.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was no ordinary plastic cup. This was an ordinary plastic
cup that said ``1998 U.S. Open'' on it, which made it something to
be embraced, clutched to the bosom and, only as a last resort,
drunk from.
</P>
<P>
   Paying $17 for a plastic cup may not be a good deal, but it's no
worse a deal than paying $12 for a tiny towel or $6 for a plastic
luggage tag or $3.33 for a golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   That was the going rate inside the giant white air-conditioned
tent where U.S. Open souvenirs were being hawked to otherwise
sensible people who all of a sudden did not mind paying $18 for a
fuzzy sock that slips over the top of a golf club and keeps it from
catching cold on chilly mornings.
</P>
<P>
   A man named Phil was selling $59 periscopes. Every golf fan
needs a periscope, he said, in order to look over the heads of
every other golf fan when crowded around the green.
</P>
<P>
   There are cheaper periscopes on the market, said Phil, but woe
be to him who buys one.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the green if you're six or seven deep in the
crowd,'' he said, as a gaggle of golf fans stood around his booth
and tried out the scopes. There were more raised periscopes than
the Sixth Fleet on maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Golf balls, which normally sell for a buck or so, were selling
for $40 a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are too expensive to hit,'' said Glenn Greer, who bought
a set. ``You would never actually play with golf balls like
these.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You stick them on a shelf someplace,'' said Richard Westover.
``Then you take them down and look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing for free was a 144-page golf rule book full
of wondrous rules about the differences among movable obstructions,
immovable obstructions, temporary obstructions and temporary
immovable obstructions.
</P>
<P>
   A few steps away, Scott Duffy was selling $82 Izod golf shirts,
the kind that used to have embroidered alligators on them back in
the days when golf shirts used to have embroidered alligators.
</P>
<P>
   That was before other shirtmakers began mimicking the alligators
with embroidered pumas, embroidered leopards and embroidered
ponies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, instead of alligators, golf shirts carry the logo of the
tournament, right where the alligator used to be. Izod sold the
rights to the alligator to another shirt company for $40 million,
which sounds like a lot of money but, in the world of golf, isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alligator is meaningless,'' said Duffy. ``The alligator is
nostalgia. This business has gone beyond the alligator.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
