<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SCIENTIFIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PFIZER TO SELL STENT BUSINESS FOR $2.1 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pfizer Inc. announced on Tuesday that it would sell its
cardiovascular devices unit to Boston Scientific Corp. for $2.1
billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The move to sell Schneider Worldwide, which makes stents used to
hold open arteries, had been long anticipated. Pfizer had announced
in February that it planned to sell its entire Medical Technology
Group to focus its resources more on its core pharmaceutical
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is basically the first component of that group that will
be sold,'' said Steven Tighe, a pharmaceuticals analyst with
Merrill Lynch. ``Even with Pfizer at the top of its game, it
continues to focus on pharmaceuticals.''
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of Viagra, its impotency pill, Pfizer has
become the nation's hottest pharmaceutical company. Sales of Viagra
are projected by most analysts to be one of the most profitable
drugs ever, with sales of more than $1 billion during its first 12
months on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Such success has made the company's top brass commit itself to
the next huge-selling drug. The Medical Technology Group was looked
upon as a drain on money that could be funneled into research.
</P>
<P>
   While the sale clearly fits into Pfizer's long-term strategy, it
also appears to be a boon for Boston Scientific. The company, based
in Natick, Mass., will be one of the top manufacturers of stents.
Schneider Worldwide, based in Bulach, Switzerland, also made
peripheral stents, used in areas outside the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to like the deal. Shares of Pfizer rose
$1.625, to $109.6875, while Boston Scientific increased $1.75, to
$62.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
