<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HAMPTON-HNS &LR;      06-16 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HAMPTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Mike Hampton's hopes for his first All-Star berth took a serious
blow Tuesday when the Astros placed the lefthanded pitcher on the
15-day disabled list because of a strained left groin.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The injury occurred on Hampton's last pitch in Monday's
rain-delayed game at Cincinnati, and he tweaked the groin while
running out a bunt in the next inning. Righthanded reliever Reggie
Harris was promoted from Class AAA New Orleans to take Hampton's
spot on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros opted for a relief pitcher because the bullpen
endured a workout in Cincinnati. Adding to the bullpen woes,
righthander Doug Henry has a sore arm and might be held out of
action until the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie will give us another fresh arm down there,'' Astros
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``We'll have another decision
to make Saturday when Mike's spot in the rotation comes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Those options include John Halama and Scott Elarton, both of
whom have pitched well this season at New Orleans. It's also
possible the Astros might tap the bullpen for a spot starter, most
likely lefthander Trever Miller. Hunsicker said using a four-man
rotation was not an option.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a day off in the schedule, Hampton should miss only
two starts if the rotation holds form. Regardless, it will be
difficult for the Astros to replace their most consistent pitcher
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who suffered the same injury in 1995, is 8-3 with a
2.80 earned run average. He pitched a shutout in his only complete
game and ranks among the league leaders in wins, ERA and innings
(103).
</P>
<P>
   Monday's injury almost certainly cost Hampton win No. 9,
considering the Astros waxed the Reds 13-2 and were leading 6-0
when he departed. It also might have cost him a spot on the
National League All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really hadn't thought much about it,'' Hampton said. ``I
mean, I thought I had a good opportunity to make it this year, but
you never really know. It's a little disappointing, because things
like that (making the All-Star team) don't happen to you every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, I can't worry about that. I've still got
to come back and pitch the best I can, regardless of that. I'm
going to miss two starts, but there's no doubt in my mind that I
can get back to where I was when I come back from the disabled
list. I didn't really want to go on the DL, but it was a logical
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the layoff caused by a 50-minute rain delay
might have contributed to his injury, Hampton said: ``That might
have had a little to do with it, but who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton became the ninth Astros player to go on the disabled
list this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate,'' Hunsicker said. ``This is very similar to
when Jeff Bagwell went down. Mike is a key member, and we're going
to miss him. On the bright side, we don't think this is a severe
injury, and we're optimistic that he'll be on his way back to being
healthy over the next 10 days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2130EDT &QL; 
