<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS REBOUND SLIGHTLY AS INVESTORS SEEK BARGAINS
</P>
<P>
   Stock-market gauges rose slightly as investors sought bargains
but shunned multinational companies with exposure to the financial
turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 37.37 points,
to 1,753.12, erasing Monday's 29.30-point decline. The 2.18 percent
gain was the largest percentage increase in the barometer in more
than three months. Among the big gainers on the Nasdaq were Intel,
Microsoft and Dell Computer. Dell jumped 5.9 percent on news that
it was in talks with Microsoft to custom-design personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   PRESSMANS TO GIVE UP TITLES
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Gene Pressman will step down shortly as co-chief
executives of Barney's, the luxury fashion retailer started by
their grandfather, executives involved in the negotiations said.
The two will remain consultants to the company as it continues to
emerge from bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   LARGER ISSUE UNDERLIES GM STRIKES
</P>
<P>
   The strikes crippling General Motors, while partly about job
security and work-place safety, reflect a broader struggle over how
the United States' auto industry will make vehicles. GM wants to
embrace efficient techniques it uses in countries like Brazil. But
where GM sees efficiency, the United Automobile Workers union sees
a threat.
</P>
<P>
   PFIZER TO SELL SCHNEIDER UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer will sell its Schneider Worldwide unit, which makes
stents used to hold open arteries, to Boston Scientific for $2.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   OBSTACLE LOOMS FOR FINANCIAL BILL
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration all but doomed efforts to update the
United States' Depression-era financial-services law this year,
saying it would not budge from its opposition to the bill passed
last month by the House and that it wants to start over next year.
</P>
<P>
   NO HARM SEEN BY MERGER WAVE
</P>
<P>
   The White House and the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board,
Alan Greenspan, agreed in testimony before the Senate Judiciary
Committee that there was little evidence of excessive consolidation
from the mergers sweeping the banking, telecommunications and
military contracting industries.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER PRICES UP 0.3 PERCENT IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Price increases for lettuce, cigarettes, gasoline and
prescription drugs pushed up consumer inflation by 0.3 percent in
May, the largest increase in 17 months. In another report,
construction starts on new homes were down 0.7 percent last month,
to an annual rate of 1.53 million units.
</P>
<P>
   MERCK EXPECTED TO GET WINDFALL
</P>
<P>
   Astra, the Swedish drug giant, is expected to buy Merck's share
of the two companies' joint venture. That, plus last month's DuPont
deal, means Merck is looking at a multibillion-dollar windfall.
</P>
<P>
   JURY REJECTS WORKERS' INJURY CLAIMS
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury rejected claims by nine people that they were
injured by using computer keyboards made by Digital Equipment.
</P>
<P>
   FUEL CELL TO GET HOME TEST
</P>
<P>
   For the first time on Wednesday, an energy technology called a
fuel cell will supply all the power to a suburban house in Latham,
N.Y. The Energy Department is helping pay for the test in the hope
that the technology will eventually be an economical alternative to
traditional energy sources, while cutting pollution.
</P>
<P>
   FEE CAP BACKED IN TOBACCO CASES
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted to limit lawyers' fees in suits against
cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   A MANAGED-CARE FAILURE IN CALIFORNIA
</P>
<P>
   The California Medical Association is closing the managed-care
company that it and 7,500 of its member physicians created to take
on the state's big HMOs. After two and a half years, three chief
executives and $11 million in losses, the association's company,
California Advantage, will file for bankruptcy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
