<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FACE17-AZR &LR;      06-16 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACE17-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP FUNDS FACIAL SURGERY FOR WOMEN SAVAGED IN DOMESTIC VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIN SHAW  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For women like her, it hurts just to look in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, every time she catches a glimpse, she's reminded of
the day her husband tried to destroy her face with an ice pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to ruin you so no man will want you,'' he'd warned
her so many times.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, he did it, said the 30-year Phoenix woman still
too afraid to be named. After smashing both of the woman's legs
with a baseball bat and breaking both elbows, he hit her 4-year-old
daughter with a lamp.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went for the woman's face.
</P>
<P>
   Severe facial injuries and scarring are not uncommon for victims
of domestic violence, shelter and medical workers said. Long after
a victim escapes her abuser, the evidence of broken jaws and noses,
missing teeth and deep gashes remains as public reminders of
private anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Phoenix organization has recognized the high demand for
medical treatment among domestic-violence victims unable to afford
it. Volunteers and financial donors said they will help restore
both victims' hopes and their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The program, Faces for the Future, will fund the repair of
facial injuries of women who have escaped abuse and are at little
or no risk of returning to their abuser. To be eligible, women must
demonstrate a commitment to establishing a new life through job
training and education. They also must be unable to afford medical
treatment for the injuries that haunt them with long-term physical
complications and low self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   The program, just under way, is a creation of the Arizona
Foundation for Women, a non-profit Phoenix-based organization. The
foundation raises private funds and matches candidates with
volunteer doctors, dentists and optometrists.
</P>
<P>
   Once approved for the program, women are referred to one of 70
doctors or 30 dentists. The foundation raises money to pay for
medical supplies, hospital stays and lab fees.
</P>
<P>
   Accepted candidates might need something as simple as a new pair
of eyeglasses or as complex as plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ginger Price looks forward to volunteering her dental
services for victims who find it painful or embarrassing to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone has decided to leave an abusive husband and is
looking for a job, crowning a tooth is just out of her realm,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Price believes that restoring a victim's smile is not only a
medical procedure but also an important tool for restoring
self-esteem damaged by years of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Patti, 40, knows it firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   She left her abuser 13 years ago after he hit her in the face
with the butt of a gun. She's undergone the initial screening for
the program and is waiting to find out whether she will be
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that if some of the physical scars are erased, so can
the emotional scars heal,'' Patti said. She described the
self-consciousness she felt facing job interviewers with purple
scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (facial damage) is like something very sacred being taken
from you,'' she said. ``It depleted my self-esteem and affects my
personal and professional life.''
</P>
<P>
   Each victim selected for help by Faces of the Future is matched
with a volunteer to provide emotional support throughout the
treatments; the volunteers also lend practical support, such as
driving victims to appointments or helping write resumes.
</P>
<P>
   Both types of support are vital, coordinator Jan Dahms said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outside appearance doesn't make the person whole,'' she
said. ``You need to feel good about yourself to become a productive
member of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Sommerdevlin, president of the Arizona Foundation for
Women, called Faces for the Future a holistic approach to healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Domestic violence is not simply a matter of someone being
beaten,'' she said. ``It's psychological abuse. When you see the
scars physical violence leaves, it's very dramatic. But the
physical damage is just a symptom of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Faces is one of the few programs aimed at helping
victims establish lives away from their abusers, its volunteers say
it can also act as an incentive for people still trapped in abusive
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It empowers them to feel there is support out there so they
``can'' leave,'' Dr. Neil Rockowitz said. ``I think that just
knowing that we are here serves a purpose for them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
