<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT &LR;      06-16 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-REFORM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MINES ON THE ROAD TO REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 17:
</P>
<P>
   After months of false starts, the House on Wednesday embarks on
a path that could lead to genuine campaign finance reform. Speaker
Newt Gingrich and other foes of change have lined the road with
mines and booby traps, but if reformers counterattack with
discipline and force they can quickly gain the upper hand. The
Shays-Meehan bill, which would ban unlimited ``soft money''
donations to parties and impose other sensible fund-raising limits,
is close to commanding a majority. Supporters need to show right
away that they have the votes to reject dozens of amendments that
the speaker and other obstructionists will try to put forward to
stymie the process.
</P>
<P>
   The first vote Wednesday will be on the false issue of whether
to create a commission to study the problem. We have urged
reformers to reject the commission idea as a diversion, and it is
expected to lose. Next on the agenda will be the bill named for its
main sponsors, Rep. Christopher Shays of Connecticut and Rep.
Martin Meehan of Massachusetts. Republicans are paying it the
ultimate compliment. Fearing that the bill is gaining momentum,
they will try to destroy it by offering dozens and perhaps hundreds
of amendments. They hope the amendments will undercut support for
the bill or at least take up so much of the 18 hours allotted for
debate that time runs out before the bill itself can be passed.
</P>
<P>
   We urge Republicans and Democrats who have spent the last two
years championing reform in principle to seize the moment. They
need to submerge their partisan instincts and reject these
amendments no matter how tempting it may be to go along with them.
Once it becomes clear that there are enough votes to thwart the
obstructionists, it will be harder and harder to carry out the
amendment charade. Amendments targeting unions and progressive
groups and repealing provisions of the Voting Rights Act, for
example, are designed solely to make the reform bill unpalatable to
many members who would otherwise support it. They should be seen
for what they are and be rejected.
</P>
<P>
   If Newt Gingrich, Dick Armey and Tom DeLay had any shame, they
would be embarrassed to oppose campaign reform only one day after
entertaining corporate fat cats, lobbyists and rich donors at a
dinner in Washington that had raised more than $10 million before
it began. If the obstructionists succeed, the fund-raising scandals
will only get worse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
