<HEADER>
A2308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-BRAZILMOROCCO-HNS     06-16 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZILMOROCCO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Brazil flourishes against Morocco, sews up Group A title
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NANTES, France _ Walk through this town, and you see women in
high-heeled sneakers and business suits sitting at cafes writing
poetry, or old men with flowing hair dancing by themselves at
plazas, or young girls in pigtails sitting in parks sketching
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes clear why this eclectic city calls itself ``the
cradle of surrealism.''
</P>
<P>
   It is Paris with an attitude. It is so many things constantly
going on at one time. It is so many creative people and only one
breezy bank on which to walk barefoot along the Loire River.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, Brazil. Welcome, Mayor Ronaldo.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there seemed to be a time and a place for Brazil to
regain its mastery of the surreal, its command of the creative, it
was Tuesday night at Stade de la Beaujoire.
</P>
<P>
   And that is what Brazil did in a 3-0 victory over Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our kind of soccer,'' Brazilian coach Mario Zagallo
said. ``This was a joy. It was happy football.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ronaldo, the awesome goal-scorer and ball-handler who was
among the most vocal critics of the Brazilians' lackluster World
Cup opener last week, was happiness personified. He took matters
into his own hands _ actually, his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo moved the ball crisply through the Morocco defense all
night, freezing defenders with stylish moves and ripping shots from
every angle at a poor, unfortunate goalkeeper named Driss Benzekri,
who probably still is looking for Ronaldo's game-breaking first
shot that whizzed by in a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played good in the first game,'' said Ronaldo, who
ultimately finished with a goal, an assist and countless
breathtaking moves before a crowd of nearly 40,000. ``But good is
not Brazil. We had to be more assertive tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The game could not have turned out better, with all the
near-misses of the 2-1 opening-game win over Scotland last week
turning into direct hits on Tuesday night, beginning with Ronaldo's
first ninth-minute goal.
</P>
<P>
   Against a Moroccan team that played well in its 2-2 opening-game
draw with Norway, Brazil dominated possession and played exactly
the type of soccer that its Samba Kings fandom has come to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a catastrophic start for us tonight against a great
team,'' Moroccan coach Henry Michel said. ``To be down a goal after
10 minutes is difficult, but even more so against Brazil. They were
extraordinary today. They got us down from the start, and then
things got worse and worse for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect kind of match for Brazil and set off a
carnival of sorts both at the stadium and on the streets of Nantes.
</P>
<P>
   Fans dressed in Brazil's green and yellow colors set off
fireworks and rained confetti on the field after the final whistle,
as samba drums echoed off the walls of the stadium and everyone
danced _ including some players, who stayed on to wave at the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   It was a festive and peaceful scene, perhaps exactly what World
Cup organizers needed in the wake of Sunday and Monday's violent
outbursts by English hooligans in the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soccer is a beautiful game, and we were frustrated when we won
(last week). We didn't think we played good soccer,'' said Bebeto,
a veteran Brazilian striker who scored his team's third goal
Tuesday on a nice assist from Ronaldo. ``All this game did was
guarantee that we will move on and play in the next round. But we
were glad we played well and played a beautiful game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, the defending World Cup champion, indeed became the
first 1998 team to be guaranteed a berth in the second round. With
two victories and six points, Brazil has clinched first place in
Group A.
</P>
<P>
   Norway (two points), Scotland (one) and Morocco (one) will vie
next week for the second ticket to the second round out of Group A.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked a lot better today than in our first game, and
that's all we wanted,'' Zagallo said. ``If we get the same people
doing the same things in our coming games, I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Ronaldo and Bebeto, Brazil also got a goal from Rivaldo
early in the second half. Another who dominated was Dunga, a
ball-controlling midfielder whose teamwork with Ronaldo was close
to perfect all night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come out today and show the world the kind of
soccer we should have played last week,'' Ronaldo said. ``We wanted
to play the kind of creative, exciting soccer we expect from
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In Nantes, they came to the right place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
