<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz start delayed
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- John Smoltz's return start has been bumped back a day
to Saturday. That's slightly better than last weekend, when Smoltz
was ready to call the whole thing off.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz will start his first game in four weeks in Montreal
Saturday night, which gives him an extra day's rest and allows
Kevin Millwood to retain a four-day off schedule. None of this
would have happened without an extended series of conversations
with friends and advisers who convinced him that returning to the
mound was best, despite two partially successful re-hab starts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the frustration of not being able to do what I wanted
to,'' Smoltz said. ''I hoped to make some subtle changes that
weren't so subtle. I'd hoped to be able to do it in two starts. I'd
hoped to feel things that you just can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz had worked on throwing a fastball with less elbow stress
and experimented with change-ups, throwing 36 of them in Sunday's
six-inning appearance with the Class A Macon Braves. He doubts he
threw 36 change-ups the entire 1997 season. During the ride back
from Macon that night, though the discomfort in his elbow has
subsided, he began to question if the last month has been a waste
of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''My frustration level was pretty bad, my confidence level was
pretty bad,'' he said. ''I tried to do everything in two starts.
I'd hoped for a miracle to find some ways to pitch differently and
to try to alleviate some (elbow) pressure. That's just very
difficult to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects to be on a 90-pitch limit Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Skip-o-gram
</P>
<P>
   An MRI to Skip Caray's back revealed the announcer is suffering
from a bruised spinal cord, and while that diagnosis allayed some
fears, Caray is still not expected to resume working until next
week. Caray was injured June 10 in a tumble from a treadmill at his
home and underwent a Monday follow-up examination when his back
showed little improvement.
</P>
<P>
   While a June 24 target date versus the New York Yankees has been
penciled in, TBS is still scrambling to fill Caray's chair. Ernie
Johnson Jr. filled in Tuesday night and with Fox Sports South
carrying tonight and Thursday night's games, TBS will rotate its
two spots over the weekend between Pete Van Wieren, Don Sutton and
Joe Simpson. Daron Sutton will fill in on radio broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Moss surgery
</P>
<P>
   Damian Moss, the Australian left-hander who made a strong
impression in spring camp before experiencing elbow problems, will
undergo ligament transplant surgery next Wednesday. Moss threw 10
scoreless innings in his first five appearances this spring.
</P>
<P>
   But he left a March 13 game after feeling something pop in his
elbow, and though a subsequent MRI showed no substantial damage, he
was placed on the DL. A subsequent exam by club orthopedist Joe
Chandler last week showed a tear in the ulnar collateral ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
