<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-ONDECK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: Florida Marlins
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: Fox Sports South, 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: RHP Greg Maddux (9-2, 1.75; 6-1,
2.32 lifetime vs. Marlins) vs. LHP Jesus Sanchez (3-3, 3.97; first
appearance vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: With a win, Maddux would have his 10th in 16 starts. He's
had only one faster start as a Brave, in 1994 when he won 10 in his
first 14 starts. Maddux has four no-decisions but left just one of
those games with a lead; that was in his last start, Friday, when
the bullpen gave up five runs in the ninth to Montreal. Since the
start of May, Maddux has given up 10 earned runs on 45 hits over 68
1/3 innings. He has struck out 53 and walked just 10 in that
period. Take away back-to-back April starts when he gave up 10 runs
to the Colorado Rockies, and Maddux's ERA this year would be 1.08.
Sanchez, acquired from the New York Mets in the Al Leiter deal in
February, has been the best of the seven rookies the Marlins have
tested as starters this season. Although he has had decent run
support _ 4.7 runs in his 10 career starts _ he also has held
opponents to three earned runs or less seven times, remarkable for
a 23-year-old who spent all of last season in the Class AA Eastern
League. Since Sanchez's recovery from 1996 elbow surgery, his
fastball reaches the low 90s in mph, and he causes particular
problems when his hard-breaking slider is working.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
