<HEADER>
A2313 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLFTECH-COX     06-16 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLFTECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    USGA's big decision: Ruling body to weigh in on equipment
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- Whatever happens with today's United States
Golf Association press conference regarding equipment, there's no
likely need to panic. Do expect something long-term, but don't
presume anything immediate. The blue blazers and white caps won't
be riding herd with the 156 participants today, ordering them to
play the first round of the U.S. Open with persimmon woods,
nonperimeter weighted irons, a low-tech golf ball, plaid
bell-bottoms and Ban-Lon shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation has been rampant ever since the USGA said it was
studying possible restrictions on the kind of high-tech, highly
successful equipment that has been helping amateurs and pros all
over the globe come a little closer to figuring out the game of
golf. The USGA is concerned that technology is taking away from
talent and that in 20 years you'll need a 750-yard par-5 to protect
Old Man Par.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting the worst, equipment manufacturers such as Ely
Callaway have been advising consumers to do everything but sleep
with their Big Bertha drivers. It's unlikely, however, that the
USGA, on the eve of its showcase championship, would unload a
blockbuster announcement to cause panic in the golf industry.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, despite theorizing you may have read about oversized,
titanium drivers soon going the way of the T. rex, until the USGA
brass met this past weekend in San Francisco, it had not decided
precisely what would be said at a press conference The Golf Channel
will televise live.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA is not expected to announce any rules changes today.
More likely is the announcement of a USGA task force to study the
equipment matter _ probably containing some people from the golf
industry, to help deflect potential legal problems. Any future
mandates are likely to contain a reasonable grace period, probably
by 2000. Plus, any changes would have to be discussed with Europe's
ruling body, the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be be surprised,'' said USGA senior director of
communications Marty Parkes, ``if the announcement Wednesday is a
dot-all-the-i's, cross-all-the-t's kind of thing. Certainly, we'll
have something to say about the issues, things to look at, some of
the future steps. But if somebody is looking for a Holy Grail or
something that's going to tie everything together comprehensively,
I think they might be disappointed.'' Indeed, the timing of a USGA
decree to potentially affect the golf consumer is puzzling. Golf is
enjoying its biggest boom since the 1960s. People are diving into
the sport by the millions. So what if modern equipment makes it
easier for them and less prone to give up? Is that, well, ``good
for golf?'' And, seriously, what's the difference between the
titanium/graphite age than what happened when golfers stopped
swinging tree branches and discovered steel?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very difficult situation because golf is doing so
well right now that it's like an economy _ you don't want to mess
with it,'' said Gary Player, who, like many older players, agrees
with the USGA's watchdog approach. ``The only disadvantage I see is
that you will never be able to compare golfers. You can never
compare Bob Jones with Jack Nicklaus because one man played with
hickory-shafted clubs and a ball that went 80 yards shorter. You
won't be able to compare Jack Nicklaus with Tiger Woods because
Tiger plays with metal-headed woods and a golf ball that goes 15
yards farther on fairways and greens that are immaculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Hale Irwin, ``I've maintained for years that we should have
our own set of rules and standards. The talent of the player should
speak before the technology. You can go down to Pro Golf Discount
and buy yourself a golf game now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The equipment has gotten out of hand,'' says Tiger Woods.
``Guys who aren't that strong are able to hit the ball over 300
yards. It's one of those things that's leveling out the playing
field. It's not putting demand on shaping shots anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   High-tech equipment is, however, putting demand on courses.
Augusta National, for example, announced last week significant
changes to four holes (Nos. 2, 11, 15 and 17) in an effort to
reward accuracy over distance.
</P>
<P>
   Distance is the number one advantage high-tech equipment offers.
Although oversized, long-shafted titanium drivers might mean just a
few extra yards for some golfers, most pros say they gain an extra
15-20 yards. Golf balls are going farther on their own, too,
although how much is up for debate. There's no denying, however,
the fact that the PGA Tour's average driving distance keeps going
up every year.
</P>
<P>
   And so do golf equipment sales. Golfers spent $2.5 billion on
equipment last year, which explains why Callaway and other
manufacturers are worried about even the slight hint of a ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``A USGA rules change would definitely affect (equipment
sales),'' said Darren Jackson, manager of Golf Warehouse in
Kennesaw. ``It just remains to be seen how much. ... Most players
really don't play under the rules of golf. If you asked everyone
who walks in here if they played in a USGA-sanctioned tournament,
maybe one out of 100 would say yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you've still got people who will walk in and ask for
whatever clubs they saw (professional players) using.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
