<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power outage cancels practice
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The lights were out Tuesday _ but not from good
marksmanship on the eve of the USA Shooting National Championships
at Wolf Creek Olympic Shooting Complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The storm took down my main power source,'' said Duane
Tallman, the chief range officer. ``We've been promised power by
midnight (Tuesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Practice was canceled Tuesday. The shooting range needs power
for the target throwers in the shotgun events and the electronic
scoring system and to give the indoor ranges sufficient light.
</P>
<P>
   Today is a set-up day for running target and a training day for
trap, with competition beginning Thursday in trap.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Rhode, Olympic gold medalist in double trap, and about 50
Georgians are among more than 400 entrants at the championships,
which runs through June 27 and will determine national team
members.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing news
</P>
<P>
   Lightweight Jacob Hudson of Augusta, a 1998 U.S. champion, and
welterweight Ebo Elder of Newnan have been chosen to compete at the
Goodwill Games this summer in New York. Boxing will be held at the
Theater at Madison Square Garden. Other members of the 24-man squad
include two 1996 Olympic alternates -- light-middleweight Darnell
Wilson, 31, and heavyweight DaVarryl Williamson, 29 _ and a pair of
teen medal hopes _ welterweight Larry Mosley, 18, and light
welterweight Ricardo Williams Jr., 16. The U.S. and Russia each
will field two complete teams with separate coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
