<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-PRESCHOOL-ART-2T     06-16 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-PRESCHOOL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATORS AND THE STATES TRY TO SHAPE PRESCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J., Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204. Graphic will
be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (af)  
 By MARY B.W. TABOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For most of this country's history, parents were
content to keep children at home playing in the kitchen until
kindergarten or first grade. Most nursery schools were considered a
luxury of the middle and upper classes. Even Head Start, the
early-education federal program begun in 1965 for poor children,
was long deemed experimental.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, more than half of all mothers of young children
work outside the home, and study after study has shown that the
years before the age of 5 are a crucial learning time. As a result,
the demand for enriching preschool programs _ in which pre-reading
and pre-math are nurtured _ has soared.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, 520,000 children, or 4 percent of the population of 3-
to 5-year-olds, were enrolled in preschool. In 1996, more than 4.1
million in the same age group were enrolled, or 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-K, a squishy term for a wide range of programs offered to
children the year or two before they enter kindergarten, is now at
the top of social and political agendas.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is pushing for early-education initiatives
like scholarships for child-care workers and teachers. On Tuesday,
a House Banking and Financial Services subcommittee held a hearing
on a new bill, nicknamed Kiddie Mac, that would provide Federal
Housing Administration loan guarantees and other help for
child-care and child development centers, including public and
private pre-kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   State governments, at least 30 by most counts, have also been
taking steps to improve options and to set up regulations. Georgia
began earmarking lottery money for pre-programs for all children in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   This coming school year, New York state will give money to
school districts that offer programs to all their 4-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts and Connecticut now have public-private
partnerships aimed at offering pre-K to a growing number of pupils.
And for the first time this year, New Jersey is providing money to
make pre-kindergarten an option for 4-year-olds in 125 districts,
with more to be added in coming years.
</P>
<P>
   But what, in fact, pre-K should consist of is just beginning to
be considered as legislators, educators and parent groups debate
not only issues of curriculum and regulation but also basic
questions like who is best suited to run the program _ private
centers or public schools.
</P>
<P>
   n a strictly legal sense, pre-K may resemble anything from
baby-sitting to group child care to a traditional kindergarten,
depending on the state. In most states, anyone caring for five or
more children for pay must be licensed and follow strict health and
safety rules, from keeping immunization records to limiting the
number of children per supervisor and square foot.
</P>
<P>
   But while states might require a pre-kindergarten program to
provide certain materials, like blocks or markers, it is up to each
center to use the materials in creative ways. In general, teachers
are not required to teach any particular skills, like the alphabet
or counting. For example, New York's new pre-kindergarten programs
``must be educationally based'' and ``promote English literacy,''
among other guidelines, but the requirements are broadly defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really are no specific guidelines for a pre-K curriculum
or even a kindergarten curriculum in this state,'' said Carolyn
Tebbetts, director of the Bright Horizons center in Lyndhurst,
N.J., which enrolls children ranging in age from several weeks to 6
years. The center is one of 155 Bright Horizons sites across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Education of Young Children,
which accredits programs it considers appropriate, says about 6
percent of the nation's 95,000 licensed child-care, or preschool
programs, are accredited. Among those are the larger franchised
centers as well as elite nursery schools, which can use their
credentials to charge fees of $200 or more a week.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing push for such quality assurance for the
programs, and thousands of them are in the process of gaining
accreditation, said Barbara Willer, an association spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has helped spark a debate over who is best suited to
educating the nation's tricycle set, with parents and legislators
pushing school districts to assume responsibility. Many public
schools, strapped for money and space, have been reluctant to take
on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In Cortland, N.Y., a small city in a poor rural county just
south of Syracuse, the school board agreed to provide a
pre-kindergarten program only on the condition that it not cost the
district any extra money. The board is using the state allowance to
hire private child-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do it ourselves, down the road we'll have to add
classrooms to the schools, and there would be a cost,'' said Donald
E. Parks, superintendent of the Cortland city schools.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Those who want enriched preschool programs to be part of the
public school system see it not only as a logical extension of the
commitment to public education but also as an issue of equality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very people who need this kind of early education
experience are the ones whose families can't afford the tuitions of
private preschools,'' said Edward Zigler, a psychology professor at
Yale University and one of those who conceived the Head Start
program. ``The public schools should be the ones taking on the
younger children.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of public-school involvement say school districts
should not pass up the opportunity to prepare 4-year-olds,
something that would make their teaching job easier later on.
Public schools are more experienced in the educational mission than
for-profit national chains, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Private preschool directors argue that their programs are
superior to those of public schools because they are tailored
specifically to the needs and skills of 3- to 5-year-olds and are
not an educational afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   They also complain that turning programs over to public schools
drains the child-care centers of the tuitions needed to keep them
going. Most also provide infant and toddler care, which is so labor
intensive that centers are barely able to break even, said Lynn L.
White, chief executive of the National Child Care Association, a
trade group representing 6,000 licensed centers.
</P>
<P>
   Most pre-kindergarten programs still consists of church-run
nursery schools and mom-and-pop operations, which run on shoestring
budgets. But increasingly, entrepreneurs are getting into the
action.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, child-care and preschool programs have grown as a
market by $2 billion and make up $30 billion, or 5 percent, of the
$665 billion spent on schooling each year.
</P>
<P>
   Some business analysts believe that education, including the
fragmented pre-K market, is an industry ripe for consolidation.
Earlier this spring, Michael R. Milken, the financier who was
convicted of securities fraud, and his new company, Knowledge
Universe, bought the Children's Discovery Centers, which provides
day care, preschool and elementary school programs for over 24,500
children across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the New York buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co.
bought Kindercare Learning Centers, the largest of the for-profit
preschool and child care companies with 1,148 child care centers
throughout the country. And Bright Horizons and Corporate Family
Solutions recently agreed to merge to form one large
early-education company.
</P>
<P>
   Even Salomon Smith Barney, which was bearish on the preschool
market in its education industry report two years ago, upgraded its
assessment in its current report, ``as demographics point to
continued increases in the demand for such services.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more than half of the 3- to 5-year-olds are in programs
outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon at Bright Horizons in Lyndhurst, a handful
of children nestled near a pint-sized desk in an area outfitted
with tape, scissors, a computer keyboard and plenty of paper for
drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Flowers, 35, greeted her 4-year-old daughter with a hug
and explained why she chose a pre-K program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted Taylor in a learning environment,'' Mrs.
Flowers said. ``Taylor was in home care, or day care, before. But I
moved her here because I didn't want her just playing or watching
TV all day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came time for kindergarten, I wanted her to be
prepared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
