<SLUG> BC-BARNEYS-RESIGN-ART-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNEY'S HEIRS TO STEP DOWN AS CO-CHIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob and Gene Pressman, the grandsons of the founder of Barney's
Inc., the luxury fashion retailer, will step down as co-chief
executives as early as this week as part of the company's plan to
emerge from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the reorganization agreement, the two
brothers will receive consulting contracts _ Gene Pressman for the
merchandise operations, and Bob Pressman for the operational side
of the business _ executives involved in the negotiations said
Tuesday. Although they will each retain the title of co-chairman,
each will relinquish the title of chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The company declined to comment Tuesday. Both Pressmans also
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The move is not a complete surprise. Under the plan proposed by
the creditors' committee last month, the brothers each received
only a 1.5 percent equity stake in the reorganized retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Thomas Shull, who was named president of the
company in September, is widely viewed as responsible for
improvements in operating income over the last year. He will take
on the title of chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is an emotionally charged transition for the brothers,
whose grandfather, Barney Pressman, financed the company's first
store at 17th Street and Seventh Avenue in New York by pawning his
wife's engagement ring in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' father, Fred Pressman, took over in the 1950s and
was widely respected in the fashion world as one of the great New
York merchant princes, transforming the business from one of men's
off-price suits to a fashion leader for New York's male fashion
elite. A women's department was added in 1981. Fred Pressman died
in July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gene and Bob Pressman joined the business in the 1970s and
eventually led it on an expansion path that put the store
everywhere from Beverly Hills, Calif., to Asia, with the help of a
partner, Isetan Co. of Japan. Disagreements with Isetan over who
owned the company's crown-jewel stores _ on Madison Avenue, New
York, and in Chicago and Beverly Hills _ fueled the
bankruptcy-protection filing in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, several potential suitors have offered to acquire
the retail chain, most notably Dickson Concepts, a Hong Kong retail
concern that made an offer last summer for the company. But the
company's creditors ultimately decided to make a go of it on their
own.
</P>
<P>
   Suppliers dealing with Barney's will not feel the change
involving the Pressmans. Judy Collinson, the general merchandise
manager for the women's-clothing division, will remain in place,
and Tom Kalenderian, who runs the men's department, will also
continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Bonnie Pressman, Gene Pressman's wife, who
learned the art of merchandising from Fred Pressman, will remain
the retailer's fashion director and perhaps even take on more
responsibilities under the reorganized retailer's plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Pressman is highly regarded by fashion companies for her
fashion sense and mode of doing business. Gene Pressman has often
said that Ms. Pressman's personal aesthetic has helped to define
the store's fashion point of view on the sales floor in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, largely devised by Bay Harbour Management and
Whippoorwill Associates, the two investment firms that own the
largest chunk of the debt of Barney's, a new board will be formed
to decide the future management and determine who will indeed run
the show. The retail industry is buzzing about who besides former
creditors might get a seat on that board, which could end up being
a coveted spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
