<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JURY REJECTS KEYBOARD INJURY CLAIMS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal jury has rejected claims by nine people
that they suffered injuries from using computer keyboards made by
Digital Equipment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, handed up Tuesday by a jury in federal district
court in Brooklyn, reverses in part a 1996 verdict that was seen at
the time as a significant setback for computer makers. But since
then, computer makers have won a number of court victories against
claims that use of keyboards contributes to a variety of arm, wrist
and hand injuries. Such ailments _ known as repetitive stress
injuries _ have become increasingly common in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, lawyers have had a hard time proving in court that those
injuries have been as a result of defects in the design of the
keyboards. By Digital's count, juries have rejected liability cases
against keyboard manufacturers in 30 out of 31 cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is how a keyboard is used, not the keyboard
itself,'' said Thomas Siekman, general counsel of the Compaq
Computer Corp., which completed its acquisition of Digital last
week. ``A hammer, if improperly used, can be quite dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the plaintiffs, Patricia Geressy, had won a judgment of
$5.3 million from a jury in December 1996 for her claims of wrist
injuries while using a keyboard made by Digital. But that judgment
was thrown out by Judge Jack Weinstein of the Federal District
Court in Brooklyn in May 1997, when Digital presented new evidence
that Ms. Geressy's injuries could be attributed to a pre-existing
neck condition.
</P>
<P>
   When a new trial was ordered for that case, eight other
plaintiffs joined the suit. Digital, meanwhile, is continuing to
appeal an award of $274,000 to Jeannette Rotolo for keyboard
related injuries, in a case that was part of the 1996 trial.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing arguments in the trial, which lasted six weeks,
Digital Equipment cited articles in prestigious medical journals
that found ``keyboard use was not a risk factor in carpal tunnel
syndrome,'' a severe wrist debilitation. Digital argued that the
injuries attributed to the keyboards were because of other health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Phillips, the lawyer for the plaintiffs, pointed to
government research that linked repetitive actions, such as the use
of keyboards, to carpal tunnel syndrome and neck injuries. ``This
stuff is not coming out of thin air,'' Phillips said in his
argument. ``This is real and is resulting in surgery and human
suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips did not return calls seeking comment Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
