<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODWARD-DECISION-BOS     06-16 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-DECISION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT UPHOLDS WOODWARD MANSLAUGHTER CONVICTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT   AND JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Closing a chapter in an ordeal that has fueled
international debate about child care and justice for 16 months,
Massachusetts' highest court has upheld the manslaughter conviction
of Louise Woodward in the death of baby Matthew Eappen, but freed
her to go home instead of sending her back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But a new phase began almost immediately. Sunil Eappen, the
baby's father, sued Woodward in federal court Tuesday, demanding
unspecified damages ``for the conscious suffering and wrongful
death'' of his son and seeking to bar her from profiting from the
ordeal. A hearing is set for 2 p.m Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very disappointed,'' Eappen said. ``We had hoped the
court would see beyond the publicity and judge the evidence as a
jury did.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, cloistered with friends in Marblehead, a suburban town
about 25 miles from Boston, for most of the day, was equally
dismayed by the ruling, her lawyers said. The 20-year-old _ later
seen skipping in the yard _ had hoped her felony conviction would
be entirely dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the prosecution nor the defense planned to contest the
court's ruling, which upheld Judge Hiller B. Zobel's surprise
decision last October to reduce a jury's second-degree murder
conviction and spring Woodward from jail.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides joined forces and asked the court to speed up its
standard rulings procedure, so that Woodward can retrieve her
passport and leave the Uunited States, possibly as soon as
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is that she will now begin the rest of her life,''
said defense attorney Harvey A. Silverglate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want her out of this country as soon as possible,'' snapped
Middlesex District Attorney Thomas F. Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal _ which divided the state Supreme Judicial Court on
several key issues _ included strong criticism of several parties
involved in the Woodward case, particularly Middlesex Superior
Court Judge Hiller B. Zobel, who exercised a rare judicial
prerogative while presiding over the case.
</P>
<P>
   In October, after a month-long trial, jurors found Woodward
guilty of murder for Matthew Eappen's death. They faced a difficult
legal construct: in an ``all or nothing'' strategy, the defense
convinced Zobel to eliminate manslaughter as an option, hoping to
avoid a compromise verdict.
</P>
<P>
   That left the jury a choice: convict Woodward of first- or
second-degree murder, or set her free.
</P>
<P>
   The jury settled on second-degree murder. The verdict, which
carries a mandatory minimum sentence of life in prison with parole
eligibility after 15 years, raised passions on both sides of the
case.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Judge Zobel's next move that transformed the Woodward
case into an international spectacle, complete with dogmatic
websites, mushrooming legal foundations and protests on two
continents and both sides of the case.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 10, ten days after the verdict, Zobel overrode the jury
and reduced the conviction to manslaughter. He then sentenced her
to the 279 days she had already spent in jail and set her free.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides immediately appealed. The prosecution contended Zobel
overstepped his bounds by tossing out the jury's verdict, while the
defense maintained Woodward should not have been convicted at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a wide-ranging, 46-page opinion written by Justice Margaret
H. Marshall, the SJC voted 7-0 that the judge was within his power
to change the jury verdict, ruling that the courts have a
``responsiblity to ensure that the result in every criminal case is
consonant with justice.''
</P>
<P>
   But the justices chastized Zobel for going along with the
defense's all-or-nothing strategy, which removed manslaughter from
the jury's options.
</P>
<P>
   Zobel later compensated for the mistake by reducing the verdict,
ensuring the system did not treat Woodward too harshly. But he
never should have eliminated the charge in the first place, the SJC
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was peculiarly inappropriate for the judge to refuse to
charge the jury on manslaughter,'' especially in light of
his &UR;  &LR; apparent belief that the evidence did not support a murder
conviction, according to the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors maintained that the baby died when Woodward
violently shook and struck his head against a hard object,
fracturing his skull. But they did not contend he was the victim of
a long history of physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the reported murder and manslaughter convictions in
Massachusetts involving the battery of young children, there was
compelling evidence of multiple injuries ... not death caused by a
single fatal blow,'' according to the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was no evidence in this case of repeated caretaker
abuse, the SJC wrote, Zobel ``did not abuse his discretion'' in
concluding that the murder verdict was out of proportion with
similar cases.
</P>
<P>
   But the SJC split 4-3 on whether the 279-day jail term the judge
imposed was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, manslaughter is punishable by up to 20 years in
prison. In tough language, the dissenters argued that Zobel should
have allowed the victim's relatives speak before he changed
Woodward's sentence to time served.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Justice John M. Greaney, the dissenters also said they
believe Woodward should have been sentenced by a judge other than
Zobel.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by Justice Ruth I. Abrams and Roderick L. Ireland,
Greaney wrote that Woodward also should have been placed on
probation _ including terms barring her from ever working as an au
pair again and preventing her from selling her story for profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not view the judgment against Woodward as a light
matter,'' according to the opinion. ``She stands guilty of causing
an infant's violent death.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Tuesday, District Attorney Reilly
lambasted the SJC's decision not to reinstate the jury verdict, but
took cold comfort in their ruling that Woodward caused Matthew
Eappen's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is clear _ Louise Woodward killed Matty Eappen,'' he
said. ``Twelve jurors, a trial judge and now seven justices of the
high court have found that Louise Woodward is responsible for the
violent death of a little boy, for ending his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reilly said, ``I remain troubled by the sentence ... I
still feel it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverglate was more conciliatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do hope that the Eappen family, at some point, will be able
to open their minds and look at the case in a more disapassonate
way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's defense team vowed to restore her reputation with an
independent scientific study that would prove Eappen's injuries
were not consistent with child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We recognize that there are degrees of injustice and that
the outcome of this case could ahve been much worse of an
injustice,'' said Andrew Good, Silverglate's partner. ``Louise
Woodward maintains her innocence as she always has and she always
will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
