<HEADLINE>
SECLUDED IN MARBLEHEAD, WOODWARD FACES THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHY MCCABE   AND ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARBLEHEAD, Mass. _ Freed from the possibility of returning to
jail, Louise Woodward remained a sort of captive Tuesday, holed up
behind the shuttered windows of a friend's home here, awaiting her
passport before flying home to England.
</P>
<P>
   The object of intense international media attention, Woodward
made only one brief appearance outside the house, joining two
friends for a high-spirited sprint around the backyard. As she
smiled and laughed, a small corps of photographers hustled into
position to record the moment.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Woodward, 20, must stay in the United States, owing to
a legal technicality plus the fact that courts in Suffolk County
will be closed Wednesday in observance of Bunker Hill Day.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's passport was turned over to authorities while the
appeal of her conviction in the death of 8-month-old Matthew Eappen
was pending. The state Supreme Judicial Court Tuesday finally
decided that appeal, affirming her manslaughter conviction and
clearing the way for her departure _ except that the SJC must first
formally file its decision _ which it can't do until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the suggestion of Woodward's defense attorneys, Middlesex
County District Attorney Thomas F. Reilly agreed to request an
expedited filing of the SJC decision. ``The sooner she is gone, the
better,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, as she awaited the SJC decision, Woodward
stayed with Timothy and Jane Hunt, who are active in an
organization that aids British citizens in America.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, friends visited the Hunts. ``She's fine, she's
healthy and she's beautiful,'' one woman said upon exiting the
house.
</P>
<P>
   But also arriving at the the gray clapboard home on Marblehead
Neck were court officials with notice that Louise Woodward had been
named as a defendant in a civil suit filed in federal court by
Deborah and Sunil Eappen.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, a federal marshal handed Woodward a summons to
appear at a hearing on the civil suit today before US District
Court Judge William G. Young. It was not clear whether she would
appear or have a lawyer represent her. Federal courts are open
despite the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The suit seeks to make sure Woodward does not benefit from
selling her story to media outlets _ talk shows, movie producers,
or book publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, Boston defense lawyer Norman Zalkind arrived at
the Hunt's house.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward is legally required to leave the country as soon as her
passport is returned, legal specialists say, because the visa that
allowed her to enter the country under an au pair contract had
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Services officials said that if
Woodward wants to later come back to the United States, she would
have to apply for entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elements of her conviction would be reviewed to see if it
was a crime of violence and if she should be admitted to the
country,'' said William Strassberger, an INS spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In England Tuesday, officials said Woodward's future prospects
in employment would not be harmed by her conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposite is likely to happen,'' said Andrew Miller, the
member of Parliament for Woodward's home district of Cheshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the families she knows will hire her as a child
minder,'' he said. ``I don't think anyone has lost faith in her
whatsoever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
