<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2341 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-u.s.open-HNS &LR;      06-16 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-u.s. </SLUG>
 open-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Even Tiger takes back seat 
to `person in the golf cart'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ It was almost like old times Tuesday for the boys
from Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods and Casey Martin played a practice round together at
the Olympic Club, a site they visited on countless occasions when
they were members of the Stanford golf team. It really wasn't that
long ago when the two were collegians, worrying about exams,
professors and beating up on rival teams.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, perhaps it was a lifetime ago for the pair, who have
found fame in the world of professional golf for two very different
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Woods entered this 1998 U.S. Open with all of the fuss and
fanfare that has accompanied him everywhere he has gone since he
left Stanford and turned professional in 1996, taking the PGA Tour
by storm. There was the usual collection of security guards and
police watching his every move, and scores of fans shouted his name
as he made his way around the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   But just as intense was the activity surrounding Martin, who is
possibly the only golfer in the world currently capable of taking
the spotlight off Woods. Martin doesn't have the game of Woods or
the flamboyant air of Woods or the track record of Woods, but he
entered his first Open as at least as big of a story as the
superstar with whom he played side by side at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was asked how it felt coming into a week being only the
second-biggest story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is great,'' he replied, flashing his famous smile.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, meanwhile, would love the attention if it were coming
because of his golf game. But it isn't. And Martin is at peace with
that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, that day will come,'' Martin said. ``That is going
to happen because of playing well. And if that does happen, that
will be great. If it doesn't, I understand why. And I just accept
that. I will always probably be known as `the person in the golf
cart.' And I can handle that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am grateful for the opportunity to be out here competing.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Martin is a lot of things to a lot of people.
He's the person in the golf cart. The little guy who went up
against the PGA Tour and won. The hero of the disabled. The
inspiration for everyone who has been told he or she couldn't do
something. The man who, against all odds, is playing in the 1998
U.S. Open Championship using a golf cart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing how things happen,'' Martin said. ``I would have
never dreamt it. I am just thrilled to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin made himself a household name earlier this year when he
took the PGA Tour to court in order to be allowed to use a golf
cart in competition. Martin was born with a rare circulatory
disorder in his right leg and doesn't have the stamina to withstand
the rigors of walking a golf course. But he has the game to compete
on the professional level.
</P>
<P>
   So Martin sued the tour and won, playing on the Nike Tour with
the use of a cart. And the USGA decided to accept that ruling for
the Open as well, allowing Martin the use of a cart in qualifying
and this week in the championship.
</P>
<P>
   If they hadn't, Martin said he would never have played.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had not extended me the golf cart, I would not be
playing, because I just would not have done that,'' Martin said.
``I was not in the position to pursue legally against them. I am
not saying I couldn't have won or not, but I just wasn't willing to
go through that.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the use of a cart, it hasn't been easy for Martin.
The USGA originally wanted Martin to use a specially designed
single-rider cart, but it proved to be nothing but trouble. On
Monday, Martin's single-rider cart broke down twice during his
practice round, at one time forcing Martin to walk three holes.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the USGA agreed to let Martin use a conventional
cart during tournament play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided from a safety standpoint, especially from a
spectator-safety standpoint, that we are better off providing the
regular, traditional golf cart for Casey, and we think that is the
right thing to do,'' said USGA official Mike Butz.
</P>
<P>
   While the use of a cart continues to be a subject of great
controversy on tour, Martin said he has received nothing but
support from fans and players this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without exception, everyone has been just extremely kind to me
and extending me support,'' Martin said. ``It has been great. It
has been a great experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are a number of players who are against the idea of
a cart being used in competition. Among the most vocal is Jack
Nicklaus, and Tom Watson concurs but maintains he feels
``compassion'' for Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Martin was not without his supporters, his former teammate
from Stanford to name just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is great that he played,'' Woods said. ``He
qualified. He earned his way out here. And he is going to go out
here and play a golf course that he is familiar with. I think it is
great. It shows a lot of courage on his part to deal with all of
the things that he has had to deal with, with the lawsuit and all
the distractions, while trying to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to be able to go out and qualify, especially the way he
did, that shows a lot of guts. That is what he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   The words were especially meaningful coming from Woods on
Tuesday afternoon. On Tuesday morning, Martin sank a pretty putt
for birdie on No. 18 that won him all the ``skins'' in the
unofficial match that Woods and Martin played during their practice
round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Woods said with a grin, ``I was taken for some cash
today.''
</P>
<P>
   And he never enjoyed paying more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
