<SLUG> BC-GLF-U.S.-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING CHAMPION ELS SAYS HIS BACK REMAINS SORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ernie Els has resigned himself to playing this
year's U.S. Open with a sore back.
</P>
<P>
   Els, the defending champion, has been undergoing treatment since
he abruptly pulled out of the Buick Classic last Thursday, after
playing nine holes of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But during a news conference Tuesday at the Olympic Club, Els
admitted that he is not 100 percent, and the world's No. 2-ranked
player was obviously disappointed that he will not be at full
strength when the year's second major begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the way you want to feel playing in a major
tournament,'' said Els, who also won the U.S. Open in 1994. ``It is
a lot better than it was Thursday, but it is still a day-to-day
thing. Obviously, it is the wrong timing for me to get this kind of
injury.''
</P>
<P>
   Els said his back has been bothering him for three weeks, and
that the spasms worsened last Wednesday. The pain is in his lower
back, near the left side of his spine, and while it is expected to
clear up with treatment, the healing process may take three or four
weeks. Els is being treated by Tom Boers, a noted back specialist
who works with Fred Couples, Davis Love III and several other
professional golfers.
</P>
<P>
   The injury could make Els tentative when hitting from Olympic's
five-inch-deep rough. He did not hit a golf ball last weekend, and
even after Tuesday's practice round, he did not plan to work on the
driving range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have really got to take it easy,'' he said. ``When you feel
the pain, you don't want to aggravate it more.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Els sounded worried, Tiger Woods sounded confident.
Woods, the world's No. 1-ranked player, has also been dealing with
back trouble recently, and he withdrew from the Kemper Open two
weeks ago. But Woods declared himself at full strength Tuesday. And
after struggling to a tie for 19th last year, he was eager to
disprove criticism that his game does not suit the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like when people say that,'' said Woods, who has spent the
past week fine-tuning his game with his coach, Butch Harmon. ``It
definitely gets me a little revved up. My preparation has been very
intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said his recent back pain was nothing serious, and was
mostly caused by jogging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing a lot of golf, and I was doing a lot of
roadwork,'' he said. ``All of a sudden, I went from no miles to
running four, five, six miles every day. That puts a little stress
on your back, and I felt a little twinging, a little tightening,
and a couple of spasms. I decided to pull out of Kemper, saw my
trainer, and basically just stretched it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Woods will face a severe test this week, as will everyone
in the field. Olympic's Lake course puts a premium on accuracy
instead of distance. Not only are the fairways lined by deep rough,
but they slope to either side. During Tuesday's practice rounds,
many balls that landed in the fairway still rolled into the rough.
And with sunny weather predicted all week, the course should play
even faster by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When the Olympic Club last held the U.S. Open, in 1987, Scott
Simpson won with a final score of 277, three under par. Don't look
for anything lower this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year, we are going to see over par win the
tournament,'' said Tom Watson, who finished one stroke behind
Simpson in 1987. ``The rough is the most difficult I have seen in
the U.S. Open. You are lucky to be able to move it 50 or 60
yards.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, players will continue adjusting to the nuances of
Olympic. And when the first round begins Thursday, most players
expect a wide-open tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty guys could win this tournament,'' Simpson said. ``That
always cracked me up when guys said there are five or 10 guys who
could win. You've got to be kidding me. A lot of guys have a shot
at it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
