<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A BRONX CHEER, GRAMMYS GO WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With a playful but pointed rebuke to New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the head of the organization that runs the
Grammy Awards announced Tuesday that next year's event would be
held in Los Angeles, at the Shrine Auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as no surprise in the wake of a
high-profile feud earlier this year between Giuliani and Michael
Greene, the head of the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences. The dispute ended with the mayor stating that New York
doesn't need the Grammys. ``If they want to go to L.A., they can,''
he said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the Grammy Awards have alternated between Los
Angeles and New York, with each city competing for the increase in
tourism, revenue and publicity the ceremony brings with it. For the
past two years, the Grammy Awards have been held in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And despite his differences with Giuliani, Greene said the
ceremony would continue to alternate between the two cities.
</P>
<P>
   What was a surprise was the way the announcement was handled.
Instead of trying to downplay the conflict, which began when
Giuliani accused Greene of verbally abusing a mayoral aide during
the preparation for a press conference last January, Greene and Los
Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan gloated.
</P>
<P>
   The press conference began with the Grammy-winning producers
David Foster and Phil Ramone, who is also the chairman of the
Grammy organization, playing piano as a choir sang a New
York-bashing song, a variation of Randy Newman's ``I Love L.A.,''
that began, ``Oh, New York City, it's cold and it's damp. And all
those cabbies act so grumpy. Let's leave Manhattan to the
Eskimos.''
</P>
<P>
   Fanning the flames of rivalry higher, Riordan said in a speech
that ``a certain Rudy'' boasted on ``Late Show With David
Letterman'' that New York can kick any other city in the rear. But,
Riordan pointed out, ``I'm here to tell you that you have to be
behind somebody'' to kick them in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``And L.A. is far ahead of anyone when it comes to music,'' he
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite this ribbing and the criticism he has weathered for
alienating the Grammys over a personal matter, Giuliani was
unrepentant. ``Well, I wasn't too disappointed that they left,'' he
said from City Hall on Tuesday. ``I thought the person who ran the
Grammys was abusive and, you know, the city had a record year for
tourism last year. It's going to have a record year for tourism
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people from the entertainment business didn't agree with
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a shame,'' Judy West, a spokeswoman for Local 802
of the American Federation of Musicians, which represents 10,000
musicians in New York City and on Long Island, said about the loss
of the Grammys. ``New York is supposedly the cultural capital of
the world. It belongs here. It brings in $40 million, which you
can't just write off with the flick of your wrist.''
</P>
<P>
   (Though other organizations have also estimated the city's
revenue at $40 million, the New York City Convention and Visitors
Bureau has said the figure is actually $23.2 million.)
</P>
<P>
   With construction of the Staples arena, which will be larger
than Shrine Auditorium, scheduled to be completed at the end of
this year, Los Angeles city officials said they had hoped the new
building would become a new permanent home for the Grammys. In an
interview after the press conference, however, Greene said that he
had received phone calls from every major record label asking him
to bring the Grammys back to New York in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, however, isn't ready to campaign for the Grammys to
return to New York, as he has in the past, saying that he wasn't
``going to work too hard on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they change their behavior, we'll be really happy to have
them back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute between the Grammys and Giuliani administration
comes at a turbulent time for Greene and the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences. Over the past year, the accuracy of
the National Academy's reports of its philanthropic activities has
been called into question as has an investigation by the National
Academy clearing Greene of sexual harassment charges, which Greene
denies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
