<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0452 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINES-CABLECAR-NYT &LR;      06-16 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINES-CABLECAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE CITES SPLIT ON JET ACCIDENT REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ One of the authors of a Marine report that
blamed a jet's Italian ski-lift cable accident on crew error
testified on Tuesday that the investigating board was divided over
how to apportion responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Thomas Blickensderfer, a defense witness at a hearing to
determine what charges should be brought against the pilot and the
navigator of the Marine jet, also said that the plane might have
been too low because of an optical illusion induced by flying from
a narrow valley into a broader one. He said that in the
investigation of the Feb. 3 accident, in which 20 people in a
gondola died, he retraced the route in a simulator several times
and faced the same illusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down to just a few hundred feet, without even knowing
it,'' said Blickensderfer, who is the director of operations at the
Cherry Point Marine base in Havelock, N.C., where the crew was
based.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, might have
seen the uppermost of six cables and believed it was the only one,
misjudged its height and dived to get under it.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing ended on Tuesday after two days that centered on
Ashby and his navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, and four days
last month that focused on the electronic warfare officers in the
back seat, Capt. William Raney II, and Capt. Chandler Seagraves.
</P>
<P>
   The investigating officer, Lt. Col. Ronald Rodgers, will write a
recommendation on what charges should be brought in a court
martial. Rodgers must decide whether the crew's action could
constitute involuntary manslaughter, defined as involving ``a
negligent act or omission which, when viewed in the light of human
experience, might foreseeably result in the death of another.''
They could also be tried for negligent homicide, a lesser offense,
and other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers did not say when he would file his report, but under
military rules he must give a decision in the case of the two
back-seat officers later this month. A court martial could come in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony on Tuesday, Blickensderfer faulted the Air Force
for failing to keep the Marine aviators well informed about local
rules and conditions as they rotated through the Aviano air base,
where the Prowler jet involved in the crash was based. He said the
Marine squadrons had done a poor job of keeping their files current
on flight information, and weeding out old materials.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the accident, local rules set a minimum height
above ground level of 2,000 feet but everyone in the Marine
squadron said that they believed it was 1,000 feet, and some of the
material on file in the flight operations center gave an even lower
number for some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Blickensderfer said that if he had conducted the investigation
alone, ``I would have done a lot of things differently,'' and that
the report, released in March, had been rewritten repeatedly to
gain consensus.
</P>
<P>
   One issue in the hearing was why the Marines Corps did not
follow the usual practice in such incidents, which is to quickly
convene a safety investigation, offering immunity to the crew in
exchange for their description of what happened, and then to
conduct a separate criminal investigation. Defense lawyers accused
the Corps of being more interested in prosecution than in
preventing a repetition of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   That position was supported in part by Blickensderfer. He
testified that he had been told by Gen. Michael Ryan, the commander
of all the Prowler squadrons, that there would be no such safety
investigation because Italian Premier Romana Prodi had warned
President Clinton in a telephone conversation, ``You Americans may
never operate out of Italy again.''
</P>
<P>
   Top Defense Department officials were afraid that an offer of
immunity in a safety investigation would outrage the Italians,
Blickensderfer said.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments, lawyers for the defendants said that
Rogers should recommend dropping the charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Maj. Vernon Couch, a prosecutor, said the crew must have
deliberately broken the rules. They thought they were supposed to
be at 1,000 feet, he said, but hit a cable at 264 feet. ``It is not
a mere mistake,'' he said. ``You just don't blink your eyes and get
down 634 feet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
