<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-VETO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. CITY COUNCIL OVERRIDES MAYOR TO RESTORE FUNDS TO BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAN BARRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sounding at times both righteous and wary, the City
Council voted Tuesday to override the vetoes of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, restoring roughly $200 million to the first budget in
memory to be passed without the mayor's consent.
</P>
<P>
   As the cheers and applause of social service advocates rained
down on them from the Council Chamber mezzanine, council members
took turns declaring personal pride in voting, 44-7, to override
the mayor's vetoes. In addition to fighting for the after-school
programs, the centers of the elderly and other items that would
have been cut, they said they were sending a message to Giuliani:
The legislative branch of city government is no longer fearful of
exercising its powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm calling upon the other side of the hall finally to make
peace now,'' said the council speaker, Peter Vallone. ``Stop the
missiles coming from the other end. This is now the law _ the law
for every citizen of this city. It will be the law as soon as we
override. And once that law takes effect, no one person in this
city _ no matter who he or she is _ is above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But beneath all the hurrahs and lectern-pounding ran an
undercurrent of fear. By adopting their own $34 billion budget, the
council members were well aware of Giuliani's promise to exact
vengeance by freezing spending and delaying contracts with various
nonprofit agencies.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday, at the same time that the Democrat-controlled
council was ceremoniously rebuking him, the mayor reiterated the
threat. He said that once the new fiscal year began on July 1, he
would take steps to contain what he called an irresponsible budget,
stuffed with special-interest spending, that will bloat the city's
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too late for negotiations,'' the mayor said. ``We will
carry out the powers that the City Charter gives the mayor to hold
spending back, which I'm allowed to do, and there are several
different ways in which I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Jones, the deputy director of Neighborhood Defender
Service, a group in Harlem that provides legal services to 2,500
families a year, was one of several advocates who voiced fears that
the budget battle could curtail or eliminate their programs. He
said that the mayor's vetoes had wiped out 80 percent of the
group's annual budget of $2.5 million; the rest came from the state
and was recently vetoed by Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue for us is what happens now,'' Jones said.
``We're going to close if the mayor starts impounding funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns like those of Jones are why Madeline Provenzano, a
Democratic council member from the Bronx, told her colleagues that
``I don't share in the joy.'' Although she was also voting to
override the mayor's vetoes, she said, his inevitable response
``makes me very nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that Giuliani keeps his promise to freeze spending or
cancel contracts, council leaders say they will sue _ a day in
court that the mayor's aides say they eagerly await. Until then,
both sides continue to blame each other in trying to explain why a
budget with a $2 billion surplus has become so contentious.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute comes down to the city's two highest-elected
officials, who accuse each other of following agendas that have
little to do with the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone once again said that the budget impasse occurred because
he refused to drop his call for a referendum on whether tax money
should pay for a stadium in Manhattan for the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor's focused on one thing and one thing only,'' the
speaker said at a news conference, his tone suggesting a struggle
to contain his incredulity. ``It's the most important thing in his
life, it's the most important thing for this city: that we must
find a way to relocate Yankee Stadium from the Bronx to
Manhattan.''
</P>
<P>
   And Giuliani once again suggested that all of Vallone's recent
actions _ from the referendum to the budget _ were designed to aid
his campaign for governor. ``This is a gubernatorial election-year
budget on behalf of the speaker,'' he said. ``That's the whole way
it's played out today. It's almost like a convention, not a City
Council hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Once talks collapsed, the two sides began to play budgetary
chess, using the City Charter for their rule book. First came the
council's adoption of its own budget, which was virtually identical
to the one presented by the mayor, save for some tax-cut proposals.
Then came Giuliani's vetoes of about $201 million from the expense
budget, $315 from the capital budget, and $165 million from a
debt-retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday came the expected veto override. But no matter how
predictable the council's recent actions may have appeared,
political analysts and council members say, they reflect an unusual
display of independence and strength.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Schwarz Jr., the chairman of the charter revision
commission that in 1989 changed the structure of city government,
said that one of the goals of the panel was to give the council
more say in the budget and in land use. Previously, the council had
been seen by some as a haven for those who bartered in patronage
and pork.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to have a council that was a strong counterweight to
a strong Mayor and we thought that the council could be the more
representative body,'' Schwarz said. ``You want an executive who is
checked, and the best way to do that is with a popularly elected
legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schwarz and others say, the council took its time in
fully realizing its new-found powers. ``I think that they've begun
to do well in lots of fields,'' he said. ``But it's been clear that
over the last eight to 10 years, they've needed to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   The council and Vallone have often been accused of not
challenging Giuliani enough on past budget issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
