<SLUG> BC-STAMPS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS OF PHOENIX RESIDENTS EXPECTED TO REAPPLY FOR FOOD
STAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ More than 4,000 Arizona residents are expected to
reapply for food stamps after Congress voted this month to restore
the benefits to needy legal immigrants over 64 and under 19 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000 are among 13,000 Arizona residents of all ages who
lost their food stamps in September after federal lawmakers
stripped legal immigrants of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't expect the food stamps to arrive until they are
shopping for Christmas dinner. Eligible legal immigrants won't be
able to apply until November. It takes about 30 days to process the
application and get the benefits to each individual, Department of
Economic Security officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the delay, many are applauding the move as a first step
in the right direction. About 250,000 older and younger legal
immigrants across the country are expected to reapply for food
stamps, or 30 percent of those who lost benefits last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's got to be a tremendous help,'' says Ginny Hildebrand,
executive director of the Association of Arizona Food Banks, ``not
only to them but to the emergency food network.''
</P>
<P>
   After Congress voted to make legal immigrants ineligible for
food stamps, 18 states voted to continue to pay for those benefits
out of state funds. Arizona was not among them, and the state's
food banks were flooded with families suddenly unable to put food
on the table. Southern Arizona food banks are especially hard-hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't come soon enough,'' says Ronna Sue Stubbs, executive
director of Yuma Community Food Bank, about the restoration. The
demand for emergency food boxes in her food bank has jumped 40
percent over June 1997, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Economic Security officials say they will rely on
food bank officials to help them design an outreach program to find
eligible individuals and make sure they reapply for benefits. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
