u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANK-BILL-NYT &LR;      06-16 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSAGE APPEARS UNLIKELY FOR BANKING BILL THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration on Tuesday all but
doomed efforts to update the United States' financial-services law
this year, saying that it would not budge from its opposition to
the bill passed last month by the House and that it wanted to start
over next year.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury Department official, speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said the administration saw no prospect of compromise
among the banking, securities and insurance industries, each of
which wants something slightly different from the proposed
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more important, the official said the Treasury
Department saw little or no chance of coming to an agreement with
the Federal Reserve Board over one of the most contentious issues
surrounding the bill: whether Treasury or the Fed should be the
primary bank regulator.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill, which passed by one vote and faces a veto threat
by the White House, would effectively strip the Treasury of its
power to oversee national banks and shift considerable authority to
the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin is scheduled to outline the
administration's position on Wednesday at a hearing before the
Senate Banking Committee. The committee's chairman, Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., has been exploring whether there is enough common
ground within the industry and between the regulatory bodies to
move ahead with a Senate version of the bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been under pressure from Wall Street, insurers and
some big banks to try to rush a bill through the Senate this year
and end a decades-long stalemate in Congress over updating the
Depression-era laws that erected barriers between banks, brokerage
firms and insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Big mergers such as the proposed combination of Citicorp and
Travelers Group have added to pressure from the industry to have
the law recognize the rapid changes sweeping the financial-services
market.
</P>
<P>
   But in signaling Tuesday that it is unwilling to compromise at
this point, the administration has given D'Amato no room to find a
workable solution.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury official said the administration continued to
support efforts to modernize the legislation. But he said the
administration wanted to begin a new effort next year, a strategy
that would allow it to avoid using the House version of the bill as
a starting point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think time is needed to work out the consensus this bill
ought to have,'' the Treasury official said. ``With relatively few
days left in this session, it's not likely that thoughtful
attention to these issues will be possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
