<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-PAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGE FIRES BACK AT DUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; COSTA MESA -- One day after the Mighty Ducks finished the
Pierre Page chapter of the team's history by firing the coach, Page
fired back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite what (Anaheim general manager) Jack (Ferreira) said
yesterday I don't believe what he says,'' Pagee said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Page and Ferreira's relationship goes back 18 years, but Page
said being fired by a friend wasn't nearly as upsetting as the
reason he gave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to God that you didn't bring me here because I was your
friend,'' Page said he told Ferreira on Monday. ``I hope you
brought me here because you knew I could do the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind you firing me even though I'm one of your
friends, but don't tell me it was philosophical differences. There
is something else. If you don't want to tell me the real reason
that's your choice, but I don't buy this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent differences, especially in player personal matters,
werethe main factors in Page's dismissal, according to Ferreira,
but Tuesday Page insisted he was just trying to help the club from
retaining the status quo, something he said Ferreira had expressed
grave concerns about over the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him `don't worry, I'll keep pushing, I'll disagree with
you, I'll disagree with anybody, just keep pushing to make sure
things keep happening,''' explained Page, who says he has no
regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy in our business to be quiet ... the best thing in
life is to stand up and be counted and if it means moving on, it
means moving on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that being fired doesn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement was like being knocked down and the season
was like being knocked down,'' said Page. ``I have a hard time
believing they brought me in for one year. I was more than shocked,
but this is what this business is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be frustrated, disappointed, but I don't have the right
to be the Ducks coach, I'd just like to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he came to Anaheim confident he could get the job done,
Page, 50, admitted he was never able escape Ron Wilson's sizeable
shadow -- even after the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   He hinted that Wilson's run to the Stanley Cup Finals might have
put the final nail in his coffin.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end it seemed like I was going to be here and we were
going to find solutions together,'' Page said. ``(But) I think
every round Ron Wilson won it seemed to take a different course.
There was a lot of heat in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to believe you rejoice in the success of others, but
it created a lot of pressure in the organization and from what I
read in the papers yesterday fans and media seemed to be happy the
organization admitted they made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Page admits his mistake might have been looking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Jack for 18 years, but maybe it was a mistake,'' he
said of joining forces with his old boss. ``Never try to go back to
the past, always look ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira was unavailable for comment. The Ducks' executive was
attending the NHL general managers meetings, which are taking place
in Washington D.C., where Wilson's Washington Capitals and the
Detroit Red Wings were playing Game 4 of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
