<HEADER>
A2364 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLAN-JASPER-COX     06-16 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAN-JASPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klan to hold rally in Jasper
 &HT;    By MITCH MITCHELL
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two factions of the Ku Klux Klan have informed Jasper officials
they will be staging a rally 10 days from now in the same place a
prayer vigil for healing was held in the wake of the brutal
dragging death of James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reaction of the community and especially the white people
is fear and shame,'' Jasper Ministerial Alliance President Bobby
Hudson said. ``They want this thing to die, to go away. They don't
want this town to be totally divided.''
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney Gary Gatlin said Michael Lowe of Waco, regional
director of the Texas Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, contacted him
Monday and Tuesday to tell him the Klan would hold a rally between
noon and 2 p.m. June 27 at the Jasper County Courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said the Klan has been taking a beating in the press and
members of both groups, the Knights of the Ku Klux Klan and Knights
of the White Kamellia wanted an opportunity to set the record
straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are appalled by this tragic death and we are glad that
arrests were made so quickly,'' Lowe said. ``We hope that if those
in jail are found guilty they are prosecuted to the fullest extent
of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said there are about 80 or 90 different groups under the
KKK umbrella nationwide and about nine of those groups are in
Texas. While Lowe said he cannot speak for all the groups sharing
the KKK name, he insist members of his group and the Knights of the
White Kamellia are not hateful or racist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest is for white people,'' Lowe said. ``The NAACP and
LULAC are targeting a certain group of people. Our group is trying
to make sure (whites) are not discriminated against. The pendulum
has swung too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said he could not deny the violent past of the KKK, but he
compared that organization's past to organized religion's past,
saying that organized religion had violent and cruel periods such
as the Crusades. Lowe said their intention is not to display any
firearms and not to use any racial slurs.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper officials expect between 15 and 20 participants at the
rally, Gatlin said. This all comes in the aftermath of a prayer
vigil and funeral townspeople hoped would go a long way toward
healing wounds caused by a grisly murder authorities say was
racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, a 49-year-old black man, was chained to the back of a
pickup and dragged for three miles, authorities said. His head and
right arm were severed from his body during the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, of Sulphur Springs, and Jasper
residents Shawn Allen Berry and John William King, both 23, have
been charged with murder and are being held in Jasper County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to say that these two men are not part of their
groups and they denounce what they have done,'' Gatlin said.
</P>
<P>
   But others are more suspicious of the groups' intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are sincere, they must atone for the sins of the Klan
in the past and help the black man and woman toward freedom,
justice and equality,'' Robert Muhammad, Southwest regional
director of the Nation of Islam said in an interview with The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just condemning what happened to Mr. Byrd is not good enough,
because the history of the Klan since its founding has been one
that rivaled and exceeded what happened to Mr. Byrd,'' Muhammad
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said plans have been set in place to deal with the Klan
rally and the community is prepared for whatever the situation
brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the white leaders in the community to stand up for the
community just like we did when the black militants came to town,''
Hudson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson said there is concern that the appearance of white
supremacists might bring other black militants to town. Jasper was
visited by representatives of the Black Muslim Movement Friday and
the New Black Panther Party came to town on Saturday after Byrd's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   The New Black Panthers embarked on an armed march throughout the
city after Byrd's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white ministers must let (the Klan) know that they cannot
separate us,'' Hudson said. ``But our strategy is peace and not in
your face.''
</P>
<P>
   On an Internet Web site message, the Vidor-based Knights of the
White Kamellia described itself as a ``legal, law-abiding, white
rights organization that does not condone violence in any form,''
an Associated Press story said.
</P>
<P>
   The group also claimed to have a chapter in Jasper County since
1996. Vidor is 55 miles south of Jasper in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Because the courthouse square is a public area, the groups did
not need permission for the rally, Gatlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
