<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 6/16/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 16, 1998 -- BARNEYS-RESIGN, 6-16 -- Bob
Pressman, left, and his brother, Gene, the grandsons of the founder
of Barney's Inc., the luxury fashion retailer, will step down as
co-chief executives as early as this week as part of the company's
plan to emerge from bankruptcy. The two joined Barney's in the
1970s and eventually put stores everywhere from Beverly Hills to
Asia. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HICKSVILLE, N.Y. -- June 16, 1998 -- NY-LILCO-SEVERANCE,
6-16 -- Dr. William Catacosinos, former chairman of the Long Island
Lighting Co., now chairman of Marketspan, in his office.
Marketspan, the product of a merger between Lilco and Brooklyn
Union Gas, supplies the electricity, management and workforce to
operate the old Lilco system. A week after the takeover, the power
authority disclosed that Lilco had made secret payments to 26
executives. Catacosinos, the prime beneficiary, received $42
million. (Vic DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- June 16, 1998 -- PAUL-SOROS-PROFILE, 6-16 --
Paul Soros, 71, the older brother of George, the 67-year-old
financier-philanthropist famous for giving away nearly $2 billion.
Last month Paul Soros and his wife, Daisy, made their first foray
into major philanthropy when they announced the establishment of a
$50 million trust to help underwrite American graduate education
for immigrants and their children. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LATHAM, N.Y. -- June 16, 1998 -- ENERGY-TECHNOLOGY, 6-16
-- Using a laptop computer, senior consultant Dan Jones, left, and
project manager Richard Maddaloni check the prototype Plug Power
7000 Residential Fuel Cell System. For the first time, an energy
technology called a fuel cell will supply all the power to a
suburban house, another sign that the innovation is on the verge of
acceptance as an economical alternative to traditional energy
sources. (David Jennings/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- June 16, 1998 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 6-16 --
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told the Senate
Appropriations foreign operations subcommittee Tuesday that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had failed to meet most of
the U.S. demands in his treatment of ethnic Albanians in the tense
Serbian province of Kosovo. Ms. Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen have said that Washington would act alone and without
a resolution, if necessary. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LYNDHURST, N.J. -- June 16, 1998 -- EDUC-PRESCHOOL, 6-16
-- Brenda Bingham and Taylor Flowers playing with dominoes at the
Bright Horizons day care center in Lyndhurst, which enrolls
children ranging in age from just weeks old to 6 years old.
Tuesday, a House Banking and Financial Services subcommittee held a
hearing on a new bill, nicknamed Kiddie Mac, that would provide FHA
loan guarantees and other help for child-care and child development
centers, including public and private pre-kindergarten. (Frank C
Dougherty/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAPPORO, Japan -- June 16, 1998 -- JAPAN-ISLANDS, 6-16 --
The Therme International Hotel, a grand resort in Hokkaido, has
everything but guests. It is suffering because of Japan's growing
economic troubles, which are nowhere more stark than on Hokkaido.
``This is a very difficult time for us,''says Kimihiko Shimada, a
manager who will soon have to start looking for a job, as 240
former employees at Therme did. ``Of all the employees, only half
have found new jobs.'' (Stuart Isett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- VILLA-VILLA-REVIEW, 6-16 --
Performers of the Argentine theater company De la Guardia hang over
the audience in ``Villa Villa'' at the Daryl Roth Theater. The
65-minute work is staged without a stage, as the audience stands in
a room like a crowd at a rock club; the music makes its way up to
rock-concert volume, moving from pearly New-Age prettiness to hints
of gamelans and African thumb pianos to pounding drums and howling
voices. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- BRAILLE-WINE-LABELS, 6-16 --
Michel Chapoutier, a well-known maker and shipper of Rhone wines,
has put Braille labels on all his premium wines, including
appellations like Hermitage, Crozes-Hermitage, Condrieu,
St.-Joseph, Cote Rotie and, this wine, Chateauneuf-du-Pape. His
reasoning is that blind customers want the same information that
other wine lovers look for on a bottle, (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- CHINA-COOKING-2, 6-16 --
Presentation is important in Chinese food preparation as seen in
the banquet platter. The Chinese, unlike Americans tend to go out
in groups to eat. ``The Chinese go in groups, it's a cuisine of
sharing,'' explains Michael Tong, the owner of Shun Lee Palace and
Shun Lee West. ``In a Chinese restaurant there are no tables for
two or four; there are only big tables and private rooms.''(David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- CHINA-COOKING-1, 6-16 -- Sun
Man Do, one of only a few New York chefs trained in Chinese haute
cuisine, cooking eel at Shun Lee Palace. Most chefs of Chinese food
are not trained in China. ``Over the years we must have had 500
chefs coming and going at Shun Lee Palace,'' says Michael Tong, the
owner of Shun Lee Palace and Shun Lee West, both in Manhattan.
``Only 5 percent were trained in China.'' (Boyd Hagen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- FOOD-NOTES, 6-16 -- These
quarts of ripe, luscious strawberries from local farms were lined
up at stands at Manhattan's Union Square Greenmarket last week.
They are more perishable than those from California and should be
available through early July. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BERKELEY, Calif. -- June 16, 1998 -- CHINA-HAUTE-CUISINE,
6-16 -- Enjoying cooking in his own kitchen, Ken Hom, 49, has his
ingredients lined-up and ready. Hom, who is leaving California for
Europe, says that Americans have never given Chinese food the
respect it deserves. In Britain his books are best sellers and his
popular cooking shows on the BBC network have kept him in front of
the public. ``In the U.K., I'm known like Julia Child is here,'' he
says. (Terrence McCarthy/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
