<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2371 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-16 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN'S RIGHT TIME TO QUIT FOR RIPKEN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN.: Md.) 
 (ja) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ As long as we're debating the merits of fading stars
and imminent retirements, let's discuss Cal Ripken Jr., the
Baltimore Orioles' third baseman and baseball's monument to
endurance.
</P>
<P>
   In the years leading up to his breaking Lou Gehrig's record for
consecutive games played, Ripken willed himself into the lineup
every day. Metaphor-prone baseball writers wrote about heroism,
valor and the timeless American Ideal: the laborer who shows up for
work every day with lunch pail in hand.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening seasons things have taken a couple of turns
for the worse _ primarily Ripken's batting and fielding range. Now
the organization can't get Ripken, who is 37, out of the lineup.
Baseball-wise, the Orioles are in a state of paralysis, unable to
go forward or backward because this proud, aging superstar won't
give way.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken, like Michael Jordan, has his own rules: For Ripken, they
include staying at a separate hotel on the road, having his own
doctor, and the power to determine, by himself, that he will be
penciled into the lineup every day.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that Jordan, at age 35, still backs up his
self-made rules.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Yankees and Orioles players watched with millions
across the world as Jordan turned in an exemplary performance,
scoring 45 points and leading Chicago to a sixth National
Basketball Association championship.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the points, when the moment of truth arrived, Jordan
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken hasn't pulled the trigger at the moment of truth since
Sept. 6, 1996. He didn't get a hit to propel Baltimore into a World
Series, or win a Series. His moment of truth came in breaking
Gehrig's record by making his 2,131st consecutive start.
</P>
<P>
   Since then pitchers, apparently no longer fearful of injuring
Ripken, have mercilessly jammed him with inside pitches. He no
longer has the bat speed to pull the ball. When it comes to
production from third basemen, Baltimore is 11th in homers, last in
extra-base hits and 13th in slugging percentage. In the field,
Ripken's range is gone.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the source of Ripken's continued prima donna reign?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that he's a tourist attraction. This is the new
vista of baseball: the stadium and player as tourist attraction.
Ripken has become one of the sights: come to Baltimore to see Babe
Ruth's childhood home, the Edgar Allen Poe House, and Cal Ripken
play another game, drilling his name deeper into immortality.
Meanwhile, the Orioles spiral deeper into a hole.
</P>
<P>
   The game we know and love is changing before our eyes. It is
contrived, scripted. This is what Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has in
mind for Yankee Stadium when the team moves to Rudyland near Times
Square. On Monday the mayor was in Baltimore, raving about Camden
Yards. What a beautiful view of the city, he gushed, though all you
can really see is a cluster of buildings over the center-field
wall.
</P>
<P>
   He wants the new Yankee Stadium be another New York tourist
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani should know that the Inner Harbor wasn't always this
cute, cuddly beehive of commerce. This was a waterfront wasteland
with longshoremen, crabs, beer and rough living until the former
mayor, William Donald Schaffer, launched a drive to make the harbor
the centerpiece of a revitalization for the city.
</P>
<P>
   A visionary mayor would develop the Bronx, make that his Inner
Harbor initiative, bring light to dark places rather than more
light to Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   There is a beautiful view from Yankee Stadium, though the vista
also includes signs of neglect and disdain for quality of life of
people who live around the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no such blemishes in Rudy's World: a world of
upper class and middle class sensibilities: no woes, no worries.
Just the Game. When the Yankees do move to Rudy's Town, they won't
simply be tossing away tradition, but entering into a new dimension
of competition where the game becomes like drama at best, pro
wrestling at worst.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman has been preparing us for this for years; Cal
Ripken is telling us in a gentler fashion. Who knows, Ripken could
be a Yankee in 2002 when the team leaves the Bronx and opens in
midtown. They'll need a celebrity to go with Simba and Uncle Scar.
</P>
<P>
   This is why we marvel all the more at Michael Jordan and his
last shot. Perhaps he is, or was, our last chance to feel something
real in a changing sports market. It is one thing to reward a
player for showing up for work each day with lunch pail in hand.
But what do you do when the pail is empty? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
