65-minute work is staged without a stage, as the audience stands in
a room like a crowd at a rock club; the music makes its way up to
rock-concert volume, moving from pearly New-Age prettiness to hints
of gamelans and African thumb pianos to pounding drums and howling
voices. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- BRAILLE-WINE-LABELS, 6-16 --
Michel Chapoutier, a well-known maker and shipper of Rhone wines,
has put Braille labels on all his premium wines, including
appellations like Hermitage, Crozes-Hermitage, Condrieu,
St.-Joseph, Cote Rotie and, this wine, Chateauneuf-du-Pape. His
reasoning is that blind customers want the same information that
other wine lovers look for on a bottle, (Fred R. Conrad/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- CHINA-COOKING-2, 6-16 --
Presentation is important in Chinese food preparation as seen in
the banquet platter. The Chinese, unlike Americans tend to go out
in groups to eat. ``The Chinese go in groups, it's a cuisine of
sharing,'' explains Michael Tong, the owner of Shun Lee Palace and
Shun Lee West. ``In a Chinese restaurant there are no tables for
two or four; there are only big tables and private rooms.''(David
Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- CHINA-COOKING-1, 6-16 -- Sun
Man Do, one of only a few New York chefs trained in Chinese haute
cuisine, cooking eel at Shun Lee Palace. Most chefs of Chinese food
are not trained in China. ``Over the years we must have had 500
chefs coming and going at Shun Lee Palace,'' says Michael Tong, the
owner of Shun Lee Palace and Shun Lee West, both in Manhattan.
``Only 5 percent were trained in China.'' (Boyd Hagen/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 16, 1998 -- FOOD-NOTES, 6-16 -- These
quarts of ripe, luscious strawberries from local farms were lined
up at stands at Manhattan's Union Square Greenmarket last week.
They are more perishable than those from California and should be
available through early July. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BERKELEY, Calif. -- June 16, 1998 -- CHINA-HAUTE-CUISINE,
6-16 -- Enjoying cooking in his own kitchen, Ken Hom, 49, has his
ingredients lined-up and ready. Hom, who is leaving California for
Europe, says that Americans have never given Chinese food the
respect it deserves. In Britain his books are best sellers and his
popular cooking shows on the BBC network have kept him in front of
the public. ``In the U.K., I'm known like Julia Child is here,'' he
says. (Terrence McCarthy/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
