<HEADER>
A2380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COL-CHAOS-NYT &LR;      06-16 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CHAOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SORRY, MAYOR, IT'S THE LAW _ CHAOS RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michio Kaku has good news for hapless hot-dog
vendors, street artists and cabbies frazzled by Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's quest to quell urban entropy. The mayor's zeal for
near-absolute order is against the law.
</P>
<P>
   Of science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second law of thermodynamics is an absolute, iron law,''
said Kaku, a professor of theoretical physics at City College.
``Entropy always increases. Disorder always increases.''
</P>
<P>
   Yikes. That means no matter how much you straighten things out
in one place, it creates a mess somewhere else. The mayor's critics
might say that has happened in parts of Manhattan that are being
cleaned out and gussied up at the expense of neighborhoods where
tourists never tread. His supporters could counter that he has only
wreaked havoc on Democrats steamrolled by municipal progress.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Kaku's musings are just the product of someone who
teaches in a system that itself has been singled out by those who
would impose order through new standards. But he sounds reasonable
when he explains that some rules preceded this administration. The
city that is the capital of the world cannot claim to be the center
of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is that there are some things that are even beyond
Giuliani,'' Kaku said. ``He can impose his will on everything but
the laws of physics. There is a higher authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Such treason. Equally alarming is the work of chaos theorists at
some universities, who look for the method in mayhem. Their
theories could explain why, say, an asteroid would tumble from its
orbit and crash in midtown _ which would handily justify the cost
and construction of the mayor's proposed emergency bunker.
</P>
<P>
   As any chaosmeister worth his pocket protector knows, minor
events can have unexpected and catastrophic results. In a way, the
administration understood this when it embraced the ``broken
window'' concept behind its quality of life crackdown. A broken
window left unfixed, it was said, sent out a message that a
community was uncared for and ripe for destruction through urban
plagues. But there is a limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real, complex systems, for example those involving the
interaction of many bodies, are, over time, usually unpredictable
and unstable,'' said Sylvain Cappell, a mathematics professor at
New York University. ``And that's the case even when the relative
motions are deterministic and governed just by the simple laws of
inertia, collision and mutual attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaos happens. Still, Cappell was loath to draw any social or
political conclusions, lest someone accuse him of being a
mathematical partisan. Math is easy. Life is hard, was all he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Greene, a professor of physics and mathematics at Columbia
University, cautioned against drawing tidy comparisons between the
realm of tiny particles and cities with life-size pedestrians. But
he was just as insistent in his belief that order in the universe
inevitably will degrade. That, presumably, includes New York,
despite any efforts to prevent it. Yet, there is hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``String theory has shown us there is an incredible elegance and
order when you look at the universe the right way,'' he said.
``Order is not necessarily a bad thing, but it has to be order that
is in harmony with the system to which it is applied. That's the
question individual citizens have to answer when it comes to order
in New York City.''
</P>
<P>
   As a New Yorker, Greene has actually been pleased with the way
things have been going in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more comfortable place to be than when I grew up,'' he
said. ``Part of me recoils against restrictions, but part of me
thinks it's been effective. I tend not to judge things in such
grand terms when it comes to day-to-day life. At the moment, it's
still moving in a useful direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to nudge a behemoth of government and people is good enough
for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at it from a Newtonian point of view, the city has
a correlation of many chaotic forces,'' Kaku said. ``So, what
Giuliani has done is try to impose some order on all of these
diverging interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is personal, but a strong mayor who is wrong is better
than a weak mayor who is right. If you are wrong there are
corrections. This is a Newtonian view. Ultimately, there will be
corrections. At least, the city is moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in case, any would-be mayor, if not Master of the Universe,
should remember the Heisenberg Uncertainty Principle. You can know
an object's speed or where it's going. But never both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
