<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-JOB-CREATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOB CREATION CONTINUES IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LESLIE GOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey's labor market continued to expand
last month, with the creation of 10,200 new jobs and a dip in the
unemployment rate to 5.0 percent, from 5.1 percent in April, the
State Labor Department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The increase brought the total number of payroll jobs to an
all-time high of 3,795,400, said Kevin Smith, a Labor Department
spokesman. Computer programming, data processing and other business
services jobs drove the growth, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's unemployment rate continued to be higher than the
national rate, which was 4.3 percent in May. Connecticut's rate was
3.9 percent, and New York's was 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A slowdown in job creation in April raised questions about New
Jersey's economic recovery. But James Hughes, dean of the Edward J.
Bloustein School of Planning and Public Policy at Rutgers
University, said the May surge indicated the slowdown was ``just a
one-month blip,'' and that the rate of job growth is on a par with
last year's total of 87,500 new jobs. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
