u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TEACHER-MURDER-TRI     06-16 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TEACHER-MURDER-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS SEEK TO EXCLUDE STATEMENTS FROM MEN ACCUSED OF TEACHER'S
KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Defense lawyers for the two men charged with killing
Jonathan Levin, a popular New York City high school teacher, sought
Tuesday to exclude statements that the suspects gave to police and
that could be important evidence for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Levin was discovered in his Upper West Side apartment on May 30,
1997, bound with duct tape and shot in the head. Eight days after
his death, which triggered a citywide manhunt, police charged a
former student, Corey Arthur, and another man, Montoun Hart, with
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the two men killed Levin, the son of Time
Warner's chairman, Gerald Levin, while stealing his ATM card.
</P>
<P>
   Among the evidence police assembled were a series of statements
given by Arthur and Hart while in custody. Tuesday, lawyers for
both men argued in State Supreme Court in Manhattan that portions
of the statements should be excluded from evidence on legal
grounds. The arguments during the preliminary stages of the trial
were the opening of what promises to be a long fight over what
evidence will be allowed in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical evidence challenged by defense lawyers Tuesday
was one of three statements that Hart gave to the police on the
morning of June 7. According to the statement, Hart told detectives
that he and Arthur had gone to Levin's apartment intending to rob
him. The statement is an important element in the case against Hart
because it could be used to show that he intended to commit a crime
when he entered the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's lawyer, David Stern, argued that police improperly
questioned Hart when they took the statement. Stern said that a
lawyer representing Hart called the police precinct house and told
a sergeant that he had been hired by Hart's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Under New York state law, Stern said, police must stop
questioning a suspect once they are informed that he is represented
by a lawyer. Stern told the judge that the lawyer who called the
precinct house had testified in earlier hearings that he thought
that he had placed the telephone call before the police finished
questioning Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Stern asked Justice Marcy Kahn to exclude the statement from
evidence because the police did not stop the questioning when they
received the phone call.
</P>
<P>
   But Eugene Hurley, the prosecutor in the case, responded that
there was no conclusive record that could show whether the lawyer
called before or after the statement was finished. He argued that a
reading of telephone records would actually suggest that the police
received the phone call from the lawyer after Hart's statement was
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Arthur argued that a portion of their client's
statement also should be excluded. Their argument is based on a
police report that indicates that an interview with Arthur
continued for some time after a lawyer called the precinct house
and told officers that he was representing Arthur. However, Hurley
told the judge that the time on the report was a misprint. He said
officers have testified that they completed the interview with
Arthur well before the lawyer called.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Justice Kahn reserved her decision on both motions.
Lawyers for both men also said in court that they plan further
challenges, which are expected to be heard in September. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
