<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SQUEEGEE-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION MAY NOT PAY LEGAL BILLS FOR OFFICER IN SHOOTING OF SQUEEGEE
MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Appearing to distance itself from the officer charged
in the shooting of a squeegee man on Sunday, officials of the
city's police union said yesterday that they were weighing whether
to continue paying his legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Michael Meyer, was provided with lawyers by the
union, the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, to guide him through
his arraignment on Monday on charges of attempted murder in the
shooting of a squeegee man who was trying to clean his windshield.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the union was considering whether the shooting
qualified as a line-of-duty incident, for which the union
ordinarily pays legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union's obligation to pay for lawyers in off-duty
incidents officially ends after the arraignment,'' said Joe
Mancini, a spokesman for the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
``If the PBA decides it's not a line-of-duty incident, that doesn't
mean we've drawn any conclusions about whether the shooting was
justified or not.''
</P>
<P>
   As the union considered the issue, new accusations emerged
Tuesday about several past allegations that Meyer had beaten and
brutalized people while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a Long Island man said he was hospitalized for a
month after being severely beaten by Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Smirti, the union lawyer who represented Meyer at his
arraignment, would not comment on Sunday's case or discuss whether
his fees would be paid by the union or by the officer's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's personal,'' he said Tuesday night. ``I think it's still
being worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Basing a decision about paying Meyer's legal fees on the issue
of whether he was off-duty would be unusual, since the union has
said in the past that police officers are never really off-duty,
using that contention to support its arguments that officers killed
while off-duty should be given funerals with full honors.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the union has paid the legal fees for some officers
involved in off-duty shootings, including Peter Del-Debbio, a white
officer who was off duty when he mistakenly shot a black undercover
police officer in 1994 on a Manhattan subway platform.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the union decided not to pay legal fees, officers
have often hired union lawyers on their own to represent them.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's incident, Meyer is accused of shooting a squeegee
man, Antoine Reid, 38, who tried to wash the windshield of his car
as he stopped in traffic on East 138th Street in the Bronx while
driving his girlfriend and her 6-year-old son home from a Yankees
game, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, who lost his spleen and had considerable liver damage in
the shooting, remained in critical but stable condition Tuesday at
Lincoln Hospital. Hospital officials said that Reid was able to
recognize his mother.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2254EDT &QL; 
