u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LILCO-SEVERANCE-73     06-16 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LILCO-SEVERANCE-735&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITY IMPOSES PENALTIES OVER LILCO PAY DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RONKONKOMA, N.Y. _ Accusing Long Island utility officials of
breaking their word by taking $67 million in extra compensation, a
state agency on Tuesday called for their resignations and imposed a
$1.04 million-a-month corporate penalty until the issue is
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves were among a series of actions voted unanimously by
the Long Island Power Authority in a board meeting here that raised
the stakes in Gov. George Pataki's battle with the officials of the
old Long Island Lighting Co.
</P>
<P>
   The power authority, which the governor controls, took over
LILCO's electricity service on May 28. LILCO's remaining parts _
its power plants, gas operations and employees _ merged with
Brooklyn Union Gas's holding company to form Marketspan Corp. It
supplies the electricity, management and work force to operate the
old LILCO system under long-term contracts with the power
authority.
</P>
<P>
   But a week after the takeover, the governor and power authority
disclosed that LILCO had made secret payments to 26 executives. The
prime beneficiary was LILCO's chairman, Dr. William Catacosinos,
who received $42 million. Pataki denounced the payments as
violations of the state's takeover agreement, which coupled a
no-layoff guarantee with a bar on severance pay.
</P>
<P>
   All the LILCO executives automatically succeeded to jobs at
Marketspan, led by Catacosinos as chairman. They defended their
payments as proper, saying they represent pension funds and other
benefits they were entitled to.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday the power authority, meeting for the first time
since the disclosures, struck back with numerous actions that the
agency's chairman, Richard Kessel, said ``will have far-reaching
consequences for Marketspan.'' He added: ``This message sends a
strong signal to Marketspan that its biggest customer is seriously
dissatisfied. These payments were a serious breach of our
agreement, and they were deliberately concealed.''
</P>
<P>
   The compensation issue must be resolved, he said, for the power
authority to resume working with Marketspan ``in a spirit of
cooperation that is built on mutual respect and trust.'' For now,
he said, ``we do not have that trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, the governor's spokesman, said, ``LIPA's action
to reverse the secret acts of greed are appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the authority's board voted to withhold in an
escrow account Marketspan's $1.04 million monthly management fee,
starting with the payment that was due on Monday. The board called
for the resignation of Catacosinos and two top aides, Joseph
McDonnell and Leonard Novello, who the authority said helped
conceal the payments. The board also banned those three men from
working on the power authority's account at Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   The board said that as a matter of policy, it would consider
disqualifying Marketspan from bidding on future authority projects
like building new power plants, laying a new electric supply cable
under the Long Island Sound or using poles or other equipment for
cellular or cable communications.
</P>
<P>
   The board voted to hire a legal expert to review whether LILCO
executives violated civil or criminal laws in granting the payments
and in their disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   The board directed a review of whether the purchase price for
LILCO's properties should be adjusted to reflect the executive
payments, and it demanded reimbursement to the authority for the
costs of investigating the compensation. And the board voted to
restrict Marketspan's access to the power authority's records
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the board demanded reassurance from Marketspan that
never again would it conceal information from the power authority.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the power authority's actions, McDonnell,
Marketspan's senior vice president, said: ``We will continue to
fulfill our obligations under our contract and to serve the people
of Long Island.'' As for the withheld fees, he said: ``We will
review our remedies under the terms of that contract. We disagree
with the premises of the LIPA action. The compensation contracts
were legal obligations of the company and were properly
discharged.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel said that the contract provided for arbitration to settle
any disputes between the parties. The power authority will continue
to pay about $37 million a month to cover Marketspan's overhead for
providing electrical power and operating the system. The $1.04
million a month being withheld is mostly Marketspan's profits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Giving his first full interviews since the dispute erupted,
Catacosinos, 68, dismissed any thought of quitting Marketspan. He
said he hopes to complete his six-year term as chairman, ``the Lord
willing.'' After that, he said, he wants to ``spend a little time
enjoying the fruits of our labors.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to talk in detail about the compensation issue
because the Marketspan board is reviewing it, Catacosinos said:
``Once the facts are carefully reviewed, then I think people's
concerns will be dispelled.'' In the meantime, he said, ``I'm here
trying to get a job done, trying not to get distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   The power authority's actions failed to mollify critics, who
oppose the takeover deal as a giveaway to LILCO. ``You handed over
$7 billion to LILCO stockholders, and you're pretending you didn't
know Catacosinos and others would get a cut of that?'' said Gordian
Raacke, director of the court-appointed LILCO watchdog group, the
Citizens Advisory Panel. ``Did you guys really trust LILCO? I don't
think the public can trust you people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
