<SLUG> BC-NJ-RAPIST-ATTACKED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOTS FIRED INTO RESIDENCE OF PAROLED RAPIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINDEN, N.J. _ In the most violent attack directed at a paroled
sex offender since ``Megan's Law'' was enacted in New Jersey four
years ago, five shots were fired early Tuesday into a two-story
house where a convicted rapist lives, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was hurt in the incident, which occurred less than two
weeks after the police began circulating a flier warning neighbors
of the presence of the man, Frank Penna, under the community
notification provisions of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Penna, 57, was convicted of kidnapping and raping two teen-agers
in 1976, and was sentenced to life in prison. He was paroled in
1992, and has apparently been living in the two-story house, his
boyhood home, since then. It was unclear Tuesday why Linden
officials first notified Penna's neighbors of his presence earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Local and state officials were quick to denounce the apparent
act of vigilantism, and said they had begun an aggressive
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The gunfire represented the type of incident that critics of the
law had long predicted would occur when sex offenders were
identified publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Peter Verniero denounced the gunfire at a news
conference in Trenton, saying, ``We will not tolerate any act of
vigilantism against a known sex offender.''
</P>
<P>
   But Verniero also denied that the incident demonstrated that the
critics of the law were correct. ``I don't think one incident,
which hopefully will remain isolated, proves any defect in the law
itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The shots, which were fired shortly after midnight Monday,
pierced the front windows and walls of a first-floor apartment. Its
resident, Joan Bazydlo, was in bed watching television at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Penna, the apparent target of the fusillade, was asleep in his
basement apartment when the shots were fired, Ms. Bazydlo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was petrifying,'' Ms. Bazydlo said Tuesday afternoon on her
bullet-scarred front porch. ``I was just watching TV in the dark
and all of a sudden it was pow, pow, pow, pow, and glass was coming
at me. I just fell to the floor and laid there.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the law had argued that community notification
would lead to harassment, threats and vigilantism against parolees
whose names, addresses and physical descriptions were circulated in
police notices to neighbors of the sex offenders' homes and
workplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The first instance of vigilantism connected to community
notification occurred in rural Warren County in 1995. Two men burst
into a home in Phillipsburg where a paroled sex offender lived and
beat up a housemate whom they mistook for the parolee. The pair, a
father and son, were arrested and served a year in prison,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bazydlo said Penna should be left alone. ``He doesn't bother
anybody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Garcia, who lives a block away, said he was appalled by
the gunfire. ``He seems like a peaceful person,'' he said. ``Who
are we to judge? If he served his time, he deserves a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
