</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROJAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROJAS STILL STRUGGLING TO FIND HIS OLD FORM
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Mets' pitching coach, Bob Apodaca, bristled when
asked whether the team had been hiding Mel Rojas in its bullpen at
times this season to keep Rojas from hurting the team's chances
late in close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's ridiculous,'' Apodaca said Tuesday of the notion, two
days after Rojas could not nail down the third out in the eighth
inning of a game the bullpen lost in Florida, 5-4. ``It's pure
matchups, getting the right pitcher against the right part of the
lineup. And sometimes, Mel isn't the right matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that the Mets, after trading Greg McMichael to
the Los Angeles Dodgers in the Hideo Nomo deal, are going to need
more out of Rojas in his setup role if they are to avoid the
disastrous consequences of last season's bullpen collapse in front
of the closer John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that he's a key to our club,'' Apodaca
said of Rojas. ``The entire bullpen is.''
</P>
<P>
   And since the bullpen has been struggling lately, more attention
is being focused on Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into this season, it was generally accepted that the
Dominican right-hander was the biggest question mark in the Mets'
revamped bullpen. As the Expos' closer in 1995 and 1996, Rojas
saved 66 games. In 1994, Rojas had 16 saves in 18 chances as John
Wetteland's setup man before the strike ruined Montreal's chances
of winning a division title.
</P>
<P>
   But after signing a three-year deal at $4.5 million a season as
a free agent with the Chicago Cubs before last season, Rojas has
struggled to regain the form that made him one of the National
League's top relievers. Last year, he was 0-6 with a 4.64 earned
run average with the Cubs and Mets, converting just 15 of 22 save
opportunities (68 percent). The four previous seasons, Rojas had
converted 79 percent of such opportunities (92 of 116).
</P>
<P>
   This year, after returning to a setup role, Rojas is 2 for 3 in
save opportunities (67 percent) and 3-0 with a 2.83 ERA. But he has
inexplicably been hit hard by right-handers, who were batting a
whopping .373 against him this season (22 for 59, including the
only home run he has allowed) before tonight, compared with
left-handers, who were hitting .170 (8 for 47) against Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   Over the previous five years, right-handers had hit just .230 in
747 at-bats against Rojas, while lefties had hit .236 in 772
at-bats. Last season, righties his just .226 against Rojas in 164
at-bats, while lefties hit .258 in 159 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not back yet,'' Rojas said Tuesday. ``I still have a
little bit to work on. It's real close, but I'm not 100 percent to
the point where I come in and this game's over. It's still early,
though. We have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistency has been Rojas' main problem, especially with his
split-finger fastball, which he said he needs to get over for
first-pitch strikes. Rojas has retired 19 of the 27 first batters
he has faced this season. When he doesn't retire the first batter,
that is when the trouble usually starts.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas retired the first batter in Miami on Sunday, in what he
called his worst outing of the season. But the Marlins then touched
him for a one-out walk, a run-scoring double, a run-scoring
groundout and another run-scoring double. All of a sudden, a 4-0
game was 4-3. Two other Mets relievers, Brian Bohanon and John
Hudek, could not hold on. And, for the second time in three games,
the Mets' bullpen had blown a game.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, Manager Bobby Valentine could have turned
to McMichael, who was something of an insurance policy for Rojas.
Since the Nomo trade on June 4, however, Valentine has tried
Bohanon, Hudek and Turk Wendell in game-breaking situations, and no
one has had much success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel's still there,'' Valentine said. ``We have to fill that
other spot.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
