<HEADER>
A2526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-BIRTH14-COX     06-16 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-BIRTH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet birth a reality even though most couldn't see it
 &HT;    By Ellen Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The first delivery shown over the Internet produced a
baby boy, but thousands who turned in couldn't see the birth.
</P>
<P>
   For those who got through, the images were abrupt _ they tended
to freeze _ and blurry at best. Still, thousands tried to see the
birth of 7-pound, 8-ounce Sean, the fourth child of Elizabeth, a
40-year-old woman who didn't want her last name used. Cameras were
discreetly trained on Elizabeth's side and in front of her hospital
bed, but nurses backs blocked any view of the actual delivery.
</P>
<P>
   America's Health Network, which put the delivery on its Internet
site, said there were more than 10 million hits at the Web site
throughout the day. At any one minute, 5,000 viewers were able to
log onto the site.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth and the network said they wanted to help educate
mothers-to-be and quell their fears. But those who logged on may
not have gotten much of an educational experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sit here and say this is the proper method to educate
the public,'' said Peggy Hotz, the department director for
perinatal services at Crawford Long of Hospital of Emory Hospital.
``The problem with the Web is that no one is there to give support
or answer questions that may rise from this.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who did not rise at the crack of dawn to follow
Elizabeth from her 6 a.m. check-in to her delivery at 10:40 a.m.,
was Christopher Rywalt, a New Jersey resident who tried to showhis
wife's delivery live through the internet last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rywalt, who wrote about the conception and development of their
first baby on a Web site called ``It's Just Another Baby''
(http://www.westnet.com/ (tilde)crywalt/pregnancy.contents.htm),
admitted that he did not find Tuesday morning's live birth ``too
thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I could just be bitter,'' joked Rywalt.
</P>
<P>
   He had arranged to show his wife's delivery over the Web, but
the hospital pulled the plug at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a natural outcome of the Web site. It was in
conjunction with the book and so those who were following it could
join in,'' said Rywalt. ``We wanted to do it because it was a fun
thing to do. The tradition on the Internet is that people say,
`This is fun, let's do it because we can.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Werbach, managing editor of ``Release 1.0,'' a monthly
newsletter that discusses trends in the computer industry, said
that the amazing factor of the Internet is that it allows
information and events such as a live birth to be broadcast, an
event that the original creators of the Internet most likely never
imagined or expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is the Internet allows everybody to be a
publisher. It lets people who would not have access to the media to
get the word out,'' said Werbach. ``It makes it possible to
distribute information, although information on childbirth may be
stretching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
