u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COP-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-16 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COP-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PROSECUTOR ANNOUNCES DIFFERENT STRATEGY IN LIVOTI TRAIL
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal prosecutor in Manhattan told a jury Tuesday
that Anthony Baez died one winter's night in 1994 outside his
parents' home in the Bronx after he was intentionally choked during
an arrest by a New York City police officer, Francis Livoti.
</P>
<P>
   But, the prosecutor also told the jury, ``This is not a murder
case.''
</P>
<P>
   In those six words, the prosecutor, Mark Pomerantz, summed up
how the federal government plans to use a different legal strategy
than the state did to try to convict Livoti in Baez's death. Two
years ago, Livoti was acquitted on state charges of criminally
negligent homicide after a judge ruled that the government had
failed to prove beyond a reasonable doubt that Baez's death was
caused by an illegal choke hold, rather than a severe asthma
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Livoti goes on trial in federal district court in
Manhattan, the federal government will only have to prove that in
causing Baez bodily harm, Livoti violated his civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell,'' Pomerantz said, ``this is a case about police
brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   But Livoti's lawyer, Stuart London, argued that his client had
never sought to harm Baez, whose death he said was accidental, the
result of an asthma attack.
</P>
<P>
   London asserted that Livoti, who was later dismissed from the
police force, did not use a choke hold on Baez. He said that Baez
and his brothers had confronted the police and were resisting
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had they just acquiesced to this,'' London said, ``the whole
situation would have been diffused at that very moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Tuesday, two of Baez's brothers testified about how
their family had come to their parents' home at 6 Cameron Place in
the University Heights section of the Bronx for Christmas, and in a
family ritual, played a late-night touch football game, not
bothering anyone.
</P>
<P>
   But several police officers drove up, and after a football
accidentally hit one of their cars several times, Livoti stepped
out of his car and threatened the brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anybody touch the police officer?'' Pomerantz asked one of
the brothers, Henry Bothwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bothwell replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did anybody make any threatening gestures toward him?''
Pomerantz continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Bothwell answered.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Pomerantz told the jury that Livoti's decision to put
Baez into a prohibited choke hold ``was not an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did that after having been warned not to use excessive
force in making arrests,'' Pomerantz said.
</P>
<P>
   Pomerantz, the chief of the criminal division of the U.S.
attorney's office in Manhattan, said that the government would
build its case in part on medical evidence, including autopsy
findings that he said would prove that an illegal choke hold was
used on Baez.
</P>
<P>
   Pomerantz said that the department prohibited officers from
using choke holds ``because they are potentially lethal; they can
kill.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the government would show that Livoti's use of the choke
hold was neither an accident nor inadvertent. Prosecutors will cite
an earlier case of police brutality in which Livoti started to
choke a 16-year-old boy who was driving a motorized cart, an
allegation that London has said that his client denies.
</P>
<P>
   By avoiding the question of whether Livoti's actions that night
directly caused Baez's death, prosecutors hope to avoid the outcome
of the 1996 state trial, after which a State Supreme Court justice
ruled that the government had failed to prove its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is not arguing to you that Francis Livoti
intentionally killed Anthony Baez,'' Pomerantz told the jury
Tuesday. ``The charge is that Francis Livoti deprived Anthony Baez
of a federal constitutional right.'' He described that as the
``right to be secure in our persons, the right not to have
unreasonable force used against us by someone who is making an
arrest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
