<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORE ELS WILL GIVE IT A GO AT OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ernie Els grimaced as he responded to the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it stemmed from the pain in his lower back. Maybe it was
simply a reflection of his disappointment at not being able to
defend his U.S. Open title while completely healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Els' face conveyed as much information as his lips
yesterday at the Olympic Club as he stopped just short of
dismissing himself as a candidate to win his third Open title in
five years when play begins in tomorrow's first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``The back is not 100 percent, obviously,'' Els said, wincing
slightly. ``It is very frustrating. This is the wrong timing for me
to get this kind of injury. Maybe I should just slow down a little
bit and take it easy for a couple of weeks. There will be more U.S.
Opens and British Opens.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments suggest that Els, who withdrew from last week's
Buick Classic because of back spasms, questions whether he will be
healthy enough to be a factor at next month's British Open, much
less this week's competition at the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Els said yesterday that he plans to report for tomorrow's noon
tee time although he characterized his status as an Open
participant as ``a day-to-day thing.'' He has spent the past week
in consultation with physical therapist Tom Boers, a back
specialist from Columbus, Ga., who accompanied Els to San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   After withdrawing from the Buick Classic, Els did not hit a golf
ball for four days. Instead, he walked, did stretching exercises
and underwent therapy. He was cleared to play a practice round
yesterday but said he still experienced some minor pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is coming from the lower back and it is on the left side of
the spine,'' said Els, 28, who has two victories and 10 Top-10
finishes in a combined 14 starts this season on the European and
PGA tours. ``It's a couple of joints that got really stiff. The
muscle started helping it to turn and when it got tired of doing
that, it just kind of seized up and went into spasm. To get that
healthy, obviously, takes a bit of time and the right bit of
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, who ranks 19th on the PGA Tour season earnings list
($667,638), said he was unsure what triggered the injury. But he
said his frequent transcontinental flights this spring probably did
not help the situation and could lead to a cutback on his European
Tour schedule in subsequent years.
</P>
<P>
   In six events on the 1998 European Tour, Els has not finished
worse than third. He won the South African Open. On the PGA Tour,
he won the Bay Hill Invitational and finished 16th at the Masters
Tournament, the season's first major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Els, who won his first U.S. Open title in 1994, said he was
unsure if he would practice today or simply show up for tomorrow's
opening round and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it is the U.S. Open, I can't really just go out and
hit balls right now. It might flare up again. So, the less tension
I put on it, the better,'' Els said. ``As bad as it is, it's still
a lot better than last week. My swing isn't where you want to be.
But at least I can go out there and make a good pass at it. I'm
hoping that old saying about `Beware of the wounded golfer' has
some truth to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Els said a more realistic goal would be that the
injury will heal in time to allow him a chance to make a legitimate
run at a British Open title. In May, Els proclaimed winning the
British Open as his primary goal for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to win all four at least once . . . and I've
already won two U.S. Opens. My sights are really on the British
Open,'' Els said while competing at the GTE Byron Nelson Classic in
May.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his back injury might impact those plans, Els said:
``If I can just get through the next couple of weeks without doing
too much damage to it, I will be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
