A2532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATOR-RETIRE-705     06-16 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATOR-RETIRE-705(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 30 YEARS AS GADFLY, A STATE SENATOR BOWS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It is the time of year when Franz Leichter's
colleagues in the state Senate ardently wish that he would
disappear.
</P>
<P>
   As the legislative session lurches to an end and lawmakers try
to rush through piles of complicated bills, Leichter, a Democrat
from the Upper West Side of New York City, starts reeling off
questions. On the last day of session, he is usually unstoppable,
challenging bill after bill as the hours creep past and his
colleagues roll their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers say they will suffer Leichter's last-minute
tirades a little more gladly this year, because they will mark the
end of an era. The session, which will probably end on Thursday, is
his last. Leichter will retire in December after three decades in
office, leaving the Legislature without one of its harshest critics
and most staunchly liberal members.
</P>
<P>
   Though his career as in-house gadfly has left him with few
concrete legislative achievements, lawmakers say that without him
the Democratic minority in the Senate will agitate less effectively
and the Republican majority will breathe more easily.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Leichter says the public has become so mistrustful
of government, and his colleagues on both sides of the aisle have
become so lethargic, that he is finally too frustrated to press on.
</P>
<P>
   Leichter, 67, entered politics at a time when leftist
philosophies were fashionable in New York City, though not in
Albany, and won an Assembly seat in 1968. He used the platform to
speak out against the Vietnam War, and he called in vain for the
legalization of marijuana and changes to the notoriously secretive
budget process in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, he moved to the Senate, where he began writing damning
reports on topics like campaign finance law, banking practices and
corporate tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Leichter, whose district snakes from Chelsea in
Manhattan to Riverdale in the Bronx, has inveighed against
pork-barrel spending, back-room deal-making and the rigidly
hierarchical leadership system in the Legislature, which he says
``stifles initiative and productivity.''
</P>
<P>
   In relinquishing his seat, Leichter says, he is relinquishing
hope that the system will change in his lifetime. ``It's a tightly
closed system that has crystallized and become even more of a way
of life since I came here,'' he said recently. ``This is not a time
to be in government. Continuing to do the same thing is not going
to accomplish much at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the minority party for his entire legislative
career, Leichter has never been able to accomplish much. But he has
frequently drawn attention to what he sees as Republican misdeeds.
And he has brought about some measure of change.
</P>
<P>
   After Leichter revealed in the early 1980s that the state's Job
Incentive Board had given Tiffany &AMP; Co. a $5 million tax credit for
expanding its store on Fifth Avenue, Gov. Mario Cuomo abolished the
incentive program. And his reports that criticized fund-raising
practices by members of the New York City Board of Estimate helped
persuade city officials to create an independent campaign-finance
board in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franz is unique because he attacks the process like an
outsider,'' said Blair Horner, legislative director of New York
Public Interest Research Group, which has worked with Leichter on
consumer and environmental issues. ``Instead of developing
relationships with more powerful members, he has tried to generate
public interest, which can have a much more powerful effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Leichter rarely stops hurling accusations and
complaints, his colleagues say he is one of the best-liked
legislators in Albany. Even lawmakers who tangle with him in the
Senate greet him warmly outside the chamber, and many even play
tennis with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franz has a lot of respect across the board because he happens
to be a warm and friendly person,'' said Sen. Guy Velella, a R-New
York City. ``He's one of the last beatnik types there is, thank
God. But he is a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans, like Sen. Ronald Stafford of Plattsburgh, are
less charitable, but hardly vindictive toward their colleague from
the 30th District. ``Well,'' Stafford said, ``he's certainly
indefatigable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An immigrant from Austria whose mother died in a Nazi
concentration camp, Leichter worked for Adlai Stevenson's
presidential campaign in 1956, while attending Harvard Law School.
After graduation, he joined the reform wing of the Manhattan
Democratic Party, which was challenging the Tammany Hall political
machine that had controlled Democratic politics for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fighting against the boss-dominated party organization
that existed in New York, which still exists, more or less, in
Albany,'' Leichter said. ``I liked the openness. I was very
idealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   He raised enough hackles in the Assembly that the Republican
majority tried to get rid of him, eliminating his seat when it
redrew the state's legislative districts in 1972. Undeterred,
Leichter moved his wife and two children seven blocks north to run
in the newly drawn district.
</P>
<P>
   Leichter decided to run for the Senate in 1974, when the federal
government declared the reapportionment illegal and carved up his
new district. The Republican majority again tried to thwart him,
redrawing the Senate district so that he once again lived outside
it. He moved a second time and defeated Sen. Joseph Zaretzski, the
Democratic minority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Leichter would presumably have trouble drumming up votes in most
other districts, though _ especially in recent years, with a
Republican in the Governor's office and many voters favoring
smaller government. In what his colleagues describe as a
quintessential Leichter move, he introduced legislation in 1995 to
repeal Gov. George Pataki's popular income-tax cuts, saying they
benefited only the wealthy. Not surprisingly, the bill died.
</P>
<P>
   So why spend hours extolling bills that have no chance of
passage, and challenging others that will pass no matter how loudly
Leichter protests?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just feel that is what I was sent up here to do,'' Leichter
said. ``To fight against that sense of futility. I have a visceral
dislike for the idea of putting these bills through without
discussion. My colleagues say, `What's the use? You get up and
debate the bill and you get three votes against it.' But if nothing
else, I want to know at least that I voted right.''
</P>
<P>
   In appearance, Leichter is more neatnik than beatnik, wearing
double-breasted suits, starched shirts and glasses with scholarly
frames. He has worked for a law firm on Park Avenue since 1988,
specializing in international corporate litigation. He likes movies
about politics, books about economics and Wagnerian operas.
</P>
<P>
   He does not talk about his wife, Nina, who suffered from
depression and committed suicide in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Even his friends describe Leichter as a workaholic, and while he
is leaving the Legislature, he has no intention of fading from
view. He is a candidate for a seat on the Federal Housing Finance
Board, and is considering teaching or working with advocacy groups.
</P>
<P>
   Although Leichter's final legislative session has been one of
the most uneventful in years, he has managed to carp with his usual
flair. He introduced a campaign finance bill and has pressed for a
bill that would speed the creation of Hudson River Park, which
would stretch from Battery Park to 59th Street in New York City.
But over all, Leichter sums up the 1998 legislative session as
depressingly stagnant, with lawmakers driven by polls and
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The paucity of new programs and ideas, whether they come from
the right or the left, shows how dispirited people are,'' Leichter
said. ``I think we can say that the Legislature is brain dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
