<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS RELEASE TOLBERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOSIE KARP 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ In a move motivated more by concerns about
productivity than about the salary cap, the Cowboys released
veteran defensive end Tony Tolbert yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tolbert, who had three years left on his contract, nor
the Cowboys were convinced the 30-year-old, who recently underwent
arthroscopic surgery on both knees, is ready for the physical
demands of an NFL season, team vice president Stephen Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   By cutting Tolbert now, the Cowboys save his base salary of
almost $2.5 million against the 1998 salary cap. The Cowboys are
responsible for almost $1 million of Tolbert's prorated signing
bonus toward the 1998 salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert, who has spent all nine years of his career with the
Cowboys, could be re-signed if he and the Cowboys determine he is
ready to play at a later date. He is free to sign with any other
NFL team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, playing in the NFL for as long as Tony Tolbert has
can take a toll on you,'' Jones said. ``...Obviously, he wants to
play at the level Tony Tolbert's accustomed to. We finally sat down
and mutually decided this was probably in the best interest for
both people at this time, although no doors have been shut for the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Cowboys have no immediate interest in any
free-agent defensive ends and will likely enter training camp next
month with rookie Greg Ellis and third-year player Kavika Pittman
scheduled to start. Jones said he probably will initiate contract
talks this week with Ellis' agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also might move rookie Michael Myers from tackle to
end and might use linebacker Broderick Thomas at defensive end
again, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have good options,'' Jones said. ``There are several
players we think can play well and come to the forefront for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The release of Tolbert was not the result of the player refusing
a pay cut, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never discussed a pay cut with Tony. It was strictly Tony
feeling what level he could play football at and how he could help
the Dallas Cowboys,'' Jones said. ``If at some point he feels he
can help us, he is going to let us know that, similar to (offensive
tackle) Mark Tuinei.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys released Tuinei, a 15-year veteran, before the draft
because of his knee injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Tolbert's off-season knee surgery was his second round of double
arthroscopic surgery in the past two years. Tolbert recorded a
career-high 12 sacks in 1996 but had only five last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0494 </DOCNO>
