<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAUL-SOROS-PROFILE-AR     06-16 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAUL-SOROS-PROFILE-ART-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OVERSHADOWED ALTRUIST SEES THE LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
(lb) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Meet Paul Soros, the invisible Soros. He is 71, the
older brother of George, the 67-year-old financier-philanthropist
famous for giving away nearly $2 billion. Big brother says little
brother got all the attention when they were children _ ``that's
always what the older one feels.'' It hasn't changed today, unless
you know that Paul Soros made his own fortune, separate from
George, building the world's largest industrial ports.
</P>
<P>
   But last month Paul Soros and his wife, Daisy, made their first
foray into major philanthropy when they announced the creation of a
$50 million trust to help underwrite American graduate education
for immigrants and their children. The Paul &AMP; Daisy Soros
Fellowships for New Americans will give selected students one-half
of their tuition costs plus $20,000, for up to three years, at any
graduate institution in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   There are 20 recipients for the 1998-99 school year. One is a
Cambodian-born woman, Na Eng, who escaped with her parents from the
Khmer Rouge at age 5 and will go to Columbia University. Another is
Rajiv Doshi, of Indian parentage, who invented a prosthesis for
upper-arm amputees. He is at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big trend in this city is putting your name on a
building,'' Mrs. Soros said. ``Which didn't appeal to my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did this instead,'' Soros said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple say their largess had nothing to do with playing
catch-up with brother George, one of the few people in the world
who can make $50 million look like chump change. George Soros has
given the bulk of his billions to build free societies in former
communist countries; last fall he pledged a $500 million grant over
the next three years to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Paul and Daisy Soros describe their gift as a creative
use of their millions when other philanthropists are searching for
something to do with their money beyond writing checks to the
ballet. So far, Soros says, he and his wife have given $4 million
to other causes this year.
</P>
<P>
   The most romantic is underwriting Midsummer Night Swing, a month
of dancing under the stars at Lincoln Center. ``I generally don't
give to endowments,'' Soros said. ``By its nature, the money has to
be very conservatively managed. I find it wasteful to contribute to
something when it earns 7 or 8 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul and Daisy Soros talked in their apartment of potted white
orchids and a very large poodle at 78th Street and Fifth Avenue, 11
blocks down the street from George, who is at this moment on
vacation in Lapland, observing reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Soros looks like a slightly older version of George Soros _
that is, another courtly might-have-been academic. Daisy Soros, 68,
has blond hair and chic suits, and looks as if she is on the board
of Lincoln Center, which she is. Soros started out the interview a
little stiff, but warmed up. His wife seemed to be restraining
herself from saying something indiscreet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the biggest difference between these two brothers?''
she said, repeating a question. ``Not much.'' Then she amended:
``The biggest difference is that George's wife is 30 years younger
than I am.'' (George Soros' wife, Susan, is his second.)
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the interesting subject of sibling rivalry.
``First of all, I was four years older,'' Soros said. ``That's a
very bad age difference. I found him a very obnoxious kid. But he
improved with age.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Soros chuckled. ``As kids, we weren't competitive,'' he said.
``Four years was too big a gap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just naturally inferior,'' his wife said.
</P>
<P>
   Soros says George has more money, but he has plenty of his own,
and the two brothers are close friends. ``There are different
yardsticks,'' he said. ``So I feel quite happy with what I have
done.'' Friends have estimated George Soros' personal fortune at $5
billion, made through his hedge funds; Paul Soros would not enter
into any speculation about the amount of that fortune, or his own.
He works today with his brother, calling himself a ``global
capitalist'' _ buying companies and investing with George.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any deal I am in, he comes in on,'' Soros said, although he
isn't in on all of George's deals. A decade ago, when George Soros
was as invisible as Paul, Paul advised him against going public
with his philanthropy. But he did not listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side of the argument was that if he wants to be
effective, it's inevitable, and it's necessary, to become a public
personality,'' Soros said. ``That's the part he followed _ not
without occasional regrets.'' Announcing the Paul &AMP; Daisy Soros
Fellowships, Soros said, was similar, ``maybe in some ways. But I
don't think it requires that much being public for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Soros, like George, grew up in Budapest, Hungary, a
lawyer's son. When the communists came to power after World War II,
Paul Soros went to Switzerland with the 1948 Hungarian Olympic ski
team, defected, made his way to the United States (he says he
docked in New York with $17), and got a master's degree in
engineering from the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   He founded Soros Associates, with offices in the basement
playroom of his house in New Canaan, Conn. _ ``I was the
associate,'' Daisy Soros said _ which eventually built vast
industrial ports. The Soroses have two children.
</P>
<P>
   He says he is a better skier than his brother, but his brother
once beat him in a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That he rubs in,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
