<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      06-16 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO WRITER'S BLOCK, BUT WRITER'S ITCH  
 FOOD NOTES  
 OUT AND ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ JAMES BRADY, a columnist for Advertising Age and
Parade magazines, was not being a schmoozy and glad-handing author
at the party celebrating the publication of his new novel, ``Gin
Lane'' (St. Martin's Press).
</P>
<P>
   Schmoozy he was. But with absolutely no glad-handing.
</P>
<P>
   Poison ivy, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out pulling weeds in the garden,'' Brady explained, his
skin a pastiche of pinks and reds. ``I don't know anything about
botany. I could be pulling up champion roses or rare botanicals, so
when I pulled up the poison ivy, I guess it just didn't register.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was not gripping and grinning at the book party, he
did manage some physical contact. ``I can still slink my arm around
a woman's shoulders and pull her close to me,'' he said. Assuming,
of course, that she is wearing long sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's previous page-turner, ``Further Lane'' (St. Martin's,
1997), looked at the celebrity-driven whirl of East Hampton, N.Y.,
where the poison-ivy garden is. ``Further Lane'' drew attention
because it dropped the names of real people. Brady said that MARTHA
STEWART, who was mentioned, still refuses to discuss it with him.
(Well, what do you expect when you kill off a lifestyle-guru
character who obviously resembles her with a privet-hedge stake to
the heart?)
</P>
<P>
   ``Gin Lane'' is set in nearby Southampton and revolves around an
early-morning radio personality a lot like DON IMUS.
</P>
<P>
   Brady's formula of naming novels for well-manicured streets in
the Hamptons seems to be working: he said that he would call the
next one Lily Pond Lane, a thoroughfare one block from the beach in
East Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either that or Nathan Lane,'' he groaned as he set down
his drink, grimaced and scratched his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Food Notes
</P>
<P>
   YVES MENES, the executive chef at the Metropolitan Club in New
York, was named chef of the year by l'Association des Maitres
Cuisiniers de France at a ceremony in Essex, Vt. ``Who would have
thought they would come all the way from France and beyond to
beautiful Vermont,'' said Menes, whose flight was delayed at
takeoff because of engine trouble and arrived 90 minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   That was not his only airplane problem: The silver trophy he won
was too big to take with him as carry-on luggage on his flight home
to New York. Solution: he entrusted it to JEAN-YVES PIQUET, the
executive chef at the University Club, who was driving to New York.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL NEWMAN, whose Newman's Own brand has raised more than $90
million for charity, told PATRICIA POE of The Free Press in
Rockland, Maine, that he was ``thinking of coming out with an ice
cream called `Soft Porn.'''Newman, who was in Maine shooting the
LUKE MANDOKI film ``Message in a Bottle,'' added, ``I would love to
get public reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Poe wrote that as ``kind of an afterthought,'' Newman said,
``People take themselves so seriously _ it just drives me nuts.''
In New York, where people take things (but never themselves)
seriously, a spokeswoman for Newman's Own said, ``There's nothing
to it on our end.''
</P>
<P>
   Out and About
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing as MILTON BERLE, 89, celebrated his
Methuselah-like career was a rim shot. ``We were sitting on the
couch one night,'' he told the crowd at the New York apartment of
the songwriter DENISE RICH, ``and she asked if we could go upstairs
and make love. I said, `Honey, you can only do one or the other.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' the Internet gossip MATT DRUDGE said of the media
magazine Brill's Content. Drudge, who wore a Walter Winchell-style
hat to a party celebrating the first issue, added, ``I'll be
covering it aggressively _ coverage of the coverage of the
coverage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
