<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUC-CUNY-490&AMP;ADD-NYT     06-16 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUC-CUNY-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO COLLEGES IN NEW YORK PLAN TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Into the swirl of proposals about how the City
University of New York should be transformed comes one more: a plan
to merge Queens College and Queensborough Community College to
create a bigger, more comprehensive university, akin to the Albany
or Stony Brook campuses of the State University of New York, with
its own doctoral programs and more generous funding.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, which was drawn up by the presidents of the two
colleges after CUNY's trustees told the colleges to be creative in
devising ways to put into practice the board's new policy to remove
remedial classes from their bachelor's degree programs. The two
presidents sent the proposal to CUNY'S chairwoman, Anne Paolucci,
late last week.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY's own projections suggest that its four-year colleges like
Queens will have empty seats as they turn away students who do not
pass placement exams, while community colleges like Queensborough
will be overrun with students. Nearly half of the entering students
at the four-year colleges failed one or more of the placement exams
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Dr. Paolucci, Allen Sessoms, the president at
Queens, and Kurt Schmeller, the president of Queensborough, said
that with their plan for the school, called the University at
Queens, they could fulfill the new remedial policy six months
earlier than the September 1999 deadline that Queens faces. Neither
was willing to comment Tuesday, college spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   For some CUNY trustees, however, the plan may be too creative,
since it raises issues about the mission of the colleges and about
CUNY's model of a central, consortial graduate center, and would
require approval not only by the trustees but also by the state
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very large, very ambitious plan,'' said Dr.
Paolucci, who called it premature and said it ``is coming from left
field.'' She said that rather than helping pave the way for the
remedial changes, the plan would divert attention.
</P>
<P>
   But Herman Badillo, vice chairman of the CUNY board, said the
proposal might point the way to the future. While it raises a lot
of questions, he said, ``it might be a good idea to review the
whole structure of the community colleges and the senior
colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   David Speidel, acting provost at Queens, said the proposal came
together quickly. The two presidents first met to discuss the idea
on June 4, and sent their one-page proposal to Dr. Paolucci, to
Christoph Kimmich, CUNY's interim chancellor, and to some local
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who says universities can't move quickly?'' Speidel said.
</P>
<P>
   At Queens, Nancy Hemmes, a psychology professor and chairwoman
of the college's Academic Senate, said the plan would have the
advantage of allowing students who do not pass the entrance exams
to enroll in two-year programs at Queens. But, she added, ``I'm
overwhelmed with the complexity; it is very difficult to evaluate
it as a complete package.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials at other CUNY campuses in Queens were reserved about
the plan. Kristin Booth Glen, dean of the CUNY law school, said she
had held back when approached about signing on to the plan, saying
she had to consult with her faculty.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Kelly, a spokeswoman for York College, said top
administrators there had not seen the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Reitano, a history professor at La Guardia Community
College and chairwoman of the university faculty senate's community
college caucus, said she feared that such a plan could undermine
the role of the community colleges and their linkages to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Shulman, Queens borough president, was more encouraging.
She called the plan ``an interesting idea that deserves
consideration,'' and said she planned to discuss it with Dr.
Paolucci on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
