<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2550 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-mcgwire-HNS &LR;      06-16 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-mcgwire-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fans come 
for grab at 
greatness
<TEXT>
<P>
   McGwire pulls 10,000 &QL; 
to see batting practice
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
This would be history, I told the kids on the drive to the
Astrodome, surprised that they seemed impressed. I told them of the
great slugger, as other fathers will for decades when another
larger-than-life lumberjack chases the record Mark McGwire could
claim this season.
</P>
<P>
   I no longer felt as unfit, having failed so to teach the
American lessons of baseball to my children. This would be one of
those family-memory nights.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that if they hear James Earl Jones intone, ``The one
constant through all the years, Ray, has been baseball,'' they
would wonder why Darth Vader was talking about baseball and who is
Ray.
</P>
<P>
   But for this night, we would sit in the left-field mezzanine and
catch history.
</P>
<P>
   If Mark McGwire was to hit a rocket, we would be there. If he is
to hit 62 this season, breaking Roger Maris' unbreakable record, or
the 75 he was on pace to hit when he arrived in town Tuesday, we
would grab one. David, my 6-year-old who might miss a putt of a
ground ball off the bat of a 45-pound tee-ball opponent, would
catch whatever the Cardinals' 250-pound human forklift would send
his way. Emily, my daughter, without a glove, would catch it.
</P>
<P>
   And an outfield full of Davids and Emilys and fathers fooling
themselves felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like this before,'' Jim Dillon said,
with his 4-year-old, Blake, and Blake's tiny glove at his side.
``I've gone to batting practice for years. Look up here. It's
great. This is special.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time we reached our seats in section 430 _ at 5:10 p.m.
for a 7:05 start _ the left-field mezzanine was packed. The Astros
estimated the batting-practice crowd at 10,000. Most seemed in our
section.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters with notebooks and minicams wandered about, believing
the news to be found 400 feet from home plate and almost two hours
before the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us stood and waited. When the Astros' Craig Biggio
reached our seats, we all knew what was to come. ``I know I've got
McGwire's now,'' Steven Maglitto said, having pulled in Biggio's
shot.
</P>
<P>
   But as the crowd grew thicker, Rick Luberger knew the chances of
catching a McGwire home run were shrinking. ``This is why we got
season tickets out here,'' he said. ``Usually you can find them
under the seats up here. But we knew everyone would be out here.
This is the biggest attraction in Major League Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   We knew it was more than even that. I imagined myself old with
that home run ball still on my desk, my kids telling their kids of
the night we brought it home. People around us shared binoculars to
watch McGwire stand still as he waited for the Cardinals reserves
to complete batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he made his way toward the batting cage. And when he
took his turn in the batting cage, we stood, as if the World Series
were reaching its final outs.
</P>
<P>
   In 21 pitches, McGwire hit nine balls to the bleachers. McGwire
hit a few to right, a bunch to center. He pulled a few to the other
side of our reach. Each shot was longer than the lines at the
will-call window. With each, we believed our moment touching
history would come.
</P>
<P>
   And just before we could give up hope, Ron Gant lined a shot
right to us. My son, I'm proud to say, lifted his glove as if to
take his best shot. My daughter reported later she could have
caught it and asked if it would have hurt. And just before the ball
could find my bare hands, Andy Ramirez of Cypress reached a glove
in its path for a clean catch. The fiend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's special because Mark McGwire's here,'' he said of his
position in the row in front of us. ``It's a special game.''
</P>
<P>
   And he admitted what we all knew about the shot hit by Ron Gant:
``Twenty years from now, it'll be McGwire's.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time McGwire came to bat in the first inning, all of us
were convinced that his every swing would land a ball in our hands,
and I felt as greedy for that $5 baseball as a contestant on Let's
Make A Deal with Monty Hall walking up the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   When he batted, the dome buzzed and hung on every pitch, every
umpire's call. The crowd in Lefty's Pub squeezed itself to the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was served one pitch to hit and lined it foul. He
walked.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Albert of Seabrook waited in the first row, wearing a
Detroit Red Wings hockey shirt with matching hat, knowing he was
missing his favorite team's chance to win the Stanley Cup to be in
the Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Mark McGwire would keep me from the Stanley Cup,'' he
said. ``This is a piece of history. Any baseball fan that does not
see this is ripping himself off.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire led off the third inning. This time, Astros starter Pete
Schourek offered little worth a cut. McGwire walked quickly. In two
at-bats, Paul Bunyan had done no more than Felix Unger could have
managed.
</P>
<P>
   By the time McGwire had grounded into a double play in the fifth
inning, the Cardinals were on their way to an 8-4 lead and the star
attraction of the visiting team was irrelevant. An inning later,
McGwire sent a soft fly ball out to right on the first pitch. In
the eighth, we wore our gloves one last time: McGwire struck out.
</P>
<P>
   We cheered when they retired McGwire, but there might have been
pangs of disappointment, too. The pressure McGwire must now feel to
send a packed left-field mezzanine home with a story to tell will
only increase as long as he chases the record. And the expectations
are not that he will excel but amaze.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Dillon had said he would like to see McGwire reach the
upper deck in center field, a shot perhaps impossible with a
College World Series sledgehammer of a bat.
</P>
<P>
   And though I should have known better, I was disappointed the
impossible had not happened. Dan Gulizia, who drove four hours from
his Navy base in Corpus Christi with his 4-year-old daughter,
Jessie, seemed to take it better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see Big Mac hit a home run,'' he said. ``I wanted
to see the Astrodome, and I wanted to bring my daughter to a
ballgame. I love baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   And for all its problems and strife, baseball had us Tuesday
back in its grasp. Even without the proof, we had seen perhaps a
glimpse into a legendary season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This field, this game, is part of our past, Ray,'' I thought
in James Earl Jones' Field of Dreams voice. ``It reminds us of all
that once was good, and that can be again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the kids understand. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
