<SLUG> BC-GLF-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SHOULD WALK A MILE IN MARTIN'S SHOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Casey Martin played a U.S. Open practice round
Tuesday at the Olympic Club. Fellow Stanford golfers Tiger Woods
and Joel Kribel tagged along. What, you were expecting Jack
Nicklaus and Tom Watson to power walk the 6,797-yard Lake Course
alongside Martin's single-rider cart?
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus and Watson both have publicly questioned the fairness
of allowing Martin, who suffers from a rare circulatory disease in
his right leg, to use a cart during tournament play. The way they
see it, the disabled golfer who successfully sued the PGA to be
able to use a cart is riding roughshod over the game's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Their perspective might be different if they bothered to change
their vantage point from, say, the inside of their glass houses to
inside the ropes. Because as the 10,000 or so people who followed
his every shot Tuesday can tell you, it's hard to schlep around the
course with Martin and not learn a little something beyond where
the most severe side slopes are on the fairways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch Casey. He has very little strength in his right
leg,'' said Kribel, a rising senior who entered Stanford right
after Martin matriculated, in 1995, but has played with him quite a
few times. ``It's hard for him to drive through the ball. His swing
is almost all upper body. It's incredible he can do what he does.
The people who criticize him, they don't know what he goes
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Picture Scottie Pippen's grimace throughout Game 6 of the NBA
Finals and you know what Martin's expression looked like as he
trudged through ridiculously thick rough adjacent to the 16th
fairway in search of an errant drive. Imagine your great
grandmother walking up a grassy hill that's only slightly less
steep than Hyde Street, where the cable cars clang, and you have a
pretty good idea how Martin looked limping on his brittle right leg
from the 18th green to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was out on the course, ``showing a lot of guts and
courage'' in the words of Woods, when, back in the
climate-controlled comfort of the press tent, Watson was asked to
imagine that his 15-year-old son Michael had the same talent and
disability as Martin. What would he tell him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell him, son, `I want you to play the best you can within
what the Tour will allow,''' replied Watson, another Stanford grad
(class of 1971). ```(If) the Tour doesn't allow it, that is just
one of the tough decisions in life.'''
</P>
<P>
   David Fay, the executive director of the USGA, faced a difficult
decision, one of many that you are bombarded with when you're
bucking tradition. The single-rider cart that the USGA had assigned
to Martin was cute and all, but like the new VW Bug, it has a few
glitches. For starters, it kept stalling.
</P>
<P>
   Fay could have adopted Watson's stance and told Martin, ``I want
you to play the best you can with the cart we'll allow. If it
drives you to distraction, oh well. That's just one of the tough
breaks in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fay put himself in Martin's seat. After taking the cart
for a spin _ and having the brakes lock on him _ Fay recommended
that Martin be allowed to use a standard cart Thursday when he
becomes the first driver in the U.S. Open that is not pulled from
the players' bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is amazing how things happen,'' said Martin, who lives 30
minutes from the Olympic Club, in a condominium in Foster City.
``In the last six months I went from just kind of struggling to
stay in this game and not knowing if I could keep playing to
(playing) in the U.S. Open. I am running on adrenaline right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the cart, he'll be required to do a lot more walking
this week than is good for his leg, which Martin is resigned to
losing, probably sooner than later.
</P>
<P>
   Every step hurts, the ostracism by some of his peers stings and
sleep is a recurring nightmare for Martin. But the next complaint
you hear from Martin will be his first.
</P>
<P>
   He has learned to take comfort where he can find it, like in the
crowd that got so loud when Martin birdied the par-4, 347-yard 18th
with a 4-iron, a 9-iron and a 6-foot putt that you would have
thought it was the 72nd hole on Sunday. And indeed, there was a
payday at the end, though Martin suspects he might have trouble
collecting his $30 in side bets from Woods, a notorious tightwad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to hear the crowd roar,'' Martin said. ``That is
the stuff that I dreamt about 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin is worth rooting for. The 26-year-old has grace to spare.
Now if he can only find some takers in the Olympic Club locker
room, which could get pretty cold this week no matter what the
thermostat is set at.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen a few of those players who were outspoken (about
his not being able to use a cart) and they didn't go out of their
way to say `hi' or anything,'' Martin said. ``At the same time, you
know, they didn't sneer at me, either.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Tom Lehman and John Cook went out of their way
to make Martin feel welcome. As for those who did not, Martin said,
``You wish people could understand what you deal with (because) if
they knew they wouldn't say the kinds of things they do.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
