<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2555 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPREMES17-AZR &LR;      06-16 1393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREMES17-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA HIGH COURT REJECTS BID TO LEGALIZE SCHOOL CONSTRUCTION
FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By HAL MATTERN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ The latest legislative attempt to equalize school
construction funding in Arizona was rejected Tuesday by the state
Supreme Court, forcing lawmakers to reopen the volatile issue in
the middle of their re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The court, in a rare unanimous opinion, said the Students FIRST
law passed in April fails to fulfill the state's constitutional
obligation to maintain a ``general and uniform'' school system
because its funding methods would ``cause substantial disparities
between public school districts.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices gave the Legislature 60 days to come up with
another plan or risk the cutoff of all school funding in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   That means legislators will be writing law with parents and
voters looking over their shoulders. They will have to go back into
special session sometime before Aug. 15, just days before many
public schools are scheduled to open for the fall and a little more
than three weeks before the Sept. 8 primary election. All 90
legislative seats are open, and the cost of failure could be the
national embarrassment of Arizona school doors padlocked by the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've obviously got a tough deadline,'' said Senate Majority
Leader Marc Spitzer, R-north-central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an election year, so that complicates things. And we've
got members who aren't running for re-election who will be voting
on this. But what I want to do, and what most members want to do,
is keep the schools running.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hogan, who successfully sued the state in 1991 over school
construction disparities, said lawmakers shouldn't be surprised by
Tuesday's ruling because they had ample warning that Students FIRST
would likely be declared unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they went ahead and passed it, anyway,'' said Hogan,
executive director of the Arizona Center for Law in the Public
Interest. ``They deserve to come back in August.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan originally sued the state on behalf of a group of poor
districts, arguing that funding school construction through local
property taxes has created unconstitutional disparities between
classroom facilities statewide.
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed in 1994 and ordered the Legislature to craft a
solution `'within a reasonable time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers attempted to comply in 1996 and 1997, but both efforts
were rejected by the court. In their earlier rulings, the justices
also upheld a June 30 deadline for legislative action set by a
lower-court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rebecca Albrecht of Maricopa County Superior Court ordered
the state Department of Education to halt the distribution of all
public-school funding if lamakers failed to resolve the case before
the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's ruling Tuesday extended the deadline until
Aug. 15, a goal Gov. Jane Hull said officials were prepared to
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Most public schools in Arizona begin their fall semesters in
mid- to late August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I . . . want to assure parents in Arizona the schools will be
operating in August,'' said Hull, who petitioned the court to
uphold the law. ``We will be prepared to have a bill to the
justices by Aug. 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Students FIRST _ Fair and Immediate Resources for Students Today
_ called for the state to spend $372 million a year to build, equip
and maintain public schools, replacing the current method of using
tax-backed bonds to build classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The state would also have set minimum adequacy standards and
assured that all public schools met them within five years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the plan would have given school districts that met
the standards the option of rejecting the state funding and
continuing to use bonds instead.
</P>
<P>
   That so-called ``opt-out'' provision was the main area of
contention over Students FIRST. Hogan argued that it would result
in a two-tiered funding system, one for rich districts and another
for poor ones.
</P>
<P>
   A separate dispute arose over a provision prohibiting districts
that accepted state money from issuing bonds to raise additional
funds. Those districts would have had to use capital overrides for
such purposes, which cost more and raise less than bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Students FIRST would also have lowered the assessment ratios
used to determine the amount of property taxes charged to
businesses to repay the capital overrides, thereby shifting more of
the burden to homeowners. The change wouldn't have affected bond
sales by the opt-out districts.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Tuesday, the Supreme Court upheld the portions of
the law dealing with standards and state funding and even said that
the opt-out provision on its own was constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the prohibition on bonding and the reduced
assessment ratios are combined with the opt-out provision, the
justices said, it ``results in systematic, structural differences
in the ability of districts to exceed state minimums through local
funding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of these structural differences, (Students FIRST) as a
whole continues to formalize and perpetuate a structure that fails
the general and uniform test,'' the justices wrote in their 15-page
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and legislative leaders said they were encouraged that the
court upheld some of the core provisions of the law, which could
wind up being the basis for any new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case of going back to square one,'' Spitzer
said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was willing to say yet which direction any new proposals
would take, but some officials said they would like to return to
the original Students FIRST plan passed by the House. That was
identical to the final version, but without the opt-out provision.
</P>
<P>
   Because that plan would have eliminated all bonding by school
districts, it was widely criticized and was unable to win enough
support to pass the Senate. It also sparked a messy political
battle that resulted in a 29-day special session on the school
finance issue before the compromise opt-out provision was approved.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Jeff Groscost, R-Mesa, said the court ruling might
persuade former opponents of the original plan to reconsider, which
would result in a quick solution to the whole issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction,
also favors returning to that plan. A longtime proponent of
eliminating bonding, Keegan had argued against the opt-out
provision in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear from the opinion that the original law is a good
plan,'' Keegan said. ``It works. Republicans and Democrats ought to
be able to read this opinion and see this. Given the time
constraints imposed by the court, it would be foolhardy to start
from square one when we have a constitutional plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Backers of continued bonding said they
still believed that districts have a constitutional right to bond.
Tuesday's ruling didn't directly address that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents of the original plan predicted another bloody
battle if legislative leaders try to press the ban on bonding, a
battle lawmakers would rather avoid with the election looming.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Johnson, Hull's Democratic opponent in the governor's race,
has already signaled his intention to make school finance a
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already a massive embarrassment for the governor and the
state,'' Johnson said Tuesday during a visit to the Capitol. ``It
just was never designed around equalization. This program was
designed around shifting the taxes from mines and utilities onto
the middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Art Hamilton, D-southwest Phoenix, also
used the court ruling as an opportunity to blast Republicans, whom
he accused of catering to business interests in passing Students
FIRST.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they put the interest of kids before those of their
(business) friends, who run this place, we won't ever get this
resolved,'' said Hamilton, who is running for secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders said they would look at a variety of options,
including possibly allowing some form of limited bonding in
conjunction with state funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole array of things we can do,'' Groscost said,
``including coming up with an entirely new plan.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hal Mattern can be reached at 444-8652 or at
hal.mattern(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
