<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REDWINGS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED WINGS WIN STANLEY CUP FOR 2ND TIME IN A ROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year after their first championship in 42 years
was marred by tragedy, the Detroit Red Wings beat the Washington
Capitals on Tuesda night by 4-1 in the MCI Center to sweep the
finals once again in four consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit was led by two goals from Doug Brown. The other Detroit
goals were scored by Martin Lapointe and Larry Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   For Scotty Bowman, it was his eighth post-season championship as
a coach, tying him with Toe Blake, his mentor with the Montreal
Canadiens more than three decades ago. The 64-year-old Bowman also
has one cup ring as an executive with Pittsburgh in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Conn Smythe trophy, awarded to the most
valuable player in the post-season tournament, was Steve Yzerman,
the Detroit captain, a 15-year veteran who led his team in the
playoffs with 24 points on 6 goals and 18 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The game, the series, the championship and the entire season
were contested in an emotional and sentimental atmosphere around
the Detroit franchise. Last June, six days after beating
Philadelphia for their first championship since 1955, their
celebration ended prematurely when defenseman Vladimir Konstantinov
and the team masseur Sergei Manatsakanov suffered severe brain
injuries in the crash of a limousine that carried them from a golf
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Konstantinov was part of the crowd, along with
many of the team's fans. Although the Red Wings were the visitors,
they heard the cheers of thousands in this big, new rink downtown
in the District of Columbia. They are one of the National Hockey
League's ``Old Six'' teams, and many of their Michigan-bred fans
have migrated across the country.
</P>
<P>
   When the Detroit players took the ice, in uniforms of blood-red
with trim of bright white, the building was filled with chants of
``Let's Go Red Wings! Let's Go Red Wings!'' Fans near the ice
carried and waved a sign that said ``Hockeytown,'' a trendy
nickname for what is also known as the Motor City and Motown.
During the second intermission, some fans chanted: ``Vladdie!
Vladdie! Vladdie!''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the buzzer ended the game, the ice surface was
decorated with an octopus, for decades the symbol of Detroit's
Stanley Cup playoff aspirations. Moments later, Konstantinov took
the ice in a wheelchair, a spotlight shining on him while his
teammates celebrated at the other end of the ice. The first players
to notice him were the Capitals, and several of them gathered near
him as the teams prepared for the ceremonial handshake across
center ice.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantinov wore a Red Wings jersey and a hat. As his chair was
wheeled to the Red Wings' bench, his teammates saw him and began to
gather around him to hug and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game ended a season that began on Oct. 1 and included
an unprecedented 16-day break to allow participation in the Winter
Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan. The regular season ended on April
19. Training camp for the next season begins in about 11 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit opened the scoring on the power play at 10 minutes 30
seconds of the first period when Brown beat Washington goalie Olaf
Kolzig. It was Brown's third goal of the tournament, second in the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings made it 2-0 at even strength on a goal by Lapointe,
who took a pass from Igor Larionov and slapped from near the blue
line at 2:26 of the second period. It was Lapointe's ninth goal of
the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Washington came back to cut the lead to 2-1 at 7:49 of the
second period on a goal by Brian Bellows, who knocked in a loose
puck from a scramble near the crease of Detroit goal Chris Osgood.
The play began with a turnover by the Detroit defense.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wings increased the margin to 3-1 at 11:46 of the second
on a power-play goal by Murphy, his third of the post-season.
Murphy one-timed a slap shot from the right-wing circle after Tomas
Holmstrom passed to him after digging the puck away from the
Capitals behind Kolzig's net.
</P>
</TEXT>
