<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS OF WEST INDIAN PARADE BRINGS DISSENSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: West Indies)  (lb) 
 By GARRY PIERRE-PIERRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With its kaleidoscope of colors, ornate costumes and
rollicking steel bands, the West Indian American Day parade has
grown to become New York City's most popular, surpassing even the
St. Patrick's Day parade in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign that this growth has also sown dissension, the
carnival's longtime organizers are facing a challenge to their
leadership by many of the band leaders of the parade who question
whether the organizers are capable of handling such a large event
and whether they are doing all they can to attract sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, members from 23 of the 30 bands that play at the
parade created the Carnival Band Leaders Action Committee
International. They have asked the organizers to meet with them to
discuss ways to improve the flow of the often-chaotic and crowded
parade. The group also wants to receive a larger share of corporate
donations to the event and set up a permanent parade office with
full-time staff.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the band leaders said, the carnival's organizers have
refused to discuss these issues. Mounting frustration has led some
of the band leaders to say that they are seriously considering a
boycott next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this continues, there's going to be a boycott next year,''
said Desmond Chase, a member of Hawks International, one of the
largest bands that participate in the parade. ``You'll see a parade
with jeans and T-shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers dismissed such talks and described Chase and his
organization as an insurgent group bent on destroying all that the
organizers have accomplished over the last 30 years. They said that
meetings among those involved in the event are held almost every
week and that any band member has the opportunity to make
suggestions then.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if you have a little puppy and you raised it and after
it's a big dog, someone wants to come and take it away, let me ask
you what would you do?'' said Joyce Quamina, business manager of
the West Indian American Day Carnival. ``Desmond Chase and his
group have to take a number and wait in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase said the carnival will go on as usual this year because
the bands have already begun preparations and have invested
thousands of dollars buying masks and the fabrics for the costumes.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a boycott from some of the band leaders has
particular resonance because of the pivotal role bands play during
the parade. Each band is, essentially, an entire production in
itself, and includes performers wearing masks and costumes, as well
as the music itself. Their participation is crucial to the parade,
and the bands' preparations often begin a year in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The parade, which is held on Labor Day weekend, unites people
from Jamaica, Barbados and other Caribbean nations, but its flavor
is clearly from Trinidad and rooted in that nation's carnival, a
celebration that is part religious and part cultural. So in
threatening to boycott the event, the band leaders are in many ways
taking on a cherished event.
</P>
<P>
   Chase said that the event, which has steadily been gaining
popularity, attracting up to a million people every year, has
become increasingly unmanageable for the organizers, who, he says,
are unable to handle the complex logistics like coordinating police
presence and negotiating local television rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we need to have a voice in the administration of the
carnival,'' Chase said. ``We don't want to destroy this carnival,
but if left as it is, we'll have no choice. Without our
participation there is no carnival.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the dispute lie some serious issues about the unsteady
pace of the floats, bands and masqueraders moving along the crowded
Eastern Parkway in Crown Heights, Brooklyn, beginning at Utica
Avenue and ending at Grand Army Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the sidewalks are so cluttered that at times people
have to elbow each other to get a glimpse of the parade. Chase said
he and his group are proposing that the organizers build bleachers
for revelers. Chase also said that the band leaders would like to
share in the roughly $700,000 that organizers raise from corporate
sponsors and vendors, since they are not allowed to solicit
sponsors on their own and often pay as much as $50,000 to make the
costumes and rent loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this thing is structured properly with full-time staff, we
can maximize sponsorship,'' said Derrick Lewis, a member of the
dissenting group. ``I really don't think the organizers know what
they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in a city of immigrants, parade organizers said that it
is a testament to their skills that the mostly Caribbean affair has
become the most popular and colorful parade in New York. Ms.
Quamina said that the sponsorship money is used to pay
administrative costs, like posting an insurance bond for the parade
and paying out-of-town performers like the calypso superstar Mighty
Sparrow. But Ms. Quamina remains defiant in dealing with Chase and
his group.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we finish paying, we don't have any money,'' she
said. ``I don't know what nonsense they're talking about. This is
New York, not Trinidad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
