A2561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-STUDENTS-LAWSUIT-5     06-16 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STUDENTS-LAWSUIT-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFIDAVIT SAYS UNIVERSITY SPIED ON STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a surveillance camera was discovered earlier
this month at City College of New York _ concealed in a smoke
detector outside a student meeting room _ cries of Big Brother
tactics were heard around the campus: The college had strayed into
invasion of privacy and was trying to silence dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Students filed a federal suit and the faculty union head shot
off a letter of protest to the college president. College
officials, meanwhile, asserted that the camera had been installed
to prevent burglaries.
</P>
<P>
   But in an affidavit filed in the students' suit and made public
this week, the college's security chief states that the camera was
installed to monitor not just theft but students as well.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit of Timothy Hubbard, the security director, said
that the college installed the camera in part because it had
received a report that ``students or nonstudents might be planning
to attempt to take over the building sometime around commencement
on June 2, 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered no immediate explanation of the purpose of any
takeover, but City University saw several protests by teachers and
students at commencements this month over the board of trustees'
plan to remove remedial courses from the university's four-year
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny surveillance camera was installed by security officials
on May 29 in a hallway of the academic center and pointed toward
the door to the room where politically active students have often
met. Acting on a tip, however, students found and dismantled it.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the college, Charles DeCicco, said Tuesday that
because of the litigation, Hubbard and other college officials
could not discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But in the affidavit, Hubbard said the camera had no audio
capability and was being used ``to address legitimate security
concerns in a public place.'' The security office does not believe
it violated student rights, Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   But others on campus disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Three graduate students _ Brad Sigal, David Suker and Ydanis
Rodriguez _ filed suit on June 3 against City College and the City
University of New York, charging them with violating their rights
to privacy and political association. They are seeking a protective
order and compensatory and punitive damages, among other things. A
hearing is scheduled on Friday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely has a chilling effect,'' said Sigal, a graduate
student in history. ``It makes people apprehensive and unwilling to
get involved politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Sohmer, a City College mathematics professor and the
new faculty representative on the university's board of trustees,
called the incident troubling. ``It is inappropriate on a college
campus,'' he said. ``It shouldn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald McGuire, the lawyer for the City College students, said
hiding the camera was reprehensible. ``It is fundamentally
antithetical to free inquiry and a free university,'' he said.
``Security operations of this type will have a chilling effect on
the exercise of First Amendment rights. That is really what's at
issue here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Suker, a graduate student in secondary education and a longtime
campus protester, said he was in the North Academic Center building
on May 29 when a college employee warned him that a hidden camera
had been mounted that morning outside the meeting room.
</P>
<P>
   The building had been the target of student protests before; it
was taken over in a 1991 protest over tuition increases.
</P>
<P>
   Suker took video pictures of the camera and found someone to let
him into a nearby office, where he found a television monitor and a
videocassette recorder that he said were part of the security
system.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Benenson, a mechanical engineering professor at City
College and chairman of its faculty union chapter, said security
officials were correct in saying that there were burglary problems
on campus _ he has lost six computers in his lab in the last two
years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the security office had done little to prevent
the thefts, and he had been told to install his own alarms. He said
he and other teachers did not take seriously the security
director's statement in the affidavit that the hidden camera was
also being used to prevent robberies. He considers the surveillance
one more attempt by the college to track politically active
students, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't think this is about burglary,'' he said.
``There is a history to this, but what just happened is more
blatant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
