<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HEALEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VINCENT HEALEY, 80, ANTI-SUBMARINE SPECIALIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., N.J., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Vincent Patrick Healey, a retired anti-submarine
specialist who, as a young gunnery officer, saw naval combat from
the Philippines to Iwo Jima to Japan itself in World War II, died
on May 30 at Georgetown University Hospital in Washington. He was
80 and lived in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh out of the U.S. Naval Academy in 1940, he was assigned to
the cruiser Astoria. The ship survived the Japanese raid on Pearl
Harbor, and Healey fought in engagements in the Coral Sea and at
Midway before enemy gunfire sank the cruiser in the first battle
for Savo Island in August 1942. He helped save the lives of the
officers and crew around him and for his ``gallantry and
intrepidity'' was awarded the Bronze Star.
</P>
<P>
   He was reassigned to destroyer duty, serving as gunnery officer
on the Beale, executive officer aboard the Ault and, in August
1945, commanding officer of the Dyson. Throughout the war Healey
took part in operations at the southern Palau Islands, Formosa,
Luzon in the Philippines and the China coast. He participated in
the assault on Iwo Jima and in raids against the group of islands
that includes Okinawa and, finally, against Japan itself.
</P>
<P>
   He then did postgraduate work at the Naval Academy and the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. He won the Legion of Merit
for his work in anti-submarine warfare and tactical aircraft, ship,
missile and electronic warfare systems while posted to the office
of the chief of naval operations.
</P>
<P>
   After he retired from the Navy in 1972, Healey became a
consultant for aerospace companies and headed the Washington
operations of EDO Corp., an engineering concern.
</P>
<P>
   Born in the Bronx in New York City, he was the first native of
the borough to reach the rank of admiral. He attended Fordham
University before his appointment to the Naval Academy in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Healey's first wife, Helen Marie Clarke Healey, died in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Joan Casey Saenz Healey; five
children from his first marriage, Dominic of Maywood, N.J., John of
New York, Mary Healey of Arlington, Jane Marie Healey Zamm of New
York and Peter of San Diego; and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980616.0507 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-16 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2567 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT     06-16 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES SHUT OUT YANKEES, 2-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Sidney Ponson ascended the mound for Baltimore on
Tuesday night practically unknown outside of his homeland of Aruba,
a young pitcher looking for his first major league victory. Now he
is the primary reason why the New York Yankees are in their first
mini-slump in more than than two months.
</P>
<P>
   Ponson held the Yankees to two hits over six and two-thirds
innings, as the Orioles won, 2-0, their second victory in this
three-game series. The defeat guarantees that the Yankees will lose
a series for the first time since the opening series of the season
against Anaheim. They had played 24 consecutive series which they
had either won or tied, giving them a share of a major league
standard held by the 1912 Boston Red Sox and 1970 Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have lost three of their last four games, all
without their star center fielder Bernie Williams, as well as
shortstop Derek Jeter. Their lead in the American League East,
however, remains quite safe: nine games ahead of the second-place
Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Ponson retired 20 of the first 21 batters he faced before Tino
Martinez drew a two-out walk in the seventh. Jorge Posada pulled a
single off the glove of the first baseman Rafael Palmeiro, and when
Ponson fell behind in the count to Chad Curtis, two balls and no
strikes, Manager Ray Miller of the Orioles replaced Ponson with the
left-hander Arthur Rhodes.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis began the game with five home runs in 59 at-bats against
left-handers this season, and was 5 for 16 in his career against
Rhodes, so Miller would have been open to considerable
second-guessing had Curtis come up with a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   But Curtis took two strikes, then swung unsuccessfully at a
neck-high fastball to strike out, flinging his bat in anger. Curtis
has only 7 hits in his last 45 at-bats (.156) with runners in
scoring position. Sidney Ponson has a brand-new identity.
</P>
<P>
   Ponson, 21, is rising from the ashes of what has been a terrible
season for the Orioles. One of only a handful of players from
Aruba, Ponson is the organization's best prospect, having shed 30
pounds and refined command of his breaking pitches. The
right-hander threw extremely well against the Yankees on May 19, in
middle relief _ an effort that was overshadowed the instant Armando
Benitez drilled Tino Martinez with a fastball that evening.
</P>
<P>
   No other pitcher has dominated the Yankees this season the way
Ponson did on Tuesday night. Throwing a fastball clocked as high as
97 miles an hour and complementing it with a curveball and a
changeup, Ponson retired the first eight hitters he faced. With two
out in the third inning, Luis Sojo chopped a grounder over Ponson's
head; Roberto Alomar, the Orioles' second baseman, attempted to
back-hand the ball and failed, a tough play that immediately was
scored a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Ponson kept right on going. The Yankees are perhaps the best
team in baseball at working walks, forcing opposing pitchers deep
into ball-strike counts, but in the first five innings, Ponson
reached two-ball counts only twice, and only one three-ball count.
</P>
<P>
   Following Sojo's hit, Ponson retired 12 consecutive batters, so
that through six innings, he had allowed only that one hit, no
walks, facing one batter over the minimum of 18 at that point. This
was the closest thing to perfection the Yankees had seen since May
17.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu wasn't much worse. He struggled more than Ponson, his
control erratic, the velocity on his fastball dipping to as low as
88 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, the Yankee pitcher, wasn't much worse. He
struggled more than Ponson, his control erratic, the velocity on
his fastball dipping to as low as 88 m.p.h. He walked Brady
Anderson to lead off the Oriole first and gave up a single to Lenny
Webster opening the third, the first of Webster's three hits
against Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   But Irabu repeatedly navigated his way through the early inning
squalls, pumping up his fastball when he needed a big pitch. Irabu
got Joe Carter to ground out to end the third inning with a runner
at third. Harold Baines walked and Roberto Alomar walked in the
fourth _ first and second and one out. Then B.J. Surhoff grounded
out and Irabu attacked Cal Ripken with an inside fastball, which
Ripken popped up foul to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Webster started the fifth inning by topping a slow grounder
toward third base, and Scott Brosius charged and gloved it.
Brosius, however, couldn't grip the ball on his first attempt, and
when he did manage to unload a throw, it was low and away. A base
hit, rightly, but Brosius looked disgusted with himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick laced a single to center, with Webster stopping at
second. In a bunt situation, Anderson failed to advance the
runners, popping up, and Carter lofted an easy fly, to center. But
then Harold Baines drove a ball through the middle, as he often
does, to score Webster with the first run.
</P>
<P>
   Alomar timed a fastball from Irabu perfectly in the sixth
inning, driving it beyond the fence in right-center field, giving
Baltimore a 2-0 advantage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-16-98 2357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
